<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<hr>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2><P align = center>PIE IN THE SKY</FONT></B><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><P align = center><B>The Downtown Real Estate Market is Picking Up, But Real Growth Remains to be Seen</B></FONT SIZE><br><i><B>By Ray Marano</B></i>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>
When Joe Blattner started shopping for a new home for his growing advertising and public relations firm a year and a half ago, his expectations were rather modest. 
<P> 
But  after about six months of looking and bartering, Blattner/Brunner ended up in 17,000 square feet at plush One Oxford Centre in April 1994 -- paying just $1.50 a square foot more than the agency was paying for 11,700 square feet on two floors at  814 Penn Avenue in the cultural district. 
<P>
Blattner considers himself and the firm fortunate. 
<P> 
"If I were doing it today, I probably wouldn't get the deal I have now," says Blattner. 
<P>
He's probably right. For the past year, downtown office rental rates have steadily climbed back from a steep drop in the late 1980s and early 1990s, a kickback from the glut of office   space dumped into the market due to corporate downsizing. The resulting lag in demand caused the reconsideration of several downtown construction projects (read: scratched) -- a move that local politicos often hail as the wisdom that saved Pittsburgh's real estate market from the tubes down which many other urban areas tumbled. 
<P>
Now, that wisdom has the potential to curtail corporate relocating downtown. Although there is still space available, according to leasing agents, and some good deals as well, there is a pinch in downtown class A space, the poshest, most modern accommodations for corporate renters. And while by everyone's account the market for downtown office space has tightened and shows no visible signs of loosen-ing any time soon, demand has, to this point, still not spurred downtown construction. 
<P>
<h2>Bigger Isn't Better </h2>
Large corporations seeking class A space, in particular, have problems.  A report compiled by local commercial real estate firm Arnheim & Neely Oncor International says that there are good opportunities for users who need up to 20,000 square feet of class A space, but corporate users seeking bigger blocks will find less to choose from. 
<P>
When Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania, for example, wanted to consolidate 1,250 employees from operations in several buildings downtown into a single 300,000-square-foot location, they had to get creative. Jim Baumgartner, president of Standard Property Corp., a Blue Cross affiliate charged with securing the new space for the health insurance behemoth, says current market conditions, which still offer good opportunities for renters, played a part in the company's decision to consolidate. But most importantly, leases in any of Blue Cross' downtown locations will terminate in the fourth quarter of 1996. Bringing operations under a single roof and a single lease agreement should allow the corporation to use space more cost-effectively. 
<P>
"That's one of our goals, and we do believe that will occur," says Baumgartner. <P>With existing space of the ilk needed hard to come by in such quantity, the company chose to revamp the Lazarus department store building, which is tethered to Blue Cross' Fifth Avenue Place offices by a skywalk. The renovation, which will be done by Oxford Development Co., will reportedly cost $49 million, $20 million of which will come from public funds. Lazarus will move to a new location, being constructed at a cost of $67 million, at the corner of Fifth and Wood. 
<P>
The Arnheim & Neely report notes that while class B space is a little less scarce, the trickle-down caused by brisk demand for class A space and upgrades of some class B space to attract tenants in the stronger market has squeezed that category, too. Class C space, by comparison, is experiencing lagging demand but offers substantial concessions to tenants and favorable rental rates. 
<P>
The demand for class B space seems to be surging this year. Jeremy Kronman with Gold & Co. says that six months ago, two of the Downtown properties he handles were at 80 percent occupancy. Now, they are filled to capacity. Four others have jumped from 75 percent to 95 percent occupied during the same period. "We're seeing some creative uses of space," Kronman says, pointing to a 110,000-square-foot, three-floor renovation in the Westin William Penn Hotel that is marketed as 555 Grant Street and stands fully leased. "A year ago, people didn't know it was there," says Kronman. 
<P>
One change affecting the market is that there are more, smaller clients. Corporate downsizing and small business creation are having their effect on the office rental industry. Leasing out 555 Grant Street, for example, entailed lining up a dozen tenants instead of two, as might have been the case in the past, with most taking 2,000 to 5,000 square feet. Some took less than 1,000 square feet. 
<P>
The creative uses Kronman describes, it seems, offer some good opportunities for companies that have managed to sustain growth and over the years have placed operations in offices throughout downtown and the suburbs. 
<P>
<H2>A Seller's Market </H2>
What's driving the landlord's market, especially for class A space? Fundamentally, it seems, the lack of major new downtown office construction in the Golden Triangle. Paired with an upswing in demand from a surging economy, this is locking up chunks of space and making it more difficult for renters to find desirable space. 
<P>
"The class A market's going to get even tighter, and that's going to make B space even more attractive," says David Knight, president of Allegheny Center Associates. <P>Strong demand for class A accommodations and downsizing companies looking for bargains in spiffed-up class B space seem to have shored up both office space categories. 
<P>
Take for instance the Federal Home Loan Bank, which moved from class A space to class B quarters in the former Porter Building, and Fiserv, which made a similar switch to the Comstock Building. Both achieved better visibility in the market and got lower rents. 
<P>
But this is often not the quality of office space that well-heeled tenants desire. Quality, a lack of contiguous spaces for large tenants and little chance of a major new development in 1995 tilts the table in favor of the landlords. 
<P>
That is increasingly reflected in the market. Rental rates and occupancies inched upward by the end of 1994, with class A space asking rates in the $20 to $22 level. Rates have continued to climb, with leasing agents reporting some class A space pushing $25 a square foot. Occupancy rates for class A space were around 88 percent. Class B space, which saw stronger activity during 1994, demanded about $14 by year's end, and showed occupancy levels at around 85 percent. 
<P> 
But though rental rates have firmed up significantly, they still haven't reached a level that would entice developers to risk a major new downtown office building. The consensus is that current lease rates are about $8 to $10 below the $30 a square foot it would take to justify major new construction in the central business district. Jon Harrigan of Pennsylvania Commercial Real Estate calls the difference between current rental rates and what developers need to pull the trigger for new construction "a giant chasm." 
<P>
Harrigan and others say there is an aching need for new class A space. "What the trend is saying is we're ready for a large chunk of space and if we don't get it, people will get pigeon-holed where they are," Harrigan says. And despite the supply of sublease and renovated B space coming onto the market, Harrigan says some tenants want a particular type of space that fits their needs. "People will say there is the Gimbel's building, the Alcoa building," Harrigan says, "but tenants are inclined not to consider facilities that won't suit their purposes." 
<P>
While no one is panicking yet, there's some concern that a shortage of class A space could cramp the downtown and perhaps hurt the city. If a major tenant can't find a large space in the city and isn't willing to wait the two or three years necessary for new construction, a big fish might get away. One broker talked of a client who looked at Pittsburgh but didn't put the city on its short list because it couldn't find the 60,000 square feet of contiguous space it needed for a 500-employee operation. 
<P>
As the market gets tighter, the problem could become more acute. 
<P> 
"It's a problem that is building, there's no doubt about it," says Don Pulver, chief executive officer of Oliver Tyrone Pulver of Philadelphia, the developer of the Cultural Trust's proposed office tower at Penn Avenue and Seventh Street. Pulver wants to stack the deck in favor of the project successfully securing financing by pre-leasing at least 90 percent of the building. But even assuming, best case scenario, that the building gets off the ground next year, by the time it is completed the newest buildings in the city -- Fifth Avenue Place and CNG Tower -- will be a decade old. 
<P> 
<H2>Cementing Commitments </H2>
Pulver's on the right track. Lenders, wary of the volatility that real estate demonstrated as an investment vehicle in the late 1980s and early 1990s, insist that developers get firm pre-leasing commitments for large portions of new buildings before they agree to bankroll construction, to prove the project's merit. They've upped the ante on developers, pressing them to assume more risk for the project, and to provide more equity to wrap up a financing package. They are looking hard at developers' credit worthiness and paring down amortization schedules. While a 20- or 25-year mortgage term was common a decade or so ago, 15 years is more the norm today. 
<P>
"The reality today is that the sponsor is taking more of the risk than he was 10 years ago," says Charles D'Amico, first vice president with Mellon Bank. 
<P>
That reality has translated into a standstill for new office construction activity downtown. The $100 million City Centre, a project that has been on the boards for Grant Street  for the last five years, is still in a hole behind Mellon Bank Center. But for lack of any major tenant commitment, it  won't happen this year -- or next. 
<P>
By contrast, the outlook for the $40 million Cultural District office tower seems a lot brighter. Pulver feels confident that he can snag a major tenant or two this year. Once the lead tenants are lined up, Pulver believes, others will follow suit. 
<P>
"We're still in the pre-leasing phase and have a number of what I would call good prospects," says Pulver, adding that there are about 10 prospective renters, most from the Pittsburgh area, who are interested in the new building. 
<P> 
No one seems to think the more stringent requirements lenders are demanding are necessarily bad, even though they aren't  making development easy. 
<P> 
"I think it has more of an upside because you have developers in a position where they really have to justify their projects," said real estate consultant Carrie Holstead. 
<P>
What does a tighter market mean for tenants? In addition to paying more for space, renters are being asked to commit to longer leases. While three-year term leases were the norm a few years ago, leasing agents say landlords are asking for five or more years on agreements in the more brisk market. Concession packages, the deal sweeteners used to lure tenants in leaner times, aren't as generous as they used to be. Moving allowances and free rent have begun to dry up. 
<P>
"Tenants remember the articles about free rent that were appearing as recently as two years ago," says one leasing agent. "Brokers talk about it, and little tenants want it, but they aren't getting it." 
<P>
<H2>Fringe Benefits </H2>
Suburban and fringe markets are posing a challenge to the downtown. Suburban landlords are luring tenants with the promise of less congestion and the perception of a safer environment, not to mention more attractive rents, convenient parking and lower taxes. <P>Some not-so-distant properties are challenging the Golden Triangle for renters. For the big-space tenant who doesn't need a prestigious address, facilities like Allegheny Center are a strong pull. 
<P>
"I can still do 100,000 square feet on one floor if someone needs to do that," says Allegheny Center's Knight. Allegheny Center, which is in the process of renovating its former retail storefronts into offices, offers tenants "B-plus" space. 
<P>
"The guy who wants to be in a class A space downtown isn't coming to Allegheny Center," Knight concedes, but he points out that Allegheny Center offers parking at $2.75 a day, and lease rates that are in the $55 per month range. 
<P>
There will certainly be other opportunities opening up. Alcoa's move to a build-to-suit North Side facility will throw an additional 110,000 square feet of space onto the open market. Another 100,000 square feet of space will come onto the market as a result of just ordinary activity,  leases up and companies moving, and that will increase supply as well.
<P>
But stiff competition continues from the suburban and fringe markets. Healthy demand in the Parkway West corridor has the occupancy rate in  class A space at about 94 percent. The shortage of large blocks of contiguous class A space downtown has pushed development out to the suburbs into build-to-suit facilities. Companies looking for space in the west, such as Legent Corp., Colonial Insurance and Roadway Packaging Systems,  found that their only alternative was to build. 
<P>
<H2>Opportunity Knocks </H2>
What's on the horizon? Arnheim & Neely Oncor International forecasts that leases on about 10 million square feet of office space in the Pittsburgh market will expire in 1995 and 1996, swelling demand for space. 
<P>
Still, Pennsylvania Commercial Real Estate's Harrigan thinks that tenants, even though they're paying more, are coming out ahead. As evidence, he says that class A space rates in the '70s reached $26 to $28. 
<P>
"If you look at the rates over time, the tenants have benefited," he says. 
<P>
Building owners, after taking a beating on values in recent years, have benefited too. Selling prices for downtown properties dipped from $68 a square foot in 1988 to $11 a square foot in 1993. Now, prices have rebounded to about $28, bolstered mostly by the higher rental and occupancy rates. Jeffrey Holroyd with Arnheim & Neely Oncor International  says longer-held properties, are going on the block in response to stronger prices. "Now, suddenly, there are viable properties out there," says Holroyd. 
<P>
If there is a single word that describes the downtown market for office space, it is opportunity. Tenants with conventional needs might have to scramble to find the space they need, but they're likely to get it at reasonable and realistic prices. Landlords can expect to get more realistic rents for their properties, while building owners who took advantage of depressed prices in past years can look forward to reaping solid profits in the future. Finally, developers who can prove the worth of a project by securing commitments from tenants who are willing to bet that a building will go up will be undertaking solid projects that the market genuinely needs.                      
<P>
<HR>
<h2>Office Market Classifications</h2>
Unfamiliar with real estate? The following defines the classifications, gives examples of prominent buildings in that class and the average rental rate per square foot that category commanded at mid-year 1995. 
<P>
<B>Class A</B> -- Excellent location and access to the major financial and commercial districts of the city; professionally maintained and managed; with state-of-the-art building systems; functional floor plate. Gulf Building, Koppers Building, CNG Tower, One Mellon Bank Center. Average rent: $21.37/square foot. 
<P>
<B>Class B</B> -- Good to fair location; professionally managed, generally older buildings showing a slight functional or economic obsolescence. Allegheny Center, Law and Finance Building, Oliver Building. Average rent: $14.95/square foot. 
<P>
<B>Class C</B> -- Buildings in need of repair and/or renovation; usually located outside the more desirable business areas; rental rates below the average market rates which reflect economic and physical deterioration. Standard Life Building, Investment Building, Fulton Building. Average rent: $12.20/square foot. 
<P> 
<FONT SIZE=-1> Sources: 1994/95 Grubb & Ellis Real Estate
<P> 
Forecast
<P>
Arnheim & Neely Oncor International 
<P>
1995 Greater Pittsburgh Commercial Real Estate Market Report
<P>
