<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2><fill> </FONT SIZE><i> By Linda A. Dickerson</i><P>
<h2>Concerns About Clean Air Are Choking Economic Development</h2>This summer's intense heat did more than singe a few flower gardens. As temperatures escalated, the region's chances of being redesignated an Attainment Area under the Clean Air Act diminished and so did our prospects for a vibrant economy. <P> The Clean Air Act designated much of this region as a Moderate Non-Attainment Area. At issue is ground level ozone, a key component of smog. This area has too much ground level ozone. Hence, the area is classified as a Moderate Non-Attainment Area and is included in the Northeast Ozone Transport Region. The result:  Our businesses and other businesses considering whether to locate here face expensive and burdensome requirements. <P>A company locating in Pennsyl-vania that emits certain pollutants known as NOx and VOC must purchase emission credits equivalent to 115% of its own emissions. The credits are difficult to find and expensive to purchase. Sony spent $3 million on credits it would not have needed if it located in West Virginia or Ohio. <P> It gets worse. The EPA also requires manufacturers in this region to install Reasonably Available Control Technology at a hefty cost of $1500 per ton of pollutants. <P>Neither of our neighboring states are included in the Ozone Transport Region, making them significantly more appealing sites for manufacturing concerns to locate.  Pennsylvania is at a disadvantage. <P> But don't think Ohio and West Virginia are doing a better job of controlling emissions. In fact, Pennsylvania's air quality problems are substantially attributable to emissions from Ohio and West Virginia.<BR>Business people can and should impact our region's attainment status. First, they can urge their Congressmen to work toward making the standards for ozone attainment more reasonable. By eliminating the unfair advantage that Ohio, West Virginia and other states have, Pennsylvania would no longer bear an unfair share of the air quality problem. <P> Furthermore, enterprises bearing disproportionate costs because they operate in a Non-attainment Area should plea their cases collectively. Legislators do not  fully understand the magnitude of the region's non-attainment status. Quantifications of the impact will mobilize change. <P> We must unite in efforts to move  our region toward ozone attainment. Erasing the legislatively imposed air quality boundaries between Pennsylvania and its neighbors will advance economic development and enable all of us to breathe easier.<BR>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
