<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p><hr>
<FONT SIZE=+3><!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/editor.JU.gif"> </FONT SIZE>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B><P align=center>Ridge's Plan to Improve business Climate Requires voter Patience</FONT SIZE></B>
<b><i> By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</i></b>
<P>
Gov. Tom Ridge says he wants to make Pennsylvania a better place to do business. He proclaimed that intent every night during his campaign last year. You remember the television commercial -- standing in a town square, microphone in hand, railing on the state's dismal business atmosphere. 
<P> 
Approaching the end of his first year in office, Ridge already has made some progress, cutting the corporate income tax by 1 percent and taming what was once a mercenary Depart-ment of Environmental Resources. It's likely Ridge will accomplish even more, but I wonder whether the voters, who tend to gauge success by the number of jobs created, will even notice. 
<P>
Some voters may not notice, because Ridge's strategy is likely to drive gradual job growth over his years in office rather than causing a big bang. Translation: The headlines won't be as dramatic. In fact, headlines may be few.
<p>
"The long-term implications for Pennsylvania's workers probably won't be as visible," Ridge himself concedes in the interview that begins on page 34 of this magazine. Asked if voters will notice, "I hope so," the governor replied. 
<P>
A lack of headlines doesn't mean Ridge's strategy isn't a sound one. The worst kind of governor would be one who is banking on the big bangs -- Sony, for example -- to drive job growth. Until there is change with other factors over which Ridge has little control, such as the burdensome Clean Air Act regulations stifling Pennsylvania businesses, corporations have little motivation to locate a manufacturing center in our region. Many don't even consider looking here. Others would like to locate here but cannot because of the impact such a move would have on profit margin. 
<P>
So it is logical to build from the base we already have in Pennsylvania, as Ridge is proposing to do. The governor wants to further ease corporate taxes and regulation while reforming workers' compensation and maximizing exports. 
<P> 
The strategy is especially crucial to our region, where job growth is limited at best. Small- and medium-sized businesses are driving our economy, yet the rate of new business start-ups and entrepreneurships lags well behind the national average. 
<P> 
In 1994, the Center for Enterprise Development ranked Pennsylvania dead last nationally in "entrepreneurial energy." The rank is a result of a combination of three factors: Pennsylvania ranked 45th for the rate of new com-pany formation, 49th for the rate of change in the formation rate and 33rd for the rate of job growth in new companies less than four years old. 
<P>
It gets worse: Western Pennsyl-vania lags behind the state when comparing new company formations. A University of Pittsburgh study showed the region's new company formation rate proceeding about 25 percent slower than the dismal statewide rate. About 3,400 new companies are formed in the region each year, half of where we would be if we reached the national average. 
<P> 
It doesn't help that many native western Pennsylvanians in the prime entrepreneurial age group of 25 to 34 have relocated to places like northern Virginia, Boston and Cleveland. Only 15 percent of our population is in the prime entrepreneurial age range, compared to other regions that typically have over 20 percent of their population in that age group. Perhaps The Enterprise Corporation of Pittsburgh said it best in its 1994 report: "Our acorns are on some other region's oak trees or are already sprouting somewhere else."
<P>
Ridge's agenda, as he points out in the interview with ER, is geared in part toward convincing existing Pennsylvania businesses to expand here instead of looking elsewhere. When that happens, jobs will be here and so will the young, talented individuals who will drive our economy in the future when they form their own entrepreneurships. 
<P> 
In the short term, up next on Ridge's agenda is an issue that is crucial to increasing the rate of small business creation: workers' compensation. Don't expect a big bang, but expect some progress that will favor business. With-out reform, Ridge knows more and more businesses will set up shop across the Ohio border. That's not the kind of job growth he wants or seeks. 
<P>
Ridge has a solid plan. What he needs is some time to see it through. In the meantime, the headlines probably won't trum-pet sudden job growth. But remember, that doesn't mean that job growth is not occurring.
<P>

<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
