<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <FONT SIZE=+2><B><fill></B></FONT SIZE><br><i><b>By Antonia L. Scarlate<fill></b></i>
<HR>
<h2>Workers' Comp Reform: Be Careful of What You Wish For</h2>Employers throughout the Commonwealth are raising their voices in unison, pleading for workers' compensation reform. Insistence on reform, however, is where the unison stops. Each employer wants to change his or her own unique perception of the problem. <P> In stressing the need for change, employers describe anecdotal case histories and voice their anger about a system gone awry. Stories range from the employee who worked only a few days prior to claiming a work injury, to the televised footage of the individual who, while receiving workers' compensation, performed physical labor that was videotaped by "60 Minutes."<BR>While government officials and legislators listen to the drone of employer groups with one ear, they lend their other ear to constituents from the other side who detail the plight of the worker wrongfully denied medical care and wage benefits when arbitrary decisions deny coverage. <P>Like weary parents trying to mediate the arguments of cranky children, legislators find that no solution satisfies everyone's needs. Broad and far reaching reform to control and manage costs is necessary. Integrating workers' compensation programs with short- and long-term disability and healthcare coverage (24-hour coverage) seem to be logical solutions. With agreement as to the need for control, and reform of the medical portion that Act 44 of 1993 brought to workers' compensation, why is everyone still unhappy?<BR>You remember Act 44. This reform provides opportunity for true managed care, granting employers the right to contract with a PPO, HMO or CCO, and to direct care for 14 to 30 days. It codifies peer review of medical care (URO). Act 44 also enacts a statewide medical fee schedule, which, though complicated, reduces medical payments by about 35 percent. That's a measurable savings. <P>Act 44 clearly presents employers with the opportunity for radical change in the way they manage and pay for medical care. However, in order to benefit from the opportunity for a truly integrated workers' compensation managed care program, employers and carriers have to redesign their organizational structure, as well as the responsibilities of departments and persons. Redesign means change in the way some decisions are made, as well as changing who or which department makes decisions. <P>The workers' compensation system is extremely complicated. There are many stakeholders, and each stakeholder may have valid reasons for resisting change impacting their area of responsibility. When the proposed change requires giving up a known  and proven pattern of decision making, file handling and accountability in favor of complete unknown, resistance becomes more entrenched.<BR>The workers' compensation manager who undertakes the planning and staging of radical change, such as implementing a true managed care program by contracting with an HMO, PPO or CCO, is venturing into un-charted territory. Taking on the responsibility for initiating such a program would be comparable to loading four children into the family car, with no destination, road map or reservations, and heading off for a two-week vacation. Depending upon one's tolerance for uncertainty, this could sound like an exhilarating challenge, or a frightening nightmare. <P>If radical change is implemented, works well, and the outcome shows savings, then the manager is recognized as being successful and is targeted for future opportunities. <P>On the other hand, if the implementation is not well designed, if there is not top down commitment and a spirit of team work, then the attempt to implement radical change could result in fragmentation, poor morale and chaos. The manager who leads this charge will soon be preparing a resume for another position. <P>Alas, what the legislature truly accomplished with Act 44 of 1993 was comprehensive, yet compromise legislation. The ultimate irony of Act 44 is that it provides the employer or carrier with every opportunity for control, but it also places the burden of making a choice upon the employer and carrier. <P>Thus, as we look to the fall legislative session, in which further reform has been promised in regard to the indemnity portion of workers' compensation, one is reminded of the wise caution, "Be careful of what you wish for." <P> Antonia L. Scarlata is chief executive officer of Options, a Pittsburgh firm that advises employers on issues related to disability management.
<P>

<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
