<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.C.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>

<h2>Eh Mate, Like Ma New Caw?</h2><P>
So your Lexus disappeared from the parking lot of your local shopping mall? Chances are it's on its way to Australia. Many foreign countries have relaxed standards as far as titles, vehicle identification numbers and shipping records are concerned. The result:  Luxury cars stolen in America are shipped and resold in foreign countries. <P> The National Insurance Crime Bureau says Lexus, Porsche and Mercedes are in demand in Australia and the Pacific Rim. Cadillac, BMW and Lincoln Towncar are the brands of choice in the Middle East. And you can thank capitalism for opening a market for Oldsmobile, Mercedes, Jaguar and Harley-Davidson in the former Soviet bloc countries. Federal agents, prodded by insurance carriers, are doing what they can to stem the tide. Last year, they intercepted 123 stolen vehicles with an estimated cumulative value of $3.8 million at the port of Los Angeles. <P> But many other vehicles slip through. One Chicago car dealer had two 1993 Nissan Pathfinders stolen from his lot on the same day. The vehicles turned up two months later in Central America (where sport utility vehicles are in demand), each with about 3,000 miles on the odometer. <P> High-priced cars are not the only ones being stolen. The top 10 automobiles reported stolen last year were: 
<OL>
<LI>Honda Accord <LI>Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme<LI>Ford Mustang <LI>Toyota Camry <LI>Oldsmobile Royale<LI>Honda Civic <LI>Chevrolet Camaro <LI>Cadillac Deville <LI>Chevrolet Caprice <LI>Toyota Corolla</OL> <P> One other note: Don't be surprised to find your car minus the airbag. The NICB says an increasing trend has crooked autobody shops paying thieves up to $200 to steal an airbag, which is then installed in another car at the price of about $1,500.<P>
<HR>
<h2>Music to Their Ears</h2>When the curtain rises on the Pittsburgh Symphony's centennial season this month, audiences will get their first glimpse of the $6.5 million facelift that Heinz Hall has undergone especially for the event. <P>"These changes have been on the table for at least 10 years," says Gideon Toeplitz, managing director of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra. "When the Benedum opened in 1987, the other groups that had resided in Heinz Hall were no longer performing here. That gave us an opportunity to make this much more of a concert hall. It was designed in the late '60s to be a multi- purpose hall." <P> Toeplitz says that audiences will hardly see the changes. The changes included a completely new shell of six-inch thick wood, which surrounds the stage and projects sound. New risers for the orchestra were also constructed to allow the audience to better see and hear individual symphony members, and help them better hear each other, enhancing play. Small changes in the hall were made too -- the arches at the back of the hall were enclosed, lessening the space in the hall for the sound to travel and creating a buffer zone between the hall and the street. <P>"About three or four years ago, we invited five acoustical experts in. There was no disagreement on the problem, but we got five different solutions," says Toeplitz, who has been with the symphony for eight years. It was acoustical architect Larry Kirkegaard, of Downer's Grove, Ill., whose design was finally approved. "He had the most practical solution. He talked to everyone [symphony members, directors, audience] before he made recommendations. That's very wise. People feel part of the process."<P>
<HR>
<h2>Build It and They Will Come</h2>So you want a baseball-only stadium in Pittsburgh? You can build one that will bear a strong resemblance to Forbes Field in your game room. It won't require a bond issue either, just $19.95. <P>Forbes Field -- Build-It-Yourself was created by Len Martin, president of Oakmont-based Point Four Ltd. The heavy-stock paper model is the second developed by Martin, who earlier marketed a paper model for Boston's venerable Fenway Park. <P>Assembly is required. The stadium actually is shipped in the form of a book, a full-color oversized paperback containing 215 pieces with easy-to-follow directions. Also included is a 28-page history of Forbes Field complete with 28 never-before-published color photographs. <P> Point Four Ltd., established in 1983, is an advertising agency that specializes in graphic design and technical illustration for industrial, engineering, architectural, transportation and high tech companies. <P>Forbes Field -- Build-It-Yourself is distributed by Publishers Distribution Service.  Order your own by calling (800) 345-0096 or fax (800) 950-9793. 
<P>
<HR>
<h2>Renaissance for the PRSA Awards</h2>None of the region's public relations firms won a single Renaissance Award this year. That's because there were no Renaissance Awards this year. <P>The Pittsburgh Chapter of the Public Relations Society of America is changing the timing and format of the annual awards, which honor the best PR campaigns. Instead of being held in the fall, the awards have been moved to spring and eventually will reflect work from the previous calendar year. This year's competition will include work done during both 1994 and 1995, with the awards themselves taking place March 28, 1996, at the Twentieth Century Club in Oakland. <P> Executive Report will continue as a sponsor and help pay tribute to two of the year's top communications professionals with the Renaissance Communicator of the Year and the CEO Communicator of the Year awards. <P><DL>
<LI>
 ER also will sponsor a PRSA professional development symposium that will be held in weekly sessions during October. Patterned after the renowned Harvard Business School case history symposiums, three professionals will describe projects they worked on related to the week's theme. A moderator from ER will lead a question and answer session at the end of each case history presentation. 
</DL>The four programs, each held at Point Park College on a Tuesday morning, will cover crisis communications,  Oct. 10, 7:30 a.m.; marketing communications, Oct. 17, 7:30 a.m.; corporate communications, Oct. 24, 7:30 a.m., and new horizons in the PR industry, Oct. 31, 7:30 a.m.<P>
<HR>
<h2>Cellular Blues</h2>
Anyone who has ever talked on a cellular telephone in western Pennsylvania knows the routine: You drive into a valley, then that cracking noise starts. The voice on the other end says, "You are starting to break up." Click. <P>Western Pennsylvania is a cellular phone nightmare. <P>The Illinois Superconductor Corporation, with the help of AT&T, may answer the call. The companies are developing SpectrumMaster, the first major product line of radio frequency filters for cellular telephones. By replacing the thin-film superconductors with thick-film, high-temperature superconductors, ISCO has found ways to enhance two-way signal transmission for static-free calling as well as to expand call-carrying capacity of cellular systems. <P>More than 20 million Americans use cellular telephones, with an average of 9,500 new subscribers activating cellular telephones daily. <P>According to ISCO, researchers found improved receiver sensitivity and increased system capacity with minimal interference when the Illinois Superconductor technology was tested last year. SpectrumMaster filters have demonstrated interference rejection levels 100,000 times greater than the conventional filters currently in use in the wireless industry.<P>
<HR>
<h2>Pitching Pennsylvania's Companies</h2>
It's showtime for the region's public companies. Emerald Asset Management and the HomeState Pennsyl-vania Growth Fund, with some help from ER, are sponsoring an investment forum Sept. 21 at the Westin William Penn.<p>
Public companies in Pennsylvania will have the opportunity to tell the region's investment professionals why they should be sinking money in the respective companies. <P>Emerald has held two comparable events in Philadelphia that were lauded by those who participated. <P> Up to 24 Pennsylvania companies will participate in the program, each alloted 30 minutes for a presentation, followed by another 30 minutes for breakout discussion. <P>"This will be a first-class event," says Emerald's David Buckingham. "It's a great opportunity for investment professionals to discover or learn more about some of the Pennsylvania companies that really are doing well."<P>
<HR>
<h2>To the Point: <BR>Global Competition</h2>"What might be good for Allegheny Ludlum, and for thousands of other companies throughout America, may not be so good for a growing segment of our society who live in increasing despair and increasing rage at what is perceived as the unfairness of it all. A society that cannot create the opportunity for meaningful work at meaningful wages for all who wish to work is a society at risk, regardless of its competitiveness." <P>
<B>-- Richard P. Simmons, chairman, Allegheny Ludlum Corp., in a speech at the Chautauqua Institution</B><BR>
 
<I><B>Chronicles edited by Susan Steranchak</B></I>

