<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ED.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<P align=center><FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>EXECUTIVE DINER</I></B></FONT>
<HR>  
<P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Sunny Side Up</B></FONT><BR>
<P align=center><B><font size = +1>Kaya Brings Caribbean to Pittsburgh</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I></B>
<P>
Until recently, a typical day in the Strip District began at 3 o'clock in the morning, when trucks rolled in with the day's fresh produce, and ended by 3 o'clock in the afternoon, when grocers shut their shops. But a fresh crop of nighttime hot spots is bringing new life to the area -- and Kaya is the freshest on the scene just now.
<p>
Kaya is a long, narrow, hip restaurant, anthropological in theme, stark yet warm, with primitive art and hieroglyphic graphics. Iron tables and railings contemporize the look; bar stools dressed like palm trees lighten it. Lilting music fills the air. 
<p>
The menu centers around tropas - small, appetizer-size dishes created with such delicacies as conch, quinoa, boniato and plantains - liberally sprinkled with peppers of all sorts - scotch bonnets, chipotle and poblano, to name a few. Never fear, a glossary is provided at the back of the menu. 
<P> 
The grilled pineapple quesadilla with black beans and chihuahua cheese was tart and savory, with melted cheese and a distinct cilantro flavor. The conch (giant sea snail, like the one you hear the sea in) fritters were a little bland, and without much conch, but a mango-tomatillo salsa spiced them up. The yuca (a root vegetable) fries were really nice, not too greasy and served with a chipotle alioli sauce that gently nipped us right back. The jerk chicken wings, refreshingly spicy, lie in a cooling bed of cilantro sauce. 
<P> 
The quinoa salad was also good -- a pile of mixed greens topped with peppers, quinoa (a nutty Incan grain) and scallions. Its lime cilantro vinaigrette was tasty, but abundant. The Kaya salad combines the same greens and dressing, but is simply garnished with pepitas, crisply toasted pumpkin seeds which are a work of art. 
<P> 
The tropas are definitely the most interesting and consistent items on the menu, which changed during the time we were researching the establishment. The paella, which varies daily, was a little dry, and without much meat or seafood. The mako shark brochettes were dry and unappealing, and didn't make it to the new roster. Owners Tom Barron and Juno Yoon say an initial, self-imposed dictum to keep menu items under $10 made it hard to achieve quality in items. The new menu upscales prices, but not dramatically. 
<P>
On the new menu, the sauteed shrimp with rum, ginger and coconut milk on a bed of yellow rice was piquant, flavorful, lifting the level of cooking up a notch from previous visits. The grilled pork calypso was first splashed with a guava BBQ sauce, then grilled crispy outside, tender inside, but not as exotic in taste as we expected. The mashed plantains needed spiced up with the Pickapeppa sauce every table boasts. (Try the relish, too.) I thought the greens a little bitter, but they seemed to vary by visit. 
<P>
Desserts here are wonderful, though the coffee was disappointingly terrible. Our favorite was a coconut chocolate brownie, baked with a hint of ginger, and topped with coconut ice cream handmade by Dave and Andy's. The guava cheesecake was perfectly textured, and not too sweet, on a cookie crust. The tart changes -- ours was key lime, tart indeed, balanced and light, with a moist graham cracker crust. A chocolate and banana bread pudding, substitute for the rice pudding on the menu, was too strongly flavored, and unevenly heated. 
<P>
If you'd like a beverage, you're in luck. There are 18 beers on tap, and 71 bottled microbrews and Belgian beers. There are also specialty drinks like the Lava Lover (coconut milk, coconut rum, pineapple juice and grenadine) and the Banana Reefna (creme de banana, light rum and pineapple juice). The wine list, though short, has been recently reengineered to compliment the food and shows real promise. 
<P>
The food here is still evolving, but the other elements of Kaya -- atmosphere, music, menu, drink, people and economical prices -- are there. Kaya is in, so the place pulls a crowd most nights of the week. All ages seem to enjoy it, but the complexion becomes younger, and the music louder, as the night wears on. Irie!
<p>
<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Kaya<BR>
2000 Smallman Street<BR>
Pittsburgh, 261-6565<P>
Sun-Thurs.: 11:00AM-10:00PM (kitchen)<BR>
Fri. & Sat.: 11:00AM-12:00PM (kitchen)<BR>
Bar open 'til 2:00AM every night<P>
Tropas, soups and salads; $2.50-5.95<BR>
Entrees: $8.95-13.95</B></FONT><P>

