<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.PMN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<P align = center><FONT SIZE = +2><B>PEOPLE MAKING NEWS</FONT></B><br>
<B><I>TOM BARON & JUNO YOON</I></B><P>
<HR>
<B>NAME: Juno Yoon <P>AGE: 31<P>PERSONAL: Single, lives in Pittsburgh<P>EDUCATION: B.S., Anthropology, <BR>SUNY/Stonybrook, 1986<P>LAST VACATION: Skiing in Colorado last February<P><HR>NAME: Tom Baron <P>AGE: 30<P>PERSONAL: Married with children: wife Amy, <BR>children Max, 3 and Eli, 1, and newborn Charlie.<BR>Lives in Pittsburgh<P>EDUCATION: B.S., History/Economics, <BR>University of Michigan, 1987<P>LAST VACATION<BR>Grandfather's 90th birthday in Connecticut last June</B>
<P>
They call themselves Big Burrito Inc., but they might just as well answer to the Mad Mexican Magi, the Barons of Beer or the Emperors of Expansion. The two proprietors of Mad Mex, Kaya and a soon-to-be opened Mediterranean restaurant in Shady Side, are tops when it comes to creating cuisine, menus and environments that Pittsburghers find innovative and just plain fun. In October 1993 they opened the first Mad Mex in Oakland with $90,000 (can you say charge it?) and no chef --  on a wing and a fajita, so to speak. In contrast, their new restaurant, opening in October, is opening on the wing of a 747 -- at a cost of $500,000. It has it's own sommelier. What's next: the Concorde? Yep. They plan to give Mad Mex to the  world, in the form of international   franchises. Executive Report's Lydia Strohl talked to them at Kaya, their new Strip District restaurant. 
<P> 
<B>Executive Report: How did your partnership start? 
<P> 
Big Burrito: </B>We've been best friends since high school at the Bronx High School of Science in New York. <P> After college we went out to San Francisco and lived there for a few months. I [Juno] guess my mom was kind of pissed off that I wasn't in New York, so she bought a restaurant from a friend of hers, a coffee shop on Third Avenue. She called me and said she needed someone to run it. That was in 1987. 
<P>
<B>ER: Why did she think you could run it? 
<P> 
BB:</B> I don't think she had a clue. Someone had to run it. After being there a few months we realized we were up against a wall. Undercapitalized, rent ridiculously high, bad setup, equipment all failing and the location was not ideal. It was a commercial area, with no nighttime business. It wasn't like we weren't busy, we were packed for lunch. But with that rent, we just couldn't cover our costs. 
<P> 
<B>ER: So what brought you to Pittsburgh? 
<P>
BB: </B>My [Tom] sister got engaged to a man from Pittsburgh. I went out to visit and got involved in a business venture called "Wheel Deliver," in 1989. I did that for several years, then I saw the opportunity to get a space, and wanted to do a Mexican restaurant because no one was doing anything cool or fun. I called up Juno to see if he wanted to get it started, correctly this time. He came, checked out the scene, agreed with me and we started Mad Mex, on our credit cards and some borrowed money, as cheaply as we could. 
<P>
<B>ER: What was the capital investment in Mad Mex?
<P> 
BB: </B>About $90,000. We did a lot of work ourselves, sweat equity. Everything we started with broke, so we more than doubled our investment the first year. We were lucky, we had positive cash flow from the beginning. We sunk all the money back into the business. 
<P>
<B>ER: Mad Mex took off fast -- was it just that there was a hole in the  market? 
<P> 
BB: </B>Absolutely. Coming from New York and California, where there's a Mexican restaurant on almost every block, and seeing Chi-Chi's voted best Mexican restaurant here kind of tells you something. From the start though, we wanted to expand it. It was meant to be a prototype, a model of things to come, so we did unique menus, unique beer lists, ambiance. We had a unique theme by combining California Mexican food, relatively healthy Mexican food, with strictly micro-brewed and Belgian beers. 
<P>
<B>ER: The types of beer available when you started the restaurant, though, were relatively limited, and Pennsylvania's alcohol laws restrictive. How did you manage to make this part of your concept work? 
<P>
BB: </B>Everyone told us that you couldn't do that here, but we ignored it. I [Juno) called up people from Brooklyn and Sierra Nevada -- it first came in through Allentown, because you can't bring it in from out of state, but you can ship it from one part of the state to another. Since we've developed the market, the beer distributors here all sell it. We were the first to have microbrewed beers. 
<P> 
The beer companies have to be registered with the state. It's not a big deal, they just have to pay taxes. We started out with 35 to 40 brews, and now we're up to 95 to 100. In Oakland, we only had six drafts put in; since then, in the North Hills, we put in 20 drafts, and here at Kaya we have 18. And there are still a lot of microbrews out there we can't get, because they're not registered with the state. 
<P>
<B>ER: When did you open Mad Mex in the North Hills? 
<P>
BB: </B>November 3, 1994, one year afterwards. Then Kaya opened April 6, this spring. From day one, it's just been incredible. All our restaurants really, from the beginning, have taken off. It seems there is definitely a void we're filling. 
<P>
<B>ER: From where did the concept for Kaya come? 
<P>
BB: </B>We were originally going to do a tropical restaurant, kind of a "hot spot" of the world, then we narrowed it down to the Caribbean. We liked the idea of tapas, which is a Spanish dish, you know, the small, little entrees. So our chef created tropas, which are tropical tapas, and we combined that with our entrees. We brought in a chef from D.C. and sent him to Florida, where there are a lot of restaurants that serve this food, and he came up with the menu. About 50 percent of our menu is vegetarian, and they are unique flavors -- no one else is doing it. Which makes it difficult actually, because there was just not that much available. We're the only purchasers of a bunch of the stuff that we buy. The prices have come down somewhat since we've been creating a market, too. But it was very difficult -- things that cost a dime in Florida cost a dollar here. 
<P>
Our menu's very reasonable, but you'd be surprised how many people think the prices are high, because it's Pittsburgh. They don't realize that if you were in any other metropolitan area it would be twice the price. We started out trying to keep everything under $10, but now we're planning to upscale a few of the items: We tried to do a paella inexpensively, but realized you just can't do the paella people want inexpensively. 
<P>
I [Juno] think there was a market for this kind of food, because we do get a lot of regulars. But we are educating people, too. We're doing great numbers and it's odd, because the Strip traditionally has been dead on a Sunday, Monday or Tuesday night, even Wednesday, except for Metropol. But we get a crowd every night. So we're definitely bringing people to the area. 
<P> 
We're also bringing a new look to a restaurant. There aren't too many restaurants in town that devote as much to the design features that are here. We care about the details. The people who do our graphics [Wall-to-Wall] do a great job. We work with an architect, Riva Sloane, out of New York City, who went to high school with us. She's designed all three restaurants. 
<P>
We haven't done a lot of advertising for Kaya, it's mostly been word of mouth. We've been doing a lot of other things though. Consistency is always a problem the first couple months. We're trying to see what we should do with the menu, we'd like to expand it. People come in here and they've tried everything we have. We've instituted a lunch menu with a lot lower prices, a lot more sandwiches. Dinner will be expanded, and I don't think we'll have a problem selling specials for $10 to $14, as long as it's great food and a great value. 
<P>
<B>ER:  And your next venture? 
<P> 
BB: </B>Mediterranean food and wines, 226 South Highland, Shadyside. We'll have about 20 bottles of wine available by the glass, it will be a wine bar. A gentleman named Brian Bennett will be our general manager; he worked at Gateway Wine, and spent time working for the wineries in Sonoma and Napa counties, he's incredibly knowledgeable.  It will be opening up sometime in mid-October. We're totally redoing the whole thing. 
<P> 
<B>ER: How has your investment in starting a restaurant increased? How much are you putting in this one? 
<P>
BB: </B>Too much. Our budget for this one is $5 million. Kaya was in that price range as well. The next one's bigger, though. It seats about 75 people, then there's an outdoor cafe that holds about 45 people. Then a downstairs that will be an upscale bar, a lounge. It will be a separate look, it won't be a heavy eating establishment. 
<P>
<B>ER: Will you present live music, as at Mad Mex in the North Hills? 
<P> 
BB: </B>No, we'll probably just get the best stereo system we can. Actually, we just stopped the bands there -- we were getting the crowds, but they weren't spending any money. It wasn't the right kind of crowd. If we find a space that's appropriate in this part of town I think we'll do it -- the North Hills just isn't as progressive or artsy. 
<P>
<B>ER: How are you two adjusting to living in Pittsburgh?
<P>
Tom:</B> Me? I have a family. I'm doing the things you're supposed to do in Pittsburgh. It takes a few years. 
<P>
<B>Juno: </B>I guess I'm still doing the things I would do in New York. Just being wild and a little irresponsible sometimes. But I'm adjusting. I actually think this city has a lot of potential. At the beginning I was somewhat homesick, but I'm a lot more comfortable. I guess I need to do the Pittsburgh thing, find a wife, then maybe I'll slow down. 
<P>
<B>Tom:</B> Somebody has to be wild, to give us the concepts. We have to stay in touch, because that's a market. It's a relatively old town, population wise, but we're actually doing stuff for a younger crowd. But it's really all over the board. People seem to know when to come. The later it gets, the younger it gets. There's a dinner hour, then later at night, we play the music a little louder, and it gets a little more funky. 
<P> 
<B>ER: In a town like this, where such a strong chain restaurant mentality exists, is it a drawback to name this restaurant [Kaya] different from Mad Mex? 
<P>
BB:</B> People know our reputation, probably more so in the East End. But we're going to get a crowd as soon as we open up something new. People realize we are doing something new. We just have to give them a good product when they walk in the door. 
<P> 
After this Mediterranean restaurant, and a couple of little projects, we're concentrating a lot on expanding Mad Mex. We're going to be starting to franchise Mad Mex this summer. We want eventually to be international with Mad Mex. It has an easy formula for replicating itself. I think we'll be outside the Pittsburgh area by next year, Philadelphia, Columbus maybe, going out in concentric circles, staying away from the major cities. 
<P>
<B>ER: How would you rate the employee pool in Pittsburgh? 
<P>
BB:</B> The good thing about Kaya is that we've attracted educated, quality kitchen people. They weren't as attracted to Mad Mex by itself, until they saw we were doing other things.
<P>
At the front of the house, it's definitely dismal compared to other towns. The restaurants that we are trying to create just aren't here. It's a high energy. The restaurants here, some have really good food, but that's pretty much what they've concentrated on. There's much more beyond that. 
<P>
<B>ER: How do you guys split up responsibilities? 
<P>
BB:</B> Good question. We're still working on that. I [Juno] try to take the daily operation and I do all the beer, that's a big job. Tom is basically in the office.  As we grow, we're bringing in a lot of highly qualified people to help us. That's why we're trying to grow so fast, to attract high quality people that we really like. The key's always to hire people that have more knowledge than we do, and can do the job better than us. There are a lot of people out there that fulfill that requirement. People that take their position so seriously that they get everything right. It seems like we're making less mistakes with each restaurant we open up. It's actually getting easier. Getting money together to open a restaurant is the most difficult. 
<P>
<B>ER: How have you raised the capital to start these other ventures? 
<P>
BB:</B> We have two investors from Indiana, Pa., that we brought in after the first restaurant. We're trying to grow with the same group of people, and make the money we have now go as far as it can. Our investors aren't Bank of New York or anything like that, but they're taking us to the level we want to be. Similar to us, they've been in business together a long time. 
<P>
<B>ER: Besides money, what else is essential to make a restaurant opening smooth? 
<P>
BB:</B> That you really need a chef when you open a restaurant. We didn't have a chef when we opened Mad Mex, the second one we had a somewhat experienced chef, and here [Kaya] we have real chefs. Also the front of the house -- it's very young. The next one we are going to have a more experienced group both waiting tables, and managing. We have a good, dedicated group of employees, but the next restaurant is going to be a little more sophisticated, we're charging a little more for our food, and we have to do a really high quality job. We're really covering three different areas, Mad Mex is a low ticket item, this one is the next level up and the next one is going to be just one level above it. We really want to show people that we can handle it. 
<P>
The most famous story is opening night, Mad Mex, Day One. We didn't get our health certificate until the day we opened, we didn't have any practice runs, we just needed the money. We opened, nobody had any experience, our chef wasn't there, both people in the kitchen were crying by the end of the night..we ran out of food by 9:30 and had to close down. Everybody came. We had these ads, and people were waiting for us to open. It was nuts from day one. 
<P>
<B>ER: What's the most rewarding aspect of it all? 
<P>
BB:</B> Being successful. So many people come in here and say `You're finally doing what this town needs.' We've really opened up some eyes. The trick for us as we grow is to become a non-chain chain. We never want to lose the feeling of the first restaurant.<P>

<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
