 <HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Life </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ED.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<P align=center><FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>EXECUTIVE LIFE</I></B></FONT>
<HR>
<P align=center><font size=+2><B> Business is Blooming</B></font>
<P>
<B><P align=center>Cigars Are Cool, and the Demand is Throwing the Industry Into a Tizzy</B><BR>
<B><I>By Lydia Strohl</B></I>
<P>
One summer Friday in July, Bonnie Smola, a unit manager in the derivative settlement area at Mellon Bank, took a long lunch. Having taken advantage of dress down day (a Mellon tradition) to wear jeans tucked into black leather boots, she headed her gleaming silver and black Harley-Davidson motorcycle for Bloom Cigars, on 12th Street in the South Side of Pittsburgh. 
<P> 
Inside, she finds Dr. Richard Gehl, an orthopedic doctor between rounds, leaning back in an old rolling desk chair, smoking an Avo Uvezian, and clad in his white lab coat. She settles in next to Rick Sensky, a truck driver with tattooed serpents ringing his arms. They all puff companionably, joking with shop owner Marc Adams. Customers continually pass through the shop's two small rooms, which are filled with the amber and green  second-hand furniture reminiscent of  a fraternity living room. The air is ripe with pungent cigar smoke, the walls lined with curling pictures of  customers, men (and the occasional woman) sporting stogies. The group ebbs and flows, changing faces, cigars the only constant. 
<P>
Decadent? Disgusting? Not to dedicated premium cigar smokers around the country -- whose numbers are growing up in smoke. In the past two years, demand for premium, hand-rolled cigars has increased roughly 50 percent, according to Cigar Aficionado magazine. About 2,000 cigar smokers belong to Bloom's self-styled cigar camp, officially in session Saturdays from noon to 8 p.m. Activities include conviviality, coffee and bagels, and, of course, cigars. Due in part to the 400 to 800 "campers" who pass through on an average Saturday, Adams reports a 300 percent increase in business over the past three years. That's high, but not too unusual; other retailers have reported annual increases of 50 percent in the same period. <P>Before that, business was crawling. Though prevalent at the turn of the century, from the 1920s on cigars gave way to the more convenient cigarette and were increasingly associated with overweight mobsters sporting shiny shoes. The Surgeon General's report on smoking, released in 1964, let more air out of the market -- and by the '80s, cigars had become a white hot no-no in a world increasingly spattered with "no smoking" signs. <P>And it didn't get any better -- in 1981, 101 million premium cigars were imported, according to federal statistics. By 1992, that number had slipped to 99 million. "It was a struggle," says Adams, who took over Bloom's, a family business, in 1987. 
<P> 
"The premium hand-rolled cigar market had largely stabilized in the early '80s, and the given psychology of the market was one that was happy to have their little niche and sell cigars. It was an industry that was content if a year was flat," says Gordon Mott, editor of Cigar Aficionado, which many credit with the rebound of the premium cigar market. In 1992, Marvin Shanken, publisher of the Wine Spectator, convinced some of his advertisers to put their considerable force behind his new venture, Cigar Aficionado. Suddenly, cigars were chic, associated with fast cars, beautiful men and women, $400 watches and the good life. 
<P>
"By the end of 1992, retailers were already beginning to report an upsurge in sales," Mott recalled from his New York office. "They were seeing new faces, often with the magazine in hand." While talking, he performed one of the more arduous tasks of his position, taste-testing a cigar identifiable only as "number 39." 
<P>
It is these new faces that are key to the upsurge in demand. Prior to 1992, says Mott, the average age of a cigar smoker was 45 to 65-plus. Some attribute the market increase to the large pool of baby boomers reaching an age where they appreciate a fine cigar. But Mott says magazine trade shows, known as "Big Smokes," attract a younger crowd. Not just men, but women. Adams, too, has noticed a change in his customer demographic.
<p>
"It's status, a symbol of success that we all in some way aspire to," says Adams. "Lighting up a cigar is like putting a $20 bill in your mouth and lighting it with a match." 
<P>
True, the pages of Cigar Aficionado reflect a high class demographic. But cigar smokers defy stratification, as absolutely as cigar smoking defies society's bans. Let's face it, cigar smoking is subtle rebellion, so politically incorrect it's become cool. 
<P>
Just north of Pittsburgh, friends gather each summer weekend to get out of the city. These men look nothing like the smooth, drop-dead gorgeous men gracing the pages of Cigar Aficionado  -- they probably don't own blow driers. They're fathers, sensitive men who read and bring home flowers. They eat out, sail and recycle -- hitting all the '90s stereotypes dead on. And when they get together, more likely for a Budweiser than for a glass of cognac, they kick back and light up cigars. 
<p>
Whether they are tolerated inside, and mingle, or are booted out to smoke in a huddle, their confident attitude is an intangible cord that binds them, like seventh graders sharing a secret. 
<P>
"It's the camaraderie," says Smola, 30, the Harley-Davidson-riding Mellon banker, now surveying Bloom's walk-in humidor. Shelves line the walls of the room, stocked with hundreds of thousands of cigars like an adult candy store. "It doesn't matter who you are --there are lawyers, doctors, jitney drivers -- nobody's different, because there is this communal bond. We get into very interesting conversations because of the diverse backgrounds." 
<P>
The society is a big part of it. Across the country, the popularity (and the pockets) of cigar smokers have cajoled formerly forbidding restaurants to open their doors for cigar dinners and other events. Cigar clubs, most much posher than Bloom's, are also on the rise. The LeMont Cigar and Spirit Society was formed in June, and charges a membership fee of $200 per year. The club has six dinners each year at the Mt. Washington restaurant, for which members pay $125, and non-members $160. The Rivers Club has just formed the Golden Leaf Society, with a $250 or $50 initiation, and an annual fee of $50 in addition to the Rivers Club regular membership fees. Seventy smokers attended their first meeting in April. 
<P>
The demand produced by this incredible growth has the cigar industry reeling. From cigar manufacturers on down to the South Side shop, business is affected: A part of that 50 percent increase in demand reported by Cigar Aficionado is an estimated 20 to 25 million cigar backorder. 
<P>
"We have millions of dollars on backorder. But the biggest volume is in the mass market [machine-made cigars] -- the high-grade market is $100 million to $200 million, tiny   compared to the $2.3 billion whole," says Sherwin Seltzer, vice president      of marketing and sales for Villazon, which manufactures Hoyo de Monterey and Punch, among others. Villazon has two plants in Honduras, with 1,000 employees, and a plant in Tampa which manufactures machine-made cigars and employs 400. "There are basically five companies that manufacture high grade cigars, and they are all having the same problems."
<p>
But they all, he adds, have increased sales by 20 to 30 percent over the last three years. 
<P>
So what's the problem? Tobacco for premium cigars, which Villazon gets from the Caribbean, Honduras, the Dominican Republic and Con-necticut, must age two years. Companies order based on future projections -- and three years ago, no one had a clue the demand would increase like this. Add to that a work force of highly trained artisans, many of whom apprentice for years to hand-roll cigars, and the reasons for the bottleneck become clear. Results of the excessive demand are reflected in price increases: according to Seltzer, Villazon has instituted two 5- to 7-percent increases so far this year because tobacco, previously $30 to 40 per pound, has increased $10. vBut even that hasn't slowed demand. 
<P>
"Every cigar maker is selling everything he makes," says Mott. "And how tough can that be? But in some ways it compromises quality because they've used tobacco before it's ready just to turn them out. It will be 1996 or 1997 before the decision to increase production begins to alleviate the shortfall." 
<P>
Will the cigar's popularity last that long? I recounted this tale to my father, a businessman manipulated by his own health into swearing off cigars. "Seven years," he said, shaking his head sagely. <P>"Until they peak?" I asked. I had been hoping for his forecast. 
<P>
"No," he said, "Until I retire. Then I can smoke them." 
<P> 
Looks like the market's in fine shape for a good while yet.
<p>
<hr>
