<HEAD>
<TITLE> ERIndex </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a><P>
<HR>
<H2>Amid Talk Of Sale, Black Box Still Looking Strong</H2>


Is Black Box Corp. destined to be sold? Neither the company nor Odyssey Partners are doing much talking, but events in July seem to indicate Black Box is on the block. <P> Black Box stock jumped over three points, then gave back much of the gain. This occurred over the summer as Odyssey, the New York-based leveraged buyout firm that controls Black Box, withdrew a secondary offering of half its stake in Black Box, then reoffered the stock. <P> Black Box just reported record first quarter results in marking the 11th consecutive quarter of double-digit revenue growth since going public. Black Box is experiencing relatively strong growth in the U.S. following management-led initiatives to revive  its domestic operations. Most impressively, average gross margins are around 54 percent. <P>The list of potential buyers for Black Box is long, for good reason. Black Box possesses an extremely attractive franchise, both in the United States and internationally. Its catalog is famous among information systems managers, and the company may prove to be resistant to an economic downturn. <P>Besides Odyssey, which has already made a bundle on Black Box, the company's two top officers also stand to make millions if it is sold. Jeffery M. Boetticher, president and CEO, and Frederick C. Young, its chief financial officer, have lucrative change of control agreements in their contracts. The agreement would pay each man three times the average of their annual total compensation for the prior two years. Additionally, both men would see all their options vest immediately. <P> 

<H2>Around the ER Index</h2> 
The ER Index continues to outperform the S&P 500 for the second consecutive month, posting a gain of 8.4 percent vs. the S&P 500's 5.39 percent gain, for the four weeks ended July 7. Since its inception, the 25-stock ER Index has climbed 21.8 percent compared with the S&P's 20.6 percent, with eight stocks posting gains of 15 percent or greater and only two stocks reporting modestly negative returns. 
<UL>
<LI> While technology stocks are still popular, cyclicals seem to be coming back in favor in recent months. Alcoa posted a      25 percent gain in the month as       the company continues to reap the benefits of higher prices  for beverage can, sheet and fabricated aluminum products. Alcoa reported an in-crease in second quarter net income of 383 percent to $219.4 million or $1.23 per share vs. $45.4 million or 25 cents per share, exceeding Wall Street's expectations of $1.17 per share.
<LI>Kennametal shares jumped 23 percent in the month to 30 7/8 as analysts began to raise expectations about the strength of the company's markets. Kennametal is the leading carbide cutting tool maker in the U.S., with a 35 percent market share. 
<LI>Although the cyclicals led the index this month, it's difficult to overlook II-VI Inc. Pronounced "two-six," II-VI is a new addition to the ER Index this month, replacing Legent Corp., which was acquired by Computer Associates. Saxonburg-based II-VI designs, manufactures and markets optical and electro-optical components for infrared devices used in high power industrial lasers and military sensing systems. Since adding II-VI to the index last month, it has appreciated 15.6 percent. Since August 15 of last year, the company has appreciated a whopping 573 percent, rocketing from 4 1/8 on Aug. 15, 1994 to 27 1/4 on July 7, 1995. 
<LI>Thomas H. Lee Co., General Nutrition Co.'s largest institutional investor announced plans to sell approximately 10 million shares in a public offering which equates to more that half of Lee's stake in the company. Since May 26, officers and people connected with GNC also have filed to sell 246,500 shares. Edwin Kozlowski, General Nutrition's chief financial officer, declined to comment on the selling when asked by Bloomberg Business News. On July 7, GNC stated that it expects earnings for the second quarter ended July 22 to exceed analysts' expectations of 32 cents due to stronger than anticipated sales. GNC stock continues to perform extremely well, rising 14.7 percent in the month to 38 1/8. <P> 
</UL>
Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research for Emerald Asset Management, tracks the ER Index, which is composed of 25 public companies in greater Pittsburgh.<BR>
