<HEAD>
<TITLE> Eye On Harrisburg </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ED.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<P align=center><FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>EYE ON HARRISBURGH</I></B></FONT>
<HR>  
<P align=center><FONT SIZE=+2><B>With GOP in Control, Business Must Get All It Can Right Now</B></FONT><BR>

<B><I>By Lydia Strohl</I></B>
<P>
Business leaders say the pro-business actions of the Republican-controlled statehouse are a step toward accomplishing reforms long sought but long unfulfilled. 
<P> 
Now, the state's business leaders want to keep that momentum rolling when lawmakers return to the Capitol this month. The legislators will be met with a wish list from business interests who are eager to continue the work begun in the first six months of Gov. Tom Ridge's administration. 
<P> 
The inauguration of the Republican Ridge in January -- teamed with a GOP majority in the House and Senate and a Republican Congress in Washington -- set in motion a number of changes Pennsylvania business has sought for years. Tax breaks led the list of improvements, totaling more than $200 million and energized by an accelerated cut in the much-bemoaned corporate net income tax. 
<P> 
A new outlook for state agencies, heralded by the governor as "user-friendly," is becoming a hallmark of his administration. From a business standpoint, the Department of Environmental Resources went from whipping boy to poster child, showing off Ridge's determination to make changes in structure and attitude. The department was split in July, separating the operations of parks and forests from a new environmental enforcement agency with a mission to help businesses comply with regulations, rather than seek out violators from the start. 
<P>
The General Assembly also passed a package of bills setting new standards for the cleanup and reuse of abandoned, polluted industrial sites across the state. 
<P>
"It's a good first start," says Fred Sembach, vice president for government affairs at the Pennsylvania Chamber of Business and Industry. 
<P>
"Our members mention three areas: taxes, regulatory reform and workplace issues," Sembach says. "In the first six months, we've seen action on each of those." 
<P>
Further reform of environmental policy is on the wish list of the chamber, which represents the interests of 4,400 Pennsylvania companies, from Fortune 500 to small business. The chamber's Business Agenda for Change highlights the environment, seeking improved efficiency in the regulatory process, including consistency between state and federal rules and quicker response from state regulators. 
<P>
The chamber also would like to see the state government continue to reduce business taxes, reform workers' compensation policies, work for cost containment in healthcare matters and simplify financing programs for capital expansion. 
<P>
Sembach says he anticipates workers' compensation being the big issue before lawmakers this fall, and Ridge has promised to push from his end. Because the state's current system is 100 percent employer financed, Sembach says, businesses want to reduce those costs. But any changes that come will be hard-won because other constituencies -- from labor to physicians to insurance carriers -- have their own interests to protect. 
<P> 
Another dominant group, the Pennsylvania Manufacturers Associa-tion, portrays Ridge's first budget as one with a meaning running much deeper than just dollars and cents. 
<P>
"Combining the tax breaks with a restrained 2 percent increase in public spending can't help but spur economic growth," PMA Chairman Frederick W. Anton III says. 
<P>
 Like others, the PMA endorsed Ridge's budget as a positive step, at the same time emphasizing that work remains to be done before Pennsylv-ania is on even footing with other states. "We're confident we can work with Gov. Ridge to win additional business reforms," Anton says. 
<P> 
Most importantly, business groups know the time for more reform is now. 
<P>
A governor sympathetic to the interests of business, working with a General Assembly dominated by his own party and falling in line with many of his views, is a dream combination. 
<P> 
But just as quickly as the GOP came into power, that power could be lost and with it the one-two punch of legislative and executive branch both backing business. The state House is in Republican hands by a margin of one member, who crossed party lines after the 1994 election. The edge has held despite rumblings of defections to the Democratic side and -- barring any such switches -- will give Republicans the chance to continue to run things from the statehouse. 
<P>
At least until next year's election.<p>


<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
