<HEAD>
<TITLE> Healthbeat </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ED.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<P align=center><FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>HEALTH BEAT</I></B></FONT>
<HR>  

<P align=center><B><font size = +2>Community Hospitals are Affiliating With large Health Systems, Without Hurting Their Community Status</font><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I></B>
<P>

Aliquippa resident Ruth Wieting doesn't know much about the ensuing alliance between Aliquippa Hospital and St. Francis Health System. But she thinks it will be a good thing. 
<P> 
"I read a brief news article in the paper, but other than that, I don't have much of an idea," says Wieting, who works for Celebration, a nonprofit business organization. "It's not a merger. My understanding is that services that are not available will be made available through linkages between the two hospitals. It will expand clientele for St. Francis, so it's not just one giving to another."
<p>
The two have, in fact, just finished "courting," according to Charles Lonchar, CEO of Aliquippa Hospital. 
<P> 
"Basically, we took a year to look each other over to see whether it's beneficial for us," says Lonchar. "Now we're in the process of working through the legal documents." 
<P>
Regionally, more and more community hospitals are joining large health systems to ensure their future in an increasingly competitive arena. The news is threatening in some communities, where residents fear the loss of services that for years have been available right down the street. And so opinions like Wieting's are crucial -- for if the community hospitals engender a backlash in the community, they risk losing their greatest asset. To garner community blessing, say experts, communications is the key. v"We recognized two or three years ago that the wave of the future is affiliation with tertiary hospitals," says Gino Piroli, former chairman of Aliquippa Hospital's board of directors. "It gives us more strength and more resources. Insurers will be making decisions in the future -- they might not pick up an Aliquippa Hospital because it's not that large. But if it's part of a 1,000-bed system, rather than just 100 beds, they'll deal with you."
<p>
Among the benefits Piroli cites are expanded physician recruitment and financial strength for projects like reopening their cardiac catheterization lab and building an obstetrics ward. Piroli says that because services like this were absent, and physicians were not present in the community to refer patients to Aliquippa Hospital, the hospital had increasingly lost patients to others, including nearby Sewickley Hospital.  The alliance with St. Francis is a logical step. 

<P>
"We had good community support in this," says Piroli. "We had a welcome luncheon for St. Francis about six months ago, and all the community leaders came, county leaders, the state legislature came and gave their support -- there's no question the community wants to see us stay open and became stronger." 
<P>
Piroli says the goodwill and support was perpetuated by the board of directors. The community was informed of the decision to affiliate after it had been made, via personal contact and news media. 
<P>
"We're a close-knit community, and a close board, and we all had contacts with different people," says Piroli. <P>Other hospitals have had to go further to ensure community support, however. As soon as the South Side Hospital began to look for an affiliate, they met with community groups to get input. By not only keeping the community abreast of the situation, but involving them in the process, the hospital garnered support for their even- tual affiliation with the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center. 
<P>
"It was a two-year process, geared towards strengthening the community and being able to provide the resources that the community needs," says South Side CEO George J. Korbakes. "Many were concerned that with the merger, the activities that occur here might change. It was an uncertainty of the unknown." 
<P>
Korbakes says that the hospital's board, medical staff, and other employees were given continual updates via an internal newsletter. Meetings were regularly scheduled. But much of the communications was informal, as well. 
<P>
"A lot of our employees live in the service area, and so we always communicated through them," says Korbakes. "There was a lot of just walking down the hall and answering questions." 
<P>
These issues will continue to come up, as more and more affiliations are made in this market. 
<P>
"I believe there will only be three or four networks that emerge in the region," says Sister M. Rosita Wellinger, CEO of St. Francis Medical Center. "Allegheny General Hospital and the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center have announced they will form networks. St. Francis will be the third network." 
<P>
These are not new issues for communities, either. Twenty years ago, Jefferson Hospital was formed by the consolidation of Homestead Com-munity Hospital and St. Joseph's Hospital in the South Side. 
<P>
"The major consideration was the people in the community," says  William R. Jennings, Jefferson's CEO. "But both, in the long run, felt that without the merger they would not be able to compete. I think the thing is to be careful going in." 
<P>
Because no matter how big the networks get, Jennings says, "health care will always be delivered locally."
<p>

<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
