<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Golf Getaway</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ED.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<P align=center><FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>THE GOLF GETAWAY</I></B></FONT>
<HR>  

<P align=center><B><font size = +2>All You Need Are Clubs And a Car</font><BR>
<I>By Joe Tuscano</I></B>
<P>

You're walking off the 18th green at your favorite golf course, and suddenly you notice that your hands are sweaty and it's hard to catch your breath. 
<P> 
There is a weakness in your legs and the joints are beginning to stiffen. You look around, wondering if anyone is noticing the sweat that is trickling down your forehead or the way your upper lip is twitching. 
<P> 
There's no need for a doctor because you already know what gives you this tormenting feeling. It's not a virus, the flu or gout. 
<P>
It's the end-of-the-season golfing blues. 
<P>
Each year at this time, your golf ball is harder to find because of the leaves falling from fairway trees. The wind has a peculiar chill to it, not like the warm, sultry breezes of July that seem to make that new Titleist travel farther off the tee. Fall is approaching and that means the golf season is nearing an end. 
<P>
For many of those who love the game, winter is as cruel for its rough weather as it is for keeping golfers off the course until March. You've tried that winter golf thing, and found it to be frustrating and costly because of all the balls you sent into snowbanks. 
<P>
What you really want right now is one final shot, one memorable weekend that includes all the pampering a golf getaway can offer: good food, great golf, spa facilities, great golf, comfortable accommodations, great golf and - most important - great golf. 
<P>
Where do you turn? That's simple, because this region is packed with resorts that offer some intriguing and lavish golf adventures that can make a weekend stretch into a week, and a 36-hole day a most enjoyable experience. 
<P>
The following is a sampling of golf resorts available for that quick getaway or a vacation spot for that special foursome for next summer. 
<P>
<H2>Seven Springs </H2>
Nestled in the Allegheny Mountains, Seven Springs offers a number of golf packages for its challenging course, a 6,360-yard, par 71. 
<P>
"We have a number of packages, with the instructional ones being the most popular," says Seven Springs spokeswoman Marcy Rigby. "The brochure says the packages ended in August but if you call the resort, they will accommodate you." 
<P>
The Instructional Golf Vacation is a three-day, two-night stay that costs $439 per person per double occupancy. The charge is $600 per person for single occupancy but a roommate may be provided if available.
<p>
The package includes breakfast on both mornings, three lunches, five hours of instruction, club storage and cleaning, and use of the driving range. <P>Each golfer receives a sleeve of golf balls, a bag tag, towel, hat and golf shirt. A video tape analysis of your performance can detect any flaws. <P>As for the course, those who have played it walk away impressed. 
<P>
"There are some relatively short par threes, but they are still challenging holes," says Rick Rohac, an avid golfer who is president of Business America Pittsburgh Metro East, a business appraisal/valuation firm. 
<P>
"I thought, aesthetically, it was one of the nicer courses in the area," says Mike Bishop, vice president of Heritage Trust Co., an asset management firm in Greentree. 
<P> 
Seven Springs offers many other attractions, including fine dining, horseback riding, mountain biking, volleyball, tennis, hiking and the famous Alpine Slide ride. 
<P>
<H2>Nemacolin Woodlands </H2>
Nemacolin Woodlands opened  a Pete Dye-designed championship course, Mystic Rock. The majestic, 6,900-yard course is as demanding as you'll find in western Pennsylvania. The course is in addition to Nemacolin's popular Links Course. 
<P>
The resort offers a number of golf getaway packages for both courses. 
<P>
"Many golfers play the Links one day and upgrade [their package] to Mystic Rock the next," says Dan Swiegert, director of sales and marketing at Nemacolin Woodlands. "We have a lot of group packages. We also have reunion groups, where guys come out for the weekend to play."
<P>
Some golfers hope the Links Course does not lose its appeal as Mystic Rock draws the crowds. 
<P> 
"The Links Course is a good course in the sense that you use all your clubs," says Luigi DiIanni, an environmental engineer at USX. "You use your driver, followed by a variety of clubs. You have a wide range of shots." 
<P> 
Nemacolin Woodlands offers two basic types of packages, one which in-cludes use of the resort's condominiums and one that includes a stay at the Inn. 
<P>
The Inn package requires a two-night minimum stay and includes dinner, breakfast, overnight accommodations, unlimited greens fees, shared cart rental, club storage, a sleeve of golf balls, daily clinics and daily access to the spa areas and spa facilities. The package's weekend rate is $207 per person based on double occupancy and $305 per person, single occupancy. The weekday rates run $199 and $282. 
<P>
The condominium package in-cludes golf on the Links Course as well as all of the Inn package, except dinner. <P>"Most take the condo package because they can do their own cooking," Swiegert says. 
<P>
Nemacolin Woodlands offers the condo package at a quad price (two couples) of $112 per person. Each condo has two bedrooms and 2 1/2 baths. 
<P> 
<H2>Oglebay Park </H2>
Located in the northern panhandle of West Virginia, Oglebay Park offers golfers the option of playing three different courses.
<P>
Speidel Championship Golf Course is the jewel of the park's golf package. Designed by Robert Trent Jones, the course runs 7,000 yards over hilly terrain and was home to the West Virginia LPGA Classic for 11 years. 
<P>
Crispin Golf Course runs 5,670 yards and, because of its central location, offers a near complete view of the park. Oglebay also has a par-three course and driving range, both lighted for night use.
<P>
For $79 per person per night, a golfer can play 36 holes, 18 holes each on Speidel and Crispin, and have unlimited access to the par-three course. Accommodations at Wilson Lodge are based on double occupancy while a minimum of four individuals are required for a stay in one of the park's rustic cabins. 
<P>
Golf carts aren't included in the rates but may be rented for $24 per round. 
<P>
Oglebay Park offers a number of other attractions for the family, including fine dining, swimming, a zoo, a nature center, hiking and jogging trails, fitness center, museum, glass works, and garden center. 
<H2>Cross Creek Resort </H2>
While famous for oil, Titusville also offers one of the finest golf resorts in western Pennsylvania. 
<P>
Cross Creek combines the beauty of its forests with the challenging contours of its 27-hole championship course. The North Course is a par-70, 6,495-yard layout, while the South Course is par-36 and 3,238 yards. 
<P>
Paved cart paths wind around the course, ponds and streams. The resort's getaway packages offer something for each golfer. 
<P>
"Everything is on site here," says Cross Creek spokeswoman Tracy Hasbrouck. "We have 94 motel rooms surrounded by the 27-hole course. Along with that are the main building with the restaurant, pro shop, lounge, gift shop and several meeting and convention rooms. 
<P>
"Our packages are a great deal and are all inclusive with unlimited golf, a cart, dinners, breakfasts and overnight accommodations." 
<P>

Cross Creek's three-day, two-night package offers all that for $229 during the weekdays (Sunday through Thurs-day), $249 for offseason weekends (April 1 through May 6 and Sept. 14 through Oct. 14), and $269 for in-season weekends (May 11 through Sept. 9). 
<P> 
A four-day, three-night stay runs $319 for weekdays, $349 for offseason weekends and $369 for in-season weekends. Three- and four-day stays include dinners, breakfasts and cart rentals. Prices are based on a per-person, double occupancy stay. 
<P>
The resort has a two-day, one-night offer for $159 on weekdays only. <P>Cross Creek offers packages without golf for individuals who wish to take advantage of the area's outstanding tourist attractions. They include the Drake Well, the first oil well in the country, the OC&T Railroad, museums and the Dandy's Frontier Park. 
<P>
<H2>Hidden Valley Resort </H2>
It started 40 years ago as a small, family-run restaurant and inn and blossomed into one of the more popular resorts in Pennsylvania. 
<P> 
Spread over 2,000 acres in southeast Pennsylvania, Hidden Valley sits in the middle of 25,000 acres of scenic parklands. 
<P>
The Golf Club at Hidden Valley, a par-72, 6,579-yard layout is spread over a mountaintop, 3,000 feet above sea level. The course was selected as one of the best courses in the Mid-Atlantic by readers of Tee Time magazine. 
<P>
"Hidden Valley is just beautiful. It's very picturesque. It's pretty challenging  also," Rohac says. <P>The resort offers three packages. The first, called Top Of The Tee, includes accommodations in the lodge, one day of unlimited golf, cart and resort amenities for $79. 
<P>
The On The Green package includes accommodations at the lodge, breakfast, one bucket of range balls, one day of unlimited golf, cart rental for 18 holes, sports club and resort amenities for $87. 
<P>
Both packages are for mid-week, per person, per night and based on double occupancy. A second day may be added for $36. 
<P>
The Fairway package is a weekend package that includes one-night accommodation at the lodge, breakfast, two days of unlimited golf, cart use for 18 holes each day, overnight bag storage, sports club and resort amenities for $159. Rates per person are based on double occupancy. 
<P>
The club professionals can also set up tournaments, exhibitions, clinics and videotape your game. 
<P>
Golf club amenities include a full service pro shop, golf cart rental, club rental and storage, a practice range and a club house restaurant. 
<P>
Many different types of accommodations are available, including contemporary three- and four-bedroom townhouses located along the golf course. 
<P>
<H2>Linden Hall </H2>
The Laurel Highlands countryside serves as the setting for Linden Hall's 6,675-yard course. 
<P>
With no parallel fairways, the course covers approximately 400 acres of land and provides an exquisite view of the countryside. The resort offers three formal golf packages. The two-day program includes unlimited golf for both days, golf cart rental, dinner and overnight accommodations starting at $121. 
<P>
The three-day program offers unlimited golf for three days, golf cart rentals, dinners each evening and over-night accommodations starting at $215.
<P>
The four-day program offers unlimited golf and cart rental each day, three dinners and overnight accommodations starting at $308. 
<P>
Linden Hall also offers fine dining, swimming, tennis, fishing, a mansion tour and picnics. It can also handle banquets, receptions, meetings  and conferences. <P>
<H2>Avalon Inn </H2>
Located between Pittsburgh and Cleveland, Avalon Inn offers a perfect getaway for you and a guest. 
<P>
The Perfect Twosome package is available for double occupancy for one bed at $209.95. Double occupancy for two beds runs $219.95. The offer is valid Sunday through Thursday. 
<P>
Overnight accommodations, dinner for two, breakfast for two, one round of golf, cart rental, a towel and two sleeves of golf balls are included when you step onto the par-71, 6,224-yard Avalon South Course. There also is the Avalon Lakes course. 
<P>
"You have to be playing well to play it," says Bob Urban, a retiree from Greensburg. "You just have to hit the ball straight because there is water and sand here and there. If you hit the ball left or right, you are going to be in trouble. It's a challenging course for the average golfer." 
<P> 
The Inn also has swimming, tennis, racquetball and volleyball courts available to help entertain you.<P>
Remember, prices and packages may change without notice.<P>
<HR><B>Golf Resorts Within A Short Drive</B>
<P>AVALON INN<BR>Warren, Ohio<BR>216-856-1900
<P>
CROSS CREEK RESORT<BR>Titusville, Pa.<BR>814-827-9611
<P>
