<HEAD>
<TITLE> Your Aching Back </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ED.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<P align=center><FONT SIZE=+3><B><I>YOUR ACHING BACK</I></B></FONT>
<HR>  

<P align=center><B><font size = +2>Some Stretching Before Tee-Off may Save Back Pain Later</font><BR>
<I>By Jim Urban</I></B>
<P>

Rich Milesky golfs three to five times a week. He knows back pain and a golf swing go hand-in-hand. 
<P> 
"Your spine is not made for that movement," says Milesky, a 1-handicapper who plays at Shannopin Country Club in the North Hills.
<P>
"Everything in the golf swing is against the way your back is supposed to bend," Milesky says. "It is not a natural motion." 
<P> 
Not at all. 
<P>
A golfer stands facing the ball, then twists the upper half of his or her body almost 80 degrees before arching the back and throwing the pelvis forward as the club passes through the hitting zone. The entire time, the legs are right where the golfer planted them. 
<P>
So golfers have two options: Limit playing or take steps to alleviate the pain.The latter option sounds best to most players. 
<P>
Dr. Patrick DeMeo, an orthopedic surgeon and director of Allegheny General Hospital's Sports Medicine Institute, says back pain is a common occurrence among those who have played golf for many years. 
<P>
"As individuals age, minor degenerative changes involving the spine are to be expected," DeMeo says. "Golfers are at greater risk of developing pain because of the high mechanical stresses placed across their lower back. Fortunately, most low back pain is usually treated with specific flexibility and structural exercises." 
<P>
Back experts recommend a minimum 20 minutes of pre-round warmup exercises for various muscle groups, as well as calisthenics emphasizing stretching of the spine area near the waistline. 
<P>
For instance, physical therapist Geoff Patterson, a 1-handicapper who plays the region's amateur tournaments, stretches his major muscle groups from head to toe before even walking to the practice tee.  His program includes the leg stretch-ing common with runners and the shoulder stretching common among weightlifters. 
<P>
Patterson says he receives some odd looks from other golfers who see him with one leg propped up against a wall to stretch his hamstrings. 
<P>
"Then I get on the course and see all these golfers who are suffering from back pain and are doing nothing to take care of it," says Patterson, who works at Eagle Physical Therapy's facility in Robinson Township.
<P>
Most golfers, one of Patterson's colleagues notes, arrive at the course just minutes before their tee time and go through no warmup exercises at all. 
<P>
"These are the guys who are tying their shoes on the first tee," says William P. Rogers, another Eagle physical therapist. 
<P>
Professionals, including Jack Nicklaus, Fred Couples and Greensburg native Rocco Mediate have suffered through their share of back troubles and were able to return to the game after committing themselves to a strenuous flexibility program. Nicklaus, particularly, espouses the benefits he gained from hours of flexibility exercises. Those who regularly watch him play have noticed that Nicklaus is hitting the ball longer since he began stretching.
<P>
Some players always will have pain, even if they go through stretching. Allegheny General's DeMeo says those golfers still can play the sport. He recommends taking ibuprofen the night before playing, two the following morning and two after the round. 
<P>
Another tip: Avoid lugging around the golf bag. Instead, hire a caddie or use a cart.
<P>

<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
