<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<b><FONT SIZE=+2>The Telecommunications Boom: </FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b> Job Growth is Expected, But Will It Come?</FONT SIZE></b><br>
 <i>By Paul Kengor</i>
<hr>

When a computer glitch hit Mellon Bank in years past, Mellon programmers who were on call had to drop whatever they were doing, hightail it into the office and correct the problem. Sometimes the trouble call came at 11 p.m. as they crawled into bed. Sometimes the call came in the midst of their spouse's birthday party on a Saturday afternoon. <P> Today, the trouble calls still come, but telecommunications technology allows the programmers to plop themselves down at their home computer, access the Mellon system and remedy the problem from home with a few keystrokes. <P> "The programmers love it," says Marty Lippert, Mellon's senior vice president for information management and research. "Their spouses love it too."Mellon's use of telecommunications is an example of how the technology has changed the way most companies do business. Because of telecommunications, companies are saving time and money. The result: They are more efficient and more competitive. <P>Most of these same companies are constantly looking for new ways to leverage telecommunications technology in a manner that pays a return. The market demand for telecommunications technology and services has firms in the industry thriving. Since hundreds of these firms are located in western Pennsylvania, that means jobs for the region. v "The more dramatic part of Pittsburgh's economy is emerging in areas such as the telecommunications industry," says Tim Parks, president of the Pittsburgh High Technology Council. "I feel that we could make the southwestern Pennsylvania region the center of an info-tech revolution. You have a confluence of a number of different technologies manifesting themselves here at a  precipitous moment for this telecom revolution."That moment is now, and the timing appears to be right. 
<P> 
<font size =+2><B>Timing </B></font size> <BR>
Not too long ago, many companies balked at widespread use of telecommunications technology because of the expense involved. Prices have since declined, motivating companies like Mellon Bank to take a closer look at technology that before may have been too costly. <P>"Two years ago it would have cost us four times what it costs us today for transmission," says Mellon's Lippert, who expects the price decline to continue. <P> In Pittsburgh and Philadelphia this summer, Mellon Bank was testing video conferencing at suburban branch offices. Mellon customers seeking investment advice could sit down at a computer terminal in Mellon's Monroeville financial center and have a video conference with a counselor at one of Mellon's corporate centers downtown. It saves the customer a trip into town. <P>"We are providing better services and providing those services at more competitive costs," Lippert says. "Telecommunications technology also gives us the ability to roll out new services that before might have been cost-prohibitive." <P> Other banks, healthcare facilities, advertising agencies, law and accounting firms, small businesses and manufacturers are among many companies now using telecommunications in their business processes. <P> At the downtown law firm of Meyer, Unkovic & Scott, a recent technology upgrade now allows attorneys to communicate via computer with colleagues, clients, prospects, the court systems and vendors. <P> "It's a competitive environment for the client's business," says Jim Caliendo, administrator at the firm. "If we can cut the cost to the client by using telecommunications technology, that will make us more competitive." <P>Another law firm, Reed Smith Shaw & McClay, is experimenting with video conferencing between its numerous offices. It also communicates with clients via e-mail. <P> "Our telecommunications technology absolutely cuts costs," says Judith St. Ledger-Roty, an attorney in the firm's Washington, D.C., office. "More importantly, the client can have a document immediately instead of having to wait overnight." <P> 
<font size =+2><B>Our Telecommunications Industry </B></font size> <BR>
The state Department of Labor and Industry estimates that 2,374 high technology firms employed 84,047 people in western Pennsylvania in 1993, the most recent year for which statistics are available. Of those firms, 858, or 36 percent, were involved with information and communication technologies. These telecommunications firms employed 20,069 people. <P> The total number of 84,047 high technology employees is actually less than the 84,269 employed in this region in 1979. But don't be misled by the numbers. In 1979, 61 percent of the high technology employees worked for companies with more than 500 employees: the Westinghouses, PPGs and Alcoas of the region. In 1993, 73 percent of the region's high technology employees worked for companies with less than 500 employees. <P> "Most of those companies are young, promising and, hopefully in many cases, are growth companies," says Parks. <P> Foremost is FORE Systems, the Warrendale-based firm that designs and manufactures systems to speed the transfer of information over computer networks via asynchronous transfer mode technology. <P> FORE's story is widely known, but worth repeating. It started with four Carnegie Mellon University researchers whose sales totaled $110,000 in 1991. Now, FORE employs more than 400 people, is looking to build a headquarters and tallied $75.6 million in sales during the most recent fiscal year that ended March 31, 1995. <P>FORE now dwarfs most of the firms in the southwestern Pennsylvania telecommunications industry. Many of the firms are niche companies -- small- to medium-sized manufacturing or service-based firms employing under 100 people and looking for their own inroad into the widening telecommunications marketplace. <P> Concepts in Communication, for instance, employs 14 people in Pittsburgh along with other installers and sales associates located across the country. It has found its niche in interactive voice response, a common application in the banking and insurance industries. If you have ever called a bank that asks you to enter your banking card number, then you are using an IVR service. Concepts in Communi-cation sees the healthcare industry as its growth opportunity. <P> "One of our innovations is when a patient is discharged from a [hospital] room, the volunteer or escort -- using our technology -- can pick up a telephone, enter the patient's ID number, and inform the admitting desk that the bed is now open and alert the housekeeping supervisor that the room needs to be cleaned," says Gene Nacey, CEO of Concepts in Communication. <P> The firm has signed on 115 hospitals throughout the country, including a number locally. Concepts in Communication also signed a deal with Marriott -- which has a hospital services division that manages food, housekeeping and maintenance -- to install 180 systems over the next three years. <P> "The beauty of the product is that the telephone is universal; there's no computer-training phobia. Also, there are telephones all over a hospital, in every room -- unlike computers," Nacey says.The company also has developed a sophisticated patient tracking system that relies on telephone-based technology to monitor an individual's whereabouts throughout the hospital. <P>"The most under-utilized piece of technology in the hospital is the telephone," Nacey says. "And in most hospitals, the most progressive thing they're doing with the telephone is voice mail, and there's much more than that. The great thing about this system is that [the hospital] has already paid for the telephone installation. We're really excited. This is a niche that's wide open, and the market has been very receptive to us." <P> Other local firms are exploring another niche market: high definition television. HDTV uses higher numbers of scan lines to provide a near-film-quality picture. There are about 1,400 television stations operating in the United States, all of which broadcast using standard analog signals. By 1996, the FCC will enact requirements for all stations to convert to HDTV by 2011. Broadcast stations will have 15 years to start phasing out the existing analog format. As a result, there is now a market with all 1,400 stations for new HDTV equipment."And that's just in the U.S.," says Dave Neff, a vice president in ITS Corp.'s broadcast systems division. "We're anticipating HDTV really happening in this country in the next year or two. The rest of the world will follow. It's a substantial market. We're developing products that will allow us to compete in HDTV." ITS, in conjunction with CMU and Ben Franklin Technology Center of Western Pennsylvania, is devising a method for adapting analog transmitters to a HDTV format. <P>ITS President Bob Unetich expects the HDTV market to hit $1 billion per year. "We're trying to develop a niche business where we can focus on something that no one else does," he says. "We're not trying to be Apple or Macintosh here." <P> Others jumping on the HDTV bandwagon include Television Computer Inc., which is owned by Robert H. Thibadeau, a senior research scientist at CMU's Robotics Institute. <P> "When the digital broadcasts begin, HDTV will use no more than half the digital space available on the channel," Thibadeau says. "Fully half the channel space is available for something else. As a broadcaster, you want to be able to figure out what to do with that other half. So, we're leading the vanguard in developing content for digital TV -- for that other half."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Tapping Foreign Markets </B></font size> <BR>
Much of the growth by local telecommunications firms will hinge on how effectively they sell in foreign markets. "Firms on the equipment side can try to sell their telephone switches, data communications equipment or fiber optic cable internationally. Then there's the service itself, which requires putting the wire in place internationally," says Carnegie Mellon professor Marvin Sirbu. <P>"We're doing more than one-third of our business abroad, all over the world, but mostly in developing countries," Unetich of ITS says. "There's more privatization and less government control throughout the world. We're extremely optimistic about overseas export markets. Our wireless equipment provides a way for suppliers to bring information to people in a hurry."In China, for instance, ITS is developing distribution through a Beijing company. <P> "An employee of ours in China works with our distributor, who imports products from the U.S.," Unetich says. <P>"We supply TV transmission hardware, which is our specialty. It's how American companies like ours can succeed as a niche business," Unetich says. <P>Black Box, a Washington County-based distributor of computer and telecommunications networking products, had $165 million in revenues in 1994, with $62.1 million from non-domestic sources. <P> Jeffery M. Boetticher, president and CEO of Black Box, expects 50 percent of the company's revenues in the next three years to come from international sources, where growth opportunities exist in cellular communications. <P>"The use of cellular communications in the United Kingdom is growing by leaps and bounds," Boetticher says. "The demand for cellular in Japan is rampant. I think there's more people in Tokyo using cellular communications than anywhere, except maybe Mexico City." <P> The Future <P>The jobs will come. vAn independent study of high technology growth markets projected that 1,051 high technology jobs would be created in the region during the next 12 months. The study released in June by CorpTech ranked the region 10th nationally. CorpTech listed San Jose, Calif., No. 1 with an estimated job growth of 1,933. Southwestern Pennsylvania ranked ahead of such notables as Sunnyvale, Calif., and Austin, Texas. <P> The public seems to sense the po-tential, too, judging by the types of students enrolling at the local universities. <P> "A lot of our students are part-time students who are going back for a career change," says Martin Weiss, an associate professor of telecommunications and information science at the University of Pittsburgh. "We get quite a number of people from the major companies, such as Westinghouse, as well as a number of small consulting companies. These students recognize the shift in the economy towards telecommunications." <P>The CorpTech study did not gauge how many of the projected jobs would involve telecommunications, but those in the industry expect the number to be substantial. Use your imagination, one insider suggested. <P> "Here's what I envision within five years," says Jim Bevington, vice president of DeltaCom, a Pittsburgh-based telecommunications management firm. "At work, you'll have a PC on your desk with a headset attached to it, and a voiceboard on that PC. Your PC could have a telephone number -- a direct inward dial. If you are not there to take a call through your headset, your computer will take whatever information you need. And as video technology quickly evolves, you may also be able to get not only a message on who called but also a picture of them." <P> When that scenario becomes reality, expect many companies to spend the money to bring such equipment on-line, keeping the telecommunications industry busy. <P>"Virtually every facet of our business, commerce and every aspect of our lives is being changed by information technology," says Parks, the High Technology Council president. "From the factory floor to back offices, the incredibly growing value of information access -- on products, consumer wishes and so forth -- will be the key differentiator in business success -- between those who win or lose. <P> "It's exciting stuff," Parks says. "And it's real. This is one industry and region where you don't have to wait to see it happen; it's happening quickly.  The shift from an economy based on raw materials to one based on knowledge is happening all over the world, but it's a big contrast from what drove this region's economy 25 years ago."
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Klink: Debating Telecommunications Legislation </B></font size> <BR>
Before Congressman Ron Klink ever won his House seat, he talked on the campaign trail about securing a seat, if elected, on the House Energy and Commerce Committee. <P>"People didn't understand why," recalls Klink, who knew then that this committee, known today as the House Commerce Committee, would consider legislation regulating the telecommunications industry. <P> "I knew we would be taking up bills like [the Communications Act of 1995]," Klink, who sits on the House Commerce Committee's Telecommunications Subcommittee says. "If we don't have a representative from southwestern Pennsylvania sitting in on these negotiations, we're really going to be left behind. This legislation is so important to the future of the next five or six generations of residents of southwestern Pennsylvania that it's inconceivable." <P>Beyond the possibility of regulation that could burden telecommunications firms from the region, Klink has aggressively tackled other issues. For one, he sponsored an amendment that would require the U.S. Attorney General to report to Congress on the enforceability of current laws on the distribution of obscenity and child pornography on the Internet. <P>"I'm concerned about the proliferation of child pornography and pedophiles using the Internet in search of innocent children," Klink says. "In the 50s and 60s we worried about the guy in the park with the trenchcoat. Now those people are surfing the Internet. I've spoken to law enforcement officials who pose as sexually confused young boys [on the Internet]. Within hours there will be hundreds of responses by pedophiles talking [in] sexually explicit language. v"We're looking at what we can do legally without infringing on civil liberties," Klink says. <P>Another issue Klink is closely monitoring is foreign ownership in the telecommunications industry. <P> "You get into national security problems, such as terrorist groups -- like Hamas or Hezbollah -- gaining access to information and causing problems in this country. The White House would need to monitor this. Or let's say that you have a wealthy Middle East businessman from Iran who owns a big American media company. The Shah is in power. All of a sudden the Shah is out and the ayatollah comes in and nationalizes the company and owns a major U.S. media outlet, and can broadcast on a U.S. radio or TV station." <P> "There is no benefit to foreign ownership aside from an infusion of capital to drive up stock prices," Klink added. "A newspaper is okay. ... They can own as many newspapers as they want. Because to run a newspaper you don't need a license. A radio station is different because the frequency it's broadcast on is owned by the American taxpayers, and you need a license from the government."
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
