<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Leasing Has Its Benefits,</B></FONT></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Especially With Technology</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Patricia Berti-Sullivan</i>
<hr>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Gary Sokulski remembers the days when his purchasing decisions were driven by a simple factor: cost. Today, rapidly developing technology has added to the mix another factor -- obsolescence. Sokulski knows that a desktop computer he procures for one of the 350 attorneys in Reed Smith Shaw & McClay's six offices might be obsolete within six months. <P> If the firm owns the obsolete computer, it is stuck with it. If it has a lease that includes upgrade provisions, the firm has some options."Before, the decision to lease or buy was based only on economics," says Sokulski, director of administrative projects and services for Reed Smith. "Now, the decision goes well beyond true economics. You must look at the cost to acquire directly, how quickly the technology turns and whether you need to be on the cutting edge. Now, cost takes a back seat to obsolescence." <P> Reed Smith, like any business, knows that cutting-edge technology can help it run more efficiently, holding down costs while optimizing service to clients or customers. Perhaps the firm can use its technology to transmit some documents to a client via e-mail instead of paying a premium to have them sent overnight. That lessens the client's costs and allows the firm to become more competitive. <P>The trick is to know when to buy and when to lease office equipment, especially when dealing with technology. Businesses that make the right decision usually end up with an edge over those that do not.<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Benefits of Leasing </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Leasing, whether it be short- or long-term, gives the lessee more options than one who purchases equipment. Foremost among the benefits of leasing is the right to upgrade if new technology hits the market or if the current equipment is not capable of handling growth. More and more, companies are turning to leasing and renting equipment as a way to avoid getting stuck with the modern-day equivalent of a buggy whip. <P>The Equipment Leasing Association of America estimates that 80 percent of U.S. companies lease equipment. Businesses like the flexibility and the cost savings. Rather than deal with depreciation schedules, the lessee makes the lease payment and deducts it as a business expense. <P>The types of leases include a conventional lease, in which the user can renew the lease for a newer model when the lease expires or just return the equipment and cancel the lease. Another type is the straight financing lease, which is like renting to own. The company owns the leased equipment when the last payment of the contract is made. <P>A third type is the fair market value lease, under which both parties agree at the time the lease is drawn on a value for the equipment at which the user can opt to purchase it when the lease expires. The price is usually determined as a percentage of the total unit price, often based on how much its value has depreciated.<P> 
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Technology </B></FONT SIZE><br>
A common scenario from the past had a company buying technology, then keeping it after it was outdated because of the investment that was made. At the same time, perhaps, a competitor was using more state-of-the-art equipment that allowed it to run more efficiently and, in turn, offer its product or service at a lower price. <P>Leasing allows businesses to protect against such a scenario, according to one finance company executive. "Leasing lets you pass the risk on to the lessor," says Frederick Summers, president and chief executive officer of Vision Financial in downtown Pittsburgh. "Profits are generated by using equipment, not owning it."In some cases, it is not necessary to have state-of-the-art technology in every facet of the business. At Reed Smith, for example, computers placed in a conference room are less sophisticated than the computers at the attorneys' individual desks. The conference room computers were purchased, but the cutting-edge computers in the attorneys' offices are leased. <P> "One of the misnomers is that you should always lease computers because they go out of fashion very quickly," Sokulski says. "That may be true, but it depends -- leasing is more expensive. We try to make informed decisions."<P> 
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Cash Flow </B></FONT SIZE><br>
When worries about obsolescence don't come into play, the decision to lease or buy usually reverts back to cost. This is more common in furniture purchases. <P>If cost is high, the business may not have the capital to cover the cost upfront. Consider an expanding business that must procure desks, chairs and other office furniture for new hires. It might face the same expense as a downsizing business that is merely looking to become more efficient by replacing its existing computers.By purchasing the equipment, a business in either situation would be faced with the capital outlay upfront, or a financing arrangement that includes profit-eroding interest charges. <P> By leasing, the company saves cash and gets equipment it desires but might otherwise have been unable to afford. For that reason, leases are particularly popular among new businesses, many of which are investing their capital other ways. By leasing, the company can use the equipment to generate revenue while facing only monthly lease payments and avoiding a huge cash outlay. <P> Beyond technology, many businesses use leases to acquire office furnishings. <P>"You are not tying up cash," says Dave Sauter, senior vice president of Delta Furniture Rental & Sales. "Renting enables companies, especially small- to mid-sized companies, to afford nice-looking, ergonomically correct furniture without spending a fortune." <P>Larger companies also look to leasing. With so many corporations downsizing, many look to consultants and temporary employees to complete tasks, but they need desks, chairs and other equipment. Some rentals last from a day or two to a couple years. When the workers pack up and leave, the corporation ships the equipment or furniture back to the supplier."Corporations are prime customers for renting. They take care of short-term needs and short-term tasks," says Jim Droney Jr., president of Mount Lebanon Office Equipment Co.<P> 
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Ownership </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Many businesses still opt for ownership, which means complete control over the equipment. In the long run, buying office equipment is cheaper than leasing if there is no intention to upgrade equipment and the cash isn't needed to be invested elsewhere. Don't forget, the equipment can later be sold, recouping some of the initial investment.	
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>The Copier Choice </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Even though businesses are permitted to depreciate copiers over five years, many businesses have turned to leasing because they change copiers every three years or so. But even leases were problematic because many were long-term and did not take into account the changing needs of the business. <P>Now, copier procurement has become a science. <P>Companies pay a monthly rate based on the volume of copying and the length of time they use a machine. A chief benefit of the practice, known as copy management, is that the company can move up to a higher machine without affecting lease terms. <P>"The lease is no longer tied to an asset [the copier] and its terms can change if needs change," says Leonard Lutes, president and chief executive officer of Van Dyk Business Systems in Greentree. "It's really popular over the last two years or so." <P> Lutes says the average copier is replaced every 38 months. Companies will try to project their copying needs well into the future, but often times they over- or underestimate. "With copy management, you get the equipment you want and you can meet your needs without overbuying," Lutes says. <P>Businesses must be careful to not mistake a per-copy lease for copy management. Cost per copy is merely a lease, often without upgrade terms. <P> Lutes says companies should consider leasing a copier when it involves an investment of $5,000 or more, and it takes about 3,000 copies a month for copy management to be cost-effective.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>A Look at Leasing </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Some Benefits of Leasing:
<DL>
<LI>Many leases allow for upgrades. 
<LI>Companies that lease don't face large cash outlays common with purchasing. 
</DL> 

Some Drawbacks of Leasing: 
<DL>
<LI>Taxes are included on monthly lease payments. 
<LI>Lessors must sometimes carry extra insurance.
</DL>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
