http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0895.Update.2.html 192.204.56.67 19970115132439 text/html 13146
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 13:29:48 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:50:20 GMT
Content-length: 12969
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Mind Over Matter</B></FONT></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Compelling new evidence shows you are how you think.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By By Lydia Strohl</i>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>
"I was a walking time bomb," says Bruce J., a traveling salesman in the competitive food industry for 18 years. "My habits were just terrible. I'd eat sample food all day, then get back to my room at 9:00 or 10:00 every night and have a couple drinks." <P> Still, Bruce was surprised when, in 1992, at the age of 44, he had a heart attack. <P>  "It was all downhill after that," says Bruce, then an overweight smoker. "I was recuperating from the heart attack and found out I had cirrhosis, because the liver breaks down the heart medication." <P> Bruce has been on disability since the attack, and now says he is ready to get back on the job. His treatment? A regimen that included psychotherapy and daily doses of the anti-depressant Zoloft. <P> "I think my ticker is working pretty good," says Bruce. "I'm not dependent on pills anymore. I've turned everything around -- I'm calmer than I've ever been." <P> He hasn't had a cigarette since the heart attack and shed 70 pounds, partly due to a walking program. <P> Bruce's case is exemplary of research proving that in medical treatment, the mind matters. It's a mistake to equate attention to a patient's emotional state with the pat after a particularly painful shot -- a nice gesture that, although it makes the patient feel better, is ultimately unnecessary. Looking after patient psychology is, say advocates, the most cost-effective healthcare strategy available. But most doctors, mired in their need for scientific evidence, are still skeptical about the commonsensical notion of treating the mind to cure a physical ill. <P> "Since 1644, physicians have traditionally thought of amount of pain as directly related to amount of physical damage," says Dennis Turk, professor of anesthesiology and director of the Pain Evaluation and Treatment Institute at the University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine. "For example, the pain from an eighth-inch cut will be twice the pain from a sixteenth-inch cut. That's what all physicians learned, and that's what they still learn." <P> But Turk points out that an anesthetized patient will feel nothing from an incision that would make a conscious person screech. <P> "We interpret pain. It's a body's response, a perception," says Turk, who has been researching the role psychological factors play in this perception, and in how a patient experiences pain. "It turns out that pain is not all that related to physical pathology -- this is where the mind comes in." <P> The last 15 years have brought us light-years forward in sophisticated medical testing technology, along with which has started to come some hard data demonstrating direct linkages between the body and brain. In one study, Turk and his researchers asked subjects with chronic low back pain to identify recent instances in which their pain was the worst -- to think about who was there, what was on their mind and any situations of conflict. They hooked the subjects up to electrodes, which indicate pain by measuring muscle contractions, and asked them to relax. Then the subjects were asked to talk about the painful situations. <P> "They showed an increase [in the contractions] of 200 to 800 percent just talking about their pain," says Turk. "But the increase was only at the site of their pain. Every time they got upset, they tensed these specific muscles." <P> Turk's conclusion: Psychological factors appear to magnify existing pain. In very few cases, he says, is the pain completely without physical basis. <P> Other studies in Pittsburgh and around the world have verified the strong linkages between mind and matter. The research into these linkages has bred a new discipline called psychoneuroimmunology, or PNI. It got its start in the late 1970s when neuroscientist Karen Bulloch, then a graduate student, uncovered a direct neurological link between the brain and the immune system. <P> Researchers have since found chemicals, produced by the immune system, which feed signals back to the brain. Karl Goodkin and his colleagues at the University of Miami reported results of one study, which discovered that homosexual men infected with HIV yet displaying no symptoms of AIDS had higher levels of helper T-cells, which are infection-fighting white blood cells, when they had effective coping strategies and low levels of life stress. <P> Even though the connections between physical health and mental wellness have now been demonstrated in study after study, just exactly how they are linked continues to elude researchers. <P> "There is considerable evidence for links between stress and infectious disease, including a number of studies that have shown that patients with increased levels of stress have greater levels of upper respiratory disease," says Sheldon Cohen, professor of psychology at Carnegie Mellon University. Cohen and his team interview their subjects to evaluate stress levels, as well as measuring biological markers of stress such as levels of hormones like cortizol, epinephren and neuro-epinephren. Then they expose the subjects to an upper respiratory infection, such as the common cold virus. <P> "The evidence that's conclusive, however, is in the realm of upper respiratory disease -- and it's not yet clear what the mechanisms are. Thus far we've been unsuccessful at identifying the processes," Cohen says. He and his team are proceeding, but slowly. <P> Research in this arena is problematic, to the extent that it is difficult to control all the variables. Researchers can't, for example, pick a sample population based on psychological makeup and then give half the group AIDS. For more severe diseases, researchers must rely on patients who are already sick, which adds another whole set of variables, perhaps even depression itself.Plus, the work is expensive, and funding in this area, as in most, is getting harder to find. <P> "It's difficult to get funding for anything. But there's not a lot of focus on this area; medical research is very molecular and biology focused right now. Funding is very political, and the current biases [in Washington] are against behavioral issues in health," says Cohen, citing a House proposition to dissemble the behavioral and social science arm of the National Science Foundation. "I think that's amazing. I think it's important to understand the role of social and environmental factors in disease. These are things that can potentially be controlled at a much lower cost for the healthcare system and for the individual than the usual medical interventions." <P> It may be that these psychological treatments are more effective, as well. For 31 years, 55-year-old Jane T., a Pittsburgh educator, has been battling pain caused by fibromyalgia, a progressive syndrome of unknown origin that spasms muscles, causing pain in all four quadrants of the human body. Searching for relief from her pain, she consulted arthritis specialists, orthopedics, chiropractors, had cortizone shots, even attended chronic pain clinics. By the late 1980s she could not hold a book long enough to read it to her daughter, or move her hands well enough to play the piano. <P> Today Jane takes anti-depressants, goes to therapy and uses biofeedback, imagery and relaxation techniques taught to her by her psychologist. <P> "I am 80 percent better, and most of that has resulted from the psychotherapy," says Jane, convinced that these techniques, and the stress relief they afford her, are responsible for the turnaround. She doesn't need to know why it works -- she is convinced of the strong link between her mind and her pain. "I grind my teeth in my sleep. Is that a physical condition or a mental one, that I am so anxious that I grind my teeth in my sleep until I have TMJ?" <P> "Yes, there's a connection," says Dr. E. Carroll Curtis, medical director for occupational health programs at Harmarville Rehabilitation Centers. "How clear is it? In 1900, medicine was 1 percent science. Now, it's maybe 5 percent -- we have a long way to go. And there is still a lot of skepticism. Physicians try to be pathological machinists -- many are uncomfortable in realms that are less clear-cut." <P> Curtis is convinced that doctors are ignoring the interaction of psychological and physical factors at a tremendous cost to individuals, societies and businesses. Much of this cost shows up under the label of workers' compensation, a phrase at the top of the minds of many of Curtis' patients. <P> "The largest cost in workers' compensation is due to disability, not injury. Impairment is a medical term, but disability is a mind-set. More years of productive life are lost to Americans due to disability -- and that's sad. We enable people to be disabled. No one can get better if the benefits they are seeking are only available if they are sick. Then they begin to believe they are disabled -- and if you believe it, you get that way," Curtis says. <P> Pitt's Dennis Turk was an expert consultant to the Commission on the Evaluation of Pain for the Social Security Commission. <P> "Disability is supposed to be based solely on physical pathology, but we found little relation between medical pathology and receiving disability compensation," says Turk, "which means that the decision makers are basing their decisions on other factors." <P> After the report was finished, he asked fellow commission member Judge Paul Rosenthal what factors he used to assess the validity of a workers' comp claim. "He said that in addition to looking at the physical pathology, he looked at the person's face, and how they move, whether they were squirming in their seat," recalls Turk. <P> Rewarding for these "pain behaviors," says Turk, "leads to more maladaptive behavior."Responses from employers, family and others can also condition pain responses. Turk works with patients and their families to teach them appropriate responses. Employers can work on this too, by offering workplace programs and counseling managers on proactively rewarding employees for good work. <P> "Employers who don't treat their workers with respect are just asking for it," says Curtis, who was formerly medical director at Westinghouse Electric Corp. He believes mental health and chemical dependency programs are the most cost-effective preventive healthcare measures available. Currently, companies spend about 20 cents of every healthcare dollar on these programs. <P> But there's no way to completely destress life. So Curtis insists there must be a  shift in the way healthcare is delivered in order to balance the system. <P> "Our medical training has failed us in the arena of human concerns that go beyond the physical," says Curtis. "Primarily, an examination has become ordering tests, so we spend less time with the patient. All research says that 90 to 100 percent of the diagnosis comes from talking to the patient. In Britain there are fewer MRIs in the whole country than we have in Pittsburgh alone. They can't just order a test. But they make excellent diagnoses, and they do it on the basis of talking to patients." <P> A healthcare system that pays physicians for tests rather than time spent with patients reinforces this focus on physical pathology. But that's the answer. <P> "Think about it -- if everyone with the same diagnosis gets the same treatment, and some aren't responding, then you'd save a lot of money if you were giving people what they really need," says Turk. "We're trying to get to the point where there's a psycho-social diagnosis and a medical diagnosis, and a menu of treatment options that match each diagnosis."He stresses that though behavioral evaluations, in the form of self-reports, could be completed ahead of time and computer-scored, "there's never a way to get physicians away from having to talk to patients." <P> The question is again one of process: How can the healthcare system teach, and then motivate, physicians to talk to their patients? So what if we don't know why -- making the mind matter may be one prong in the attack against rising healthcare costs. Not to mention the fact that it could just be the cure, or aid the cure, for many people. Adding some psychological component to standard medical practices should be a no-brainer.
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
