<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2>Don't Fight Innovation in our Schools </FONT SIZE><i> By Linda A. Dickerson</i><P>
That's not the way it was when I was in school" will echo throughout the living rooms of southwestern Pennsylvania as schools once again roll out this year's innovations in teaching practices. The outcome is predictable. Over time, angry and ill-informed parents or political leaders will squelch the innovation. Status quo will return. <P> As students march in to area classrooms this September, a lucky few will confront new opportunities to expand their minds. Emerging technologies, progressive curriculum writers and entrepreneurial administrators will create innovative learning environments. Sadly, I predict that their spirited efforts will not flourish and expand. <P> Unfortunately, innovation is rarely, if ever, rewarded in today's public schools. A potent but undiscovered law of nature ultimately returns our classrooms to the way they were 20, 30, or even 50 years ago. <P>If Sir Isaac Newton were alive today, he would be able to quantify, define and name this inertial force which precludes schools from moving ahead. I will call it the rubber band effect. When you stretch schools, they always return to their original state, unchanged by the experience. <P>The forces stretching schools these days are societal pressures: the break-up of the family unit, a pervasive sense of hopelessness among disadvantaged populations of youth, exponential increases in teen pregnancies, and the emergence of a burgeoning youth underclass. The status quo represents a safety zone for schools struggling to cope with the further deterioration of our society. Under stress, the schools rely on familiar practices with predictable outcomes. <P> The forces that should be stretching and shaping our schools are globalization, teamwork, the increased complexity of workplaces, quantum advances in technology and highly diverse work environments. <P> Risk-taking is severely discouraged in public schools. Superintendents stake their careers on their ability to please a fickle public. Virtually the only sentiment that the general public seems to share about education is that habit should prevail. Most believe that chalkboards, desks in rows and textbooks are fixtures without which schools cannot function. <P>Why should schools, unlike all other institutions, be exempted from the need to change? Schools are impervious to change because the public refuses to accept innovation. The cost for this visceral opposition to change is a lost generation. <P>A sense of sameness blankets our area classrooms, dampening our young people's chance to succeed. This must stop. The public must not only accept change; they must demand it. <P>If superintendents' futures were vested in their ability to implement, not impede, change, I'd be much more optimistic about our future.
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
