http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0895.Editorial.html 192.204.56.67 19970115132505 text/html 4697
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 13:30:14 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:50:17 GMT
Content-length: 4521
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/editor.JU.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2>Our College Graduates are Burdened With Too Much Debt </FONT SIZE><i> By Jim Urban</i><P>
Our world is one that hires on  credentials. Those who possess a bachelor's degree find doors opening more easily than those who don't have a degree. That's why education does not stop at the 12th grade in this day and age. <P> But the many high school graduates moving on to college face a problem that grows more difficult with each annual tuition increase: How will they pay for their college education without facing huge loan indebtedness once they graduate? <P> The numbers are alarming:  Four years at a public university cost an average of $26,000 today. At a private school, the average four-year tab runs $66,750. <P> Don't expect those numbers to become any more manageable as time goes on. Some educators were patting themselves on the back in 1994 for holding the average price of a college education to a 6 percent increase from the year earlier. What they didn't tell us was that the 6 percent increase was more than double the inflation rate of 2.9 percent. <P> With only so many grants or scholarships to go around, most institutions today are building the maximum amount of federal Stafford loans into their financial aid packages. That means a minimum of $17,125 in loan indebtedness for four years of education. Since many college students do not graduate in four years, the loan amount can jump to $22,625. That translates to minimum monthly loan payments of $200 for the 10 years following graduation. The amount can range higher if the schools bring other loans into the mix. <P>Perhaps it's time for parents and their children to look at college choice the way we look at business decisions: We think about the bottom line, factoring in cost and evaluating ways to reach the same objective at less expense. For example, many students today ignore one of the most inexpensive higher education options: our region's network of community colleges. Students who want a degree from a four-year school can spend the first two years at a community college before transferring their credits to the four-year school at which they wish to complete their degree. <P> Last school year, full-time undergraduates at Pitt paid $5,416 in tuition and fees, compared to $6,870 at Robert Morris and $11,879 at Duquesne, according to state education department data. The full-time tuition at the region's five community colleges ranged from $1,193 at Westmoreland County Community College to $1,760 at the Community College of Beaver County. Butler County Community College was an even $1,500, and Community College of Allegheny County cost $1,602. <P> Is this opportunity presented to the 17- and 18-year-olds deciding on college? Hardly. Many high school guidance counselors keep score as to the number of their students placed in "name" colleges or universities. The community colleges? They usually are presented to the student as the last option. <P>That's dead wrong, and it hurts us all. We can't expect a 17- or 18-year-old to understand the burden of student loan indebtedness they will face as a 22-year-old college graduate. They don't know that many recent graduates who are burdened with college loan payments struggle to afford  a car, let alone a home. Our work force suffers, too, since many of today's graduates won't consider pursuing a master's degree because of the debt they already incurred as undergraduates.With higher education costs spiraling annually beyond the rate of inflation, we can't hope for cost containment. At the present rate, today's newborns will be freshmen in 2012 and paying $70,000 to attend four years of college at a public institution.  For a private school, the typical tab would be $180,000. <P> We must educate our young people as to the burden of student loan indebtedness and present them with options to minimize it. 
