<TITLE> Letters </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.L.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<font size =+2><B>Ethically Speaking</B></font size><BR>
I am bewildered by the recent spate of writings about ethics.Queen Victoria once asked one of her ministers for advice on what course to follow on a certain matter. He answered that it would be "most expedient" to proceed in such and such a manner. <P> She replied: "I know no such word as expedient. I only know right and wrong." <P> How far away have we gotten from such a simple statement? <P> <B>-- Joe Boerio, Ligonier, Pa.</B>
<hr>
<font size =+2><B>Internet Surfers</B></font size><BR>
I am a subscriber to Executive Report and just found you on the World Wide Web. Congratulations! You are the most forward-looking magazine in Pittsburgh. 
<P><B> -- Robert L. Byer, partner, Kirkpatrick & Lockhart, djdh71a@prodigy.com</B>
<P>
I hope to see you guys do things in this area that are innovative and interesting -- hell, maybe even fun. Goodness we will never see it from the sick, gray, old Post-Gazette. <P> <B>-- Scott Schober, president, Allegheny Petroleum Products Co., sschober@telerama.lm.com</B>
<P>
<I>Editor's Note: Find Executive Report on the internet at http://www.execreport.com/er.html</i>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Common Sense </B></font size><BR>
 <P> Henry Frantzen, head of global investing for Federated Investors, is certainly right when he tells readers, "The object of the investment game is to end up with more money than you started with" (International Investing: Rationale for a Modern World, July 1995). <P> My dad, a good old Scotsman, taught me, "A little arithmetic and common sense will solve most any problem." <P>The July 1995 issue of Executive Report is loaded with common sense. <P> <B>-- Jack B. Kenning Pittsburgh </B>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Education: Another View </B></font size><BR>
The purpose of education is not to prepare good workers for business, but rather to help form productive citizens for our country. If the schools do a satisfactory job then it will naturally follow that our young people will readily adapt and contribute to our society not only in their work, but in all the diverse responsibilities required of citizens in a free society. <P> Here are my suggestions: <P>(1) Schools are not surrogate parents. <P>(2) Standards must be maintained. <P> (3) Students should dress neatly and appropriately. <P> (4) The teacher's word is the law. <P> (5) Vocational schooling should be encouraged for the noncollege bound. <P> These are just a few suggestions. Old fashioned I suppose, but they will work. <P><B>-- William J. Meisler, radiologist and medical director, Community Imaging Associates, Harrisburg, Pa.</B>
<HR>
