<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <FONT SIZE=+2><B>Clinton's Desire to Beef Up Union Bargaining Power Will Endanger Businesses, Push Up Consumer Costs</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By John E. Lyncheski</i>
<HR>
When labor and management sit down at the negotiating table, each is holding a trump card that neither really wants to play: The union can call a strike; management can hire replacements provided the strike is over contract demands.President Clinton wants to stack the deck in favor of unions. He recently issued an executive order that bans federal agencies from contracting with companies that hire permanent replacement employees. <P> Don't mistake this action as being about employees' or workers' rights. The president's move clearly is nothing more than an attempt to give unions the edge in collective bargaining. But in the process, the president will drive up consumer costs, threaten the viability of businesses and endanger the jobs of these same union members from whom he so desperately seeks support for the 1996 election. <P> The executive order authorizes Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich to make a finding on whether a company is permanently replacing its employees. If the labor secretary so finds, he can then direct other federal agencies and departments to terminate contracts with the company or bar it from receiving federal contracts as long as the replacements remain on the job. The order affects federal contracts valued at $100,000 or more. <P> It's obvious the politicians and academicians of the Clinton administration have very little, if any, meaningful exposure to the world of collective bargaining. <P> While all employers have the option to hire replacement employees during an economic strike, very few employers actually do it. It is not a widespread practice, even though the right to hire replacement employees in economic strikes has existed, virtually unchanged, since 1938. In fact, the respective rights of employers and unions have been the same for more than 50 years. v So why substantially alter the existing balance of power in labor-management relations? <P>Let's face facts: Employers who pursue the hiring of replacement employees do so extremely reluctantly and as a last resort. Striking employees almost always are forewarned of the employer's intent to pursue replacements and are urged to return to work before replacements are hired. Even if the employer does hire replacements, the law still protects the replaced employees' status by affording them preferential rehiring rights. <P> Think about what happens when a strike shuts down an employer. Cash flow soon screeches to a halt. Many employers have substantial loans they have to satisfy without any revenue coming in. Loyal customers who used the employer's products find other suppliers, with whom they may remain after the strike ends. In some cases, the employer has no choice: It either capitulates, hires replacements or goes out of business.But sometimes, the employer's right to hire replacements plays a different role: Just like the employees' right to strike, it helps push both sides to a compromise without a protracted dispute. <P> The right to hire replacement employees is crucial to maintaining this balance in collective bargaining that in most cases allows labor and management to resolve disputes in a manner fair to both sides. Just as no employer wants a strike, no union wants its members sitting on a picket line for months on end as replacement workers collect paychecks. <P>With the Clinton administration altering this balance of bargaining power, we could see several results: <P> 	More Strikes: The unions will be quick to call a strike to take advantage of their bargaining leverage. Em-ployers will be backed into a corner. <P>	Longer Strikes: Employers will have to weather much longer strikes to obtain a reasonable settlement that won't drive the company out of business. <P>	Increased Costs to Consumers: Those employers who can't afford a lengthy strike will have to succumb to unreasonable or costly union contract demands to stay in business. Consumers will absorb the increased costs in the form of higher prices. <P>	Less Jobs: In the long term, some employers eventually will shut down because the unions will price themselves out of jobs. <P> The right to hire replacement employees is crucial to keeping the collective bargaining process just that -- a bargaining process. If the government takes away an employer's right to resort to hiring replacement workers during a prolonged strike, employers will struggle to compete and survive. When these businesses fail, you can kiss many of those union jobs goodbye. <P> John E. Lyncheski is a director with the Pittsburgh law firm of Cohen & Grigsby, P.C.
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
