<HEAD>
<TITLE> ERIndex </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a><P>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>Specialty Steelmaker Looks Strong Six Months After Going Public</B></FONT><BR>

Not long ago, the phrase "mini-mill" wasn't especially popular around here. Recently, though, in what amounts to a boost for Pittsburgh steel production, a relatively new, relatively small company has set up shop in Bridgeville, making some of the world's finest specialty steel. <P> Universal Stainless & Alloy Products went public in December at $8 per share and has steadily worked its way up to over $12 per share recently. The company's primary products are stainless steel, tool steels and high temperature alloy steels widely used in the automotive, power generation, aerospace, food handling and chemical processing industries. <P> Universal, which is listed on the NASDAQ under the symbol USAP, is the first steel company to bring back specialty steel melting operations to the greater Pittsburgh area, and the company did it through an extremely unique and collaborative effort that involved the U.S. Steelworkers and the Duquesne Light Co. <P>The Bridgeville facility, which previously had been owned by Armco and Cyclops, employed 2,700 employees as recently as 20 years ago. Armco, which consolidated the plant's operations into its Baltimore facility in 1993, sold it to Universal last August for $3.7 million. The estimated cost to replace just the equipment in place was $112 million. And Armco indemnified Universal against any past environmental or employee benefit (pension) obligations. <P>Clarence M. "Mac" McAninch, Universal's president and CEO, is highly respected and highly incentivized. McAninch was with Armco in its Alloy Products Division from 1989 to 1994, and before that, he served at LTV Steel and Reese Tool and Metal Service Company. He and the rest of the management team as well as all roughly 100 hourly employees have a portion of their cash compensation based on pre-tax income. One of the first things the company did upon going public was to make all employees shareholders. <P> Nancy C. Moore, an analyst with Keane Securities Co., estimates Universal will earn $1.15 per share this year and $1.86 in 1996 on sales of $60 million and $83 million, respectively. <P> "USAP is on a fast track in terms of its operations, customer base, revenues and earnings," Moore said. <P> 
Around the ER Index
<DL>
<LI>The proposed acquisition of Legent Corp. by Computer Associates helped propel the ER Index to a 1.28 percent increase for the month ended June 9, versus a 0.45 percent performance by the S&P 500. The ER Index continues to lag the S&P 500 since last August 15, with the ER Index up 12.36 percent and the S&P up 14.46 percent. <P> As for the impact on Pittsburgh, where Legent employs about 350 people, we would be surprised if any significant changes are in the offing. The software development business is characterized by an unusual degree of autonomy. Duquesne Systems, the local forerunner to Legent, is a cornerstone of the company, and we don't think CA will want to alter what is already working. 
<LI>The other big mover of the month was General Nutrition Centers, which reported a 51 percent improvement in net income on a 30 percent increase in sales. Earnings per share for the quarter was 38 cents versus analyst projections of 33 cents. GNC's shares rose 17.7 percent for the month and are up more than 66 percent since August. 
<LI> The biggest loser for the month was MK Rail, which lost more than 22 percent of its value. The stock has bounced back, as the result of the release of its much delayed financial results for 1994 and the first quarter of 1995. The numbers were ugly but not unexpected. Clearly, Morrison Knudsen, the majority owner of MK Rail, is seeking a buyer for its stake. MK Rail stock is down by nearly two-thirds since August. 
<LI> Black Box Corp. has filed to sell 3.5 million shares belonging to Odyssey Partners, the New York LBO firm that bought the company in 1988. That represents half of Odyssey's stake. Odyssey will now control 22 percent of Black Box' shares, and we believe that the resulting expansion in liquidity and float should make Black Box more attractive to a wider group of investors. That should push the share price up. 

</DL>
<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research for Emerald Asset Management, tracks the ER Index which is composed of 25 public companies in greater Pittsburgh.</I>
