<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.C.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>An Eye for Fashion </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Pittsburgh's flair for fashion helps the city keep its finger on the pulse of the international marketplace. K. Barchetti Shops, one of the major players in Pittsburgh's international retail trade, was recognized by the Italian Trade Commission's Moda Made in Italy program for increasing awareness of Italian-made products in secondary markets like Pittsburgh. <P> "People are surprised to find that Pittsburgh is indeed a cosmopolitan city; though K. Barchetti Shops carries 90% European merchandise, their sales per square foot are double the national average," says Mame Bradley, Executive Director of the World Trade Center Pittsburgh. "Obviously Pittsburghers enjoy fashion when it is presented tastefully. We acknowledge the role of European fashion in Pittsburgh." <P> Retailers, like Katherine Barchetti, owner of K. Barchetti Shops, continue to enhance trade relations between Pittsburgh and Italy. "As international markets continue to expand, businesses are increasingly faced with global commoditization and competition," says Barchetti. "Our customers trust us to bring them true value with an emphasis on quality. Italy offers the finest materials in the world, and unsurpassed craftsmanship. The American consumer realizes the value of Italian merchandise."
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Do You Trust Me? </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Do you trust your boss? Does your boss trust you?Trust in the workplace was the topic of a recent survey by Development Dimensions International.  Surveying 1,108 employees in 57 service and manufacturing organizations worldwide, DDI found that 56 percent of nonmanagement employees said that lack of trust was a problem in their organization.  Nearly 70 percent said that they trusted their peers more than their supervisors. <P> Of the four groups -- peers, leaders, other teams and senior management -- senior management was the least trusted. <P>Many in the survey put communication at the top of the list of trust-building behaviors. Others included having confidence in employees' abilities, valuing what employees say, keeping promises and commitments, and working as a team. <P>Experts say trust is a basic essential in successful companies. It creates widespread cooperation, commitment and positive energy.  Nearly 95 percent of those surveyed said that they considered themselves trustworthy people, 6.37 on a scale of 7. <P>As one survey participant said, "Trust is something you earn from your fellow workers.  It is not something that comes with a position' or title.'  It takes a great deal of time and effort to earn trust and very little to lose it."
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>'The Dog Ate It' </B></FONT SIZE><br>
When a process breaks down or a deadline is missed, employees often are full of excuses. It wasn't their responsibility. They didn't have enough time. They've never done it that way. <P>What hurts is that many of the excuses are legitimate. And if that's the case, it's likely that the problem is not with the employee, according to the Jacksonville, Fla.-based Leadership Development Council. <P>"We believe you need to fix the processes that run your corporation before you can fix your people, and that approach represents a paradigm shift in corporate management theory," says James Bleech, chairman of LDC and a former top executive with Meridian Engineering Inc. <P>Bleech urges companies to study organizational structures and processes, identifying the failures that allow, tolerate and sometimes force employees to offer an excuse. <P> Shred-All, a document destruction and recycling firm that includes AT&T, IBM and Pittsburgh-based Westinghouse among its clients, took Bleech's advice and saw productivity jump by 30 percent. <P> "Instead of a reactive mode, we began anticipating the problems that might prevent us from reaching goals," says Shred-All President Barry Grahek. "There is a lot of talk about thinking ahead, but too many companies are reactive. We now tell our employees, If you don't think you can fulfill the goal, you better know why you can't fulfill it and make some changes that allow you to fulfill it.' " <P> To an extent, companies like Shred-All are empowering employees to identify potential problems and recommend or take steps to solve the problems. In the end, employees feel they have more power and may be happier with the job. <P>LDC offers three-day executive retreats, a variety of seminars and individualized consulting. Bleech calls his strategy the "let's get results, not excuses, system of management."
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>PNC's Plum Card </B></FONT SIZE><br>
In an apples-to-apples comparison of credit cards offered by 577 financial institutions, an independent research group is listing the Prime Value card offered by Pittsburgh-based PNC Bank as a plum. <P> CardTrak of America Inc. evaluated credit cards offered by banks, saving institutions, credit unions and firms engaging in issuing of VISA and MasterCard. <P>What makes a credit card like the Prime Value so juicy?  The top reason is interest rates: PNC offers a delicious long- term interest rate of 12.75 percent, which is about 30 percent below the national average of 18.31 percent. The other reasons CardTrak cited for ranking the PNC card so highly include its low annual fee,  which is $18 for the standard card and $28 for the gold card. CardTrak also cited adequate credit lines and a commitment from PNC to maintain interest rates below the national average. <P>Many credit-card users waste money on high interest costs and annual fees. In order to find out the facts behind the credit card sweet talk, CardTrak recommends reading the fine print in the disclosure box, which is required by federal law and can usually be found on the back of an application in small type. <P> Since most Americans carry a balance of $1,700 or more, a good long-term interest rate is important.  Another thing to keep in mind when applying are the real values of rebate programs. CardTrak estimates that on many airline VISA/ MasterCards you'd have to charge somewhere between $1,750 and $5,000 to offset the annual fee of $35 to $100. <P> Today, three out of four cards have variable interest rates, 80 percent of which are based on the prime rate with which many consumers are familiar. However, an increasing number of cards are now using the LIBOR rate instead of the prime. The LIBOR, or the London Interbank Offered Rate, makes it hard for consumers to track and compare rates.  CardTrak's advice? Discard any card offers that use this obscure index.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>'Ever Meet Anybody Who's Been Hit By A Train?' </B></FONT SIZE><br>
asks the headline on a slick folder from the U.S. Department of Transportation's Federal Railroad Administration.Probably not, but 6,000 people were hit by trains in 1994. The agency spent $500,000 developing this public service campaign, which includes ad slicks, radio and TV public service announcements and camera-ready print ads. <P> In contrast, U.S. Department of Transportation's Office of Alcohol and State Programs Acting Director Jim Fell says they spent roughly the same amount on a public service campaign with the Ad Council to combat drunk driving. In 1993, 17,461 people were killed by drunk drivers. 1994 statistics were not available yet, but to date show 16,970 deaths -- which Fell says will go up. The drunk driving campaign gets a lot more bang for the buck because the Ad Council gets pro bono work for much of its campaigns, but Fell had no figures on the actual value of the campaign.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Heart to Heart </B></FONT SIZE><br>
About 68 million Americans have heart-related disease, the leading cause of death in the U.S. To evaluate its treatment, the Pennsylvania Cost Containment Council can help. Since 1990, the group has collected statistics on the success and cost of this operation from hospitals across the state. <P> Letters from hospital administrators which accompany the study argue that these results should be taken with a grain of salt. Hospital administrators say the reporting mechanisms for the study still have not been perfected and the study did not fully take into account other conditions from which patients suffered. <P> The study found that in western Pennsylvania, Allegheny General Hospital was the only hospital reporting fewer deaths than the number expected for this procedure, losing 10 patients out of 954 who underwent the surgery. The expected range for this category is 18 to 35. Hamot Medical Center in Erie, Mercy Hospital, St. Francis Central Hospital, St. Francis Medical Center, St. Vincent Health Center, Shadyside Hospital, University of Pittsburgh Medical Center, Washington Hospital and Western Pennsylvania Hospital all had a similar number of deaths as expected. Only one, Westmoreland Regional Hospital, reported more deaths than expected: in 106 surgeries, five patients died; zero to four was the expected range. <P>The average cost of the procedure was also reported. Western Pennsylvania hospitals were all over the map, ranging from a low of $46,967 (Mercy Hospital) to a high of $93,743 (University of Pittsburgh Medical Center). <P> Interestingly, the study noted that women are at greater risk than men: The leading cause of death among women, cardiovascular disease caused 46 percent of all women's deaths, 40 percent for men. And nearly 44 percent of women will die within one year after a heart attack, compared to 27 percent of men.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Remembering Chuck Muer </B></FONT SIZE><br>
When the so-called "Storm of the Century" worked its way up the East Coast in 1993, it claimed among its victims Chuck and Betty Muer, who were lost at sea off the coast of Florida. Many Pittsburghers knew the Muers, who were the founders of the Grand Concourse restaurant and the Gandy Dancer Saloon at Station Square.Now Susan Muer, daughter of the couple, has developed a cookbook as a tribute to her parents. "The Simply Great Cookbook II" features recipes from the 20 restaurants owned by the Muers, whose holdings included dining spots in Florida, Ohio and Michigan. Perhaps the best known outside of Pittsburgh are the seven Charley's Crab locations. <P>The Muers were with close friends George and Lynne Drummey off the coast of Florida when the couples disappeared in turbulent seas. Investigators suspect a 911 call placed offshore from a cellular phone was their last contact. <P>Chuck Muer had published his own cookbook five years ago. He appears on the cover of the tribute edition, seated behind plates of seafood and a glass of wine. Inside are recipes for Crabmeat Balls, Roasted Garlic Soup, Swordfish Picata, White Chocolate Mousse and dozens of other delicacies. <P>"This book is dedicated not only to the memory of Chuck and Betty Muer but also to their friends, in gratitude for the richness you brought into their lives," writes the daughter.The cookbooks are available locally at the Grand Concourse for $19.95.
<HR>
To The Point: Education"Even our best schools are not as competitive as they should be in today's globalized world." <BR>-- Eugene Hickok, Pennsylvania Secretary of Education
<P>
"As long as I am governor, I will work to promote change in education. There is no hope, no future, nothing we can do for a child who doesn't have a good education." <BR> -- Gov. Tom Ridge
