<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.PMN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
Name:Ganassi.Floyd Robert "Chip" Ganassi Jr.<BR>Age:37<BR>Personal:Lives in Mt. Washington, marrying Cara Marie Small September 22, 1995<BR>Education:B.S., Finance, Duquesne University, 1982<BR>Last Vacation:Mexico, at the end of 1994 racing season.<BR>Last book read:"The Kid Stays in the Picture" by Robert Evans<P>
<HR>
Chip Ganassi, at 37, is one of the youngest team owners on the Indy Car circuit. In 1995, his Target/Chip Ganassi Racing Team (named for its largest sponsor) fielded two Reynard Ford-Cosworth entries, driven by Bryan Herta, age 24, and Jimmy Vasser, 29. Ganassi, a former driver himself, made news last spring when he added football star Joe Montana to his roster as a partner. Still a kid at heart? Most definitely. But he's playing in the big leagues now, and it's easy to see why the team's 16 sponsors think the former driver -- with his impish, "I love life" confidence, affable, expressive face and head of unruly sun-bleached hair -- can propel his team to success. ER's Lydia Strohl talked to him in his Oxford Centre office last month.<P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>Executive Report: How did you get involved in racing? </B></FONT>
Chip Ganassi: My father was in the asphalt paving business. He paved a go-cart track and the guy couldn't pay for it. I was like three years old. So the guy gave us three go-carts, and they sat for two or three years before I could even reach the pedals. Go-carts turned into dirt bikes. Dirt bikes turned into snowmobiles. By 18, I was racing cars, having raced all of the above before that. I learned to drive when I was 12 -- my uncle has a driving range on Route 51, and I used to drive around and pick up the golf balls. I was entering sanctioned events with motorcycles by the time I was 14 years old. So driving always came very naturally to me. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: Did you intend to make it your career?</B></FONT>
CG: I don't know that at that age I did. I guess I always thought of being in my family's business. One day I just woke up and realized I was in a small group of people who could actually drive and probably earn a living at it. And I was fortunate that I could pursue that. I grew up in a household with a lot of support from my parents. <P>I raced through my whole time in college. My first weekend as a freshman at Duquesne University was Labor Day weekend, and I didn't get there until Monday night because I was at a race. I never missed a class when I was on campus, only when I was at a race. <P> There were three different levels. I did Formula Fords for three years. Then, I did Super V, a mini-Indy class, they don't even have it any more. By the time I was a senior, I was racing Indy cars. I remember telling my economics professor that I had to miss class on Friday to go to Phoenix to be in a car race. He gave me a piece of his mind about what I wanted to be, a student or a car racer. I took a red-eye flight back and showed up at class on Monday morning. I was the star of ABC Sports World the day before, and in taking attendance he said, Mr. Ganassi, I see you weren't here on Friday, but I saw you on television yesterday.' So at least he knew I wasn't lying to him. <P> I graduated in May, turned 23 years old and qualified as the fastest rookie in the Indy 500 -- all within a 10-day period. For the next three or four years I drove for a living. You go from something costing you money to making you money with no in-between. But I didn't really intend it. It's like you know where it can possibly take you some day, but it's hard to keep in mind that the Indy 500 is out there when you're just trying to find out where you're going to get your next set of tires from. You start as a hobby, then you start doing good and you take the next step. I would have been perfectly happy with it as a hobby. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: What was the first race that you won?</B></FONT>
CG: In the fall of 1977, at Nelson's Ledges, Ohio, in a Royale Formula Ford. I had been racing everything you could think of. And the minute I got in cars, I was right there. There was nothing in the world that was unattainable in those days. No one had ever won more than five races in this series [of 14]. Myself and my best friend at the time each won six -- and the other two we didn't go to. We were bulletproof. It was a heady time. I ended up finishing third in the nation that year. My best friend was second. I couldn't advance fast enough. The next year I went to Super V. I finished third in the championship. And the next year, I went to the Indy 500. The next three of four years -- you couldn't script a more fulfilling, exciting life. I was getting paid six figures to drive cars in my early 20s. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: What was the life like?</B></FONT>
CG: All the cliches are true. That's all I can tell you. I mean, you're single. ... I don't know, it's like any other sports figure in those days. But after a while I felt like I was using my body instead of my brains. There's 33 cars in the Indy 500. If you look at the grid in 1985, of the 14 that had started the race in 1982, 11 of them had leg injuries. It was a dangerous time in racing. It's gotten much safer. I felt like I had too much to give up on -- and after five years in Indy cars without putting together a win, I thought it was time to get on with the business of racing. I thought it was time to use my education and use my experience growing up in a family business. And I seem to be much better at this. I have a lot more wins as an owner. <P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: You once had a bad accident. What happened?</B></FONT>
CG: In 1984 I was in an accident in the Michigan 500, and was in a coma for a day. It's nothing that any race car driver doesn't expect, it's just that it's pretty horrific. Something broke in the car at about 200 miles per hour. I hit the wall, the car turned over maybe 15 times, disintegrated. I basically just hit my head hard. I had a broken hand, and some stitches in my knee, but other than that it was just lights out for a little while. <P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: How did you make the transition from being a driver to being an owner?</B></FONT>
CG: You would think the transition would be a simple one, but it's not. I actually draw more on my experiences from family business [FRG Group, a Pittsburgh-based holding company involved in manufacturing, telecommunications and real estate] and business school than I do on my driving background. A team that I had driven for was for sale, and I acquired it after the 1987 season. In 1989 the team won the Indy 500, and we won the championship that year. We've had a great record at Indy. This year we crashed out of the lead 25 laps from the end. <P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: What does it take to make it in racing?</B></FONT>
CG: It takes a good team, and I don't just mean a racing team. It takes a good team of mechanics, of engineers. It takes good management. It takes good sponsors -- sponsors first, probably. It takes good communication. It's not unlike any other business. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: What kind of investment does it take to get into racing? </B></FONT>
CG: It's the fourth most popular sport in the country, and the largest spectator sport -- and if you look at what it takes to run the other teams, it's less expensive.The car costs $425,000. That's without the engine. The engine's another $100,000. And you've got to have about four of them. It takes about $6-1/2 million to run one car per year -- the car's actually inexpensive. When you're talking about racing them week in and week out, that's what gets expensive. It's like picking up a traveling circus and moving it week after week. <P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: What kind of returns can you get?</B></FONT>
CG: Depends how much you crash. Profit comes from winnings, sponsors. It's a building block thing. If you win a lot one year, you should be able to translate that into earnings the next year. For a star athlete, you should easily double your income on outside promotions. For a team, those numbers aren't the same, but you have to develop good sponsors. Like any other business, if you take in more than what you spend, you make money. <P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: Did you capitalize the team with money you made as a driver?</B></FONT>
CG: Only about half was from that, and half was my family's money. I am the sole owner of the team. Target [an upscale discount retailer headquartered in Minneapolis] is the main sponsor of the team. We have two cars, one is Target/Scotch and one is Target/STP. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: What is your agreement with Joe Montana?</B></FONT>
CG: Joe is a partner in the team. I met Joe about five years ago, and he is from the Mon Valley also. We grew up probably 8 or 10 miles apart. I didn't know him then, but when we met we struck up a conversation about our upbringing. He was getting some calls about getting involved in racing. His agents at IMG [International Manage-ment Group, in Cleveland, Ohio] are my agents as well. And they called me and said, Montana's getting a lot of calls about being in racing, and he had this deal thrown at him. He said to call you because he'd met you, and you're from his area. Would you do the same deal?' And I said, Sure.' So I did. <P> Joe is one of the few sports personalities who I think transcends sports. When you think about winning, come from behind, team player, you think of Joe. <P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: What kind of involvement will he have?</B></FONT>
CG: The simple thing I can point to is that he just raises everybody's game right away. Success begets a certain amount of success, and you want to keep that snowball rolling. <P>He'll be involved, talking to the team, motivating them, helping with sponsorship opportunities and developing strategies, being in our team meetings before the race, keeping everybody loose. The guy is an asset. But more importantly, he's just a nice, normal guy. <P> It was quite a feather in our cap that he announced his interest in racing right on the heels of his retirement from football. The deal was already done. But the Sports Illustrated retirement article says that he's going into Indy car racing. <P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: Did he have any prior involvement in racing before?</B></FONT>
CG: Yes, that's how he kind of got hooked. He drove in the Toyota Celebrity race in Long Beach [Calif.] a couple times. He was never able to pursue that because his contracts would forbid it. Not that he ever wanted to be a race car driver or anything, but there's no reason he shouldn't get involved and enjoy it now. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: Will you maintain Pittsburgh as your headquarters once you are married?</B></FONT>
CG: Yes. I like Pittsburgh. It's an oasis away from racing, away from my business. I can concentrate on it here. It's home for me. It's an easy place to travel from. The quality of life here is good, and I think the cost of living here is inexpensive. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: When are you away for the race season?</B></FONT>
CG: The actual race season itself is 16 races, March through September, but the traveling doesn't stop. It's always travel, whether it's with Target or other sponsors, doing business. v 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: What kind of car do you drive?</B></FONT>
CG: A Lincoln Mark 8. Not a sports car -- I get enough of it on the weekend. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: Are you in this for the long term?</B></FONT>
CG: I'm one of the younger owners, even at 37. You can go a long time. I don't know what else I would do. I could think of some things I could do on the side, but I wouldn't have the passion that I do for this. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: Have you spun other businesses out of this?</B></FONT>
CG: Yes, I'm the importer for one of the racing cars as a side business. I introduced the Reynard chassis, from England, to Indy car racing. I am the North American distributor. We had half the field this year at the Indy 500 and it's only our second year. <P> 
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: Looking back, what do you think was the turning point in your career?</B></FONT>
CG: When I got third in the Formula Fords, then in the Super V -- that's semi-pro -- I was sponsored by First Commercial Corporation, a company that's defunct now. That's where you start to get noticed. Then I went to Indy cars, and that's when I got Sea Ray, STP, Old Milwaukee beer -- that's when it really started to take off. That's what I do now, I get [sponsors] every day. I just did a deal today with Warner Lamber/Shaving products group. [Reads:] Ganassi agrees that the sponsorship rights shall be exclusive in the category of blades, razor blades and razor products.' <P>What do I give them? Two credential hard cards for VIP executives, the right to purchase credentials and tickets, press materials, provide hospitality, provide a driver for appearances, use of a show car, assist on making travel arrangements with special race discounts, cooperate in developing and implementing promotional activities. They'll be roughly this size on the car [points to Speed Stick logo] -- the more dollars, the more square inches. <P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>ER: Will you expand the team?</B></FONT>
CG: I think that two cars is a good size effort. If you were to ask me that question a year ago, I would have said yes. But today, I'm back into the mode of focusing. I think it's better to focus on one thing than to be everything to everybody. I used to want to be everything to everybody, today I just want to focus.              
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
