<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ED.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Palio</B></FONT><BR>
<B>The Bread Alone is Worth the Trip</B>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I>
<HR>
Palio is not for the faint-of-stomach. The rich atmosphere, the fresh, simple and abundant quantities of food, the heady Italian wines -- all bespeak Tuscany, the northwestern Italian region from which the restaurant takes its identity. <P> Palio, the menu tells you, is named for the Palio della Contrade, a tournament held in Siena's Piazza del Campo since medieval times. An intimate restaurant, seating 36 in the dining room (10 more at the long copper bar), Palio replicates an Italian trattoria, painted with faux marble and frescoes in warm golden tones, corners filled with urns of dried sunflowers. The tables are marble, the chairs mission-style oak and leather, comfortable and curiously private for such a small space. <P> On the tables are set bottles of herbed olive oil and huge pots of grated Parmesan cheese, armed with a big spoon. A loaf of hot Tuscan bread, doughy on the inside and crusty on the outside, arrives just as you do, accompanied by a spread of Gorgonzola, roasted peppers and olives. This is by far the best bread we have tasted in this town -- and worth the trip itself. The secret, according to chef Michael White, is the heat achieved by the commercial grade stone-floored oven. (Another secret -- the restaurant makes pizzas with this dough, for take-out upon request.) <P> Next, an antipasto is added to the spread of food in front of you. Endive stuffed with buffalo mozzarella, a pile of shaved ham and a marinated salad of banana and red roasted peppers, artichoke hearts and black olives was the offering that night, but the menu indicates this changes. <P>This is a meal in itself, perhaps accompanied by a bottle of wine from the heavily Italian wine list, which ranges from $20 to $40. And, for $7.95 each, it is indeed possible to just get antipasto and bread. <P> But the offerings on the entree menu, as well as the pricing structure, encourage diners on. Both range from staple (linguine marinara, $13.95) to sublime (lobster and shrimp in a sauce of vodka and cream, sprinkled with caviar, $27.95) and include the antipasto and bread. Poultry, seafood and meat entrees also come with a pasta course. Servers advise diners that with the $10 shared plate charge, it's more economical to order another entree, even if it ends up as your lunch the next day. <P>So pace yourself. The menu offers an array of pasta, chicken, veal and fish dishes like veal scaloppine, glazed with grappa and port, then pan-fried with mushrooms ($16.95), chicken breast and sausage with white beans and tomatoes ($16.95), or scallops with red peppers and spinach, pan-fried in garlic butter ($17.95). Specials include a double veal chop layered with prosciutto and fontina cheese, crumb-coated and pan-fried ($32.95), risotto with lobster, shrimp, mussels and sundried tomatoes ($27.95). If there's nothing just right on the menu, ask. The service here is as friendly and accommodating as the proverbial corner tavern. <P>We chose pasta: tagliatelle coi gamberoni, tossed with over-sized shrimp, fresh spinach and cream, and tagliarini col granchio, linguine with jumbo lump crabmeat and toasted pignoli nuts in a mild garlic butter sauce. After the festival of zesty appetizers, the pastas seemed dry and their flavor subdued. The cream sauce was extremely rich, the shrimp, as well as the portion, over-sized. The garlic butter flavored, rather than sauced, the pasta, which contained much seafood and a generous sprinkling of pignoli. It would appear that the local take-out container distributor has truly benefited from the opening of Palio. <P> For dessert we ordered ladyfingers, layered with strawberries, fresh whipped cream and cream cheese. The portion was so large that there must have been a brick of cream cheese in it (surprised?). The coffee was strong and hazelnut. <P> Chef White says his secret is high heat and flash-cooking to sear in the flavors of the fresh food. On my last visit, I tried the scaloppine alla piemontese, veal coated with breadcrumbs and topped with spinach and chestnuts. It was melt-in-your-mouth moist, made rich with the exotic combination of tastes, and I still have a lot of that in my freezer, too. <P> Just 21, White has been working for four years with owner David Ayn, who also owns the adjacent Davio. <P> "David's worked in every restaurant in Pittsburgh," says White. Four years ago, Ayn established Davio, which serves "peasant Italian," and, though it has no liquor license, is booked weeks in advance. "There are only seven tables next door, and we have a liquor license here." <P> Though Ayn based the menu on the cuisine of Tuscany, White says they experiment with unusual combinations that are often quite improvisational. <P> "Last night, I made brownies, and David and I had them with hazelnut coffee," White, who, amazingly, has no formal training, told us. "We thought -- what about brownies with hazelnut coffee in them?" <P>The "all-inclusive" pricing structure can make this a hefty evening, and be forewarned that the restaurant accepts only cash or check, no credit cards. But it's worth a trip to Palio. In a city redundant with Italian restaurants, this one clearly stands out. <P> 
<HR>
Palio<BR>
5422 Broadway<BR>
Beechview; 531-8211 <P> 
4pm to last diner, seven days weekly<BR>
Reservations suggested <P>
Appetizers: $3.95 - $7.95 <BR>
Entrees: $13.95 and up<BR>
Shared dinner charge: $10.00<BR>
