<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<b><FONT SIZE=+2> 1995 Performing Arts Guide </FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b>A Guide to the Arts</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By ER Staff</i>
<hr>
The Executive Report Performing Arts Guide for 1995-1996 includes information about some of the region's major players, from music to dance to theater. <P> Space constraints prevented us from listing every performing arts group in the region, but we think we've compiled a list that can help our readers plan a special evening out on the town. <P> Each listing includes background information about the group, a telephone number and detailed performance schedules. <P> The groups are listed alphabetically. <P> Enjoy.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>The Carnegie: </B></font size> <BR>
After 100 years The Carnegie is still going strong. In addition to the museums, libraries and science center, The Carnegie also promotes the performing arts. The Carnegie Institute's Performing Arts Department presents 35 to 45 performances throughout the year. Programs include children's theater, jazz concerts, jazz classes, outdoor summer concerts and a wide variety of holiday programs each December. Most performances are free with museum admission or nominally priced and feature regional performers and groups.<BR>The Carnegie<BR>4400 Forbes Avenue<BR>Pittsburgh, Pa. 15213<BR>tel. (412) 622-3131<BR>fax (412) 622-1970<BR>Ellsworth Brown, President<BR>Phillip Johnston, Director, Museum of Art<BR>Cynthia Ference-Kelly, <BR>Performing Arts Manager<BR>Founded 1895<BR>Aug. 11, 1995<BR>Afro-American Music Institute Jazz Ensemble<BR>Aug. 25, 1995<BR>Henry Shapiro & Swing Fever<BR>Oct. 20, 1995<BR>Carnegie on Tap<BR>Dec. 10, 1995<BR>United We Sing: A Centennial Christmas Concert<BR>Dec. 12-31, 1995<BR>Holiday Concerts at The Carnegie<BR>Art Exhibits<BR>Through Aug. 13, 1995<BR>Other Places, Other Times Photographs from the Collection<BR>Through Aug. 24, 1995<BR>85th Annual Associated Artists of Pittsburgh<BR>Through Sept. 3, 1995<BR>Peter Contis<BR>Through Oct. 1, 1995<BR>Ritual and Fashion: The Taste for Tea<BR>Through Jan. 7, 1996<BR>Master of the Wild  The Art of Guy Coheleach
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>City Theater: </B></font size> <BR>
One of the region's foremost professional theaters, City Theater offers critically acclaimed productions of some of the hottest urban contemporary dramas and comedies. For those with a yen to do something different, City Theater provides provocative, innovative entertainment in an intimate and comfortable performance space. For nearly 15 years the City Theater has operated under the direction of Marc Masterson in their South Side location.<BR>    The 1995-96 season features a wide variety of productions, including Squonk Opera's multi-media revisioning of George Romero's Night of the Living Dead. Other highlights include Don Marshall in the controversial story Paul Robeson; Richard Dresser's comedy Below the Belt, and What's Left??, a co-presentation of the City Theater, the Pittsburgh Dance Council and the Three Rivers Arts Festival. <BR>City Theater<BR>57 S. 13th Street<BR>Pittsburgh, Pa. 15203<BR>tel. (412) 431-CITY;  fax (412) 431-5535<BR>Marc Masterson, Producing Director<BR>Leonard P. Perfido, President<BR>Founded 1974<BR>Sept. 6-30, 1995<BR>Squonk Opera's Night of the Living Dead: The Opera<BR>Oct. 20  Nov. 12, 1995<BR>Paul Robeson by Philip Hayes Dean<BR>Dec. 1-14, 1995<BR>American Song from the songs and writings of Woody Guthrie<BR>Jan. 19  Feb. 11, 1996<BR>A Beast on the Moon by Richard Kalinoski<BR>Feb. 23  March 17, 1996<BR>TBA<BR>March 24-31, 1996<BR>What's Left?? <BR>April 12  May 5, 1996<BR>Below the Belt by Richard Dresser<BR>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Civic Light Opera: </B></font size> <BR>
The Civic Light Opera has been producing live musical theater for Pittsburgh since 1946! Presenting the holiday season's delightful production of A Musical Christmas Carol in December, the CLO's summer season features six full-scale musicals in June, July and August. Subscription hotline: (412) 281-2822.<BR>Civic Light Opera<BR>The Benedum Center<BR>719 Liberty Avenue<BR>Pittsburgh, Pa. 15222<BR>tel. (412) 281-3973<BR>fax (412) 281-5339<BR>Gene Kelly, Honorary Chairman<BR>James E. Rohr, Chairman<BR>Robert C. McCartney, President<BR>Founded 1946<BR>July 25-Aug. 6, 1995<BR>Singin' in the Rain<BR>Aug. 8-13, 1995<BR>Godspell<BR>Dec. 7-23, 1995<BR>A Musical Christmas Carol
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Dance Alloy: </B></font size> <BR>
Dance Alloy is a contemporary dance company that engages in a wide variety of performance and educational activities. Pittsburgh audiences enjoy fall and spring performance series at the Fulton Theatre in the cultural district, while audiences nationwide and abroad benefit from the Alloy's extensive touring.<BR>    The Dance Alloy School at The Carnegie, the region's only professional contemporary dance school, provides movement and dance instruction to children and adults of all abilities. Outreach programs at Dance Alloy include Dance Exchanges, a series of open rehearsals hosted by guest choreographers; Meet the Artist post-show discussions, and Wood Street Works forums for area choreographers to present works-in-progress. <P> With Mark Taylor's work and artistic vision serving as the company's defining force, the commissioning of new works is central to Dance Alloy's mission. Since its founding, the Alloy has commissioned over 100 new works from renowned national choreographers, consequently bringing important, cutting-edge world premiers to Pittsburgh. This year's 1995-96 season of the Dance Alloy begins with a world premier choreographed by Mark Taylor to the music of Brave Combo.<BR>Dance Alloy<BR>4400 Forbes Avenue<BR>Pittsburgh, Pa. 15213<BR>tel. (412) 621-6670; fax (412) 621-6671<BR>Stephanie Flom, Managing Director<BR>Mark Taylor, Artistic Director<BR>Lorrie E. Rabin, President <BR>Founded 1976<BR>Nov. 10-11, 1995<BR>Brave Combo<BR>Mark Taylor, choreographer<BR><BR>>HR><BR>Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre<BR>    Under the artistic direction of Patricia Wilde since 1982, Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre has scored local and national triumphs performing a distinctive blend of ballets, including classics by the great George Balanchine and exciting new works by today's most exciting choreographers.<BR>Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre<BR>2900 Liberty Avenue<BR>Pittsburgh, Pa. 15201-1500<BR>tel. (412) 454-9107/281-0360<BR>fax (412) 281-9901<BR>Steven B. Libman, Managing Director<BR>Patricia Wilde, Artistic Director<BR>Leonard M. Carroll, Chairman<BR>Thomas W. Danielson, President<BR>Founded 1969<BR>Oct. 19-22, 1995<BR>Cinderella<BR>Nov. 24-26, 1995<BR>Amazing Grace<BR>Dec. 7-10, 1995<BR>The Nutcracker<BR>Feb. 15-18, 1996<BR>Giselle<BR>March 21-24, 1996<BR>Billy the Kid<BR>April 25-28, 1996<BR>The Great Gatsby
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Pittsburgh Center for the Arts: </B></font size> <BR>
Pittsburgh Center for the Arts is the largest community art center in Pennsylvania, serving the artists, arts organizations and art audiences in southwestern Pennsylvania. Housed in two renovated mansions in Mellon Park, the Center for the Arts features contemporary regional, national and international art exhibitions. <P> The Center for the Arts School offers four terms of art classes for all ages and summer art camps for children. Community Arts Education Network provides arts programming to individuals from high-risk environments and to those with special needs. The Center for the Arts Shop sells handcrafted artwork by regional and national artists.<BR>Pittsburgh Center for the Arts<BR>6300 Fifth Avenue<BR>Pittsburgh, Pa. 15232<BR>tel. (412) 361-0873; fax (412) 361-8338<BR>Robert J. Schuler, President<BR>Founded 1945
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Pittsburgh Dance Council: </B></font size> <BR>
For over 25 years the Pittsburgh Dance Council has thrilled audiences with the world's most renowned dance/theater companies. Season after season, they have startled, amazed, confused and confronted audiences by presenting not only the very best the dance world has to offer but also the newest, most diverse and most progressive work being created today. From cherished classics by modern dance masters to the daring, cutting-edge work of artists defining the next wave, the Dance Council is dance in all its glorious, tempestuous, unpredictable forms.<BR>Pittsburgh Dance Council<BR>719 Liberty Avenue<BR>Pittsburgh, Pa. 15222<BR>tel. (412) 355-0330<BR>fax (412) 355-0413<BR>Carolelinda Dickey, Executive Director<BR>Edward H. Harrell, President<BR>Founded 1969<BR>Sept. 14 & 16, 1995<BR>Carbone 14<BR>Oct. 21, 1995<BR>Le Carre des Lombres<BR>Nov. 18, 1995<BR>Rhythm in Shoes<BR>Dec. 1, 1995<BR>Bebe Miller Company<BR>Jan. 20, 1996<BR>Mark Morris Dance Group<BR>Feb. 23-24, 1996<BR>Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater<BR>March 2, 1996<BR>David Dorfman Dance<BR>May 4, 1996<BR>Jean-Pierre Perreault<BR>June 8, 1996<BR>Meredith Monk/The House<BR>TBA Spring 1996<BR>Maureen Fleming
