<p>
<hr>
<b><FONT SIZE=+2> NAFTA - Did We Hafta</FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b>A year later, a look at the treaty's effect on the local economy</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Paul Kangor</i>
<P>
On December 17, 1992, Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, Presi-dent Carlos Salinas de Gortari and President George Bush signed the North American Free Trade Agreement. <P> The ceremonies marked the end of a process that began on February 5, 1991, when the three leaders an-nounced they would negotiate NAFTA. The trade accord became effective January 1, 1994.<P> The debate that ensued over NAFTA between 1991 and 1994 was contentious. The wrangling featured the usual suspects: labor vs. big business, Democrats vs. Republicans, old manufacturing sectors vs. new high-tech industries and, of course, Ross Perot vs. Al Gore. <P> Opinions in southwestern Penn-sylvania often fell along similar lines. A common division pitted elements of the region's industrial and manufacturing past against new, thriving, export-oriented, high-tech sectors. There was concern in southwestern Pennsylvania -- as throughout the nation -- that labor-intensive manufacturing sectors would lose out to cheaper Mexican labor. Conversely, the premise was    that high tech -- an area in which southwestern Pennsylvania has a distinct advantage over Mexico -- would benefit. <P> A year and a half later, the jury's still out. <P> "I wouldn't want to say anything at this point," says Jack Shea, director of organization for the International Union of Electrical Workers, a local affiliate of the AFL-CIO. "It's too early. But we may look over our shoulders a few years from now; just like we look back and see how we've lost out in radios, TVs and footwear." <P>"It's too early to see the broad picture," says Martha Harris, the deputy secretary of trade, technology and economic development for the Pennsyl-vania Department of Commerce. <P> "But there have been benefits in some industries." <P> There are some roadsigns. Post-NAFTA numbers show significant in-creases in state exports to Mexico and Canada. Anecdotal evidence points to local companies that have benefited from the agreement: some with years of experience in Mexico and others enticed by new opportunities, particularly in the environmental technology sector. Their preliminary response to NAFTA just might be "ole." <P> 
<font size =+2><B>NAFTA Defined: </B></font size> The implementation of NAFTA creates a free trade area in North America that is the largest of its kind in the world, with a combined GDP in 1992 of $6.9 trillion and 368 million consumers. Over 15 years, tariffs on goods originating in Canada, Mexico and the United States will be eliminated. <P>Before NAFTA, trade and investment between the United States and Mexico was increasing rapidly. Between 1986 and 1991, U.S. merchandise exports to Mexico rose by 168%, from $12.4 billion to $33.3 billion. As of 1992, Mexico was our third largest trading partner. <P>Before NAFTA was signed, the majority of studies showed a positive net effect. One of the best known studies was by G.C. Hufbauer and J.J. Schott, who found that NAFTA would result in the net addition of 609,000 jobs in Mexico and 130,000 in the United States in 1995. The U.S. Department of Labor and KPGM Peat Marwick both estimated gains of 60,000 jobs in the United States over 10 years. <P>Studies indicate the U.S. sectors expected to experience the largest gains from NAFTA: capital goods, chemical goods, pharmaceuticals, metals, agriculture and transportation equipment, including both finished automobiles and components for assembly. In regard to U.S. wages, most studies estimate gains by workers in high-wage segments of the work force and a decline for those in low-wage categories. <P>"Our estimates were that the first wave of dislocation would be mid-range, assembly, low-wage jobs," says Gary Hubbard of the United Steel Workers of America. "Everybody, including the Department of Labor, believed those would take the first hit." <P> 
<font size =+2><B>PA Projections: </B></font size> Despite rampant national prognosticating, few projected NAFTA's regional effects. A September 1992 study by The Trade Partnership in Washington, D.C., said Pennsylvania trade with Mexico "would be accelerated and strengthened" as a result of NAFTA, estimating job gains offsetting losses almost five-to-one. <P>The study claimed benefits would be spread throughout the Pennsylvania economy. Manufac-turing would gain from improved market access and competitiveness, while market opportunities would be expanded for Pennsyl-vania banks, insurance companies and transportation firms.The study projects that NAFTA will stimulate $294 million in business for Pennsylvania exporters over a 10-year period -- an average of $29.4 million per year -- and expand employment in Pennsylvania by more than 10,300 new jobs over 10 years. <P>Few studies narrow the focus to southwestern Pennsylvania. A lone April 1994 study by Carnegie Mellon University concluded that, in general, NAFTA will have a "marginal" effect on the region. <P>"It's really hard to get data," says the Pennsylvania Department of Commerce's Harris. "We need to bring the tracking mechanisms up to speed." <P>
<font size =+2><B>NAFTA Negatives:</B></font size> There is, however, some trackable evidence. Since NAFTA took effect, a number of U.S. companies and employee groups have filed petitions with the U.S. Department of Labor, which promised compensation to those hurt by the accord. Following the first six months of the trade pact, Pennsylvania led the nation with 26 petitions, seven of which were certified, 13 turned down and six pending. <P>"That's a fact," says Shea. "Those are things that we knew would happen. There's nobody protecting our good U.S. jobs. They're shifting production to the low-wage areas. Where would you locate a company if you could get your labor for $1 to $2 per hour without paying benefits?" <P>But using wages as a rationale for a company's location decision ignores other critical factors, such as worker productivity. According to the U.S. Department of Labor, Mexican wages are about eight times lower than American ones -- a difference offset by the fact that the average American worker is roughly eight times as productive as the average Mexican. <P>But Shea's point has some merit. <P>Take, for instance, the maquiladora program. Under the 25-year-old program, U.S. firms manufacture components that are shipped to Mexico for assembly by 560,000 Mexican workers in 2,200-plus maquila plants along the Mexican border. Finished products reenter the United States for packaging and redistribution by, say, General Motors. <P>American firms find maquilas attractive because of lower Mexican wages and a favorable tariff differential. Critics cite a loss of U.S. jobs to plants characterized by overcrowding, pollution and faulty infrastructure. <P>"We don't make radios anymore, and very few TVs," argues Shea. "We're losing them to offshore assembly in places like maquiladoras, where you have people working on dirt floors."Gary Hubbard expresses similar sentiments: "I don't want to give the appearance that we're opposed to trade. We recognize its value. But our concern is the exploitation of workers, Americans and Mexicans." <P>Those who favor NAFTA are not surprised by the fact that some labor groups have been adversely affected by the trade accord. <P> "You can't fight the structural differences in the economy," says Harris. "But the whole idea of free trade is that you try to create more advantages and more open markets." <P>Kathleen Lynch, program manager at the World Trade Center Pittsburgh, seconds that notion: "No one likes to see unemployment and dislocation. But the reality of the global economy is that those changes would take place anyway in industries of comparative disadvantage.""That's nothing more than a way for them to justify [support] for NAFTA," Shea retorts. "You have to be out there with the people losing the jobs. Go to the Mon Valley. Look at Home-stead, Braddock. People are going to say [those losses] would have happened anyway? We're giving away our industrial base. Our kids can't find jobs." <P>Some industries have been hurt in the near term by NAFTA, such as PPG Industries. Before the trade accord, PPG glass faced a 20% tariff in Mexico. While that tariff is now 16% and will be eliminated completely within 10 years, the U.S. tariff on Mexican glass was immediately reduced to zero. <P>At the end of 10 years, tariffs on glass will be zero for both countries. In the meantime, the tariff differential is hurting PPG's ability to compete with Mexican glass. As a result, company officials are lobbying for a quicker tariff reduction. <P>"The bailout package would have been a very good bargaining chip [to eliminate the glass tariff quickly]," says Kears Pollock, PPG vice president of coatings and resins. Apparently, the Clinton administration did not agree. <P>
<font size =+2><B>The Good News:</B></font size> On the sunny side of NAFTA, Pennsylvania exports to Mexico and Canada reached record levels in 1994, jumping 30.6% from 1993. Mexico, absorbing $853.8 million in Pennsyl-vania exports, is the state's second largest export market, surpassing Japan and the United Kingdom, according to data from the U.S. Census Bureau's Foreign Trade Division. Exports were up in 23 of the 32 standard industry classifications that cover state exports to Mexico. <P>Of the 12 Pennsylvania industries that exported over $10 million in merchandise to Mexico in 1993, all but three saw gains in NAFTA's first year. Big increases in state exports to Mexico are among industries in the capital goods area -- specialty metals, computers, chemicals and electronics -- which potentially confirms predictions of those who stated that such sectors would be among those to benefit most from more open trade with Mexico. <P>"That's probably true," says Harris. "But I'm not comfortable in making a direct cause-and-effect leap. The im-plementation of the agreement is still early. It takes a while to develop international markets." <P>Beyond numbers, the experiences of local companies venturing into Mexico register distinct opportunity. High technology companies, in particular those from our environmental products and services cluster, are finding their services distinctly in demand. <P>"In any market things can happen quickly to alter the trends," says Lynch. "It may be too early to say that we'll have record export numbers each year, but the majority of the indicators are saying that Mexico will continue to be a growth market of opportunity, particularly in high-tech areas, such as environmental cleanup technologies. The word we're getting from Mexican officials is that there's a real sincerity about enforcement [of environmental standards]." <P>Provisions within the NAFTA environmental side agreement are forcing Mexico to impose tighter environmental standards and establish a Com-mission for Environmental Coopera-tion to ensure domestic enforcement of environmental laws. <P>
<font size =+2><B>Higher Standards:</B></font size> NAFTA could spur a multi-pronged interest in environmental cleanup. <P>"Goods and services will become more available [to Mexicans]. As consumer markets improve -- raising the standard of living -- that's going to improve municipal markets. People will become more concerned and de-manding of municipal governments to improve quality of life," says Tony Callery, international manager at the 150-employee F.B. Leopold Company Inc., a Zelienople supplier to the pot-able water market with representatives throughout Mexico. "If we can help raise the standard of living for the average Mexican, [the country] can become a better trade partner."Most Mexicans are a long way from being full-fledged consumers of the McKnight Road variety. But de-mands for improved quality of life could pressure local Mexican governments to deliver amenities like cleaner water for drinking, irrigation, etc. <P>This makes Pittsburgh a natural partner for Mexico: Nationally, southwestern Pennsylvania has the third largest concentration of environmental companies, according to the National Environmental Technologies Applica-tion Corp. A sector spawned from technologies developed to clean up Pitts-burgh's own industrial legacy of pollution, 850 southwestern Pennsylvania firms are directly or indirectly involved in environmental tech, counts the Pittsburgh High Technology Council. <P>
<font size =+2><B>Converting Pollution to Pesos:</B></font size> One local company capitalizing on NAFTA is 350-employee Chester Environmental, Inc., located in Moon Township. The company, a specialist in environmental engineering and waste-water treatment systems, signed a multimillion dollar contract in April 1994 to design and install sanitary and industrial wastewater purification systems in Saltillo, Mexico. Other big projects have followed. <P> "We had been very successful domestically, so about three years ago we decided to expand to international markets, such as Mexico and other areas," says Jim Hall, Chester vice president. "We exceeded gross revenue expectations of $4 million in international operations in 1994." <P>The company's decision to do business in Latin America had much to do with NAFTA and the region escaping its debt crisis of the late 1970s and early 1980s. <P>"We saw a serious need for water and sewage treatment with U.S. technology in Mexico, and went after this market," says Hall. "NAFTA accelerated the opening up of this market to us."Much of Chester's entree into Mexico was through existing clients, large southwestern Pennsylvania companies building plants in Mexico and finding they needed Chester's services to help them adhere to NAFTA's environmental provisions, adds Hall. <P>NAFTA environmental regulations were also the catalyst for a $20 million water treatment plant built by U.S. Filter Corp. for a resort community in Cuernavaca, Mexico in May 1994. U.S. Filter says that the increased security of investment rules liberalized by the Mexican government after the trade accord prompted their decision to get into the country. <P>U.S. Filter, a leading manufacturer of water treatment systems headquartered in Palm Desert, Calif., has more than 35 U.S. locations, including one in Warrendale, Pa., and 50 global sites.The construction and operation of the Cuernavaca facility created an estimated 600 jobs in Mexico and used nearly 11,000 cubic meters of concrete and 1,200 tons of steel. It created at least 15 jobs at U.S. Filter's facility in Warrendale, for an estimated $1 million in design work, and 30 jobs at the Rockford, Ill., plant to help fabricate   $6 million worth of specialized process equipment. <P>The project also spawned job creation among other southwestern Penn-sylvania companies. Due to the project, Chester Environmental received a "sizable" contract from U.S. Filter, adding jobs in the process. <P>U.S. Filter sees business potential in the privatization of municipal services and build-own-operate projects in Mexico."This project is a sign of our confidence in Mexico's growing economy and commitment to environmental protection," said Richard Heckmann, chairman and CEO of U.S. Filter. <P>Another local company poised to build from NAFTA is Calgon Carbon, which, among other things, specializes in infiltration media used for water purification and separation. The company, which has 343 local employees, estimates that 43% of its business is international, done primarily in Eur-ope but also in Japan and Mexico. <P>"We traded with Mexico well before NAFTA was proposed,"says John MacCrum, Calgon senior vice president. "NAFTA itself hasn't made much of a difference from a product standpoint. What will make a difference will be the enforcement of environmental regulations and the improvement in the Mexican economy as a result of NAFTA. The actual removal of tariffs won't make a big difference one way or the other." <P>MacCrum sees opportunity in Mexico, despite Mexico's recent economic trouble and peso devaluation. <P>"Environmental regulation and enforcement is a slow process in any case," says MacCrum. "The peso devaluation and current economic problems will slow that more. But the development of the market is a 10- to 15-year horizon anyway. Part of that [time frame] is based on the tariff phase-out. But there also are processes, negotiations for investment and investments themselves that take time. I mean, NAFTA was signed, but you don't just build plants overnight." <P>

<font size =+2><B>"Paperwork Nightmare": </B></font size> Creating a bureaucratic structure for NAFTA will take time, too."Every item sent down there now has to have a harmonized tariff schedule number," says Dom Palmieri, international sales representative for Mine Safety Appliances. "Shipments have been delayed because of rules of origin requirements -- it has been a paperwork nightmare." <P>Mexico, with its prominent coal mining industry, is a multimillion dollar market for MSA, which manufactures safety appliances. The company, with $500 million in 1994 worldwide sales, has been in Mexico since the '50s. <P>"We sell our complete line, in ex-cess of 4,500 items in Mexico. It's a very strong market for us," says Palmieri. "It translates into a lot of local jobs here in Pittsburgh." <P>Despite the current bureaucratic slowdowns, Palmieri is optimistic. <P>"It will get better and easier as time goes on," says Palmieri. "And there will be advantages, mainly in reduced tariffs. This will allow companies like MSA to compete favorably in a global market, because it saves us money. And a lot of our products are used by local environmental technology firms." <P>Like MacCrum, Palmieri is not overly fearful of the peso setback."It [has] created some interesting problems for us," says Palmieri. "Our advantage, however, is many years of experience. In order to be successful in Latin America you must be in the game for the long term and totally committed. The business climate remains good and will only get better." <P>
<font size =+2><B>911: </B></font size> Several local agencies have been set up to help regional companies negotiate the Mexican marketplace. One major player seems to be the World Trade Center Pittsburgh. <P>"On a regional level, our organization is involved in helping companies to identify opportunities in Mexico," says Lynch. The WTC sponsors matchmaking sessions to provide Pittsburgh companies with opportunities to meet privately with international representatives and discuss business partnerships, such as a recent three-day event trying to match local environmental technology companies with Latin American markets. "There are a lot of companies in Mexico looking for joint partners. It's our mission to help local firms identify and hook up with those companies." <P>The mission appears to be a common one. The Pennsylvania Depart-ment of Commerce's Pennsylvania Export Partnership Trade Event Pro-gram promotes trade, as does the WTC. The latter is part of a seven-member group of trade assistance or-ganizations called the Western Pennsylvania Export Consortium. The consortium brings together local, state and federal programs to provide local firms with access to trade assistance services, including market identification and assessment, market penetration and on-line and direct access services.Some groups are even putting their money where their mouth is. The Pennsylvania Department of Com-merce instituted the Pennsylvania Export Partnership Trade Event Program to incent small- and medium-sized manufacturers to enter the global marketplace. The program offers up to $2,500 (or 50% of eligible costs, whichever is less) for a company to attend an exhibit or international trade event. <P>"It's a great program for new-to-export companies," says Lynch. <P>But lack of coordination among these agencies might actually be hindering companies seeking to establish an international connection. A January 1994 report by Pitt's University Center for Social and Urban Research concluded that "foreign export assistance agencies tend to be small, understaffed and underfunded. Both duplication of services and gaps in services are perceived to exist. Further, the scattered and fragmented delivery of services creates barriers to firms receiving the full range of services needed. Export assistance agencies need to coordinate themselves and improve programs." <P>
<font size =+2><B>Reigning Confusion: </B></font size> Surprisingly, part of the problem in promoting exports among local firms is lack of interest. <P>"There's a psychology of fear among many small companies," says Rita L. Pollock, executive director, Southwestern Pennsylvania Regional Development Council. "[They feel] that exporting is only done by the big guys.' NAFTA has already helped to eliminate some of that fear. That's why NAFTA [has been] so important for exporting in general, not just to Mexico and Canada--it raised the awareness and stature of exporting among local companies." <P>To overcome such fears, Pollock recommends creating a "culture of ex-porting" with forums, publicity and education on its benefits. She says that  as more businesses have export success, others will gain confidence. <P>But it may be slow. "We'll do a mailing to 300 to 400 [companies], trying to tell them about a [trade] show," says Pollock. Sometimes such a mailing will gain as few as six responses. But inquiries about exporting are up since NAFTA passed, as are responses to export-oriented events. <P>This is a good sign that some local companies are beginning to understand the tangible benefits that can be achieved beyond the U.S. border. And the higher export numbers among the majority of state industries doing business in Canada and Mexico since NAFTA's implementation may be testament to the fact that the trade agreement seems to have benefited more industries than it hurt. But what does the future hold? 
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Tipping the Scales: </B></font size> What makes gaging the results of NAFTA problematic is that it is hard, if not impossible in many cases, to directly correlate NAFTA with any local economic results. <P>Relationships between the two economies were opening up long before NAFTA was signed, a benefit of the general economic liberalization begun under Miguel de la Madrid, continued under Carlos Salinas de Gortari and cemented in place by NAFTA. <P>But the focus put on U.S.-Mexico trade relationships with the negotiation and introduction of NAFTA is increasing interest on both sides. <P>"Trade would have happened regardless," says WTC's Lynch. "NAFTA provided a boost, particularly with the environmental side agreement. You've seen an acceleration in [trade among] high-tech areas because of NAFTA." <P>Clearly, debate will continue over whether or not NAFTA has been good for southwestern Pennsylvania. The troubled peso also makes gaging success difficult. <P>"I'm bullish on Mexico, though," says Chester Environmental's Hall. "The future is very strong. The need is there, it's just a matter of the financial situation being stabilized and everyone's trying to help. I think that by 1996 business will be good again." <P> In the meantime, the road to Mexico is opening up other doors, too. <P>"We've continued into other Latin American countries -- we continued to want to do business, and there was interest there [when Mexico was stalled]," says Hall. "We were positioned very well." <P>Ole.
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
