<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>
<b><FONT SIZE=+2> Westmoreland County: </FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b>A new day dawns in the east.</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Michelle Fanzo</i>
<P>
If optimism was an economic generator, the streets of Westmoreland County would be paved with gold. <P> After the wait-and-see attitudes prevalent in the early 1990s, the positive outlook for nearly every economic sector of the region is more than wishful thinking. <P> Development started looking up in 1994, but economic development officials were hesitant to prematurely predict growth for Allegheny County's neighbor to the east. This year, after a number of hospital expansions, relocation inquiries by businesses both small and large, and increasingly focused marketing campaigns, Westmoreland movers and shakers are nearly unanimous in their upbeat predictions. <P> The hot spots continue to be in the western portion of the county. Murrysville, North Huntingdon, and especially Penn Township are experiencing a combination of commercial, industrial and residential growth, spurred in great part by proximity to Pittsburgh as well as good schools and low taxes and utility rates. <P>Meanwhile, Andy Stofan, president of the Latrobe Area Chamber of Commerce, says he knows of a number of promising projects currently in the works. "What may happen here in the next few years could really make a     significant economic impact in West-moreland County. In a couple of these cases, if even one project that's currently on the boards materializes, it would really make a big difference in the community, as well as be a magnet to draw other business," says Stofan. <P>Lue Ann Pawlick, general manager of the Middle Monongahela Industrial Development Association, Inc., agrees the economic climate is improving. "I'm getting a lot of calls from companies looking for property, and everyone else is saying the same," she says. <P>Even the traditionally slow-growing northern portion of the county will soon be home to a significant riverfront development called Lighthouse Landing. "It is, in my mind, the best vote for the future of New Kensington when an individual developer invests the kind of money that this project requires," says Diane Sheets, secretary of the New Kensington Industrial Development Corporation. Developer Ron Williams is targeting completion of the project, which includes a marina, restaurant and professional complex, for fall 1997. <P>Overall, Sheets sees a healthy and growing economic climate in northern Westmoreland County. A number of smaller businesses, like Insulations Inc., have grown and are looking to move from leased space to permanent sites of their own. <P>If they can find them. Lack of developable land is deterring area growth, according to Sheets. She says the area could definitely use more spaces in the 5,000 to 8,000 square foot range as growth from other parts of the county continues to head north. <P>"I've seen the business climate improve dramatically within the last eight months," concurs Joe Sisley, marketing representative for economic development at Westmoreland County Industrial Development Corporation. The county presently has seven industrial parks, with an eighth preparing to open within a year. "We have been getting a number of inquiries in regard to the county and its industrial parks system. Many of those who call are from companies outside the county looking to expand or relocate to Westmoreland." <P>Partnerships between chambers of commerce, economic development organizations and utility companies are the key to Westmoreland's ability to adapt to a changing economic climate, says Stofan. <P>"There is great willingness to work together for common improvement, without jealousies and competitive attitudes. That makes a big difference," he says. <P>The national rise in interest rates has given many projects that were on hold initiative to get off the ground, says Sisley. He also believes a number of state programs, like empowerment zones, have made the area more attractive. Yet, with increased attention from industry and business trained upon the county, Westmoreland's shortage of developable sites has become increasingly apparent. <P>"We have more people interested than we have places to put them," says Stofan, who is hoping an upcoming renovation at the former Latrobe Diecasting Plant will partially solve that problem, at least for the central section of the county. 
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Road Trip:</B></font size>  There is more than ample land to support growth planned through the year 2015, according to a recent report by KCI Technologies, a PennDOT consultant. The trick is getting there. In Westmoreland County, crucial stretches of road are stalled in the planning stages. <P>"The only stumbling block to growth in this area remains the road system. Very simply, you can't get in and out," says Terry L. Daughenbaugh, chairman of the Transportation Committee for the Eastern Westmoreland Development Corporation. "The roads to the north and south are circuitous, twisted, two-lane highways. To the east are the Laurel Mountains, whose safety problems are well documented. To the west U.S. 30 is beginning to be congested to the point of gridlock." A trip to Pittsburgh International Airport, which now takes 87 minutes from eastern Westmoreland County, adds Daughenbaugh, is projected to take 141 minutes by 2010. <P>Many herald the Laurel Valley Expressway, a proposed 22-mile highway, as the answer to Westmoreland's transportation problems. The expressway would connect the area's air hub -- Latrobe Airport -- with its highway hub -- the New Stanton interchange of Interstate 70, the mainline Turnpike, U.S. 119 and the Amos K. Hutchinson Bypass. Current travel time from the interchange to the airport is upwards of 45 minutes, says Lynn Showalter, physical development coordinator for the Westmoreland County Industrial De-velopment Corporation. He expects travel time to be reduced to 15 minutes when the expressway is completed. <P>"Growth in the New Stanton area, especially near the Sony plant, is astounding. So the need for the Laurel Valley Expressway continues to grow," he says. <P>Larry Larese, executive director of the Westmoreland County Industrial Develop-ment Corporation, believes that 30,000 high-tech jobs can be created along the expressway corridor from the Sony plant to the county airport, but only if the road is built. A feasibility study for the new road is expected to be complete by early summer. 1998 is the earliest construction could begin. <P>Near Delmont, various sections of notoriously slow-going U.S. 22 are now being widened. When completed, the four-lane Route 22 will stretch 24 miles, from the Indiana/Westmoreland County line to the Allegheny/ West-moreland County line. Another key project coming up this year is the reconstruction of the Smithton Inter-change on U.S. 70 in South Hunting-don Township, where a 636-acre industrial park is under development. The interchange is needed to provide safe access to that park. <P>Engineering studies continue on the Kiski Valley Expressway in the northern part of the county. The project is in the preliminary engineering stage, ex-amining alternative alignments for the road. <P>"Transportation is very significant to economic development," says Sheets of New Kensington. "It's a long pro-cess that tries your patience most of the time. If you believe in the project, you have to lobby for it every chance you get." 
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Educational Outlook:</B></font size> The link between education and economic development is clear and active in Westmoreland County. The region boasts five diverse schools of higher education: Penn State New Kensington, St. Vincent College, Seton Hill College, University of Pittsburgh Greensburg and Westmoreland County Community College. <P>Rapidly changing technology has had a major impact on manufacturing industries such as those found in Westmoreland. Researchers at Penn State New Kensington proposed a Bachelor of Science degree in Electro-Mechanical Engineering Technology be offered beginning fall term 1996. The viability of offering bachelors degrees in technology management and health technology management is also being explored. <P>"Engineering technology is a high growth area in our region," says Jeffrey Arnold, director of University Relations, Penn State New Kensington. "We're working closely with people at the government level to bring the school back to the land grant purpose of the campus: to develop plans and programs that meet the needs of the community." <P>Phase I of a three phase plan to upgrade and expand campus facilities, begun in 1993, saw the completion of a new student computer center two years ago and continues this summer with the remodeling of the campus dining hall and enlargement of the kitchen. One campus classroom has been remodeled to create a multimedia classroom, offering teleconferencing capabilities among other new learning technologies. <P>Phase II, beginning July 1, includes remodeling the Advising and Counseling Center, the main entrance to the campus, the conversion of another standard classroom to a multimedia classroom, and offering a distance learning center where courses from anywhere in the Penn State system can be accessed. Additionally, the school is waiting on funding approval to begin construction on a Science and Technology Center. <P>And as of July 1, the school  has a new chief executive officer, Dr. Catherine C. Gannon, former professor of English at California State University, San Bernardino. <P>This year, Seton Hill College in Greensburg began offering a Saturday degree program that has proven extremely popular. Students can get a four-year degree by attending school year-round one day a week."For older adults already working, it's a nice way to get the degree without investing the next ten years of their lives. Many area companies are helping their employees with tuition for the program," says Linda Mitchell, director of public relations for Seton Hill. <P>"The income gap between college graduates and those holding only a high school diploma is widening in Pennsylvania," says Dr. JoAnne Boyle, president of Seton Hill, citing a recent study by the Pennsylvania College and University Research Center. At the end of the 1980s, people with advanced degrees saw their income, adjusted for inflation, rise 20% while income for those holding high school diplomas fell 13% during the decade. <P>"We knew there had been some gap, but it was a shock to see how it  had widened," says Boyle. She anticipates schools will continue to develop new ways to accommodate students' busy schedules. "It's the wave of the future for colleges." <P>Seton Hill has recently begun offering a masters degree in elementary education. Previously, teachers in the area had to drive to Pittsburgh or Indiana University of Pennsylvania for such a program. An accounting program was also started last September. <P>Westmoreland County Commu-nity College in Youngwood has also added two new programs in the past year to address changing workplace demands. An associate degree in travel and tourism has been added to the school's hospitality cluster of programs, and a commercial art and design associate degree is now part of the graphics/communications/media photography cluster of programs. WCCC works closely with the community to offer a variety of non-credit programs, such as enrichment classes in computers, languages, job skills and the arts. In February, the school began offering a non-credit truck driver training course at the request of local companies. <P>WCCC is anticipating purchasing the Pyrex Corp. building adjacent to the campus for a business and industry training center. Though the plan is not definite, the school is hoping to turn it into an incubator for small businesses.Other institutions too are taking advantage of the new economic strengths of the region. St. Vincent College in Latrobe began offering an environmental science program last year. Students choose either a science-oriented curriculum or an environmental administration program of-fered through the business department."Early signs are that this is going to be a very popular program," says Don Orlando, director of public relations at St. Vincent. The school invested $500,000 in establishing an environmental lab for the program. <P>In response to a number of requests by students and people in the surrounding community, the Univer-sity of Pittsburgh at Greensburg is now offering a bachelors degree in environmental science. In September, a communications bachelors degree, with course emphasis on speaking and interpersonal skills, will be added to the curriculum. A masters in business administration is currently under consideration as well. A preliminary survey suggests there is enough interest in the area to make the program viable, says John R. Spark, director of admissions and financial aid at Pitt-Greensburg.In May, the campus completed construction of the $8 million, 57,000-square-foot Fanny K. Millstein Library. And plans have been finalized to break ground for a $2.7 million, 102-student dormitory. Completion is expected in July 1996. 
<P> 
<font size =+2><B>Retail Tales:</B></font size>  "If you're looking for the downer in the bunch you just hit it," says Roy Houston, president of the Westmore-land Economic Development Cor-poration, of the county's retail market. Greengate Mall, located one mile west of Greensburg, has been struggling, he says, since JC Penney left last year for the greener pastures of the newly renovated Westmoreland Mall. Greengate, with about 85 stores, has not filled that space yet, and the complex is still feeling the effects of that transition.Westmoreland Mall, on the other hand, is thriving. Retail in the area is considerably better than last year, says Michael Egan, general manager of the Westmoreland Mall. In addition to gaining JC Penney, a food court and 60,000 square feet of space were added in 1994, bringing the number of retail stores in the mall to 150. <P>But downtown Greensburg struggles to keep its retail shops healthy. "I see people working together to create specialty markets," says Houston, "and I think they are, for the most part, successful. In Greensburg, the business people and others are trying to revitalize the commercial district and, frankly, it's happening. I've seen more vitality downtown recently than I've seen in years."Greensburg has benefited greatly from a number of renovation projects, such as the Palace Theater, which brings large numbers of residents downtown to eat and shop as well as to attend events. The next major renovation in the town, undertaken by the Westmoreland Trust, is the historic renovation of the downtown train station along the lines of Pittsburgh's Station Square. <P>"There are a great many stores here, yet the large majority seem to be surviving, even prospering," says Jennings F. Womack, president and CEO of Westmoreland Trust. While he says retail is as good as he's seen it in his 35 years in the business, he cautions that the market is close to saturation. 
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Healthy Healthcare:</B></font size> Hospitals in Westmoreland Coun-ty continue to have significant impact on their surrounding communities. Latrobe Area Hospital in Latrobe had 1,305 full-time employees (excluding physicians) last year and paid out $54 million in salaries, benefits and specialty physician services. The facility continues its expansion and upgrades with a new addition to the maternity ward, called the Women's Suite. This area offers all private rooms for women's services, including the opportunity for women to deliver babies in their rooms in a more comfortable atmosphere than the traditional operating room.Frick Community Health Center in Mount Pleasant, employing 788 full- and part-time employees, paid out   $25 million in salaries and benefits last year. Currently the medical center has two projects under way -- a $2 million OB expansion and renovation and a   $1 million infrastructure upgrading -- and will be opening a Skilled Nursing Unit this summer. <P>In the last 14 months, Monsour Medical Center in Jeannette has doubled patient volume, added a mobile MRI service, expanded the in-patient child and psychiatry unit, physically updated its facilities and purchased a new mammography machine and special equipment for cardiac studies. Home health services have increased to include psychiatric services and physical and occupational therapy. <P>Monsour employs 325 full-time employees -- and at the end of the last fiscal year, June 30, 1994, had paid out $9.2 million in salary. <P>Another strong presence in the county's healthcare landscape is Jeannette District Memorial Hospital, which paid out $17.7 million in salary and wages to approximately 700 employees last year. In the past 12 months, the hospital has opened an 11-bed New Skills Nursing Center, the Joslin Center for Diabetes, a satellite of West Penn Hospital, and a Center for Sleep Disorders, also a satellite affiliated with West Penn. 
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Development News:</B></font size> Jobs are being created in the area, resulting from both new businesses and the expansion of existing businesses. Following is a rundown of some activities in the works: 
<DL>
<DT><DD>Sony Electronics Inc. plans to build a $300 million glassmaking facility at the East Huntingdon Township plant, where it currently assembles rear-projection televisions. The expansion will create at least 500 additional jobs at a site that will employ 1000 by the end of 1995. <P>At press time, Sony said it expects to begin building the facility in October, with glass production commencing within two years. Outside of a few top management and technical positions, most of the positions will be filled with local candidates. Hiring will begin late in 1996. <P>Volkswagen used the plant to assemble Rabbits for a decade before bailing out in 1987. When Sony announced in 1990 that it would occupy the plant, it projected an 1,800-person workforce. <P>The glass plant is a partnership be-tween Sony and Corning Asahi Video Products Co. and will be called American Video Glass Co. Sony said it needs the new plant to offset a current shortage of picture tube glass in the U.S. and to meet an expected demand explosion. Sony currently gets its picture tube glass from Corning Asahi's other plant in State College, Pa.
<HR>
<DT><DD>A Pennsylvania Industrial De-velopment Authority loan has just been processed for Koppers Industries of Pittsburgh, a producer of carbon compounds and treated wood products. Koppers will purchase a coke plant in Monessen from Sharon Steel Corp., creating 223 jobs, according to the Middle Monongahela Industrial De-velopment Association. 
<HR>
<DT><DD>Founded in 1993, Take 2 is a cutting-edge computer company in the midst of quiet, bucolic Latrobe. The team of 27 employees (affiliated with a New York office) has rapidly  and   successfully moved into the interactive CD-ROM arena, developing popular video games such as Star Crusader and Hell. 
<HR>
<DT><DD>Halmar Robicon, producer of motion control equipment for sewage treatment plants, is nearing completion of its new building in the Westmoreland Business and Research Park in the northern part of the county. The 350-person firm, currently located in the Plum Boro area, expects to move operations in early summer. 
<HR>
<DT><DD>DreamForge Intertainment, manufacturer and creator of computer games, is a major success story in the region. In five years, the company has grown from the three founders working out of a garage to 25 employees working in the old News Dispatch building in Jeannette. Staff is expected to expand to 40 by summer's end. 
<HR>
<DT><DD>The old Latrobe Diecasting Plant was purchased recently by Bill Hurt of Pittsburgh. A complete overhaul is planned for the site, which requires extensive environmental cleanup. "They're doing a beautiful job in   terms of rehabilitating and reusing a significant old industrial site," says Stofan. 
<HR>
<DT><DD>A $1.1 million Pennsylvania Economic Development Financing Authority loan was recently secured for Sun Star Inc. in Youngstown, a new company that manufactures plastic injection molds for the medical and electronic industries. The total project was $2.2 million and will employ 45 people over the next few years. 
<HR>
<DT><DD>Vraco Inc., Laurel Interiors, Latrobe Leasing & Supply Co., Inc., and Laurel Construction Group are companies owned by Robert Vrable. More than 33 employees are part of the various companies, located in the former Kennametal building, which Vrable purchased after that company vacated following a recent consolidation. An outside business, Invotech Manufac-turing, makes collapsible chests for the military and mirrors for HUMVY vehicles. Employment is presently at 45, but may increase to 100 to 150 in the near future. 
<HR>
<DT><DD>Versatech, a machine shop in the tool and die business with 60 employees, is a new addition to Penn Township this year. A few companies have signed option agreements in Westmoreland Business and Research Park. Canon Boiler Work and Indus-trial Warehouse Supply have both signed options in the same park. 
<HR>
<DT><DD>Clive Cutler, an Australian born businessman, recently bought the abandoned Vulcan Valley site in Latrobe. While some antiquated facilities are being razed, others are being rejuvenated for future development. 
<HR>
<DT><DD>Crown Cork and Seal, a $7 billion Philadelphia company, recently purchased New Stanton-based plastic manufacturer Constar. The company will continue to operate under the Constar name. No expansion or downsizing is expected.
<HR>
</DL>

<HR>
