</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<hr>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Banking: Your Number's Up</B></FONT></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Rising interest rates threaten an industry swelled by good times past.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Richard Bierck</i>
<p>
Since the heady refinancing days of 1993, residential mortgage lending has returned to earth -- with a crash. <P> From 1991 through 1993, plummeting interest rates sent business soaring. Despite a slight decline in the first half of 1995, rates in May were still substantially higher than in the salad days of 1993. Area mortgage bankers complain that public perceptions of interest rates, tinted by doubts about rate stability, are holding buyers back despite a bountiful inventory of unsold homes.While down periods with less-than-sexy rates are hardly new to veteran companies, today's mortgage market is uncommonly crowded. For between 1990 and the first quarter of 1995, the number of first mortgage bankers licensed by the commonwealth more than doubled, as did the number of first mortgage brokers. <P> "There are too many people in the industry right now. It's the most intense I've seen it in my career," says Jack F. Karaszewski, senior vice president of PNC Mortgage, a subsidiary of PNC Bank. <P>The competition is cruel. 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Boom Babies:</B></FONT SIZE> The refinancing boom that birthed many of these companies was brought on by rates that began dropping in 1991 and hit a regional 25-year low of about 6.75% on 30-year fixed mortgages (with three points) in October 1993. <P>To the industry, such rates were nothing less than providential. Two out of 3 trillion mortgage holders nationwide raced to refinance, finding mortgage companies understaffed and backlogged as they stumbled over themselves to handle the onslaught of applications. <P> The industry expansion was as frenetic. On Dec. 31, 1990, 88 first-mortgage bankers and 277 first-mortgage brokers held licenses from the Pennsylvania Department of Banking. <P>By the end of 1993, refinancing still going like gangbusters, the numbers had increased to 142 licensed mortgage bankers and 524 brokers. Though figures specific to western Pennsylvania are not kept, anecdotal evidence suggests that the increase in licenses was at least as great in the region as it was statewide. <P> And it didn't stop there. There were still moderate increases in 1994, when the totals rose to 187 licensed mortgage bankers and 638 brokers. In the first quarter of 1995, the number of brokers increased to 663, but the number of mortgage bankers decreased by five, to 182. (These figures do not include commercial banks and thrifts, which are chartered by the federal   government.)
<P> 
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>That Was Then, This is Now:</B></FONT SIZE> Enter the Federal Reserve. Concerned that rapid economic growth would trigger inflation, the Fed elevated interest rates seven times between early 1994 and the first quarter of this year. The local result: an average rate approaching 9% in mid-December, the highest since 1990. Rates decreased somewhat this year, with the average local price of a 30-year fixed loan sliding below 8% in early May, down from 8.53% a year earlier. But the mortgage business remains a crowded forest with less game: Mortgage companies are, by necessity, leaner, hungrier and far more aggressive. <P>"There had been a tremendous growth in the industry, of mortgage brokerage firms that were thriving in the refinancing market. When that volume dissipated, you found a lot more brokers competing for the traditional mortgage business," says Jerry Tegethoff, branch manager with Chase Manhattan Mortgage Corporation. <P>Though the number of mortgage companies operating in Pennsylvania has increased since 1991, employment in the industry has been dwindling in recent months. Western Pennsylvania's mortgage industry is projected to shed 25% of its jobs. <P>"A lot of people have taken a close look at their operation and made cuts. We have made cuts. Everybody has," says Mark Steele, president of Howard Hanna Financial Services. <P>It's not as bad as it could be. Jonathan Gray, an analyst for the West Coast firm Sanford C. Bernstein & Co., has predicted that up to 40% of the nation's mortgage banking professionals will lose their jobs by late this year. 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Perception, or Reality?:</B></FONT SIZE> One obstacle that mortgage companies are seeking to overcome is what they call the "perception" of high rates. <P>"After the rate spike of early 1994, there ensued an interest rate shock that consumers perceived through the media -- I don't know how well-founded it was, but it happened just the same," says Tegethoff. <P>In late May, the best regional rates on 30-year fixed mortgages were around 7.5%, with three points. But to the chagrin of mortgage lenders and realtors, the perception of high rates has persisted despite this downtick. <P>"Consumers reach a comfort level with interest rates," says Diane Cipa, president of the Mortgage Bankers Association of Western Pennsylvania and co-owner of Family Home Mortgage in Ligonier. "They were so low for so long; folks took a step back."Howard Hanna's Steele adds: "I can tell you, having lived through 1979 to '83, that when rates jumped 18%, then back to 13%, 13% looked real good to a lot of people."To combat this perception, lenders are slicing prices. <P>"You're seeing the difference in pricing between competitors narrowing, and that's an indication that things are bottoming out," says Tegethoff. "If things get much lower, some won't be doing business at a profit at all." 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Blue Light Special:</B></FONT SIZE> Lower prices mean lower margins -- the difference between the cost of money to the mortgage originator and the borrower. <P>"When we talk about making prices competitive in this type of market, it's about narrowing down margins to an absolute minimum," says Steele. "If our margin was 1.5% two years ago, today it's a point or lower." <P> Some companies have cut their margins to the bone, originating loans at cost to stay in business while hoping for more lucrative days ahead. Says one mortgage lender: "These days, it's cutthroat." <P>In addition to slicing their margins to attract business, those who remain are offering discounts on add-ons such as appraisal fees, even advertising inducements such as airplane tickets. Some are courting realtors with a new solicitude, while others rush to strengthen existing alliances or seek formal affiliations with realty companies. <P>While maintaining a wide array of products has long been the strong suit of larger vendors like the big commercial banks, smaller companies are fast following suit. Many small concerns are expanding their offerings to include second mortgages, home-equity loans and mortgage loans at higher interest rates to borrowers who don't qualify for premium rates. <P>Mortgage companies are also seeking to qualify more applicants to make the most of their market. <P>"When we had so much refinancing and there was so much business, these folks probably would have been turned away," says Cipa. "But now [companies] are trying to qualify everybody." <P>Integra Mortgage Co. is even counseling applicants who don't qualify, to help them become eligible next time around. <P>"The idea is that if they don't qualify for a mortgage at this moment and they reorganize [their personal financial situations], maybe they'll qualify six months to a year later," says Tom Finnegan, Integra Mortgage's executive vice president. "We don't have a 100% batting average, of course. It's not just an income-level thing, but management of finances, keeping installment debt down and learning to save." 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Alphabet Soup:</B></FONT SIZE> For some companies, qualifying as many borrowers as possible has meant offering high-rate mortgage loans -- known as "B," "C" and "D" paper -- to applicants who don't qualify for the standard-rate mortgages, known as "A" paper. ("A" paper mortgages are those underwritten according to the tougher standards of the Federal National Mortgage Association, known as "Fannie Mae," or the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation, referred to as "Freddie Mac." These institutions purchase loans made to these standards, returning money to the market and thus permitting lenders to make more loans.)As the "A" paper market has declined, lenders, seeking new avenues of business, have been more motivated to assess risks and offset them with higher rates. Last spring, companies offering fixed rates of about 7.8% on "A" loans offered "B" paper for 11.25%, "C" paper for 12.25% and a "D" loan for 13.25%. <P>"Ten years ago, there were very few people doing this type of lending, particularly in this market," says Steele. "The West Coast has been doing it for a longer time; they are the avant-garde of lending." <P>Two payments 60 days late and one 30 days late can put a borrower in the "B" category. "C" paper loans often involve a debt-to-income ratio of 55%, or a history of multiple late payments of 90 days or more. "D" paper means customers have filed for bankruptcy. <P>As for the increased risk, Tegethoff of Chase Manhattan Mortgage, which has been handling these loans since early 1994, quotes San Francisco-based Wells Fargo Bank, one of the pioneers of "B" and "C" paper: "They say, Risk has its rewards.' <P>"Bad things happen to good people. You could have a retired steelworker who owes nothing on his home, but for one reason or another didn't pay his taxes, and the liens make him a B' or C' instead of an A,' " says Tegethoff. <P>Usually, qualified applicants for "B" and "C" paper can reorganize their finances and qualify for "A" loans a year or more later. "B" and "C" products are designed to provide a mortgage for borrowers who, for whatever reason, cannot wait. After these borrowers make timely payments on such loans for a year, their mortgage companies often refinance them into an "A" loan. 
<P> 
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Are You Being Served?:</B></FONT SIZE> Borrowers in a slackened market have the leeway to shop for service as well as price, so mortgage companies compete closely on the speed of approvals. <P>Some lenders will approve loans over the telephone, with the condition that the buyer find a home within seven days and the oral statements are verified. <P>Other programs give buyers a financing commitment within a week if they bring required documentation to a pre-qualifying interview, allowing them to close on a house in as little as two weeks. <P>In 1993, this option wasn't available. For one thing, there was a backlog. <P>"An appraisal was taking us three to four weeks and a credit report, about two weeks," says Steele. <P> In addition to speedier service, some home mortgage vendors are offering discounts. Some companies, such as Dellwood Mortgage Co., have offered discount title insurance."This has cost us money, but because the borrowers benefit, the realtor gets a happier client, and the realtors then, hopefully, bring us more business," says Kevin Laird, Dellwood vice president. <P>Conversely, some mortgage banking concerns that own title insurance companies as controlled businesses have underwritten mortgages more or less at cost to get the insurance business -- anything to pinpoint potential customers in a slow market. <P>Mortgage lenders' access to business is "diminishing as realtors form their own mortgage companies," says PNC's Karaszewski. "Everybody is looking at their sourcing." According to Karaszewski, PNC Mortgage is setting up a joint venture with Coldwell Banker that is expected to be in force later this year. <P>This alliance is being formed to take on the likes of Howard Hanna Financial Services, a subsidiary of the same holding company that owns Howard Hanna Real Estate Services. Howard Hanna Real Estate has the largest market share in Pittsburgh, and Howard Hanna Financial is the largest mortgage banking entity in western Pennsylvania not owned by a bank or thrift. <P>Mortgage lenders who don't have such arrangements with real estate companies have sought to have them tightly regulated. Last year, in response to lobbying from the National Association of Mortgage Brokers, the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development proposed regulations prohibiting real estate companies from paying their employees for referrals to their own mortgage banking firms. The proposal died a tacit  administrative death. <P>In Pennsylvania, mortgage banking interests have lobbied the state legislature to impose a requirement that such controlled companies be required to do at least 51% of their business on properties not handled by their affiliated realty companies. <P>Rep. Victor Lescovitz, a Democrat on the state House of Representatives' Commerce and Economic Develop-ment Committee, said last spring that he had considered including the measure in a broader bill to be introduced this summer. Afraid of muddying the waters for the bill's other elements, he decided against including it. <P>"It's an issue we're not going to resolve," says Lescovitz, who represents Washington and Beaver counties' 46th state House district. <P>A governmental issue that weighs more heavily on mortgage minds is the idea of dismantling the Federal Housing Administration, because of criticism that it drains tax revenues and contributes to the nation's budget deficit. As the FHA is a key underwriter of mortgage insurance for low- and moderate-income home buyers, its dissolution would mean tougher credit criteria and an even tighter market. <P> Opponents of the FHA have suggested that a private agency could replace it, but Karaszewski is skeptical: "We're not sure the private sector can take the place of what the FHA has done." <P> With or without the FHA, some believe the industry is entering a new era. They say the slackening of the market, combined with the multiplicity     of players, is creating fundamental change. There are predictions that the mortgage industry is moving toward a supermarket concept where companies, accepting the competitive reality of lower margins, will set up for higher volume and Spartan cost containment. They see the expected role of computers in helping borrowers access lenders from their homes as fitting into this high-volume scenario. <P>Others believe that the current market is a blip on the screen, and that the industry will return to margins which, though perhaps not as profitable as those of the early 1990s, are better than today's.One thing is clear. An economic Darwinism has hold of the market, and only the strong, the innovative and the lucky will survive.
<hr>
