<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2>Change is in the Air</FONT SIZE><i> By Linda A. Dickerson</i>
<P>
Smart organizations today must be chameleon-like, adapting their ways to the circumstances which surround them. This magazine is no exception. <P> Executive Report is pleased to announce the appointment of a new editorial team. Just as we went to press with this issue, Jim Urban became the magazine's new editor-in-chief, and Lydia Strohl the magazine's executive life editor. <P> Jim Urban, a powerhouse editor/ writer, cut his teeth at some of the choicest outlets in town -- from UPI to the Tribune Review to the Associated Press. Under Jim's capable leadership, the magazine will strive to provide the in-depth, analytical, business coverage that is its market niche. Jim's savvy instincts will bring readers incisive information to help them improve their businesses. <P> "Executive Report will be hard-hitting and forward thinking," said Jim recently. "I want our readers to look forward to getting it every month." <P> Working in tandem with Jim, Lydia Strohl will spark a human interest dimension in the magazine. Lydia has freelanced for many  local publications and is the Pittsburgh correspondent for Money magazine, but Executive Report readers know her best as  our healthcare reporter of many years. Her life has taken her from Athens, Greece to Tokyo, Japan and back again to Pittsburgh, and with that international perspective, Lydia will broaden our horizons and inject the magazine with a kaleidoscope of opinions. <P> "There are just as many perspectives on business as there are people, " she said to me yesterday. "We need to bring them onto our pages." <P> I am eager to work with our new dynamic duo. Executive Report, under Lydia and Jim's leadership, will provide its readers with the provocative information they need to challenge the status quo in their own thinking, in their own operations and in their own communities. So breathe deeply, Pittsburgh. Change is in the air.
