<HEAD>
<TITLE> Letters </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.L.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<font size =+2><B>An Educated Response</B></font size><BR>
Your article "Why Johnny Can't Work" in the April issue was right on target. The future of our state and our country is related closely to the work we do in reforming education. <P> Under the Goals 2000: Educate America federal legislation, Pennsyl-vania 2000 (which Governor Ridge and I co-chair) has been selected as the "State Improvement Panel" to develop a "State Improvement Plan" for K-12 education in this state.  <P> Now is the time for all educators, businesses, unions, foundations and others to join with us and make their voices heard. <BR>-- Edward Donley, former chairman, Air Products & Chemicals, Inc., Allentown, Pa.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Welcome To Cyberspace</B></font size><BR>
Imagine my surprise and delight to see Pittsburgh so wonderfully represented on the 'net. <P> I lived in Pittsburgh for over 20 years. It was a sad moment when I had to leave. The corporate tax structure stifled my fledgling PC-based software support and development company just on the verge of knocking the socks off the mainframe-entrenched corporations in Pittsburgh. <P> Your recent article on the strikes and Pennsylvania tax structure ("Opportunities Lost," February 1995) said it all. The corporation I work for is looking to buy a financial-based company.  But despite my praise for the city of Pittsburgh and its people, they will not consider any place in Pennsylvania as suitable. After all, I now live in a state that functions fairly well without a state personal income tax. <P> One day ... like so many other homesick Pittsburghers I find on the 'net ... one day, we may find employment and career opportunities once again in Pittsburgh.<BR>-- Beverly Freed, Computer Language Research, Dallas, Tx. bfreed@fasttax.com
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Corrections</B></font size><BR>
The May 1995 issue of Executive Report incorrectly listed Blair Corporation's total dividend payments for calendar 1994 ("The Pennsylvania 100," page 19). The correct figure would have been $2.05 vs. the $1.40 figure used. Please note, too, that our actual dividend total for 1994 would have merited our inclusion in your Top 10 in Dividends listing (page 16).
<BR>-- Thomas P. McKeever, vice president, employee and public relations, Blair Corporation, Warren, Pa.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>A Good Bet</B></font size><BR>
I am extremely distressed by the blatant omission of Ladbroke Racing Pennsylvania in the "Economic Devel-opment Profile: Washington County" feature (April 1995). Ladbroke Racing Pennsylvania is headquartered out of Meadow Lands, Pa. (Washington County). We own and operate Ladbroke at The Meadows and five state-of-the-art off-track wagering and dining facilities in New Castle, Greensburg, Harmar Township, Johns-town and Moon Township. We had a record year in "handle" (monies wagered or sales) in 1994 with over $300 million being wagered at our facilities. We attracted 1.3 million patrons in 1994 (more than the Pittsburgh Pirates). We directly employ 900 to 1,000 people (500 just at The Meadows) and have a payroll over    $11 million. Bottom line ... our success story began and continues to emulate from Washington County.
<BR>
-- Tony F. Mediate, director of marketing & communications, Ladbroke Racing Pennsylvania, Meadow Lands, Pa.
<HR>
