<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <FONT SIZE=+2><B>Innovative Small Banks Can Survive The Consolidation Wave</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Thomas J. O'Shane</i><P>
Innovative small banks can survive the consolidation wave.By Thomas J. O'ShaneOnly the strong will survive. That refrain has long been the law of the jungle and is quickly becoming the law of the banking industry. <P> Indications are that banking is strong. In the last three years, industry-wide earnings were remarkable. <P> But the brightness of the numbers may blind us to the facts. We cannot rest on our laurels: The remainder of the 1990s will bring unprecedented chal-lenges -- particularly for small banks. <P> Firstly, increased competition will escalate the need for change. In the not-too-distant past, banks competed against other banks and with savings and loans. Today, they compete against finance companies, mortgage companies, investment bankers and even auto-mobile and machinery companies --competitors typically facing far less regulation than banks. <P> Also, with advances in technology, banks are not just competing with local rivals, but with national and international competitors. So the challenge to keep customers is greater than ever -- particularly for small banks that may not have access to the latest technology. <P> The level of government regulation also drags on banks' competitiveness. Our company is examined on a regular basis by five different regulatory bodies, some of which duplicate services. These exams consume valuable employee and management time. <P> Further, government regulations prevent banks from marketing the same financial services that other institutions provide. For example, banks are prevented from directly providing investments, so we must do it through a third party to meet customer demand. <P>With increased competition and regulation, it is no wonder that a wave of consolidations has sharply reduced the number of banks operating in the United States. The FDIC counts less than 10,000 banks today, compared to nearly 14,500 in 1982. <P> What will it take for small banks to survive and grow as these difficult conditions continue? <P> Small banks must demonstrate the marketing savvy of big banks while capitalizing on their traditional strength -- friendly service. <P> Small banks need to respond quickly to demand for attractively priced, efficiently delivered services. Debit cards, affinity credit cards, indirect auto loans, loans by phone, touch-tone automated account access, mobile loan originators -- larger banks have led the consumer to expect them. <P> But banking customers also want the personal touch smaller banks provide. And they want to bank in their neighborhoods, where many small banks have built solid reputations over decades. Banks that can deliver this kind of service have a strong distinction from the standardization for which larger banks have been criticized. <P> In spite of the challenges facing banks in this decade, U.S. banks still are the number one supplier of credit to this country. Holding that position means committing to the path that promises success in exchange for a willingness to change. <P> Only small banks that distinguish themselves with innovation and first-rate service will survive. <P> Thomas J. O'Shane is president and CEO of First Western Bancorp, a bank-holding company based in New Castle, Pa.

<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
