<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.PMN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<h2>PHIL SCHALTENBRAND</h2>
Ever purchased a piece of souvenir pottery -- the traditional, gray and blue colonial pottery, embossed with the name of the town you're visiting? <P> It might read Old Sturbridge Village, Cape Cod, Kennebunkport, Maine, or even San Francisco, but turn it over. Chances are it's stamped "Made in Pennsylvania," and was made just south of Pittsburgh, at Westerwald Pottery in Scenery Hill. <P> Almost 20 years ago, public school art teacher Phil Schaltenbrand discovered he was making something people wanted -- hand-thrown stoneware, reminiscent of 19th century colonial pottery. <P> "It was right around the bicentennial, and I realized I had something that really appealed. It started as a spin-off business, and it just kept escalating," says Schaltenbrand. <P> Today, his company, Westerwald Pottery, ships 150,000 pieces annually, 95% of them with hand-lettering. Schaltenbrand projects 1995 sales will reach $1.5 million to $2 million. Eighty-five percent of the pieces go to towns across the country, predominantly in the east; 8% to 10% are custom decorated for companies like H.J. Heinz and American Standard, and the other 5% of business is done from the retail showroom at Westerwald Pottery, on scenic Route 40. <P> Westerwald has 30 employees, who make everything from traditional functional pieces like pitchers and pots to more modern creations such as lamps and chip'n dip platters, all in Westerwald's signature blue and gray stoneware. Stamped with a potter's mark, signed and dated, each individual piece undergoes a minimum of 12 separate hands-on processes. Wheel-thrown, brush-decorated and kiln-fired, pieces are originals and meant    to be used. In fact, Schaltenbrand suggests the pottery be passed on to future generations. <P> "There's no substitute for hand work," says Schaltenbrand, who has authored two books about pottery: "Old Pots: Salt Glazed Stoneware of the Greensboro-New Geneva Region," published in 1979, and "Stoneware of Southwestern Pennsylvania," which will be published in the fall by the University of Pittsburgh Press. "With the Made in Pennsylvania' stamp embedded in each piece, people can do a history of our pottery 100 years from now."	-Dorothy Yagodich
<HR>
<B>Occupation:</B> Founder and president, Westerwald Pottery. <BR>Professor of art,  California University of Pennsylvania
<P>
<B>Family Life:</B> Lives with wife Kathy and daughter Cassandra in Scenery Hill, Washington County, on 110 acres that was once a horse farm
<P>
<B>Age:</B>52
<P>
<B>Education:<P> Kutztown University, Tyler School of Art at Temple University
<P>
<B>Hobbies:</B>Golf, raising llamas
<B>Last Vacation: </B>Visiting Civil War battle sites in Virginia
<B>Last Book Read: </B>"Thomas Mellon and his Times" by Thomas Mellon
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
