<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ED.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><b>Once Upon a Suburb:</B> </FONT> <BR>The Stone Mansion Offers Innovative Cuisine And An Extraordinary Wine List.<BR>
<i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
<HR>
Owner Don Mervis, former manager of Rico's, has remodeled and reopened the former Gryphon, in Wexford, as the Stone Mansion. He types his offerings as "continental." <P> "I wanted to do something different. My criteria to Michel [Wetli, executive chef] was I don't care what you put on the menu, but it has to be delicious,' " says Mervis. "In this business, you're only as good as your last dinner." <P> The building itself is a 1930s mansion, built by former Allegheny County sheriff Robert Woodside. A stained glass window graces the wooden staircase, which leads down to a kaleidoscope of dining rooms and retains the wandering feeling of an old home. <P> Disappointingly, though, the main dining room is sterile, with a dropped ceiling and a view of the air treatment system. But we had a small corner table, perfectly proportioned to the chairs, promoting maximum coziness. Dining al fresco, which Mervis has planned for the summer, will be a welcome alternative. <P> It is the food that really commands your attention here. The menu is well-balanced, with something for all palates. The wine list -- 120 selections, ranging from benign to adventuresome, with prices to match -- is one of the most exciting in the region. <P> Among the more interesting appetizers was a duck strudel, offset by a common fried zucchini. Sea scallops Gorgonzola was perfectly cooked and complemented by a rich creamy sauce. Wild mushrooms grigliare are marinated in a smooth, herby vinaigrette. The temperature (cold) was unexpected, but they were tasty. A pile of domestic mushrooms garnished the plate, making the helping large. <P> A house salad comes with the meal, or you can choose a more exotic offering (Caesar, mozzarella, even caponata). The house salad was over-dressed, and though the salad of hearts of palm and artichoke was wonderful, beware, for the waiters did not inform us there were no substitutions, and that added $6.25 to the bill. <P> For the entree special, Wetli, former chef at Disney World, offered parrot fish, which was cooked til moist and flaky and served on a bed of lobster cream sauce. Though the sauce was rich, it was tomato based and served under the fish, so it didn't physically or otherwise smother the wonderful flavor of the fillet. A bed of saffron and green peppercorn couscous was the perfect complement. <P> The continental menu has a wide range of meats, poultry, fish and pasta, even a grilled vegetable entree. The lamb chops montglas are to be raved about -- a thick double chop, broiled to perfection and served with a simple, rich reduction. But other diners reported lesser experiences with pastas and fish off the regular menu. <P> Mervis acknowledges the challenge in presenting elegant hand-cooked meals consistently in a restaurant with a 220 seating capacity, but says he's beginning to be satisfied."It's been a rocky road," he says. "If I was where I am today when we opened [in November], I would have unbelievable results right now." <P> Mervis is working diligently on the consistency and the menu (this is the fifth draft). To say the service is attentive would be an understatement. Upon our arrival, four valet parkers leaped from a small shed and whisked the car away. The wait staff have been trained by the same hand. Luckily, they are more like eager young boys than haughty purveyors of haute cuisine. <P> The prices are steep for this market, so those wanting a sure bet should wait a few months before venturing to the Stone Mansion. But, if consistency can be maintained, and the decor rendered a little more unique, the potential is clearly there for greatness.        
<hr>
