<HEAD>
<TITLE> ER Index </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a><P>
<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.</I>
<HR>
<H2>S&P 500 Continues to Outpace Local Stocks</h2><P>
Sometimes good just isn't good enough. Such continues to be the case for our basket of local stocks, which inched up 0.68% for the month ended May 12. But the ER Index's continuing positive returns, a cumulative 10.94% increase since inception, are lagging behind the runaway and more heavily technology laden S&P 500, which for the same periods increased 3.78% and 13.95% respectively. 
<P> 
The less than a percentage gain in the ER Index last month masked several strong individual issues, including Kennametal, which jumped 19.65% to 28 5/8 following the announcement of a 95% increase in fiscal third quarter EPS to 84 cents per share. Kennametal shares have risen nearly a third since last August. The strong gains are due to growing domestic and international demand for the company's metalworking products, as well as strong productivity gains. Perhaps most impressive is the showing of Hertel, its German subsidiary, which was acquired just last year. For the quarter, Hertel contributed 14 cents per share in earnings, vs. a loss of 2 cents last year. Quite a turnaround. 
<P> 
<DL>
<LI>Alcoa gained 11.34% last month, to 46 5/8. Aluminum companies such as Alcoa have benefited from increased demand and profitability. Chairman Paul O'Neill expects higher profits as Alcoa continues to experience increasing consumption, higher pricing and falling inventory levels. 
<LI> Legent reported fiscal second quarter EPS of 43 cents per share, falling short of Wall Street's expected 50 cents per share. However, Legent's share price gained 6.14% for the month to 30 1/4 as investors focused on the company's strategic shift toward client-server based computer software products. As we went to press, Legent was bought out by Computer Associates, but the closing price is not reflective of the closing acquisition price, which was 47.85 per share. 
<P> 
The Index also had its share of dogs for the month, three in particular. 
<LI>American Eagle Outfitters posted this month's largest decline as the company's shares fell 25.88% to 15 3/4. In early May the company revealed that it had incurred additional expenses from its rapid expansion from 176 to 274 stores this year, as well as higher than expected inventory shrinkage, the retail industry's term for stolen goods, which will significantly affect bottom line results. 
<LI>FORE Systems fell victim to profit-taking this month, declining 18.96% to 33 5/8 after announcing financial re-sults exceeding analysts' estimates. For fiscal year ended March 31, 1995, FORE's profits rose 300% to 27 cents per share on a 235% increase in sales to $75.6 million. 
<LI>MK Rail slumped amid growing realization that its troubles and those at its parent, Morrison Knudsen, were both worse than believed. MK Rail's stock fell more than 23% to 7 for the month, as the company continued to delay the release of its 1994 fourth quarter and 1995 first quarter results. Losses may include overruns for locomotive remanufacturing contracts and troubles at its Argen-tinian joint venture and its Australian operations. <P>Five companies on our list recently announced earnings that put a smile on investors' faces. 
<DL>
<LI>Astrotech International reported its fiscal second quarter EPS improved to  5 cents per share versus a 2 cent loss   last year, on an 82% rise in revenues to $28 million. 
<LI>Black Box Corp. reported record revenues and earnings for its fiscal year ended March 31, 1995. The company's EPS rose 25% to 89 cents on a 16% sales gain to $164.8 million. 
<LI>Railcar maker Johnstown America got back on track in the first quarter, reporting a 94% increase in earnings to 31 cents per share on a 91% sales gain to $178 million. Johnstown America finished off 1.02% to 12 1/8 for the month. 
<LI>Mylan Labs reported superb fiscal year end results for the period ended March 31, 1995. Net income increased 65% to $120.9 million, or $1.52 on a 57% increase in revenue to $396.1 million, as compared to revenues of  $251.8 million and net income of  $73.1 million, or 93 cents per share. Mylan finished off 7.14% for the month to 29 1/4. Since August, however, Mylan has risen more than 23%. 
<LI>PPG Industries announced an increase in first quarter earnings of 60% on an 18% increase in revenues to $1.74 billion.  
</DL>
</DL>
<HR>
<H2>Respironics' Meteny Takes a Deep Breath</h2>
Nobody needs to remind Dennis Meteny that bad things come in threes, as in Barron's, Investors Business Daily and The New York Times. Recently, each of them has taken a shot at his company, Murrysville-based Respironics, innovative maker of respiratory therapy equipment used primarily by patients with sleeping and breathing disorders. <P> The articles raised questions about Respironics' pricing, competition and insider selling. They also cast doubts about the company's credibility and integrity in light of a warning letter from the Food & Drug Administration last December regarding several areas of disagreement. The Times, for instance, insinuated that Respironics was receiving special treatment because its chairman, Gerald McGinnis, had a private meeting with Newt Gingrich. McGinnis is a charter member of Gopac, Gingrich's political action committee. <P> The Times also accused Respiron-ics of ignoring the FDA and acting illegally. Specifically, the Times says Respir-onics should have quit shipping those products addressed in the warning letter. <P> Well, I have read the letter carefully, and couldn't disagree more. Further, I have met few people with higher ethical standards than either Dennis Meteny or Gerald McGinnis. Meteny had been the company's chief financial officer until last November, when he was named     to succeed McGinnis. What an initiation it has been --  as if competititors like HealthDyne, Puritan-Bennett and Sunrise Medical aren't tough enough. <P> I don't believe it a coincidence that Respironics' short sellers -- investors who bet a stock will fall by selling borrowed shares in hopes of buying them back later at a cheaper price -- currently control more than 2.6 million of the company's nearly 17.7 million shares outstanding. How else can you explain all the negative public sentiment? Were the stories planted by some shrewd shorts? I don't know. <P> What I do know is that at this price, 13 1/2, Respironics is selling for less than 17x expected earnings for its next fiscal year (June 1996). The company has plenty of cash, virtually no debt and superb margins. I know management has consistently met or exceeded estimates. I also know the company is an attractive acquisition candidate. With all that said, it probably won't surprise anybody that Dennis Meteny seems little concerned with short sellers or rumors. In a recent meeting with institutional investors and analysts, he was low-key, confident and upbeat. What was he doing about this ruckus? Just concentrating, he said, on running the business-- the stock price will take care of itself.-- D.T.

