<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.C.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Lights, Camera, Action </B></FONT SIZE><br>
When the Lawrenceville Development Corporation approached Charles L. Desmone and Associates to assess their interest in the Pennsylvania National Bank Building, the keystone of Lawrenceville's central Doughboy Square, a package deal was not what they had in mind. <P> But like today's celebrities that produce, direct and star in their own movies, the local architecture firm saw the proposition as more than just relief to their tight quarters in a former Point Breeze beer distributorship. They took on the project not only as tenants but also as architects and part owners. <P> "It was pretty trashed," says Chip Desmone, project manager. "It had been abandoned for 12 years. Most of the windows were boarded up and there was a lot of water infiltration. There were a couple of thousand pigeons living here, so we had to do toxic waste remediation before we even started." <P> The building cost the partnership (formed by Desmone and Associates and the Lawrenceville Development Corporation) $130,000, and another $800,000 was raised to finance the renovations, which were done with such integrity that the firm was awarded the Pittsburgh Historic Review Commission's 1995 Historic Review Commission Preservation Week Award for its rehabilitation. <P> One of the last times that the building was recognized by the city was in 1980, when the area was declared "slum and blight." Lawrenceville has turned a new page since then."It really did help get development going," says Desmone, referencing an adjacent townhouse project, the NASA Robotics Consor-tium and a strip mall, all in differing stages of development in Lawrenceville. "Not a lot of people know about over here -- they tend to focus on the South Side." <P> Obviously, some people have noticed. The project also received a 1995 Historic Preservation Construction Award from the Pennsylvania Historical Museum Commission and a 1994 Honor Award from the AIA Pittsburgh Chapter.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>The Wild Blue Yonder </B></FONT SIZE><br>
The Wild Blue YonderAccording to the Tourism Works for America Report, travel and tourism is a $416 billion industry -- the largest U.S. services export industry. Figures for 1994 show that international travel-related spending within the U.S. was $75 billion. <P> Here in Allegheny County, that industry brings in $1.07 billion annually, according to Marla Meyer, director of communications at the Pittsburgh Convention and Visitors Bureau. "If you took [the revenue] from just meetings and conventions like it was one private company, it would be the eighth largest in the region," says Meyer. "3.6 million people come to Pittsburgh each year." <P> Nationally, the travel sector is the second largest employer, directly employing 5.2 million in 1993, and indirectly employing 5.4 million in that same year. In Allegheny County, 42,000 are employed in tourism -- 12,000 of those by USAir -- making it one of our top industry segments, following manufacturing, healthcare and government.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Small Businesses Make Big Gains in Employment </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Small businesses continue to take giant strides in creating new jobs for America's workers. <P> Approximately 50% of the estimated 3 million jobs to be created in 1995 will be attributed to small businesses with less than 20 employees, according to the Dun & Bradstreet Corp. annual Dun's 5,000 Survey of Employment Expectations. The surveys are based on a sample of 5,000 U.S. firms and are statistically representative of the distribution of firms by size and industry in the U.S. economy. <P> "Smaller and typically younger firms are taking advantage of the current economic strength to grow. In addition, fewer large firms plan for work force reductions; the downsizing trend has slowed and many are beginning to hire again," says Douglas Handler, manager of econometric analysis for Dun & Bradstreet. "Despite these improvements, it should be noted that these larger firms will still account for only 6% of all new jobs during 1995. Job levels seem to have stabilized, but executives predict slow growth at best." <P> Retail and service sectors exhibit the strongest expectations for job creation during 1995. Of the service sector executives surveyed, 27% said they will increase staffing levels, accounting for 35% of expected job creation during 1995. The hiring increases anticipated by 32% of retailers surveyed make up a total of 25% of all expected new jobs.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Kudos </B></FONT SIZE><br>
To Kirkpatrick & Lockhart, recipient of the 1995 Louis J. Goffman Award for outstanding pro bono work. According to Ken Argentieri of Kirkpatrick & Lock-hart, approximately 50 lawyers have spent about 1,100 pro bono hours each year since 1992.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>How Does Your Garden Grow? </B></FONT SIZE><br>
In the Netherlands, 50% of the people employed in the horticultural industry are handicapped. That's what Parkman Clancy, a retired Pittsburgh businessman, and his friends learned when exploring Clancy's idea of founding a not-for-profit that would train mentally handicapped persons for horticultural careers. <P> Presuming the concept could also work here, they formed the not-for-profit Controlled Environment Horticulture Inc. <P> "[Horticulture] is a very therapeutic environment with low stress," says George Jones, executive director. "And these tasks can be successfully accomplished by a wide variety of people. The [mentally] disabled are being asked to take a greater part in their own lives and this would allow them jobs." <P> Last fall, the group acquired a farm market and greenhouse in Franklin Park called Brookside Nursery, where 30 people are employed -- about half of them with disabilities. According to Jones, the venture is blossoming."On a scale of 10, I would give [the employees] a 9. I think the reason that I wouldn't say 10 is because they haven't worked for a period of time," says Jones. <P> But he hopes to change that: The group plans to expand the nursery into a year-round operation and set up a training facility that will perhaps even be accredited through community college. "In Maryland, the American Horticulture Assembly uses this therapeutic aspect to encourage [handicapped] employment -- and thousands of people have been placed."
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Lend Me Your Ear </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Yes, it's the '90s, and another volume has just been added to the modern library of convenience. On Craig Street in Oakland, you can take out Chinese, pizza, or a CD. Yes, that's right, a CD. <P>The Japanese have been practicing this odd tradition for years. CD Trader owner Sal Greco explains: "Call, e-mail or visit and request 10, 20 or 50 CDs and charge them to your credit card. Return the CDs you don't want within three days and pay for the CDs you keep." <P> It's the ultimate in browsing. At home or in your car. On your own time. <P> To find out more, call 687-6626 or e-mail sgreco@aol.com.
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
</BODY>
