<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Money Matters</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.MM.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>International Investing: Rationale for a Modern World</B> </FONT SIZE> <BR>
<i> By Henry a. Frantzen</i>, executive vice president and head of global investing for Federated Investors
<p>
Twenty-five years ago, the financial news on any given day ran down the Dow Jones Industrial Average, the transportation index and the blue chip issues on the New York Stock Exchange. <P> Today, we also learn whether the Nikkei Index is up, Hong Kong is off or Australia is even; what stocks did on the London and Paris exchanges, and what the dollar is doing against the yen and the deutschemark.The difference makes absolute sense, considering that in 1970, stocks issued by companies in the United States represented 70% of all the stocks in the world. Today, that ratio is reversed -- about 70% of the world's stocks are issued outside the United States. <P> In other words, the field of play in the investment game is global. Only an investor with the courage of a mountain lion would sink everything into one stock. And today, restricting investment to one regional economy creates much the same vulnerability. <P> In 1970, most people in this country had a car, television, radio and camera, all made in the United States. No one had ever heard of Club Med or Perrier Water. <P>Today, of the four major companies that produce the tires we drive on (Bridgestone, Goodyear, Michelin and Perelli), only one is a U.S. company. <P> Having an international component to an investment portfolio is one way to enjoy the fruits of our international consumption. <P> This is not a new concept. The pros started doing it about 20 years ago, and their exposure to international securities has grown measurably ever since. <P>The object of the investment game is to end up with more money than you started with. And a comparison of growth over 10-year periods for major categories of investments -- stocks, bonds, Treasury bills, collectable art, etc. -- shows that international securities are one of the fastest growing categories over the long term. <P>For example, the 1980s were a decade of remarkable growth for U.S. stocks, which rose an average of 17.4% per year. But international stocks grew 22.3% in the same period. <P>Don't be lulled into thinking anything is a sure bet. In fact, returns from international securities don't always outpace U.S. investments. <P> But over the long term, the international sector of the investment landscape is difficult to ignore, considering events of the last quarter century. <P>After two consecutive years of economic expansion, the U.S. economy may now be in a period of transition, heading toward a period of slower growth, or perhaps recession. Europe, by contrast, has just emerged from recession and seems to be returning to traditional rates of economic growth. Japan is now emerging from recession. <P>These differences provide opportunities for investors. Just turn on the financial news some time and listen. 
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
