http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0695.Feature.1.html 192.204.56.67 19970115133349 text/html 22503
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 13:38:32 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:49:55 GMT
Content-length: 22326
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Feature: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>

<img align=left hspace=5 src="0695.Feature.1.0.gif"><font size =+2><B>1994 Executive Report/Price Waterhouse Best Deal Awards </B></font size> <p>

Each year, the Best Deal Awards celebrate leadership in business, economic development and community service: leadership distinguished by singularity of achievement and potential for prosperity.<P>
For the fifth annual Best Deal Awards, a panel of dissenting judges and the sponsors, Executive Report and Price Waterhouse LLP, considered numerous nominations.<P>
Executive Report sought nominations by placing an advertisement in the magazine and mass-mailing letters and forms to business and community leaders. Judges voted on nominees via written ballots, using a point system. The votes were then tabulated and assigned to categories by Price Waterhouse.<P>

<b>The Best Deal Award winners for 1994 are:</b><P>

<b>Best Regional Impact:<BR></b>
Pittsburgh Supplier Training Center<BR>
Corporate-caliber management training is accessible to mid-sized companies.
<P>
<b>Best Merger/Acquisition:<BR></b>
Federated Department Stores Inc.<BR>
Horne's became Lazarus in a deal that hinged on more than money.
<P>
<b>Best Real Estate Development:</b><br>
Southpointe<BR>
What was once rolling farmland is now home to industries, families and golfers.
<P>
<b>Fastest-Growing Company:	<BR></b>
Fore Systems Inc.<BR>
Taking a different path, this computer tech-nology company has tapped new markets.
<P>
<b>Best Community Impact:	<BR></b>
St. Francis Health System<BR>
"The Courage to Come Back" recognizes a special kind of mettle.
<P>
<b>Best International Impact:	<BR></b>
Westinghouse Electric Corp.<BR>
An American company is now a power-producing partner with the Chinese.
<P>
<b>Most Innovative:	<BR></b>
NASA Robotics Engineering Consortium<BR>
Academic and industrial engineers work in the same shop.
<P>
<b>Quality Is Everything<BR></b><p>
<img align=left hspace=5 src="0695.Feature.1.1.gif">
For years, large manufacturing companies have established and nurtured their own mini-universities to improve suppliers' products by enhancing their quality management skills.<P>
Some of these large manufacturers have made their educational offerings more accessible around the country through the National Consortium for Supplier Training, which enables managers of smaller companies to receive training locally.<p>
The management prowess of some of the nation's most prestigious companies is now available in the form of short courses through the newly established Pittsburgh Supplier Training Center (STC).<P>
It all started in April 1994, when a group of business leaders began working together to develop a means of providing the area's base of midsize companies with quality management instruction.<P>
The product of these efforts, the Pittsburgh STC, has been accepted as a member of the National Consortium for Supplier Training. The local center will teach courses, which are the property of the National Consortium, at the center's headquarters at the Connelly Center of Duquesne University's School of Business. Some courses will be taught at company locations.<P>
"We could have 20 courses by the fall," says Barry Maciak, director of the Connelly Center. Maciak, who is also director of the Pittsburgh STC, says the center's program will begin before then with four courses.<P>
Maciak views the local availability of these quality management programs as an opportunity "primarily for companies trying to change their management style by working toward total quality management: producing the highest quality product at the most affordable cost exactly when the company needs it by empowering the work force to identify and solve problems, reduce waste and improve efficiency."<p>
The local availability of the courses will make them not only more accessible geographically but also financially. "If you went to, say, Eastman Kodak Co. for a course, you might pay $550. The same course [taught in Pittsburgh] through the consortium would be only about $150," says Jay Duffy, manager of training and development for Bayer Inc., the center's primary sponsor.<P>
A key distinction of the Pittsburgh center is the multiplicity of sponsor companies - a total of 11 - compared with other consortium training sites around the country, most of which have one or two sponsors.<P>
"This is a relatively new model for supplier training centers around the country, and the team of sponsors is growing," Duffy says. "We hope to add five to 10 more. The fact that we have so many major local companies involved means a tremendous number of suppliers will benefit because their customers will ask them to take advantage of these courses."
<P>
<b>Acquiring Tradition<BR></b>
When executives of Federated Department Stores Inc. were negotiating for the acquisition of Joseph Horne Co. Inc. by the Lazarus chain, they were aware they were dealing with a venerable Pittsburgh retailing institution.<P>
With 145 years in Pittsburgh, the eight Horne's stores were as much a part of the Iron City as the Mount Washington inclines or the Smithfield Street Bridge.<p>
Sensing Horne's desire not to turn its back on Pittsburgh, Federated knew its acquisition-by-merger offer was being judged on far more than the face value of $123 million in cash and notes.<P>
"Other companies were interested in the acquisition," says Jerry Gafford, Lazarus' senior vice president of corporate affairs. "I can't tell you unequivocally that ours was the best deal."<P>
Financially, that is. But, Gafford adds, Lazarus was willing to give more than money.<p>
"It was not just a willingness to pay x' number of dollars, but a concern for associates and customers. They wanted people who would do the right thing, and we have a great history of corporate citizenship," says Gafford.<P>
Federated completed the acquisition of the Pittsburgh stores and two Horne's locations in Erie in May without imme-diate layoffs.<P>
"We weren't going to transfer [employees] around. We didn't want to do that," says Gafford.<P>
Mike Trafford, regional vice president for Lazarus, said that Pittsburgh was a natural place for Federated to set up shop.<P>
"For one thing, there wasn't a Federated retailer in Pittsburgh," he says. "For another, Pittsburgh was a natural geographic location [for Cincinnati-based Federated] because of its stores in the region." Federated has stores in neighboring West Virginia and Ohio.<P>
Despite this, Gafford adds, "coming to Pittsburgh gave us pause. It would be as if someone came into Ohio to change the Lazarus name. So we obviously have a challenge in overcoming that obstacle for several years to come. It will take us a couple of years to do the kinds of things we need to do in Pittsburgh - to show we're here for the long term."<P>
One of those things is something Horne's couldn't afford: remodeling the stores. Lazarus' $85 million remodeling plan, including virtual remakes of locations in Monroeville and suburban Pittsburgh's South Hills, got under way from the outset.<p>
"We decided to defer some of the grand opening hype until we open the South Hills [store] in October," says Trafford. The Monroeville store is to open in March 1996. "We didn't want a major grand opening because we're still putting our stamp on Pittsburgh."<P>
Nevertheless, Lazarus' arrival in Pittsburgh was obvious to all but ostriches, as the company advertised heavily in an autumn campaign that melded into Christmas season blitz.<P>
Gafford says the advertising budget was nothing out of the ordinary for an acquisition, though it was "a little larger at Christmas than the norm."
<P>
<b>Industry Goes Rural<BR></b>
In the mid-1980s, there lay in Washington County 600 acres of state-owned property not unlike much of the rolling land that abounds in southwestern Pennsylvania.<p>
Its raw beauty carried a downside for development, as it was unserved by utilities and roads. Yet the parcel's proximity to I-79 - it was contiguous to the interstate's right-of-way - offered enormous development potential, assuming the construction of an interchange nearby.<P>
The interchange has since been built. The land was purchased by Washington County for $706,710 and turned over to the county's redevel-opment authority in 1985.<P>
What were once farm pastures are now golf course fairways. And the previ-ously inaccessible property in unassum-ing Cecil Township is now the address of some big corporate names, employers of more than 700 people. Some upscale housing has also been built.<P>
Rod L. Piatt, president of Millcraft Investments Inc., Southpointe's marketing agent, says it's the first development in the tristate area to combine light industrial, recreational and residential uses. He remembers some skepticism that the local market would tolerate the concept.<P>
Yet the faith of Millcraft and Washington County officials in the project was well invested. By the end of 1994, six industrial clients had purchased sites from the county and built plants ranging from Digital Concepts' $1.3 million investment in 21,000 square feet to AEG Automation's $19 million stake in 220,000 square feet.<p>
The first corporate resident at Southpointe was Accutrex Products' headquarters, encompassing 66,000 square feet. Neighboring structures include Digital Concepts' headquarters, and facilities for Mitsubishi and Stevens Painton. Early this year, they were joined by several other corporate tenants, including the Pittsburgh Penguins, whose organization has built a 100,000-square-foot training center comparable to the Steelers' Latrobe redoubt.<P>
One reason for the commercial response is the 100%, five-year tax abate-ments the county was able to offer after financing infrastructure improvements with $5 million raised through a bond issue and another $2.5 million obtained in state and federal grants.<P>
Equally compelling, Piatt says, is the location: 20 miles from Pittsburgh International Airport and 16 miles from downtown Pittsburgh, with nary a traffic signal along the way.<P>
Robert Umstead, executive director of the Washington County Redevelop-ment Authority, says the key to tapping this location's commercial potential - and, concomitantly, increasing the county's tax base - was persuading state officials to build the interchange nearby. The commonwealth had already been planning to place a new interchange somewhere between Canonsburg and Bridgeville. Getting state officials to build it near Southpointe, Umstead says, "was one of the big hurdles."<P>
Had the interchange been built elsewhere - or if Millcraft hadn't focused on the land that is now Southpointe - the project might never have been realized. Says Piatt: "We really didn't have any other parcels in mind."
<P>
<b>Gone Public<BR></b>
<img align=left hspace=5 src="0695.Feature.1.3.gif">
Five years ago, four computer scientists from Carnegie Mellon University formed a company, with no additional employees, to design and manufacture systems to speed the transfer of information over computer networks.<p>
In typical computer parlance, they named their company in cryptic capitals representing the first names of the founders: Francois J. Bitz, Onat Menzilcioglu and Robert D. Sansom, each a vice president and director, and Eric C. Cooper, chairman, president and chief executive officer.<P>
Yet there has been nothing typical about the market's rapid acceptance of Fore's products, nor anything cryptic about its meteoric growth.<P>
Gross sales rose from $111,000 in 1991 to $23.5 million in the year ending March 31, 1994. The company reported that sales reached $75.6 million in the year ended March 31, 1995.<P>
The Warrendale-based concern went public in May 1994, and its stock sky-rocketed from the initial price of $16 per share to $70 per share just before a two-for-one split in late December. The April 17 issue of Fortune listed Fore Systems as the fourth fastest-growing company in the country. And as of late April, Fore's work force had grown from the four founders to more than 360 employees.<P>
Indeed, remarks Don Reckles, public relations manager, it's a company that would seem more at home in the Silicon Valley than in the Ohio Valley.<P>
Fore's success began with an early, tight grip on the theretofore untapped commercial market for solutions to local area networking problems through asynchronous transfer mode (ATM) technology.<P>
The company's initial products derived from a research and development contract with Naval Research Laboratories, according to Reckles. The four founders, who retained the patents on the innovations developed for the Navy labs, started shipping products in November 1991.<P>
Fore's prominence in the market is attributable, says Reckles, to the compa-ny's development of technology to ease networking between computers or different groups of computers in local areas - systems separated by relatively short distances.<P>
"Most people were concentrating on wide area networking. These guys took the other viewpoint. They saw it sooner than others," Reckles says.<P>
Another reason Reckles cites for Fore's jackrabbit start is its development of individual systems that could handle the network transfer of information in different forms: data, video, imaging and voice.<P>
Asked how Fore plans to stay competitive in a specific ATM market now hotly contested by the likes of IBM and Digital, Reckles contrasts his company with the others, citing its singular focus: "ATM is what we do - that's our business."
<P>

<b>The Courage to Come Back<BR></b>
I looked around,<BR>
The care, the love I found<BR>
Gave me the courage to come back.<BR>
<P>
Thus wrote Ray Werner, now chair-person of St. Francis Health System, when it launched "The Courage to Come Back" eight years ago.<P>
The lines are lyrics in the theme song of the program that annually bestows awards on individuals who have overcome spiritual defeat from illness or accidents. Presented at an annual dinner each spring that last year packed in more than 900 people, the awards are a recog-nition of triumph over the toughest kinds of adversity.<P>
The program has raised nearly $1.8 million from corporate sponsorships and the awards dinners. The money goes to pay for medical care for the indigent at St. Francis Medical Center.<P>
Werner says his inspiration for the theme song was the mettle possessed by each award winner.<P>
"One of the main reasons we do this is to get these people's stories in front of other people - there's poetry here, rich poetry. All you have to do is hear them say thank you to 900 people in a room so quiet you can hear a pin drop. To be a poet is to be heard, to let them know their lives mean a lot to other people," says Werner.<p>
Whether incredible or merely inspirational, the stories of the program's award winners are heartening.<P>
For example, there's Anthony Razzano, 19, who wasn't expected to survive the burns he received over 85% of his body in an accident at his New Castle home at the age of 12. Forty-plus operations later, and without fingers on his left hand, Razzano is playing football for New Castle High School, resuming the game he'd so desperately wanted to play at the time of the accident.<P>
And there's Bob Commer, 28, of Johnstown, a former 312-pound alcoholic and chain smoker who suffered heart attacks and a stroke. He's since been immortalized with more than 11 entries in the Guinness Book of World Records for rope-jumping milestones that include a 37-hour marathon.<P>
Rocky Bleier, the program's honorary chairman, knows a lot about coming back. After Bleier sustained severe leg wounds from shrapnel in Vietnam, doctors told him he would never play football again. He ignored this prophecy and worked to become a key player on the legendary Steeler team that brought home Superbowl trophies in the 1970s.<P>
The broadcasting of such capsuled narratives on radio and television has brought their subjects into one-on-one contact with similarly afflicted individuals in need of support.<P>
Says Senior Vice President David T. Dombrowiak: "People call after hearing things on television or radio and we try to hook them up."<P>

<b>Sino-American Generation<BR></b>
There are three ways a nation can increase its capacity to generate electric power: It can manufacture its own equip-ment to build additional new plants; it can import this equipment; or, it can use domestic resources to upgrade existing plants.<P>
When Westinghouse Electric Corp. signed an agreement with the Shanghai Electric Corp. last year, Westinghouse had become involved in all three means of generating increased power capacity in the People's Republic of China.<P>
Under the agreement signed in August 1994, Westinghouse committed an investment of about $100 million for a 35% stake in power generation equipment.<P>
U.S. Secretary of Commerce Ronald Brown, who signed the agreement in Shanghai along with Westinghouse CEO Michael Jordan, praised the joint venture as an exemplary international economic partnership.<P>
This deal and a 1993 joint venture agreement Westinghouse signed with the Chinese government are the first such arrangements between China and a U.S. company in the power generation industry.<P>
The Shanghai deal and the 1993 agreement to modernize and upgrade existing power plants, known as the Lon-Wei joint venture, represent a ready conduit for export deals in a burgeoning power market that is being pursued by competitors, including General Electric Co., Siemans AG and Boveri Ltd.<P>
Moreover, Westinghouse's well-developed relationship with the Chinese doubtless has helped to obtain contracts not directly linked to the joint ventures. The company last year announced four contracts for $140 million to supply two 350-watt steam turbine generators for the Ligang Electric Power Co. in Jiangsu.<P>
How did Westinghouse suddenly corral all this business? The answer, says Westinghouse spokesman Paul Tobin, is that the company didn't do it over two years. Rather, Westinghouse had been working on it for more than 20.<P>
With President Richard Nixon's historic visit in 1972, the United States and China agreed to normalize relations. Westinghouse became one of the first companies to send industrial envoys through the commercial swath Nixon had cut in the bamboo curtain.<P>
This preparatory work paved the way for a technology transfer agreement Westinghouse signed with the Chinese government in 1980 that designated two generator manufacturers as licensees of Westinghouse designs. The following year, Tobin says, "Westinghouse started bringing in their engineers for intensive training" at the company's power gener-ation business unit in Orlando, Fla. Over the next 14 years, about 800 Chinese engineers received training that enabled them to execute their own designs.<P>
Tobin recalls that last year's Shanghai announcement, which received wide-spread media coverage, might have seemed sudden to many observers. "But the reality is that we'd had people over there laboring in obscurity, some for more than 10 years."
<P>
<b>Public-Private R&D<BR></b>
Research laboratories in the United States are considered to be among the world's most productive, yet their dis-coveries usually have a tougher time becoming commercialized than do the fruits of foreign genius.<P>
This lamentable techno-commercial state of affairs has prompted some gov-ernment development officials to coin a somber moniker for the hapless journey from lab to plant. They call it "the valley of death."<P>
One of the few efforts to span this commercial chasm got under way last year in Lawrenceville. There, engineers from Carnegie Mellon University's renown robotics program, which develops robots for the space program, are working under the same roof with engineers from private industry. The goal: to get robotic technol-ogy to the marketplace and, as a result, to stimulate the creation of employment-intensive manufacturing jobs.<P>
"It all began with a white paper we sent to NASA in May of 1993," says the center's director, David Pahnos. "The subject was the fact that advanced mobile robotic technology would soon be ready to be commercialized and that commer-cialization models weren't working." <P>
What followed was a series of public-private agreements.<P>
After obtaining a $6.5 million grant from the state Department of Commerce, the Urban Redevelopment Authority pur-chased a six-acre site in the Lawrenceville Enterprise Zone, the former location of National Valve & Manu-facturing Co. The price: $1.3 million. The rest of the grant is going toward rehabilitating the site, which the consortium will lease from the URA.<P>
NASA has provided funding for operating expenses, and private compa-nies are supplying development funds. Among the concerns represented at the consortium thus far are New Holland Co., Caterpillar, Boeing Helicopters, Arm-strong, Silicon Graphics and LunaCorp, which intends to use robotic explorers on commercial moon launches.<P>
"It's like a big BYOB," Pahnos explains. "The state and the URA provide the hall; NASA buys the mixer; the corporations bring their own fifth; and, the engineers come in and party by developing new products."<P>
However festive, this analogy explains the roles of different entities in a serious project designed to overcome long-standing obstacles to commercial-izing technology in ways that would translate into manufacturing jobs.<P>
"We are particularly reaching out to companies that are basic industrial manufacturing firms instead of high-tech government contractors," Pahnos says. "The idea of our commercialization is to get products into main-line manufacturing."<P>
The center's founders concluded that the only way to approach this goal was to capitalize on "the strengths of the dif-ferent players."<p>


<hr>
