<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Feature: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<h2>Shades of Gray</h2><i>By Angie Mullig</i>
<hr>

<img align=left hspace=5 src="0695.Feature.2.1.gif">
Southwestern Pennsylvania's senior citizens constitute an unusually large percentage of the area's population - and the numbers represent both challenges and opportunities.<p>

Though it's inevitable that as individuals we age, it seems that as a region, we're also growing older. Most people have heard the figures: Southwestern Pennsyl-vania ranks second nationally in the percentage of its population that is age 60 or older. And our region is the fourth in line when ranked by total number of residents age 60 and over.<P>
More than 20% of the region's total population is over the age of 60, and the number of people age 85 and older is the fastest growing segment of our population, increasing 32% between 1980 and 1990.<P>
This shift toward an older population - which will intensify as the baby-boom generation ages - will almost certainly dictate new and expanded social and health-care services. But will it offer oppor-tunities for economic growth?<P>
Yes and no. A study released by Pennsylvania State University examines the economic impact of the elderly in the state's rural areas. Two segments of the older popu-lation are compared - those who had lived and retired in the same community and those who had moved into a community after retirement. It seems that economic impact is linked to the type of retirement: Long-term residents have little impact on a local economy, but those who migrate to a community may provide a boost to some market segments.<P>
However, even in the case of new residents, an influx of well-to-do elderly has little overall economic impact on the state's rural regions, according to the study. In one instance, the demand for housing had a positive impact on local construction trade - but the gain was offset by Pennsyl-vania's tax code, which exempts most of the elderly population's income from state and local taxes. The study also determined that new jobs created by a migration of affluent elderly tend to be low-wage service jobs with few or no benefits.<P>
Other states have wooed retirees and enjoyed prosperity as a result. But Pennsylvania's local, property, occupation, per capita, in-come, amusement and real estate transfer tax structures make it possible for the elderly to avoid contributing to the public coffer - and offset the economic contri-butions of retirees to local communities.<P>
Statistics show that 78% of Pennsylvania's older citizens have incomes that range from adequate to affluent. Although society has traditionally thought of the elderly in terms of needs, the marketplace now is beginning to think of wants as well. Opportunities for providing consumer goods and services are being recognized as a large contin-gent of healthy, financially secure adults move into the 60-years-and-up category. Two sectors almost sure to see increased demand are healthcare and housing.<P>
<HR>
<b>The Managed Care Mandate<BR></b>
In Florida, eight major com-panies have already joined forces in an effort to persuade 27,000 retirees to switch to managed care. Joe Vater, a partner at Meyer, Unkovic & Scott who specializes in employee benefits, says the effort is now moving into Pennsylvania, and self-insured, multi-employer funds are being encouraged to consider the significant cost benefits of shifting retirees to managed care programs.<P>
Dom Pascucci, sales manager for Aetna Health Plans of Western Pennsylvania, sees the effort to switch retirees into HMOs as a major growth opportunity for managed care companies.<P>
"The federal government is losing its shirt in Medicare," says Pascucci. "Under the right circum-stances, managed care companies can take over that care, receive a portion of the premium that formerly went to Medicare, provide quality care and increased benefits - and still earn a profit. HMOs know how to manage the cost."
The projected dramatic increase in the percentage of the population that moves into the oldest, most-frail category will also drive demand for long-term home healthcare. In "The Pennsylvania Advantage and Telecommunica-tions: Business Creation and Attraction Plan," a report compiled by Bell Atlantic, skilled nursing facilities, intermediate care com-plexes and other nursing and per-sonal care facilities are expected to increase by 5%, with pro-jected dollar expendi-tures for those services rising  10% to 15% per year. The report predicts that franchised opera-tions will grow in impor-tance, providing oppor-tunities for both manage-ment and service deliv-ery. Building and running such care facilities will also require outlays for real estate, maintenance/ repair services, utilities, wholesale trade and labor. And as pressure mounts to contain costs and help seniors retain independence, the study notes, home healthcare will follow growth pat-terns established by child day care centers in the 1980s.<P>
There is a need for long-term care reform and subsidized housing to meet the needs of the 22% of the state's older adults who exist at or below the poverty level, according to Pennsylvania's "1993-1996 State Plan on Aging." But other groups are stepping in to meet the demands of more affluent seniors. They provide comfortable living now and guarantee long-term care if it is ever needed.<p>
Sherwood Oaks, a develop-ment in Cranberry Township, reflects a trend new to this region - a package that combines housing and health insurance. The development is a continuing care retirement community (CCRC) for adults age 62 and older that offers a spectrum of services designed to meet the changing needs of seniors as they age. The campus includes 257 single-story units for independent living, 37 rooms for assisted living and a 59-bed skilled nursing facility.<P>
Residents of Sherwood Oaks sign a contract that guarantees independent housing for as long as it's appropriate, and assisted living and skilled nursing facilities if and when they're needed. Resi-dents are assured of healthcare for life, says William Silbert, marketing director. "We're still educating western Pennsylvania consumers about life care," he says. "This is not a nursing home; we have a skilled nursing facility as one com-ponent, but that's not the reason to move into our community."<p>
"Most of our residents are very healthy and independent," says Judy Comer, CEO and president of Sherwood Oaks. "Some of our residents work as consultants, practice law and medicine - one is an interior decorator." And Sherwood Oaks revives a spirit of community, Silbert adds. With two-paycheck families the norm and the extended family a thing of the past, many older adults feel isolated in the neighborhoods where they've spent their lives - there's literally no one else at home. "In this type of community, there's a network of support from peers," Silbert says. "And our residents rediscover a sense of neighborhood."<P>
Long-term healthcare and nursing care are the most expen-sive medical costs older adults face as they age, Silbert continues. "Such expenses are usually not covered by Medicare," he says. At communities like Sherwood Oaks, resi-dents pay an entrance fee and monthly service fee; in return, they are guaranteed access to personal care and skilled nursing care in their community for as long as they choose to live there.<p>
The monthly service fee includes a daily communal meal, house-keeping and linen ser-vice, and a host of amenities that a country club might envy. Sher-wood Oaks' 84-acre spread features manicured nature trails, an indoor swimming pool and jacuzzi, an auditorium, a greenhouse, art studio, wood shop, photo darkroom, music room and a five-acre stocked lake. Resident committees are active participants in the community's governance. Activities ranging from regular trips to Pittsburgh for concerts and theater productions to on-site continuing education and exercise classes are available.<P>
But Comer stresses a strong respect for the residents' inde-pendence - people come and go, participate in activities and pursue interests as they please.<P>
Such a lifestyle carries a price tag. Entrance fees for a one-bedroom unit range from $81,000 to $121,000; the monthly fee is $1,535 for an individual, $2,245 for a couple. If that sounds steep, compare the cost to the monthly rates of a personal care home: Based on double occupancy, the cost average is $912, according to a report issued by the South-western Pennsylvania Partnership for Aging. Nursing home stays are even more expensive, and there are no guarantees that places will be available if an older adult requires such accommodations.<P>
Lutheran Affiliated Services is another organization providing services ranging from retirement living to specialty services for those with Alzheimer's disease. LAS-managed facilities include the LAS/St. John Lutheran Care Center, a skilled nursing facility; Newhaven Court at Passavant, an assisted living apartment complex, and the Passavant Retirement and Health Center in Zelienople, which includes cottages and apartments and optional services like personal and medical care.<P>
But some seniors are not looking for care - only like-minded (and -aged) neighbors. LAS recently launched an independent-living retirement community, the Village at Spring Crest. A condominium develop-ment near Latrobe, the older-adults-only complex has no health and personal care services; there are no communal meals, no on-site care-giving staff. Spring Crest was designed for the active, older adult who prefers the convenience and security of condo living, says Robert E. Johnson, LAS vice president for marketing, who thinks the development reflects a growing emphasis on healthy old age.<P>
Is there a market in south-western Pennsylvania for such a development? Apparently so. Recently more than 300 people attended an open house celebrat-ing Spring Crest's first units. LAS is exploring the possibility of building more units on other parcels, but Johnson says the scarcity of large tracts of affordable land within Allegheny County necessitates looking for sites in Westmoreland, Butler and Beaver counties.<P>
The need for a variety of living options is a primary concern for older adults, says Pamela J. Casey, a member of an accreditation team from the Continuing Care Accreditation Commission. CCAC is a national commission made up of consumers and professionals that rates continuing care retire-ment communities on a host of factors. Earlier this year, Casey and fellow team members Cynthia H. Dunn and David Scruggs were in the region doing that assessment, which includes rating admini-stration, planning, personnel, marketing strategies, the quality of resident life, the scope and quality of services, and the community's financial resources.<p>
"Nationally, it looks as if the rate of building is keeping pace with current needs," says Dunn. She notes that the growth in older-adults communities is a fairly recent development in the Pittsburgh market, though common in eastern Pennsylvania and the southern United States. One of the reasons for this, says Johnson of LAS, is that Pittsburghers are "condo-resistant." We like our single family homes - nationally, condominiums average 20% of urban residences, but in Pittsburgh, just 5% of the housing stock is in condos.<P>
Waiting lists for apartments in retirement communities vary according to market, Scruggs says, but generally waiting lists are shorter than they were a few years ago. Not only are there more units available, he explains, but community-based services have also grown, allowing those who want to remain in their home to 
do so.<P>
<HR>
<b>More Than Health and Housing<BR></b>
<img align=left hspace=5 src="0695.Feature.2.3.gif">
While housing and healthcare are the obvious growth areas, other industries are attracting patronage from senior citizens.<P>
For some time, retailers have wooed older adults with senior citizen discounts; now other industries are beginning to notice the financial clout of the older population. Banks are finding it worth their while to open branches in retirement communities, and some are offering special checking programs and services like reverse mortgages. According to the International Health, Racquet and Sportsclub Association, the elderly exercise with gusto; men in the 65-plus category average 180 visits to their club each year.  Smart marketing calls for new programs to attract even more older members to the health club scene.<P>
Other groups have created inroads to this market, too. The Allegheny County Bar Association is offering special programs to assist low-income elderly people with preparing wills, living wills, creating power of attorney and estate planning documents, and untangling legal issues surround-ing Medicaid and Medicare. The association's Young Lawyers section offers the Very Important Papers Program to affluent elderly seeking legal advice on such issues as living wills and powers of attorney.<P>
When launching a new product or service, it's important to recognize that the elderly are not a homogeneous group. "Twenty years ago, we focused on warehousing' sick, old people," says Johnson. "We have to abandon stereotypes. People who are elderly represent the full spectrum of education, health, income and interests found in younger adults."<P>
This diversity creates a host of marketing opportunities, ranging from in-home services to help older adults maintain their inde-pendence to investment, educa-tion and entertainment opportu-nities that cater to the elderly.<p>
With the huge baby-boom segment - the best-educated, most affluent generation in this country's history - marching toward retirement, businesses that begin developing products targeting the diverse needs of older adults today will have a competitive edge tomorrow. <P>
<HR>
<b>Re-defining Old Age<BR></b>
The good news is that medical advances have dramatically lengthened the average person's life span. The bad news is that medical advances have dramatically lengthened the average person's life span.<P>
At the turn of the century, most people didn't worry about how they would live at the age of 90 because most people didn't expect to come close to that age.<p>
But now a sizable portion of the population can expect to live for decades beyond retirement. And while medical advances have improved the health of the elderly, it's also true that the longer the life, the greater the risk of chronic disease, disability and age-related impairment.<P>
Longevity has made the broad terms "senior citizen" and "elderly" obsolete. A few years ago, government and social service agencies began to create categories within those age designations - the young-old (age 60 to 70), the middle-aged old (age 70 to 85), and the old-old (over age 85). Other categories began to appear as well, as efforts were made to distin-guish among active, independent older adults; older adults who could remain independent with a little help; the frail elderly, and those with severe illnesses or incapacitating conditions.<P>
The stereotype of "old" is someone who is mentally and physically incapacitated, impoverished, incapable of self care - and living in a nursing home. But census data show otherwise: In Pennsylvania, less than 6% of those over the age of 60 live in personal care or nursing homes. More than 63% of those over the age of 65 live in what the census defines as family households. Although "family household" may include parents living with an adult child, most often the senior citizen family household is an older married couple living independently.<P>
For the population that does not reside in a nursing home, about 20% have some mobility or self-care limitation. These limitations can range from such relatively minor things as finding it difficult to drive at night to an inability to bathe or dress without assistance. The limitations, however, tend to increase with age. Only 7% of those between 65 and 74 years of age need help with self care or routine activities of daily living; that figure jumps to 44% in the 85-plus age group. Even here, however, the definition of help varies widely - a healthy 88-year-old woman who may need a cleaning service to tackle heavy housekeeping chores may be perfectly comfortable and capable of preparing meals, bathing, dressing, paying bills and managing all other aspects of living independently. An incapacitating illness, on the other hand, may dictate home services that range from bathing and dressing the client to providing skilled nursing care.<P>

--A.M.<BR>
Source: The 1993-96 State Plan on Aging for Pennsylvania


