<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Update: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<hr>
<B><font size =+2>Teaching the American Dream</font></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Education is one key to boosting local entrepreneurs.<BR></B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Mark Sullivan</i>
<p>
Many people dream of starting their own business. And many of those dreams remain just that, because the start-up seems overwhelming.<P>

But there are those who believe that entrepreneurial ventures are the key to jumpstarting southwestern Pennsyl-vania's economy. Though currently not a haven for entrepreneurs, the region is not without resources to attract them. Increasingly, local universities are taking the lead in doing so.<P>

"This region has the worst entrepreneurial vitality in the country," says Thomas Canfield, president of the Enterprise Corporation, a nonprofit founded in 1983 to promote entrepreneurship and help people to start and build businesses. "We do not make it easy on entrepreneurs. We need some symbols to say we are an entrepreneurially-friendly town,' and linking in to the universities, which attract young people with the ideas, is absolutely the key."<P>

According to the results of a study done by the Enterprise Corporation, entrepreneurial activity in southwestern Pennsylvania must increase by at least 90% to create the foundation of new companies that are needed to meet the job creation goals put forth by the Regional Economic Revitalization Initiative.<P>

The analysis suggests that of the 100,000 new jobs needed in the region, 30,000 will come from companies that don't currently exist. Others agree. "The economy in Beaver is so depressed that small business is the best shot for revitalization," says Randy Nutter, chairman of the business, accounting and management depart-ment of Geneva College. <P>

Alarmingly, the study points out that the rate of new companies being formed in this area is 27% below the state average. Pennsylvania ranks 50th of 50 states in a study of entre-preneurial vitality done by the Center for Enterprise Development in Washington, D.C. It is from these statistics that Canfield takes the region's low rating. To meet national growth, the number of new companies being formed in our region must double.<P>


<b>Mining Regional Resources</b><br>
Coal, iron and water used to be considered our primary regional resources, but the Enterprise study points a different direction, to "talented people, knowledge and technology." The best place to mine for these resources? Local universities. <P>

"Universities have the highest potential for spinning out technical companies," says Jack Thorne, director of Carnegie Mellon's Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship and founder of the Enterprise Corporation. "Universities can either thwart these companies or support them, depending on their encouragement activities."<P>

At Carnegie Mellon, University President Robert Mehrabian has pushed the transfer of technology from the labs and classrooms into the community. CMU can provide resources to help en-trepreneurs license and take a product to market. In return, CMU receives an agreed upon percentage when the venture turns a profit. CMU will give faculty entrepreneurs a two-year leave of absence to start a business. <P>

"The university can help them find management for their ideas," Thorne says. "CMU sees it as its mission to take what is learned and give it to the outside world and make sure it gets used."

There are also three Small Business Development Centers in the region, at St. Vincent College, Duquesne University and the University of Pittsburgh. These centers are part of a state network of 14 such centers which provide comprehensive assistance to new and emerging businesses in their areas at no charge. They also provide entrepreneurship training and seminars throughout the year. Washington and Jefferson College, California University of Pennsylvania, Indiana University of Pennsylvania, Geneva College and Slippery Rock also service would-be entrepreneurs.<P>

A major factor in many of these programs is the affiliation and support of the Ben Franklin Technology Center (BFTC), which anchors an entire web of entrepreneurial assistance. The three-fold mission of BFTC is to support growing industries, invest money in new technology and take advantage of Pennsylvania's impressive research capabilities.<P>

"If entrepreneurs are working on an idea or product or process that will put western Pennsylvanians to work, they should come to us no matter where they are in the commercialization process," says Larry McGeehan, BFTC president.<P>

By supporting regional programs, BFTC's web of support reaches into local communities. Since the late '80s BFTC has helped fund Geneva College's Center for Technology Development, which gives small companies resources to develop ideas for new technology. Small business owners work on their ideas with teams of faculty and students. When the product is finished, they can consult the business department for advice on how to market the new product. To date, two products have gone to market and several others are in development.<P>

<HR>
<b>The Chicken or the Egg?<BR></b>
Because local business people are not raised in a culture promoting entrepreneurialism, it doesn't top career choice lists. <P>

"Too often I see students who have never thought about entrepre-neurship," says Dr. Tom Falcone, chairman of the management depart-ment at Indiana University of Pennsylvania. "So many students have good ideas and high energy, but they presume that there'll be a job for them at a big company. I see that as a mistake."<P>

In today's economy it can take between six months and a year to find a "real" job: one with benefits, a future and a salary big enough to pay the rent. Even then, job security is questionable. Time spent sending out resumes and cover letters could be invested in starting a new business. Although it's an attractive alternative for recent college graduates, too often students aren't exposed to the idea.<P>

"We need to encourage and train those who have an entrepreneurial bent," says Bill Newlin, a corporate finance lawyer with Buchanan Ingersoll and an architect of Pittsburgh's high tech foundations.<P>

"You can take those who have the inclination and develop it by having schools focus classes on encouraging the entrepreneurial spirit," says Newlin. But he cautions that formal classes don't always excite those with the entrepreneurial spirit. "These classes should be taught by people who are entrepreneurs themselves because they can convey the feeling that being an entrepreneur is exciting and a worth-while pursuit."<P>

Ami Elis, president of Elcomp Systems and a graduate of CMU, thinks that good entrepreneurial programs balance the theoretical with the practical.<P>

"You need to teach the students the mechanics of starting a business. Teach them the little things like where resources are," says Elis. "On the other hand, you need to work on real-life projects. In my classes at Carnegie Mellon we worked on real-life problems, one of which became my business."<P>

<B>Growing Entrepreneurs in Captivity<BR></b>
CMU's Center for Entrepreneurial Development, located in East Liberty, is headed by Dwight Baumann, professor of engineering design. Baumann claims that he is the founder of entrepreneurial classes, having taught the first in 1960 at Massachusetts Institute of Technology.<P>

Today, Baumann is an entrepreneurial legend. According to a 1983 interview with Smithsonian magazine,  he moved to the region in 1970 to prove that entrepreneurship could be taught, at a time when Pittsburgh was void of entrepreneurial activity. The Entrepreneurial Center, started in 1971, has spun out such successes as Compuguard, Bactex, Suprex, Ergonics, Vectran and Remlik Foods.
Baumann evaluates the ideas of the students in his entrepreneurship class, and promising ones get their start using office space in the center's five-story building. Sometimes, financial support can even be found. This leg up can make or break an idea.<P>


<b>Finding "Adventure" Capital<BR></b>
"Adventure capital" is the term coined for funding of young upstart businesses, because their development is never predictable. In the Enterprise survey, insufficient capital was the biggest impediment to entrepreneurial activity.<P>

"If you are already in business and you are producing something, it's no problem to get money. But if you are just starting out, it's difficult. That is why businesses die on the vine," says Jack Roseman, associate director of the Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship. <P>

Canfield advocates setting up a regional adventure capital fund - something no other region has done to date. For now, universities are helping alleviate this problem with incubation centers like the one that Baumann runs at CMU. Indiana University of Penn-sylvania also has one.<P>

<b>Running Behind</b><br>
Despite the number of entrepre-neurial training programs, the region needs to deepen this resource to become real players. The Enterprise Corporation recommends that univer-sities improve their entrepreneurial programs until three local universities become ranked among the top national contenders. But education must start before the university level.<P>

"We need to begin in grade school to establish a link that develops an attitude of entrepreneurship. The process should be similar to developing a long-term basketball team and building a program. At an early age children might be more inclined," says Mike Brna, director of the Entrepreneurial Assistance Center at California University. That can start early: Canfield says that in Indianapolis, Junior Achievement, a business outreach to grades K through 12, reaches 50% of students. In Pittsburgh, 3% to 4% are exposed. <P>


<b>The Numbers Game<BR></b>
But training in these developing programs does the area little good if students must go elsewhere after graduation in order to realize their potential. The need most frequently cited to those conducting the Enterprise study was the need to attract and keep would-be entrepreneurs. <P>

"We are attracting students because of the reputation of the schools here," says Canfield. "Forty percent of all students that graduate from GSIA [The Graduate School of Industrial Administration at CMU] eventually start their own company. But if they moved to Denver for a job after they graduated, they'll likely start that company in Denver."<P>

The problem is the lack of job oppor-tunities in entrepreneurial companies.  "We need to glue them here by offering job opportunities with entre-preneurial companies where they can cut their teeth, learn their craft and then be compelled to start a business themselves," says Canfield.<P>

In the meantime, they make a home and a family here, and they stay here. The average age of an entrepreneur starting a business is 30 to 31 years, says Canfield, after a few years of working for someone else. <P>

The region's demographic mix is another drawback. [See Shades of Gray, page 50.] Just 15% of Pittsburgh's popu-lation is in the 25-35 age bracket. In Seattle and Boston both, over 20% of the population is the age when people most likely start businesses. <P>


<b>Slow Start-Up<BR></b>
Given the region's lag in entre-preneurial activity, can we count on new businesses to fill the necessary economic gaps? No one seems ready to throw in the towel.<p>
"Although we have a good infrastructure of support groups, we don't have risk capital and the tradition of starting new companies," says CMU's Thorne, "but it is starting to come." <P>

"Entrepreneurs are very diverse, ranging from high tech to mom and pop. But high tech is not everything. It is important, but you can't look down on those who are only trying to make a living for themselves and their families," says IUP's Falcone.  It is here, perhaps, that purposes of education and economic develpment will diverge. <P>

"Just 7% of the businesses that are started turn out to be the gazelles - the ones that really create the jobs," says Canfield. "It's often the difference between selling a product or service regionally or nationally, bringing in money from outside the region, as opposed to starting up a beauty shop.  We have to focus on the gazelles."
<HR>
<b>Four Myths About Financing a New Business</b>
<P>
The Enterprise study dispels these common misconceptions:
1. Most companies can "boot strap" themselves to be self-sufficient. In other words, an individual can start a business using their own personal savings and loans from friends and family. This myth breaks down when you consider that people between the ages of 25 and 35 haven't had a chance to accumulate extra capital.<p>

2. Entrepreneurs with good ideas always find the money they need. In the early stages of development, when capital is most needed, it is the most difficult to find. The Enterprise Corporation says that of the 125 or so entrepreneurs that come to them for help each year, about 10 of those with viable ideas cannot secure the money they need to succeed. <p>

3. There are plenty of "adventure capitalists" in Pittsburgh. Over the years there have been a few private investors, but not enough. What the region needs are more rapid growth companies to nurture small companies in their develop-mental stages.<p>

4. The Ben Franklin Program and the federal Small Business Innovation and Research Program (SBIR) are sufficient forms of capital. Not all companies can qualify for the Ben Franklin programs because of its focus on technology.                    <p>-- M.S.


<hr>
