<HEAD>
<TITLE>Update: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<hr>
<B><font size =+2>Business Golf:  Do It With Attitude</font></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>A little preparation can avert a lot of anxiety.</B></FONT SIZE><p><i>By Sandy Thomas</i>
<p>
Clear blue skies magnify the warm rays of sun beating down on your arms. The smell of fresh grass lingers in your nostrils. Steel golf spikes crunch on the asphalt as you drift towards the first tee. You're thankful for five hours of freedom from the office phone and irritating peers.<P>

Bright white golf carts gather around the encampment of the first tee. Out of the corner of your eye, you catch a glimpse of motionless, semi-erect bodies as eager golfers gently tap practice putts into three and a half inch diameter holes. Silence penetrates the air. Sports tension begins to mount, and a mild excitement flushes through your body as you prepare to take your position on the first tee.<P>

Suddenly, anguish, the fear of everybody watching, jump-starts your heart rate. Your heart positions itself in your throat. You begin to shoot up silent prayers, "Please, God, don't let me screw up." You swing; the adventure begins.<P>

Is there any way to avoid this annual, annoyingly public reckoning with your own golf skills - or lack thereof - the inevitable result of being an infrequent, business golfer?<P>

For the newer player, or someone who gets out just a few times each summer, here are a few practical suggestions. These tips - and a lot of attitude - will put you on the first tee filled with golf confidence.<P>


<b>1. Be prepared.<BR></b>
Arrive at the golf course at least 45 minutes before your designated starting time. Change your shoes, find the rest room and head to the practice tee. Even if you just hit 10 chip shots, it will help loosen your tense office muscles. Ideally, you should hit 20 to 25 practice balls with a variety of clubs.<P>

Next stop, the putting green. Practice putting. Courses vary, and a few minutes on the putting green will help you get a feel for the speed of the greens. At least 60% of your putts should be from the two- to three-foot range. Dropping those short putts will help build your frail confidence.<P>

If you analyze mathematically what is about to happen on the golf course, at least 30 of the strokes you encounter will be putts. If you two putt nine of the 18 holes and three putt the other nine, that will be 45 strokes added to your score. A few minutes on the putting green is a good investment.<P>


<b>2. Know the rules and etiquette.<BR></b>
Rules are black and white. If you don't know the rules, it will appear that you are cheating. The IRS doesn't over-look tax obligations because you're bewildered by tax laws. Your golf partners will have that same pitiless IRS mentality: They expect you to know the rules.<P>

The lack of proper golf etiquette smacks of rudeness. Simple considerations like repairing your ball marks on the green, carefully raking sand traps, replacing divots and maintaining absolute silence while someone is hitting reflect common courtesies. If you overlook the basics, much will be inferred about your character and business ethics.<P>


<b>3. Attitude</b>
Golf is a mind game. Poor play will drop you to the depths of depression in just a few short minutes.<P>

Suppose you have a bad hole, shoot a nine instead of the regulation par four. A tree jumps up and grabs your tee shot in mid-air, then throws your ball into the deep rough out of bounds. You struggle and hit a low liner banana ball into a massive sand trap. Gracefully, you skulled the ball out of the trap, airmailing it across the green. You dump a simple wedge shot, and feel grateful to have dropped the third putt.<P>

An ugly hole, an ugly memory. We've all been there. Humility was not your goal. How can you possibly approach the next tee? Where is the confidence?<P>

The right attitude is to immediately re-build. Forget the bad hole. Overcome the choking feeling in your throat. Move on and play each shot on the remaining holes to the best of your ability.<P>

Golf anger will destroy your confidence. Keep a positive attitude by viewing the rest of the course as a new adventure.<P>


<b>4. Confidence<BR></b>
There are a number of ways to increase your golf confidence.<P>

Take lessons. You take your car in for regular tune-ups, and it makes sense to see a good golf pro for a golf swing tune-up, too. But all golf professionals are not necessarily good teaching professionals: Ask the better players you know to recommend a high-caliber teaching professional. Drive the extra distance; pay a few extra dollars. It is worth the time and expense to learn from a top-notch instructor.<P>

Participate in off-season training. Read golf magazine articles and books to improve your knowledge. Take a winter golf vacation in the Carolinas, Florida or the Southwest. Improve your physical condition; join a health club and get on a regular exercise and strength training program. Wouldn't it be nice to hit your tee shots five to 10 yards farther next summer? Winter workouts not only make you feel energized and look better but also may contribute to lowering your golf scores.<P>


The game of golf is a leveler of egos. One missed shot can bring your heart to your throat, tears to your eyes or fury to your soul.<P>

But golf outings with friends or business associates should be viewed with excitement and enjoyment. They are not a time of terror. Simply come prepared. Play your game one shot at a time. Forget the bad holes; focus on your achievements, the good shots.<P>

Take the time to enjoy the warmth of the sun and the smell of freshly cut fairways. Enjoy your companions. The office will be there Monday.<P>


<hr>
