<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Publisher's Note: Together or To Gather? </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2><fill> </FONT SIZE><i> By Linda A. Dickerson</i><P>
Togetherness. That's what we need to succeed at economic development in this region.<p>
This area's fractionalized approach to economic development exacts a hefty price in lost opportunities. Over 200 economic development agencies, each singing a slightly different tune, results in a cacophony of sounds distasteful to most listeners. Disjointed development, at times, can be worse than no development at all.<p>
The word "together" is strikingly similar to the words "to gather." That's probably not accidental.<p>
This area needs to gather its economic development agencies, and channel their energies and resources into one, single, cohesive effort. Stewarded by CMU President Robert Mehrabian, the Regional Economic Revitalization Initiative (RERI) proved that this community can work together across all demographic and geographic boundaries to shape a strategic vision and to espouse a list of agreed upon priorities. Not to diminish RERI's accomplishments, but implementing its recommendations is the tougher challenge.<p>
The Working Together Consortium, is the group orchestrating the implemen-tation of the RERI recommendations, and definitely faces the more imposing assignment. Headed by a stellar corporate and community leader, Dick Simmons, chairman of the board of Allegheny Ludlum Corporation, the Working Together Consortium holds true promise. Heralded by many as the salvation for local economic development efforts, the consortium will succeed only if the "Together" in their name really stands for to gather. The consortium must engage 200-plus economic development agencies throughout the community in its efforts to revitalize the local economy. Then, it must reach beyond traditional organizations to enlist the entire community in our region's job creation activities.<p>
We desperately need a single point of entry to this community - a veritable storefront for economic development. This storefront must represent more than the four primary agencies involved in the Greater Pittsburgh Development Initiative (GPDI), a joint-venture of the World Trade Center, the Greater Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce, RIDC and Penn's Southwest. Although the GPDI is a good beginning, it mustn't stop at four agencies. It must embrace the entire economic development spectrum and the community at large.<p>
This area's job creation rate is one-quarter of the national average. A sad commentary indeed. We must, therefore, quadruple our economic development efforts. The untapped synergy between economic development agencies is a tremendous source of new energy and better results.<p>
Through RERI, we gathered our thoughts. Now we must gather our community. <p>

<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
