<HEAD>
<TITLE>Letters: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.L.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<font size =+2><B>An Incentive to Learn</B></font size><p>
The April issue's "Johnny Can't Read" article nicely conveys the need for continued development of innovative school-to-work oppor-tunities for Pennsylvania students and businesses.<p>
Student apprenticeship programs are a winning situation for all involved. Businesses will spend less money teaching new employees basic work skills; students will graduate from high school with expanded options to pursue further study, enter the work force or enter a union apprenticeship program with the advantages of real world training and practical appli-cations of academic work.<p>
Pennsylvania Senate Bill 581 creates guidelines for student appren-ticeship programs. The bill gives local businesses, schools and economic development organizations local control in developing appropriate programs to meet regional needs and resources. The plan also encourages schools to develop training specialties based on their communities' needs by utilizing the proven magnet school concept.<p>
Senate Bill 582 offers tax credits for businesses who participate in a student apprenticeship program.<p>
Such unique partnerships between the private business community and education will help make today's students into tomorrow's well-qualified, high skilled workers.<p>

Melissa A. Hart <br>
Pennsylvania State Senator<p>

<hr>
Letters may be sent to: <br>
Editor, Executive Report, 3 Gateway Center, 5th floor, Pittsburgh, PA 15222-1004.
Fax letters to 412/644-3006 or e-mail to er_editor@excreport.comm. Please include a daytime phone number.<p>

