http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0695.GuestEditorial.html 192.204.56.67 19970115133601 text/html 5713
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 13:41:12 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:49:56 GMT
Content-length: 5537
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Guest Editorial: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <FONT SIZE=+2><B>Can Public and Private Interests Converge?</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Emily Buka</i><P>

Successful eco-nomic develop-ment initiative in Pittsburgh, par-ticularly in real estate, has histor-ically combined efforts of public and private sectors. Pittsburgh serves as a model to the nation in this regard. Finding common ground among conflicting objectives is essential to these alliances.<p>
Traditionally, public sector dollars are used to revitalize blighted sites. Tax dollars are used to assemble land, remedy environmental problems and provide infrastructure. Once prepared, these sites are available to private developers. The public involvement thereafter is often limited to low interest financing to reduce higher building and occupancy costs.<p>
When the public steps aside, having returned valuable inner city land to productive use, the private sector assumes control. In return for the initial public sector investment, private developers may need to meet some job creation and are precluded from speculating on the improvements. They are essentially, however, free to pursue their entrepreneurial objectives uninhibited.<p>
A second model of public-private partnerships, popular in the 1980s, is far more complex. In addition to eliminating blight, these projects also have social and community development goals, like assistance to start-up companies, support for businesses owned by women and minorities, and job training. The partners, public and private, develop and own these projects together.<p>
The public side typically includes nonprofit entities, supported by philanthropists. Their charters mandate more ambitious social and community development objectives.<p>
On the other side, the private partners and lenders endeavor, as usual, to maximize their return on investment and secure the collateral.<p>
This model worked well when real estate ownership provided favorable tax benefits, especially income tax credits. Private investors were willing to forgo cash flow as long as they derived returns from the deferment of taxes.<p>
In the late 1980s, the tax benefits in real estate were virtually eliminated. The private partners were left not only with no cash flow but also with the threat of horrendous tax liabilities in the event of foreclosure.<p>
Most speculative commercial real estate was similarly disadvantaged. Unlike investors in purely private transactions, however, private partners in combined ventures could point to their public partners' objectives as the problem. If marketing was reoriented to only credit worthy tenants, they reasoned, projects could be saved. Consequently, pressure to change the nature of these projects by eliminating their public purposes, and by leasing to anyone who could pay the rent, was inevitable.<p>
Given this history, are there ways for the public and private sectors to partic-ipate together in real estate projects which go beyond the restoration of inner city sites, attracting private capital and development expertise? Yes, but only if certain guidelines are met.<p>
<dl>
<li>  Define each party's objectives.
Surprises can be deadly. The first topic of discussion should lay out respective expectations. If new small businesses are the public goal, when is the goal achieved? There should be a defined point when the public goals have been met. At this juncture, an exit for the public partner should be available.<p>
Our experience indicates that real estate develop-ments cannot sustain too many public purposes or they become more appro-priate for public institutions than for speculative real estate projects.<p>
On the private side, the private developer/investor can quote an expected rate of return or level of secu-rity but should be reminded that all real estate is risky. Developers and investors must be forewarned against expecting public bailouts just because they have a public partner.<p>
<li>  Underwrite the project realistically.
Excessively aggressive forecasts can lead to disappointments. The public partner may be especially vulnerable to overly optimistic projections in its desire to see the project under way.<p>
In addition, there is the danger of wasting scarce public resources. It is critical that tax and philanthropic dollars be targeted to projects and pro-grams with the biggest impact. If the ultimate amount of subsidy to a venture is not known to funders until it is too late, other projects and programs with better social returns will have suffered.<p>
Though some developments may not be appropriate for private equity,. nonprofits need design, construction, leasing and other private expertise throughout the complex development process.<p>
In the end, public-private devel-opments can work if both parties are aware of their potentially conflicting interests. Finding and building the common ground is the challenge.<p>
</dl>

<i>Emily Buka is president of the North Side Development Council.</i>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
