<HEAD>
<TITLE>ERIndex: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a><BR>
<p>
<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.</I>
<HR>
The ER Index roared through the last weeks of March, gaining 3.96% for the month ended April 7, while the S&P 500 for the same period was up 3.44% . Since the inception of the index in August 1994, we have seen a gain of 10.25% compared with the S&P 500's gain of 9.80% during the same period.<p>
Of our 25 stock index, American Eagle Outfitters led the pack, appre-ciating 51.79% to 21 1/4. The company reported a sales increase of 64% to $18.7 million, on same store sales gains of 6%, for the five weeks ended April 1. This increase came amidst a 5.92% decline in the Bloomberg Specialty Apparel Same Store Sales Index, which includes such companies as the Gap, The Limited and Ann Taylor.<p>

<DL>
<LI>General Nutrition Companies (GNC) also had a stellar month, gaining 18.32%. In mid-March the company announced earnings for the fourth quarter and year ended Feb. 4, 1995. EPS for the year increased 48% to $1.14 per share on a 23% increase in net revenues to $672.9 million. Additionally, in recent weeks rumors have surfaced regarding a possible acquisition of Nature's Bounty, a New York-based manufacturer of vitamins and supplements.
<LI>In past weeks, aluminum and steel stocks have come back into favor as stronger demand has enabled many companies to raise prices. Alcoa has been a major beneficiary of the industry's resurgence. The company reported first quarter earnings of $1.08 per share versus 5 cents per share, on a 36% increase in revenues to $3 billion, exceeding Wall Street's expectations of 71 cents. These increases can be largely attributed to sharply higher prices for fabricated aluminum products. Alcoa has also announced its first step into China through its acquisition of 60% of a Shanghai, China aluminum fabrication plant in a joint venture with the Shanghai Bureau of Light Industry.
<li>Legent was the biggest loser of the month, declining 16.18% to 28 1/2. In recent weeks, Legent Chairman Jerre Stead has made some significant changes to the company infrastructure. In doing so there have been several personnel changes, including the addition of Glen Hazard, formerly of AT&T Global Solutions, who will take the position of vice president of business transformation and CIO. Additionally, Franchon M. Smithson, the company's CFO and senior vice president, announced that he would be leaving to pursue other opportunities. As we went to press, Legent announced that second quarter earnings would come in slightly lower than expected, around 43 cents per share versus the expected 50 cents per share on revenue of $121 million. The shortfall is a result of changes in its sales structure that have resulted in slower than expected earnings growth.
<li>NorthStar Health Services, the Pittsbugh-based provider of rehabili-tation therapy, reported an increase in net income to $715,000 from $671,000, on a 119% increase in revenues to $13.4 million. The stock finished off 11.67% for the period to 6 5/8. The company has also filed to sell an additional 1.75 million shares of stock.
<li>Respironics announced the acqui-sition of Vitalog Monitoring Inc., a privately held California-based designer, manufacturer and marketer of sleep monitoring and diagnostic equipment. The acquisition will help to further enhance Respironics' effort to diagnose and treat sleep disorders, specifically in the treatment of obstructive sleep apnea.
<li>Net income increased 104% in the second quarter for New Brighton-headquartered Tuscarora Inc., the nation's largest manufacturer of custom- molded expanded foam plastic products, as well as other protective packaging and material handling solutions. Net sales for the quarter increased 42.1% to $37.9 million and EPS increased 100% to 30 cents. The increase is attributed to continued strong growth in the company's primary markets, increased market share and further acceptance of the company's newer products.
</DL>
<HR>
A Real Bonus
Calgon Carbon Corp. President and CEO Colin Bailey reinforced his message to shareholders and employees of short-term sacrifice for long-term gain by refusing his 1994 bonus, which is an unusual and impressive gesture in today's corporate world. 
Pittsburgh-based Calgon, maker of activated carbons used to purify liquids and gases, suffered through a tough year. In 1994 the company lost $8.6 million and announced a $41.8 million restructuring that includes the closing of its operations in Brilon Wald, Germany.
But things finally seem to be turning in the right direction for the company as it is enjoying sales gains in the U.S. and Europe, its first price increases in four years and wider profit margins. The early results show a 68% rise in first quarter profits to $3.9 million, or 10 cents per share, and a 20% rise in the stock price since January.
Bailey's decision to turn down the bonus was but one of many signals Calgon has been sending the investment community recently. The company has paid a special dividend, increased its regular dividend, continued to buy back its own shares and dissolved the voting trust that was viewed by some analysts as an impediment to growth.
How much he turned down, we're not sure, but it was at least as much as was paid to Ronald Tisch, Calgon executive vice president, who received more that $26,000. Bailey's not hurting, mind you. His salary last year was $278,898. Still, in this day and age, CEOs don't turn down bonuses. "We've gotten some calls about it from investors," Gail Gerono, the company spokesperson, told Bloomberg Business News. "They've been pleasantly surprised. They've never seen anything like it before."
<p><BR>- Doug Thomas


