<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chronicles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.C.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Gay Grants </B></FONT SIZE><br>
The Lambda Foundation, established in 1983, is offering Work Place Equality Grants. The grants, which range from $100 to $1,000, can be used for the formation of a gay/lesbian employee group, gay-friendly hiring policies, or nondis-criminatory clauses and domestic partnership benefit plans.<p>
"This grant is intended for any individual, group, employee or employer in the Greater Pittsburgh business community with intentions of supporting Pittsburgh's gay and lesbian community by implementing gay-friendly policies and procedures," says Bill Nist, foundation president.<p>
Although several companies have requested application forms, none had been returned by press time. Nist says the goal is to fund at least $3,000 in grants this year. The foundation's board has granted more than $215,000 to gay and lesbian organizations in the past 11 years.<p>

<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Traveller's Aid </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Convinced that the commission cap instituted by the major airlines this spring would close many small travel agents and increase already long holds for travellers calling the airlines directly, Rosenbluth International Travel recently activated a new reservations service.<p>
By calling 1-800-33-CHOICE travellers can get air, hotel or car reservations through a trained agent. The benefits? These agents have the information at their fingertips to provide a tailored travel schedule at the lowest fares available. And you don't have to deal with the airlines directly.<p>
Rosenbluth spokesperson Liz Joseph says that the increased volume and opportunities to add to their existing client base will mean profit for Rosenbluth's despite the commission cap.<p>

<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>PA Job Forecast </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Healthcare and printing/ publishing are expected to be big job generators for the next 10 years in the state, according to the Penn State Center for Regional Business Analysis.<p>
David L. Passmore, professor of vocational education at Penn State in University Park, says healthcare employment should grow in Pennsylvania regardless of how reform shakes up the industry. Passmore's study shows a 36.9% growth in that sector by 2005. Even if the average annual growth in health-related industry spending was 2%, employment would still increase by 18%. Under a high-spending scenario, jobs would increase by 81%.<p>
Not all sectors will grow evenly. For example, registered nurses in the baseline forecast will increase by more than 40,000 from 1990 to 2005. At the same time, an increase of less than 300 dentists is predicted.<p>
For the printing and publishing industry, the study predicts an 11% growth in jobs by 2005. More than 75% of the new jobs will be generated by increased exports of printed material to other states and countries. Total output for the in-dustry could grow by $2.79billion.<p>
What may stimulate demand for printed products over the next decade are improvements in literacy, population and school enrollment growth, enhanced international copyright protection and lower international trade barriers. Impediments include higher postal rates, environmental legislation, increasing labor costs and challenges from electronic publishing and distribution.<p>

<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Better Labor Record?</B></FONT SIZE><br>
There were fewer labor strikes in Pennsylvania in 1994 than in any previous year since 1970, the first year the state began collecting statistics, according to the Department of Labor & Industry in Harrisburg. In 1994, there were 108 strikes, six fewer than 1993.<p>
While the number of labor disputes dropped in 1994, the number of employees involved in strikes rose by 81%. Workdays lost also increased last year. Why? Many of the strikes involved large numbers of workers in steel, apparel, machinery and trucking. Those industries accounted for 76% of total lost workdays.<p>
There were 17 strikes affecting school districts, a 6% decline from 1993. Some 47 of Pennsylvania's 67 counties registered at least one labor dispute. Of 1994's stikes, 86 were in the private sector and 22 in the public sector.<p>

<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Harassment Up Again</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Filings of sexual harassment went up again in Pennsylvania, by 8% over the previous year. Nearly 97% of the 432 sexual harass-ment cases filed were employ-ment related, says the Pennsylvania Human Relations Commission in Harrisburg. Almost 88% were filed by women. Philadelphia County had the most filings with 77, and Allegheny came in second with 71 filings.<p>
"The commission is fast approaching a saturation point where it cannot continue to process more cases with less staff and financial support," says Robert Johnson Smith, chair of the PHRC. "Also distressing is the ever-increasing number of racial, religious and ethnic tension situations that are occurring across the commonwealth which are addressed by staff."<p>
In the 1993-94 fiscal year, 5,668 new complaints were filed, adding to 6,979 pending cases. Of the new cases, 85% were employment related. Allegheny County accounted for the majority of employment cases, with 1,099.<p>
Of the 4,842 docketed employment cases in the state, manufacturing was identified most often, 14% of the time. Medical services and retailers followed, tied at 11% of the cases.<p>
Some 29,465 informal complaints were handled by PHRC staff, up 20% from the last fiscal year, and the staff closed nearly 5,000 cases, awarding $9.4 million to victims of discrimination.<p>
The PHRC handles cases of discrimination involving race, color, religion, ancestry, age (40 and above), sex, nationality, non-job-related disability, known association with a person with a disability, familial status or possession of a GED. The commission's jurisdiction covers employment, housing and commercial real estate, public accommodations, education, refusal or willingness to participate in abortion procedures and racial tension.<p>

<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Pacesetters in Pittsburgh</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Last month, Executive Report got a call from the U.S. Department of Commerce's Office of Technology,  informing us that they have awarded three Pittsburgh organizations with PACE Certificates of Recognition.<p>
The three local recipients are the Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship (see "Teaching the American Dream," this issue), FORE Systems Inc.(see Best Deals, this issue) and Medrad Inc. <p>
"The purpose of PACE [Partnerships for a Competitive Economy] is for us to take technology policy debate outside of the beltway, to people in local markets," says Kelly Carnes, deputy assistant secretary for Technology Policy at the U.S. Department of Commerce. "The PACE awards highlight models of success, models people can learn from about how to compete in the new global economy, employing training and technology innovatively."<p>

<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Kudos for Some Locals</B></FONT SIZE><br>
<dl>
<li>John Swanson, founder and chief technologist of Ansys Inc. in Houston, Pa., was the only Pennsylvanian on Industry Week's 1994 top 50 list of R&D stars. Swanson was described as "a pioneer in the development and application of computerized finite element analysis." Ansys develops software for computer-aided engineering analysis and design.
<li>Eyetique in Squirrel Hill was named one of the best eyewear stores in the world by Kim Johnson Gross and Jeff Stone in their book, "Eyeglassesface to face."
<li>Rankings recently published by Qualified Remodeler magazine indicated that KoolVent Group Inc. of Monroeville is the third largest U.S. remodeler. The company was named No. 1 in full-line remodeling, with sales of $34 million.
<li>Bowman's Accounting Report included Pittsburgh-based Alpern, Rosenthal & Co. in its "Best of the Best" CPA firms listing for 1994.
<li>Jones, Day, Reavis & Pogue got the highest rating for any law firm with offices in Pittsburgh (selection in 10 practice areas) in a national survey of 400 corporate counsel by The American Lawyer.
</dl>

<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Subscribers Like HMOs</B></FONT SIZE><br>
HMO consumers are more satisfied than those in fee-for-service plans, regardless of health status, according to a survey by Sachs/Scarborough HealthPlus.<p>
"Even in markets with low managed care penetration, consumers are choosing HMOs, and they are satisfied. Nationally, and in individual markets, people prefer HMOs," says Gary Pickens, senior vice president of Sachs Group Inc., Evanston, Ill.<p>
Here are some findings based on the initial results from Chicago, Cleveland, Dallas, Denver and Pittsburgh:<p>
<dl>
<li>Consumers gave themselves nearly identical rankings of 68 points, on a scale of 0 to 100, for their own health status.
<li>Eighty-two percent of the respondents in HMOs said they were satisfied with their plans, compared to 72% in traditional fee-for-service plans, 71% in PPOs and 69% covered by Medicare.
<li> People are in HMOs because they want to be: 67% of HMO subscribers had a choice of plans.
<li> HMO subscribers are pleased with the range of services. Seventy-five percent are satisfied, compared to 68% of people in fee-for-service, 67% in PPOs and 69% in Medicare.
<li> Traditional plans still rate high on access to physicians. Eighty-three percent of the people in traditional plans are satisfied with physician access for routine services, compared to 82% for those in Medicare, 77% for HMO members and 76% for PPO subscribers.
</dl>

<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>New Business</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Eastern Mountain Sports of Peterborough, N.H., has opened its first Pittsburgh store in South Hills Village.<p>
<li>Starbucks Coffee Co. of Seattle has entered the Pittsburgh market in Squirrel Hill. 
<li>New York-based Peter Kump's School of Culinary Arts is opening a satellite school in Sewickley.
<li>Mesonic of Austria has opened its U.S. headquarters in Oakdale.
</dl>

<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Ten to One</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Some 6,000 people were expected to apply for 600 jobs at the 200,000-square-foot Wal-Mart super center in Indiana County. The store, to open this summer, will be the largest in the state and will be open 24 hours a day. Wal-Mart is based in Bentonville, Ark.<p>

<hr>
<H2>Coming in July</h2>
Next month, Executive Report will investigate Pittsburgh's stake in NAFTA, the economic promise of Westmoreland County and the state of the state in the mortgage industry. <p>
We'll also be debuting an all new lifestyle section, which over the months to come will take you into executive homes, dining with the Executive Diner and exploring the favorite haunts of some of Pittsburgh's top executives. And that's just for starters.<p>

