<HEAD>
<TITLE>Money Matters: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.MM.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Buyouts and Real Estate Planning</B> </FONT SIZE> 
<br><i> By Glenn R. Flickinger</i>
<hr>
Owners of closely held, small to midsize companies are discovering a new way to reach their estate planning goals and to achieve liquidity at the same time: the company buyout. Sound sur-prising? Perhaps. But buyouts, in many creative forms, are back in a major way, and the timing for such transactions for family-owned companies could not be better. There are many good reasons.<p>
Recently, the available pool of equity specifically targeted at small to medium-sized companies has grown dramatically. In the past two years alone, an estimated $5 billion in equity has been raised by various types of buyout funds throughout the United States, searching not for the mega-deals of the 1980s, but for small and medium-sized transactions in the $5 million to $100 million range.<p>
Because this equity will be leveraged with debt, the total amount of capital available for buyouts of this type exceeds $15 billion. Improved conditions in the commercial bank lending market mean the debt required to leverage this pool of equity has become more readily available, helping to increase buyout activity.<p>
All these factors have combined to result in higher prices/valuations for closely held businesses. Today, a price multiple of five to six times cash flow, occasionally even higher, is possible to achieve. That's compared to price multiples of four times cash flow available several years ago, if any buyer could be found at all.<p>
In addition, equity investors have come to better understand closely held companies. They realize that most of these firms are not managed for financial reporting purposes and tend to understate actual earnings compared with publicly held companies.<p>
These sophisticated investors know how to normalize their valuations of closely held companies, and have come to understand the enormous value imbedded in the family-held business market.<p>
According to one study, an estimated $6.8 trillion of net worth will change generational hands in the next decade. Buyouts in various forms done with the appropriate supportive investor can help businesses survive the generational transition.<p>
Equity investors focus on several key factors in searching for attractive targets. They concentrate on businesses with strong earnings histories and dominant niches in the markets they serve. They look for companies with growth potential, or those that can be strategically merged with other firms to increase value in what is referred to as a build-up strategy.<p>
The most important factor is demonstrated management capability. In general, investors are financially oriented, not operationally oriented. They desire to provide financial backing and to support strong business managers. They want little or nothing to do with day-to-day oper-ations. Therefore, the management team that will lead the company is always the focal point of any type of buyout.<p>
Equity investors have developed several variations on the basic buyout theme. In the traditional buyout of a family-held company, the business is sold to the investor and to a core manager or group of managers.<p>
The family sellers receive a cash price, sometimes 100% cash, sometimes with a portion of the purchase price tied to future performance, dependent on circumstances. The managers receive a minority equity stake alongside the new majority owners.<p>
Often the managers obtain the first refusal rights to "buy back" the company, or an "earn out" clause specifying that they can obtain ownership of the company over time under agreed upon performance levels. Management retains operating control with a knowledgeable partner to help grow the company.<p>
The variations on this basic theme are infinite and are limited only by the creativity of the buyers, sellers and their advisors. In one variation, owners desire to achieve personal liquidity without sacrificing operating control. In a private recapitalization, buyout firms will purchase a significant minority share of the value of the company so that the seller achieves partial personal liquidity for financial planning purposes, retains control of the company and obtains a financial partner who will help grow the overall value of the company.<p>
Another variation is the family succession buyout or a private family recapitalization. This involves the purchase of the company by a younger generation of family management from the prior generation. Such a transaction can achieve liquidity for estate planning purposes, transfer wealth to the younger generation and preserve the family identity of the business.<p>
The bottom line is that there are a large number of sophisticated financial buyers with large amounts of capital focusing on the purchase of family-owned businesses. Combined with the current availability of commercial bank lending, this factor has forced selling prices significantly higher.<p>
But perhaps more important than price is the fact that these investors, properly understood and properly matched to the business value of the family owners, can be excellent business partners in generational transition situations, in management transitions and in growing the value of a business.<p>
In any case, owners of closely held businesses should seriously consider the buyout as a sound estate planning alternative. And they should carefully negotiate any buyout package to achieve full value for their companies in ways that are realistic and satisfying.<p>

<i>Glenn R. Flickinger is president of Epic Capital Corp. </i>
