<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report June 1995 Issue: People Making News</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <FONT SIZE=+2><B>People Making News
: Harry Ferrair</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By David Hasley</i><P>
<HR>
<b>Occupation:</b>	President and CEO of Gamma Sports International<br>
<b>Age:</b> 62<br>
<b>Family Life:</b> Ferrari, who is married with two sons, lives in Fox Chapel.<br>
<B>Education:</B> Ph.D. in materials engineering from the University of Michigan<br>
<b>Hobbies:</b> Tennis<br>
<b>Last Vacation & Where:</b> U.S. Open<br>
<b>Last Book Read:</b> "Of Permanent Value" by Warren Buffet<br>
<HR>

At a time when many people's thoughts would be turning toward retirement, Harry Ferrari is patenting an improved irradiation technology for an elastic nylon racquet string which he believes can outplay natural gut. It's all part of Gamma Sports, the tennis string and grip manufacturing company he founded in his basement following the loss of a local tournament in 1974. Ferrari maintains he lost the match because of a replacement racquet, strung with inferior nylon, which he played with after his natural gut racquet popped a string.<p>
Ferrari used his knowledge of irradiating polymers (he's a former materials scientist for Westinghouse Electric Corp.) to create a synthetic string that played as well as gut. The industry's reception was warm: The string was rated the No. 1 synthetic string in the world for 17 years running.<p>
The company has done well. Gamma Sports, which Ferrari's older son recently joined, introduced a new line of racquets, apparel and tennis balls this year. Not long ago, Gamma surpassed Prince as the second largest tennis string supplier in the world.<p>
Meanwhile, Ferrari kept his day job with Westinghouse until 1990. "The company was running so well on its own, why interfere?" he says. While at Westinghouse, Ferrari obtained more than 25 patents, published over 50 articles and received the American Nuclear Society's highest honor. And, yes, he is related to foreign auto manufacturer Enzo Ferrari. (Enzo is Harry's father's cousin.)<p>
<BR>-- David Hasley
