<b><font size =+2>Violence in our community:<br></font><font size =+1>  How can we make their future safer?</font></b>



<h3>Message From Linda Dickerson</h3>
<b>Dear Readers:<BR></b>
Over the years, United Way of Southwestern Pennsylvania has used this Executive Report supplement to inform the community about the vital role it plays in bringing us all together to help our neighbors. United Way has shown us how, through a single gift, we can reach out to people confronted with abusive relationships, poverty, trouble in school, drinking and other drug problems, homelessness, teen pregnancy and a host of other problems.<P>
In this publication, United Way has also talked about its efficiency - how more than 87 cents of each dollar we give supports programs that help those in need. It's shown us that hundreds of local people serve on committees that support the annual campaign, that allocate contributions, that guide volunteer projects like United Way Day of Caring, and serve on the boards of directors, holding United Way accountable, providing oversight and making sure our gifts are used efficiently to help people with the greatest needs.<P>
With this year's supplement, our local United Way joins a variety of local individuals and organizations in bringing to our attention the issue of community and family violence, as if repeated news reports of murder, crime and domestic and gang violence are not enough to tell us there is a problem.<P>
Already individuals and organizations throughout southwestern Pennsylvania have responded, including the NAACP, U.S. Attorney's Office for the Western District of Pennsylvania and U.S. Attorney Frederick Thieman, the Allegheny County Policy Council, and even the Pittsburgh Steelers. Also confronting violence are countless social agencies throughout southwestern Pennsylvania that you'll read about in this supplement.<P>
But we can't sit back and wait for these groups to act for us. We must become involved. Our United Way offers all of us that chance by two simple steps: making a pledge and volunteering.<P>
For all of these reasons and more, Executive Report supports our local United Way. If you haven't already done so, we urge you to get involved, too. If you have, I hope you'll pledge your continued support.<P>


Sincerely,<BR>

Linda Dickerson, Publisher

<HR>
Violence Is a Community Issue<BR>

Violence is an equal opportunity phenomenon. It destroys without regard to race, religion, nationality or socioeconomic status. Whether it's living behind locked doors, wearing gang colors, suffering the wrath of an abusive partner, waking to the sounds of gunfire or becoming another statistic, no one is immune to its impact.<p>
According to the National Crime Prevention Council, every 17 seconds someone somewhere in the United States reports a murder, rape, robbery or assault. Still, there are those who would choose to close their eyes to this crisis rather than acknowledge the reality of violence. "Until you've watched a child get shot, it's hard to imagine. Seeing is believing," says Mike Hepler, president and CEO of Boys and Girls Clubs of Western Pennsylvania.<P>
"Violence is spreading," Hepler continues. "We must all be part of the solution."<p>
But violence is a complex problem that offers no easy solutions. Compounding the issue further is the fact that violence can take on many different forms. "There's the overt street violence," explains Bill Brammer, executive director of the Rankin Christian Center, "and there are the more subtle kinds of violence - the injustice, the neglect, the racism.<P>
"We're also experiencing something new," Brammer adds. "People are being shot for no reason. Random violence puts everybody at risk."<P>
In a society where no safe haven exists, the boundaries of violence must constantly be redefined. "Twenty years ago, domestic violence wasn't even recognized," says Marty Friday, executive director of the Women's Center & Shelter of Greater Pittsburgh (one of the first in the country). "Since that time, however, there have been changes in the laws and changes in our culture. The situation has improved."<P>
And while this piece of the puzzle has benefited from increased awareness, violence in general continues to grow in intensity. "Violence is not only becoming more violent," says Laura Tiedge, executive director of Camp Fire/Boys and Girls Greater Pittsburgh Council, "but there's also more youth-on-youth violence."<P>
The National Crime Prevention Council affirms that a disproportionate number of young people are both the victims - in excess of 5,000 children a day are subjected to violence - and the perpetrators of violent crimes. In Allegheny County, juvenile crime increased dramatically between 1988 and 1993, according to statistics from the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Western District of Pennsylvania. Specifically, statistics indicate that juvenile homicide rose 400 percent; aggravated assault increased 85 percent; sex offenses increased 116 percent, and robberies, 55 percent.<P>
But how did this happen? How did violence become such an ingrained part of our lives? Some authorities point to substance abuse. "Where I sit, people are killing each other over drugs. Drugs and alcohol perpetuate violence," asserts Karen Payne, project director of the Homewood/Brushton Collaborative, a group of agencies mobilized by United Way to help substance abusing women and their families.<P>
Some believe it's the availability of guns. "There's a big difference between the right to bear arms and arming children," Hepler insists. "We have to get the guns out of the hands of the kids. Until then, we're fighting a losing battle."<P>
Others blame the media. "Television reflects violence in our society and promotes violence," Friday maintains. "Children see violence as a way of solving conflicts and getting what they want. Television desensitizes people to violence, so violence is accepted."<P>
Many look to the need to cooperate. Notes Bishop Donald Wuerl of the diocese of Pittsburgh, "Deep within each of us is the spirit of God that gives us both the desire and the strength to work together to overcome any human problem, even the violence that haunts our streets, schools, families and communities."<P>
Some look to a decline in values as the true culprit. "When I was growing up, we always had our families, our community," recalls Barbara Baulding, a project coordinator of the Urban League of Pittsburgh, which is coordinating an anti-violence initiative, "It Takes a Whole Community to Raise a Child."<P>
Explains Baulding, "The whole neighborhood raised us. That's the difference between then and now. We must work to strengthen the family and strengthen the children. Kids are our future. Without them, what will we be?"<P>
Clearly no single cause is responsible for violence, but most experts agree that without a singular effort, there's no true hope of stopping it. And that's what the individuals and organizations fighting violence deal in - hope. "Yes," Payne asserts, "I think we are making a difference, but it's a day-by-day, hour-by-hour process."<P>
And although striving to do better is often an elusive goal, it is always an essential part of any program's success. To that end, Tiedge says, "we must find creative ways to involve people, to empower neighborhoods, parents, schools. Violence isn't one agency's issue - it's the community's."<P>
So what are we doing about violence?<P>

"No one wants to live in the world we're creating right now," admits Gary Lasinski, executive director of the YMCA/McKeesport. "We try to take a positive approach. We treat young people as resources, not as problems to be solved."<P>
Nonprofits, foundations, and other community-based organizations throughout southwestern Pennsylvania share that positive philosophy. From the Boys and Girls Clubs of Western Pennsylvania to the YMCA of Beaver County, these groups have become a powerful force in the struggle against violence. Their programs are about providing choices, opportunities and hope to those segments of the population that are most at risk and most in need.<P>
The following are exam-ples of the organizations and initiatives combating violence in our community:<P>

<b>Boys and Girls Clubs of Western Pennsylvania<BR></B>
With 6,000 youth members and nine locations, the Boys and Girls Clubs, a United Way-supported agency, is looking to get more teens, particularly girls, to take advantage of its services, thereby avoiding disruptive and violent behavior. One of its newest programs - Teen Force - is a grassroots effort aimed at encouraging young people to work within their communities. <P>

<b>Boy Scouts of America, Greater Pittsburgh Council<BR></b>
More than 4,000 local youth benefit from the Scouts' Urban Scouting Program, which is supported by United Way gifts. This program prepares young men, many of whom are disadvantaged, for leadership roles in the community, and it helps them to develop a sense of responsibility. Based on the principles and lessons in the scouting manual, adult volunteers, usually parents, lead the troops, tailoring activities to meet the needs of their particular community.<P>

<b>Family Services of Beaver/Butler County<BR></b>
Breaking the cycle of violence is the key to the Play Therapy Program of the United Way-supported Family Services of Beaver/Butler County. Through music and play therapy and other activities, children under 12 who have been abused and/or who have witnessed violence in their family learn to heal their psychological and emotional trauma. In the long run, the program helps them become violence-free parents.<P>

<b>Hill House Association<BR></b>
Hill House Association helps residents of the Hill District and Pittsburgh reduce violence in the family and among youth through a variety of services, including a child care center - the after-school Kaufmann Program Center, which features computer learning and tutoring for ages 6 to 12 - and the Kay Program Center, where job training and placement are emphasized. Hill House, which United Way contributors support, is also home to Pittsburgh in Partnership with Parents, a program that enhances parenting skills and reduces violence in families.<P>

<b>Homewood/Brushton Collaborative<BR></b>
United Way mobilized 62 agencies in this cooperative effort, which seeks to serve as many families experiencing substance abuse problems as possible by putting them in touch with the appropriate organizations that can help.<P>

<b>Mon Valley YMCA<BR></b>
The YMCA's Juvenile Referral and Prevention Program is designed to address the economic and social factors contributing to violence and other problems youth face, including drugs, alcohol, peer pressure and teen pregnancy. This program of the United Way-funded agency provides education, public forums, family recreation and community socialization.<P>

<b>Mon Valley Youth and Teen Association<BR></B>
This organization offers youth a variety of productive activities, including clubs, day camps, group camping, resident camp, and youth and teen centers. In addition, the association, supported by United Way gifts, recently introduced its Teens in Control Program to deal directly with such issues as gang violence, AIDS, teen pregnancy, and drug and alcohol abuse.<P>

<b>NAACP/Pittsburgh<BR></b>
"Strategy `95: A Plan to End Violence in Pittsburgh" is the NAACP's latest initiative in this arena. Although still in the preliminary stages, the strategy's early work sessions have produced a number of viable solutions to the problem of violence. This grassroots effort will challenge employers, schools and government to join the fight.<P>

<b>Pittsburgh Action Against Rape<BR></b>
This United Way-supported agency helps victims of sexual assault, domestic violence and other violence with counseling and support services. Its educational efforts in the community also help to prevent violence.<P>

<b>Rankin Christian Center<BR></b>
Offering a number of different services, the center concentrates on developing parenting skills and personal goals. Literacy classes, support groups, pre-natal care, after-school programs and career training are all part of the United Way-supported agency's big picture approach to reducing violence.<P>

<b>Three Rivers Youth (TRY)<BR></b>
Targeting high-risk youth and their families, TRY works to prevent violence by providing a comprehensive, integrated system of services. A United Way-supported agency, TRY offers residential, educational <P>
and vocational programs as well as outpatient mental health, drug and alcohol treatment.<P>

<b>Urban League of Pittsburgh<BR></b>
In addition to its prime objective of providing employment, housing and education opportunities to youth and adults, the Urban League, which benefits from United Way contributions, recently unveiled its ground-breaking initiative "It Takes a Whole Community to Raise a Child." The project seeks to raise awareness of violence and involve the community in responding to this issue.<P>

<b>Urban Youth Action<BR></b>
Established nearly 30 years ago, UYA has managed to stay current by offering young people programs that confront issues of conflict resolution, self-esteem and negative peer pressure. The UYA, supported by United Way contributors, also provides computer instruction as well as career research, selection and planning.<P>

<b>Women's Center & Shelter of Greater Pittsburgh<BR></b>
The Women's Center & Shelter provides women and children who are living in immediate danger of domestic violence with a safe place to take refuge from violence. In addition to counseling women housed at the center, the United Way-supported agency offers other forms of counseling, including a telephone hot line and assistance to women maneuvering through the judicial system. It also strives to educate the medical community about domestic violence.<P>

<b>YMCA/McKeesport<BR></b>
Bringing services directly to a neighborhood in need is the impetus behind the Crawford Village Outreach Program of the YMCA of McKeesport, an agency that benefits from the annual United Way campaign. From cooking classes to basketball leagues, tutoring sessions to computer workshops, this program is helping more than 340 children ages 7 to 14 in this public housing community stay away from violence and violent behavior.<P>

<b>YMCA of Pittsburgh<BR></b>
Taking a proactive stand, the East End Outreach Program of the United Way-supported YMCA not only offers job internships and gang prevention activities but also places outreach workers in the communities in an effort to link youth and families with available services. Participants in the program have also started their own computer company and commercial cleaning venture, learning firsthand an alternative to violence.<P>

<b>YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh<BR></b>
The YWCA of Greater Pittsburgh is the lead agency in a multi-agency effort to reach young women involved in violent or antisocial behavior or those at risk of such behavior. The FORCE (Female Outreach Collaborative Effort) program places outreach workers in five local communities to identify the young women and then connect them with community resources. <P>

<b>Anti-Violence Initiative at work in Allegheny County<BR></b>
Residents of Allegheny County are lucky. They happen to live in one of the safest major metropolitan centers in the country. But that good news is also cause for concern. According to the U.S. Attorney's Office of the Western District of Pennsylvania, there's one aspect of violence that continues to escalate.<p>
Between 1988 and 1993, the country has seen juvenile crime increase by nearly 80 percent. And, unfortunately, Allegheny County is no exception to this national trend. During that same time period, our region has experienced a more than 50% rise in juvenile crime.<P>
In an effort to respond to this growing problem, the Allegheny County Anti-Violence Initiative was founded last year. This program presents a two-pronged plan of attack. The first component involves a concerted and coordinated effort by federal, state and local law enforcement agencies to target those individuals exposing young people to guns, violence and drugs.<P>
The second revolves around a community-wide venture to offer children alternatives to violence. To that end, a coalition of neighborhood, government, police, foundation, corporate and church representatives have joined forces to establish the Youth Crime Prevention Council of Allegheny County.<P>
The Prevention Council's goals include providing kids with after-school safe places, in-school activities, sports leagues, summer jobs, family support, mentoring, Head Start and day care programs, leadership development, health and wellness services, juvenile justice and community accountability. In addition, the Council will actively work to stop the proliferation of guns, substance abuse and domestic violence.<P>
But it won't be easy. "The problems we face didn't begin overnight," asserts Frederick W. Thieman, U.S. District Attorney, "nor will they end overnight."
However, in Thieman's view, Allegheny County has gone a long way to creating a foundation of hope. "A broad cross-section of the community has come together to act rather than argue," he affirms. "The question is not whether a well-planned Anti-Violence Initiative can succeed, but how each citizen can become part of the solution."<P>

<font size =+2>Help Stop Violence: Volunteer!<BR></font>
Putting an end to violence - whether it be spouse battering, robbery or even threats - requires personal commitment and action. One of the ways we can become involved in the solution to violence is by volunteering. Volunteering - as an individual or as a group - is uplifting for both the volunteers and the people in our community who stand to benefit.<P>
United Way volunteer centers can put you in touch with community service opportunities ranging from tutoring kids at youth centers to helping teen parents become good mothers and fathers. Or, form a team of co-workers and "adopt" a local nonprofit that serves youth and families and volunteer year round. To volunteer, call the United Way volunteer center nearest you: Allegheny County 394-5380; Beaver County 728-3900; Greene County 852-2893; Mon Valley 684-7800; Washington County 225-7480.<P>

<b>Callers respond to TV show on violence<BR></b>
On the evening of March 4, Pittsburgh television stations came together in an unprecedented simulcast of "It Takes a Whole Community to Raise a Child." Designed to increase awareness of violence and commitment to becoming involved in fighting it, the telecast included the United Way HelpLine telephone number for callers who wanted more information on how they can help as well as how they can find help for community and family violence problems. Here is a sample of the 500 calls that came in that night:<P>
<dl>
<li>A man called wanting to start a sports recreation program for the youth in his community. United Way HelpLine referred him to a local agency serving youth as well as the City Department of Public Parks and Recreation.
<li>A man who runs a fencing school called to offer scholarships to young men interested in learning fencing but unable to afford lessons.
<li>A woman called for help for her two young children who, having witnessed a violent altercation in front of their home, were suffering post-traumatic stress disorder. They were referred to a local nonprofit for counseling.
<li>A film producer called to volunteer his time and talents to producing videos promoting non-violence and was referred to the Urban League of Pittsburgh.
<li>An actor wanted to become involved with theatrical productions promoting anti-drug and non-violence. He was referred to a production company of local artists concerned with our community's health.
<li>Several teachers and readers called, interested in anti-violence curricula for their students. They were referred to organizations such as the Heartwood Institute, Pittsburgh Peace Institute, and the Allegheny County Health Department violence prevention program.
<li>Many callers wanted to mentor a youth. They were referred to many local agencies, including Boys and Girls Clubs of Western Pennsylvania, Big Brothers and Sisters, Generations Together, Cities in Schools, Hosanna House and local neighborhood organi-zations and churches.
As a follow-up to the simulcast, local radio and television stations are continuing to run public service announcements that tell people how to get involved in stopping community and family violence. If you want to help, call United Way HelpLine at 255-1155.<P>
</dl>
<b>Day of Caring: September 13<BR></b>
The fifth annual United Way Day of Caring will kick off the 1995 United Way of Southwestern Pennsylvania campaign Wednesday, September 13, 1995. On that day, more than 6,000 people are expected to volunteer at local nonprofits, learning firsthand some of the needs in our community and how their community service work lets them respond to those needs. If your organization would like to participate, call Carla Barricella, United Way of Allegheny County special events coordinator, at 456-6863.<P>

<b>A message to local business leaders: <BR></b>
It's time to stop the violence<P>

It's time. It's time that we did something about the violence that is ripping apart our families and our community. It's time to stop waiting for the groups and individuals already dedicated to ending violence to act for us. We must all take action.<P>
There are hundreds of ways we can help put an end to violence in our communities and in our families by doing one thing: by becoming involved in our local United Way. As campaign chairs for the United Way of Southwestern Pennsylvania partners, we challenge all local business leaders to join our organizations in supporting our community through United Way.<P>
Specifically, we ask you to conduct a United Way campaign in your organization. Make the campaign a personal and an organizational priority. Select your best people to conduct the campaign and then give them the resources to do the best job they can to plan, organize and conduct a winning campaign.<P>
United Way's single, coordinated workplace campaign offers you and your organization a comprehensive approach in:<P>
<dl>
<li> responding to multiple needs in our community at the same time
<li> saving administrative time and costs associated with conducting multiple campaigns
<li> giving employees a greater understanding of community needs and how they can become involved in responding to these needs all at the same time
<li> saving agencies the expense and time of conducting campaigns and processing pledges 
<li> contributing easily and conveniently through payroll deduction
<li> volunteering, which boosts morale among employees, builds teamwork and helps local people in need.

</dl>
