<HR>
10 things you can do:<P>

1.	Teach your children how to reduce their risk of being victims of violent crime. Insist on knowing at all times where your kids are, what they're doing and who they're with.<br>
2.	Get involved. Volunteer to help neighborhood anti-crime and other improvement efforts.<br>
3.	Use common-sense tips to reduce your risk of being a crime victim. Stay in well-lighted, busy areas; travel with a friend if possible; walk in a confident, assured way.<br>
4.	Report crimes and suspicious activities to police; agree to testify when necessary.<br>
5.	Get to know your neighbors and agree to look out for each other.<br>
6.	Find ways to settle arguments without violence. Be a good role model for your children.<br>
7.	Use common courtesy. It helps ease tensions that lead to violence.<br>
8.	Don't carry a weapon. You lose, whether you use it or it's used on you.<br>
9.	Don't support illegal activities like buying stolen property or using drugs. It's the wrong message for children.<br>
10.	Volunteer your home as a reliable source of help for kids who are scared or need assistance.<br>
<P>
Source: National Crime Prevention Council

