<HEAD>
<TITLE>Feature: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B> It Was a Very Good Year: The Pennsylvania 100 </B></FONT><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b>Most of Pennsylvania's largest non-financial publicly held companies continued to enjoy the recovery in 1994.</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Jane A. Black</i>
<HR>

If Pennsylvania's large, nonfi-nancial publicly held companies are any indication, the economy continued to improve last year.<P>
Total revenues for the Pennsylvania 100 rose a healthy 7.5% in 1994 to $208.9 billion, surpassing the previous year's 5.7% increase. Net income went up almost 48% from $5.1 billion (adjusted) to $7.5 billion.<P>
John Frankola, director of research for Parker/Hunter Inc., says, "We are coming off a very good year, following two good years." He estimates that operating earnings for the Pennsylvania 100 companies would be similar to, if not greater than, those for the S&P 500. "The operating earnings for the S&P 500 were up 17.6%. Operating earnings are a little bit different than what we have for the Pennsylvania 100 because we didn't [isolate] non-recurring items. But I would guess that the operating earnings for the Pennsylvania 100 are in the 20% to 30% range."<P>
Like last year, Parker/Hunter compiled this year's list using "as reported" figures instead of those with extraordinary charges and income removed.<P>
Frankola says that one reason why Pennsylvania companies did so well was because cyclical companies did well, and the Pennsylvania 100 has a plethora of those. 
"It was a good year for cyclical companies, which is a trend we see developing with the overall economy strengthening. Steel, other metals like Alcoa, chemicals - most of those companies are cyclical and had revenues and earnings above average," says Frankola.<P>
For proof, he points to the double-digit revenue growth of Alcoa, PPG, Bethlehem Steel and AMP, all mature companies in the top 25.<P>
Other large companies, which often don't grow as rapidly as smaller companies, had revenue growth above recent historical rates. "USX had 7% growth in revenues," says Frankola, adding that Sun had 5% growth, which is an improvement over its five-year rate of about 1%.<P>
What's helping is a steel boomlet that's been underway, a relatively unheard of phenomenon since the late 1970s. Demand from U.S. manu-facturers last year caused steel consumption to jump to 108 million tons, a 3% increase over 1993. Prices rose 9%.<P>
Of course, that's good news for Pennsylvania, a steelmaker hub. For U.S. Steel, it meant the highest quarterly shipments in more than five years. The company shipped over 2.9 million tons in fourth quarter 1994 from three primary facilities. U.S. Steel shipped some 10.6 million tons total in 1994, and expects to send off 12.5 million net tons this year.<P>
"We expect average 1995 raw steel production to exceed 1994 levels, reflecting operating improvements successfully implemented by the steel group," says USX board chairman, Charles Corry.<P>
Bethlehem Steel enjoyed similar success. "This is the first time Bethlehem has been profitable for the full year since 1989," says Curtis Barnette, chairman and CEO. Bethlehem shipped 9.3 million tons in 1994, up 3%.<P>
Some others in the steel category also did well. Lukens posted a 9.8% growth in revenues, as did J&L Specialty. Armco is a notable exception in the steel category, as it leads the Pennsylvania 100 in revenue decline with a -13.6% change from its 1993 performance.<P>
Allegheny Ludlum, which experi-enced its first-ever labor strike in 1994, bounced back by year-end, shipping a record level of 156,000 tons of product in the final quarter. Rich Sporrer of Parker/Hunter's research department continues to recommend the purchase of ALS for long-term investors. "In 1995, we expect ALS to benefit from continuing strong demand for stainless products, reduced competition from imported steels and year-over-year price hikes of 5% to 10%," says Sporrer.
Thirty-two percent of the companies in the top 25 had double-digit growth, Frankola notes. For the remaining 75 companies, 44% had growth of 10% or more. Only 14% of the Pennsylvania 100 had revenues that were lower than their previous year's.<P>

<font size =+2><B>Good On Paper</B></font size> 
Of the top 25, Alco Standard had the highest growth in revenues, up 24%. The company is one of the largest U.S. distributors of paper products. Alco Standard is also a growing distri-butor of office products and a manu-facturer of food service equipment.<P>
It's the office angle that intrigues Frankola. "When the economy is good, we are all passing paper more," he notes. "Alco is also in office equipment leasing, selling and servicing." The increased use of and demand for office equipment, such as fax machines, low-cost copiers and color copiers, bodes well for companies in that industry, Frankola says.<P>
Revenues for Alco Office Products were up 41.3% to $2.2 billion, and operating income advanced 43.7% to $199.4 million. The growth reflects a record number of companies acquired in 1994. Excluding those purchases, Alco Office Products revenues increased 14% and operating income rose 24%. The company's other business group, Unisource, increased revenues 18.3% to $5.8 billion.<P>
"The past year was one of the most significant in Alco Standard's 29-year history," says John Stuart, president and CEO. "Internal growth, combined with a strong acquisition program, will sustain our overall growth rate through 1995 and beyond."
No. 82 on the Pennsylvania 100, Hunt Manufacturing, is also in the office product and supply business. The maker of X-acto brand knives had record net sales of $288 million for the year ending Nov. 27, 1994. The 95-year-old company saw office furniture sales grow by 17%, and sales of desktop accessories and supplies increase 13%.<P>

<font size =+2><B>Another Office Leader</B></font size> 
"It's interesting to note that the company in the top 25 with the second largest jump in revenues was Intelligent Electronics. That also reflects the office automation trend," comments Frankola.<P>
Intelligent Electronics is one of the nation's largest distributors of computer products and services with approxi-mately 1,700 franchised stores in the United States and Canada, according to "The Emerald/Home State Guide to Pennsylvania Business." Among its stores are those operating under the names Todays Computer Business, Entre Computer Centers and Connect-ing Point of America. (The company sold its BizMart division for $265 million in 1993.)<P>
Intelligent Electronics posted reve-nue growth of 18.2% from 1993 to 1994. <P>
It's likely that more of the company's income will be paid out to law and advertising firms this year than was anticipated. The company was taken to task in The Wall Street Journal for using marketing funds from suppliers, a practice Intelligent Electronics considers fundamental in its industry. Other business practices were also questioned in the article, which was based in part on a lawsuit by a former employee.<P>
The article touched off a spate of media coverage and more lawsuits to which Intelligent Electronics responded with a full-page ad in the journal in January. In it, Richard Sanford, chairman and CEO, indicated that the company expects its position to be upheld and invited doubting Thomases to learn more about the company by calling or writing.<P>
Prior to the company's third quarter 1994 results, Intelligent Electronics had announced a plan to transform the company into a leaner, more efficient organization.<P>
"Actions have been taken to exercise control in a challenging operating environment, including the installation of new systems. While these measures are commencing, we cannot expect instant gratification," says Sanford. "We expect recurring costs associated with transformation and continued inefficiencies until the switch over to our new systems is accomplished."<P>
Intelligent Electronics certainly is not alone in its quest to "transform" to remain competitive. It seems that any company that didn't restructure in 1993 or earlier did so (or announced it would) in 1994. Hershey Foods' restructuring plan is expected to produce $15 million to $20 million annually in pre-tax savings by next year.<P>
Scott Paper Co. implemented a major restructuring plan under new chairman and CEO Albert Dunlap. Dunlap has been shedding employees, business units and even Scott's headquarters to improve profitability. The company, which called Phila-delphia home for 115 years, is pulling up stakes for Boca Raton, Fla.<P>
Significant downsizing continued for many companies on the Pennsyl-vania 100. Westinghouse, for example, took a fourth quarter "pre-tax restructuring charge of $71 million, primarily associated with 1,200 additional employee separations that extend beyond our previously announced headcount reductions of 6,000," according to Mike Jordan, chairman and CEO.<P>
Unisys eliminated more than 4,000 positions worldwide, creating an annual savings in excess of $200 million. A small consolation for those let go perhaps: the bonus for Unisys chairman and CEO, James Unruh, was halved to $420,000 based on disappointing 1994 results. (Unruh's 1994 salary was up 3% to $792,336.)<P>
PECO Energy instituted voluntary retirement and separation incentive programs, estimated to save $60 million per year by 1996 after taxes. And, Bethlehem Steel announced that it will lay off another 1,700 workers at its Bethlehem plant. From 1984 to 1994, Bethlehem has reduced its work force by 63%.<P>
Another industry standout for Frankola, in addition to steel and office supplies, was healthcare. "For the last couple of years, we talked about healthcare being strong, but last year, the stocks tanked," says Frankola. "This year, we're seeing a return of stock prices in healthcare."<P>
The threat of healthcare legislation led many in the industry to search out alliances, mergers and acquisitions.<P>
Interestingly, almost every healthcare-related company in the Pennsylvania 100 enjoyed revenue growth, much of it double-digit. The largest on the list, managed care company U.S. Healthcare, had a 12.4% increase. And the company with the highest increase in revenues of all, Genesis Health Ventures, is considered an innovator in the delivery of geriatric healthcare.<P>
Amsco, a surgical products and services company, was the one exception. However, the company is in the midst of a turnaround under the leadership of the new president and CEO, Dan Barry.<P>

<font size =+2><B>Interest Rate Factor</B></font size> 
What the future holds is anybody's guess. Some economic indicators have been positive - inflation has been checked by the Federal Reserve's campaign of hiking up interest rates - however, the Fed must make sure that rates are just right. Interest rates that are too high will discourage consumer and corporate spending, effectively ending the economy's expansion. And, interest rate hikes can negatively impact cyclical companies, the very ones enjoying some recovery in 1994.<P>
Economic statistics released in early 1995 indicate that growth has slowed. In February, jobless claims increased; retail sales soured; inventories began to rise, and auto demand started to drop.<P>
Companies are also now facing an increased merger and acquisition climate, a more litigious environment and changes in international markets. Most of the nine companies that appeared on last year's list but are missing this year are gone because they've been acquired by out-of-state companies. At least 31% of the Pennsylvania 100 companies partici-pated in an acquisition, divestiture (or both) in 1994.<P>
And manufacturers are losing some of their optimism. A March 1995 survey by the Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia indicated that expectations of future expansion of manufacturing have diminished markedly over the past several months.<P>
That's not particularly encouraging for Pennsylvania. "We're still manufactur-ing and industry based," Frankola says. <P>

