<HEAD>
<TITLE>Update: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Office Systems: Outfitting the Home Office</FONT></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Equipping the home business requires creativity, especially when operating capital is slated for other areas.<BR></B></FONT SIZE><i>By Anne Louise Feeny</i>
<HR>
Increasingly, home is where the business is. Last year, Pittsburgh was named one of the top 10 cities for home-based businesses by Home Office Computing. "It's a lifestyle choice now, not so much a financial issue," says Beth Terranova, owner of Advanced Marketing Edge Inc., a South Side firm that tracks new businesses in western Pennsylvania. She concedes that low overhead does allow for investment in other areas of the business, such as equipment and training.<P>
Most home businesses start small: in a bedroom or a corner of the family or dining room. For Mina Bancroft, of South Hills-based Mina Bancroft Associates, "claiming space was a personal issue - taking my son's bedroom even though he [hasn't] lived at home for many years," she says. She advises against thinking that setting up is a one-time proposition, noting that her office is continually being re-designed.<P>
Relocation can't be ruled out either. David Goldman, founder of The Goldman Group, relinquished his basement space to his teenage son, to give him more privacy. His daughter shifted to her brother's old room, and Goldman moved into her former space.<P>
After working for an ad agency for seven years, Emil Kuhar launched his graphic design and photography business in a spare bedroom. He soon found his work encroaching into other parts of the house, and realized that wasn't efficient.
His accountant suggested an addition. "It made more sense than renting a storefront," Kuhar recalls. "We weren't looking for street traffic." <P>
Emil Kuhar Visual Communications now resides in a 390-square-foot studio with large windows, sliding glass doors that open to the backyard and 14-foot ceilings that accommodate photographic lighting. Amenities include a bathroom and a brick-faced, corner fireplace - chosen for resale value as well as current comfort.<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> Do Your Homework</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Prior to selecting a computer, Steve Myers, of Vandergrift-based S.J. Myers Associates, researched for about a year. "I knew exactly what I wanted," he says. Myers found two brothers who work part-time on computers, and spent $1,720, vs. $2,555 retail.<P>
Physically setting up the office can present another challenge. Myers, a marketing specialist, hired cabinet-maker Al Tweton to make his office functional without breaking his bank account. Tweton maximized storage and desktop space, and accommodated the need for bookshelves by fitting some over the work space and building another into the desk's side panel.<P>
Dennis Snedden, owner of Time Management Services, shows clients how to manage time more effectively. <P>
 His dining room work space houses a Compaq 486 computer with built-in fax/modem, a Hewlett Packard 4p laser jet printer and a postage meter. The meter saves time and gives the impression that the company is larger than it is, he says.
Snedden makes copies at an Office Depot or a Kinko's, where he can also send and receive faxes. "I keep a file there," he explains, "and pick them up as part of my out-and-about routine."<P>
A copier is on his wish list, which is "planned, pre-thought out and written down, so it's recognized when the opportunity presents itself."<P>
Rod Hess, founder of Applied Organi-zational Concepts, also wants a copier. Hess, who helps clients manage organizational change, has written workbooks and training manuals, and would prefer the convenience and quality control of handling their reproduction in-house.<P>
In business since 1982, Hess is on his third computer - a 486 Columbia Systems with a built-in fax. He recommends establishing a relationship with somebody who knows computers. He also suggests purchasing an extended service contract for the computer. Why? His contract paid for itself when his computer was infected by a virus. "A computer is my livelihood, and I can't afford the downtime," Hess says. Knowing how seductive new technology can be, he advises against "being in awe of all the glitzy options. Expand where you can, find out what's compatible with your system, and be open to opportunities."<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> Wanna Trade?</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Sometimes that means bartering. "I was able to secure services before I was ready to pay cash," says Snedden.<P>
Bancroft advocates bartering, but reminds those who engage in it to conform to the tax requirements established by the Internal Revenue Service. A former Latin teacher, she provides training in self-presentation and interpersonal effective-ness. Now in business for 10 years, she remembers swapping tutoring services for secretarial support, and later exchanging staff development training for a copier.<P>
In the beginning, office equipment was not a large line item in Bancroft's budget. That meant trying to produce professional-looking letters on an electric typewriter, which was frustrating at best.<P>
Consequently, Bancroft truly appre-ciates the state-of-the-art equipment she acquired at Comp USA last November: a Compaq Presario CDS 924 with CD-ROM. 
In between the typewriter and her current system, Bancroft used a PC and a Macintosh, bequeathed to her by her children. At one time, she used both, which prompted her to buy a printer that was compatible with either - an NEC Silent Writer laser, model 95. For now, at least, she's committed to her new PC.<P>


<FONT SIZE=+1><B> Shop Around</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Goldman found reasonably priced furniture at a close-out sale. "I bought a beautiful desk, two desk chairs, a computer table and two four-drawer file cabinets, plus lamps and all kinds of supplies for less than $1,000." That's quite an upgrade from his first desk - a door stretched across two file cabinets.<P>
Advice on equipment selection and space design is available from office furniture suppliers, like Mt. Lebanon Office Equipment Co. Inc., which is celebrating its 35th anniversary this year. President and CEO James M. Droney Jr. says company representatives can make house calls or look at floor plans for suggestions and recommendations.<P>
Account manager Robert C. Baierl says that the sales staff at Wright Office Furniture in the Strip District also works hand-in-hand with clients, visiting the space and making recommendations. "We can design the office on CAD for them," he adds, "and walk them through it so they get a real feel for what it will look like."<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> It Takes Two for Some</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Alan Grishman of Grishman Asso-ciates, has two offices at home: one where he sees clients and the other which houses his equipment.<P>
That equipment includes a Zeos 486DX 2-66, a Hewlett Packard 4-PostScript printer, a fax and a paper cutter. There is also a postage meter he bought at a flea market and a light table that he built for pasting up ads. And, a copier that "cost about half-price, because Mita has a Monroeville site which takes copiers in and reconditions them," he says. Grishman advocates having a separate telephone line and an answering machine.<P>
Some businesses that are home-based now, started up outside the home. <P>
After renting downtown for four years, Sally Mizerak of Mizerak Towers & Associates, moved her office to her home's third floor. She no longer saw the need for an established address, "as long as there's a computer, fax, modem, copier." She has all of those in her two-room office, plus a conference table, a TV-VCR for reviewing training videos and a library.<P>
Mizerak and her partner, Cheryl Towers, are management consultants. They communicate via e-mail on America Online.<P>
Although she purchased much of her equipment, Mizerak has found leasing a valuable option. She leased a Panasonic fax and a Toshiba copier with a bin sorter, and even though the leases are now paid out, sees no need to upgrade. She attributes that to having "top-of-the-line equipment. If you don't have the cash, you're better off leasing it and having it, and be sure to calculate the tax advantages."
There are a number of options for furnishing the home-based business. "As a sole proprietor, you have to cover all things, but you don't have to do them all yourself. Get technology to do it for you, and buy or barter to get it," sums up Bancroft.
<hr>
