</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Update: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Unconventional Care: Is It Growing?</B></FONT></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>About a third of Americans have sought care from nontraditional healthcare providers. That figure may be less in conservative western Pennsylvania.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
<p>
<hr>
Karen Rehder had a lot of pain after the birth of her first baby. The 29-year-old knew there was pain in childbirth. But how much surprised her.<P>
"I didn't know I had so much trauma; I just thought I was wimpy," says Rehder, now 38, who practices at St. Francis Medical Center. What she and her doctors didn't know was that delivery had severely weakened the ligaments around her pelvis.
Her pelvis completely separated more than two months before her third child was due. The pain led doctors to induce labor three weeks early. Delivery went well and she returned to work six weeks later.<P>
"I was still in pain, and I noticed that when I walked I would click and grind, like I was not hooked together properly," says Rehder. "The doctors didn't know what to do."<P>
Two surgeries later, the doctors still did not know what to do. Though the pain was less intense, it was present every day.<P>
"The doctors did tests, which all came back normal," says Rehder. "They said, We don't know why you're still having pain, but we can do another surgery.' I said, 'No.'<P>
Physical therapy didn't help. Through a friend, Rehder heard of Tassos Spanos, a trigger-point myotherapist at the Center for Pain Treatment on the South Side.<P>
"I am like a new person," declares Rehder, who finally found relief with myotherapy. "I get a tiny bit of pain, but nothing like before."<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> Breaking with Tradition</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Myotherapy is one of a growing number of therapies that, because they are outside of the medical mainstream, are often titled "alternative," or "nonconventional." (See sidebar for glossary.)<P>
It is a category defined by the newly founded Office of Alternative Medicine at the National Institutes of Health, as therapies "not reimbursed by insurance, not taught in medical school or not proven by research." Not all therapies meet all the criteria. For example, most of Spanos' work is covered by insurance, since he is affiliated with a licensed chiropractor.<P>
Though this broadness may confuse consumers, it does not dampen their ardor to venture beyond conventional medicine. A 1990 study in the New England Journal of Medicine found that one-third of respondents sought care from uncon-ventional providers. These therapies are  not necessarily new - acupuncture and chiropractics are thousands of years old. Some, like myotherapy, have been developed in the past 50 years.<P>
Like Rehder, 83% of those who used unconventional therapy for serious medical conditions also sought treatment from a medical doctor. But 72% of these patients did not inform their doctor of the use of these therapies. The antipathy between the conventional medical establishment and alternative practitioners is attested to by both parties.<P>
"I believe there's a place for everything," says Rehder. "What M.D.s do is important, but we don't know everything - and if doctors would stop being so arrogant they would see that. The major problem is that there's so much to know in the medical profession right now. And we get no training [on these therapies] in medical school."<P>
One morning, eight months after the birth of her daughter, Malissa Kazmer blacked out getting out of bed. The 20-year-old had been having chest pains, shortness of breath and dizziness. A couple of times a week, her heart rate raced up to 260 beats a minute. Her hands were shaky, and often she couldn't get up until noon.<P>
It took two years and four doctors to diagnose her condition as mitral valve prolapse, an abnormal closure of one of the heart's four valves.<P>
"They made me think I was crazy," says Kazmer. "I got migraine headaches. I couldn't keep up with everyday life. So I went to my family doctor to see if he could refer me to someone else. He said there was a clicking sound in my heart, ran an electrocardiogram and diagnosed the condition. Those other doctors, maybe they just didn't want to be bothered. But they prescribed drugs without even knowing what was wrong."<P>
Over three years, she took four heart medications, resulting in leg cramps, weakness and a 60-pound weight gain.<P>
"They were giving me medications to cover up the side effects of the heart medicine," she says. "I finally got tired of it. Then my mom suggested I see this doctor she worked with at Harmarville Rehabilitation Hospital."<P>
David M. Goldstein is an M.D. who practices nutritional and preventive medicine. Kazmer's symptoms led Goldstein to believe Kazmer had a magnesium deficiency. So he put her on a magnesium I.V.<P>
Goldstein says nutritional therapies tend to be inexpensive and safe. (From 1983 to 1990, 2,556 fatalities occurred from pharmaceutical drugs while just one death resulted from vitamin supplements.) Kazmer changed her eating habits and added a magnesium supplement, vitamins B6, A and E, as well as fatty acids. <P>
"Two weeks later, people started noticing I looked good and had color," says Kazmer. "Two weeks after that, I got off my medication and felt completely well. It's like a miracle." She's lost 25 pounds, has energy enough to perform her job (as a hostess at Eat n Park), attend school (in June she'll be through training as a pharmaceutical technician), and get engaged (on Valentine's Day).<P>
"It makes sense to look for the natural approaches that work in concert with the body rather than going to drugs first," says Goldstein, who opened a solo practice in the North Hills last July. "There's much research to support the idea, but it's not widely known. We're not taught this in medical school. I had to go learn myself."<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> Slighting Nutrition</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Despite research linking nutrition with health, the number of medical schools requiring courses in nutrition has declined in recent years, according to a 1993 survey by Vegetarian Times.<P>
Goldstein determines a person's nutritional state via a lengthy questionnaire which asks about ringing in the ears, cracking at the corners of the mouth, muscle twitching and other symptoms.<P>
"These are not symptoms you would take to a conventional doctor, perhaps," says Goldstein. "But if you are more sensitive, you can pick deficiencies up early. We need to shorten the area between having a symptom and having clinical onset of disease."<P>
Other critics accuse the medical establishment of far more serious aggression toward alternative therapies than ignorance.<P>
"Traditional medicine is when you get sick, you come see me and I'll give you an antibiotic," says Candace Campbell, executive director of the American Preventive Medical Association. "Our members tend to focus on diet, lifestyle and nutrition to prevent disease. They choose the point of least resistance first. But it's hard for them to advance medicine; they are harassed by state medical boards."<P>
Campbell cites a straw pool done at a meeting in which 85% said they had administrative action taken against them by their state medical board - a request for a hearing to review patient records and practice.<P>
"Most of these are not based on patient complaints," says Campbell, citing cases of M.D.s being raided or put out of business for using unconventional therapies.<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> Bill of Rights</B></FONT SIZE><br>
"We are lobbying for a bill that says, Patients have a right to be treated by a healthcare practitioner with any method of medical treatment as long as therapy is not dangerous; the patient is fully informed, and the doctor has personally diagnosed the condition,' " says Campbell. The bill is being introduced in the Senate and House by Democrats Tom Daschle, of South Dakota, and Peter DeFazio, of Oregon, respectively. "It doesn't sound radical, but it is. People who oppose this say it opens the door to quacks," says Campbell.<P>
The bill protects consumers, says Campbell, by covering only those practitioners who are legally authorized to provide services in a state. Campbell says this includes acupuncturists, naturopaths, homeopaths and allergists. It doesn't mean, however, that the American Medical Association will be recommending these practices any time soon.<P>
"We'd like to see them tested, have the health claims evaluated and see the data shared," says Dr. M. Roy Schwarz, group vice president for scientific, educational and practice standards at the Chicago-based AMA. "Many doctors would say, 'That's bunk,' but we have to allow them to go through some assessment. There is review in some instances, but we find that most of it is anecdotal, not scientific."<P>
Thorough research would no doubt debunk some claims of alternative therapies and make the industry more navigable for consumers and practitioners alike. But getting data is difficult.<P>
"There is a built-in bias in the system against research in natural substances, because [pharmaceutical companies] cannot patent and market them as their own," says Goldstein. "What would be the purpose of drug companies researching vitamin C if they couldn't make a lot of money off it?"<P>
As a result, these studies must be funded from the public purse.
"That's why the Office of Alternative Medicine was established at the National Institutes of Health," says Schwarz. "They have $5 million budgeted for research such as this, but you can't do many evaluations with that."<P>
Many alternative therapies don't lend themselves to scientific, double-blind studies with controls for placebos.<P>
"There may be five or six home-opathic remedies for arthritis, and which one works will depend on the individual's temperament and other factors," says Jane Critchfield, president of the Homeopathic Society of Greater Pittsburgh. "So the group response will be positive, but the individual response is hard to prove because everyone may take a different remedy, but have the same effect and cure."
Jim Bryant, a spokesman for the Office of Alternative Medicine, says that is being taken into account. The office has made 30 research grants, studying acupuncture as a treatment for severe depression in women, whether hypnosis induces brain wave changes in patients with chronic low back pain and other therapies. The first results are expected this summer.<P>
In December 1993, Jalaire Craver began feeling queasy. The nausea lasted into January. Occasionally, the now 43-year-old mother of three would wake up and her hands would be asleep. Her tongue was sore, like she had burned it with a hot drink. One night after supper, she felt a tingling sensation, which continued up and down her back throughout the night.<P>
"I was scared," recalls Craver. She went to her doctor at U.S. Healthcare, who gave her blood tests and put her on an anti-viral drug which made her tired and affected her bladder. "My legs got really weak, but I could still walk."<P>
In July, she had another attack of dizziness and nausea, which lasted three days. By August, she was so weak, with pain in her lower back and difficulty using her hands, that she again consulted the doctor.<P>
"They ran all sorts of tests, for a whole long list of things that they associate with tingling," says Craver. "They took me seriously, and never ignored me."
But they also could not find out what was wrong. She had an MRI, and went to a neurologist, where she passed all the tests for balance and strength in the arms.
"I was going to my doctor's office and crying. I felt really foolish, yet I wanted to follow up," says Craver. The neurologist told her that maybe she should take an antidepressant, and come back in three months. Now not just her hands, but her lower arms had lessening mobility. "It's a horrible feeling. I felt crazy and obsessed about my health. I started asking around."<P>
A friend suggested that she see Martin Gallagher, D.C., clinic director of Chiro-practic Nutritional Associates in Jeannette. At her first appointment, Craver and Gallagher talked for two hours. He did a number of tests, both nutritional and chiropractic, including a hair analysis. He concluded Craver had a yeast imbalance and her spine was misaligned. Gallagher prescribed a 10-day fast to detoxify her body, a strict diet to keep her yeast level down, daily supplements of vitamins and oregano pills, and a weekly regimen of chiropractic adjustments.<P>
That was in October of 1994. By Thanksgiving, Craver began to feel better. By January, the regimen had become part of her life, though she admits that she cheats occasionally.<P>
"But I am so much better. The biggest difference is my mood," says Craver, who holds up the bottle of oregano pills with a twinkle in her eye. "My kids call Dr. Gallagher a freak. But if I hadn't gone to this guy, what would have happened to me?"<P>
Gallagher isn't sure what specifically might have resulted, but he is certain it wouldn't be desirable.<P>
"A lot of people are functionally ill," says Gallagher. "They can stand, walk, move and take care of their family. They're only functioning at 40% or 50%, but by conventional medical standards they are considered to be normal. They'll say, It's stress, learn to live with it,' and eventually it evolves into diabetes or cancer and demands emergency medical attention. Now, the conventional medical system will pay attention, because you can prove it."<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B> Not Covered</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Better or not, U.S. Healthcare won't pay for Craver's care. (Much research proving chiropractics' efficacy does exist, and, according to Gallagher, more than 700 insurers cover it. U.S. Healthcare denied requests for comment.) The family pays about $250 a month out of its savings for her treatment.<P>
This is not uncommon. The New England Journal of Medicine study found that Americans spend approximately $13.7 billion annually for unconventional healthcare, 70% of which is paid out of pocket. Local insurers share the AMA's view of these therapies.<P>
"In general, we practice pretty mainstream medicine," says Dr. Robert Gormley, medical director of Health America. "We have medical school-trained doctors with a fairly middle-of-the-road approach to disease."<P>
"We cover anything that is recognized for its medical necessity and appro-priateness of care by the medical profession," says Steven Jones, market vice president of Aetna Health Plans of Western Pennsylvania.<P>
"We don't see much at all," says Jones. "The primary reason is that it's not accepted by the medical profession. Not many primary doctors refer to herbalists."<P>
"I heard a great line at a medical conference just last weekend: The plural of anecdote is not data," says Cliff Waldman, regional medical director of health operations services for Blue Cross. "We need to be sure the treatment worked, that it wasn't just time or a change in psychological factors. So we use the scientific method, with advanced controls."<P>
Waldman and Jones reinforce, however, that it is the customer designing the plan that picks the coverage.<P>
"We don't deny our members any treatment that is of value to them, just the payment of it," says Jones. He points out that many alternative therapies rely on the individual taking responsibility. "What makes it effective is that they had to dig in their pocket. If we pay, it take as that incentive away."<P>
There is insurance for those who desire the option to use alternative healthcare providers, however. The Alternative Health Group, based out of California, is offering a plan nationwide that allows members to pick the provider of their choice. The plan will include homeopathic, acupuncture, naturopathic, chelation and other therapies, and pay for preventive nutritional counseling. <P>
"They think it makes sense," says  Founder Steve Gorman. "The big risk comes from heart disease and cancer. No one runs up $50,000 in acupuncture or $100,000 in naturopathy. In fact, we think it will be cheaper in the long run, because there will be less spent on preventable disease down the road."<P>
Gorman, like others who claim that alternative healthcare is cheaper, has no figures to support this. But he hopes to prove it. He also hopes to help pro-fessional associations set standards and gather credible data to support their claims.<P>
"Insurance companies don't under-stand what these therapies are," says Gorman. "If I had five years of data and could show insurance companies that they would save money [covering alternative therapies], they wouldfind a way to incorporate them."<P>
Local insurance providers say there is no call for coverage of alternative therapies. "Pittsburgh tends to be fairly conservative; it's a traditional community," says Waldman. "My impression is that there is less use of alternative therapies here."
Rehder, Kazmer, Craver and their practitioners, each with thriving practices, might disagree. So might the nurses in the office of Franne Berez, M.D., Pittsburgh's only homeopathic doctor, who must tell prospective patients they have to wait four months for an appointment. Such evidence is, of course, anecdotal.<P>
One weekend last March, some 3,000 people made their way to the Health and Life Enrichment Expo at the David L. Lawrence Convention Center downtown. They cruised aisles of booths touting everything from super blue green algae to Reiki massage to Baltic amber. They listened to speakers talk about reflexology, light therapy and magnetism. <P>
A table near the door was laden with pamphlets from other community resources: the Homeopathic Society of Greater Pittsburgh, the Center of Light (presenting karmic astrology workshops) and Nature's Goodness, a natural foods supermarket  in Cranberry.<P>
Upstairs was an energetic Gary Null, nationally syndicated radio show host and nutrition and fitness expert who sells books, supplements and other healthcare products. He bludgeons the audience by saying that 80,000 patients have died eating hospital food, because it is so nutritionally deficient. He teases those assembled over the fact that this is the first convention of its kind to be held in Pittsburgh.<P>
"It's amazing what happens - there's a lot of good and a lot of foolishness down on that floor; you get people making all kinds of promises.<P>
"But Pittsburgh, you're walking down these aisles, looking suspiciously at the sunflower seeds," he says. "Now that's bad. What century are you all in, anyway?" <P>    
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> Glossary of Alternative Therapies</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Derived from literature from the Office of Alternative Medicine and the Alternative Health Group<P>
<DL>
<LI><B>Acupuncture</B> - A needle is inserted at an appropriately chosen energy point, to disperse or activate the qi, or vital energy, which alleviates pain and increases immune system response by restoring energy balance.<P>
<LI><B>	Ayurvedic Medicine</B> - The traditional system of India, Ayurveda has been practiced for 5,000 years. It provides an integrated approach to the prevention and treatment of illness through lifestyle change and natural therapies.<P>
<LI><B>	Biofeedback</B> - This process furnishes an individual with information, usually in an auditory or visual mode, on metabolic states (temperature, heart rate, muscle tension) to enable the individual to gain voluntary control over that state.<P>
<LI><B>	Chelation Therapy</B> - Intravenously applied to draw toxins and metabolic wastes from the blood, chelation therapy is the major form of alternative therapy for cardiovascular disease.<P>
<LI><B>	Chiropractics </B>- Recognizing the relationship between body function, primarily of the nervous system, and structure, primarily in the spine, chiropractics seeks to cure imbalances by adjustments to the spine.<P>
<LI><B>	Herbal Medicine</B> - Herbs contain a large number of naturally occurring chemicals that have biological activity and are effective in enhancing the functions of the body.<P>
<LI><B>	Homeopathy </B>- Derived from the Greek words "homeo" (similar) and "pathos" (suffering from disease), homeopathy is derived from the principle of "like cures like" and uses minute doses of natural substances to produce the symptoms of an illness and immunize the body against those symptoms. Shadyside Hospital was originally founded as a homeopathic hospital.<P>
<LI><B> Massage Therapy </B>- This scientific manipulation of the soft tissues of the body to normalize those tissues provides relaxation and healing. Techniques include myotherapy, neuromuscular massage, reflexology and rolfing.<P>
<LI><B>	Naturopathic Medicine </B>- Traditional natural therapeutics are integrated with modern scientific medical diagnostic science and standards of care. Tailored to individual patients, a trained professional works to restore and support the body's own healing ability.
<HR>
