<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Publisher's Note: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2>Once Upon a Time </FONT SIZE><i> By Linda A. Dickerson</i><P>
An 18th century government cannot possibly service the needs of the 21st century. All of the king's horses and all the king's men created our current local government structure in the mid-1700s. The structure they designed is still in effect today - largely unchanged. Although probably effective then, that structure is not appropriate today.
<P>
Imagine the world over 200 years ago. Electricity was a relatively new discovery, so, of course, little attention to a technology-driven, information-based society was considered in formulating government. Information, when it existed, was processed solely by hand, making armies of clerks a necessary part of local government. Not true any longer.<P>
Challenge any self-respecting business person to administer local government, and 10 distinct offices each attending to separate functions is unlikely to emerge as the recommended approach. Yet, Allegheny County sports 10 row offices, each isolated from the other by barriers imposed by an antiquated structure.<P>
Admittedly, my quest for a county commissioner's seat taints my observations. However, reform is so blatantly required that no one should doubt the need for an unbiased, independent and analytical examination of Allegheny County government's structure.<P>
Led by a man of impeccable credentials, John E. Murray Jr., president of Duquesne University, COMPAC 21, the Committee to Prepare Allegheny County for the 21st Century, is an idea whose time has come. Under Murray's distin-guished stewardship, COMPAC 21 will enable Allegheny County to take a quantum leap forward by examining alternative structures and identifying the ultimate approach to meet today's needs.<P>
COMPAC 21 should be heralded as a major breakthrough for this community. Everything and everyone is reinventing itself. Local government, which cries for modern approaches, should certainly not be the exception.<P>
Opposition to change is imbedded in strong political moorings. As a result, our community does not progress. In today's incredibly dynamic world, by standing still, we are effectively moving backward.<P>
A thoughtful, independent and apolitical examination of our local government can only produce positive results. It will make the difference between change and progress.
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
