<HEAD>
<TITLE>Letters: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.L.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<font size =+2><B>Feeling Left Out</B></font size><BR>
Your article, "Is It Worth Going Online?" [March 1995], defined online services as Internet providers. These are not services - they are access providers. What we do at infoWorks is similar to the large, commercial services you featured, including CompuServe, Delphi and America Online; these are online services.<P>
We build the same types of serv-ices, only on a smaller, client-tailored scale. We have established online serv-ices that serve an entire city, a business or simply one or two communities.<P>
World Wide Web design and development and Internet access provision are pieces of what we can do.<P>
Members of our firm are moderating a meeting of regional information and high technology firms to design a centralized information service that will link all regional high-tech firms and information technology firms. Our firm hopes to take the lead in that development.<P>
The local firms you featured in your article offer pieces of what online truly means. Obviously, the field continues to grow and evolve, as does the definition of what online services include.<P>
Brian A. Vidic, managing partner,<BR>
The infoWorks Partnership, <BR>
Pittsburgh, <BR>	
infowork@telerama.lm.com<BR>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Behind the Times</B></font size><BR>
I'm afraid February's Healthcare Update, "Learning to Cope," is a little behind. Currently, psychologists have a handful of revolutionary treatment procedures that produce profound results in just one session. Some of these procedures can be taught to patients and the patients can administer the treatment themselves as needed. The article made no mention of even the most powerful of these discoveries, i.e., thought field therapy (TFT).<P>
As a certified TFT psychologist, I have relieved stress, as well as its accompanying head and muscle pain, in just minutes. This treatment is painless and can be applied with your own fingertips once your therapist has accurately diagnosed your problem.<P>
Unbelievable? Of course it sounds unbelievable; most revolutionary discoveries do. But as always, seeing is believing.<P>
Donald Zandier, private-practice psychologist (also affiliated with South Hills Interfaith Ministries), Library<BR>
