<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ERIndex: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a><P>
<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.</I>
<HR>
With few excep-tions, local stocks performed rela-tively poorly for the month ended March 10, allowing the S&P 500 to surpass the ER Index for the first time since we initiated the 25-company Pittsburgh-area composite in the October 1994 issue.
<P>
Johnstown America Industries, Cable Design Technologies and American Eagle Outfitters paced the percentage losers, averaging declines of more than 16% for the month. Legent, Tuscarora and MK Rail led the list of winners.
<P>
In total, the ER Index declined 1.89% for the month, and is now up a respectable 6.05% since inception. But the S&P 500, which has been catching up in recent months, did better, returning 1.68% for the month, and is now up 6.14% since August.
<HR>
Legent's new CEO, Jerre Stead, made an extremely upbeat presentation at the Robertson Stephens and Co. technology conference in San Francisco in early March. It was Stead's first appearance at such an event since taking the helm of the software manu-facturer in January. Stead demonstrated an impressive understanding of the challenges Legent faces and, what's more, outlined a clear, concise strategic 
plan for improving the company's fortunes.<P>
Stead discussed the need for an integrated platform approach in Legent's sales philosophy, an extremely clever way to expand into open systems, or networked, desktop applications, without abandoning the company's leading position in the mainframe business. Legent has been announcing a steady stream of new products as part of the company's collaboration with industry leader Hewlett-Packard to develop appli-cations that bridge the mainframe and desktop markets.<P>
Stead says he expects the company's sales will return to the double-digit growth level in the third and fourth quarters, and since Legent is emphasizing its higher-margin services segment, profits should also begin to improve substantially.
Gone are the days when Legent salespeople give away free advice and consulting to get an order. Under Stead, Legent will get paid for every-thing, or the company won't do it. So far, Stead has made believers out of us.
<HR>
Tuscarora reported that earnings for its second quarter, ended Feb. 28, doubled to a record $1.8 million, or 30 cents per share, vs. $903,000, or 15 cents per share, in the same period a year ago. Sales for the quarter rose more than 42% to $37.9 million. The New Brighton-based custom packager is gaining market share and having success cross selling new products to its existing customers. Higher volumes helped push gross margins up 1.5% for the quarter. The next several quarters also look bright, as incoming orders for product shipments continue to run well ahead of last year. Among the strongest areas of Tuscarora's growth is high tech, where customers like IBM, Philips and RCA are all doing extremely well.
<HR>
MK Rail bounced back as its parent company, Morrison Knudsen Corp., put its 65% stake up for sale. The ultimate buyer could be General Electric, the world's largest locomotive manufacturer in Erie, which could find MK Rail's component parts business an especially good fit. Or it could be MK Rail's own Pittsburgh-based management team, who knows the business better than anyone. Whoever it turns out to be, MK Rail has hired the New York investment banking firm of Wasserstein Perella & Co. to assist as its financial adviser. As we mentioned last month, the loco-motive components business continues to be strong, and with the company selling for just about book value and generating strong cash flow, MK Rail could be attractive to plenty of folks.
<HR>
Cable Design Technologies announced that net income rose more than 34% to $2.93 million, or 26 cents per share, in the company's second quarter ended Jan. 31. Sales for the quarter rose 33% to more than $44 million. The extremely good results reflected continued growth in CDT's domestic shipment of cable products for both network systems and automation/sound/safety customers. Despite the fact that earnings came in above expectations, the stock declined substantially, mainly the result of the company's announcement that a temporary reduction in deliveries of Teflon from Dupont could cost CDT 2 cents to 4 cents per share in earnings this quarter.
<HR>
Barron's took a shot at Respironics in March, raising questions about the company's products and whether competitors, managed care and the FDA would combine to lower the boom on Respironics' profits. Most of the issues were old ones and the effect on the stock was temporary. In the meantime, the company effected a 
2-for-1 stock split and announced it would purchase Vitalog, a privately held California-based designer, manu-facturer and marketer of sleep monitoring and diagnostic equipment. Vitalog's annual sales are about $1 million. There has been some insider selling recently, which is rarely a good sign. But we never begrudge profit-taking by insiders if they've earned it.
<HR>
Consolidated Natural Gas laid out plans to analysts and investors to grow earnings 10% per year starting this year, and to produce a 12% to 15% return on equity by 1999. George A Davidson Jr., the company's chairman and CEO, says Consolidated is considering a wide variety of cost-cutting and restructuring measures to help reach those goals, and continues to make strides in the growing unregulated energy market. Davidson says the company was intent on "turning net income around" although he concedes it will not be easy. His strategies emphasize aggressive marketing and stringent cost controls.
<HR>
II-VI Corp., the Saxonburg-based manufacturer of optical and electro-optical devices used in products like high-power lasers, primarily for commercial and industrial customers, reported impressive results for its second fiscal quarter ended Dec. 31. Sales for the quarter rose to more than $11.3 million vs. nearly $4.4 million, while earnings per share rose to 30 cents vs. 3 cents. II-VI also completed its acquisition of the Virgo Optics division of Sandoz Chemicals. Virgo designs, develops and manu-facturers laser materials, optics and coatings for visible laser applications and will significantly expand II-VI's market, which has been primarily focused on infrared applications. The company's stock, which has risen from $3 to $11.75 during the past year, was the fifth best performing Pennsylvania stock in 1994.<P>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
