<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chronicles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.C.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Small Business News</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Several local business professionals were honored last month at the SBA Small Business Awards luncheon for the Pittsburgh district. For the past 32 years, the SBA has celebrated Small Business Week.<P>  
And the winners are:
<DL>
<LI>Small Business Person of 1995 - Sara Ann Sargent, owner and founder of The Sargent's Group (Sargent's Court Reporting Service, Sargent's Personnel Agency and Sargent's Temporary Service) of Johnstown.
<LI>Minority Small Business Advocate - Benjamin W. Butler of the Minority Business Opportunity Committee
<LI>Media Advocate - Lucille Treganowan, founder of Transmissions By Lucille and host of "Car Talk" on WQEX-TV channel 16
<LI>Women in Business Advocate - Dee Dotter, Women's Business Network and the Greater Pittsburgh Women's Yellow Pages
<LI>Financial Services Advocate - Robert Meeder of SPEDD
<LI>Accountant Advocate - Samuel J. Stephenson, Terry and Stephenson
<LI>Small Business Exporter - Venkatesh N. Sharma, Aquatech International
<LI>Young Entrepreneur - Myles D. Lilley and Matthew C. Vidic, Procopy Inc.
<LI>District Entrepreneur Success - Terry J. and Charlene P. Ruot, Charter Plastic Inc.
<LI>District SCORE Volunteer of the Year - Shirley Goldstein, Pittsburgh SCORE chapter
</DL>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Boards Are Starting to Diversify</B></FONT SIZE><br>
PNC Bank Corp. has elected Dianna L. Green, senior vice president of administrative services for Duquesne Light Co., to its board of directors. Green is not the first woman to be appointed a director, nor is she even the first African-American woman named to the board. Patricia Clifford, a Philadelphia civic leader who recently retired from the board, had that distinction.<P>
Kalamazoo, Mich.-based Sid Cato, who publishes a newsletter on annual reports, says diversification of the corporate board is on the rise. Based on the number of annual reports in which photos of the board are featured (some 25%), about one-third have no women or minorities at all. That's down from 56% the year earlier. Cato's theory on why there's been a decrease in "white-bread male boards," as he calls them, is increased media scrutiny forcing companies to change.<P>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Hooray for Hollywood</B></FONT SIZE><br>
February marked the fifth anniversary of the Pittsburgh Film Office, which has assisted in the production of 42 feature and TV films. Those films have had an economic impact of $158 million, according to Dawn Keezer, film office director.<P>
More than $35 million was spent on film production last year, representing a nearly 100% increase over 1993's figure of $18 million. Five feature films and two TV movies received assistance from the office in 1994. The largest production was "Sudden Death," which dropped $25 million into the local economy and was co-produced by Pittsburgh Penguins owner Howard Baldwin.<P>
Other movies recently filmed partially or entirely here include "Houseguest," "Boys on the Side" and "Roommates."<P>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>PA Restaurants Profit</B></FONT SIZE><br>
A survey conducted by Restaurant Advisory Services of Wayne, Pa., found that the majority of eating places across the state are profitable and that profitability is directly related to sales volume.<P>
"More than 67% of participating restaurants report they are making money," says Ron Gorodesky, president of the RAS, which conducted "Pennsylvania Restaurant Operations 1994" in conjunction with the Pennsylvania Restaurant Association. "Those making the most money - an average of 8.5% before taxes - report annual sales volumes of $2 million and over," he adds.<P>
The survey groups restaurants by six menu themes: sandwich/hamburger, steak/seafood, Italian/pizza, continental, American/regional and diner. Results showed that steak and seafood restaurants took a 6.2% loss in revenue and a 17.3% loss of income from the previous year. The biggest gainers were restaurants in the Italian/pizza category - collectively they boasted a 5.7% revenue increase and a 1.2% profit growth.<P>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>New Business</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Perkins Eastman Architects of New York has opened an office in Pittsburgh. Cafe Biscotti, which plans on franchising by February 1996, has opened in Beechview. Franklin, Pa.-based Seneca Printing is opening a Pittsburgh office. Wellesley, Mass.-based EG&G Inc. has formed EG&G Environmental Inc. in Pittsburgh. Philadelphia-based Schnader, Harrison, Segal & Lewis opened an office in Washington, Pa. Phoenix Treatment Center, an outpatient substance abuse treatment facility, has opened downtown. Butler-based Frank N. Cicco Custom Tailor has opened in the Westin William Penn, also downtown.<P>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> Corrections </B></FONT SIZE><br>
In the 1995 Pittsburgh Addy Awards Program, which appeared in the March issue, Joan Gaul should have been listed as the writer for the Heinz Memorial Chapel Book. Also, incorrect phone numbers for Seven Springs Golf Course, Southpointe Golf Club, Mystic Rock and The Woodlands Golf Links appeared in the March Pittsburgh Golf section. The correct numbers are as follows: <BR>
1 (800) 452-2223 for Seven Springs, (412) 746-2950 for Southpointe, <BR>
1 (800) 422-2736 for Mystic Rock and  1 (800) 422-2736 for  The Woodlands. 
