<DOCHDR>
http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0595.MoneyMatters.html 192.204.56.67 19970115134051 text/html 5640
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 13:45:54 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:49:45 GMT
Content-length: 5464
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Money Matters: </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.MM.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Retirement Plan for Small Businesses - A Simple Solution</B></FONT SIZE> <BR>
<i> By Robert A. Shoaf</i><p>

In today's environment, employ-ers must offer an excellent retirement plan to attract and retain quality employees.<P>
However, all plans are not alike and each has its own distinct advantages and disadvantages. Plans differ in important ways, such as who makes the contributions, how they are taxed, and how much money can go into the plan each year.<P>
Simplified Employee Pension (SEP) and Salary Reduction SEP (SAR/SEP) plans are excellent choices for smaller firms seeking a cost-effective, simple retirement plan. These plans require only minimal administration and paperwork, unlike other retirement plans such as 401(k)s. Also, both plans permit employees to save for retire-ment while reducing current taxes.<P>
SEP and SAR/SEP plans would be suitable for smaller corporations, 
S corporations, nonprofit organizations (SEP only), partnerships and sole proprietorships. The employer must have 25 or fewer eligible employees at all times during the preceding year to use the salary reduction feature.<P>
The major difference between the SEP and the SAR/SEP is that SEP plans feature employer contributions only, whereas in a SAR/SEP, the employees can contribute on a pre-tax basis to their retirement plans in addition to optional employer contributions .<P>
Eligibility requirements for both plans are relatively simple: The employer must include employees who have attained age 21, worked three or more of the last five preceding years and have annual compensation of at least $396.<P>
As to plan contributions, the SEP maximum limit for the employer is 15% of each participant's W-2 compen-sation, not to exceed $30,000. The overall limit includes employer basic and salary reduction contributions. Regarding the SAR/SEP contributions, salary reduction contributions are limited to 15% of each participant's 
W-2 compensation, not to exceed $9,240. This figure is adjusted each year, based upon the cost of living index.<P>
Salary reduction amounts in SAR/SEP plans may be limited for highly compensated employees, as determined by a nondiscrimination test required by the Internal Revenue Service. <P>
Setup and funding of these plans should be done on or before the employer's tax filing deadline, plus extensions. Contributions will still be deducted on the prior year's return. A SEP may be maintained on a calendar or fiscal year basis, while SAR/SEPs are generally maintained on a calendar year basis. Depending upon the plan custodian and the employer's restric-tions, plan participants can choose from a narrow range or a wide spectrum of investments in which to place their retirement assets. Investment choices would be limited to those approved by the IRS for individual retirement accounts, which would include most mainstream investment vehicles. The ability to diversify among various investment classes is a feature of many plans.<P>
The benefits of SEP and SAR/SEP plans are many, both for the employer and the employee. For example, on a business tax basis, the money employers contribute for their employees is deducted from their taxable business profits, thereby reducing the company's federal tax liability.<P>
Besides providing retirement in-come, the plan has significant tax advantages for both the employer and employee. Contributions to the plan made by the employer are tax deductible on the tax return of the business. All salary reduction contri-butions made by the employees are made on a pre-tax basis. Also, all earnings on the investments are not subject to tax until withdrawn by the participant. Over time, tax deferred compounding can provide higher investment returns compared to taxable investments.<P>
Some other key points to consider are that all contributions are invested into separate IRAs for each employee and that employers can change their SEP contribution to suit their cash flow. The amount contributed can vary from year to year and, in fact, the employer can skip a year altogether.<P>
Costs are low with a SEP or SAR/SEP as no IRS approval is required and no annual form 5500 has to be filed with the IRS or the Department of Labor. This is in direct contrast to a 401(k) plan, which requires both, plus typically sizable annual administrative charges.<P>
These plans can increase revenue for the company as well, since employees are the key to revenue. An employer-sponsored plan is a way to hire and retain quality employees by giving them a valuable retirement benefit while decreasing the employer's federal tax obligation. Smaller firms that do not have a retirement plan should seriously consider the many advantages of SEP and SAR/SEP plans, as a benefit to both the employer and the employee.<P>
<i>Robert Shoaf is an investment executive at the Upper St. Clair office of Legg Mason Wood Walker Inc.
</i>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
