<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report February 1995 Supplement:</B> Three Rivers Environmental Awards</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<img align=left hspace=5 src="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.0.gif"><b><font size =+2>Three Rivers Environmental Awards:<br></font><font size =+1>  Sponsored by Pennsylvania Environmental Council and Duquesne Light Company</font></b><BR>

1995 Three Rivers Environmental Awards<P>
<HR>
 PENNSYLVANIA ENVIRONMENTAL COUNCIL AND DUQUESNE LIGHT COMPANY RECOGNIZE LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL ACHIEVEMENTS<P>

Second Three Rivers Environmental Awards Honor 29 Western Pennsylvania People and Organizations<P>

Some define a generation as 25 years--and last month marked the 25th annual celebration of Earth Day. <P>
That means the spirit of Earth Day--a legacy of environmental stewardship--is being passed on to a new generation of Americans.<P>
<img align=left hspace=5 src="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.1.gif">	And, in fact, we can see this happening every day, in schools across Western Pennsylvania. Our children and grandchildren are learning about such environmental issues as recycling, clean water, and endangered species as part of their schoolwork--and even kindergarten-aged children appreciate the need to protect our vital natural resources.<P>
	It's fitting that we're teaching our children to safeguard these resources. After all, our children represent one of the most important reasons that    we act as environmental stewards, whether we're recycling aluminum cans at home or complying with environmental regulations in our work. In either case, our common goal is to create a better world for our children.<P>


<font size =+2><B>The Three Rivers Environmental Awards</B></font size><BR>
Together, the Pennsylvania Environmental Council and Duquesne Light Company established the Three Rivers Environmental Awards in 1994 to honor local individuals and organizations for their demonstrated commitment to environmental excellence, leadership, and accomplishment.<P>
	The 1995 awards, which helped to celebrate the 25th anniversary of Earth Day, were held last month at the Pittsburgh Vista Hotel. Twenty-nine local people and organizations competed for top honors as finalists in 10 categories--including business; education; community groups; government; communication; and planning, design, and development.<P>
	Recognizing the important role of children in protecting our natural resources, the event this year focused on the relationship between children and the environment.<P>
	Once again, chairpersons for this year's program  were Joanne R. Denworth, president of the Pennsylvania Environmental Council, and Wesley W. von Schack, chairman and chief executive officer of Duquesne Light Company.<P>
	 "We are very pleased that these 29 outstanding finalists and winners serve as excellent examples for       all of Western Pennsylvania," said Denworth of the Pennsylvania Environmental Council. "After all, our     goal in creating these awards was to encourage others     to emulate their achievements--bringing environmental benefits to all of Western Pennsylvania."<P>
	"Our honorees represent people and organizations from all walks of life who have recognized their environmental responsibilities--and are living up to those responsibilities every day," said Duquesne Light's von Schack. "They are setting the standard for this region, and we're proud to salute their accomplishments."<P>
	The 1995 Three Rivers Environmental Awards competition was open to individuals and organizations from throughout Western Pennsylvania.<P>
Applications were accepted in response to a Call for Nominations last fall, and were evaluated by a distinguished panel of independent judges who selected the finalists and winners.<P>
	Nominations were evaluated on the basis of environmental benefit and impact, effectiveness, value of the program to the community, and overall excellence. Finalists and winners were selected by the judges from among more than 100 nominations.<P>
	In addition to receiving an award and earning public recognition, each winner received a check for $1,000, to be donated to the nonprofit environmental organization of his or her choice.<P>
	Following is a brief summary of the achievements of the 11 winners of the 1995 Three Rivers Environmental Awards, as well as a listing of the other finalists in each category (listed in alphabetical order).<P>

<HR>
<font size =+2><B>COMMUNITY-SOCIAL ORGANIZATIONS</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner: Boy Scouts of America Troop 495</B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.2.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
The members of Boy Scout Troop 495 in Custer City, Pennsylvania, are making quite a contribution to the environment near Bradford and Kinzua Bridge State Park. These Scouts have overseen the efforts of 8,000 young volunteers--who have done more than 60,000 hours of public service and conservation work on the Kinzua Bridge Historic Trail. The Scouts have also begun to       re-establish the American chestnut tree as a part of Pennsylvania's forests. In addition, Troop 495 helps to reduce erosion along the Allegheny River by stabilizing the riverbank, and recycles Christmas trees for fish habitat in the Allegheny Reservoir. In recognition of their efforts, these Scouts have earned a number of national conservation awards.<P>
<B>
Finalists:<BR>
Ora Lee Carroll<BR>
National Allegheny Wild and Scenic River<BR>
Southern Advisory Council</B><P>
<HR>

<font size =+2><B>COMMUNITY-ENVIRONMENTAL ORGANIZATIONS</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner: PA CleanWays </B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.3.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
PA CleanWays was formed in 1991 to clean up litter and illegal dump sites in Westmoreland, Somerset, Lawrence, and Cambria Counties. Since then, the volunteer group has eliminated more than 25 dump sites, removing more than 300 truckloads of trash--including appliances, furniture, tires, vehicle batteries, and motor oil. The group has also worked to increase public awareness, encouraging roadway "adoption" programs and sponsoring recycling days for hard-to-dispose-of items. The group--which includes citizens, legislators, area businesspeople, and law enforcement officials--also plants approximately 1,000 trees each year. Family Circle magazine recognized PA CleanWays as one of 20 organizations nationwide that "make America great."<P>


<B>Finalists:	
Loyalhanna Watershed Association<BR>
Western Pennsylvania Conservancy


</B><HR>
<font size =+2><B>GOVERNMENT</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner: Environmental 	Technology Group, US Bureau of Mines-	Pittsburgh Research Center</B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.4.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
Acid mine drainage is our state's greatest source of water pollution. In fact, more than 1,000 miles of Pennsylvania's rivers and streams suffer the effects of our industrial past. But the Environmental Technology Group of the US Bureau of Mines' Pittsburgh Research Center is solving this problem--while also restoring our disappearing wetlands. The Group has developed a method to construct wetlands at active and abandoned mines--using cat tails, limestone drains, and natural bacteria to neutralize contaminants. The method has been named "Best Available Technology" by the Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Resources, and the Group has won a Stewardship Award from the US Secretary of the Interior. To date, more than 250 wetlands have been constructed in Western Pennsylvania through the Group's efforts.<P>

<B>Finalists:	<BR>
Allegheny County Planning Department<BR>
Pennsylvania Forest Stewardship Program
</B><HR>
<font size =+2><B>COMMUNICATION</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner: Washington County Groundwater Coalition </B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.5.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
A survey in 1991, sponsored by the Washington County Groundwater Coalition, showed that few local residents knew what groundwater was--let alone how to protect it. In response, the Coalition began a communication program to increase public awareness    of groundwater quality and related issues. Informational pamphlets, displays, workshops, and free water analysis all work to increase knowledge and concern among homeowners, municipal officials, and environmental groups. The Coalition also works with 14 local school districts to educate students about groundwater issues-- and this month will sponsor the first annual Washington County Children's Groundwater Festival, for 600 sixth-grade students.<P>

<B>Finalist:<BR>
Allegheny County Sanitary Authority
</B><HR>
<font size =+2><B>PLANNING, DESIGN, AND DEVELOPMENT</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner: Mercury Recovery Services </B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.6.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
The Environmental Protection Agency has mandated the clean-up    of more than 250,000 mercury-contaminated sites nationwide. Mercury Recovery Services--headquartered in New Brighton, Beaver County--has developed and patented a removal and recovery process to make that task easier. The process effectively removes mercury from the soil at mining, manufacturing, and drilling sites--so that the land can     be safely re-used by future generations. It also recovers  the metal in a nearly pure form, so that it, too, can be    re-used. The EPA has designated this process the "Best Demonstrated Available Technology" for mercury removal and recovery, and Forbes magazine recently named Mercury Recovery Services one of the 25 leading new technology companies in America.<P>

<B>Finalists:	<BR>
Regional Trail Corporation<BR>
Washington's Landing at Herr's Island<BR>
Urban Redevelopment Authority of Pittsburgh
</B><HR>
<font size =+2><B>PRIMARY OR SECONDARY EDUCATION</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner: Scrubgrass Creek Project, Chartiers Valley High School </B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.7.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
The pollution in the Scrubgrass Creek in Scott Township became a real-life learning experience   in environmental manage-ment and remediation for students at Chartiers Valley High School. Teams studied the chemical, ecological,   and regulatory challenges involved in cleaning the creek and restoring water quality. Together, they developed a comprehensive plan of action and then performed the clean-up work. Today, the water in Scrubgrass Creek        is cleaner, although students plan to bring about even more improvements this year. Through the Project, these students not only make an important contribution to      the community and local environment, but also learn firsthand the challenges involved in environmental management and site remediation.<P>

<B>Finalists:<BR>
Joy A. Kretzler and Ed Smith<BR>
Baldwin-Whitehall School District<BR>>
Robert H. Miles<BR>
Laurel High School
</B><HR>
<font size =+2><B>ADULT, VOCATIONAL,   OR CONTINUING EDUCATION</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner: George W. Freeman, Freeman Tree Farm </B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.8.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
Forest landowners throughout Pennsylvania regard George Freeman as  a model of environmental stewardship. Acting on his own initiative, Mr. Freeman has hosted workshops and seminars for more than 350 landowners at his 600-acre Freeman Tree Farm in Clarion County. These seminars emphasize timber management; soil, water, and wildlife conservation; and harvesting and safety practices. Mr. Freeman has also initiated education programs in conservation and resource management for school districts, 4-H members, and Scout organizations. He is the founder of the Clarion County Forest Steward-ship Committee, and uses his farm for Penn State University's demonstration projects on new harvesting techniques. Mr. Freeman has been honored as one of Pennsylvania's leading foresters and conservation advocates.<P>

<B>Finalists:	<BR>
Rachel Carson Ecology Curriculum<BR>
Chatham College<BR>
Local Government Academy<BR>
</B><HR>
<font size =+2><B>HIGHER EDUCATION</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner (Tie): <BR>
John P. Carroll, Ph.D.<BR>
California University  of Pennsylvania </B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.9.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
The bachelor of science program in wildlife management created at California University of Pennsylvania offers one of the few such courses of study locally, thanks to the work of Dr. John Carroll, an assistant professor of biological and environmental sciences. In this program, students work in partnership with such agencies as the Pennsylvania Game Commission and the US Fish and Wildlife Service to  study and practice habitat management with a variety of species, including the pheasant, the American woodcock, and other small game animals. Additionally, Dr. Carroll's pheasant management program has become a model for wildlife management on Pennsylvania farmland. He is also a founder of the Tri-County Chapter of Pheasants Forever, and is one of this region's most esteemed wildlife conservationists.<P>

<HR>
<font size =+2><B>HIGHER EDUCATION</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner (Tie): <BR>
Environmental Technology Consortium Program<BR>
Community College         of Allegheny County</B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.10.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
Environmental technology  is a growth industry in Western Pennsylvania, with more than 400 local environmental firms. To meet the demand for skilled professionals in this field, the Community College of Allegheny County, the Center for Hazardous Materials Research, and the Allegheny Policy Council have developed a unique associates degree program in environmental technology. Designed by an advisory board of industry and government leaders, this curriculum combines classroom study with hands-on experience. In just three years, more than 250 students have enrolled, and graduates have accepted positions in environmental engineering firms, public utilities, and the Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Resources. For new students, as well as those who lost jobs in other industries, the Program has meant a chance to succeed in one of this region's fastest-growing fields.<P>

<B>Finalist:<BR>
Air and Waste Management Association<BR>
Western Pennsylvania Section
</B><HR>

<font size =+2><B>BUSINESS-PRODUCTS   OR SERVICES</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner: International Metals Reclamation Company </B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.11.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
INMETCO--International Metals Reclamation Company--is an Ellwood City business that's setting new standards for metals recovery. INMETCO is the only company that currently uses High-Temperature Metals Recovery (HTMR) technology to reclaim nickel, chromium, and iron from waste products generated by the US specialty steel industry. This process has been named "Best Demonstrated Available Technology" by the Environmental Protection Agency. INMETCO estimates that it has diverted nearly a billion and a half pounds of materials from our waste stream since 1978. In addition, INMETCO is the only company in North America to recover metals from nickel-cadmium and nickel-iron batteries, and works closely with customers worldwide to facilitate battery recycling.<P>

<B>Finalists:	<BR>
Envirotrol<BR>
Equitable Gas Company
</B><HR>
<font size =+2><B>BUSINESS- ENVIRONMENTAL STEWARDSHIP</B></font size><BR>
<B>Winner: John M. Stilley, Amerikohl Mining</B> (<a href="../pictures/0595.Supplement.pict.12.gif"> See Their Picture</a>)<BR>
In March 1993, one of the Commonwealth's largest coal producers went out of business, leaving behind 11,000 scarred acres in five Western Pennsylvania counties. Seventy-eight sites in all required backfilling, seeding, water clean-up, or tree planting--representing a potential multi-million-dollar cost to taxpayers. But John Stilley, owner of a successful Butler mining company, formed an innovative partnership with the Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Resources and three independent insurance companies to reclaim these sites at no cost to taxpayers. To date, 19 sites have been restored; the remainder will be completely reclaimed within a year.  John Stilley's company, Amerikohl Mining, has received more than 30 state awards for environmental quality     and innovation.<P>

<B>Finalists:<BR>
Girl Scouts of Southwestern Pennsylvania<BR>
Environment, Health, and Safety <BR>
Program--PPG Industries
</B><hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
