<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT10-B35-60</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA061-000345-B036-138</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0495.Feature.1.html 192.204.56.67 19970115134128 text/html 16743
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 13:46:35 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:49:33 GMT
Content-length: 16566
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<b><FONT SIZE=+2> Do The Right Thing </FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b>Are business ethics an oxymoron nowadays?</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Jane A. Black</i>
<HR>

A rabbi is summoned at midnight to counsel a member of his congregation on whether to cook the books and rip off the government, per the boss's instruction, or get fired for telling the truth. Sales agents at a major life insurance company in Pennsylvania and three other states are investigated for using unethical and quite possibly illegal tactics to peddle policies. The president of a small manufacturing concern can't help wondering when an adulterous supplier will begin taking unfair advantage of their relationship. These issues and others like them are inherent in all business dealings and at all levels of the corporate hierarchy.<P>All human interaction has a moral dimension, says the Rev. Dr. Frank D. Almade, interim secretary for social concerns at the Catholic Diocese of Pittsburgh, whether it's personal, familial, societal or commercial.<P>"There was a time when business relationships were out of bounds," says Almade. "It didn't matter that 11-year-olds [were employed] for 60 to 70 hours a week. It didn't matter that [they were employed] at bare level wages in very unsafe conditions."Thank God our society has changed its ways on those things. You can see where those questions have crept in whereas formerly they were out of bounds. As a theologian, I think there is a sharper focus that there are ethical issues in business."It's getting sharper all the time. Financial World devoted an entire issue to the subject last summer, and more business books are covering it either by chapter or in whole. Ethics instructors are leaving academia to open private consultancies. Local law firm Lindner & Simpson does practically nothing but provide advisory ethics opinions to attorneys, law firms and corporate legal departments.<P>Why? Are ethical dilemmas in business and industry increasing? Or are we simply hearing about untoward practices more? Some would argue that it's not so much a deterioration of ethical behavior but an increase in expectations. It's impossible to know for sure.<P>Statistics are spotty because of the myriad of imponderables. The U.S. Chamber of Commerce estimates that white-collar crime costs American businesses more than $40 billion a year. Harder to put a price tag on is a more insidious form of swindling -- a poor work ethic. Slackers can rob their employers just as methodically as those who plunder the supply cabinet.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Part and Parcel: </B></font size> If you use how business is portrayed on prime-time tele-vision as a barometer, unethical behavior is "part and parcel of doing business," says Thomas Johnson in the January 1995 issue of MediaNomics, a publication of the Media Research Center in Alexandria, Va.<P>Johnson cites "Out of Focus: Network Television and the American Economy," which analyzed 1992's prime-time entertainment programs. While businessmen made up 24% of prime time's characters, they were 43% of its criminals and 36% of its murderers.<P>Despite TV's villainous guest tycoons and rapacious bigwigs, small-business characters are almost always portrayed positively on the little screen. Johnson's conclusion? Prime-time TV implies that it is possible for good people to be businessmen, but they are good in spite of their careers.<P>Certainly Americans have developed a pervasive cynicism toward companies' commitment to ethical behavior, a feeling which has intensified in the ultracompetitive 1990s. Motiva-tional mantras borrowed from other arenas -- "Whatever It Takes" and "Just Do It" -- enable some business people to justify behavior they would otherwise find abhorrent. Likewise, many employees have lost faith in management's ability to do right after repeated downsizing.<P>Peter Madsen, executive director of the Center for the Advancement of Applied Ethics at Carnegie Mellon University, likes to define business ethics as having two branches: issues of conduct, which he calls managerial mis-chief, and cognitive issues, or moral mazes that managers must wend their way through.<P>Madsen, who offers training in business ethics for managers, has worked with many local organizations such as Alcoa, Duquesne Light Co., the Easter Seal Society of Allegheny County, the Pittsburgh branch of the Internal Revenue Service, PPG Industries, Westinghouse and Pitt's business school.<P>Madsen is cited in "Making the Right Decision," an extended case history based on the five-year, $5 million business ethics pro-gram of Arthur Andersen & Co., and he is co-editor of the forthcoming book, "Essentials of Business Ethics." Madsen says that white-collar crime appears to be on the rise and that business ethics is a nascent field.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Sticks and Carrots: </B></font size> The 1991 Federal Corporate Sentencing Guidelines no doubt helped germinate the current focus on business ethics. Congress wanted guidelines for federal judges who were sentencing corporate lawbreakers, says Madsen. "They raised the pen-alties dramatically -- they quadrupled them in some cases -- that was the stick part. The carrot was to allow judges to use discretion if the company had a viable ethics compliance program in place," he says. Fines imposed in one corporate case topped $280 million.<P>That new tangible, mone-tary responsibility prompted many companies to begin ethics pro-grams, or beef up existing ones. Rare, says Madsen, is the large company that doesn't have at least a code of ethics. Some 90% of 235 large companies that responded to a 1992 survey by Business Ethics magazine had a formal code.<P>That's not to say that small companies don't have ethics codes. It's just that their codes are more likely to be implicit and unwritten, says Jim Weber, Ph.D., associate professor and director of the Beard Center for Leadership in Ethics at the A.J. Palumbo School of Business Administration at Duquesne University.<P>"Smaller companies are more seat of the pants -- they are just trying to sell their product," says John Putzier, president of FirStep and adjunct faculty member of Robert Morris College.<P>A full-fledged corporate ethics program might include a statement of values and beliefs or a mission statement, em-ployee training, an ethics committee or officer, and hot lines for advice or whistle-blowing, Madsen says. Ideally, the officer or committee reports to the top brass.<P>"Writing a code doesn't have much impact by itself," Weber says. "The code is a necessary first step, but is insufficient alone. You can't just write and forget about it."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Follow the Leader: </B></font size> While an ethics code can and should be prepared with input from employees at every level, experts agree that ethical behavior must come from the top down or the effort is all for naught.<P>"[Ethical behavior is] really created by the actions of the leadership," says Putzier, a management consultant. "Lead-ership goes so much farther than a code of ethics. It doesn't do a thing if the boss is a crook."<P>Putzier says he learned much of what he knows about ethical behavior from working at PPG Industries for 10 years a decade ago. "I sat in on a lot of closed-door meetings and never once was an expedient or un-ethical decision made," he says. PPG conducted a major employee attitude survey right after Putzier left. Integrity was the No. 1 response when workers were asked what made up the corporate culture.<P>The vision and commitment of top management, the rights and responsibilities of the employ-ees and the realities of business should all be incorporated into a company's code.<P>That's no mean feat since one of the realities of business is that competitive advantage often goes directly against ethical behavior. "It doesn't have to be a decision of whether to be a good person or be profitable. You can be both," says Weber. "But I rec-ognize the counter position: There are cases when doing the right thing will mean less profits." Indeed, Weber's students often challenge him on that very point, opining that behaving ethically is like kissing your sister -- it's nice but meaningless.<P>Some would even argue that ethical behavior can harm a company, at least in the short term. Denver-based Manville Corp. posted a 40% decline in Japanese sales when it put a cautionary label on its fiberglass products. However, the manu-facturing firm's sales in Japan later bounced back to profitability.<P>Respironics of Murrysville pulled a popular line of resus-citators after some minor defects were discovered, a potentially costly move in light of incon-veniencing or unduly alarming customers. However, its new re-suscitators have two-thirds fewer parts and require two-thirds fewer operations to manufacture.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Pride Before Fall: </B></font size> Contrast that with the hubris of Audi. The foreign carmaker attributed sudden unexplained accelerations in a model it manufactured to driver error. Sales dipped as the public began to perceive the company as apathetic to consumers. "Now to regain market share, they've instituted a bumper-to-bumper full warranty. They're paying more now than they would have if they had addressed the problem differ-ently initially," says Putzier.<P>Certainly there can be benefits from doing the right thing even when it is more expensive. J.W. Connolly, retired senior vice president for the H.J. Heinz Co., recommended dolphin-safe tuna in the late 1980s, flying in the face of the conventional wisdom of providing the lowest-cost product possible consistent with quality. The result? Enough recognition that much of the industry responded by joining Heinz in responsible citizenship. Not only was it masterful public relations, but the gratuitous injury and death of some highly intel-ligent creatures were curtailed.<P>Ralph Reiland, associate professor of economics at Robert Morris College and owner of Amel's Restaurant, insists that ethical behavior pays off. "In operating Amel's Restaurant, for the most part, I find the relationship between doing the right thing and earning profits is complimentary, not in conflict." As examples, Reiland says better wages mean more qualified applicants; higher quality food means repeat business, and diversity in the work force adds to customer satisfaction.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Remove the Opportunity: </B></font size> While it's not prudent to hypothesize about who is more likely to be unethical, it does make sense to be aware of certain conditions that can foster such behavior.Experts say that people are more likely to misbehave if they think they can get away with it. Moreover, "people will be uneth-ical if they see it as a way to get ahead," says Putzier. So if the chance of apprehension is mini-mal, and the return is hefty, or at least outweighs the reper-cussions, the situation is ripe for chicanery.<P>Rationalizations can play a part. Employees may feel absolved of responsibility if they are instructed by superiors to do something questionable. "There's no doubt that in-centives to do wrong will be picked up from the top," says Madsen. <P>It can also mean trouble when people are under intense pressure to perform. "There seems to be some correlation to unethical behavior when com-pensation is driven by a reward system. Industries that histor-ically have bad raps -- car sales, insurance sales, brokerages -- are almost pure commission," says Putzier.<P>The trick then is to reduce the opportunities for wrong-doing, Madsen says. Restructure the compensation system, for example. Protect whistle-blow-ers. And, walk the talk, as dif-ficult as that may be.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>It's Getting Worse: </B></font size> All indications are that it's not going to get any easier. "It's clear that as business becomes more complex because of an-swering to the various stake-holders, operating on a global level and so on, balancing different ethical issues is going to be more difficult," says Weber.<P>Humility helps, Almade says. "[Ethical behavior] might be connected to a willingness to listen to other people and a concerted effort not to be arrogant. Humility is saying, I don't have all the answers, but I'm willing to listen to people and, once in a while, decide I have to change.' " And when making a difficult choice, Almade says to ask yourself, "What decision can I make that will do the least amount of harm?" <P>                         
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Ethical Issues from One Week in The Wall Street Journal: </B></font size> 
<OL>
<LI>Stealing: taking things that don't belong to you<P>  
<LI>Lying: saying things you know aren't true<P>  
<LI>Fraud and deceit: creating or perpetuating false impressions<P>  
<LI>Conflict of interest and influence buying: bribes, payoffs and kickbacks<P>  
<LI>Hiding vs. divulging information: concealing information that another party has a right to know or failing to protect personal or proprietary information<P>  
<LI>Cheating: taking unfair advantage of a situation<P>  
<LI>Personal decadence: aiming below excellence in work performance (e.g., careless or sloppy work)<P>  
<LI>Interpersonal abuse: behaviors that are abusive of others (e.g., sexism, racism, emotional abuse)<P>  
<LI>Organizational abuse: organizational practices that abuse members (e.g., inequitable compensation, misuses of power)<P>
<LI>Rule violations: breaking organizational rules<P>
<LI>Accessory to unethical acts: knowing about unethical behavior and failing to report it<P>
<LI>Ethical dilemmas: choosing between two equally undesirable options
</OL>
<I>Source: Adapted from J.O. Cherrington and D.J. Cherrington, "A Menu of Moral Issues: One Week in the Life of The Wall Street Journal," Journal of Business Ethics 11 (1992): 255-265. Reprinted by permission of Kluwer Academic Publishers.</I>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Why Be Good?: </B></font size> Ethics experts say that operating within ethical guidelines can help you:
<DL>
<LI>win more contracts
<LI>reduce litigation and arbitration
<LI>facilitate project completion
<LI>foster repeat business
<LI>attract quality employees
</DL>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Three Litmus Tests for Ethical Conduct: </B></font size> 
<DL>
<LI>The Skunk Test: Does this course of conduct smell?
<LI>The Child Test: Would I advise my own child to do this?
<LI>The Newspaper Test: Would I like my board to read about this?
</DL>
<I>Source: "Doing the Right Thing: Business Ethics and Boards of Directors," Director's Monthly, National Association of Corporate Directors, Washington, D.C.</I>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>A Word About Competition: </B></font size> At first blush, the competition of a capitalistic society would seem to promote Machiavellianism, because a free capital market is profit driven. It's not that simple, however. And the alternatives can be worse. Says John Putzier, president of FirStep and adjunct faculty member of Robert Morris College, "We know socialism is anything but ethical."<P>As a businessman and an associate professor of economics, Ralph Reiland has strong feelings on competition as it relates to ethical behavior. "Competition provides much of the discipline in the business sector, and that's basically missing when we're dealing with the monopoly of government. We wouldn't survive in the restaurant business if we raised prices as our quality declined. Our customers are free to choose to go elsewhere," says Reiland. "With public schools, in contrast, taxpayers' costs per student have doubled in the past two decades while SATs fell. Parents are only free to choose a different school if they pay for both the school that they're rejecting and the one they're choosing.<P>"What would be my incentive as a restaurant owner to offer a good product to my customers if the government gave me their money whether they came back or not?" he asks. Reiland owns Amel's Restaurant and teaches at Robert Morris College.


<hr>
