<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Education: Why Johnny Can't Work</B></FONT></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>What are educators, businesses, unions, foundations and governments doing to correct a wrong decades in the making?</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Michelle Fanzo</i>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>
If there is any doubt that there are high school graduates who lack basic reading, math and communication skills, Matt Botsford, chairman, CEO and president of WorldClass Pro-cessing Inc., a processed steel pro-ducer in Ambridge, suggests taking a look at his job applications.<P>Poor work attitude, he adds, is a bigger problem. "Schools need to get people from industry and business to talk to these kids and tell them what's really going on. Books and classrooms are not enough," he says. <P>Rich Stanizzo, business manager of the Pittsburgh Building & Construction Trades Council says he has seen a marked decline over the last 10 years in the percentage of applicants who can pass the basic apprenticeship test. He finds ap-plicants are not as skilled in math and English as in the past, and that an understanding of workplace conduct is severely lacking. "We're frustrated by this," says Stanizzo. "It really hurts our business."<P>With the vitality of a region increasingly dependent on an educated citizenry and skilled work force, such concerns reach far beyond any one company's bottom line.Labor market projections for the next 10 years say most future jobs will require some training beyond high school, but not necessarily a four-year degree. According to a 1989 National Resource Council study, 75% of all jobs require proficiency in simple algebra and geometry -- just two of several skills, say employers, that many applicants lack. This mismatch has spurred widespread reassessment of how students are being shaped for their futures.<P>Though Pennsylvania was one of the first states to try to strengthen school and work linkages through its creation of the Pennsylvania Ap-prenticeship Program six years ago, some local employers have so much trouble finding qualified job applicants that they resort to enticing employees away from their competitors. Edu-cators agree that there is a serious problem, which is why they, along with business, unions, foundations and government, are busy trying to correct a wrong decades in the making.<P>"I once heard a colleague say if a person had left this planet 70 years ago and come back, the only thing he would recognize would be the schools," says Nancy Bunt, managing director of the Regional Math and Science Collaborative, formed a year ago to advance math and science education. <P>Schools are out of step with the times, which causes students to be out of step with the realities of the workplace. The obvious conclusion is to create better communication between the two. The more com-plicated reality is how to do that effectively. One solution: school-to-work initiatives.<P>"When we talk about career preparation we aren't talking about a specific vocation," says Pam Wiegman, coordinator for Applied Technology and Career Development, part of the unit of school support services for Pittsburgh Public Schools. "We realize that for many of the students presently in the school system, the jobs they will ultimately fill don't even exist now. So we need to prepare them to be employees and to prepare them broadly."
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Local Connections: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Local organizations that have been developing school-to-work initiatives for the region are working in concert with federal legislation -- the Goals 2000: Educate America and the School-to-Work Opportunities acts.<P>In September 1992, the Pennsyl-vania Youth Apprenticeship Program was introduced in certain Pittsburgh schools. The following year, other districts initiated similar programs. In May 1994, as part of Pennsylvania's plan to create a statewide school-to-work system encompassing many career paths, the state renamed the program the School-to-Work Opportunity System.<P>Industry is seen as an integral partner in this endeavor and has been asked to help identify career pathways for students in the region. Namely, businesses will be asked, "What are the skills needed now and who will be offering jobs in the future? What skills are needed for today's students to fill tomorrow's jobs?" The program will expose students to the workplace as early as elementary school.<P>Southwestern Pennsylvania is home to one of eight state industrial resource centers -- non-profit economic development organizations whose primary client is the business community -- selected as a regional coordinator and agent for the school-to-work program.<P>The Southwestern Pennsylvania Industrial Resource Center is cur-rently piloting the program in eight schools. Originally aimed at manufac-turing, the program has been expand-ed to include healthcare and other service and technology industries.To ensure communication be-tween workplace and classroom, SPIRC recently established the Southwestern Pennsylvania Business Consortium for School-to-Work Opportunities. <P>"Industry needs to come to the realization that we are the customer of the schools. So we really should take the more proactive role rather than complaining about what we see as a falloff in performance levels," says Dennis Meteny, president and CEO of Respironics Inc., and chairman of the consortium. "Jobs have changed,and I don't think industry did a very good job of communicating that to the schools. For this initiative to be a success, it has to be a collaborative ef-fort between industry and education."
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Doing It Differently </B></FONT SIZE><br>
The Allegheny Policy Council was formed two years ago, spearheaded by leaders in the civic, business, educa-tion and philanthropic communities, and by the Allegheny Conference on Community Development.<P>The council is coordinating a strategic approach to the way the region educates its youth and prepares its work force. Hence, while it shares a common goal with SPIRC, it is unique in its non-governmental collaborative approach.<P>Using national education goals established under the Bush admin-istration as a framework, a number of council initiatives have already been implemented, such as the Regional Math and Science Center at Carnegie Science Center, the Youth Employ-ment Alliance and the Workplace Skills Development Network.<P>The Career and Academic Pass-port, one of the primary education reforms initiated by the policy council, addresses making sure students have a foundation of certain work-related skills and academic knowledge.<P>Currently, different schools emphasize different skills -- a student in Pittsburgh may have completed different lessons than ones in McKees Rocks or Upper St. Clair. But when a student is awarded a passport, in 10th grade or thereabouts, it will mean a set standard of foundation knowledge and skills have been achieved, no matter what school issued it.<P>The policy council convened a commission from business, education, community and government to specify what these core skills need to be.<P>Ideally, students will acquire these basic skills before exploring career-learning opportunities in the 11th and 12th grades. If students have not achieved these standards by age 16, there is still time before graduation to do so. The passport is meant to better prepare students for their transition from school to work or to ensure their success if they pursue higher education in an economy that finds the average worker changing professions seven times.<P>The passport will be piloted in six area schools this fall. Though similar concepts are being implemented in other states, Allegheny County's approach is singular because employ-ers and college representatives are partners in the initiative and school district participation is voluntary. No state or federal agency is involved.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Repeat Offender </B></FONT SIZE><br>
While new initiatives suggest progress in better preparing students for the workplace, they are not the first endeavors created to obtain such results. In fact, the School-to-Work Opportunity System is an extension of existing legislation, such as the Job Training Partnership Act and Tech Prep. Unfortunately, some of the past educational programs designed to elevate basic skills learning and prepare students for the workplace have been futile.<P>Speaking as an employer, Stanizzo feels the school-to-work and appren-ticeship programs already in place have been thoroughly ineffective. He says he has seen young people trained for jobs already suffering from an overabundance of applicants, leaving them single-skilled and jobless. Other programs, he feels, were not very rigorous.<P>Any new initiatives must identify work force needs in the future, Stanizzo asserts. "People have said to me the apprenticeship programs are a semi-German system. What makes it semi is that they left out the portion where people get a job."What makes the new initiatives any better?<P>"What's going on now is not a program. It's a different way of under-standing the task. It's putting into place policies and systems that will respond to that," says Rob Rogers, senior policy analyst for the Allegheny Policy Council and executive director for the Allegheny County Commission for Workforce Excellence.<P>"Vocational education is a program. Apprenticeships are a pro-gram method. What we're trying to do now is put in a new way of seeing the world and responding to its realities. And only if it is viewed this way will it work. We need an organization that will not run a program, but will iden-tify the best practices and translate them into public policy that will then change the very systems themselves.<P>"So the policy council is not about coming up with a better mousetrap. We're about helping to craft the public policies that will change the systems that influence youth and work force development," says Rogers.<P>The emphasis on input from the business community further separates the initiative from previous attempts. It is not designed in isolation from labor market statistics or from what business is saying it needs for a trained work force.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>What Went Wrong </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Though business has evolved faster than education, it is only since the belt-tightening of the late 1980s that the incompatibility between the needs of industry and the product of the schools has become patently obvious. From the industrial revolution through the mid-1960s there was harmony between education and the workplace.<P>Then worldwide competition arrived, and business evolved to meet the demands of a new market. "But schools, which are funded through government and taxes, did not have to be market sensitive," says Rogers. "They didn't have to be responsive to their customers so they are still doing in 1995 what they did in 1950. But by this time the incompatibility is evident, and businesses are absolutely red-faced and screaming that it has to be done differently."<P>Until recently, says Gregory Spencer, vice president of human resources at Equitable Resources, there were still a large number of jobs where people could start with simple tasks and slowly move into more skilled positions. Not anymore. "Business can no longer afford to offer such training programs and low-skilled jobs. From the time someone starts to work you want to begin to see a return on your investment of hiring them. It is much smarter, from a business standpoint, to hire someone who already has the skills you need, or at least have prepared themselves to have ongoing learning."<P>What this has done, he says, is cause everyone to reexamine their role. "Schools are looking at the fact that they have a responsibility to educate students, but that there's really a small percent that go on to college. So there's a large group of people who are going into the work force, and they don't have work force skills. As customers, business needs to go to the schools more and tell them what we need, and schools have to respond to that," says Spencer. "If I have to devote some of my time for that to happen, it's well worth the effort."<P>Even the vocabulary used to describe these educational reforms will play a role. "For so long, vocational education has had a status problem because of its history as a dumping ground for people not going on to college," says Bunt. "Almost no parent would chose to put their child in vocational education. That perception is still there, but now we have a group of students who do not need a college education but need to be techno-logically literate -- and they need to have those basic skills at a much higher level than they did in the past."
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> Hands--on Exposure</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Equally misunderstood are apprenticeships, historically viewed as training for a trade. Now, it is often a hands-on exposure to the workplace much like a college internship. Even school-to-work is a misnomer as it is really school-to-life preparation.<P>Educators emphasize that school-to-work is not a fancy synonym for the vocational education of the past, nor is it just for non-collegians. College-bound students also need more exposure to basic skills. According to a recent report by the policy council, more than 25% of community college students are required to take remedial classes before they can qualify for credit classes.<P>Many of the initiatives discussed are in the planning phase or about to be piloted. Others, like apprentice-ships, have already been instituted in a few districts. "Things are already happening in pockets," says Rogers. "Fox Chapel has been going through a major change for the past year to move to 80-minute class periods because you can't do much integration in 40 minutes. Shaler School District, with its Project Rigor, is attempting to blend work and school in creative ways. We're trying to magnify those efforts and see what policies are successful so they can be implemented for everyone and not just a select few."<P>The question being asked today is not what academic track can we fit students into, but how can all students be better prepared for the 21st century workplace.                    

<hr>
