Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:49:36 GMT
Content-length: 16186
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Commercial Real Estate</B></FONT></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Builders and community officials struggle to protect natural resources while strategically zoning development.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Krista Hughes Ramsey</i>
<hr>

As commercial developments pop up around the suburban Pittsburgh area, few of us think about their prepara-tion. But the planning behind these developments must delicately balance the pros and cons for residents, businesses and the environment. Local municipal officials and builders strive to weigh growth against preservation.<P>Although development does bring jobs and increased tax revenues -- pluses for any municipal manager -- it can also bring congested roadways, increase air and water pollution, and raise the cost of public services. So most officials create comprehensive growth management plans to nip problems in the bud.<P>Such a plan provides a foundation for developers. It takes into account utilities, community facilities, trans-portation routes, land use design, water resources and future develop-ment. Successful plans also consider the relationship of new development to a community's fiscal status.<P>Southwestern Pennsylvania's communities are primarily stand-alone ones with a hodgepodge of buildings and zones in any given area. It comes as a surprise to some that there are parts of the United States where the same ordinances apply to an entire county and developments are zoned by type. "We will never see this type of situation in Pittsburgh, which makes it even harder to keep all ordinances current," says Jeff Ferris of Kacin Design Contractors Builders in Plum Borough.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Obsolete at Birth: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Few places here have adopted comprehensive plans for growth management that are completely up to date. As rapidly as the new ordinances go into effect, they need to be revised. "Rules change quickly in our fast-paced world," says Ferris. "We just have to do our best trying to keep up with them."<P>With a proper plan, developers face less uncertainty. "Once a municipality's rules and regulations are in place for a particular type and size of construction or development, no one really can afford to challenge them," says Ferris. "If there is an ordinance in place when we submit for a site plan, we have to follow what is required. Most officials are doing what is best for their communities."<P>Although Pennsylvania does not mandate reviews of growth manage-ment plans, it is in the best interest of a community to keep its plan current.<P>To deal with population and employment projections or new highways that may affect their ordinances, many municipalities emphasize continued planning.<P>Cranberry Township in Butler County is striving for continued planning as it handles being one of the fastest growing communities in the area. Plans for nearly 1.5 million square feet of retail space in the township, including J.J. Gumberg Co.'s The Marketplace at Cranberry, are on the drawing board.<P>Dan Santoro, director of the department of code administration, says Cranberry has been working on its comprehensive growth manage-ment plan for the past year and a half. "We are in the final stages of com-pleting our strategic action plan and will be ready to formally adopt it [soon]," he says.<P>The community's accessibility accounts for some of its growth. Located conveniently to I-279 and downtown Pittsburgh, Cranberry is ideal for all development.<P>The township expects its rapid growth to continue. "The elected officials of Cranberry are encouraging and creating an environment con-ducive to industrial growth," says Santoro. "We promote growth manage-ment. It's essential and beneficial to the quality of life of the people who reside, shop and do business here."Penn Township in Westmoreland County is also growing. The township has seen a 4% annual growth rate for the past several years with no sign of abatement. Dallas Leonard, Penn Township's director of community development, and the planning com-mission have been working to revise ordinances and specifications on zoning, sewers, solid waste manage-ment, construction and subdivisions.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Growing Pains: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Commercial and residential growth in Penn Township and Monroeville is increasing the traffic congestion. Murrysville, located between the two, is feeling the effects of this growth as well as its own.<P>The Pennsylvania Department of Transportation has proposed widening the Route 22 corridor through Murrysville from four lanes to six. Allen Cohen, Murrysville community development director, says that the proposal is being met with concern because it would require 20 to 30 businesses on Route 22 to relocate.<P>The municipality must weigh easing traffic snarls against displacing local businesses. "The East Suburban Chamber of Commerce and a few other groups are looking for an alternative solution to the problem," he says. "PennDOT says they will respond after they get some feedback and hopefully will agree to a less severe plan of action."<P>Murrysville adopted a compre-hensive growth plan in 1990. The plan attempts to maintain the "rural resi-dential atmosphere. We strongly regulate the type of development we approve so that it consistently pro-motes the inherent character of Murrysville," says Cohen.<P>Many local governments are es-tablishing impact fees, which charge developers for affecting the infra-structure. "If a developer does some-thing to affect a borough's budget, this is when impact fees come into play," says J. Roger Glunt, 1993 president of the National Association of Home Builders and owner of Glunt Building Co. Inc. in Turtle Creek. "They provide a feasible means to offset raising taxes, which is why local officials favor them. Development follows the infrastruc-ture, so there must be a means to maintaining and creating it."<P>Cranberry Township uses impact fees for transportation. "We assess these fees based on a development's impact on our roads, or how much traffic it will create," says Santoro.<P>Environmental laws have been put into effect over concerns for hazardous waste, water pollution and increased auto emissions. "Because of the rapid spurt of commercial growth in this area, Penn Township is experiencing an overburdening of its infrastructure and currently is under a sewer tap prohibition from the Department of Environmental Resources," says Leonard.<P>"These regulatory changes do impact development, and we make it a point to inform developers so that they can make modifications in their proposals," he says. "These are minor problems that can be corrected. The benefits of substantial growth far outweigh the problems we are expe-riencing," he adds.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Tax Refugees: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Growth is likely to continue in the counties that offer lower costs. In Allegheny County, taxes are higher, often by several mills, and utilities are generally more expensive. <P>"Many businesses looking to build and own property are going to other counties because that's where the incentives are," Ferris says. "Much of our work is done in Westmoreland County, which is pro-controlled quality, pro-job creation and pro-small business expansion."<P>Some counties, Westmoreland included, offer temporary tax abate-ments for large projects that bring new jobs into the area. Washington County is doing the same. "To attract new business, companies can relocate to, for instance, Southpointe, and receive tax breaks for doing so," says Ed Zuk, Peters Township's planning director. "This is a successful economic tool set up by the county, which benefits its municipalities."<P>At the same time, officials work hard to ward off suburban sprawl. Scattered development causes more traveling, thus, more air pollution, and weakens the sense of community. It also can burden taxpayers with the expense of spreading municipal services over large areas.<P>Peters Township actively combats sprawl. "Under the Pennsylvania Agricultural Security Act, we have designated the 1,000-plus acres of active farming land that runs through our township as an agricultural security district, which protects it from undesired development," says Zuk.<P>Officials also have divided the township into two regions -- preferred growth and nonpreferred growth -- to steer commercial development.<P>Washington County's lower taxes have drawn lots of development to the Peters area, including Prizant's Carpet, Ski North, Wendy's, the 10,000-square-foot Heather Office Building along Washington Road and Bell Tower Shops (scheduled to open later this year) on East McMurray Road.<P>Residential growth also is on the upswing. The township granted a record 156 new single-family construction permits in 1994. "We have been growing steadily for the past 10 to 15 years, and we are strongly committed to planning and zoning for the future," says Zuk.<P>The township has a computerized geographic information system that allows planners and developers to see topography, sewer, water and electric lines, wetlands, buildings, railroads, loading districts, flood boundaries, etc., in digitized form. "We can choose any area of property, call it up on our screen and determine its specific geographic characteristics," says Zuk. "This tool gives us the capability to assess the development potential of a property ... and manage growth at our fingertips."Bruce Hill, president of Hill Commercial Properties, one of the oldest downtown Pittsburgh com-mercial real estate firms, says that municipalities have begun to look at the big picture. "They're developing plans of attack to combat problems caused by mismanaged development," he says. "Permits are becoming more difficult to acquire, but it's to everyone's benefit."<P>"Growth management is an issue that the National Association of Home Builders has been dealing with for quite some time," says Glunt. "Our position is that growth is good as long as it's handled with reason, balance and logic. There can become a point where growth in a community must stop, and each of us must determine when enough is enough." <P>    
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>In Other RE News: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Mayor Murphy has proposed a revolving loan fund for residential, commercial and industrial projects costing at least $1.5 million. Ad-ministered by the Urban Rede-velopment Authority, the Pittsburgh Development Fund will make up no more than 30% of a project's cost, according to the Pittsburgh office of the National Association of Indus-trial and Office Properties.<P>URA floated $60 million in special tax development bonds for the loan money. The city will make the bond interest payment with the $7.5 million it will accrue from the regional asset district countywide sales tax. A second fund of about $50 million will be set up with private sources through the Allegheny Conference on Community Development.<P>The URA has applied for a    $6.5 million Strategy 21 grant from the state to help develop Carnegie Mellon University's NASA Robotics Engineering Consortium adjacent to the Lawrenceville Industrial Park. The 6-acre site will be leased by the URA to CMU. The grant will help fund demolition, site prep and renovations.NASA has committed more than $50 million in grants for R&D, admin-istration and operation. Corporations expected to sponsor research projects there include Boeing, Caterpillar, McDonnell Douglas, Lear Astronics, IBM and Lockheed.<P>In other URA news, $450,000 will be lent to the owners of the former St. Mary's German Catholic Church, who plan to renovate the building into Pittsburgh's Grand Hall. The 1854 landmark on the North Side will host banquets, business meetings and trade shows. Total cost for the conversion is estimated at $1.5 mil-lion, with additional financing being provided by Pittsburgh Home Savings Bank and the developer.<P>	In the last six months of 1994, some 650 jobs were created by 25 newcomers to the Bridgeville, Collier and South Fayette area, according to the Greater Bridgeville Chamber of Commerce. Among the companies are AllPak Inc., Bell Atlantic Mobile, Dollar Bank, Grant Street Associates, Kem Tech Consulting, Sears, Taco Bell, Universal Stainless and U.S. Property. PennDOT has allocated  $2.6 million for road work along the Route 50 corridor which should jumpstart $50 million in projects, says Louis J. Phillips, chairman of the Route 50 Corridor Commission.<P>	Johnson/Schmidt and Associates of Pittsburgh is designing Devel-opment Dimensions International's 96,000-square-foot, $8 million center for advanced learning technology adjacent to DDI's headquarters in Bridgeville. Initially, DDI will lease 54,000 square feet of the building, which is expected to be completed by May 1996.<P>	Magee-Womens Hospital is in the midst of an $86 million expansion program. Turner Construction Co. has completed $9 million of work. A $40 million acute care center is expected to be completed by September 1997 and a $3 million medical office building atop the OB pavilion should be finished in December.<P>	Gold & Co. has been selected to handle Bell Atlantic's properties in Pennsylvania, Ohio and West Virginia. Responsibilities include the dispo-sition of 20 properties. Gold was appointed the agent for McKnight Development Corp. (owners of the Wendy's and Chuck E. Cheese franchises in western Pennsylvania) for acquisitions, dispositions and some property management. The company is also now representing the office and retail space of the Westin William Penn.<P>	Conrail Inc. will construct an intermodal terminal at the Pitcairn Yard by 1996. The truck-to-train freight terminal is needed for the double-stack train traffic which is expected once the railroad completes its $75 million clearance project on Pennsylvania lines. About 30 acres will be used for the terminal and warehouse and distribution centers.<P>	The Pittsburgh Cultural Trust is renovating the Art Cinema on Liberty Avenue into a 200-seat theater for the Pittsburgh Filmmakers and small live productions and lectures. Bohlin, Cywinski, Jackson is the principal architect on the project, which is expected to be completed in August.<P>	The Environmental Protection Agency has announced it will pick up the tab for assessments -- $25,000 to $50,000 per site -- for 10 to 12 brownfields in southwestern Penn-sylvania. Under the agreement, the EPA will also shield investors from future liability and create levels of cleanup.<P>	The Rubinoff Co. of Pittsburgh has sold I-79 North Industrial Park in Allegheny County to Aleppo Property Holding Co. Rubinoff will lease and manage the 124-acre park, which has 460,000 square feet in eight buildings. APHC plans new landscaping, signs and development of build-to-suit and flex buildings. Tenants include Xerox Corp., Benthin Systems, AG, Columbia Gas, Pepsi-Cola Metro-politan and Pella Door & Window Co.<P>	Grubb & Ellis Co. is leasing Abele's Business Park in South Fayette Township in Allegheny County. The 66-acre park is owned by Hickory Hill Associates. Park residents include Schwan's Sales Enterprises, Niobium Products Co. and Cintas Uniforms.<P>	The resources of Langholz/Wilson & Associates Inc. have been expanded through the company's membership in CORFAC, a North American office and industrial network. CORFAC formed a joint venture with King & Co. International, a group of European real estate companies with 22 offices in the United Kingdom, Belgium, France, Spain, Germany, the Czech republic and Austria.             <P>                                           -- Jane A. Black

