<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2> To Be or Not To Be an Entrepreneur </FONT SIZE><i> By Linda A. Dickerson</i><P>
One of the formidable challenges confronting our new governor is the stark realization that last year Pennsylvania ranked 45th among all the states in new company formations and 49th in the rate of change in new company formations. In fact, the state bottomed out as No. 50 in the Center for Enterprise Develop-ment's Entrepreneurial Energy assessments. We are dead last in our new business kinetics.<P>If the state picture is bleak, our local perspective is dismal at best. This region's rate of new company formation is 25% below the state's average. According to The Enterprise Corp. of Pittsburgh, approximately 3,400 new companies start here each year. To equal the national start-up rate on a per capita basis, our region would have to form 6,500 new businesses annually. We would have to double our local new business formation rate to equal, not surpass, our counterparts across the nation.<P>Our aging demographics exacer-bate the problem, because the 30-something crowd is the one most likely to risk a new business venture. <P>In its "Acorns to Oak Trees" report, The Enterprise Corp. issued a clarion call to this region to create a more nurturing and supportive environment for would-be entrepreneurs. The Enterprise Corp. challenges area universities to lead the region's entrepreneurial charge. By accelerating their efforts to move their technologies to market, universities can mobilize job creation and stimulate growth.<P>The young, enthusiastic graduates of area universities and colleges bring the vitality and fortitude necessary to achieve entrepreneurial success. Potential entrepreneurs are this area's most valuable resource. <P>If we need to double our entre-preneurial output, then let's accelerate production. I agree with the Regional Economic Revitalization Initiative's assertion that high performance manufacturing is the anchor tenant of our economic superstructure. However, we can't have high performance manufacturing without high perfor-mance manufacturers. Likewise, we can't achieve entrepreneurial success without entrepreneurs.<P>Universities and all other community institutions must challenge our best and brightest young people to chart an entrepreneurial career path here, not elsewhere. The medical community is shrinking, so who needs more doctors? Lawyers abound; just ask any business owner. And, the need for Indian chiefs diminished after the French and Indian War. Doctors, lawyers and Indian chiefs are definitely pass. Now, we need more entrepreneurs. Our future depends on them!

<hr>
