<HEAD>
<TITLE> Letters </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.L.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<font size =+2><B>Letter to a Letter</B></font size><BR>
Recently Rep. Albert W. Pettit wrote concerning school strikes [January 1995]. His statements compel an answer.<P>To begin with let me state emphatically that I have never seen a teacher who really wanted to strike. That is why the Pennsylvania State Education Association is seeking some reasonable impasse resolution to the collective bargaining process in our public schools.<P>PSEA also recognizes the need to deal with property taxes. We have strongly supported real and equitable tax reform. Unfortunately our State Legislature has not dealt with this issue; has ignored calls for the establishment of a statewide tax commission re-sponsible for creating real tax reform, and in-stead has chosen to debate superficial political solutions such as referendums.<P>Rep. Pettit draws a correlation between teacher strikes and the rising cost of education and alleged failing results. There is absolutely no research to sustain that allegation. As to failing results, certainly there is a need to improve our public schools but indeed there is factual information that argues to the continuing progress and success of our public schools.<P>Rep. Pettit's so-called solution is obviously politically correct for it is directed toward teachers only. Incredibly there is not one mention of the other party to negotiations -- namely the school board. Nor is there any acknowledgment of the continuing success in bargaining in that over 90% of the contracts are settled without a crisis.<P>A responsible solution to eliminating all strikes embraces the needs of all parties and is based on fairness as well as equity. This will occur when leadership prevails over punishment, bashing and political correctness.<P>-- Robert C. Baldis, assistant executive director, Allegheny County/ Pittsburgh PSEA-NEA
<hr>
<font size =+2><B>Giving Credit</B></font size><BR>
It's nice to see that Executive Report is now online, and with a very attractive interface. But I thought it was curious that Jane Black's very learned "Editor's Note" [December 1994] included no mention of the fact that graduate students from Carnegie Mellon assisted you in creating a World Wide Web site for the magazine. Why not?<P>-- William Thomas, director of publications, Carnegie Mellon University GSIA, Pittsburgh, bt16@andrew.cmu.edu
<P>
<I>Editor's note: We were remiss. The graduate students in Daniel Boyarski's communication and design programs at CMU who helped design Executive Report Online include: Molly Bigelow, Michael Cytrynowicz, Shannon Ford, Anne Humphreys, Christopher Myers and Bill Thomas. We appreciate their hard work.</I>
<HR>

