<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <FONT SIZE=+2><B>The Next Monopoly to Fall: Electricity</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Peter C. Christensen</i>
<HR>
On the heels of successes in the airline, telecommunications and natural gas industries, the electricity industry is undergoing fundamental structural changes that will introduce competition to the last of the major "natural" monopolies. Savvy executives are learning all they can about the issue, recognizing that competition will mean significant savings for the industrial consumers who are ahead of the curve.<P>What is ultimately at stake here is whether a retail electricity consumer should be able to shop an open market for electricity rather than be forced to purchase power from the local, native utility. Since the end-user must still be physically interconnected to local distribution and transmission lines, the local utility would have to transmit, or "wheel," power purchased from another supplier to the end-user. The concept of retail wheeling has shaken this normally static industry and will forever change the way consumers buy electricity.<P>California has been leading the charge for retail wheeling. I chaired a conference there in December at which a commissioner of the California Public Utilities Commission outlined its proposal to implement retail wheeling for large industrial consumers by 1996 and for residential customers by 2002. That means that California industries could begin realizing the benefits of accessing an open market for electricity in one year. It's clear that this will attract business to the West Coast. In an illustration of competitive forces at work, I expect a domino effect as other states implement retail wheeling to compete with California.<P>Where is Pennsylvania? The state Public Utility Commission has instituted an investigation of competition in the electricity industry and the state General Assembly has held hearings on the issue.<P>But it is only a matter of time. Providing power from heavily regulated monopolies has worked rather well since the days of the large electricity trusts in the 1930s. We all assumed that electricity was a natural monopoly in which economics of scale applied. However, in the 1980s, federal legislation, intended to maximize industrial energy efficiency and promote alternative generation resources, spurred the development of the independent power industry. It was an overwhelming success.<P>Today, non-utility developers are responsible for more new generation than the regulated public utilities. One survey of electric utility executives found that 44% of all U.S. utilities will never build another generation facility. So much for natural monopolies with respect to power production.<P>The nation's transmission grid and local distribution systems, however, are still natural monopolies. Nobody wants multiple power lines running down the street. Because the major utilities control these systems, consumers do not have access to the newly competitive generation market. The Energy Policy Act of 1992 requires utilities to transmit power to wholesale buyers, such as other utilities, municipal electric companies and rural electric cooperatives, from any supplier the wholesaler chooses.<P>But where does that leave the retail consumer? Powerless for the time being. Federal law leaves implementation of retail wheeling up to the states. As I've pointed out, some have been more vigorous than others.<P>Why the drive for retail wheeling? Because electricity prices are too high in many parts of the country. This is especially evident in those areas where a high-priced utility is adjacent to a low-priced utility. This disparity will not exist in a competitive market. In California, for example, the average industrial rate is 7.6 cents per kilowatt hour; while in neighboring Oregon, the average rate is only 3.2 cents per kilowatt hour. These high rates are especially debilitating to electricity-intensive industries, such as steel, aluminum, oil and chemical.<P>Moreover, they are debilitating to California's efforts, and those of other states, to attract and keep such industries. U.S. industry is rightfully demanding that its electricity suppliers face the same competitive pressures that it does.<P>The success in restructuring the natural gas industry has shown that the market can be trusted to meet the needs of society while pushing costs down and increasing quality of service. Although many local distribution companies warned otherwise, even residential gas prices are lower now than they were before competition was introduced.<P>Of course, many utilities are fighting retail wheeling, and the sheer technical complexity of the electricity infrastructure is slowing down restructuring. Too few end-users understand the industry well enough to properly prepare for the competition to come.<P>However, the door to the free market has been opened, and as history repeatedly has proven, there is no turning back. If properly structured and regulated, competition is a good thing. It's the electricity industry's turn to face this reality and your turn to benefit.  
<P>
<i>Peter C. Christensen is manager of energy projects for Strategic Energy Ltd. of Pittsburgh. </i>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
