<HEAD>
<TITLE> People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.PMN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>Thomas S. Joseph III</B></FONT>
<I> By Don Rebel </I>
<HR>
Occupation: Founder and president of Bookminders Inc.<BR>
Age: 34<BR>
Family Life:  Joseph and his wife, Andrea, live in Whitehall.<BR>
Hometown:  Allison Park<BR>
Education:  Bachelor of science degree in engineering from Carnegie Mellon University<BR>
Hobbies: Skiing and playing uncle to his nieces and nephews<BR>
Last Vacation & Where:  Riding up the coast of California in the summer of 1994<BR>
Favorite Book or Quote:  "The Works of Nations" by Robert Reich<BR>
<HR>
After working for nine years for Westinghouse and Cimflex Teknowledge Corp., Joseph capitalized on the outsourcing craze by putting a twist on home-based businesses: He founded a bookkeeping company where the employees work from home.<P>"It was kind of by accident," he says. "My father needed a bookkeeper for his construction company, so I tried to save him some money."<P>Joseph decided in 1991 to invest significant time and money into his concept. After 18 months of market research, installing systems and training a staff, the company was set to go. "We used some data clients who are friends of the family as guinea pigs early on," Joseph says. "By the time we took it out into the market in 1993, we were ready."<P>Bookminders now has seven "offices" and links each employee via online services, fax, phone and voice mail.<P>"Like any business, we had to do a lot of public relations," he says. "We also had to let accountants know we're not a threat to them. We're not a CPA firm. We handle bookkeeping; we don't do taxes. Our responsibility to our clients is to work with both the customer and their accounting firm."<P>Despite providing seminars on virtual corporations and how businesses can improve through outsourcing, Joseph's focus is on Bookminders, which has tripled its revenues each year since 1992.<P>"We will continue to refine our customers' needs and our prices," Joseph says, "but we finally have enough in place to concentrate on growth. Someday, I'd like to expand into new geographic markets."
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
