<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> ERIndex </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a><P>
<HR>
Continued highs for the ER Index's two leading stocks, Res-pironics and Fore Systems, as well as the first signs of life from Astrotech in a while helped offset sizeable declines in MK Rail, Legent and USX -- U.S. Steel, and helped the index to a 1.19% gain for the month ended Feb. 10. Meanwhile, the S&P 500 gained 3.32%. Our basket of 30 local stocks continues to lead the S&P by a wide margin however, 8.09% vs. 4.39%, since we kicked off the index on Aug. 15.
<DL>
<LI>Fore Systems, which has risen almost 150% since August to $75.25 per share, announced net income for its quarter ended Dec. 31, 1994, was $2.1 million or 15 cents per share vs. $701,000 or 6 cents per share for the same period a year ago. The Warrendale-based designer and manufacturer of ATM-based networking products saw total revenue climb to nearly $21 million in the quarter, up from slightly more than $7.2 million last year. The company has announced a joint venture with global telecommunications giant Northern Telecom. Fore has also declared a 2-for-1 stock split.
<LI>Respironics gained 18% for the month, closing at $32.75 per share. The Murrysville-based company reported higher than expected earnings for its second fiscal quarter ended Dec. 31. Net income climbed 31% to a record $2.7 million or 31 cents per share vs. $2.06 million or 24 cents per share in the year-earlier period. Revenue for the respiratory therapy company rose 28% to $23.9 million, from $18.6 million for the quarter.
<LI>And Astrotech, whose stock has been relatively quiet since September, gained more than 20% to $3.31 per share on the news that first fiscal quarter income from continuing operations jumped to $659,000 or 7 cents per share vs. $227,000 or 3 cents per share for the comparable period last year. Revenues for the three months ended Dec. 31 rose to $24.9 million from $11.5 million. The company is finally beginning to see some meaningful growth in its core petrochemical and refinery markets. Astrotech also announced its intent to acquire Starco Inc., a privately held storage tank manufacturer outside of Dallas.
<LI>On the downside, MK Rail got whacked again, falling more than 27% in the month to $7.38 per share. The company, 65% owned by Morrison Knudsen, has been caught up in the tragic saga of William Agee, who was recently ousted as Knudsen's chairman and CEO. With the Boise, Idaho-based majority owner in financial disarray, investors are treating the two companies as if they are one, which we believe is unfair. Mike Farrell, MK Rail's CEO, says the locomotive remanufacturing business is extremely healthy and a recent visit to the Braddock Motor Coils division seemed to indicate that. Also, Farrell maintains that much of MK Rail's recent problems stem from decisions that were made by Knudsen people while they ran his company.
<LI>Despite reporting a banner year in 1994, and a rosy outlook from Chairman Charles Corry, investors sold off shares of USX -- U.S. Steel, mainly on interest rate fears. The nation's largest steelmaker, U.S. Steel reported it made $201 million or $2.35 per share last year, its first annual profit since 1990. For his part, Corry expects 1995 will be a strong year, with tonnage about the same, but accompanied by higher selling prices.
<LI>Legent was down more than 18% in the month, to $29.63, as the company turned in another subpar earnings performance. Product sales for the most recent quarter weren't even close to expectations. Clearly, new CEO Jerre Stead has his work cut out for him. Mainframe-related sales still account for about two-thirds of Legent's revenues.
<LI>It looks as if Allegheny Ludlum Corp. has bounced back from a   10-week labor strike in early 1994. Fourth quarter revenues for the specialty steelmaker were up 22% to $328 million and operating income rose 63% to $34 million.
<LI>Sam Forman retired as American Eagle Outfitters president and CEO. Forman was the architect of American Eagle's turnaround from a $9.2 million loss in fiscal 1992 to a $6.6 mil-lion profit in fiscal 1994. Roger Makefield, the company's top merchant, will take over as president, and Robert G. Lynn, former CEO of the $9 billion F.W. Woolworth Corp., as COO.
<LI>Crown American Realty Trust added the Wyoming Valley Mall in Wilkes-Barre and Middletown Mall in Fairmont, Va., to its portfolio in January. Both were already being managed by the REIT. Meanwhile, Crown continues to gear up for the opening of seven new May Co. department stores at its properties. While you're waiting for the May store to hit the financials, Crown's dividend yields 10.5%.
</DL>
<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.</I>
