</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Money Matters</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.MM.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Prepare Your Return Carefully</B> </FONT SIZE> <BR>
<i> By Paul M. Matvey</i><p>
<HR>
The art of wondering may have worked for Socrates and Plato, but not everyone should be left alone on a philosophical quest. Take the San Diego office of the IRS, for example. West Coast IRS agents wondered why many local attorneys did not file their tax returns. As a result, audits may never be the same again.
<P>
In the course of the inves-tigation, agents discovered attorneys in small firms manipulated their books to avoid paying taxes. Further investigation revealed that personal injury attorneys had the highest   rate of noncompliance in their profession.
<P>
The IRS learned it could collect greater sums in tax, penalties and interest if its agents knew how attorneys ran their businesses. Therefore, the IRS developed specific tax guidelines and then trained agents how to perform comprehensive audits of attorneys.
<P>
A 40+ page book instructs auditors how to do asset searches, going as far as contacting the Division of Motor Vehicles and asking for licenses issued for cars and boats. The manual also instructs the agents to look for anything else of value compatible with the attorney's lifestyle to see what has been skimmed off the income. In addition, the guidelines inform auditors how attorneys collect payments, how they keep records, how they run their offices and what professional organizations they belong to.
<P>
Examiners using specialty guidelines on attorneys successfully collected more taxes than what the computer-selected returns normally netted. With such good results, the IRS developed Market Segment Special-ization Program audit guidelines for other industries.<P>Guidelines are intensively subject-specific. They include:
<DL>
<LI> how to gather documents from third parties;
<LI> sources for industry books, trade associations and newsletters;
<LI> glossary of industry terms, and
<LI> statistics, data, tax laws and relevant court cases.
</DL>
Examiners trained to audit cab drivers, for example, learn how meters work, how cab companies are set up and how to reconstruct income based on mileage and gasoline prices.
<P>
Examiners working with gas retailers are instructed to do a little sleuthing on their own before scheduling the first interview by gathering third-party records from dis-tributors. Does the retailer own or operate a convenience store? Is gas delivered by unmarked tankers?
<P>
Detailed information is the most important prerequisite for an MSSP examiner. Some CPAs worry that during the guideline creation state, the information may have been slanted for or against the taxpayer. For example, based on its studies so far, the IRS tends to believe that pop music stars handle their businesses better than lawyers. Why? Because the musicians tend to employ competent business managers. According to the guidelines, musicians account for cash payments in their gross income, their contracts reflect income, and royalty agreements, press or distribution deals reveal other financial opportunities. Before MSSP, an examiner might not know to ask an artist about such agreements.
<P>
Although MSSP has its flaws, there are advantages to the new program. Your tax return is less likely to be selected for an examination if it falls within industry standards. In the past, the computer compared returns by income level and kicked out items that didn't fall into normal categories. Under MSSP, a sales company's entertainment ex-penses would be expected to be higher than a dry cleaner's expenses, even if its taxable income was the same.
<P>
You and/or your CPA will spend less time teaching the IRS examiner the norms of your profession. You'll be less inconvenienced and you may reduce the expenses you formerly paid a CPA to represent you in an IRS audit.
<P>Also, the IRS, in the future, will better understand the impact of tax compliance on a particular group. Since no one has kept statistics by professional groups nationally, all income figures will be measured against the initial study area. These studies may prove inapplicable to other parts of the country until MSSP becomes more refined.Finally, MSSP will help the IRS identify tax evaders and enforce fair taxation practices across the board.<P>So far, the MSSP has identified more than 60 specialties. They include air charters, attorneys, bed and breakfasts, commercial banking associations, construction companies, eating establishments, the entertainment industry, the grocery industry, healthcare institutions, insurance, plastic surgeons, real estate companies, taxicab drivers and truck drivers.<P>You're wise to suspect that guidelines have been written, or will be written, for your specialization. Call your CPA and ask if the IRS has MSSP segment guidelines for your industry. What should you be aware of? Are there particular areas of concern the IRS will be looking for in your field?<P>Overall, MSSP is a good concept. If the IRS exercises care in writing and implementing market segment guidelines, they will become much more efficient.   <P>Paul M. Matvey is a CPA and tax  partner with Schneider Downs & Co. Inc. He is also a contributing editor of "95 Ways You Can Save Taxes in '95."

<hr>
