<HR>
"We're going through an unprecedented period of change in civilization, and not just in the econ-omy. I'm an optimist, and I think we will demonstrate again the power of human beings to raise the standard of living for the whole world."<P>-- Paul O'Neill, CEO and chairman, Alcoa, on WQED's "Does Making Things Matter?"
<HR>
"We are extremely proud of FORE Systems' rapid rise to industry leadership. It is one of the most dramatic spin-off success stories in the university's history and a good example of our contribution to our regional economy."
<P>-- Robert Mehrabian, president, Carnegie Mellon University
<HR>
"GATT has both positive and negative aspects for the state's farmers, but on balance, this agreement is good for Pennsylvania agriculture. Few, if any, agricultural sectors will be negatively affected."<P>-- Milton Hallberg, professor of agricultural economics, Penn State University, on the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
<HR>
"We should take a strong stand against the movement in the inter-national arena to im-pose, in effect, a world energy law."<P>-- B.R. Brown, chairman and CEO, Consol Coal Group Co.
<HR>
"When dealing with environmental issues, the public can no longer be so easily generalized. Companies must deal with the concerns of a panoply of green concerns -- from the volatile eco-warriors [like] Greenpeace, to the more respected and highly sophisticated organizations [like] the Sierra Club and World Wildlife Fund, to the grass-roots, not-in-my-backyard coalitions concerned about their health, their children and their property values."<P>-- Stephen F. Lee, president and owner, Lee & Co.
<HR>
"My ultimate aim is to have the audience walk out of the theater and feel that they've actually done the piece. I want the audience to be gripping and groaning and flying and falling with the dancers -- so that it's an experience and not an event -- something they did, not something they watched."<P>-- Elizabeth Stred, choreographer, Dance Alloy
<HR>
"Organizations which succeed in their objectives help to improve the quality of people's lives."<P>-- H.J. Zoffer, dean of the Katz School and the College of Business Administration, University of Pittsburgh
<HR>
"Because PCPE's focus was on the quality of education, and I felt there was need for greater involvement concerning black students, I became involved."<P>-- Emma Lucas, associate professor of social sciences, Carlow College and re-elected president of the Pittsburgh Council on Public Education

<P>"In these tumultuous times, it's easy to become hardened and cynical. But within the realm of The Salvation Army, I see hope, a sense of stewardship and a deep love and concern for all mankind."<P>-- Col. Paul M. Kelly, divisional commander, The Salvation Army of Western Pennsylvania
<HR>
"All families today must be strong enough to deal with the awesome responsibilities of making and keeping the family healthy. The concerns for our youth, single parents, and social and economic inequality issues can be better and more strategically addressed when the family unit is healthy. When we realize we are part of the same family, then we'll come up with better solutions."<P>-- Esther L. Bush, president and CEO, Urban League of Pittsburgh Inc.
