<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Special Supplement </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>
<b><FONT SIZE=+2> Economic Development Profile: Washington County: Where the Grass is Greener</FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b>Better taxes, cheaper utilities and greener pastures continue to cause a migration to Washington County</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Mark Sullivan</i>
<P>
The Rib Cook-Off isn't the only thing that moved to Washington County re-cently: The area has been pulling businesses from Allegheny County like a magnet. "Companies are relo-cating from Allegheny County because Washington County has a lower tax structure. Also, you can save on utilities," says Richard Conrady, executive director of the Greater Wash-ington Chamber of Commerce and the Washington Industrial Development Corp.<P>Washington County offers a different quality of life than Allegheny. "Businesses want to satisfy their employees," Conrady says. They can do so in Wash-ington County because the area offers a rural or an urban lifestyle within a 30-minute commute. Also, easy access to the Pittsburgh International Airport makes further travel that much easier.<P>With the success of South-pointe and the plans for the Mon Valley/Fayette Expressway start-ing to take shape, Washington County is gearing up for some long-term growth. "We're looking to get into position for future growth," says Neil D. Bassi, vice president of Charleroi Federal Savings. "The year 2000 is only five years away and we want to be ready."<P>It's not as though people are expecting overnight miracles, however. It will take a number of years before these projects cause a noticeable increase in jobs.<P>Unfortunately, current long-range planning can't do much to fill the void created by the closing of the Cooper Power Systems plant in Canonsburg last November. (See sidebar on page 24.) <P>Metro Petrosky Jr., chairman of the county commissioners, tries to take everything in stride. "Losing Cooper was quite a blow and it serves as a warning. When you work on economic devel-opment you can never lose sight of something like that." But Petrosky points to Southpointe as a boon.<P>Petrosky replaces Frank Mascara, who was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in November. As a county commis-sioner, Mascara was a promoter of the Mon Valley/Fayette Express-way, and Petrosky plans to follow in his footsteps with the other commissioners, Joseph Ford and governmental newcomer Melvin Bassi, president of Charleroi Federal Savings.<P>The expressway has been in the works for over 25 years, says Richard Webb, executive director of the Mon Valley Renaissance    at California University of Pennsylvania. "The section between routes 70 and 40 has been completed for a few years and has had a great effect on California University," says Webb.<P>The Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission plans to extend       the expressway north to the Pittsburgh International Airport and south to Morgantown, W. Va. The finished product will be a 65-mile toll road. Progress, however, has been slowed by court battles. "The expressway would be great for the county," says Paul Stiffle-mire, director of the Center for Entrepreneurial Development at Washington & Jefferson College, "but no one wants it in [his or her] backyard."<P>Some fear that the expressway will ruin existing businesses along Route 51. Proponents say that although the expressway might take away from a few small businesses, the growth it spurs elsewhere will make up for it.<P>Stifflemire says infrastructure is crucial to economic develop-ment and that the expressway will bring the water and sewage systems needed to attract new business.Petrosky hopes that the work on the expressway will begin in the Fayette area in 1996. He adds that "the key to economic devel-opment is access to the airport and Allegheny County. The exit off of I-79 for Southpointe is the icing on the cake for that project. It is one of the first interchanges built off an interstate in this area in a long, long time."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Electronic Highway: </B></font size> Mike Brna, director of entre-preneurial assistance at California University, says the big news      in Washington County is the increased use of electronic com-merce. "Using computers for pur-chasing, placing orders and accessing business information has helped give companies a competitive advantage," Brna says.Businesses who do contract work with the government now have to do everything electron-ically thanks to a mandate issued by President Clinton.<P>The university has been working with the Government Agency Coordination Office to help local businesses learn the ropes. GACO aids companies by pro-viding seminars and technical support on navigating through the maze of government specifications.<P>Regional businesses have received some $292 million in government and export contracts through the university's economic development programs. Currently, GACO has more than 100 clients in Washington County.<P>California University has also brought technology into the classroom, or make that, out of the classroom. Recently, it launched a distance learning program whereby anyone with a high school diploma or GED can take a three credit course without ever setting foot on campus. The first class, parenting, is broadcast two nights a week on Channel 29. Students can talk to faculty members on the phone via a toll-free number.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Good News for Banking: </B></font size> If financial institutions were getting grades, Washington Coun-ty's two largest would receive As. Both thrifts had good years in 1994. Washington Federal Savings Bank, the largest locally owned thrift in the county, reported record levels in assets, deposits and loans.<P>Washington Federal recently installed a local area network. The LAN helps the bank provide better customer service by connecting all the offices to the data processing center via satellite.<P>Richard White, bank president, expects the good times to continue. "The increasing demand for business loans seems to indicate a higher level of confidence and perhaps a need to provide for higher levels of anticipated business activity in 1995," he says.<P>Charleroi Federal Savings Bank is also coming off a banner year according to Neil Bassi. "Our net profits exceeded last year and our assets grew to $232 million in 1994," he says.<P>Retained earnings jumped to 13.5%, double the minimum requirement. Bassi reports a 40% increase in the checking account base. In addition, the main office in Charleroi has undergone an expansion to prepare for future growth.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Healthcare Update: </B></font size> One of the only things more important than money is health, and healthcare continues to    make up a sizable part of the Washington County economy. Monongahela Valley Hospital is the second largest employer in the county and the major healthcare system in the mid-Mon Valley.<P>In the past year, the hospital expended over $43 million in wages and fringe benefits to its nearly 1,100 employees. It provided almost $5 million for charity care, reduced-rate care, public health education, disease prevention and early detection programs. During the same time, it admitted 11,500 patients and rendered 182,000 outpatient services.<P>The county's largest employer, Washington Hospital, has been busy establishing programs for the youngest members of the county. It is creating an outreach program to provide free health-care to children who are un-insured, under-insured or on Medicaid.<P>In McMurray, Washington Hospital opened a pediatric physical medical center for children with developmental delays. The hospital also acquired the Visiting Nurse Association to provide home healthcare.<P>At the hospital itself, a $21 million patient tower should be completed this summer. It will have three floors with a helipad on top. <P>Canonsburg General hopes to have a 9,200-square-foot out-patient center completed in July. The $1.8 million project is in response to increased outpatient surgeries. The new facility will also be the site for chemotherapy treatments, gastroscopies and pre-surgery testing.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Other News: </B></font size> 
<DL>
<LI>Washington Steel had a good year in 1994. Sales and pro-duction were at record levels. "The only negative occurred during the first part of the year when we had a lot of foreign competition because the economy in Europe was so slow, but now it's getting back to normal levels," says Grant John, company president.<P>John reports that current demand is equal to or higher than last year and imports are down. "We are running at capacity," he says.<P>The steelmaker is spending about $23 million to reduce costs while increasing quality and capacity. "Our employment is flat and we are working hard to improve quality internally. In three years, we hope to produce   a lot more with fewer people," John says.<P>
<LI>The Mon Valley Progress Council in Monessen received a $400,000 grant from the U.S. Department of Human Services to improve a building the council owns in the Donora Industrial Park. The council is working on getting tenants for the 30,000-square-foot building. Work should begin this spring. Funds from the sale or lease of the shell will be used to construct additional buildings.<P>The council also owns property adjacent to the Rostraver Airport that it wants to develop into an airport-related industrial park.   The council serves Washington, Westmoreland, Fayette and Alle-gheny counties.<P>
<LI>Washington Power Co., a subsidiary of Air Products & Chemicals Inc. of Allentown, expects to construct a $260 million power plant in Washington County. The plant, fueled by coal refuse, will be built near the the state's largest coal refuse pile in Robinson.<P>Building the plant will create 700 construction jobs and 70 full-time positions with a $5 million payroll. The otherwise useless refuse will generate enough electricity to power 80,000 customers.<P>
<LI> The Coca-Cola Star Lake Amphitheatre set an attendance record last year with 590,063 visitors and 11 sellouts. The $10 million facility hires 300 to 400 people each summer, many of whom are county residents.<P>
<LI> Washington County will be home to a new golf course community called Pine Oaks. The 426-acre site, which will have an Arnold Palmer-designed course, is in Carroll Township off Route 837 between Donora and Monon-gahela. Plans include 270 housing units. Atlas Construction Co. will build the course for Pine Oaks Development Co.<P>
<LI> The Pennsylvania Trolley Museum in Washington is, after 40 years, becoming a fast growing tourist attraction. During 1994, the museum had 19,000 visitors, a 30% increase over the year before. <P>Also last year, former Gov. Casey set aside $4.3 million for the museum's growth. A 37,000-square-foot Pennsylvania Trans-portation Heritage Center is planned adjacent to Thepitt Manufacturing Co. The center is a joint venture of the Pennsylvania Trolley Museum and the Trans-portation & Technology Museum. A 25,000-square-foot trolley display area is also planned.<P>
<LI> A $16 million justice center will be completed in late July in Washington with room for 258 prisoners. The current facility is over 100 years old and is operating at double its capacity.<P>
<LI> Pittsburgh-based STAT MedEvac, an air medical trans-porter, has established a helicopter base at the Washington County Airport to respond faster to emergencies in Washington and Greene counties, as well as parts of Ohio and West Virginia.<P>
<LI>Jack Underwood, director of industrial development for the Redevelopment Authority of Washington County, reports that $35.8 million has been invested by industries at Southpointe. More than 570 people are employed there. Underwood projects 1,270 employees by the time the project is finished.<P>
</DL>
The eight corporate residents at Southpointe are Accutrex, AEG Automation, AT&T, Bailey Engineers, Chem Steel & Con-struction, Continental Design, Digital Concepts and Mitsubishi. Homedco, Centimark and the Pittsburgh Penguins are awaiting completion of their facilities.<P>But Southpointe isn't all business, Mike Donahie, director of sales and marketing, says. "Our motto is live here, work here and play here." The 600 acres are divided among commercial, resi-dential and recreational uses.<P>Golfers began to tee off at the $9 million Southpointe Golf Club last June, and residents have started moving into the three styles of houses. There are plans for 84 townhomes; 30 are sold and 20 are built. Fifty single-family homes have been planned; 15 are completed with 10 more expected by year's end. Twelve patio homes are in the works. One is finished and occupied, and two are under construction."In order for something like this to work it must be done high class, and everything the Piatts have done has been high class," Donahie says. Jack Piatt, Rod Piatt and Jack Piatt Jr. of Millcraft In-dustries in Washington are the developers of Southpointe. Millcraft includes Millcraft Products, Millcraft Mining, Millcraft Invest-ments, Millcraft Center, Global Travel and The Boyd School.<P><HR>Residential Real Estate Activity<P>Washington County	1993	1994<P>New listings	1,837	2,048<P>Closed/sold	1,240	1,263<P>Dollar volume/closed	$126,688,220	$132,540,823<P>Average price	$102,168	$104,941<P>Source: West Penn Multi List Inc., Pittsburgh<P><HR>County Employment<P>The largest single industry in Washington County is services. The average monthly employment was 63,177 in 1993, not including federal jobs.<P>Industry Average Monthly Employment Services	16,212<P>Retail trade	13,071<P>Manufacturing	12,003<P>Local government	6,326<P>Construction	3,881<P>Transportation and public utilities	3,281<P>Wholesale trade	2,735<P>State government	2,063<P>Finance, insurance and real estate	1,791<P>Mining	1,498<P>Federal government	667<P>Agriculture, forestry and fishing	316<P>Source: Pittsburgh Office of the State Department of Labor & Industry, 1993<P><HR>Washington County At A Glance<P>Industry (excluding federal employees)Total number of industries: 3,697<P>Employees: 55,898<P>Annual Payroll: $961.9 million<P>ManufacturersNumber of manufacturers: 218<P>Employees: 10,948<P>Annual payroll: $267.5 million<P>Steel and Primary MetalsNumber of steel mills: 4<P>Number of foundries and fabricators: 34<P>Employees: 3,470<P>Annual Payroll: $102.9 million<P>Source: Millcraft Industries<P>County ThriftsInstitution	Headquarters	Assets* ($ million)	Deposits ($ million)	Branches<P>Washington Federal Savings	Washington	342.5	307.6	6Charleroi Federal Savings Bank	Charleroi	225.2	196.2	4Slovenian Savings & Loan Association of Canonsburg	Strabane	78.3	67.6	1*As of Dec. 31, 1993Source: R.L. Polk & Co., Nashville, Tenn.(cutlines)(rendering)Architectural firm Apostolou Associates of Pittsburgh designed the $16 million Washington County Justice Center.<P>A state grant of $4.3 million must be matched for the joint venture of the Pennsylvania Trolley and the Transportation & Technology museums to begin. Shown here is one of the many operating trolleys of old that the museum runs.<P>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Energizing the County: </B></font size> AEG Electric Power Systems Inc. is a newcomer to Washington County. The company moved into new digs in Speers last July. AEG-EPS produces dead tank high-voltage circuit breakers, circuit switchers and gas insulated switchgear. It also provides the North American headquarters for its Stuttgart, German-based parent, Daimler-Benz, maker of Mercedes Benz automobiles.AEG-EPS is not to be confused with sister company, AEG Automation, which has consolidated and moved into Southpointe from three locations in Allegheny County. AEG Automation is a systems integrator of complete factory automation systems.<P>AEG-EPS has kept a tight schedule since incorporating in September 1993. After a November groundbreaking, the company received its first order in December and shipped it by April. In May 1994, it received a three-year purchase agreement from Florida Power & Light Co.<P>Michael Kangas, president and CEO of AEG-EPS, says the business has exceeded expectations. "The biggest news has been our acceptance into the marketplace. For a company starting from zero to succeed in serving new customers in the U.S. and international markets so quickly is very pleasing," Kangas says.<P>AEG-EPS has 19 employees and is hoping to hire six more by year's end. "We have ample room for expansion and will do so in the next four years depending on the success in the marketplace," Kangas says.<P>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Cooper's Blooper: </B></font size>Cooper Power Systems in Canonsburg once employed nearly 4,000 workers, but on Nov. 23, 1994, the company closed its doors for the last time. Cooper was the last American factory of its size to build giant power transformers. Other companies that used to build them, such as General Electric, Westinghouse and McGraw-Edison, abandoned the business years ago to pursue more lucrative fields. In the meantime, foreign companies stepped in to fill the void.<P>A number of factors contributed to the fall of Cooper. One was that American utility companies had turned their attention to conservation and efficiency instead of new construction. The trend was fueled in part by the Energy Act of 1992.The closing of Cooper could cause some problems for American utilities down the road. If a sudden need for a transformer develops, a foreign supplier will need six months to build it and several months to ship it.<P>The possibility of a company purchasing the Cooper site and replacing the 800 lost jobs is a long shot, according to Paul Stifflemire, director of the Center for Entre-preneurial Development at Washington & Jefferson College. "If an American company buys the Cooper facility it will most likely bring its own employees. The only hope is to sell it to a foreign company that won't bring a work force with them. But in that case, workers from all over would migrate into the area to compete with Washington County residents," Stifflemire says.<P>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>10 Largest Private Sector Employers: </B></font size> For this ranking, employees of the government, higher education and school districts were excluded.<P>Washington Hospital<P>Monongahela Valley Hospital<P>Washington Steel Corp.<P>84 Lumber Co.<P>Corning Glass Works<P>Jessop Steel<P>Canonsburg General<P>Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp.<P>Giant Eagle Inc.<P>Black Box Corp.<P>Source: Pittsburgh Office of the State Department of Labor & Industry, 1994<P>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Centimark Makes A Mark: </B></font size> Centimark, a commercial and industrial roof contractor, is leaving Bethel Park for Washington County. The company, listed by Engineering News Record as the second largest roof contracting firm in the United States for the last three years, is moving its headquarters to Southpointe.<P>Last year, Centimark eclipsed the $100 million mark for sales and seems poised to take over as the country's No. 1 roofer.<P>Edward B. Dunlap, the CEO who founded the company in 1968 with $1,000 and one employee, has been the guiding force behind Centimark's rise. The move to Southpointe is another step toward the top. "We needed a facility that can accom-modate our future growth," Dunlap says.<P>Centimark employs 120 people in the Pittsburgh area and more than 1,100 nationwide at 50 locations. The company could have moved anywhere but chose Southpointe because it offered the most amenities.<P>Company officials enjoy bringing clients in to see the home office, using professionalism as a selling point. "Roofing hasn't always fit into the corporate mentality. Anybody with a truck and a ladder can call themselves a roofer," says John Bugay, director of marketing communications.<P>"When you walk into McDonald's you know what you're going to get. We're trying to do the same for roofing. We want our customers to see a strong company behind the warrantee. A big problem corporations have had with smaller roofing contractors is that [they] hire someone and two years later when the roof starts to leak the guy is out of business. We want to be the first to have one-stop shopping," Bugay says.<P>With Centimark, developers don't have to deal with a local roofer in each construction area. Centimark handles that and provides post-installation care.Dunlap sees Southpointe as a major plus. "We liked the fact that our out-of-town customers and employees alike would be able to fly into the new airport and drive up to our front door without hitting a traffic light."       
<hr>
