<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<b><FONT SIZE=+2> That's Just the Way It Is </FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b>For African Americans, the regional outlook is bleak.</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Angie Mullig</i>
<hr>
Well they passed a law in '64To give those who ain't got a little moreBut it only goes so farBecause the law don't change another's mindWhen all it sees at the hiring timeIs the line on the color barThat's just the way it is-- B.R. Hornsby  1986 Zappo Music/Bob-A-Lew Songs (ASCAP)In the 30 years since civil rights  and affirmative action legislation supposedly leveled the employment playing field, the economic base that supported southwestern Pennsylvania  has undergone dramatic changes. Gone are the heavy industries that offered opportunities and decent salaries to   those whose skills rested primarily on a strong work ethic. The service-sector industries that have replaced the steel, coal and heavy manufacturing businesses rely on an educated, technologically savvy work force. <P> For many of the area's minorities -- a population made up primarily of African Americans -- the demise of heavy industry slammed the door of opportunity shut. Last-hired, first-fired policies left minorities, who had finally begun to claim their places in the labor force, open to layoffs. The loss of high-paying manufacturing jobs represented the postponement or end of dreams that had been realized by the generation of white workers who had preceded African Americans in the area's manufacturing prosperity: a college education, if not for the employee, for his or her children; comfortable housing; the hope of advancing. <P> The University of Pittsburgh recently issued a report that confirmed what many African Americans have long suspected -- that their community took a disproportionately hard hit when manufacturing withered and that they have not shared equally in the region's slow but steady economic resurrection.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Dreams Deferred: </B></font size> 
Released last October, the study, "Economic Benchmarks: Economic Indices for the City of Pittsburgh and Allegheny County," was commissioned by the county and the Urban Redevelopment Authority of Pittsburgh. Conducted by Pitt's Center for Social and Urban Research, the study is a comprehensive review of historic trends and the current status of the region's economy. <P> Overall, the picture is encouraging. The report cites low unemployment rates, significant job growth, a comfortable standard of living, rapid real per capita personal income growth and above average real wage growth. Employment opportunities in health, business, education and social services have fueled economic development, although that growth is now beginning to slow. <P> But the report notes that for African Americans, the regional out-look is bleak. Census figures for 1990 show that, when ranked with the country's 50 largest metropolitan areas, the region's minorities are plagued with the fourth highest poverty rate, the fifth highest unemployment rate and the fourth largest gap between minority and white poverty rates. African-American unemployment in the city stood at nearly 19%, while unemployment for whites hovered at about 6%. And while the area's whites enjoyed the 13th highest standard of living compared to residents of the nation's largest counties, Pittsburgh's minority population ranked eighth from the bottom in terms of standard of living. <P> The report calls for further study of the disparities between African Americans and whites in employment, income and standard of living. But businesswoman Cathy Williams identifies two interrelated problems: prejudice that bars African Americans from employment opportunities and the lack of role models for African-American youth.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>On Their Own: </B></font size> 
A little more than a year ago, Williams opened her own business. Crowning Glory Unlimited is nestled in the heart of Wilkinsburg's shopping district and is the fruit of Williams' marketing education and experience and her astute observation of Pitts-burgh's retail market. <P> Williams, 33, holds a degree in consumer affairs with minors in business and sociology from Indiana State University. She combined the fashion sense she honed as department store ready-to-wear buyer and the business acumen she developed as a health insurance executive to research and launch a hat and accessory boutique that recently celebrated its first anniversary debt-free. <P> Williams started her own business after a decade in corporate America convinced her that African Americans are barred from advancement. "If you are African American, you must go out on your own to get ahead," she says. <P> Without rancor, Williams describes some of her corporate experiences. "My first job out of college was as a buyer for a major department store chain. My supervisor told me I was talented and could get ahead -- but I would have to shuck and jive if I wanted to be promoted. <P> "I was the first African American to be hired as a national accounts manager for a particular health insurance corporation," she continues. When senior executives mentioned difficulties in recruiting minorities, Williams began forwarding resumes of qualified acquaintances. "I was called into an office and asked Why the resumes? If you want to work in personnel, it can be arranged. I suggest you concentrate on your job.' It was a nicely smiled threat." <P> Williams left her job after additional incidents -- including an effort to block payment of commissions earned on her accounts -- convinced her of the impossibility of staying. "I didn't want to believe I was a token," she says. "I wanted to believe life is fair, that if you work hard, are honest and have professional integrity, you'll get ahead." <P> It's even tougher for today's youth, who have few role models in the African-American community, Williams says. "In previous generations, profes-sional people stayed in the neighbor-hood and set examples," she says. Today, however, for a host of compli-cated reasons, successful African Americans tend to leave their old communities. "Those left behind are shut out by the system and are either unemployed or pushed into illegal activities."There certainly is an obligation to accept some individual account-ability," she adds. "But there is a pool of African-American men and women, educated and capable, who cannot find entry-level corporate positions." <P> When Russell L. Bynum, owner of Bynums Advertising Service in Pittsburgh, posted an opening for professional communicators, he was nearly overwhelmed with responses. His experience supports Williams' contention that many qualified African Americans are denied employment opportunities. "The talent is there; we found it. But in the communications industry, you'd be hard pressed to walk into an agency and find even 5% minority employees," says Bynum, a man with such a gentle demeanor that it's no surprise to learn he teaches Sunday school. "One of my goals is to run a business that introduces African Americans to this business." <P> When he graduated from La Roche College with a degree in graphic design, Bynum landed a designer's post with an agency. He stuck with the job for more than five years, but in 1984, he "bought a desk and a T-square" and started his own advertising and design business in his home. <P> Bynum and his wife Kathy, a Duquesne University graduate who holds a degree in business administration and marketing, established a number-of-calls-per-day goal and hauled out the phone books. "We worked out of our home for two years," says Bynum, whose agency is now housed in a comfortable downtown office complex. <P> In the 10 years he has operated his agency, Bynum has attracted clients like Integra Bank and Gateway Health Plan. In addition to traditional advertising and marketing services, Bynum also offers special counseling for firms hoping to reach minority consumers. "It's educating the company as well as consumers," Bynum says. "It makes me angry that more ad campaigns are targeted to minorities for products like cigarettes than mortgage services. Everyone is selling something; we just have to convince companies to sell products with real value to minority communities." <P> Bynum's passion is to convince his clients that marketing to minorities means integrating minorities into their corporate structure. "Those companies who realize how demographics are changing are seeking help from firms like ours," Bynum says. He tries to show firms that advertising alone means nothing. When an African American follows up an ad and walks into a bank for a mortgage, the consumer is intimidated if there are no African Americans in key positions. <P> Bynum also wants to put role models back in the African-American community. "African Americans in business must give back," he says. "One of my goals is to introduce people into this business through internship programs."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Building Networks: </B></font size> 
The goal of building networks for African Americans and women is part of Fran McNeal's dream, as well. The founder of Strategic Computer Assistance Inc., McNeal is a 1983 Princeton graduate who worked in healthcare and chemical corporations before launching her computer consulting business. "I left the corporate environment because, as a young person, I was told to sit in a corner and do as I was told," she says. <P> Her fledgling firm landed an important city contract, then branched out to offer training programs in word processing, spreadsheet programs and other computer programs. Originally based in East Liberty, McNeal moved her offices to Riverside Commons, a restored office building complex on the North Side renovated to house businesses owned by women and minorities.Embedded in her company's course offerings are community-sensitive classes for prospective parents and youths who need skills training. McNeal is also an ardent proponent of internships and offers numerous opportunities for young people to learn on-the-job skills before they venture into the competitive work environment."My original goal was to franchise my business; now, I want to establish a more traditional company structure so I can manage and market, rather than conduct training classes," says McNeal. "The idea is to improve the resources I can offer to my customers, because if my business isn't successful, I won't have anything to give back to my community." <P> For Connie Portis, it isn't a matter of giving back to the community. "I am the community," says Portis, founder, owner and president of Renaissance Publications. A decade ago, Portis established her publishing business to "create a voice for the African-American community in Pittsburgh."Renaissance Publications publishes a weekly newspaper, an annual black business directory and Renaissance Too, a magazine that focuses on issues of interest to the minority community. Portis studied mass communications in Washington, D.C., and worked as a public relations consultant for several agencies in the D.C. area before moving back to Pittsburgh. <P> The Pitt report, says Portis, was no surprise. "It's something that we in the African-American community knew," she says. "I hope the majority community will now act and take some ownership in the problem. <P> "There are all kinds of reasons," she continues. "Part of the problem is racism; part is a lack of direction in education; part is a reluctance on the part of the majority to understand what African Americans bring to the table and to see the value of cultural diversity in the work force. Equal opportunity means equal opportunity for everyone," Portis says. "We must have a holistic view and see that differences are positive, not negative. Unfortunately, most African Americans are still fighting to be equal." <P> For entrepreneurs, equality has yet to reach the financial community. In addition to much-publicized reports about prejudice in granting mortgages, the banking industry may be discriminating against minority members seeking business loans. "We went to Pittsburgh's major banks for a loan," says Jacek Ghosh, administrator for Bidco, a nonprofit arm of the Bidwell Training Center that works with entrepreneurs and runs a food service operation. "We were armed with multiyear, multimillion dollar food service contracts for the Carnegie Science Center and the employees' cafeteria at the Pittsburgh International Airport plus a debt-free $7 million facility [the Bidwell Training Center] as security," he says. Bidco was seeking a modest loan to buy equipment for two new food service contracts but was dismissed by the region's leading banks. "There's a whole informal set of presumptions about minority enterprises," says Ghosh. "Minority businesses find it difficult to get capital."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Seeking Balance: </B></font size> 
Not everyone can or should start a business, but for minorities seeking traditional employment, the picture is a complicated mix of economics, attitudes and broad-based social issues. Rich Stanizzo, business manager of the Pittsburgh Building & Construction Trades Council, says his organization has struggled to balance opportunity, jobs and necessary skills. <P> The council represents 26 unionized construction trade groups, including carpenters, electricians, plumbers and iron workers. Apprentice programs in these trades pay well, averaging $8 to $10 per hour during an apprentice period that includes free schooling. After completing a four- to five-year apprenticeship program, workers become journeymen union members and can anticipate wages from about $15 to $20 per hour.All apprentice program openings are posted through area job banks, schools and minority community organizations. Stanizzo says he is puzzled by the relatively low percentage of minority youth who apply for apprenticeships. "I can't even hazard a guess," he says. "We do our best to notify the minority community, and I just don't know why we're not getting more applicants." <P> But there's one thing Stanizzo is sure of -- the segment of the applicant pool that can pass the basic apprenticeship test has shrunk noticeably in the last decade. Those applying for union apprenticeships must be able to pass a basic math and language skills test, and fewer and fewer applicants are able to do so, Stanizzo says. "Young people just aren't graduating with basic skills. I believe it's a larger social issue," he says. "There's much more stress and pressure on parents and children today, and that's reflected in what's happening in our educational system." <P> Stanizzo's assessment is backed by the Pitt report, which cites low reading and math skill levels among Pittsburgh's public school students as a "major disadvantage" for local economic development.Jesse Fiefe, vice president of operations at the Bidwell Training Center, echoes Stanizzo's concerns. "We're picking up school system problems," says Fiefe. "We have high school graduates who are reading at a fourth grade level -- they can't begin to compete." <P> The Bidwell Training Center has its origins in a grass-roots community effort in 1968. The goal was to equip low-income and minority group members with skills that would gain them entry into the work force. Center directors launched an ambitious fund-raising campaign in 1984; the state agreed to match the $3.5 million raised, and a state-of-the-art, 62,000-square-foot training center opened in 1986. <P> Fiefe, who holds a degree in political science and history from the University of Pittsburgh, has been with the center for more than 20 years. Operating funds for the nonprofit center come from various state and federal agencies and from contracts with corporations. The Bidwell Training Center has developed into a model of what can be accomplished when industry, government and community sectors work together. <P> Healthcare, a booming industry that's now leveling off in the region, has supported several Bidwell programs, Fiefe says. "For example, Thrift Drug came to us and asked if we could train pharmacy technicians," says Fiefe. Thrift provided financial, educational and technical support for a pharmacy technician training program and made a commitment to hire Bidwell graduates. Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania made a similar commitment to a medical claims processor training program; both programs are boasting a 70% placement rate. <P> Bidwell also offers training for medical transcriptionists, medical secretaries, chemical laboratory technicians, information sciences and culinary technicians. "We identify needs and build programs to meet those needs; we're very flexible," says Fiefe. Graduates from Bidwell Center training programs typically land jobs with starting wages of $6 to $10 per hour and full benefits. "Our programs offer careers, not Band-Aids," Fiefe says. "And I think the corporate community is making an effort; we  just have to help applicants develop the skills." <P> But giving people the skills needed for today's job market is becoming an increasingly difficult task. Remediation, says Fiefe, is becoming the rule, not the exception, and nonprofit organizations like Bidwell must compete with other educational facilities for funds. "Colleges are tied into the state budget. We don't get that kind of money," Fiefe says. "But the government expects to take people from welfare rolls to employment -- it can't be done unless government recognizes the kind of contributions nonprofit educators like Bidwell make to the economy and community."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>It's the Attitude, Stupid: </B></font size> 
In December, Pittsburgh Mayor Tom Murphy announced he would steer a larger share of city contracts to women and minorities by expanding the office that monitors compliance with the city's affirmative action policy. The compliance office will also be charged with monitoring professional service contracts and contracts awarded by quasi-independent city authorities. The goal, says Murphy, is to see that at least 25% of city contracts are awarded to minority-owned firms. <P> The mayor's move echoes strategies recently announced by major firms. Bell Atlantic Co., for example, recently hosted a trade fair for minority- and women-owned businesses interested in winning supply contracts from Bell. Flagstar Cos. Inc., corporate parent of Denny's -- stung by a flurry of racial discrimination charges, worked with the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People to develop a plan that would put ownership of Denny's franchises into the hands of minority owners. <P> But large-scale corporate strategies are less important than the attitudes of those who make hiring decisions. "Affirmative action is a joke," says Williams. "Corporations will tell you that 12% of their workers are members of minority groups -- but where are they? At entry-level, low-paying jobs, for the most part. And they're systematically blocked from advancing." <P> Portis says that all sectors in the region -- private, public and political -- must make a commitment to equal opportunity from the top down, and corporations must respond to the inequalities in opportunity. "I hire African Americans," she says, bluntly. Those in the position to affect hiring practices must address the imbalance, she insists. "If that means hiring only African Americans until the work force is balanced, then that's what needs to be done -- and you can quote me."  


