<p>
<b><FONT SIZE=+2> Vocational Rehabilitation Center Mulach and Compton Awards 1995</FONT></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b></FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>Compiled By Teresa K. Flatley</i>
<hr>

Each year, the Vocational Rehabilitation Center in Pittsburgh presents awards to two people who have provided leadership to others in the business community on behalf of people with disabilities.These awards are the Joseph F. Mulach Jr. Award, to recognize an individual who has helped make life more meaningful for people with disabilities, and the James F. Compton Humanitarian Award, which recognizes the efforts of a chairman, president or CEO (or those of his company) in improving the quality of life for people with disabilities through enhanced employment opportunities.The Mulach award was established to honor the former VRC board chairman, philanthropist and indus-trialist for his determination and commitment to the VRC. <P> Mulach, who is 88, joined the VRC board in 1962 and served three terms as chairman. He continues to serve on the board in an advisory capacity.Mulach's special leadership as chairman came at a very critical time and led to the construction of the present VRC facility on Forbes Avenue, which dramatically changed the course of the association's growth. <P> Past Mulach award recipients include John T. Hoover, Abraham J. Twerski, Vincent A. Sarni, Linda A. Dickerson, Douglas Danforth, Leonard C. Staisey, Ginny Thornburgh and Robert Dale Lynch.The Compton award was estab-lished in 1992 following the VRC board chairman's death. The award acknowl-edges James F. Compton's own desire to honor top executives in the business community for their leadership role in providing opportunities to people with disabilities. <P> Compton, himself a businessman, served nearly 10 years on the VRC board of directors, including two years as vice chairman and two years as chairman. During his tenure as chairman, the VRC was undergoing tremendous change and transition. He gave generously of his time and resources, and played a crucial and visionary role as he guided the VRC to financial stability and positioned the agency for the future. <P> Past Compton Award recipients are Wesley W. von Schack, Eugene J. Barone and Robert Mehrabian.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>People: The Greatest Resource </B></font size> <BR>
By John E. McGrady Jr.<BR>
Because no two people are alike, the Vocational Rehabilitation Center has always adapted its services to meet the needs of each and every consumer who comes through its door. <P> The VRC does this because it shares the long-range vision that western Pennsylvania business leaders have long understood: This area's greatest asset is its people, and the wise person will use that asset to the best advantage.Every day companies in this area recommit themselves to helping those with disabilities which ultimately helps all of us who live in this community.The ongoing support the VRC receives from the business community makes many things possible, but maybe the best thing it provides is independence to those who might not otherwise enjoy what many of us take for granted. The VRC allows people to make their own choices and then supports those choices so that they become a reality. <P> All of us in the community should constantly be searching for more ways to help people with disabilities because in the end, we all benefit from this area's greatest resource -- its people. <P> John E. McGrady Jr. is the retired senior vice president of provider affairs of Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania. A member of the VRC board since 1988, McGrady also serves on the boards of numerous other organizations serving people with special needs. He is currently chairman of the Vocational Rehabilitation Center's board.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>A Job Well Done </B></font size> <BR>
By Robert J. Mather<BR>
For the past 67 years, the Voca-tional Rehabil-itation Center has been helping its consumers experience the sense of accomplishment that comes from a job well done as it prepares people for their futures through retraining and job placement.Last year we helped 1,200 people with disabilities experience this same sense of accomplishment others often take for granted. <P> More consumers were served at the VRC last year than ever before while at the same time placements for competitive employment also increased. <P>Consumers earned more and worked more hours than the year before. This was accomplished even though the total number of non-paid training hours decreased. <P> All of these facts reflect back to the people who help the VRC perform its job, including two men we are honoring this year: Edward V. Randall Jr., this year's Compton Award winner, and Fred Rogers, the Mulach Award winner. <P> We are pleased to acknowledge the tremendous work these two men have done for people with disabilities. They have been tireless advocates for those with disabilities and their efforts have broadened the horizons for others. <P> We would like to express our sincere gratitude to the business community for helping us find placements for our consumers, and to the greater community which has always given us its generous support. <P> Our newly adopted mission statement states that the VRC will continue its unique and innovative community leadership role of assisting persons with disabilities or other special needs to achieve dignity through independent living and productive employment opportunities. <P> Those with disabilities who are not employed make up the largest group in the unemployed population. In the Pittsburgh area alone, there are an estimated 34,000 people with disabilities. More than half of these people are unemployed. <P> Statistics such as these show us that we have a long way to go to prepare all of the people who need our help for their future by retraining them and placing them in productive, fulfilling jobs. <P> But the efforts of people like Ned Randall and Fred Rogers make our job a little easier. For that, we thank them. <P> The VRC was the first rehabilitation facility in Pennsylvania and one of the first in the nation to be accredited by the Commission of Accreditation of Reha-bilitation Facilities, which  accredited the VRC in seven vocational areas.We work closely with each of our consumers, becoming familiar with his or her skills, attitudes and habits so that after retraining, our consumers have been matched with placements offering the highest possibility of success, both for the consumer and our business clients. <P> The only way we at VRC can know if our services are genuinely meeting the needs of our consumers is to ask. So we did that, and our consumers told us that last year VRC met or exceeded their needs, a true vote of confidence. <P>We only have to look at our financial statement from last year to know that the VRC is a well-managed organization, showing an excess of public support and revenue over expenses, an efficiency level we have achieved time and time again. <P> That tells us that we are successfully adapting to ongoing changes in revenue support and to the needs of our consumers, and our goal of striving to continuously improve is being realized. <P> In fact, every VRC department, including vocational evaluation, work adjustment, work activities, skills practice, supported employment and job placement services, exceeded its service goals last year. <P> Last year, the VRC received a 5.4% increase in allocations and contributor choice pledges from the United Way after earning high scores from the organization's volunteer service review. <P> We also want to thank the community for making our "Challenges and Triumphs" capital campaign a success, the results of which were much needed renovations to the center to help us better serve our consumers. As the capital campaign draws to an end, we will continue to implement other necessary improvements to the center in 1995. <P> Robert J. Mather is president and CEO of the Vocational Rehabilitation Center.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>1995 James F. Compton Humanitarian Award Winner </B></font size> <BR>
Edward V. Randall Jr., this year's James F. Compton Humanitar-ian Award winner, doesn't know the exact date when he began his commit-ment to help people with disabilities but "it's been a lot of my life," he says. <P> Randall, the presi-dent and CEO of PNC Bank in Pittsburgh, is also chairman of the PNC Bank Foundation, which is responsible for donating millions of dollars throughout PNC Bank Corp.'s markets. <P>Each year, the Compton award is given to a president, chairman of the board or CEO for his or her efforts or those of the company, to improve the quality of life for people with disabilities through enhanced employment opportunities.Randall has spent his career searching for ways to help others help themselves because he believes that will eventually result in a better world for all of us.After starting with Pittsburgh National Bank in 1964 as director of personnel, it didn't take long for Randall to become aware of what the Vocational Rehabilitation Center was doing for people with disabilities.  He began to look at what could be done at the bank to help those with disabilities find productive employment.Working with the VRC, Randall was able to place several individuals in positions at the bank, which eventually led to these employees learning and performing other jobs which were then opened up to them. PNC Bank continues the association with VRC to this day. <P>His interest in tapping into the diversity of people has led to advantages for the bank and the community through affirmative action, community develop-ment, affordable housing and by provid-ing employment opportunities for people with disabilities. <P>In 1994, PNC Bank was named VRC Employer of the Year after the bank requested and used 80 people to help set up files at its western loan center. At the conclusion of the project, five individuals were asked to stay on at the loan center, and some are still employed there.PNC Bank also arranged a tour of its operational facilities for VRC repre-sentatives at the end of last year to determine if there might be additional employment opportunities for people with disabilities. <P>Further, PNC Bank has used VRC-associated workshops to assist in a variety of projects over the years. <P>Randall strongly believes those who hold company positions with the power to make things happen should do just that. In this way, he feels, they are telling their employees that someone else cares about what is happening in the community and is willing to help. <P> Company officers need to emphasize the "human side of the enterprise," Randall says, not stopping with providing an employment opportunity but striving to ensure that the work place is user friendly for those with disabilities."Once you've sat and talked with someone with a disability who only asks for a helping hand to become an independent member of society, you have to accept the challenge to go out and do something," Randall says.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>1995 Joseph F. Mulach Jr. Award Winner</B></font size> <BR>
Mister Rogers has been a television friend to millions of children for 28 seasons. But "grow-ing people of all ages," as he says, benefit from what he has to say as well.Fred Rogers, a Pitts-burgh area native and creator of "Mister Rogers' Neighborhood," is the Joseph F. Mulach Jr. Award recipient for 1995. <P> Each year the Mulach award winner is chosen by the Vocational Rehabilitation Center's board of directors to recognize an individual who has helped make life more meaningful for people with disabilities. <P> Speaking slowly and directly, Mister Rogers talks with his young friends during their television visits, his caring voice having special meaning for children who may feel they have no friends because they are different in some way from others. <P>Mister Rogers tells them again and again how special they are. He tells them he likes them just the way they are. And they believe him, proven with letters he receives from parents of children who have made remarkable strides over the years of watching the program. <P> What a gift he gives to children who may feel undeserving of friendship or love because of a disability; to children who are afraid they will be rejected by other children. <P>Mister Rogers' message of individual worth comes across every day in his program, but he considers his message only a basic foundation on which to build. <P>It's why he named his company Family Communications. He hopes people will expand his message with family and friends, but also with the other people they come into contact with each day, including people who have disabilities. <P>"Mister Rogers' Neighborhood" has positively introduced many people with disabilities to this country's children. Each of these appearances is part of the library of television visits aired annually, showing children these guests are an essential part of his neighborhood just as they are of ours. <P>Guests to the TV show have included people with hearing and vision impairments, Down Syndrome, spina bifida, and those who use wheelchairs. Mister Rogers asks his guests questions many of us may are too uncomfortable to ask. So instead we may avoid talking about the person's disability and often, we may simply avoid contact with that person. <P>By talking openly and respectfully with his guests, Mister Rogers shows children their curiosity is not a bad thing. He opens up a world to them where everyone is different and those differ-ences should be embraced. He affirms each person's self-worth. <P> Mister Rogers' favorite quotation is from "The Little Prince." It reads: "What's essential is invisible to the eye." In other words, it's what's inside that matters most.As he visits daily with children across the country, he reaffirms that belief. It's a foundation to build on.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Fred Lang: Consumer of The Year </B></font size> <BR>
In the three years of rehabilitation that Fred Lang underwent after a serious accident in 1987, he had a lot of time to think about his life. <P> He thought about why he had survived the accident which left his body broken and in agony. He thought about how his life was not worth living. He thought about dying. <P> Today, 30 surgeries later, Lang feels that he has been given a new start. He is ready to move on to the dream that he thought would never be realized: owning and operating a landscape business. <P> Lang knows what made the difference in his life during those years of recovery. It was his daughter, Jennifer, now 13. "If it hadn't been for Jennifer, I would have given up. She's been an angel to me." <P>Lang, 44, is this year's recipient of the Leonard Weitzman Consumer of the Year Award. The award was established in 1989 in honor of the VRC's former president who retired after 41 years. <P> The award recognizes the outstanding performance and excellence in the workplace of a person placed by VRC. <P>It would be difficult to imagine Fred Lang ever really giving up. After his rehabilitation was finished, he attended a technical school to become retrained from his previous occupation as an electrician. <P> Lang was working as an electrician when the accident occurred. He was standing on a ladder at the former Volkswagen plant building in New Stanton when the ladder rung collapsed beneath him, sending him crashing to the ground. He suffered a fractured skull, broken ribs, broken legs and damage to six discs in his back. <P>The surgeries have helped, he says, and the pain he feels throughout the day is not so intense as it had once been. But he is not completely recovered. Further surgery for his feet and ankle are being scheduled. <P>After completing his technical school training, Lang faced a new obstacle. While interviewing for new jobs, he was always asked if he had any medical restrictions. <P> Lang gave the interviewers an honest answer. He couldn't remain standing or sitting in one position too long without moving or else his back would lock up on him. Thinking about how far Lang had come from the accident, this may have seemed relatively minor. But it was enough to keep employers from calling back. <P> When he began working with the Vocational Rehabilitation Center in 1992, Lang says he couldn't believe how much help he received from the staff. "They were fantastic. They did more for me than anyone else would do," he says, adding that staff always responded to his phone calls with a simple "come in and let's talk about it." <P>Within three months, Lang landed his present job working with computerized pipeline maps at Peoples Natural Gas where his supervisors generously allow him freedom to move around when he needs to. <P>He is planning to place his North Hills home on the market soon and begin following his dream of a landscape business this spring. He owns about 30 acres of land in Lawrence County off Interstate 79 and has already ordered 5,000 trees to plant as the first step to his new business. <P>He says he's a quiet man who likes to stay to himself and will enjoy the open space at his new home. <P>"I'm getting better," Lang says. "The pain, even though it ripples down my leg continuously, is not as severe as it was originally." It's something he's gotten used to, and to his way of thinking, it's not enough to stop him from pursuing his dream.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>1995 Executive Committee </B></font size> <BR>
