Peoples Natural Gas Co.<BR>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Opening Doors</B></font size> <BR>
By Eugene J. Barone<BR>
I am pleased and honored to have been chosen to serve as honorary dinner chair at an event acknowledging the selfless accomplishments of Edward V. Randall Jr. and Fred Rogers, the 1995 Compton and Mulach Award winners, respectively.Ned Randall and I have known each other for nearly 20 years, having worked together on many community projects. I have always found him to be a bright man who engages himself fully in whatever he does. I believe his support of people with disabilities has been great evidence of that. <P> Mr. Rogers' name is synonymous with affirming self-esteem in children and accepting the differences in people. I have always found Fred to be exactly the same off-camera as he is on; a warm, caring man who quietly, but firmly, gets his message across. <P>We at VRC are grateful to these two men for their vision in supporting and encouraging people with disabilities and all people. <P>Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania, where I worked for 36 years, was one of the very first companies to employ VRC consumers, and for that I have always been very proud. <P> As more and more consumers are placed by VRC at companies which open their doors to people with disabilities, we all reap the benefits of having helped others become the best they can be. <P> Eugene J. Barone is honorary dinner chair for the VRC awards. He is the past president, chairman and CEO of Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania.

