<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Shaking Up the DER</B></FONT></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Gov. Ridge wants to overhaul the state Department of Environmental Resources. Businesses stand to benefit.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Raelin Sawka</i>
<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Environmental regulations and the Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Resources have often been criticized as deterrents to economic development. While busi-nesses regularly cite the DER as an impediment, complaints are often louder and harsher during election years. Last year's gubernatorial race was no exception.Each candidate, from Democrat Mark Singel to the Independent Peg Luksik, had something to say about improving the DER, but no one's rhetoric was as strong as now-Gov. Tom Ridge's. <P> During his hustings, Ridge called the DER a "job-crushing, community-harassing, regulatory nightmare," and vowed to "end the intimidation, end the grandstanding and end the know-it-all attitude that plagues the department." <P> As a result of his promise to restructure the DER, Ridge was dubbed a "danger to the environment" by the Sierra Club, an organization that broke a long-standing tradition by making its first gubernatorial endorsement -- for Singel. <P> While environmentalists may be concerned about Ridge's intentions, business and industry leaders are hopeful that he will bring an end to the regulatory red tape, inconsistent enforcement and adversarial attitude of the state's environmental regulatory arm.<P> "Dealing with the DER has been very complicated, very bureaucratic and very costly to businesses and taxpayers," says Stephen Lee of Lee & Co., a communications consulting firm for environmental issues management. <P>Lee adds that the DER and the Environmental Protection Agency fail to consider "the burden [regulation] places on industry. These people think companies can afford to spend the money, but today companies are streamlined. They have limited resources." <P>Politically spawned, formed from a hodgepodge of smaller state agencies in 1970 and allowed to grow without any real plan, today's DER is a classic bureaucracy. Despite several reorganization and downsizing attempts, the department, which has a budget of over $500 million and more than 4,100 employees, is considered by many to be indecisive and mismanaged. <P>"The DER's delays in making decisions are common complaints among industry and citizens," says Bob Thompson, environmental senior partner at Pittsburgh law firm Meyer, Darragh, Buckler, Bebenek & Eck.  <P>Ridge proposes splitting the DER. The Department of Environmental Protection would continue with regulatory functions for air, water or land pollution; surface and deep mining; drinking water; radiation, and solid and hazardous waste. The Department of Conservation and Natural Resources would oversee the state parks and forests.Ridge also proposes delegating several ancillary programs to departments better suited for them. <P>New LeadershipA third way that Ridge plans to whittle the bureaucracy is to bring in new leadership. New management could engender a real change in employee motivation. <P> Ridge announced his executive appointees to the DER prior to his   Jan. 17 inauguration: James M. Seif to head the department as secretary, David E. Hess to serve as executive deputy secretary and Terry R. Bossert as chief counsel.Ridge's appointees, who all appear to have firsthand knowledge of environmental issues, have to be confirmed by the state Legislature. <P>Seif, a Philadelphia lawyer, served as legal counsel for the EPA's regional office in Philadelphia from 1973 to 1975 and as regional administrator from 1985 to 1989. Following his nomination, Seif stated that the DER is too "insular, bureaucratic, over-layered, slow and insulated from other parts of Pennsylvania life, such as economic growth."Seif is straightforward about problems and solutions for the department. He says the DER is "run by too many lawyers," causing it to be adversarial. <P>Before his nomination, Hess was the executive director of the Environmental Resources & Energy committee of the state Senate. <P> Nominee Bossert supervises the environmental practice for Harrisburg law firm McNees, Wallace & Nurick. He also has prosecuted environmental crimes with the state Department of Justice.  <P>"With this new appointment of Bossert, it appears that the governor meant what he said [that he will overhaul DER]," says Harley Trice, partner in the environmental section at Reed, Smith, Shaw & McClay. "Bossert will bring a balanced viewpoint to the DER." <P>While splitting up the department and appointing new leadership are steps toward the metamorphosis that Ridge envisions, environmental professionals believe there are other areas to address, such as regulation development. <P>"There is a lot of misconception by the public about the environment and what is good and what is bad. Our regulations are based on [public opinion] and not science," says Lee. "Regulation development has to be science based." <P>Others agree. Thompson says, "Regulations are currently based on politics, pop-science and the media. Too many decisions and regulations have been run by publicity and politics, not good science." <P> Seif says Ridge's proposed 21st Century Environmental Commission will help in this area. He adds that the commission will be balanced and eclectic, stating that it could include scientists, business people, politi-cians, educators and even experts from out of state if need be.Although Seif and Ridge advocate appointing such professionals to the new commission, critics say that with such a diverse mix, it will no doubt be difficult to reach consensus. <P>Environmental professionals and business leaders do agree, however, that with the DER working under principles of science, both the department and companies will be able to accomplish more, in less time, for less money.<P>An Expensive ExampleA client of Trice's wanted to redevelop a contaminated site adjacent to the company's existing building. Using risk analysis, the EPA approved the company's plan to encapsulate contaminants. Encapsu-lation cleans up the land to a safe -- rather than pristine -- level. The DER, however, "took a hard-line position," insisting that the site be completely decontaminated, says Trice."It was very frustrating. The company's proposal would have cost $120,000. The EPA indicated that was acceptable, but the DER insisted on excavation. DER-outlined excavation carried a $2 million price tag." <P>As a consequence, the company couldn't redevelop the land -- leaving it unused and contaminated for five years until the EPA finally did the work. Trice says that this case clearly points out the DER's inflexibility and is typical of the breakdown in communications that occurs between the state and federal agencies. <P>"The DER's inability to get along with the EPA has caused problems for industry many times," says Trice. <P>When talking with business and industry leaders, environmental professionals, environmentalists and even private citizens, it seems the DER's belligerence hampers not only commercial growth but environmental growth as well. <P>"Everybody feels that we need to take a step forward. ... With DER focused on a risk-based approach, we'll be able to do more for the environment and for business," says Trice. <P>Ridge and Seif agree. That's why the state Legislature will see an  industrial site recycling bill during its first session. This bill will set "standards for remediation so that you won't be on the hook forever," says Seif. <P>The bill is promising for business, including Pittsburgh's strong envi-ronmental industry. "I believe that it would be very positive for the economy," says Bruce H. Laswell, senior vice president of ICF Kaiser Engineers. "Environmental con-sulting, business and even local gov-ernments benefit from an active, growing economy and active, growing projects. Development of these sites means a lot to Pittsburgh as a city." <P>Attitude AdjustmentThe posture of an organization, especially one accustomed to being besieged, is difficult to change. For years, DER employees have been in the unenviable position of trying to protect the environment without costing jobs. Employees are roundly criticized, told by businesses that they are slow, combative and pro-environmentalists. Environmentalists accuse them of pandering to industry. The press stands by ready to air any dirty laundry. <P>Seif says the result is procrasti-nation, inconsistencies and irrespon-sibility. He also believes that he can bring about an attitude adjustment without losing valuable employees. <P>"There are a lot of good people at DER. They must be supported and defended in their mission. In the past, many employees have been personally attacked by environ-mentalists and the media. We can't let that happen," says Seif. "There are also some people that need to move around or be fired. That's very motivating to those left behind." <P>Seif's hard-line stance may be difficult for some workers; the DER has historically resisted reform. <P>When asked how he would handle those disinclined to such adjust-ments, Seif replies, "I can't help it if people don't like change. Part of why Tom Ridge was elected is because he promised changes." <P>Seif proposes a variety of refinements, including achieving goals over following procedures, help-ing people not "zapping them" and remembering that compliance is more important than enforcement. Some efforts will be guided by Ridge's pro-posed office of Pollution Prevention and Compliance Assistance. <P>The office of Pollution Prevention and Compliance Assistance will assist citizens, companies and governments with laws and regulations. <P>Ed Burkey, president of the Pittsburgh Center for Hazardous Materials Research, says that the office of Pollution Prevention and Compliance Assistance is needed. <P>"I've seen firsthand the value of not using the enforcement stick but rather a technical assistance carrot. Companies respond much better to a helping hand," says Burkey. <P>Seif says that the Ridge admin-istration has set a July target date for the department breakup and plans to pass environmental reform early in the legislative season. <P>For now, industry is skeptical, yet eager to see what takes place. If Ridge and Seif can follow through, it will mean less expensive compliance, better options for industrial site use, more realistic regulations and less per-case investment for environmen-tal consultants and lawyers. 
<hr>
