<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Update </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Is It Worth Going Online?</B></FONT></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Going online has advantages for certain businesses depending on their needs.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By By David J. Molter</i>
<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>
T-shirt hangs on the wall of Ed Chang's North Side office. On the front of the shirt, juxtaposed with the imprint of a tire tread, are these words: "I got run over on the information superhighway." <P> Chang chuckles about the shirt, but acknowledges that its message is not far off the mark. "It's very easy to feel intimidated by the amount of material that's available about going online," Chang says. "We're trying to help people sort it out." <P> Chang's Common Sense Interactive Group Inc., a company he started over two years ago, is one of a growing number that specialize in giving the equivalent of driving lessons to local businessmen who want to travel in cyberspace, but don't want to become "digital roadkill." However different these businessmen may be -- and they range from first-time business owners to the heads of corporations -- they share a common question: "What will going online do for me?" <P> The answer isn't always simple.Working With a NetMost Americans probably became familiar with the term "information superhighway" not long after the 1992 election, when Bill Clinton and Al Gore began touting it as vital to the country's ability to compete in a global market. But an information super-highway of sorts has existed since 1969. It's called the Internet, and it's a worldwide linking of computers that began when the Pentagon asked its computer experts to develop a way for military and academic researchers to communicate electronically. Initially, only four research labs were linked in what was then called ARPAnet; by the late 1980s, however, millions of com-puters had joined. Today some 25 mil-lion users tap into Internet. Once a sport enjoyed mostly by academicians, "surfing the Net" has become a leading pastime for almost anyone able to afford a basic computer and a modem. The profiles of these recent converts fit no norm; one Pittsburgh entrepreneur confided that his 6-year-old granddaughter has an e-mail pen pal in Australia. But perhaps the largest group of first-time users last year was made up of businessmen. <P> Because in 1994, particularly in the last two quarters, companies large and small began to explore the impact of working with a Net. And to do that, they had to go online.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Tapping In: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
"Going online can have a lot of advantages for certain businesses depending on their needs," says Chang, whose company provides consulting services along with design of interactive programs that a company can use for sales presenta-tions or to market itself via electronic storefronts. <P>"It can provide ways of advertising and selling products and, through e-mail, a very easy way of commu-nicating with clients if they're out of town. It's a lot less expensive than picking up the phone and having a one-hour conversation." 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>What's the best way to get online? </B></FONT SIZE><br>
 There isn't one, experts say. <P>Several programs providing access to online services are available at almost any store that sells computers or software, and most have retail prices under $40. Most current desktop computer systems, whether IBM and compatibles or Apple, have the required 4K of random access memory, hard drive space (at least 150 megabytes) and internal or external modems (14,400 baud is the current benchmark) fast enough to handle loading of files from databases.CompuServe, Prodigy and America Online (AOL) are the big three commercial communications services. How big? CompuServe has 2.2 million subscribers; Prodigy, 1.2 million; AOL, just over 1 million, a figure that doubled in the last six months of 1994. Genie, eWorld, Delphi, Internet Online Services and Interchange Online Network have far fewer subscribers, but probably will gain members rapidly, especially since the Apple-developed eWorld is being bundled with Macintosh computers and a Windows-based version for IBMs is due this year. Each service offers a variety of options. But all provide what users agree can be a valuable tool for any business: a way of sharing information among peers.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>B-boards and Forums:</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Don Peebly, director of marketing for Pittsburgh's KSBH Architects, uses AOL, both at work and at home. He has used CompuServe and Prodigy, but finds AOL more user-friendly. <P> "It's Windows based and very easy to use," says Peebly. "From a business perspective, it's been very valuable to me, and I expect it to be even more so in the future. It's probably going to become indispensable to anyone in marketing or advertising." <P> Peebly uses AOL for research into distance education. "We do a lot of work at colleges and a fair amount at broadcast facilities, and we've detected a trend that combines interactive media with higher education and distance education," Peebly explains.  "We've visited several sites, but through America Online, I've been able to track any new information that's been published on the subject." <P>Peebly also uses AOL to research for articles, and he has used its online forums to see what's current in direct-mail marketing, which KSBH plans to explore this year.  <P>An informal survey of Pittsburgh area firms reveals that most use at least one online service to keep up with the latest developments. <P>"Online sharing of information is becoming more and more prevalent in accounting," says Bob Padgett, firm administrator of S.R. Snodgrass, an accounting firm with offices in Green Tree, Wexford and Beaver. Snodgrass' main location shares files with branch offices in Ohio and West Virginia. <P>Padgett and several Snodgrass employees also are online nationally through CompuServe. Snodgrass is online with a national association of CPAs, which has a committee contin-ually studying the latest technological advances. "And we are beginning to share simple spreadsheet information with almost 40 accounting firms from Maine to California," Padgett adds. "There's no need to reinvent the wheel because we have access to things other firms have on file." <P>That is just one way to use online services. Because the Internet allows virtually any business access to 25 million potential customers, it was inevitable that it eventually would be tapped for commercial purposes. Internauts, as longtime users call themselves, may not be happy about it, but the electronic mall is upon us. <P>Just down the hall from Chang's office in the converted brewery that hugs the base of Troy Hill, Abu Noaman is introducing Pittsburgh to the world, and vice versa. <P>Noaman's Internet Services Corp., a company he started in late 1993, provides services for organizations that wish to promote themselves over the Internet. ISC provides consultation, training and installation of connections and networking equipment. But the service Noaman feels has the most growth potential is the development of electronic domains or storefronts for commercial users of the Internet. <P> Electronic storefronts are a relatively recent phenomenon. In 1991, about 9,000 commercial ventures had storefronts in the Internet mall. By last year that figure had grown to 25,000. The rapid increase was due in large part to the growing ease of navigating the Net, which was made possible by user-friendly interfaces such as Mosaic. <P>Mosaic is a point-and-click interface that allows users to jump from one place on the Net to another through World Wide Web, a network of some 7,000 computers scattered around the globe that, although owned independently, operate together. <P> Noaman calls WWW "the Disneyland of the Internet," a significant enhancement for users who are less than technically adept. WWW made navigating the Net easy enough for potential consumers that companies such as Ford, IBM and JCPenney soon thought it viable to open Net storefronts. These commercial giants are being joined by smaller firms, including a number of western Pennsylvania companies.And on Jan. 19, the city of Pittsburgh went online through ISC. <P> The city of Pittsburgh's storefront is the online equivalent of promotional videos now being used by several cities, including Pittsburgh. ISC's design makes full use of available technology, which means video and audio clips abound. Through the storefront, anyone with access to the Internet can see and hear what Pittsburgh is all about. City assets are featured, including housing, universities, sports franchises, cultural resources, businesses and industry. All that's required to learn more about any of them is the click of a mouse button. <P> "It's not just a travelogue," Noaman points out. "It's a great marketing tool that Pittsburgh can use to attract companies that might be looking to relocate." <P>ISC's development of Pittsburgh's storefront illustrates how far the parameters of online marketing can be expanded. But simpler approaches are available. <P>For example, among ISC's clients is Gift Gallery Inc., a Murrysville-based gift basket company that, thanks to ISC, has tapped into the global marketplace. Internet users who find the Gift Gallery storefront attractive and click on the appropriate icon may browse through its online catalog. The catalog is complete, even down to graphic replication of the textured stock on which its paper cousin is printed. <P> Customers can examine pictures of the items and click on highlighted hypertext for descriptions. They also may fill out order forms that are sent to the ISC server, which in turn sends the order by fax to Gift Gallery. The company then contacts the customer to confirm and arrange payment. <P>Costs for putting a catalog online vary, but Noaman says a small company might expect to pay $150 per page for initial design, then a $100 per month Internet access fee. Although Noaman feels commercial use of the Internet will grow, he admits an electronic storefront is not for every business."Any company whose customers are not on the Net yet would not benefit, for obvious reasons," Noaman says. 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Three for the Road:</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Black Box Inc., a Canonsburg-based computer products company, has found that consumers are be-coming more comfortable with electronic shopping. <P> In the last six months, Black Box has launched three online pilot programs. The first was through IndustryNET, an online service started in 1993 by Don Jones, a Pittsburgh entrepreneur nationally considered a pioneer of online technology. <P>In July 1994, Black Box established a number of bulletin boards describing the company's products on IndustryNET, which is free to users. Through IndustryNET, Black Box gained access to more than 150,000 suppliers of computers, controls, instruments and manufac-turing systems in the United States. <P>"We're very pleased with the response," says Doug Goodall, vice president of business development at Black Box. But Black Box also decided to venture into cyberspace on a larger scale. In the last week of November, the company launched an online version of its catalog on the Internet. It was a big move for a company that had built its business using a direct-mail catalog with no field sales force, and an even bigger move considering that two years ago, Black Box had experimented with, but decided against using, a CD-ROM version. <P> "We found that although the CD-ROM catalog was well received, not enough businesses had PCs equipped with CD-ROM units," Goodall explains. "Our idea in going online was that with an Internet-based server here at the company, we would be able to have a lot of the dynamics of a CD-ROM -- pictures, text and, ultimately, video and audio -- but with a worldwide reach. It was very appealing -- if we could develop something that would cause people to come into our server."Working with Michael Bauer of The Internet Group, a Pittsburgh-based consulting company, Black Box developed software that allows ordering from its online catalog and installed a $50,000 in-house server. Obtaining Internet access through PREPnet Inc. and leasing high-speed phone lines will cost about $20,000 annually. About $200,000 was budgeted for the first year for development and refinement. <P> "Clearly, you can put something on the Net for a much lower cost at a much smaller scale, but we decided to be as robust as possible," Goodall says of the investment. <P>Users at 7,000 sites in 44 countries visited the Black Box storefront during its first six weeks of operation. A small number of orders have been placed, including one from Moscow, "which solidified in my mind that this does indeed have worldwide reach," says Goodall. Because there are so few benchmarks for successful performance of such ventures, however, Goodall isn't sure when the system will pay for itself.  <P>"We decided the real measure of its success would be if people used it and if they commented favorably on it," he says. "So far, they're doing both."As a third test of the power of online communications, Black Box ran a single-paragraph billboard on Prodigy, asking if users would like to receive a free catalog. Two thousand users asked to be added to the company's mailing list in the first four weeks. <P>"We're excited about all three pilots, even though we're not sure where they will go," Goodall says. "But we think it's a good leadership position for us to be taking." <P>Chang and Noaman agree with this approach. "The first step is to access," says Chang. "Pick a service and sample what's out there. Then contact a consulting service. They'll tell you what you're doing right and if you can benefit from linking up. Any good service will give you an honest assessment of where you stand. We're a multimedia company, but multimedia isn't right for everyone. We'll be honest enough to say, No, what you're doing is working fine. Stay with it.' ""Historically, electronics and computer companies have had the greatest success with electronic storefronts, but it can't hurt to test the waters," says Noaman. "If you're unsure, don't make a big investment: rent space on someone else's server on a trial basis, gather some information about the marketplace, then do it more strongly. <P>"Sooner or later, all businesses will be on the Net. The question is,  do you want to be a leader or a follower?"                                        
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Toolbox: Local Companies in the Industry:</B></FONT SIZE><br>
If you want to learn more, there are several local companies who make online services their business. The industry is in a growth mode, with new providers popping up all the time. Here are some of the ones we were aware of at press time.<P>
<DL>
<LI><B>Common Sense Interactive Group Inc.</B> (412) 231-3566.	Consulting services and design of interactive programs for sales presentations or electronic storefronts
<LI><B>IdeaLab.</B> (412) 934-6200. clabash@cerf.net . A management innovation resource company that assesses the value of online marketing for clients, provides testing and presents recommendations on e-marketing
<LI><B>The Internet Business Pages.</B> (412) 242-5245; alpha@lonewolf.com . A service of LoneWolf Systems Inc. created to provide home pages on the World Wide Web for local specialty businesses
<LI><B>The Internet Group.</B> (412) 661-4247. Consulting services 
<LI><B>Internet Services Corp.</B> (412) 321-2912; info@netservices.com . ISC provides Internet storefront development and deployment, education and training, connection, installation and maintenance
<LI><B>PREPnet Inc.</B> (412) 268-7870; nic@prep.net .The Pennsylvania Research and Economic Partnership Network is the principal Internet access provider in the state. It is a mid-level regional network, initiated by the commonwealth, Bell of Pennsylvania and a consortium of universities: CMU, Drexel, Lehigh, Penn State, Temple, Pitt and the University of Pennsylvania.
<LI><B>Telerama Public Access Internet.</B> (412) 481-3505; telerama.lm.com . Terminal dial-up and SLIP Internet access to individuals and businesses, free online classes for customers, technical support, onsite consulting and setup
<LI><B>USA OnRamp Network.</B> (412) 391-4197; info@usaor.com . Connectivity for businesses and individuals, educational seminars and Web server for individual or business advertisements. USA OnRamp is a trademark of ComputerTech.
</DL>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Paving the Way:</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Don Jones may not have built the information superhighway, but he has helped smooth the traveling for its users. <P>In 1990, Jones and some management professionals with expertise in electronic communications, marketing and publishing founded Automation News Network. It was Jones' goal to automate the buying and selling process. <P>His first step was to establish The Locator, an electronic yellow pages that currently lists 150,000 manufacturers and suppliers of products used by business and industry. ANN is now the largest supplier of electronic yellow pages in the United States, serving 22 states with 12 regional editions. The Locator is available on floppy diskettes and online via a number of information superhighway on-ramps. <P>One way is through IndustryNET, the online service Jones started in 1993 so businesses could tap into a comprehensive listing of products and services provided by other businesses. <P>IndustryNET was accessed by more than 350,000 users in 1994, and Jones expects log-ons to exceed 1 million in 1995. Like the Locator, IndustryNET is free to users. Some businesses pay a fee for more detailed descriptions of their products and services and amenities such as graphics. <P>Jones says IndustryNET is unique in that it can be accessed four ways: via computer using a standard modem; through the Internet's TelNET service; by using ANN's graphical user interface software, which can be downloaded for free; or, through World Wide Web, an international network of computers accessible through the Internet. <P> IndustryNET and The Locator proved so successful that in 1994, Jones decided to link the two. In early December, Jones rolled out the Western Pennsylvania Locator, the first of what he says will be 12 regional yellow pages editions similar to its predecessor. WPL lists information about some 9,500 companies in the region, including about 650 of Pittsburgh's largest businesses. And through the Internet's WWW, these businesses now have a foothold in the       global marketplace. <P> All are listed by name and by the products or services they provide. Cross-indexing allows users to search by product, then learn more about suppliers. ANN  software allows users to ask for more information, call sales representatives directly or place an order, all with a keystroke or the click of a mouse button. <P>"I'm a stickler for making these systems not just user friendly, but user intuitive," says Jones. <P>Over the last five years, ANN has expanded from a staff of three to 127 full-time and 30 part-time employees. Jones is aware of the burgeoning consumer online market, but for the time being he is content to serve business customers only. <P> "The business community is already here online," says Jones. "We'll go consumer when we serve our advertisers well."
<HR>
Comparing the Big Three<P>America OnlineCost: $9.95 per month for five hours access; $2.95 for each additional hourServices: Bulletin boards, chat rooms, e-mail, finance, shopping, sports, travel, limited Internet access. Additional Internet features are being added this year.Drawbacks: Because AOL is popular and growing, users often get a busy signal.Strengths: One basic fee. Users with faster modems do not pay more.<P>CompuServeCost: $8.95 per month for unlimited access to basic servicesServices: Databases and discussion groups, e-mail, news, reference sources, shopping, sports, travelDrawbacks: Access to databases most useful for business costs $4.80 per hour at 2,400 baud, $9.60 per hour at 9,600 baud. Access to the Internet is limited to e-mail, but features are being added.Strengths: Access to almost 2,000 databases for research, news services and magazines<P>ProdigyCost: $9.95 per month for five hours use of all services, $2.95 per hour thereafter. $14.95 per month for unlimited use of basic services plus five hours of premium services.Services: Bulletin boards, chat rooms, e-mail, finance, shopping, sports, travel, limited Internet access. Additional Internet features such as discussion groups are being added this year.Drawbacks: Onscreen ads proved to be a major distraction to users surveyed. Although it offers many of the same services as CompuServe, business users found it less convenient.Strengths: Few for business, although that may change in 1995. Windows compatible upgrade should be available soon.Source: Survey of Pittsburgh businesses and information provided by the services themselves.

