<HEAD>
<TITLE> Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2><fill> </FONT SIZE><i> By Linda A. Dickerson</i><P>
Is This Area Becoming a Region?Aside from those who were not funded to the extent that they felt was appropriate, most people complimented the Allegheny Regional Asset District board on its ability to reach a consensus on how to allocate  <P> $53 million when the requests for the money more than doubled the available funds. A unanimous vote on who gets money, or who does not get money, when the stakes are $53 million high, was a celebrated accomplishment by almost any standard. <P>The competition for funding was intense. Allegheny Regional Asset District board members made some difficult choices. They reviewed over 1,000 pages of documentation, made dozens of site visits and listened to hours of public testimony. Seven individuals who hold demanding jobs and have other commitments zealously undertook their ARAD assignment and invested thousands of hours collectively in enhancing Allegheny County's quality of life. Precision teamwork facilitated an unprecedented and somewhat unanticipated unanimous final budget decision. <P> Not to discount the accolades bestowed upon the board, the most outstanding accomplishment was the passage of the legislation and not the passage of the budget. Yes, without a permanent staff or office, the district board beat the odds, packed a year's work into six months and reached consensus on extremely tough decisions. Yet, this accomplishment should in no way dominate the district's most preeminent end result. For the first time in recent history, the city, county and state joined forcesand worked together symbiotically to share resources and govern more efficiently. Each surrendered parts of their territory for the greater good. <P> This unprecedented cooperation is the most remarkable aspect of the Allegheny Regional Asset District, and the more ephemeral victory of a unanimous vote on the first budget should not overshadow the importance of the cooperative spirit which created the district. This landmark legislation will assume its rightful place in history as the first true foray into regionalism. <P> Let's hope that the ARAD's results spawn countless other regional approaches to government. This area must turn into a region to ensure its long-term vitality.Editor's note: Linda Dickerson served on the Allegheny Regional Asset District board.

