<HEAD>
<TITLE> Letters </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.L.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>

<hr>
<font size =+2><B>Upgrade and Correction:</B></font size><BR>
Your Chronicles in the January 1995 issue reported on the Weiss Rating opinions on Pennsylvania HMOs. HealthAmerica Pennsylvania Inc. has received an improved rating grade, subsequent to the original report. HealthAmerica Pennsylvania Inc. is currently rated C (fair). C indicates that this company offers fair financial security and is currently stable. This new rating is the result of additional information HealthAmerica Penn-sylvania provided to Weiss Safety Ratings.Thank you for publishing this information to correct the earlier report.Sue Ann Bailey, director of com-munications, Weiss Research Inc., Palm Beach Gardens, Fla.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Setting the Record Straight:</B></font size><BR>
We were dismayed when we read "Ranking Health Insurers" in January. Because the infor-mation on HealthAmerica is misleading and inaccurate, we want to set the record straight. <P>The article quotes Weiss Ratings Inc., an agency which, for a fee, offers consumers [ratings] on insurance companies' financial strength. Weiss only recently began to evaluate health insurance companies and HMOs, and based on our experience, their methods and analyses are irresponsible and inconsistent with industry norms. <P> Your article lists Weiss ratings for five insurers and HMOs that do business in western Pennsylvania. None of them scored very well. Given the enormous financial resources and stability of most of the firms listed, and the low ratings Weiss assigned to these same firms, one has to wonder what net worth Weiss requires for an A rating. <P> We contacted Weiss when we first heard about our rating. They had not contacted us before developing their rate -- a validation procedure you would expect any responsible rating agency to follow. Once we furnished them with pertinent data, they immediately upgraded our rating two tiers to a C. Apparently, they made no attempt to correct the press release they had issued earlier. <P> <I>Thomas J. Murray, vice president of marketing, HealthAmerica of Pittsburgh</I>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Defending HealthAmerica:</B></font size><BR>
The January 1995 Chronicles section had an article entitled "Ranking Health Insurers." As an independent brokerage writing a large amount of group health insurance, we were interested. <P> The source was Weiss Ratings Inc. The ratings would be humorous except the subject matter is so serious. <P> We are quite familiar with HealthAmerica, its mode of operation and its financial position. HealthAmerica is sound. <P> HealthAmerica's reserves far exceed the requirements of the Pennsylvania Insurance Commission. Their fiscal soundness is not an issue, yet Weiss awarded a low mark. This is unjustified. <P><I>A.V. Papa Jr., principal, Comprehensive Assurance, Monroeville</I>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Environmental Economic Engine:</B></font size><BR>
I read the article on the brownfields and the greenfields [January 1995] with interest and warm support. Not only does the brownfields' reuse legislative thrust make sense for the commercial property market, but it actually makes sense for the somewhat beleaguered environmental industry. Greenfields virtually put a dead halt to risk analysis. What is more, they are invariably a depletion of natural resources. <P> So in an unusual unity of environmental activists with commercial interests, brownfield development is the best way to go. From an environmental testing laboratory standpoint, brownfields are also the best route. There should be more old industrial properties to evaluate if marketing reuse is handled properly. Moreover, the time needed to test and evaluate should be far less and also less likely to get bogged down. <P>Our environmental achievements give us an advantage over world competition. Legislators should see the environment as a huge business opportunity, an economic engine, an employment generator, a technology developer and, of course, a quality of life enhancer. <P><I>A. Warne Boyce, chairman and CEO, Microbac Laboratories Inc., Pittsburgh</I>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Getting Technical:</B></font size><BR>
Western Pennsylvania is known for the number and quality of its business, trade and technical schools, some of which are the largest of their type in the country. I am surprised that you did not see fit to include some information about these institutions [in your December 1994 Leadership Directory]. <P>I note that three of the 10 growth com-panies listed in the magazine [cover story] are electronics com-panies. The reason that they are successful is that schools like ours train the technical personnel which they need to perform their mission. <P><I>Philip Chosky, president, Electronic Institutes, Pittsburgh</I> 
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Geography Lesson</B></font size><BR>
I read with no little interest the story in your December issue about target marketing by colleges and universities. Bethany College, less than an hour's drive from downtown Pittsburgh, retains the services of the city's George Hill Co. for target advertising. <P>Upon inquiry, I find that Executive Report wouldn't include Bethany because the college was not in western Pennsylvania. That's sad. Sociologists have known for a long time that political boundaries do not limit a community. Greater Pittsburgh certainly includes Bethany. Our major banking is in Pittsburgh, it is our transportation and entertainment center, we read Pittsburgh newspaper and watch Pittsburgh TV. <P>More importantly, western Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh in particular, has provided the largest contingent of students to this old college as long as anyone can remember. But that's no surprise, since 82% of the people living within 50 miles of Bethany are Pennsylvanians. <P>Pittsburgh business does not limit itself by state line; why doesn't Executive Report expand its view of Greater Pittsburgh? <P><I>Robert A. Sandercox, vice president of development, Bethany College, Bethany, W.Va., r.sandercox@po.Bethany.wvnet.edu</I>
<HR>
Editor's note: Well said, well spoken. We appreciate your comments and suggestions and will take them under consideration. All of this month's letters were edited for space. 
<b>Executive Report welcomes your feedback.</b><i> Send letters to Jim Urban, Editor, Executive Report, 3 Gateway Center, 401 Liberty Ave., 5th Floor, Pittsburgh, PA 15222-1004 or fax them to (412) 644-3006. or email them to er_editor@execreport.com</i>
