<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <FONT SIZE=+2><B>The PA Crime Debate: Make It About Character and Community</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Don E. Eberly</i>
<HR>
In January, the Legislature began a special session on crime that was expected to last up to six weeks. It presented a rare opportunity for citizens to gain insights into one of society's most vexing problems. <P> The session was this state's response to a nationwide move-ment to get tough on criminals. In exchange for costly new provisions, citizens deserve to know what will likely work.  <P>The legislative agenda, set forth by the new governor, offers a long list of provisions aimed, in dozens of small ways, to tighten state criminal laws. <P>Most of the provisions, of course, have merit -- lots of merit. But what seems to be missing thus far in this debate, like so many, is an overarching understanding of where exactly crime is coming from and what society, not just politicians, must do to reverse it over the next decade. <P>The debate cannot simply be about more cops, better caseworkers or tougher criminal statutes. The evidence that tougher penalties, better policing or improving social spending, by themselves, will substantially reverse growing criminality is weak. These measures can help communities cope, but they are powerless by themselves to cure crime. <P> Crime is a function, according to America's foremost expert James Q. Wilson, of the presence or absence of character in society and the strength or weakness of institutions that foster it. <P> The explosive rise in juvenile crime illustrates the point. Those involved in the criminal justice system today report that youthful offenders are more ruthless and free from the shackles of personal conscience than ever. These are not individuals who are likely to stop and thoughtfully ponder the penalties or rewards of this or that course of action. For many juveniles, a trip to prison is a rite of passage, a source of pride. <P> Moreover, in many communities, residents are retreating into their fortified homes because street life has degenerated into incivility and disrespect. Many neighborhoods are under virtual assault, not always from violent crime but from petty harassment and offensive behavior. No crime bill will do much to affect this mean and disorderly behavior. <P>If crime is the price civilization pays for abandoning character, where does society turn? <P>Character and moral reasoning are internalized in children through healthy value-shaping institutions of society, starting with the family. The business of restoring these institutions will not be undertaken so long as the debate over crime is fixated entirely on policy reforms.It will require society-wide movements to strengthen community and parenting. Young people, particularly young males prone toward aggression, must be habituated -- a term used by Wilson to describe how positive habits of self-regulation and concern for others are developed. <P> Crime is and always has been overwhelmingly a male problem. Violent crime in particular, from rape to armed robbery, is perpetrated by aimless males who lack strong attachments to family and community. <P> The key factor is the presence or absence of a father. Social research indicates that when this factor is taken into account, the relationship of crime to both income and race disappears. Why? Because it is the father, not just a child support check, that socializes the male into responsible adulthood.There is no record in history of a society that has succeeded without paying attention to this unavoidable fact. For political debates to contribute to long-term change, they should engage the public in a new understanding of the role citizens and communities    must play. <P> A real conversation about crime might emphasize the following: 
<DL>
<LI>Citizen-led strategies for neighborhood crime prevention. A lot of crime occurs simply because communities have become too tolerant of general social disorder. 
<LI>Community projects to discourage teen pregnancies and involve fathers in the lives of children. Gov. Ridge's emphasis on organizing community-based strategies aimed at root causes deserves praise. 
<LI>Rigorous character education programs in schools and other community institutions which can reinforce pro-social behavior. 
</DL>
The crime debate presents an opportunity for a serious shift in the state from an old paradigm of governmentalism, which emphasizes what politicians can do about crime, to a new paradigm centering on civic-moral renewal and the role every individual person can play. Over the long haul, such a strategy could strengthen the security of our neighborhoods and revitalize civic life in the process. <P> 
<i>Don E. Eberly is the president of The Commonwealth Foundation, a Harrisburg-based think tank. The opinions expressed here are the author's own.</i>

<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
