<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> ERIndex </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a><P>
<HR>
Advances in local cycli-cal issues along with a stronger market in general combined to send the ER Index up 6.6% for the month ended Jan. 13. That compares favor-ably with the 4.06% turned in by the S&P 500 during that same period.Since inception, the ER Index is now up 6.82% vs. just 0.84% for the S&P 500. We continue to believe that investing locally is the best choice. Though there are probably a few scattered up in the hills, we've not been able to locate any insurgent rebels in the area. Additionally, we don't believe either Bill Clinton or Tom Ridge favors devaluation of the nation's currency. And while there continue to be some rumblings following the Steelers' playoff loss, earthquakes and other natural disasters are still rare in these parts. There's something to be said about stability. 
<DL>
<LI>Johnstown America led the list of winners, up nearly 36%, as the company recovered from a dreadful couple of months that saw its stock price sink to a low of $10.50 per share in early December. The railcar maker announced it purchased Bostrom Seating Inc., of Piedmont, Ala., for $30 million. Bostrom, with approximately $55 million in sales last year, is the leading manufacturer of suspension and static seating for the heavy truck market. More importantly, it was the first acquisition for Johnstown since the company went public in 1993. Management has said all along that it intends to acquire other transportation-related manufacturing companies. 
<LI>Legent advanced nearly 24% for the month, to $36.25 per share. On Jan. 3, Legent announced it had hired Jerre Stead as its chairman and CEO. Stead, who had been chairman and CEO at AT&T's computer unit, has a reputation as a turnaround specialist. He is expected to speed Legent's transformation from its historic focus on mainframe-based software to smaller networks of personal computers and workstations. Stead is also expected to smooth the company's financial performance, which tends to be erratic and difficult to predict.
<LI>Respironics jumped almost 20% for the month, to $27.75 per share. Despite receiving a warning letter from the Food and Drug Administration, the manufacturer of respiratory therapy products is rumored to be the potential target of a number of possible suitors. Cowen & Co., an investment banking firm, said there were several large medical-supply companies that would have an interest in acquiring Respironics.
<LI>Both steel companies in the Index, Allegheny Ludlum and USX -- U.S. Steel, posted more than 11% gains, and Alcoa and PPG Industries also moved up significantly.
<LI>Mellon Bank Corp. reported a strong end to 1994, with fourth quarter earnings up 24% from the prior year. Those results did not include its $130 million charge the bank took to protect its Boston Co. clients from further losses due to rising interest rates. Mellon finished up more than 11% for the month, to $34.25 per share.
<LI>Heinz advanced more than 6% for the month, but actually traded higher, as rumors swirled that the company would be the next large food processor to be bought out. Speculation intensified following the acquisition of Pet Inc. by Grand Metropolitan's Pillsbury unit.
<LI>Crown American also posted a nice gain, of nearly 7% to $13.63 per share, despite a fire at its Logan Valley Mall in Altoona just before Christmas. The shopping center REIT an-nounced that it hired George M. Sakakeeny to head up its acquisition-related activities. Sakakeeny was previously with the much larger Equitable Real Estate Invest-ment Management, where he helped manage a $7 billion real estate portfolio consisting of 77 regional malls and 42 strip centers.
<LI>Cable Design Technologies, which announced record results for the quarter ended Oct. 31, said it would sell 2.5 million shares, including 1.7 million owned by current shareholders, in a secondary public offering.
<LI>In mid-December, Michael Baker took another step in its turnaround efforts, announcing a reorganization of its operating units to more specifically target core markets, a strategic redirection of its Mellon Stuart Construction subsidiary and the imple-mentation of stronger financial controls at its Baker/MO subsidiary. The company also said it would take fourth-quarter charge of ap-proximately $10 million, pre-tax, which had been expected. The objectives of the re-structuring: to improve project and operating performance and to make money.Doug Thomas is vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.
</DL>

<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.</I>
