<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.C.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> </B></FONT SIZE><br>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Around the World: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Ever wanted to learn Swahili in Nairobi? If you have the time and money, Frontiers International Travel of Wexford can help make Swahili your second language.Frontiers has been specializing in unusual trips to more than 40 countries for 25 years. "We have a great repeat [business] with our travelers," says Susan Fitzgerald, owner of the family-run agency. Robert C. Duff, vice president of the Pittsburgh office of Smith Barney Shearson Inc., spent his last two summer vacations salmon fishing in Russia on Frontiers' trips. Duff, active in fly fishing for years, wanted to experience the sport in another country. <P> "I got plenty of pointers on where to go," says Duff. "And when I decided to travel to Russia, they set up the entire trip, from the flight to all my reservations. It was one-stop shopping." <P> Among those who have taken a seven-day, six-night salmon fishing trip to the Ponoi River above the Arctic Circle in northwest Russia for nearly $7,500, are Hugh McColl, chairman of NationsBank Corp. in Charlotte, N.C., and Paul Volcker, former Federal Reserve chairman. <P> Frontiers organizes fishing, bird-shooting, safari, natural history and other sojourns for more than 5,000 travelers a year. Trips run anywhere from $1,200 to $10,000 a week. <P> In addition to 50 employees in Wexford, Frontiers has an office in London and recently bought out a competitor in Boston. About 15% of Frontiers' clientele live in western Pennsylvania; 75% come from across the country, and 10% are international globe-trotters. <P> Frontiers hopes to continue expansion. "We're doing something right because in the past 10 years we've doubled our size," says Fitzgerald. "I think we have a special niche in the travel world." Although most of Frontiers' clients are men, Fitzgerald has noticed more women growing interested in outdoor traveling. Trips to Brazil and Christmas Island in the Central Pacific have become popular with couples and families.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>More Home Sweet Work: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Another group for home-based business owners has sprung up -- the Ohio Valley Homebased Business Association in Shippingport. Formed in July, the association meets regularly for networking and presentations. The group also puts out a newsletter.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Windows of Opportunity: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
The Department of Commerce invested $3.3 million in Gorell Enterprises, an Indiana County window manufacturing plant. It's the state's largest economic development project in the county. <P> The window maker opened at the former Season-all plant, which closed in 1993, costing 200 jobs. <P> U.S. Rep. John P. Murtha helped secure $1.5 million in federal funds along with an economic development partnership loan from the Commerce Department. Other monies included a $500,000 equipment loan, a $200,000 Pennsylvania capital loan fund and a $509,000 business infrastructure development grant. <P> The state Department of Community Affairs invested $200,000 through its enterprise zone loan program.The company is headed by former Season-all co-owner Wayne Gorell, whose family founded the operation in 1954. <P> According to former Commerce Secretary Andrew Greenberg, who resigned last year, the $7.8 million project should create 500 jobs within five years. "Without [Gorell's] personal and financial commitment, these jobs would have been lost for good," says Greenberg.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Cup of Joe: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
There's no need to limit yourself when visiting Tuscany Premium Coffee. The company has as many varieties as days in a year. <P> Tuscany, in Fifth Avenue Place, Oakland, One and Two Mellon Bank Centers and Arabica Inc.'s former shops in Oakland, Squirrel Hill, Shadyside and the South Side, credits its success to the popular Seattle-style blend. <P> The use of arabica beans rather than robusto beans, says Edward Wethli, president of Tuscany Western Pennsylvania/West Virginia, is what makes the coffee special. "Once [people] try it, they don't want to go back."Pittsburgh's per capita consumption of coffee, an average of 3.1 cups per day, is the highest of any American city, according to the National Association for the Specialty Food Trade. <P> The industry is in for another growth spurt in Wethli's opinion, thanks in part to the popularity of cafes in bookstores. Borders in Norman Centre II in the South Hills has expanded with a coffee section and Barnes & Noble stores often have an area for java lovers. "There will be a lot of growth for coffee in the next two years," Wethli says. Seattle-based Tuscany hopes to establish 25 locations in metro Pittsburgh.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Stars in PA Manufacturing: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Plastics and drugs are the growth areas for Pennsylvania's manufacturing base. At least that's the conclusion of economists at Penn State University. "In 1992-93 alone, plastic products and drugs generated more than 9,000 jobs," says Theodore E. Fuller, a develop-ment economist in agricultural economics and rural sociology at the college of agricultural sciences in University Park. "These two industries ... are now among the commonwealth's top five manufac-turing employers. Plastic commodi-ties are likely to replace steel as the state's main manufacturing product in the next few years if current developments continue." <P> Recent trends suggest that Pennsylvania manufacturing is finished with the major downsizing that has characterized it since 1980. "This indicates that the state's manufacturing industries are more competitive and efficient than in the past," says Stephen M. Smith, associate professor of agricultural economics and rural sociology. "This in turn bodes well for future growth in the increasingly open global economy."
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Take Home Pay: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Average annual wages in Allegheny County increased nearly 50% from 1982 to 1992, according to the Pennsylvania Department of Labor and Industry. The county ranked sixth highest in wages out of all 67 counties. <P> Greene County ranked seventh highest in annual wages with an increase of 42% from 1982 to 1992 due to high wages in mining. Mining accounted for 22% of all jobs in Greene.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>New Business: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Exercise Equipment Inc. opened a second store. It now has locations on the North Shore and in the South Hills. The Money Store Investment Corp. has opened an office in Pittsburgh at One Oxford Centre.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Measuring Success Is Easy: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
Katherine Barchetti of K. Barchetti Shops says it's easy  to measure success when "every aspect of managing a store relates to customer service." The high-fashion Pittsburgh retailer is one of five businesses profiled in a recent Tom Peters' video, "Service With Soul." The documentary training film is available through Video Publishing House Inc. of Schaumburg, Ill.This month's Chronicles was written and compiled by Jane A. Black and Kristin Giron.       
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Congressional Makeup: </B></FONT SIZE><br>
U.S. Rep. Ron Klink made a list compiled by the Washington, D.C.-based National Restaurant Association of representatives who have first-hand knowledge of the food service industry. As owner of Dagwood's in Pittsburgh, Klink, along with 10 other members of Congress, is being looked at as a probable ally by restaurateurs. Klink, who has offices in New Castle, Beaver and North Huntingdon, also has experience as a TV journalist.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Government Prep </B></FONT SIZE><br>
More representatives have law expe-rience than any other background.
