<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report February 1995 Issue</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.netservices.com"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=top SRC="../zine/Ads/isc.tran.gif"></a>
<HR>
<img align=left src="../pictures/0295.Feature.1.gif"><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Opportunities Lost: </FONT SIZE></B>
<FONT SIZE=+1><b>Our region has negative labor-management relations, a punitive tax structure and a lack of regionally coordinated marketing. Now what?</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Paul Kengor  </i>
<P>

Despite having the fifth highest population of any state in the country, Pennsylvania ranked 18th in new business facilities and expansions from 1991 to 1993. Meanwhile, next-door neighbor Ohio ranked first. The 1993 Top 20 Business Climates list in "Site Selection" did not include Pennsylvania. While it is difficult to know precisely how the southwestern Pennsylvania region performs in business attraction and retention, there is a consensus that there is room for improvement.
<P>
"There is a clear need that we can and should do better than we are," says Tim McNulty, director, Center for Economic Development, Carnegie Mellon University. "I think that the real focus for the region should be on retention and start-up." 
<P>
There has been disagreement over the regional economy's per-formance in recent years. A "White Paper" developed under Robert Mehrabian, CMU president, gives a gloomy assessment of manufacturing - it fell from 27.7% of the employment base in 1970 to 11.7% in 1990. Some 40 industrial plants permanently closed in Allegheny County from 1979 to 1985.
<P>
Reports by the University of Pittsburgh's Center for Social and Urban Research are more rosy. Ralph Bangs, co-author of the Pitt study, shows that from 1987 to 1992, Allegheny County had the second highest rate of growth in per-capita personal income among the nation's 50 largest counties, a key indicator of economic growth. The county also had higher than average job growth.
Both studies agree, however, on the region's liabilities. In fact, most analyses of the region come to the same conclusion: We have negative labor-management relations, a punitive tax structure and a lack of regionally coordinated marketing. Which hurts the most?
<P>
"I would vote for all three,"   says Thomas J. Murrin, dean of Duquesne University's School of Business and Administration. 
<P>
Murrin argues that the negative labor-management image is mostly a misperception. The area's high level of unionization gives it a global reputation as an old mill town where labor and management are constantly bickering.
<P>
Publicized strikes at the Port Authority, Giant Eagle, Moonlight Mushroom Co., The Pittsburgh Press, Allegheny Ludlum and a number of school districts have fueled the fire. In 1993, Fortune magazine ranked Pittsburgh's labor relations as America's worst.
<P>
According to a 1994 study by Tripp-Umbach & Associates Inc. for the Conference on Real Estate of Southwestern Pennsylvania, 47 states have lower levels of union elections than Pennsylvania.
<P>
For many, unions mean higher operating costs and strikes. The Tripp-Umbach study concludes: "A number of the companies we interviewed confirmed that union activity (both perceived and real) is still a serious deterrent to attracting new employers, especially manu-facturing companies, to the region. It is not just an issue for those trying to attract new companies, union-ization is also an issue effecting business retention and expansion."
<P>
The Three Rivers Labor and Management Committee says 98% of the region's labor disputes are resolved without a strike. Still the 2% that aren't settled promulgate the negative image.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Make a Pledge</B></font size> <BR>
A report from the Regional Economic Revitalization Initiative, which was developed at CMU's Center for Economic Development as a result of the white paper, calls for the establishment of a Pittsburgh Pledge between labor and man-agement to "use all means possible to resolve disputes without a strike" and "help establish a new era of labor-management partnership" to clean up the image.
<P>
Murrin is hopeful that the pledge will help. The problem is "as much a management challenge as a labor challenge. It's not one-sided," says Barry Maciak, director of Duquesne University's Connelly Center for Entrepreneurship and Emerging Enterprise.
<P>
Our second liability, a punitive tax structure, is quite damaging, too. "Everyone seems to agree that [our tax structure is one of the] worst in the nation," says Murrin. "That's terrible. It's a major deterrent not only to attract new businesses but also to retain the current ones."
<P>
Pennsylvania has the country's highest corporate taxes. Until recently, the state had the second highest corporate net income tax rate at 12.5%. In the Tripp-Umbach study, the region's CNI tax rate was significantly higher than much of its competition. Also, Pennsylvania is one of only 15 states that has both a corporate income tax and a capital stock and franchise tax.
<P>
Taxes ranked as the No. 1 issue facing Pennsylvania companies in a survey of commonwealth business leaders published by Coopers & Lybrand L.L.P. in September 1994. Although the "Fourth Annual Pennsylvania Economic Survey" yielded the most optimistic responses in its history, "... it's clear that we still have some serious work to do in terms of improving the overall business climate of the state," says Warren Jones, managing partner of Coopers & Lybrand, Pittsburgh.
<P>
Despite the tax problem and the poor labor-management image, many see a panacea for the area's ills: greater regional cooperation to promote our strengths. "We need to work on ... building a better image for Pennsylvania and a perception of a solid economic base," says Jones.
<P>
The region has an outstanding quality of life, excellent work force, impressive philanthropic network, world-class educational facilities and blossoming technologies.
<P>
Pittsburgh's high quality of life earned it the nation's highest livability ranking 10 years ago by "Places Rated Almanac," rating well in education, healthcare, housing and safety. (The city is currently ranked fifth in livability.)
<P>
In recent years, the city has been recognized as the Safest U.S. City Over 1 Million Population by Century 21 Real Estate and the Sixth Best City for Raising Children by Savvy magazine, among other accolades.
<P>
"One of the biggest selling points Pittsburgh has to potential businesses is its traditional neigh-borhoods," says Cathy Curley, media communications specialist, Neigh-bor Fair Pittsburgh Inc. 
<P>
The city also has major league baseball, football and hockey teams, and outstanding fine arts. "Look at the downtown cultural district - the Pittsburgh Opera, the symphony, the ballet - then cross the bridge to the Warhol museum," says Curley, "Go to Oakland and the nationality rooms at Pitt, the Carnegie Library and museums. Those are all big attractions. That has to serve as an advantage to businesses."
<P>
The region also has strong technology capabilities in environmental engineering and reme-diation, information technology, healthcare, biomedicine, software, specialty metals and high per-formance manufacturing. Some say technology will play a large role in our future.
<P>
"I think it's the future of the city," says Lawrence McGeehan, president, Ben Franklin Technology Center of Western Pennsylvania. He adds that if the region is going to remain in the forefront, it needs to continue to manufacture. "The kind of manufacturing that we can compete in is in producing knowledge-driven manufacturing products," he says.
<P>
A group of industrialists from Pennsylvania, Ohio and West Virginia recently formed a private foundation to develop a high performance manufacturing zone in the tristate region. In November, 45 industrialists had the first meeting for the project, which encompasses 10 counties in Pennsylvania, and 15 each in Ohio and West Virginia.
<P>
"[The project] allows the region to look at its strengths and needs and inform local governments what changes are needed to help improve high performance manufacturing," says Maciak, whose center is a temporary home for the foundation. 
<P>
According to Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., the organization will be an industrially focused effort "with the objective of making us globally competitive."
<P>
Maciak feels that nearby states should be seen as partners in a global economy and models of the best practices, not rivals. "The future of high performance manu-facturing in the region is tied real close to neighboring regions," he says, "because a lot of economic activity occurs between state lines. We need those lines to disappear. ... We need to look beyond  south-western Pennsylvania."
<P>
The region does need to aggressively enter the global economy to take advantage of an increasingly economically inter-dependent world. A Penn State study indicates that the overriding problems facing Pennsylvania manufacturers in the 1990s are competitive in scope. "These [problems] are simply symptoms of an underlying challenge to the state's abilities to become a more vibrant and competitive player in the national and world economy," says David L. Passmore, professor of vocational education at Penn State in University Park.
<P>
According to a 1994 study by the Southwestern Pennsylvania Regional Development Council, "there is very little interest in international trade between the region's small- and medium-sized manufacturers - exporters and nonexporters alike" despite countless studies documenting the benefits of foreign sales. Worse yet, the report notes, "perhaps most surprising is the point that the local manufacturers are aware of these benefits."
<P>
If they know the rewards, why don't they export?
<P>
"What we find is a psychology where a businessman will say, I don't want to try something hard that I don't know.' It is a fear of the unknown - an intimidation," says Rita L. Pollock, executive director, SPRDC. "Also, many simply don't know how to export. [They ask,] How am I going to get paid, in dollars or foreign currency? Who will buy my products?' They simply don't know because they've never done it before."
<P>
Pollock notes that many local firms have no problem establishing ties in, say, California, but outside of the country, even in Canada, is out of the question.
<P>
To overcome such fears, Pollock advocates creating "a culture of exporting" through publicity and education. She argues that export success by some will give others the confidence to do the same. 
<P>
Pollock's group wants to attract local companies to trade shows that might give them a valuable foothold in the global marketplace. Response is poor, however. Sometimes a mailing to 300 or 400 manufacturers will net as few as six responses.
<P>
Another organization poised to assist is the World Trade Center Pittsburgh, which, among other things, sponsors matchmaking sessions for local companies and international representatives to discuss partnerships. A recent example: a three-day event introduced environmental techno-logy companies based here to markets in Latin America. The group is joining with the Nicaragua/ Pittsburgh Cooperative Program and Duquesne's Small Business Devel-opment Center to sponsor a Nicaraguan trade and investment mission later this month.
<P>
World Trade Center Pittsburgh is also part of the Western Pennsylvania Export Consortium, which includes the Pittsburgh offices of the U.S. Department of Commerce and Small Business Administration, Duquesne's Small Business Devel-opment Center, the Ben Franklin Technology Center, the Western Pennsylvania District Export Council and SPRDC. The con-sortium brings together local, state and federal programs to provide market identification and assess-ment, market penetration, and on-line and direct-access services.
<P>
Additionally, the Pennsylvania Department of Commerce has instituted the Pennsylvania Export Partnership Trade Event Program to provide financial incentives for  manufacturers.
<P>
Despite such programs, a January 1994 report by Pitt's Center for Social and Urban Research concludes: "The region should do a better job promoting foreign exports, especially with the increased opportunities available through the recent NAFTA and GATT agreements. Foreign export assistance agencies tend to be small, understaffed and underfunded. Both duplication of services and gaps in services are perceived to exist. Further, the scattered and fragmented delivery of services creates barriers to firms receiving the full range of services needed. Export assistance agencies need to coordinate themselves and improve programs."
<P>
Most everyone agrees on the need for enhanced cooperation among economic development agencies.
<P>
"We need strategic planning for economic development more than once every 10 years," says Bangs, referring to the reports completed by the Allegheny Conference on Community Development in 1984 and 1994. "We need a strategic planning organization which has the expertise to do good economic analysis on an on-going basis, in-cluding analysis of the region's strengths and weaknesses, as      well as the ability to forecast        the likely economic impacts of  strategic plans."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Look to Albany</B></font size> <BR>
Ron Gdovic is a local economic development consultant who has analyzed regional development planning organizations throughout the country. He recommends that the region look at the Center for Economic Growth in Albany, N.Y., as a prototype. Albany's center focuses on job creation through the attraction and expansion of business. It cooperates with the Albany Times Union and the Rockefeller Institute to promote regional cooperation and consol-idation of government functions.
<P>
"The Albany group, in my opinion, is the best model for this area," says Gdovic. "The key to that group is that it is an umbrella organization that coordinates efforts, and that's what south-western Pennsylvania is lacking. What also makes it effective is its relationship to the media. The key to the media link is that it helps promote not only the region but also the organization."
<P>
The recently completed RERI report, "The Greater Pittsburgh Region: Working Together to Compete Globally," goes a long way toward exploiting regional assets, laying out a strategy that incor-porates real-world suggestions into an action-oriented timetable.
<P>
The report is the product of a nine-month effort by local civic leaders to develop a vision for economic development for Greater Pittsburgh.
<P>
"There was a sense throughout the community to balance a need for greater coordination, while also trying to retain some of the strengths of decentralization," says McNulty. "We call for creating a unified marketing strategy. That is one of our top priorities."
<P>
Within the report is a plan to stimulate job growth in the region's advanced technology sector. The report calls for mentoring teams from a cross section of public, private and community leadership to support an R&D effort to make Pittsburgh the robotics capital of the world, establish the biomedical industry of tomorrow (through a tissue engineering initiative) and create the sustainable Pittsburgh environmental initiative.
<P>
The report calls for improving the links between Greater Pittsburgh and the world economy and creating an independent tax council charged with developing a reform for the state development business plan. According to McNulty, some actions were to take place within 100 days after the report's release on Nov. 17, 1994.
<P>
The RERI report, says Maciak, "challenges us to take those initiatives and make something happen." Murrin echoes those senti-ments: "[The report] is tremendous, with all of these worthwhile ideas. Now we come to the most impor-tant part-implementation." Indeed, the region's ability to act on the report will say a lot about its ability to serve its future economic interests at home and abroad.
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Our Internationalism Report Card</B></font size> <BR>
<PRE>
