<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report February 1995 Issue</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<hr>
<center><!a href="[fill]"><!img border=0 src="Ads/[fill].gif"></center></a>
<!hr>
<img align=left src="../pictures/0295.Update.1.gif"><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Learning To Cope: </FONT SIZE></B>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>There can be no doubt that stress exists in the workplace, and that it is damaging to both worker and company.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
<HR>
On an unseasonably warm and drizzly day early last December, seven employees of the Westinghouse Energy Center gathered around a conference table during their lunch hour, eating hamburgers, salads and vanilla frozen yogurt out of plastic cafeteria carry-out containers. Much of the talk centered around the devastating layoffs that had gone into effect at Westinghouse the previous week, cutting 20% of the 1,500 employed at the energy center alone, as the group shared job, family and community worries and optimisms.
<P>
The group, members of the Pittsburgh Experiment, an inter-denominational ministry that provides spiritual resources to the business community, also shares prayers. This meeting, and the dozens like it that take place throughout the area in any given week, are an uncommon solution to a common business problem: stress in the workplace.
<P>
"You see people getting on the berm, where it's easy to slide off and hit gravel, and you don't know who will survive," says one member. "There are a lot of people hurting and not enough people helping. They're saying, Thank goodness they're on the berm, not me.'"
<P>
"I think that's survival instinct," says another.
<P>
"Those left are absorbing even more work, and that drives you even closer to the berm," points out another. "I know one secretary who now has 20 [executives]. She's on the berm just thinking about it."
<P>
"I've also felt grief. Members of this group have been laid off," says a fourth member. "One volunteered himself - that was a gutsy move. I've survived 13 layoffs. Now I try to turn it over to God, and not sweat the details, but I wasn't always this way. I try to put it in perspective."
<P>
And so the discussion goes, each member taking a turn to voice concerns, affirm the worries of others and occasionally to offer advice. For 40 years, the small groups of the Pittsburgh Experiment have con-ducted what the secular world might term "group therapy." The group comes together via a collective faith in God, and support is lent by talking amongst themselves and praying for one another. It is not an official program of Westinghouse, but according to Jim Mottley, the group's leader, the company encourages the group and lends its support in the form of a meeting place.
<P>
"This location is good at promoting stress management," says Mottley, for 30 years a fellow engineer with Westinghouse. "They have an excellent workout facility; counseling is available and so are courses on stress management. This meeting is thought of as another outlet for stress."
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>What's the Damage?</B></FONT SIZE><br>
There can be no doubt that stress exists in the workplace, and that it is damaging to both worker and company. Just look at the facts:
<P>
 Sixty-seven percent of all visits to family doctors are prompted by stress-related symptoms, including asthma, allergies, headaches, excessive fatigue, indigestion, loss of appetite, insomnia, nausea, anger, anxiety, irritability and depression. (Source: The American Academy of Family Physicians)
<P>
 Forty-six percent of a 1991 random sample of U.S. workers said their jobs were highly stressful, up from 20% in 1985. Thirty-nine percent said they felt so much stress they were thinking of quitting. Only 4% said they were nearly stress-free. Respondents having multiple stress-related illnesses increased from 13% in 1985 to 25% in 1991. Thirty-five percent reported that stress caused them to leave their last job. Seventeen percent reported that stress caused them to miss one or more days of work in 1990. (Source: Northwestern National Life Insurance Co.)
<P>
 More than 1 million days of absenteeism and more than $20 bil-lion in workers' compensation costs each year can be traced to stress. (Source: Paul Siegel, attorney, Jackson, Lewis, Schnitzler and Krupman)
<P>
 The average stress-related workers' compensation claim costs employers at least $13,339. (Source: The National Council on Compensation Insurance)
<P>
 Stress-related illnesses cost U.S. industry more than $150 billion annually. (Source: Dr. Peter Hanson, author of "The Joy of Stress")
<P>
 Job stress can triple the risk of high blood pressure and cause potentially dangerous physical changes to the heart. (Source: 1990 study by Cornell University Medical School)
<P>
At work or at home, stress is not caused by external forces, but rather by one's perceptions of events. One man's heart attack is another man's hobby. We have become a society of go and do - a double curse. For when we are going and doing, our bodies long to slow down and smell the rain. And when we do tarry, then we consider ourselves to be laggards.
<P>
"We need stress to keep ourselves motivated to get out of bed in the morning," says Anne M. Kowatch, R.N., manager of administration for Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania's health promotion services. "The catch is, however, that we have to learn to manage it and know when it is too much."
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Pump You Up</B></FONT SIZE><br>
So what exactly is stress?
<P>
"Physically, stress is a patterned physical reaction; the body is pumping itself up to cope with a stressful event or situation," says Joe Cvitkovic, Ph.D., of South Hills Health System. Physically, stress can increase the heart rate, bring on irritability and sleeplessness, even lead to complaints like asthma or muscle cramping. Emotionally, stress can cause depression, anxiety, disassociation and memory lapse. "Because they become so absorbed in stressful situations, some people actually detach from reality. Work performance decreases because it is difficult to concentrate on the job."
<P>
It is difficult, after digesting the litany of dire stress-induced reactions, to believe that stress is all in how you look at things. There is no doubt, however, that certain workaday  factors are practically guaranteed to cause stress: a down economy, an uncaring supervisor, unrelenting corporate policies. What do these things have in common? Workers cannot control them.
<P>
"I have never, in 20-plus years in psychology, talked to so many un-happy workers as in the past couple of years in the Pittsburgh area," says Cvitkovic. "Employees work under constant fear. There used to be a cradle-to-grave contract between employee and employer, and a feeling that their identity was part of that. Now, with massive layoffs, that identity is threatened."
<P>
Many companies recognize that and bring specialists like Cvitkovic into the work environment for sessions in change.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Talking Cure</B></FONT SIZE><br>
"People do have to talk, do have to process," says Cvitkovic. "A stress specialist can organize some discussion and help the company be sensitive to the kind of grieving that goes on as a result of downsizing. There are ways to organize our lives so our whole being and existence doesn't revolve around work - people need to rethink how they fit into the world of work and how they can function by getting enough healthy involvement in other parts of their lives."
<P>
This sounds an awful lot like the small group philosophy of the Pittsburgh Experiment, minus God. Balance, support, understanding - all of these are acknowledged to help decrease stress. And, of course, all of these could be introduced into the workplace before a catastrophic occurrence. But some say that companies are less willing to spend money on prevention in this area.
<P>
"Even five or six years ago, this was a bigger topic," says Debra Trachy, of Trachy Healthcare Management Co. "The issue is trying to divine a direct result, like: because there were x stress management classes they had fewer days of sick time."
<P>
Others say that stress prevention has not been abandoned by corporations, but that those efforts show up as more specific programs.
<P>
"For years, people were saying we've got to get rid of stress," says Paul Kowatch, manager of Allegheny General Hospital's Employee Assistance Program and president of the Pittsburgh chapter of the Employee Assistance Professional Association. "But now we've realized that stress is here to stay, and we are dealing with it in different ways, like providing elder care and child care resources for employees. But, again, it is hard to measure."
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Tangible Results</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Aerospace giant McDonnell Douglas Corp., St. Louis, however, did spend the time and money to evaluate the results of its EAP, and found that the program will save $5.1 million in reduced time off, health claims and attrition over three years.
<P>
"EAPs were started in the '40s as occupational alcohol programs," says Kowatch. "But there was a big change and growth in EAPs in the '80s, and now we place a lot of emphasis on stress, whether it comes from the job, family life or both. It makes good business sense - we spend half our waking hours at work, and it is hard to leave our personal problems out of the workplace."
<P>
One benchmark of corporate interest in prevention is that membership in Pittsburgh's local chapter of EAPA is up to nearly 100 members, from around 40 three or four years ago, according to Kowatch. Most EAPs educate employees on substance abuse, stress and the nature of change, and provide assessment, short-term counseling and referrals to other resources. Employees and family members (which AGH loosely defines as people with whom the employee has close personal relationships) can avail themselves of the services.
<P>
But education in stress doesn't mean just teaching coping skills any longer. AGH offers a bevy of seminars in areas that can lead to stress, or result from stress. Besides the usual advice on exercise and nutrition, employees have access to education on budgeting and the wise use of credit and forming healthy relationships. AGH also has the Quality Resource Center, a self-development office where employees can access a multitude of resources. AGH has a family loan program, which allows families to borrow money at low interest. Another program enables AGH employees to purchase homes on Pittsburgh's North Side at reduced cost, helping to finance half the down payment and most of the closing costs.
<P>
Companies are taking all sorts of innovative approaches to derailing stress. Providing child care and elder care are popular with hospitals and universities here, but less common among manufacturers and corpo-rations. One way that local employers have provided child care is to fund a consortium day care center downtown. City, state and foundation monies, along with contributions from corporations, provided the money needed to build the center at One Smithfield Street, which houses elder care, child care and the get-well room, a facility which will accept children with mild illnesses, so that parents do not miss work.
<P>
Another response to stress is the increasing number of companies instituting flex-time.
<P>
"Flex-time gives the employee more control and it works," says Rex Gatto, president of Gatto Training Associates, a local consulting firm. "The company says, in effect, we would like you to come when you are most productive. It can reduce time pressures, and treats the employee like an adult."
<P>
And that, it seems, is what every-one wants. Not only to be treated like an adult, but like a human, rather than a numbered cog.
<P>
"It doesn't take a lot to be sensitive to the employee and [what his behavior is telling you]," says Anne Kowatch of Blue Cross' Health Promotion Services. (If you caught it, yes, Paul Kowatch of AGH and Anne, are husband and wife.) "Sometimes, someone that is very vivacious will turn inward. Some people actually break down. Some people are sick a lot, with minor problems. Some will show decreased production. But sometimes, it is more subtle.
<P>
"I said hello to a person today and [she] said My grandmother fell and broke her hip last night.'   Obviously, that's going to be on her mind," Kowatch says. "So I offered to help her locate resources to help her solve her problem. Supervisors can be taught and encouraged to handle what's going on."
<P>
Programs aside, experts agree that one of the most effective stress reducers - understanding - is free.
<P>
"Corporations have become so impersonal that it almost paralyzes quality and empowerment, but they don't carry through. That makes stress worse."
<P>
To reduce stress and improve quality, Gatto says, just takes common sense.
<P>
"Ask employees What will cause us to have quality?' and listen," he says. "It will give them a sense of fulfilling their own destiny."
<P>
And nothing relieves stress more. 
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
