</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report February 1995 Issue: Update</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<hr>
<center><!a href="[fill]"><!img border=0 src="Ads/[fill].gif"></center></a>
<!hr>
<B><h2>Steel City Going Soft</h2></B>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>While Pittsburgh has not quite shaken off its image as a steel town, it has quietly become one of the leading software centers in the country.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By John Schriefer</i>
<HR>
When you think of software, you think of Silicon Valley or Seattle; Pittsburgh still can conjure up thoughts of steel. But south-western Pennsylvania has developed into one of the top software producing areas in the United States. It now ranks fifth in software industry employment, just behind Silicon Valley, Boston, Seattle and the Austin-Dallas corridor in Texas.
<P>
Pittsburgh does not have any highly visible, dominant software companies, like Microsoft in Seattle. Nor is there an obvious connection between the software industry and a thriving microchip or computer industry. What this area does have, however, is technical and business resources, a strong engineering tradition and one of the top computer science universities in the world, Carnegie Mellon.
<P>
CMU's influence is enormous. The university has drawn federal software research to Pittsburgh. It has estab-lished major research institutions like the Software Engineering Institute and Pittsburgh Supercomputing Center.
<P>
Dennis Yablonsky, president of The Carnegie Group, says that Carnegie Mellon's "open attitude toward spin-offs" has been important. His company, for example, was founded in 1984 by four CMU professors who commercialized their academic research with funding from Digital Equipment Corp.
Pittsburgh's Fortune 500 companies have provided their own spin-off contributions to the software industry -  selling internally developed software to the outside. 
<P>
The number of big corporations headquartered in Pittsburgh gives the city good business support infrastruc-ture - accounting, law and financial firms - lacking in some other cities. Says Michael Pochan of Monroeville-based LeaseTek, "Pittsburgh is a smaller city with a lot of big city attributes."
<P>
"In the early days," remembers Pochan, "when we didn't have any money, [CPA firms like Ernst & Young] gave us a lot of free advice." Pochan and his partner also got advice from executives at established software firms.
<P>
The best known of these early software mentors was Glen Chatfield, founder and president of Duquesne Systems. The company, which was started in 1970 as a provider of software for IBM mainframe computers, was in the early 1980s one of the world leaders in the field. By 1989, Duquesne Systems had grown to $100 million in sales, and it was merged the following year to form Legent Corp., the world's second largest software company for IBM mainframes.
<P>
Chatfield took an active role in promoting the development of high-tech industries in the region, sharing his knowledge and experience with software start-ups and establishing a local high-tech venture capital fund. This tradition of involvement continues with other successful managers, including Yablonsky, taking leadership roles in new efforts to further grow the industry.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Success Breeds Success</B></FONT SIZE><br>
For example, Chatfield, Yablonsky and Alfred Spector (a former CMU professor who founded Transarc Corp. in 1989) are co-chairs of the Pittsburgh Software Business Forum founded last year to promote the exchange of ideas and information between local companies.
<P>
Besides actively promoting the industry, local software executives say Chatfield's success demonstrated to other budding entrepreneurs what could be achieved. Says Mike Bussler of Algor Inc., "It doesn't take many success stories to provide a kind of catalytic reaction."
<P>
Adds Yablonsky, "It's certainly im-portant to have a few big oaks. Up to the late 1980s, it was Duquesne Systems. That was probably the only company with over 50 employees. Now there are 10 to 12 with more than 100 employees."
<P>
Today, the objective is to promote the development of more oaks among the 300-plus mostly smaller companies already in the region. Yablonsky suggests that further development will occur as new companies spin off from the established leaders, and that industry employment will increase to 20,000 by the turn of the century from just under 10,000 today.
<P>
The only things holding back the industry from faster growth are a relative scarcity of venture capital to fund start-up ventures; few management professionals with experience in small, growing companies, and a traditionally conservative, nonentrepreneurial business culture.
<P>
"Twenty years ago," says Yablonsky, a Pittsburgh native lured back in 1987 to manage The Carnegie Group, "it defi-nitely was not OK to be an entrepre-neur. ... If you couldn't go to work for PPG or Westinghouse, and you had to start your own business, [people said,] Isn't that too bad.' " He contrasts that to Silicon Valley, where "not only is it OK to be an entrepreneur, it is desirable."
<P>
This is evidently less of a problem in the software sector than in other local industries, as eight new companies have already been formed by former Duquesne Systems/Legent employees, and four software start-ups have been started by ex-Carnegie Group people. 
<P>
Though entrepreneurship and a large number of spin-off companies is a good sign for future development in the region, spin-offs also present a challenge. Says attorney Gregory Jordan of Reed Smith Shaw & McClay, "If you allow people from within to simply copy and take [know-how of your product], and set up a direct competitor ... that is not a help to the region." 
<P>
Though most of the separations locally have been friendly, the employee and the former employer have had to negotiate a settlement in some cases. 
<P>
A more immediate and unique problem for Pittsburgh-area software start-ups in particular is capital availability. Theodore Glyptis, a partner in charge of the high technology practice at Coopers & Lybrand/Pittsburgh and an advisor to the Software Business Forum, notes that many companies today have to look for venture capital funding outside of Pittsburgh. And Yablonsky says many in the industry complain that it is relatively hard to get seed capital in Pittsburgh for early product development. (It is not so tough, he says, to find growth capital.)
<P>
Local software companies also have had to reach beyond the local market for executive talent. Says Yablonsky, "You don't have a lot of people with experience taking a $1 million company to a $50 mil-lion company, so [there's] a lot of recruiting from outside."
<P>
Despite these few potential bottlenecks, all signs point to further development in the Pittsburgh-area software industry. Companies that have staked out a place in global markets - like Algor, The Carnegie Group and LeaseTek - seem set for continued strong growth. New entries like Dasys, a start-up founded by three Carnegie Mellon Ph.D.s, indicate that there is plenty of  talent waiting to make a mark.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Seizing the Opportunity</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Monroeville-based LeaseTek is to leasing software what WordPerfect is to word processing and Lotus is to spread-sheets. Like these better-known software companies, LeaseTek's success is the re-sult of recognizing the market potential presented by the IBM PC and developing a unique, feature-rich application.
<P>
LeaseTek's products enable auto and equipment leasing companies to perform complex lease term analysis and to process credit applications on a standard personal computer. When partners Michael Pochan and Robert Culbertson got into the business in 1983, the first IBM PC had just been introduced, and leasing was only beginning to take off. The two CMU engineering graduates, who also attended the Graduate School of Industrial Administration together, quickly saw the potential of the IBM PC. 
<P>
"We decided that our goal was to become a software company, except we had no idea what our market would be," says Pochan. The partners had three false starts before hitting on the idea of leasing software  in October 1983.
<P>
To generate cash flow while they sought out a profitable product niche, the partners did consulting work. In the course of one consulting project for Algor, Mike Bussler, the president of Algor, mentioned that his car lessor was always complaining that he couldn't find any leasing software for his PC.
<P>
A little research convinced them that leasing was what they were looking for. "It is a complex problem that is tough to solve; the niche it is in is growing dramatically ... and there is hardly any competition," says Pochan.
<P>
By February 1984, they had delivered a first version of the product to Bussler's lessor. In the following months they marketed and refined it further for other local car dealers, including Bill Gray Leasing, which uses LeaseTek soft-ware to this day. Pochan and Culbertson continued to do consulting work to generate cash flow - as the software package "didn't just sell 1 million copies the first day," Pochan says.
<P>
For the first year, all sales were based on word-of-mouth referrals, including the first sale outside of Pittsburgh (in Cleveland). Then, in 1985, Pochan and Culbertson attended a leasing conference in Atlantic City and hooked up with New York/New Jersey lessors and national leasing associations. That marked the beginning of a fast growth phase that landed LeaseTek on Fortune magazine's 1991 list of the 500 fastest growing privately held companies.
<P>
Today, LeaseTek sells its software in 10 countries, mostly in Europe. In addi-tion to English, there are Spanish, Italian and French language versions of its software packages, which now include six closely related programs.
<P>
According to Pochan, Europe accounted for about 10% of LeaseTek's predicted sales of $2.8 million in 1994.  In 1995, he says, it will account for half. In anticipation of fast growth, this quarter LeaseTek will open a sales and support office in the United Kingdom. It has recently doubled its office space, and planned on hiring 15 new employees, bringing the staff count to 50.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>The Indirect Route</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Algor founder Mike Bussler got into the software business by a roundabout route. Like LeaseTek, Algor anticipated the PC revolution, and made the most of it.
<P>
At about the same time as Bussler put the LeaseTek founders on the scent of what became their market niche, he was in the process of transforming Algor from an engineering services bureau into a package software company. Algor's original software products - there are now 80 separate modules - grew out of computer time-share services it had been providing to Pittsburgh-area engineering firms since 1977. Bussler says he began writing custom software programs for his customers, and "sort of inadvertently developed packages" that could be used for any number of general engineering applications. In 1985, Algor translated its software to run on Digital Equipment Corp.'s VAX computers and also IBM PCs. "Putting this stuff on PCs was revolutionary," Bussler says.
<P>
Still, the software was not an immediate hit. Says Bussler, "Most people thought it wasn't a real serious thing, to try to do this on PCs." That changed when IBM introduced more powerful second- and third-generation PCs beginning in 1986. The PCs could now handle higher demands, giving Algor a jump on the engineering soft-ware market. 
<P>
Algor's software today enables engineers using a standard personal computer to predict how a product they are designing will perform under real-world stresses. Among products designed using Algor software are Black & Decker's Dustbuster and Nautilus exercise equipment. The software was also used recently by engineers restoring the 111-year-old Smithfield Street Bridge. 
<P>
Though some of its competitors are billion-dollar companies, Algor has maintained a comfortable share of the engineering software market. Bussler sees one key to keeping ahead of the field. "It won't do to be competitive locally - that's not good enough. To be competitive nationally - that's not good enough. You have to be competitive globally. That means you need the best people you can find, period."
<P>
Algor has found those people - currently 75 - in southwestern Pennsylvania, elsewhere in the United States and overseas. The company's customer base is skewed even more to the outside: Only about 100 of Algor's 10,000 customers are in Pittsburgh.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Continuing Tradition</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Most of the software coming out of Pittsburgh today is targeted at a specific product niche. Many others, however, are for more esoteric engi-neering and production functions.
<P>
Consider Dasys Inc., a company started in 1991 that develops software to automate the design of electronic circuits. Explains President David Springer, the software allows designers to describe what they want the circuit to do, and the program figures out how to do it, either by designing a custom integrated circuit (like the microchip that controls your computer's video display) or many ICs in combination. The program determines a sequence of functions to be performed by the circuit, selects components and then provides the wiring design.
<P>
Like their longer-established associates in the Pittsburgh software community, Springer and his partners see nothing but opportunity selling to the world software made in the cradle of the American steel industry.     

<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Selected Makers</B></FONT SIZE><br>
There are scores of interesting software makers here in southwestern Pennsylvania. Stephen David, president of Applied Quality Methods Inc., is developing software for implementing total quality management. He says the idea was originally conceived by Steve Heilman, founder and director of Medrad, and initially was healthcare oriented. Now the idea is to have TQM within reach of everyone. "It's for reducing costs and improving quality at the same time," says David. The company plans to market the package nationally next year.
<P>
Much of the software developed here is healthcare related although developments abound in other industries and for personal computers as well. Several major insurance companies and Fortune 500 in-house legal departments are reviewing a system developed by Carol Ross, president and CEO of Lecor Inc. Over the past four years, Ross has invested more than $1 million in R&D for the Lecor System. The program is intended to dramatically reduce legal costs associated with litigation management. The system recently produced a comprehensive billing report for a Fortune 500 company in eight minutes, compared to the two days the process previously took. Ross says the law firm management package can reduce mass representation defense costs by 30% to 70%.                                     

