<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report <fill> 1994 Issue</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"><FONT SIZE=+2><B> Behind the Scenes</B></FONT SIZE><i> By Linda A. Dickerson</i>
<HR>
Last year, the Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre produced a brilliant performance of Cinderella. For me, this production was a poignant reminder of the arts community's plight.
<P>
The arts community is one of the most underappreciated segments of the broader community. In many ways, its situation is analogous to Cinderella's. Employing almost 9,500 individuals full time with a payroll of over $2.3 million, the arts sector is a significant contributor to the region's economic vitality.
<P>
Those who attend the fine performances or exhibits of the more than 150 arts groups in the area appreciate the art form but not necessarily the arts organization. Arts organizations spend over  $270 million dollars annually. Studies estimate that beyond their direct expenditures, arts organizations generate $235 million in spending on ancillary activities such as hotel stays, dining out and parking.
<P>
One can quibble about the exact amounts, but not about the order of magnitude. Arts organizations from the Pittsburgh Symphony to the River City Brass Band to the Tuesday Musical Club are critical to the region's fiscal well-being. Apart from their immense contributions to this area's psyche through the enjoyment they provide to more than 12 million patrons, arts groups are a key component of the region's economic framework.
<P>
Consequently, we must work cooperatively to solidify the arts community's current position. As arts organizations flourish, the ambiance of the community as a whole improves.
<P>
Often viewed as the domain of only the rich and famous, arts organizations are rarely recognized for the enormity and value of their overall contribution. Children in the Hill District have the same senses to be awakened by the melodious tones of the American Wind Symphony as do those from Sewickley. Senior citizens enjoy the dance of the sugarplum fairies as much as a child on a first grade field trip to The Benedum. Art forms are a universal language.
<P>
Arts organizations can and should embrace an entire community, reaching out to every nook and cranny to engage all people in experiences unavailable through any other means.
<P>
Despite arts organizations' proven track record of engaging eclectic groups of people in their volunteer bases and their audiences, we still treat arts organizations largely as unwanted stepchildren.
<P>
Perhaps it's time to invite Cinderella to the ball. By nurturing our arts community, we ensure a vibrant, energetic and alive downtown, and we enhance everyone's quality of life.
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
