<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report <fill> 1994 Issue</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a><P>
<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.</I>
<HR>
<P>
Sharp declines in four of the companies included in the Executive Report Index contri-buted to a decline of 4.3% for the month ended Dec. 9. In spite of the poor showing, the ER Index remains well ahead of the S&P 500, which declined 3.4% during the same period. Since inception on Aug. 15, the ER Index is up 0.2% while the S&P 500 has lost more than 3% of its value.
<P>
Johnstown America led the list of losers, down a whopping 43%, as some of its analysts cut estimates and expressed concern over the company's continuing string of disap-pointments. Nevertheless, the company says business, as measured by backlog and new orders, continues to be strong and that sell-off is unwarranted.
<P>
American Eagle Outfitters, which bears no relation to the airline of similar name, has coincidentally experienced a few crashes of its own. The company lost 26% of its value during the past month, following a decline in enthusiasm for the specialty apparel chain's growth prospects. Alex. Brown & Sons cut its rating of the stock, citing weak same-store sales figures and less than sterling holiday sales. But the bottom line is still healthy, and profits from the holiday selling season are expected to be up more than 40% from last year.
<P>
Mellon Bank was down more than 13%, following the company's disclosure that it would take a fourth quarter charge of $130 mil-lion, or 88 cents per share, for losses on derivatives tied to interest rates. Since August, the stock has dropped from $38 per share to $30.75. Seeking to bolster its price, Mellon announced in late November that its board had authorized a repurchase of up to 3 million shares.
<P>
Kennametal also declined by nearly 13%, as concern over cyclical stocks weighed on the market. Kennametal is experiencing strong demand for its products, and the potential exists for positive earnings surprises over the next several quarters, as pricing and margins both improve. The market, however, is clearly concerned about the effect of interest rates on industrial demand.
<P>
Other local companies in the news:

<P>
<DL>
<LI>Fore Systems continued its torrid pace, tacking on another 17%. Since Aug. 15, Fore has doubled, from $30 per share to nearly $60 per share, as analysts continue to raise their expectations about the company's portfolio of asynchronous transfer mode products. In mid-November, Fore announced a licensing deal with Alantec Corp., a leader in local area network switching, that should extend Fore's reach into the networking marketplace.
<LI>Alcoa announced a two-for-one stock split and raised its quarterly cash dividend 12.5%, effective this month. Alcoa continues to benefit from higher demand, higher prices and steadily declining inventories of aluminum ingot. In November, the company announced it would raise prices of can sheet by approximately 50%.
<LI>Amsco, in the midst of a turnaround, recently eliminated 160 salaried positions throughout its operations, including some in Erie and Pittsburgh. The company, which employs 3,150 worldwide, is expected to announce details of its restructuring this month. Under the leadership of new president and CEO Dan Barry, Amsco has already taken several significant steps to regain some measure of credibility. In November, Amsco withdrew its Food and Drug Administration application for a new vaporized hydrogen peroxide sterilizer, after it became clear that approval was not likely. The company's plan is to return to the drawing board and resubmit the product to the FDA sometime this year.
<LI>Tuscarora Inc., the New Brighton-based packaging manufacturer, reported record first-quarter earnings for the period ended Nov. 30. Net sales rose nearly 33% while net income jumped almost 52%. Earnings per share rose to 41 cents vs. 27 cents. The company attributed the super results to significant growth in its consumer electronics, high-tech, major appliance and automotive markets. Year-to-date orders are up nearly 40%. The company's recent acquisitions are also starting to contribute. Tuscarora raised its semiannual cash dividend to 11 cents per share, from 10 cents, the company's 21st consecutive annual increase.
<LI>Astrotech reported its performance is improving, with income from continuing operations more than doubling for the year ended Sept. 30. The company's acquisitions of Rubbaglas and Brown-Minneapolis Tank helped contribute to top-line growth, with revenues for the year increasing to $68.7 mil-lion from $39.5 million last year. Income from continuing operations was 9 cents per share for the year, vs. 7 cents in 1993. Astrotech has roughly 1.7 million shares more outstanding than a year ago, primarily because of its acquisitions. The company, whose products and services are targeted at the construction and maintenance of above-ground storage tanks, derives much of its business from the petroleum industry, and is aggressively focusing on the wastewater treatment, agricultural and pulp and paper markets. High utilization rates and environmental issues at refineries, both domestic and international, are fueling storage tank maintenance spending.
</DL>
<P>
<I>Doug Thomas is vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.</I>

