<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report 1995 Issue</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.C.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> Stressing and Obsessing</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Job insecurity is the No. 1 source of stress in the workplace today, according to Robert Half International of Menlo Park, Calif. A survey conducted by an independent research firm polled 150 executives from the nation's 1,000 largest companies.
<P>
"Despite the economic recovery, there is still a lingering uncertainty in the workplace," says Max Messmer, chairman and CEO of Robert Half. "Staffing cuts have been so deep in recent years that even those employees who have kept their jobs remain uneasy."
<P>
Messmer advises companies to be open with employees when belt tightening becomes necessary. "Managers who try to protect workers by hiding bad news are setting themselves up for disaster. It is the uncertainty that causes the most stress," Messmer says.
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> All Stressed Out</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Executives were asked, "Which of the following would you say is the No. 1 cause of stress in the workplace?"
<PRE>
Cause				Percent responding
Job insecurity			41%
Understaffing			32
Personality conflicts		9
External competitive pressures	8
Changing technology		7
Other				3
</PRE>
<i>Source: Robert Half International, Menlo Park, Calif.</i>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Vice Magazine</B></FONT SIZE><br>
The premiere of "The Working Wine Guide" was published by David R. DeSimone of Oakland last fall. DeSimone's goal is to highlight the best wine values available in western Pennsylvania at Pennsylvania Wine and Spirit Shops or through local wholesalers.
<P>
"Instead of using numerical ratings, we make specific, practical recommendations based on quality of production and value for the listed price," he says. The guide is not affiliated with any winery, wine distributor or the Pennsylvania Liquor Control Board, and DeSimone hopes people will pay $40 for the publication's bimonthly "unbiased opinion."
<P>
The first issue features a regular column on cigar smoking by Marc Adams of South Side's Bloom Cigar Co. Sales of premium cigars increased by 24% from 1989 to 1993, according to the Cigar Association of America in Washington, D.C.
<P>
Nationally, wine consump-tion is down, according to figures published by The Wall Street Journal. In 1993, table-wine shipments were down 3%, after a slight increase in 1992, following a 10-year slide.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Take It Private</B></FONT SIZE><br>
According to The Commonwealth Foundation of Harrisburg, Westmoreland County is one of the state's leaders in privatization. In 1992, the county contracted out $27 million of its $181 million operating budget to third-party providers.
<P>
Terry Marolt, Westmoreland County minority commissioner, believes privatization is popular because it saves tax funds.
<P>
"The most intelligent way to administer privatization is to get the government's role reduced and use administration more to distribute funds," says Marolt. "It works."
<P>
Marolt says about $20 mil-lion went to human services programs, with $17.9 million of it going to the mental health and retardation program. Other privatization programs included road maintenance, alcohol/drug treatment, cafeteria, janitorial, laundry, security, transportation and pharmaceutical services.
<P>
The county will continue to privatize where possible.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> Making Way for the Busway</B></FONT SIZE><br>
A U.S. Congressional conference committee approved $30 million for the Port Authority's airport busway/Wabash facility, according to the Allegheny County commissioners. The recommendation must get full House and Senate approval.
<P>
Phase one is an 8.1-mile project which includes a seven-mile bus-only roadway going from Carnegie to Station Square, where it will link with a new 1.1-mile HOV route via the Wabash Tunnel. From there, it will cross a new bridge over the Mon River and enter town on Fort Pitt Boulevard at Market Street.
<P>
PAT expects this to open in 1997, prior to the closing of the Fort Pitt Bridge and Tunnel.

<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> Teeming With Teamwork</B></FONT SIZE><br>
"Inside Teams," a new book by two execs at Development Dimensions International of Bridgeville and a consultant, chronicles the success of teamwork at 20 organizations, including three from around here.
<P>
The authors, Richard Wellins, William Byham and George Dixon, were particularly struck by three common factors:

 payoffs from 
teams are consistent across the organizations;
 the impact in many cases is in the range of 50% to 100%;
 teams improve many facets of the organization's business from quality to turnover.
<P>
At DDI there has been a 43% reduction in client-reported errors, and an increase of 65% in revenue per employee. At Mine Safety Appliances Co., there has been a 110%-plus increase in productivity.
<P>
Westinghouse Electric reports that teamwork has cut cycle time from 12 weeks to two, work-in-progress inventories by 65%, rework in half and product cost by 60%.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> New Business</B></FONT SIZE><br>
GCS Service Inc. of Danbury, Conn., has opened a Pittsburgh office for food service equipment maintenance. The first franchise of North Hills-based Betsy Ann Chocolates has opened in South Hills Village. Jay Design Almond Oatmeal Soap is operating in Oakland.

<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B> Correction</B></FONT SIZE><br>
Law firm Frank, Bails, Kirk, Murcko & Toal was inadvertently omitted from "Getting the Best Counsel" in the December 1994 Chronicles section. (The firm had one lawyer mentioned.) Executive Report regrets the erratum.

This month's Chronicles was written and compiled by Jane A. Black and Kristin Giron.           
