<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report January 1995 Issue: Feature</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.netservices.com/"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=top SRC="../zine/Ads/isc.tran.gif"></a>
<HR>
<b><h2>Reinventing Banking</h2></B><FONT SIZE=+1><b>PNC Bank Corp. has reorganized into a financial services conglomerate to battle the competition.</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Richard Bierck</i>
<HR>
Five years ago, PNC Bank Corp. decided not to act like a bank any longer - at least, not in the traditional sense.
<P>
Beset by voracious competition, PNC, then called Pittsburgh Financial Corp., reorganized to battle a horde of financial services companies.
After all, that's how nonbank competition had been operating to drain bank vaults of American wealth. In 1984, 50% of the nation's assets were in banks. That figure has dropped to 30%.
<P>
"We don't even talk about being in the banking business anymore. ... Now we're a financial services conglomerate," says Thomas H. O'Brien, PNC's chairman and CEO.
<P>
"Before [the reorganization], we were trying to give customers the products we had. They didn't happen to be the products that customers truly wanted."
<P>
From his corner office on the 30th floor of One PNC Plaza in downtown Pittsburgh, with his back to a panoramic view of Mount Washington and the three rivers, O'Brien likens banking's plight in recent years to that of department stores.
<P>
"High-quality, low-cost competitors were coming in, targeting niches, and department stores were getting picked off. Only strong depart-ment stores that were well-managed could survive.
<P>
"We were doing fine against Mellon [the nation's 22nd largest banking company] and Integra, who were good competitors. But there were Fidelity Funds, Merrill Lynch, GMAC - they were the competition. It could be characterized as a fist fight between banks. Meanwhile, someone is sneaking around and taking stuff out of the store."
<P>
The move to reorganize was dynamic by the standards of a stodgy industry still fettered by traditionalism.
<P>
"It was extraordinarily challenging," says O'Brien of the reorganization process. "A lot of banks haven't elevated themselves above banking. If you can't compete head to head with nonbank providers, you're going to lose the majority of your customers."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>A Dying Breed</B></font size><BR>
Michael Durante, a banking analyst with McDonald & Co. in Cleveland, says: "Banks as we know them are a dying breed. A lot of bankers are sitting on their hands. PNC has been trying to posture itself as more of a broad-based financial services provider."
<P>
Since the reorganization, PNC has earned a reputation among analysts like Durante for efficiencies that keep costs low and earnings up against a backdrop of mounting assets. In 1972, PNC had $2.1 billion in total assets. Today, it has about $64 billion, making it the 12th largest banking company in the country.
<P>
Aided by low interest rates that spurred mortgage lending and refinancing, PNC achieved earnings of $2.36 per share in 1992 and $3.14 per share in 1993. Earnings for the first half of 1994 were $1.66 per share, up from $1.42 for the same period of 1993.
<P>
But this growth halted in the third quarter, when the company reported earnings of 79 cents per share, down from 92 cents for the third quarter of 1993.
<P>
One reason for the decline in earnings, according to PNC executives, was a $72.5 million gain on the sale of securities in the third quarter of 1993 that produced a comparative peak.
<P>
But they don't dispute that the primary cause was a surge in interest rates that depressed the value of PNC's mortgage-backed securities, catching the company off guard.
<P>
"The increase [in interest rates] was more sudden than most economists were projecting," says Jonathan Williams, vice president of corporate and public affairs.
<P>
Bob Kanters, senior vice president and director of research for Legg Mason Wood Walker in Pittsburgh, says PNC wasn't "positioned for the rising interest rate environment. ... Some banks would have played that more conservatively."
<P>
Kanters says that in "winding out of these positions" by replacing the fixed-income securities with variable-rate assets, PNC "had to incur some losses along the way."
<P>
Durante adds: "They purposely took the losses this quarter to reduce their interest rate going forward."
<P>
When the third quarter report was issued, rapid selling pushed PNC's stock to a new 52-week low on the New York Stock Exchange. Durante and Kanters attribute this to the glandular reactions of institutional investors.
<P>
Kanters believes the poor third quarter performance "has made us mark time for the near-termer. ... But for anyone looking at the next six months or couple of years, it's not a problem. Over the long haul, this has been a superb bank. Their efficiency ratios are among the best in the country."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Workhorse Performance</B></font size><BR>
While Durante predicts thoroughbred performance from some other bank stocks in the next two years, he views PNC as more of a workhorse.
<P>
"PNC is more of a defensive stock. There's not a lot of risk. PNC is one of the most efficient banks that we follow, and has been for some time. They do very well on the cost side, and that has enabled them to make acquisitions."
<P>
Acquisitions have allowed PNC to venture further into fee-producing services, a realm less subject to the vagaries of interest-rate shifts than more traditional banking endeavors. Thirty-five percent of PNC's total revenues came from fees in the third quarter, up from 29% for the same period in 1993.
<P>
The company has directed much of its management energy toward increasing that fig-ure by concentrating on fee-intensive lines of business targeted for growth, including mort-gage servicing, cash management for corporate customers, and securities brokerage and underwriting. Recent acquisitions in asset management are also expected to boost fee income.
<P>
The five-year plan PNC adopted at the outset of its reorganization included provisions to expand the mortgage portfolio gradually. But as it turned out, there was nothing at all gradual about the company's mortgage business growth.
<P>
In 1993, PNC received a telephone call from an investment banker concerning the availability of Sears, Roebuck & Co.'s mortgage banking unit, including a $27.2 billion mortgage servicing portfolio - triple the size of PNC's.
<P>
In November the same year, PNC acquired the business for $328 million, a move that would make it the nation's fourth largest originator of mortgage loans and the 10th largest mortgage servicer. This put PNC Mortgage in a rarefied atmosphere that includes Fleet Financial Group, Norwest Corp. and General Motors Corp. The previous year, PNC had originated mortgages totaling $1.9 billion, compared with the Sears unit's $11.8 billion.
<P>
"We didn't envision this," says O'Brien, explaining that the company had expected a more piecemeal mortgage growth.
<P>
The purchase came amid a spate of mortgage company acquisitions by commercial banks such as BankAmerica Corp. of San Francisco, the nation's second largest banking company, and Barnett Banks Inc. of Jacksonville, Fla., the 24th largest. Experts attributed this to the need of mortgage companies to get better prices than those offered on the stock market, where their values were falling because of dwindling refinancing business. These companies were worth more to large commercial banks already processing high volumes.
<P>
While Sears executives said that $328 mil-lion was about what they'd hoped for, analysts view the price as cheap indeed. O'Brien declines to reveal the Sears' initial asking price, saying only that it was "extraordinarily attractive."
<P>
Especially attractive, that is, for the economies attainable by a bank holding company that was already crunching mortgage numbers on a gargantuan scale.
<P>
"It's a business we're going to be in forever, and we have the volume to justify it," says James E. Rohr, president. "We used to have branches with [mortgage] processing. ... Historically, you couldn't shrink processing [cost] numbers enough. When volumes go to pot, I'm stuck."
<P>
Formerly, PNC Mortgage Corp. had 40 processing centers covering 32 states. It has reduced those 40 to seven, Rohr says, "because we can manage seven without losing critical mass. With 40, we couldn't."
<P>
Greater Pittsburgh is one of PNC's remaining processing centers, with facilities in Bethel Park. Sears had an office in Wexford, but it has been consolidated into the Bethel Park operation.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>BlackRock Bombshell</B></font size><BR>
In June, PNC Bank dropped its second bombshell in two years when it announced an agreement to buy New York-based BlackRock Financial Management LP for $240 million in cash and notes.
<P>
The deal, which was expected to close at the end of 1994, was to increase PNC's assets under management by $21 billion to $75 billion, making it the nation's sixth largest bank money manager.
<P>
While the BlackRock deal was big news for asset managers, it was regarded as less surprising than the Sears purchase, for consolidations in the mutual fund industry were running apace. An example was Mellon Bank Corp.'s agreement to buy Dreyfus Corp.
<P>
The sheer size of the Sears and BlackRock deals, and their rapid succession, have increased PNC's profile as a behemoth that takes care of its competitors by consuming them. Between 1991 and 1994, the company acquired 10 banking companies in Pennsylvania, Ohio and Kentucky.
<P>
Richard C. Caldwell, executive vice president for investment management and trust, says it only took two or three months to strike the BlackRock deal. "It was a modern courtship."
<P>
Another key area of fee income is corporate banking. In 1993, PNC's earnings from services to large businesses (those with annual revenues of more than $250 million) increased marginally, to 47% from 44% the year before. Large customers include Westinghouse, USX, Proctor & Gamble, General Electric and Mobil Oil.
<P>
But revenues from services to mid-sized companies (between $5 million and $250 mil-lion in annual revenues) were a different story. These earnings increased from $101 million to $223 million, boosting year-end profits from 18% to 40% in the middle market alone. This resulted in a profit margin of 42%, up from 23% in 1992, on corporate banking as a whole.
<P>
In the first half of 1994, earnings from middle-market corporate banking services increased about 20% over the same period in 1993. Customers in this market have included businesses involved in healthcare, cable television, cellular telephone and mining.
<P>
Among the services PNC sells these specialized clients is cash management. Also known as treasury management, these services center on handling payments to and from their clients' customers.
<P>
In today's competitive environment, says Bruce E. Robbins, executive vice president for corporate banking, "country club banking is dead. That's when you bank with somebody because they belong to the same country club. ... Corporate customers [today] expect excellent execution."
<P>
One service gaining popularity is the electronic lock box. "We take data and format it onto mag tape. The customer gets it electronically, so it updates their receivables instantly," says Rohr. "What treasury management is going to is information."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Securities and Underwriting</B></font size><BR>
Another growth area for PNC has been securities brokerage and underwriting, which brought earnings of $32 million in 1993 with a 37% profit margin, up from $21 million and 35% in 1992. In the first half of 1994, earnings were $14 million, compared with $13 million in the same period of 1993.
<P>
One source of this growth in underwriting revenues has been the access to new bond issue clients in municipal, healthcare and higher education afforded by acquisitions in the East, including those in Delaware and Kentucky. "We've been doing it for a long time in Pittsburgh, and now we're doing it across the 800-mile platform of PNC," says Rohr.
<P>
Moreover, he continues, handling a major bond issue for such clients is a good entry that can lead to cross-selling relationships for other lines of business.
<P>
When the company restructured itself, the idea was to take aim at financial services vendors by becoming more like them: more focused, more flexible and more marketing-oriented.
<P>
PNC has since aimed this new structure at brokers. "God knows, plenty of brokers are in our business trying to snake our customers," says Rohr, a Cleveland native who, like O'Brien, is a Notre Dame alumnus. "They don't have the constraints" that banks do.
<P>
Another investment banking function for the company is mergers and acquisitions, an area that has shown a flurry of activity in late 1994.
<P>
While PNC executives hardly express an aversion to handling massive mergers of the 1980s variety, they indicate that an openness to such business from smaller companies has served them well in the downsizing '90s.
<P>
In no arena has PNC's restructuring had more visible impact than in retail banking. Without consolidation, branches, including those of newly acquired banks, would have totaled more than 720 by late 1994. PNC has limited itself to 621. The bricks-and-mortar reductions, common in the industry of late, are demographic in design. Says O'Brien: "Four out of 10 cus-tomers prefer never to go inside a branch."
<P>
PNC's market research further shows that the majority of the retail customers who prefer automated teller machines and telephone banking are between 25 and 45 years old - the age bracket that borrows the most money.
<P>
In the coming years, the company expects the public penchant for remote banking to increase as young people comfortable with it enter the work force. Meanwhile, as customers now between 25 and 45 age, their preference for remote banking isn't expected to change.
<P>
Such goes the rationale for PNC's decision to expand its telephone banking center at One Oliver Plaza in downtown Pittsburgh, a building where PNC leases space next to its two headquarters structures. Previously, PNC Bank Corp. had one telephone center in each of its eight markets. The center being expanded in downtown Pittsburgh will consolidate these eight into one center that will employ about 450 people. The current staff in Pittsburgh totals 88.
<P>
Scheduled for completion at the end of 1995, the center will provide expanded service from what is now available in the eight existing centers. PNC is touting the new center as being capable of taking care of 95% of all customers on their first call, as opposed to the 50% currently achieved.
<P>
"We'll be able to handle a loan transaction by phone, followed up by mail, and people won't even have to go into a branch office to close. We're doing that now in Chicago," says A. William Schenck III, executive vice president for retail banking.
<P>
"The cheapest way to deal with us is by mail or phone. Over time, fees will vary with the cost of access, and this will drive the shape of our distribution system, evolving toward a hub with fewer and fewer branches."
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Enhanced Marketing Skills</B></font size><BR>
At the same time, Schenck says, PNC bankers are developing new ways to enhance marketing skills within each branch, seeking to develop a "highly charged" sales atmosphere.
<P>
"What we're moving to is a process where, every day, we have a sales meeting in the branch and talk about what goals we have and how we're going to go about achieving them. Then the next day we have another meeting and talk about how we did. Then we trade information back and forth. Wherever we do this, there seems to be a tremendous increase in sales. ...
<P>
"We don't think of ourselves as bankers. We're pragmatic and marketing-oriented. ... In the old days, we had autonomous business units with their own sets of customers. They didn't necessarily talk to each other. You can't do that anymore."
<P>
Upper management's encouragement for managers from different lines of business to interact has resulted in an organization whose managers know each other better.
<P>
This made it all the more devastating when six PNC executives were killed on Sept. 8 in the crash of USAir Flight 427. The Boeing 737, which had taken off from Chicago, suddenly corkscrewed to the ground six miles from Pittsburgh International Airport, killing all 132 people aboard.
<P>
"It affects the entire company, not just [the] Pittsburgh [offices]. Some of these people were known across the company," says Rohr. After the crash, individuals from various departments went and spent weekends with the families.
<P>
"We immediately provided counseling for families and employee groups, and financial counseling by an outside firm that handles this in these types of circumstances," says Rohr.
<P>
In memory of the six employees, PNC set up a nonprofit foundation to make education funds available for children of victims and to qualifying children of employees. Also, the company plans to erect a memorial marker in PNC Plaza, the fulcrum for One PNC Plaza and its newer 34-story companion, Two PNC Plaza.
<P>
These two buildings, along with surrounding structures where PNC leases space, encompass management operations over 23,000 employees nationwide.
<P>
While the past year or two have been "externally driven," O'Brien says, he sees the coming months as a time to work on training new employees. "They all have to be trained in a whole new way - segmenting customers."
<P>
But he doesn't rule out further acquisitions.
"Traditional banks," he says, are "less of a priority" than businesses more centered on investments.
<P>
As baby boomers age, they borrow less and invest more, O'Brien says, and a key goal of PNC is to tap that wealth through its targeted lines of business.
<P>
"We're looking at businesses that are growing. Mutual funds, money markets - we want to see that continue to grow. That's the type of thing we would probably pursue."
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Thomas H. O'Brien - Local Banker on Top</B></font size><BR>
<B>Age:</B> 58 <BR>
<B>Hometown:</B> Penn Hills <BR>
<B>Roots:</B> County Clare, Ireland <BR>
<B>Education:</B> B.S. in commerce, University of Notre Dame; M.B.A., Harvard, 1962 
<B>Elected chairman:</B> June 1988 <BR>
<B>Family:</B> Married with children (two sons and a daughter, all twentysomethings) <BR>
<B>Residence:</B> Fox Chapel <BR>
<B>Getaway:</B> Second home in Vero Beach, Fla., where he likes to "walk on the beach and play golf" <BR>
<B>Community service:</B> Chairman of the Allegheny Conference on Community Development; board member of the Pennsylvania Economic Development Partnership, United Way of Southwestern Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh Opera, Children's Hospital and University of Pittsburgh
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>M&A Activity Since O'Brien's Been Chairman</B></font size><BR>
PNC Bank has assimilated 25 companies over the past 10 years. Since 1991, nine transactions with total assets of more than $14 billion have been completed.

