<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report January 1995 Issue: Feature</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.netservices.com/"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=top SRC="../zine/Ads/isc.tran.gif"></a>
<HR>
<b><h2>Hey, Beer Here</h2></B><FONT SIZE=+1><b> Local brewers are staying alive by serving local tastes.</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Patricia Berti-Sullivan</i>
<HR>
Both nationally and locally it is a highly competitive industry that's not for the faint of heart. It's fast-paced, and you must be able to introduce new products to the marketplace. After an initial surge, however, many of these products will fall by the wayside becoming nothing more than a fad to the consumer and a footnote in company archives. After years of growth, your market becomes stagnant and the only way for you to boost market share is to lure customers away from your competitors. What industry are we talking about here? Could it be the computer industry? No. Fashion? No. Surprise! It's the beer industry, an industry that continues to evolve. And the big guys and little guys alike are pouring it on in hopes that you'll be pouring their brand.
<P>
Nationally, the major players haven't changed. A handful of brewing companies still ring up the majority of sales. In fact, the largest players - Anheuser-Busch, Miller Brewing and Coors Brewing - control about 75% of the $6 billion domestic market. That leaves everyone else - smaller national brewing companies, regional breweries, microbreweries and brewpubs - competing for 25% of the beer drinking public.
<P>
This region has a rich brewing history, thanks, at least in part, to German immigrants who brought their love of beer with them when they settled here in the 1800s. Today, western Pennsylvania is in many ways a microcosm of what is happening nationally in the industry. From the giants to the brewpubs, the players have recognized the consumer's thirst for something different, and they're all scrambling to quench it.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Stealing Market Share</B></font size><BR>
One way companies lure drinkers is through line extensions: A few years ago, it was dry beer. Sales for dry beer have gone flat, but ice beer has moved in as the latest hot product. "With beer sales being flat overall in this country, you have to steal market share. The way they've been doing it is through new product gimmicks or line extensions," explains Tom Pastorius, president and founder of Pennsylvania Brewing Co., a microbrewery located in the former Eberhardt & Ober Brewery in Pittsburgh's Troy Hill neighborhood. The brewery's flagship product is Penn Pilsner, but it also produces a number of other specialty beers.
<P>
Larger area brewers say that such line extensions are the lifeblood of the industry. If you don't introduce new products, you won't be around a few years down the line. Brewing companies feel peer pressure to imitate what their competitors are doing or risk being left behind, according to Robert Caruso, vice president of marketing and sales for Jones Brewing Co. in Smithton. Jones Brewing brews a number of brands, including Stoneys, Fort Pitt and Esquire. It produces 90,000 barrels a year, the bulk sold in its core market of Westmoreland, Allegheny, Fayette, Greene and Somerset counties. "Initially there was pressure to do an ice beer, but now they're not doing so well," says Caruso.
<P>
Another area brewing company, Latrobe Brewing Co., has come out with its own ice product - Rock Ice - in certain markets, according to Al Spinelli, vice president of operations, but it is amber in color to further distinguish it from its competitors.
<P>
Despite the big marketing push behind dry and ice beer, neither is gaining a significant foothold in the marketplace. "Dry and ice beers are not big sellers, but you have to put them out there," says Michael Graham, chief operating officer at Pittsburgh Brewing Co., which produces its own ice beer, I.C. Ice, but is most famous for its Iron City and I.C. Light brands. "One thing about this business - if you don't develop anything new, you're going to die."
<P>
Pittsburgh Brewing, the ninth largest in the country at roughly 1.3 million barrels a year, traces its roots to 1861, when Edward Frauenheim and Leopold Vilsack founded Frauenheim and Vilsack Brewery. Eventually a brewery was erected at Liberty Avenue and 34th Street, the present site of Pittsburgh Brewing. The company later changed its name to Iron City Brewing, and, in 1899, Iron City and 20 other local brewing companies merged to become the Pittsburgh Brewing Co. In 1985, the company lost its local ownership when it was acquired and merged with Swan Brewery Co. Ltd. of Perth, Australia. But in 1992, the company returned to local hands when it was purchased by Uniontown native and entrepreneur Michael Carlow.
<P>
Pastorius maintains that ice and dry beer won't do well over the long run because they rely on a gimmick - not a distinctive taste - to attract new drinkers. "This is beer that doesn't offend anyone. Bland, bland, bland. It's all about advertising and marketing, not what's in the can," he believes.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Finding a Niche</B></font size><BR>
The desire to offer consumers something different is the force behind another trend nationally and locally among both the large and small players: the proliferation of craft-brews. "Consumers like hand-crafted beer. But, Miller and Coors can buy market share by spending oodles and oodles on advertising," says Jones Brewing's Caruso. "But this gets repetitious to the consumer, and it loses its uniqueness." Pittsburgh Brewing's Graham, agrees: "Ten years ago there were a couple of big brewers and a couple of imports. But in the last few years, regional and microbreweries have begun producing craft brands."
<P>
Graham is right. Just over 10 years ago, only 19 craft-breweries were operating in North America. Since then, the industry has had an average growth of 35% for each of the past four years. According to the Institute for Brewing Studies, based in Boulder, Colo., the craft-brewing industry grew by 40% in 1993 with the addition of 30 new microbreweries and 70 new brewpubs across the United States. The total number of operating craft-breweries, including micro-breweries, brewpubs and regional specialty brewers in North America, was more than 460, as of January 1994.
<P>
Craft-brews appeal to consumers who prefer a bolder taste. They achieve this by using 100% barley malt instead of cheaper substitutes of rice and corn, according to Pastorius. Brewing a beer so distinct gives Pastorius a market niche the industry giants can't fill. He says, "We don't compete with the big guys. We make it the old-fashioned way, using pure barley malt. Ninety percent of beer drinkers in this country won't drink our beer. The 10% who drink imports and specialty beers are our market."
<P>
Pastorius finds himself a member of the brewing industry's fastest-growing segment quite by accident. He lived in Germany for 12 years, where beer is perceived differently. "It's not alcoholic - it's nutrients ... it's liquid bread," he explains. After returning to the United States, Pastorius found that he missed the hearty brews of Deutschland and he made a decision: "It got to the point that I said I'm going back to Germany, or I'm doing something here."
<P>
Pastorius and his wife, Mary Beth, who is the manager for Pennsylvania Brewing's restaurant, took their life savings, purchased the former Eberhardt & Ober Brewery buildings, bought brewing equipment and had it shipped to Pittsburgh from Stuttgart, Germany. They also brought over from Germany a brewmaster who was a graduate of the Technical University of Munich at Weidenstephan - the oldest such school in Germany. In the spring of 1989, Pastorius began producing beer at the old E&O Brewery. Until recently, Pastorius referred to this site as the Allegheny Brewery. That, he says, was a mistake. "In July 1994, I realized it was a mistake to give the brewery a different name from its principal product, so I renamed it Pennsylvania Brewing." At this Troy Hill location, Pastorius brews about 10,000 barrels a year, which serves patrons for his restaurant and those at about 100 other locations that offer his products on tap.
<P>
Despite the recent proliferation of craft-brews, they are still a very, very tiny segment of the market. According to statistics from the Association of Brewers, craft-brews held 0.9% of the market in 1993 compared with 0.6% in 1992. Yet, the industry giants don't want to be left behind this trend. In response, some have begun selling brands that appeal to this type of beer drinker. For example, Miller produces Amber Ale and Coors makes Killian's Red.
<P>
"The beverage industry is undergoing the most dramatic change in its history, and microbreweries are leading the charge. It's a trend that is changing consumers' habits forever," says Ray Werner, president of Werner Chepelsky & Partners, which recently added Penn Brewery to its ad agency client roster.
<P>
Other local brewing companies have launched or are planning to launch their own craft-brew lines. Pittsburgh Brewing is among the brewing companies hoping to tap into the lucrative craft-brew niche, according to Graham. Two of those brews are J.J. Wainwright Select lager beer and its spin-off, J.J.'s Evil Eye Ale. Caruso reports that Jones Brewing is investigating the craft-brew niche: "We're looking into doing some handcrafted items. It's now on the drawing board. Ultimately, we'll be doing it in the next year or so, but it's important for us to take our time and do it right the first time."
<P>
Despite the look-alikes from the major companies, Pastorius is certain there is no substitute for true craft-brews. "Our niche is that once you get used to drinking our beer, you can't go back," says Pastorius. "The big guys recognize it and are putting out their entry into our market."
<P>
Pittsburgh may soon be home to another homegrown brewery. Developer Thomas Tripoli and Ron Kosko have preliminary plans to open a brewpub and hotel on the former Mackintosh-Hemphill Foundry property on the South Side. The two hope to begin the first phase of their operations early this year.
<P>
<font size =+2><B>Image Is Everything</B></font size><BR>
David Fuhrer, president of Frank B. Fuhrer Wholesale Co., is well aware of how effective marketing and image translates into beer sales. Fuhrer Wholesale distributes Budweiser in most of Allegheny County and Coors in a nine-county area. Since its introduction into the local market in 1988, Coors Light has become the biggest seller in Pittsburgh, according to Fuhrer. "There's a mystique about it," he says, explaining in part the brand's huge local success. "Consumers will drink whatever has the right type of image in the marketplace."
<P>
Except for the largest players who have deep pockets for advertising and promotion, most other brewing companies are selective about where they spend their advertising bucks. A big selling point for Pittsburgh Brewing is its point of origin, according to Graham. "Our beer is made here. We're as much a part of Pittsburgh as the Pirates, Steelers and Penguins," he says. Playing this to its advantage, the company uses sales programs that appeal to its audience, such as the I.C. Light Concert Series and commemorative beer cans. Remember those "It's a 'burgh Thing" commercials? Pittsburgh Brewing stresses its Pittsburgh roots in its advertising. "We're not about beaches and babes. When you try to be something you're not, you get into trouble," says Graham.
<P>
Jones Brewing relies on selective promotions. One such successful promotion was tied into the Motor Drome, one of three asphalt racing tracks in Pennsylvania. Jones Brewing came out with a commemorative can and did other tie-ins with the track. "The response was incredible. One hundred and eighty-one distributors participated and we made 181 friends. That's something the giants can't do," says Caruso.
<P>
Until its purchase in 1987 by Labatts USA Inc., a division of John Labatt Ltd., Latrobe Brewing marketed Rolling Rock primarily in the upper northeastern United States. But for the last few years, Rolling Rock has been marketed nationwide. And, for the first time, Latrobe Brewing surpassed the 1 mil-lion barrel mark during its most recent fiscal year. Despite its mass distribution, Spinelli says Rolling Rock has retained a niche. "We don't consider ourselves a mainstream product or a mainstream player. Even though we're sold nationwide, you won't find us in stadiums or places of mass-market consumption," he explains, adding that young professionals are Rolling Rock's primary consumer. "Our beer has a higher price than the Buds, Millers and Coors. We have a unique product."
<P>
Pastorius says Pennsylvania may be a bit less image-conscious than other areas of the country. "Pennsylvania is a big draft state - we sell more draft beer than any other state. You drink draft beer because of the product. But when you buy bottled beer, you're buying an image to set on the bar," 
he says.
<P>
Obviously, Pastorius is unable to compete dollar-for-dollar with the larger breweries to market his products. Instead, he utilizes his restaurant as an advertising vehicle. "Our biggest ad campaign is our restaurant. Great food, fantastic service and great beer," he says. In addition to the draft beer Pennsylvania Brewing produces to supply area bars and restaurants, bottled Penn Pilsner is contract brewed by Jones Brewing for a seven-state market that includes Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Delaware and Virginia. Despite the inroads he's made, Pastorius sometimes gets discouraged. "It's a long, hard process to get to where we are, at capacity. Unfortunately I didn't know what I was getting into," he says. "Too much work, too little reward. The only reason we've gone on is I love beer, and I get some enjoyment bringing this to others."
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>New Suds, Old Method</B></font size><BR>
Penn Brewery recently added two beers to its menu, Penn Dark and Helles Gold, both brewed in the centuries old traditional German method. "Our two new beers [started] coming off a brand new bottling line at the Penn Brewery on Monday, Nov. 21, 1994," says Tom Pastorius, president of Penn Brewery.
<P>
The bottling and labeling line, purchased in Bavaria for $500,000, has a capacity for 8,000 bottles a hour. "Our goal is to bottle all of our specialty beers at our plant," Pastorius adds.
<P>
Between seven and 10 employees will be added to the Penn Brewing Co.'s work force this year. Thirteen authentic German beers are produced there, including Penn Pilsner, which is distributed in seven states in Northeastern United States, Kaiser Pils, Oktoberfest, Christmas Bock, Maerzen, Altbier, Weizen, Weizen Bock, All Star Lager, Maibock and Pastorator.


<hr>
