<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report January 1995 Issue: Update</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<hr>
<center><a href="http://www.netservices.com"><img border=0 src="Ads/isc.tran.gif"></center></a>
<hr>
<B><h2>The Brownfields and the Greenfields</h2></B>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Industrial site reuse legislation may unlock development opportunities that could make Pennsylvania competitive again.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Paul Kengor</i>
<HR>
Environmental issues regularly lead to clashes between activists and business people when the interests of the two do not mesh.
<P>
But there is one area of common ground: the desire to reuse former industrial sites - the plethora of shuttered steel mills and manufacturing plants in western Pennsylvania. In purchasing these brownfields, industry is able to set up shop with much of the necessary infrastructure already in place. The benefit to environmentalists is that industry avoids developing virgin land - also known as greenfields.
<P>
Jack Hubinger is administrative partner of the Pittsburgh office of Jones Day Reavis & Pogue, a law firm with clients who own contaminated industrial real estate. Hubinger says that a typical brownfield is a turn-of-the-century manufacturing site that operated until about 1970. He says most were contaminated not through bad faith or reckless disregard, but merely through normal operating practices.
<P>
According to the Allegheny Conference on Community Develop-ment, nearly two-thirds of the leasable industrial park space in Allegheny County in 1993 consisted of brown-fields, with the proportion higher within certain communities.
<P>
Edward P. Doran is senior vice president of Grubb & Ellis Co., a nationwide real estate company with 98 offices in 61 cities. The company specializes in industrial properties and publishes quarterly real estate market forecasts. Doran brokered the 
$26.5 million sale of the old U.S. Metalsource site (formerly known as U.S. Steel Supply Co.), a steel distribution center next to Kaufmann's warehouse on the North Side.
<P>
The 12-acre site includes a roofed portion of 275,000 square feet, rail access and frontage on the Ohio River. "The consensus in the real estate and development communities was that the maximum that would be obtained for that site was $5 million," Doran remarks. It's been suggested that the site will be used for riverboat gaming and that is what helped elevate the price.
<P>
Among the many local industrial sites currently listed by Grubb & Ellis are two USX properties: 36 acres at Neville Island and a 49-acre site in Dravosburg. The Neville Island site is right off Interstate 79, within 15 minutes of the airport, near rail and water transportation, and a number of major feeder roads.
<P>
Doran maintains that zoning laws will dictate much of what happens to such sites. "It's a lot easier to go from industrial to residential, to get that changed in terms of zoning," he says. "The infrastructure is there. The utilities are already there."

<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Shot in the Foot</B></FONT SIZE><br>
In their zeal to ensure cleanup of post-industrial sites, environmen-talists shot themselves in the foot. Sympathetic legislators implemented stringent and costly remediation requirements. As a result of the unquantifiable liabilities under state and federal law, businesses began shunning brownfields.
<P>
Franklin L. Kury, a partner in the Harrisburg office of Reed Smith Shaw & McClay, contends that state Department of Environmental Resources has "unrealistic" stan-dards for cleanup and that its "desire for perfection" works against its goals. "[DER has] got to decide whether they want perfection or action."
<P>
Kury says that a company cannot meet some requirements without spending lots of money. He says that a firm will meet 98% of the requirements before investing a large sum trying to finish the final 2%. "If they want action, they have to get targets that are reachable and keep them steady," says Kury. "You can have very strict standards or something more realistic that you can get some action on. Corporations don't have unlimited money to spend to get there. If the standards are too unrealistic, you'll never get [the reuse] you're looking for."
<P>
Recent major studies by Carnegie Mellon University's Heinz School, Pitt's Center for Social and Urban Research and the Conference on Real Estate of Southwestern Pennsylvania (CRE) emphasize the critical need to maintain and attract business as a means of economic revitalization.
<P>
The CRE study, released in June and conducted by Tripp-Umbach & Associates Inc., concludes: "[I]f the Pittsburgh region is going to compete for manufacturing projects, it has to have legislation ... to indemnify companies against potential legal liability related to their occupancy of brownfield sites. It is no good having marketing programs, incentives, loans, tax abatements and all the other tools of economic development if the region is going to saddle every potential company that uses these sites with multi-million dollar legal environ-mental liabilities. The companies simply will not come when they can receive a more welcome reception in, say, Ohio."
<P>
In many local communities, brownfields are the only available sites. "A lot of the older industrial sites - the Mon Valley for example - have significant unemployment around them and the use of these sites can produce employment for people nearby," says Hubinger. "They often have rail access, natural gas connections, electrical power and with some rehabilitation are ready to be used."
<P>
"The communities in the Mon Valley are hanging on by their fingernails," says Frank Brooks Robinson, president of the Regional Industrial Development Corp. "Banks are not making loans because of liability. The whole thing is kind of stalemated."
<P>
Over $28 million in state and federal funds have been spent at two RIDC sites for new infrastructure and to accelerate demolition and reme-diation. The sites were the former homes of U.S. Steel's Duquesne works and national tube works, in Duquesne and McKeesport, respectively, over 400 acres total. Demolition is about 90% complete and environmental remediation is more than 70% done.
<P>
Despite the progress at City Center of Duquesne and the Industrial Center of McKeesport, RIDC is forced to lease spaces at the sites because companies are unwilling to buy due to liability fears.
<P>
Tim McNulty, who heads the Regional Economic Revitalization Initiative, says, "We've had blinders on in that the net effect of our current environmental laws is to push development into new areas, and that's why we're losing wetlands [and] contributing to the greenhouse effect. Our current environmental policies encourage sprawl. Other states - including Ohio - have acted swiftly in putting laws into place. It enables them to foster development in areas similar to the Mon Valley."
<P>
McNulty believes many laws fail to look at sites on a specific basis. "It's dangerous to generalize sites," he notes. "But it's safe to say that the potential threat of the contamination depends in part on how the site will be used. And I think that many environ-mental policies today haven't taken that into account. The new site may be used for parking and not pose much of a danger to human health."
<P>
How does Pennsylvania stack up compared to competing states? "I wouldn't say we're behind the curve," says Hubinger. "There were actually bills introduced in the prior Legislature three or four years ago. At that point, Pennsylvania was probably right on or ahead of the curve." He notes, however, that while other states have closed their legislation recently, Pennsylvania has not.
<P>
"Given our business and technology base in the environmental industry," McNulty notes, "it could be a job growth, as well as site development, strategy." Indeed, not only would better reuse of brownfields promote job growth at the sites themselves, but it could also serve to bolster employment in the region's environmental technology sector. The region has the third largest concentration of such companies in the country.
<P>
In a typical scenario, says Hubinger, a company has a facility that no longer fits into its long-term plans. The company wants to sell it, but often can't find a buyer. In some cases, the company doesn't even try to sell the site, Hubinger says. "Therefore you have a reservoir of sites that aren't even being put on the market."
<P>
Ronald Gdovic, a local environ-mental development consultant, is heading up a project with CMU professor Paul Fischbeck. The project, informally dubbed "Industrial Site Reuse Project of Southwestern Pennsylvania," is sponsored by the Heinz Foundation and involves people from Pitt and CMU. Among the chief goals is stimulating economic growth by promoting industrial site reuse.
<P>
Gdovic says that there is currently no comprehensive list of industrial properties in southwestern Pennsyl-vania. "That's a problem because if people from outside the region [want to] acquire an industrial site there is no central database or clearinghouse of information," he maintains. "Nor is there an umbrella organization that could direct people to contacts in the area."
<P>
Gdovic's project goes beyond being just a marketing tool. It incor-porates the demographics of the sites. "The really ground-breaking thing about this project is that we're proposing to offer it on the Internet," he says.
<P>
It will work like this: Suppose a German firm wants to put some manufacturing facilities in the United States. The company can log on the Internet, enter certain key words or site requirements - such as rail access, minimum square footage and labor force - and identify potential properties in the Pittsburgh region. "There's nothing like this anywhere in the world - not at this level on the Internet," says Gdovic.
<P>
In all likelihood, industry would prefer brownfield sites, assuming standards were relaxed. The reason is not necessarily some altruistic con-cern for pine trees and groundhogs. In a simple cost-benefit analysis, developing a rural site can mean paying out for new roads and utilities.
<P>
Purchasers of brownfields must accept liability for past contamination. Developers can spend more than $1 million just conducting environ-mental assessments. Often a company meets the necessary requirements only to be told that the standards have been raised. The business is then forced to spend money on further remediation that could have been reinvested to expand operations and create jobs.
<P>
According to the Southwestern Pennsylvania Growth Alliance (a nine-county partnership for economic development), DER standards order owners to restore brownfields to pristine "background" conditions, defined as "prior to human habit-ation." If a site is unable to achieve pristine standards using today's technology, DER reserves the right to require added cleanup when new technology becomes available. Such uncertainty makes it extremely difficult for a developer to assess the desirability of reusing a site.
<P>
Fortunately, Harrisburg is getting the message. A variety of legislation has been introduced to promote the reuse of industrial sites.
<P>
House Bill 1895, which passed the House in 1994, modifies cleanup standards for abandoned industrial sites. House Bills 952 and 2565 offer liability protection for financial institutions and economic develop-ment agencies. The recently intro-duced H.B. 2700 authorizes limited risk-based remediation standards in cases where a cleanup to meet back-ground conditions has been proven to be infeasible and unaffordable. Senate Bills 650 and 972 allow businesses a choice among three alternative standards in developing cleanup plans. The bills also provide for liability protection for buyers, owners, economic development agencies and financial institutions.
<P>
Reed Smith's Kury cites S.B. 972 and H.B. 2700 as the ones of primary interest. The original 972 passed the Senate, then went to the House, where it was gutted. In the House, 972 was largely replaced by 2700, which is the legislation favored by the DER and Gov. Robert Casey (who leaves office this month). If the House passes the amended version of 972, the bill then goes to the Senate for approval. The Senate will most likely favor the original 972. The two chambers will probably have to reach some sort of compromise between 972 and 2700 - ditto for industry and environmentalists.
<P>
Industry seems to favor the original S.B. 972, opposing H.B. 2700 and the amended version of 972 that incorporates 2700. "The House version [of amended 972] is not acceptable to RIDC," states Robinson. "The position that RIDC has taken - similar to the Mon Valley Commission and the Southwestern Pennsylvania Growth Alliance - is that we support the original S.B. 972 and also the House Bill 3060 because these bills come up with reasonable risk-based standards and there's finality to the remediation costs, so industry knows what it has to do." At the same time, he says, the bills ensure that industry cannot act in a manner detrimental to health or safety. "Critics will argue that industry is going to use this [legislation] as a means to be careless again," Robinson comments. "But other laws in the commonwealth prevent that from happening again."
<P>
The Pennsylvania Environmental Council seems supportive of most industrial site reuse legislation. It is, however, against S.B. 972. "The council believes that no bill is preferable to [the original] S.B. 972," says Hill. Hill is careful to note that there are provisions that the group supports. "We are unusual in that we are one of a few environmental groups supporting much of this piece of legislation. We are against some provisions of the original 972, but not all of them."
<P>
Hill's group has not taken a position on the amended version of 972. "Our concern with 972 as it existed - and this applies to H.B. 3060 also - is this: We are all for the reuse of industrial sites along the riverfronts in Pittsburgh and throughout the state. The problem with the legislation is ... it doesn't just apply to former industrial sites. [It lowers] cleanup standards throughout the commonwealth at greenfield sites as well as brownfield sites. We're opposed to that, vehemently opposed."
<P>
He concludes: "We are an environmental group that strongly believes in legislation, but we don't want it to be used as a vehicle for environmental degradation through-out Pennsylvania." Kury, who is a board member of the council, seems to agree. The original 972, says Kury, would be "great if you limit it to sites with a previous industrial history."
<P>
McNulty cautions that legislation to promote industrial site reuse is not a cure-all. "You still must stimulate the economic engines to bring business to those sites. The danger is to think that legislation will solve the problem. It is critical. But the law itself will only create the potential for change. How we benefit from the laws depends on how the various commu-nities - in real estate, economic development, government, academia - work in marketing these sites. The laws are only the first step."
<HR>
Pittsburgh Industrial Market								
Almost 23% of the brownfield market is available.
