<center><a href="http://www.netservices.com"><img border=0 src="Ads/isc.tran.gif"></center></a>
<hr>
<B><h2>Making the Most of Mutual Funds</h2></B>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Banks are blasting into an area where the growth has been explosive.</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Lydia Strohl</i>
<HR>
Tired of seeing customers withdraw money from their vaults to invest in higher risk, higher yield vehicles, banks have jumped on the mutual fund bandwagon. Their aim? To become a pecuniary Wal-Mart, providing the entire spec-trum of financial services to customers and in the process add an income stream to their own bottom line.
<P>
"We were missing the boat by not marketing mutual funds to branch-based customers," says Don Jacobson, first vice president and manager of retail investment services at Mellon Bank. "We saw there was a large and growing segment of what we call searchers,' not happy with their portfolio, but they didn't really know what they should invest in. Mutual funds are a good vehicle for the mass market - they are diversified, with professional fund managers, and people can get in for a relatively small amount."
<P>
Trend? More like a ground swell. From the first to the second quarter of 1994, the number of banks selling mutual funds and annuities increased from 2,378 banks to 2,569 banks, according to Veribanc Inc., a banking research firm in Wakefield, Mass. Fifty-three Pennsylvania banks sell mutual funds and annuities; 23  in west-ern Pennsylvania sell mutual funds.
<P>
The extreme drop in short-term interest rates at the beginning of the 1990s is one of the factors fueling this skyrocketing growth. Concurrently, banks dropped their rates, making interest-bearing deposits less attrac-tive. Seeing 40% of mutual fund growth coming from bank deposits, bank officials knew this was one game they couldn't afford not to play.
<P>
"If we can serve the customer's needs, they will not go elsewhere," says Jacobson. "If our customer goes to Merrill Lynch for mutual funds, they could sell him a home equity loan. And we want them to buy that here."
<P>
That's the indirect benefit. The direct benefit is income. That amount varies, depending on how the bank approaches the mutual fund market. Some banks, eager to make mutual funds available to their customers, will broker third-party funds. In this scenario, the bank gets a percentage of the sales and service fees and commissions, and also keeps the customer. Or, a bank might chose to set up its own mutual funds, in which case it would get not only the sales and servicing fees, but also profit from the investment, management and administration of the funds. But there are complex issues involved with both of these avenues.
<P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>Two Issues</B></FONT SIZE><BR>
"There are two issues that a bank truly has to come to grips with," says James F. Getz, president of the broker-dealer division of Federated Securities Corp. "One is distribution - they have nothing if they don't have the market for it. If a bank is thinking of manufacturing and distributing their own fund, there is a critical mass of assets that they have to have to make it efficient for themselves and the client. If it isn't realistic to achieve $5 billion in assets in a relatively short time frame, then they should look at third-party funds."
<P>
Banks have an advantage in the mutual fund arena because they have a developed customer base. The March issue of The Bankers Magazine reports a Fidelity Investments survey in which 32% of investors already owning funds replied that they were "very likely" to purchase funds from their own banks. Only 8% of investors are likely to develop new bank relationships.
<P>
There are very real risks for banks selling mutual funds. Traditional bank deposit vehicles are guaranteed by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.; mutual funds are not. It is the bank's responsibility to make sure that the customer is notified of the uninsured nature of mutual funds, and the potential loss of principal. Failure to follow guidelines recently set by the office of the Comptroller of the Currency on this issue can open the bank to lawsuits from dissatisfied customers, as well as regulatory action.
<P>
Last May, The First National Bank of Herminie in Irwin began selling mutual funds. James R. Lauffer, chairman and CEO of the bank, is also chairman of the board of the Independent Bankers Association of America. His bank is one of the first to offer mutual funds through IBA Financial Services, a division set up for community banks to sell mutual funds. The IBA service is contracted with the Massachusetts Financial Services family.
<P>
"Because the customer can come in here and grab me by the tie, we have to be careful of what we sell," says Lauffer. "We have to do more due diligence to make sure that the customer knows that mutual funds can go down in price. And we have to go overboard to make them understand that these funds are not insured, and they have to be in them for the long run."
<P>
Lauffer says that the bank was going to contract with a third-party provider to come in and manage the whole mutual fund program from soup to nuts, but that didn't give enough control; other community banks have had bad experiences with this strategy.
<P>
Instead, First National hired a broker from Wall Street, with series 6 and 7 license. The desks from which mutual funds are sold are clearly marked, and segregated. IBA Financial Services provides a qualifying software program that the broker goes through with a potential customer to assess objectives, risk tolerance and other investment criteria. With the aid of the software, the broker gives investment advice that spans seven of Mass Financial's funds. Though the broker can sell any Mass Financial fund, only seven of them are in the mix, because Lauffer feels that the consultants must know each of them inside out.
<P>
"The broker is salaried, so that he is getting no incentive on the commis-sion from the sale. The objective is to put the customer in the right situation," says Lauffer. "He has told people he doesn't think mutual funds are the right investment for them."
<P>
Though he states that getting into mutual funds was a defensive tactic, Lauffer is committed to developing the service. He believes that there is a conflict of interest when banks sell their own funds.
<P>
"There is more incentive to sell your own fund - it only makes sense that way," says Lauffer. "Then they make the management fee and the commission."
<P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>Selling Proprietary Funds</B></FONT SIZE><BR>
The banks in the Pittsburgh region that sell their own funds, which include Mellon Bank, Integra Bank and PNC, are well aware of this criticism. They go out of their way to point out the structural elements of their programs that discourage this from happening.
<P>
Though Mellon Bank has offered mutual funds in the trust manage-ment mix for years, the bank has only just entered the retail mutual fund business. Two years ago Mellon introduced personal investment consulting, which also uses software to assess customer needs. The personal investment consultants (PICs) are employed by InvestNet, a brokerage subsidiary of Mellon Bank. PICs sell stocks, bonds and annuities (through Talbot Insurance Agency), as well as a range of 35 mutual funds which include the Laurel Funds, Mellon's proprietary funds. After the bank merged with New York-based Dreyfus Corp. last summer, the Laurel name changed to Dreyfus.
<P>
Dreyfus, a well-recognized name in mutual funds, gives Mellon an even bigger entree into the market. This November, Mellon had $76 billion in mutual fund assets under manage-ment. Fully $69 billion of those assets were in proprietary funds, including the Dreyfus assets. The remaining $7 billion are managed in other funds, among them Federated and Fidelity.
<P>
"Offering the better funds from each family offers objectivity," says Jacobson. "There are banks that sell only their own funds, but we couldn't cover as wide a range of investment goals."
<P>
Jacobson says that the program experienced tremendous growth at the onset, which has slowed. He estimates that there are about 20,000 customers in the program; 20% of which are new to Mellon Bank. About half a dozen funds have been dropped and added in the ongoing review of recommended funds; Jacobson says customers' investments are discussed with them once a year.
<P>
"If they are only investing money for a year or two mutual funds don't make sense," says Jacobson. "We don't want to cause them to pull their money out and incur another sales charge. It is illegal, too, to cause account churning. We recommend that they stay in a fund; they all fluctuate and the customer is much better off if the underlying dynamics of the fund are sound. They should be willing to ride it out."
<P>
Mellon is by no means the only local institution jumping headlong into the mutual fund fray. In January 1993, PNC Bank launched the PNC Family of Funds, which now includes 24 funds with $5 billion in assets. PNC also acts as manager for funds with assets approaching $30 billion. The bank provides custody, accounting and transfer services for other mutual funds and, in October, introduced MutualPartners asset allocation service, a PC-based system that allows community banks to give customers investment advice. That service is similar to one called Capital Directions, which is available to PNC customers.
<P>
"The merger of PNB and Provident National Bank brought together a large institutional trust division in Philadelphia," says George Bernard, senior vice president of mutual funds with PNC Securities Corp. "We had the discipline and expertise develop over time, so it was a natural progression."
  <P>
PNC Bank offers its customers personal investment counseling through PNC Brokerage Corp., which has brokers throughout the PNC branch network. The brokers sell PNC and other mutual funds, like Putnam and Alliance. Bernard says that the PNC Family of Funds accounts for about 20% to 30% of these sales. Depending on customer needs, the broker can refer to ProVest, a subsid-iary selling insurance products, to PNC Securities Corp. for stocks and bonds, or to the investment manage-ment and trust department. The bank assures that their counselors are giving sound, objective advice by using mystery shoppers and by compen-sating counselors by salary and long-term bonus.
<P>
"Just jamming product is a long-term formula for disaster," says Bernard. "Educating the customer is paramount. No one family of funds can meet all needs."
<P>
<FONT SIZE =+2><B>Similar Philosophies</B></FONT SIZE><BR>
This philosophy is shared by Steve Hartle, president and chief operating officer of Integra Trust Co., which unrolled a similar program through Personal Investment Services Inc., owned by the Richard Leahy Co., deploying 45 securities licensed counselors throughout Integra's 260 branches to sell third-party mutual funds and annuities.
<P>
"This structure reinforces that, legally, these are not employees of Integra Financial," says Hartle. "There need to be contracts and agreements that maintain the appropriate arm's length relationship, not giving the impression that we are compensating people directly."
<P>
Hartle also stresses determining customer needs, and says the compensation system, which is salary plus a commission that is based on production but is product neutral, is designed to uphold that.
<P>
"We don't want to put the philosophy of needs-based selling at risk," says Hartle. "The focus is determining what our customer needs and providing products that meet that need. We're not product jockeys, trying to sell the product of the month. If the customer feels he is well-served that bodes well for a long-term relationship."
<P>
Last year, the first year of the program, which Integra rolled out in stages throughout the region, mutual fund sales reached a volume of $40 million, and represented 65% of the total volume generated by Personal Investment Services. In the first nine months of 1994, mutual fund sales reached $30 million, and Hartle extrapolates that to another $40 million year. But this year, mutual fund sales are only 43% of the total volume.
<P>
"The environment and the market are much different - markets have been hammered this year," says Hartle. In this scenario, annuities have 
performed far better. "Annuity rates are set annually, a reflection of the interest rate environment. Last year, interest rates were low and annuity rates low. This year, that's reversed."
<P>
That trend is reflected nationwide; for although more banks have entered the mutual fund market, sales volume dropped from $111 billion to $105 billion from the first to the second quart-er of this year.
<P>
"Bond mutual funds have seen the fastest declines," says Mellon's Jacobson. "As interest rates increase and bond prices decrease, people who have invested in bond market funds move their dollars. Volatile markets can slow sales - but that is cyclical and not unexpected. Money market funds and annuities do better and so we see a shifting of purchase behavior and that's appropriate."
<P>
These are general rules of economics, and of investing, and these players are not likely to be driven from the market. They seem to see their task as one of educating consumers on the nature of this game, signing up only those who can afford to play for the long haul.
<P>
"We've seen some redemption, but it is by no means massive," says Federated's Getz. "The personality of the consumer is different today - they are more sophisticated. We have what was essentially a crash in the bond market, but there have not been mass redemp-tions. People have the right attitude towards investing - it's over time."
What will affect the mutual fund market, Getz believes, is the influx of players.
<P>
"Look at the dynamics. There has been a lot of money invested in mutual fund product participation over the past 48 months and a lot of banks entering the market. Thirty percent of all households are into mutual funds, and with 401(k)s that will grow," he says. "There will be a move to the macro, a consolidation. Some players with fund complexes in the couple of hundred million dollars are wondering how long they can stay in. But Sears launched the Discover card into what was thought to be a saturated market. And when Thomas Monaghan formed Domino's Pizza, who would have thought we needed another pizza delivery service? There will still be parties entering the mutual fund industry, but the focus will be macro."
<P>
Stay tuned. It seems we have some players in the Pittsburgh region. 
<HR>
