<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report January 1994 Issue: Publisher's Note</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2>This Work is Taxing </FONT SIZE><i> By Linda Dickerson</i><P>
Exorbitantly high business taxes and the prevailing view of southwestern Pennsylvania's horrendous labor climate are frequently cited as the two most significant deterrents to locating or growing a company here. To grow and prosper, we must eliminate the region's barriers to entry by creating a welcoming environment attractive to start-up companies, existing growth enter-prises and other firms on the move.
<P>
Pennsylvania distinguishes itself in many ways. Unfortunately, one of the ways that we stand apart from the crowd is by having one of the highest business taxes in the country. I purport that another mark of distinction would be a better trademark.
<P>
Economic development in the region will stagnate without an appropriate tax structure. Although the Pennsylvania Legislature provided some relief by lowering our corporate net income tax to 10.99% this year, we still remain grossly uncompetitive.
<P>
Recognizing that governments require money (usually in significant amounts) to operate and serve their constituents, taxes are the framework around which communities build their future. At the height of frustration, an entrepreneurial friend of mine retorted that if he just didn't have to manage a sales force, his company would prosper. While sales forces frequently rank among the most difficult to manage, they nonetheless generate a company's income. Without sales, most, if not all, enterprises fail. Without taxes, most, if not all, governments and the communities they serve would collapse.
<P>
The Regional Economic Revitalization Initiative's recommendation that the region create a Tax Review Council is a brilliant suggestion. Designed to be an independent, bipartisan effort to successfully revise the commonwealth's tax structure, the council will engage the nation's best thinking, and analyze alternative tax structures. Following on the heels of countless unsuccessful local and statewide tax reform efforts, the proposed Pennsylvania Tax Review Council distinguishes itself by the depth and clarity of its assignment.
<P>
The council will focus exclusively on developing the optimal tax structure to recommend to the state Legislature. Quite simply, its assignment is to suggest revisions to the commonwealth's tax structure that as part of an integrated effort will restore economic vitality to this region. This is a noble goal worthy of the magnitude of resources requisite to assure the council's success. With the nation's best and brightest at work and a region committed to the council's vitality, the council will craft a blueprint to achieve economic growth through progressive tax policy. We can no longer afford to stand in the way of such progress.
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../zine/pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
<ADDRESS><h5>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <a href="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments or suggestions?</a><br>
