<DOCHDR>
http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0195.Letters.html 192.204.56.67 19970115135553 text/html 5217
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 14:01:03 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:49:01 GMT
Content-length: 5041
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report January 1995 Issue: Letters to The Editor</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.L.gif" ISMAP></a>
<HR>
<font size =+2><B>Strike Back</B></font size><BR>
I was interested to read Lydia Strohl's article, "Strike Down" [September 1994]. I was pleased that you focused on school strikes in the companion article, "Round and Round."
<P>
Twenty teachers' strikes this year are more than enough to establish a problem. A number of Pennsylvanians believe that teacher strikes are a serious problem which the State Legislature must solve. Most see this tragic parade as directly related to rising education costs and falling results.
<P>
This is not a problem without an answer. We can ... ensure uninterrupted education for children, fair compensation for teachers and relief from runaway property taxes for taxpayers.
<P>
What do other states do? Forty do not permit teachers to strike. If strikes occur, penalties are assessed such as lost wages, forfeiture of tenure or termination.
<P>
New York is considered a labor-oriented state, but teacher strikes have been banned since 1967. Teachers who strike lose two days' pay for each day of strike. Nevertheless, New York teachers rank third in the nation in average salary. Teachers need not fear financial purgatory if strikes are banned. Most of the 10 states with the highest average teachers' salaries prohibit strikes.
<P>
Pennsylvania teachers' average salaries rank sixth, and comparisons show [they] are well compensated in salary, benefits and job security, no matter what yardstick is applied.
<P>
If we repeal the right to strike, should we replace it with binding arbitration?
<P>
At first glance, binding arbitration does seem a neat way to end unsuccessful negotiations. But a wealth of tragic experiences clearly demonstrate the fallacy and cost of this flawed theory.
<P>
Of the top 20 states in average teachers' salaries, only four provide for binding arbitration. In Connecticut, this process has been so shocking that Gov. Weicker is leading the effort to repeal it. Rhode Island has restricted [it] to apply only to non-salary issues. North Dakota passed binding arbitration in 1991, but it was repealed a year later by citizens referendum.
<P>
In 1967 ... the Pennsylvania Legislature granted police and firefighters binding arbitration because of public safety and welfare [issues]. Yet, three years later, the Legislature refused to grant binding arbitration to teachers and other public employees and, instead, permitted them to strike.
<P>
In the private sector, binding arbitration is rarely considered for any substantive issue, let alone pay and benefits. Yet private strikes are declining as both parties recognize the need to solve their problems.
<P>
The process normally leads to splitting the differences or accepting the position of one of the parties. Neither serve the needs of [both]. It is wrong and presumptuous for the Pennsylvania Legislature to force communities to abdicate their responsibilities for bargaining with their teachers and for setting local school tax rates.
<P>
Pennsylvania teachers can strike with almost none of the financial loss experienced by all others who strike. Teachers ... are guaranteed a full years salary when days are made up in June. It's this unique certainty of pay that serves as a significant disincentive to settlement.
<P>
Another disincentive is retroactivity, which calls for the pay and benefit increases of the new contract to apply for all days worked since the old contract expired. Our laws should promote settlement for the good of all, particularly the students. For this reason, retroactive increases should be prohibited.
How can we solve this problem? The answer is to repeal the right of teachers to strike or to require pay to be lost and not made up.
<P>
Solving the teachers' strike problem in Pennsylvania is not only possible, but imperative. The task ... will require a considerable effort to ensure that the Legislature understands the problem, the unique aspects of teacher bargaining and strikes, and the solutions. It will require courage for the Legislature to do what is necessary.<P>
<I>-- Rep. Albert W. Pettit, 40th district
Editor's note: Rep. Pettit's letter was edited for space. </I>
<hr>
