<DOCHDR>
http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0195.GuestEditorial.html 192.204.56.67 19970115135634 text/html 6825
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 14:01:28 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:49:01 GMT
Content-length: 6649
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report January 1995 Issue: Guest Editorial</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <FONT SIZE=+2><B>Eliminating Pennsylvania S Corporations: The Simple Way to Export More Jobs to Other States</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Grant M. Wirth</i><P>
<HR>
It's hard not to ignore politicians when they call for higher taxes on S corporations in Pennsyl-vania. Because dozens of other states give some form of preferential tax treatment to S corporations, higher taxes would likely retard the growth of inbound investment, and most certainly add to the cost of the goods and services produced within the commonwealth.
<P>
Recent statements by several politicians that a need exists for more taxes on Pennsylvania S corporations, solely because they dont generate as much tax revenue as other corporations, are a not-so-clever way of attempting to divide and conquer corporate taxpayers so they can be squeezed for more tax. As I read it, the strategy is to pit the small companies against the big ones, and then try to get a few of the big guys to say that the corporate tax burden isn't being borne fairly. State legislators will then have all the ammunition they need to increase taxes on the S corporations, the justification being provided by finger pointing from within the business community.
<P>
The only fly in the ointment is that, so far, I haven't heard anybody agree with the politicians who have said that there's inequity with the status quo. What I hear is that business is pretty much united in their belief that the corporate tax reductions that occurred in 1994 are a sorry and miserable excuse for real action on the part of the legislative and executive branches to clean up the financial mess we have in Pennsylvania. The real problem is not that we don't have enough tax revenue to balance the state budget, it's that we don't have enough responsible people in Harrisburg who are watching how our tax dollars are currently being spent.
<P>
S corporations are generally small businesses that could just as easily operate as proprietorships or partnerships, both of which pay no tax. Instead, the income is taxed in the personal tax return of the owners. Back in 1958 when the U.S. Congress first invented S corporations, the thought process was that small businesses would prosper if their owners could have the benefit of limited liability for corporate debts and yet retain the simplicity of one tier of tax on profits. True, there are exceptions to the generality that S corporations are small businesses. But there are exceptions to every rule, and to change Pennsylvania S corporation tax policy based on the exception to the rule is just plain wrong.
<P>
I cant remember the last time that I spoke to someone who believed that there was something less than excessive waste and inefficiency in state government. I also can't find anybody who thinks that state government needs more money, or that our tax dollars are currently spent wisely. How can politicians, in good conscience, call for more taxes on the very companies that are driving the state's economy with job creation?
<P>
Recent reports that small businesses aren't generating their share of jobs anymore aren't substantiated by anything that I've recently seen published by the Small Business Administration. In fact, very small businesses are creating jobs like wildfire. What sense does it make to nurture small companies through a myriad of state-funded programs only to tax the profits heavily and then waste the tax collected?
<P>
I think that big business in Pennsylvania has a legitimate gripe about corporate tax rates in this state. But the fight is not with small business, it's with the state Legislature. The mission of the legislative branch of state government should be to reduce both corporate and individual taxes through governmental downsizing. When I use the word tax, I also mean unnecessary governmental regulation of the behavior of both individuals and businesses. The cost of compliance with excessive regulation is no different than paying a tax, and it doesn't take much thought to understand that the compliance burden of unnecessary regulation of business is felt most heavily by smaller companies.
<P>
Regardless of whether it's large or small corporations paying excessive taxes to the state, or compliance with unnecessary rules, the citizens of Pennsylvania ultimately bear the economic brunt of irresponsible state spending and excessive business regulation. Everything costs more to produce, and, therefore, our goods and services are less cost competitive than those produced elsewhere.
<P>
To get state spending back to where it should be, I favor long-term spending and hiring freezes, privatization of government and anything that forces state government to find ways to become more effective and efficient in the delivery of services. In essence, what I advocate is that both individual and corporate taxpayers unite in their demand for government that is run in a businesslike manner. We must expect more in the way of results, and hold accountable those who don't deliver what is expected. We must force our system to work better. There's really no other option.
<P>
Corporate taxpayers who aren't S corporations have a legitimate concern about corporate income tax rates, but their situation won't improve by taking it out of the hide of small business. I'd like to see tax cuts for both business and individuals that are funded by slicing the fat out of the state budget. I can't believe that state government couldn't function on many hundreds of millions of dollars less in revenue.
<P>
If there's a playing field that's not level in Pennsylvania, it's not the corporate tax field, it's the place where our Legislature spends the taxes that we all work so hard to pay. It's going to be an uphill battle all the way to get state spending back to where it should be. The question is whether business in Pennsylvania is up to the fight.
<P>
<I>Grant M. Wirth is a partner at D.G. Sisterson & Co., certified public accountants. The opinions expressed here are the author's own.</I>
<hr>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/BottomBar.gif" ISMAP></a><br>
