<DOCHDR>
http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0195.ERIndex.html 192.204.56.67 19970115135644 text/html 5768
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 14:01:57 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:49:00 GMT
Content-length: 5592
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report January 1994 Issue: ER Index</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a><BR>
<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.</I>
<HR>
Continued strength in local technology and healthcare stocks could not offset weakness in bank, basic materials and capital goods stocks, as the Executive Report Index declined 1.89% for the month ended Nov. 11, 1994. That com-pares with a 1.44% decline in the S&P 500 Index. Since inception, the 
25-component share-weighted ER Index is up 4.71% vs. 0.24% for the S&P.
<P>
Rising interest rates are never good for bank stocks, and now is no exception. Mellon, Integra and Parkvale have performed poorly, mainly due to investor concerns that spreads will shrink and earnings will follow. PNC, which is not in our index, announced that it expects net interest income to decline by as much as 15% this year. PNC has seen its stock fall from 31 5/8 in early June to 20 5/8.
<P>
Banks are struggling to offset this by increasing noninterest income from nontraditional products, like mutual funds and other asset management services.
<P>
Integra became the latest local bank to announce its own mutual funds, called the Investor Funds. Integra's move followed substantial restructuring that chairman and CEO William Roemer hopes will refocus the bank on improved customer service. The move was not designed as a cost-cutting exercise, Roemer says. Rather, after a series of acquisitions and mergers to consolidate, Roemer says Integra began to lose touch with its customers, and he wants to stem the tide. Integra's stock has fallen from 49 1/2 in June to 39 3/8. Meanwhile, in an attempt to bolster their share prices, many banks -- including Integra and Parkvale -- have undertaken share buy-backs.
<P>
The index wasn't helped by American Eagle Outfitters, which fell 18.58%, to 23, on weaker-than-expected October sales, which the company attrib-uted to a delayed holiday shopping season because of unseasonably warm weather. However, fiscal first quarter sales rose 49% and same store sales increased 5.7%. The company continues to open stores at a rapid clip, with 45 since August and 40 more planned by July.
<P>
Also weighing on the index was USX - U.S. Steel Group, which declined 10%, and Alcoa, which fell nearly 7%. In addition to worry over interest rates, investors clearly are concerned about where we are in the business cycle. If, as many fear, the U.S. economy is at its peak, then how much growth is there left for the steels, aluminums and other basic industries? We fear a self-fulfilling prophecy.
<P>
Our technology stocks continue to perform superbly, with Black Box, Cable Design, Fore Systems and Legent all averaging a 14% price increase. All report significant earnings and revenue momentum.
<P>
General Nutrition was also strong, up nearly 20%, following fiscal third quarter earnings that rose 59%, beating expectations. GNC, which intends to dominate the vitamin and nutrition supplement market, plans to open 300 to 350 stores annually for the next four or five years.
<P>
Northstar Health Services rose 13%, following a 210% increase in its third quarter net income and a 166% increase in revenues. The outstanding performance was due to growth in outpatient operations and several acquisitions, which have expanded the company's capabilities while leveraging fixed costs.
<P>
Respironics reported better-than-expected results for its most recent quarter, and its stock rose 13.6%. Net income rose 12% to 28 cents per share, from 25 cents last year.
<P>
Heinz agreed to purchase the All-American Gourmet Co., maker of Budget Gourmet frozen foods, from Phillip Morris' Kraft General Foods. The popular brand has annual sales of about $300 million. Heinz shares rose over 4%.
<P>
Kennametal, which had terrific fiscal first quarter results, followed that up by announcing a joint venture with W.W. Grainger Inc., one of the nation's leading distributors of industrial supplies. The two companies will market maintenance, repair and operations supplies and metal-cutting tools. The deal should yield positive results for both companies soon.
<P>
Johnstown America has a new contract with the United Steelworkers, but that did little to boost the company's stock price. The other related company in the index, MK Rail, also continues to struggle, mainly due to uncertainty about a sizable money-losing contract for Southern Pacific, and questions about the prospects for continued economic growth. The railroad industry is booming, with no letup in sight, and apparently, that worries some folks.
<P>
Shares of Industrial Scientific Corp., the maker of portable gas detection devices, have been walloped recently. The company, which is not in our index, reported sharply lower than expected earnings for its fiscal third quarter. Its shares tumbled to a 52-week low of 17 3/4, from a high of 31 1/2 last January. Revenues for the quarter declined 15%. Earnings per share were 25 cents. One of the company's analysts had forecast 45 cents.
<hr>
