<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report January 1995 Issue: People Making News</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> <FONT SIZE=+2><B>People Making News
: Harry Guidotti</B></FONT SIZE><br><i>By Kristin Giron</i><P>
<HR>
<B>Occupation:</B>	CEO of Selemoh Cookie Co.<BR>
<B>Age:</B>		50<BR>
<B>Family Life:</B>	Guidotti and his wife, Vivian, live in Library. They have three 			children: Erik, 29, Ross, 27, and Sarah, 18.<BR>
<B>Hometown:</B>	Pittsburgh<BR>
<B>Education:</B>	South Hills High School<BR>
<B>Hobbies:</B>		Magic, astronomy, billiards and classical guitar<BR>
<B>Last Vacation & Where:</B>	Mr. and Mrs. Olympia contest in Atlanta<BR>
<B>Favorite Book or Quote:</B>	"A few facts are revealing, too many are obscuring."<BR>
<B>The News:</B><BR>
Guidotti has been making his mark in the sales world since high school when he peddled Bibles door to door. He went on to become chairman of the Guidotti Marketing Group, a $30 million sales promotion company that is 40% employee owned. Now he has invested more than $150,000 in a nonprofit cookie company, hoping his business acumen will help less fortunate folks.
<P>
Guidotti started Selemoh to raise money through retail outlets and fund-raisers for homeless families. "I came out of a restaurant in New York years ago and I noticed large boxes piled up near a heating vent," he explains. "I walked past and noticed a set of bare feet that belonged to a small child sticking out of the box. I was devastated and vowed I would do something about it."
<P>
Guidotti retired as chairman of Guidotti Marketing so he could work full-time at Selemoh (homeless spelled backward minus one s). Nine employees work at the South Hills bakery, which opened in September. Later this year, Guidotti plans on going national.
<P>
"We're helping people get back on their feet and my hope is simply that, to help people out," he says. "The money we raise will stay in the community that raised it."
<P>
Despite his focus on Selemoh, Guidotti has also recently opened JC Flippen's Eatery, a diner in Pleasant Hills.
<P>
Guidotti's outlook on his success is simple: time and effort. But throughout his career, he has never sacrificed the beliefs and ideas of his employees.
<P>
"I've invested so much into my companies, but I would never compromise my people for my business," says Guidotti. "That's a sacred trust I won't break."
<hr>
