<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report December 1994</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Features.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<hr>
<a href="PncFunds.html"><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=top SRC="Ads/PncFunds1.gif"></a>
<HR>
<b><h2>
Top 10 Growth Companies </h2></B><br><FONT SIZE=+1><b>Banks dominate the fifth annual compilation of area performers.</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By Richard Bierck</i>
<P>
After a rough stretch of economic road in the early 1990s, banks across the country are enjoying a resurgence in earnings, and banking companies in western Pennsylvania are no exception. <p>
With lending business hoisted by interest rates that plummeted in 1992 and 1993, bank earnings nationwide this year have skyrocketed. <p>
But while hundreds of banks across the country careened to failure two years ago, the stronger of their ilk in this region continued to gain in earnings.
Their momentum proved propitious. <p>
Amid this year's national scenario of banking strength, six bank holding companies place among the 10 fastest growing public companies in western Pennsylvania for 1994. Executive Report's annual survey, conducted by Parker/Hunter Inc. of Pittsburgh, is based largely on compounded earnings per share over the past five years. It includes earnings projections for 1994. <p>
John Frankola, Parker/Hunter senior vice president, says that three factors have spurred bank earnings: declining interest rates; improved credit quality in the lending market, decreasing the amounts banks put aside for losses on loans and greater operational efficiencies. <p>
Although analysts aren't predicting an austere rerun of the national banking scene in the early 1990s, Frankola believes that the same economic cycle that accelerated banks' earnings in 1994 may slow them a bit next year. <p>
"I would be surprised if there are as many banks on the Top 10 list in 1995," Frankola says, adding that manufacturing concerns will probably knock some of the banking companies off the list next year. <p>
In 1992 and again in 1993, there was only one banking institution in the Top 10: First Western Bancorp Inc. This year, First Western is joined by PNC Bank Corp., Parkvale Savings Bank, Fidelity Bancorp Inc., S&T Bancorp Inc. and USBancorp Inc. <p>
Nevertheless, high technology and medical manu-facturing concerns lead the list this year, as they did last. <p>
Industrial Scientific Corp., which placed second in 1993, moved to No. 1 this year, with a compounded annual growth rate of 35% since 1989. <p>
Appearing on the Top 10 list for the third consecutive year in 1994 is Medrad Inc.; for the fourth consecutive year, Mylan Laboratories Inc., and the fifth consecutive year, Respironics Inc. <p>

<font size =+2>PNC Bank Corp.: </font size> 
Far and away, the strongest earnings per-formance in banking earnings this year was that of PNC, one of the nation's largest banking companies. <p>
PNC has a compounded annual growth rate of 29.8%, including projected year-end earnings of $3.31 per share.<p>
For the quarter that ended June 30, PNC posted returns of 1.26% on average assets and 17.7% on average shareholders' equity.<p>
Walter E. Gregg Jr., executive vice president of finance and administration, attributes this showing to a variety of factors. One of the most systemic took root in early 1990.<p>
"That's when we moved the organization as a bank to a line-of-business management structure. We started in January 1990 to handle this company as a single business long before it was fashionable. It's more efficient this way," he says.<p>
PNC began running four basic lines of business -- retail banking, corporate banking, investment banking, and investment management and trust -- centrally by using a $200 million infrastructure that includes the new data processing center on Parkway West. <p>
"This way, we have the ability to deliver the power of a $62 billion bank into every market with sophisticated products and services," Gregg says. <p>
Aggressive pursuit of the financial services market, combined with cost reductions made possible by centralized lines of business, he says, is one reason that PNC Bank had an after-tax profit margin of 25.75% in the second quarter. <p>
He attributes some of this profitability to cost controls: "In the financial services industry, the low-cost producers are the ones who are going to win the war."<p>
Also contributing to earnings growth, Gregg says, have been "acquisitions that have been intelligently priced and that have allowed us to implement ... our strategies."<p>
Using such efficiencies, he says, PNC Bank has been able to blend in acquisitions such as Sears Mortgage in November 1993 for $328 mil-lion. Sears brought in more than $27 billion in mortgage servicing. <p>
And in June, PNC agreed to acquire BlackRock Financial Management L.P. for 
$240 million in cash and notes, casting PNC as one of the larger managers of fixed-income assets. <p>
The five-year earnings story at the other banking institutions on the 1994 Top 10 list also has a strong narrative of acquisitions. <p>
Yet, as these companies are considerably smaller than the behemoth PNC, their acquisitions are of a different sort. <p>
Parkvale Savings, First Western, USBancorp, Fidelity and S&T all took advantage of fire-sale rates in acquiring properties of failed thrifts through the federal Resolution Trust Corp. at the turn of the decade. <p>
As a result, these institutions have strategically improved their geographic coverage, increased their customer bases and positioned themselves for the flurry of increased consumer and mortgage lending spurred by falling interest rates. After absorbing the costs of taking over new financial terrain, these companies have reaped earnings gains.<p>

<font size =+2>Parkvale Savings: </font size> 
As Parkvale was the first banking institution in the region to take over thrifts from the RTC, it was able to acquire 11 offices of Concord Liberty Savings and Loan for the low premium of 0.3% of the liabilities, officers say. <p>
Parkvale assumed Concord Liberty liabilities, totaling $210 million in late 1989, only a few months after the RTC had set up shop.<p>
This move, coupled with the bank's stock acquisition of Lyman Savings and Loan in Pittsburgh, increased Parkvale's size 40% -- from $538 million to $755 million -- virtually overnight.<p>
"We wanted to fill in gaps in our geographic network," says Timothy Rubritz, senior vice president, treasurer and chief financial officer.<p>
"When we acquired Concord, there weren't a lot of bidders," Rubritz recalls. "We got in at the very beginning, and we were in unknown territory."<p>
"There's no question that we leveraged our balance sheet to accomplish those transactions," says Robert J. McCarthy Jr., president and CEO. "The regulators had confidence in us and allowed us to go forward."<p>
Bank officers weren't certain whether they would bid because they weren't sure whether the RTC would accept their low figure of $650,000. "We weren't sure we were going to bid until the day we did it," says Rubritz.<p>
But, Rubritz says, the RTC was highly encouraging. " 'Go ahead,' they said. 'We may not be insulted.' "<p>
There was one catch: Parkvale had to move fast. The savings bank took over within a week.<p>
"We'd like to pursue other growth oppor-tunities as they become available," Rubritz adds.<p>
Parkvale has a compounded annual growth rate of 15.8%. In September, directors declared a 5-for-4 stock split.<p>
The company's return on average assets for the year that ended June 30 was 0.82%, and its return on average equity was 13.69%.<p>

<font size =+2>Fidelity Bancorp: </font size>
Like Parkvale, Fidelity increased its deposit base by 40% overnight, largely through RTC acquisitions.<p>
In November 1991, the company, owner of Fidelity Savings Bank, went from six to nine branches by acquiring two former Atlantic Financial Savings and Loan branches, one in Allison Park and another in Bloomfield.<p>
At the same time, Fidelity bought from Parkvale Savings Bank a former Concord Liberty Branch in Mount Lebanon.<p>
Richard G. Spencer, executive vice president, treasurer and chief financial officer, says that the premium Fidelity paid the RTC for the two Atlantic Financial branches -- 1.5% of the liabilities -- was a favorable rate, considering the access to new customers that the move afforded.<p>
"It was an easy call," Spencer says. "The opportunity presented itself. And interest rates were going down."<p>
He says the $235 million bank's earnings have been boosted by the new customers that the acquisitions brought.<p>
"We're looking for that core deposit customer. After all, it's hard to entice customers to try your bank. Do they need a credit card? A home-equity loan?"<p>
Fidelity's compounded annual growth of 14.9% includes projected earnings of $1.88 per share.<p>
For the quarter that closed June 30, Fidelity had a return on average assets of 0.7% and a return on average equity of 9.7%.<p>

<font size =+2>S&T Bancorp: </font size>
In 1991, the Indiana holding company bought through the RTC nine offices of Vanguard Savings and Loan, including two in Blairsville and one in Indiana, that were literally in sight of existing branches of S&T Bank. (S&T Bancorp later sold two of these branches, one in Pitcairn and another in Trafford, as they were on the fringe of the bank's marketing area.)<p>
"It was all or nothing -- a package deal," says Robert E. Rout, senior vice president and chief financial officer. "The new branches have given us synergy."<p>
S&T also acquired four offices of Atlantic Financial: one in Indiana (where S&T is headquartered), which were merged into existing S&T branches, and three others: Holiday Park, Westmoreland Mall and Youngwood.<p>
"This expanded our coverage to areas that were growing faster than where we are," says Robert D. Duggan, chairman and CEO.<p>
Access to this new market, along with vigilant cost controls, resulted in a double-digit growth in loan portfolio, much of it from Allegheny and Westmoreland counties, officers say.<p>
This fall, shares were split 2-for-1, bringing earnings to $1.60 per share. Compounded annual growth is 14.8%.<p>
For the quarter that closed June 30, S&T's return on average assets was 1.5%, and its return on average equity, 13.11%.<p>

<font size =+2>First Western Bancorp: </font size>
This year marks First Western's third consecutive appearance on the Top 10 list. Thomas J. O'Shane, president and CEO of the New Castle-based company, indicates that some of the same planning and acquisition moves that put the company on the list in 1993 and 1992 are keeping it there this year.<p>
"We made some very prudent acquisitions. And they were priced right," O'Shane says.<p>
The first of these was First Federal of Western Pennsylvania, a $350 million thrift, in 1990.<p>
"We paid book value at the time," says O'Shane. "Since then, we've converted its balance sheet to look like that of a community bank. It had never made more than $1.7 million. Last year, it made $4.3 million." Over four years, that's a 153% increase.<p>
Next came the acquisition of some RTC holdings of Colony Federal Savings Bank in 1991.<p>
"There was a premium on the deposits of nearly 4%. But we were able to buy $100 million in residential mortgage assets at a [15%] discount from face value. I can spend the next 25 years in banking and never pull another grand slam like that."<p>
A more recent factor pushing up earnings, O'Shane says, is a project to eliminate duplication throughout the organization.<p>
First Western has a compounded annual growth rate of 13.2%, based on projected earnings of $3 per share for this year.<p>
For the quarter that closed June 30, First Western registered a return on average assets of 1.15% and a return on average shareholders' equity of 15.54%.<p>

<font size =+2> USBancorp: </font size>
Like most of the other banking institutions on this year's list, USBancorp traces much of its earnings success to earlier acquisitions. But most of USBancorp's acquisitions, unlike the others, have resulted from private sales instead of RTC auctions.<p>
The most recent of these was the acquisition of Johnstown Savings Bank in June, $360 million in assets that were merged into U.S. Bank.<p>
In 1992, Johnstown-based USBancorp bought Community Savings Bank, adding another $350 million in assets, and in 1993, it acquired four offices of Integra Bank and wrapped them into Three Rivers Bank.<p>
USBancorp had already acquired the Century III Mall branch of Atlantic Financial from the RTC at a 2% premium. This branch proved fruitful in reaching new loan customers.<p>
"One reason we wanted the Century III branch was that we had a small branch near Allegheny County Airport that was not doing well," says Terry K. Dunkle, chairman, president and CEO.<p>
Another steady source of profits in recent years, Dunkle says, has been fee income from trust management services.<p>
USBancorp, which has a 26% market share in Cambria County, has a compounded annual growth rate of 11.5%, based on projected 1994 earnings of $2.54 per share. USBancorp had a return on average assets of 0.88% and a return on average equity of 9.65% for the quarter ending June 30.<p>
The stocks of these banking concerns emerged as some of the best performing securities in the region this year. Yet they joined a cadre of manufacturing companies that have become perennials on ER's Top 10 list in recent years.<p>

<font size =+2> Industrial Scientific: </font size>
The leader, Oakdale-based Industrial Scien-tific, manufactures compact gas monitors carried by police officers, pipe fitters, wastewater treatment workers, firemen, oil workers and safety inspectors.<p>
Company executives attribute this year's strong first-quarter sales to rapid market acceptance of a new model, the LTX310 multi-gas monitor. This is one of the company's three basic models in a newly designed line.<p>
"We had more than 20 models a year ago. Now we have three that do more, with interchangeable sensors," says Kent D. McElhattan, president and CEO.<p>
In April 1993, Congress passed regulatory legislation, originally proposed 20 years earlier, requiring gas monitoring in certain confined spaces. Industrial Scientific executives estimate that this may have increased the domestic market by 10% or more, but add that competition has sprung up concomitantly.<p>
McElhattan calls the LTX310 an "exact hit on the confined space legislation."<p>
The company has a new plant in Oakdale. "The new building was part of a strategy to treat employees properly," says McElhattan. "There are few [such] opportunities to put your money where your mouth is."<p>
Currently, about 5% of the company's sales are in exports. This year, Industrial Scientific received certification from Europe's International Organization for Standardization, a requirement for marketing such products on the continent. "We're the first in our field to be certified," says McElhattan.An international sales manager is now on the ground in Europe. "Certainly it's not going to happen overnight, but Europe has terrific potential," McElhattan adds.<p>
Industrial Scientific's compounded annual growth rate of 35% is based on projected earnings of $1.68 per share for 1994. The company's first-quarter sales this year increased 26.5% over the same period in 1993.<p>

<font size =+2> Mylan Laboratories: </font size>
After earning 93 cents a share in 1993, Mylan is projected to have earnings this year of $1.25, chalking up compounded annual growth of 30.3%. For the quarter that ended June 30, Mylan had net sales of $85.15 million, up from $58.5 million in the same period last year.<p>
One reason this Pittsburgh-headquartered manufacturer of generic drugs and original compounds is continuing to post such numbers, executives say, is the rapid distribution network the company has established in recent years.<p>
The company claims to have the fastest distribution in the business, with 97% of its orders delivered in three to five working days, says Patricia Sunseri, vice president for investor and public relations.<p>
In addition, Mylan has reaped increased sales from its inroads into new products through the 1991 purchase of Dow Hickam, a Texas-based wound- and burn-dressing manufacturer and the 1992 acquisition of Bertek Inc., a Vermont transdermal (patch medication) company.<p>
"Patient compliance is a big problem. If you put on a patch, you can't forget to take your medicine," says Sunseri, discussing the potential of the transdermal market.<p>
The chief attraction of Dow Hickam, she says, was the accomplished sales force. "This was important to our growth in mid-sized and large hospitals nationwide."<p>

<font size =+2>Respironics: </font size>
Including projected year-end earnings of $1.20 per share, Respironics of Murrysville has compounded annual growth of 30.2%. Net income for the quarter that ended March 31 was $2.24 million, up from $1.9 million for the same period of 1993.<p>
Controller Dan Bevevino attributes the contin-ued earnings growth, in part, to watching costs.<p>
"We look at our expenses monthly and our product costing monthly in a good bit of detail," he says.<p>
This manufacturer of various medical ventilation devices is headed by Gerald E. McGinnis, an engineer who founded the company in 1971 with $13,000 after a two-year stint in surgical research at Allegheny General Hospital.<p>
"I was an engineer, but my approach was more of a marketing approach. I learned over those early years that people wanted to buy a product that solves a problem.... At Allegheny General, I learned what those problems were. We define our mission as being a company that wants to be first to solve the problems of the pulmonary physician."<p>
Accordingly, McGinnis says, Respironics has profited from "differentiating ourselves [from] the hardware we're selling -- through service, teaching, informing and educating the customers."<p>
In late 1993, Respironics voluntarily recalled one of its products, the BagEasy resuscitator, because of a potential for it to malfunction, though the company received no reports of actual problems.<p>
The company announced this fall that it was putting a re-designed version of the product on the market.<p>
 
<font size =+2>Medrad: </font size>
With a compounded annual growth rate of 26.2%, Medrad's projected earnings for the year are $1.13, up from 90 cents in 1993.<p>
The manufacturer of medical imaging products continues to grow from an emphasis on new products, international expansion and cost reduction, says treasurer Gary W. Bucciarelli.<p>
"We invest 10% to 11% back into research and development," Bucciarelli says. "We're interested in expanding our market share and we do that by investing heavily in new products."<p>
This year, he says, the O'Hara-based company has put on the market 12 new products related to magnetic resonant imaging (MRI).<p>
"And we're continuing work on a new injec-tion system for CT [computed tomography] scans."<p>
This year, Medrad started a subsidiary in Italy and in 1993, one in Germany. It established an export hub in the Netherlands in the mid-1980s.<p>
"We're putting people and resources in places where we'll be able to expand," says Bucciarelli, citing as an example Germany, where sales have increased 74% since the company set up a subsidiary there.  <p>
<hr>
<font size =+2>About the Rankings: </font size>
<hr>
