<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report December 1994</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Updates.gif" ISMAP></a>
<!IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="picard.part.gif"> 
<p>
<b><h2>
PC Networks for Small Business </h2></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1><b>Low costs make PC networks an attractive investment for even the very smallest companies.</FONT SIZE></b><br>
<i>By John Schriefer, Illustrations by Joseph Fiedler</i>
<hr><P>
The personal computing revolution of the past decade has given rise to a paradox: The influx of PCs to businesses in the 1980s corresponded to a period of stagnant productivity among the office workers using them.
<p>
The crux of the problem is that many companies are not making full use of their computer resources. Says Brady Bisson, a manager in the business system consulting group at Deloitte & Touche LLP, "If you are just using word processing and spreadsheets to replace the typewriter or the pencil and ledger, that's not really going to help as much as if you take fuller advantage of the capabilities of the computers."
<p>
Most computer consultants and experienced computer users agree that one of the surest ways to overcome the productivity paradox is to tie PCs together in a network, in order to take advantage of the machines as data sharing devices. According to Joe Vetter, whose company Document Services Inc. last year installed a three PC network at its Ambridge headquarters, "The beauty of getting into the network is the cost is minimal for the power you can put at your disposal."
<p>
Another local company that has realized significant benefits from networking its PCs is Industrial Scientific Corp., a $30 million manufacturer of personal gas monitors in Oakdale.
<p>
Dennis Pike, chief engineer for product support, was one of the leading advocates for installing a network. Pike explains that he was looking for a way to automate the engineering revision process. The prior system involved changing original drawings on mylar and circulating blueprints for approval. "This whole business with paper was pretty nasty," he says.
<p>
In early 1993, the company installed a network to connect roughly two dozen PCs in the engineering department. According to Pike, the company now employs workflow automation software on the network to control the flow of engineering revisions and approvals. "The electronic document management system is a lot cleaner and a lot faster," he says.
<p>
Peter Schmalz, manager of engineering, says that the engineering department had to adjust its operating procedures to get the most out of the network. "As we changed to a network system we had to change the way we did some things. We weren't fully appreciative of everything that was going to have to be done differently. It took us a while to figure out the best way for us to do it.
"At first," he says, "it was a struggle ... but now that it is getting smoothed out, we are getting used to working in this environment. We are much more efficient."
<p>
According to Schmalz, the computer network has provided some unexpected benefits, including a better, more readily accessible record of engineering revisions for future reference. In the paper system, just searching for prior copies of drawings, he says, could take hours. Now, "people can look at the whole history in 10 minutes."
<p>
Though the system at Industrial Scientific was originally installed to benefit the engineering department, Schmalz says the success of the system led to fast expansion outside of the department. "Everybody wanted it," he says. Other departments that use the engineering drawings, such as manufacturing, purchasing and service, were given access to the network.
<p>
The PC network was also tied to the existing system used by the accounting department. According to Pike, it is more cost effective to add a PC workstation than it is to add a terminal directly connected to the accounting department's computer. "We get the same thing. [The PC] emulates the terminal on the [computer], and we can do a whole load of other things, using standard PC software," he says.
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><b>ISO 9000 Payoff </FONT SIZE></b><p>
"Another big influence driving it outside of engineering was our attempt to achieve ISO certification. This is where it really paid off," Pike says.
<p>
Preparing the documentation of processes and procedures within every department in the company "was becoming a monumental task," he says. To smooth the process, the company adapted its network workflow system to control the ISO 9000 documentation process. This provided a more efficient means of standardizing manuals created in different departments, and also made it possible to make changes on the fly. Pike says the company was able to respond to the findings of the ISO auditors during its one-week inspection. "By the time they left on Friday afternoon, we had cleared every finding."
<p>
Compelling as this success story is, it may appear that the benefits of networking are limited to larger organizations where many users are sharing information. Can small businesses reap similar benefits from networking? Ask Vetter, Document Services' company controller, and the response is a resounding yes.
<p>
According to him, last year when the company was purchased by a group of Pittsburgh investors, a decision was made to consolidate the accounting for the company's three offices--Ambridge, Detroit and Atlanta--at the Ambridge location. Previously, he says, the company had used an outside CPA firm in Detroit.
<p>
Vetter's objective was to plan and install a network for corporate accounting, and on-site operations for the secure document destruction business of the company. To minimize the expense of setting up the computer system, Vetter bought a used PC and other peripherals. Though he gave some thought to handling the entire installation project on his own, he relied on Pinnatech Computer Services of Allison Park to do the installation and provide other equipment.
<p>
In one Saturday, Pinnatech wired the offices and installed the network. That same day Vetter began to put his own software on the system, and it was up and running Monday morning.
<p>
Vetter, who has 20-plus years' experience using accounting systems on mainframe, minicomputer and PC-based networks, sees clear advantages of using PC networks, even in the smallest organizations. For one thing, he says, PC networks give small businesses the ability to computerize account and business management functions in-house inexpensively, instead of relying on outside CPAs or other consultants.
<p>
Besides maintaining greater control over operations, and doing more work at lower cost, the PC network enables employees to go beyond their traditional tasks and perform greater analysis of the data on the system. "Their efficiency really picks up," he says. "Also, there is a lot of drudgery that is now being removed." This gives workers a higher level of job satisfaction as they are able to exercise more creativity and make a greater contribution to the organization.
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><b>Security and Cost Savings</FONT SIZE></b><p>
Two other advantages of computer networks over unconnected PCs, according to many users and computer professionals, are improved data security and cost-efficient sharing of expensive peripheral devices like laser printers.
<p>
According to Mark Fantozzi, director of consulting at computer and network supplier RG Technology in Avalon, most individual PC users do not make backup copies of their data, which places valuable corporate information at risk. If a user's PC fails, the data is lost. At worst, this could threaten a company's survival, and at a minimum it may make additional work to recreate the data. In a typical client-server network, all critical data files are stored on a central PC server that is backed up every day. With centralized backup, says Mark Steward, president of Pinnatech, "You won't have George or Jane running to you at tax time saying, `My drive blew, I don't have a backup!' "
<p>
Despite the clear advantages to networking, managers have to weigh the potential benefits against likely costs. Bisson points out that "the cost of networking has come down significantly." Still, the costs are by no means negligible.
<p>
Assuming a company already has desktop PCs in place, Steward puts the cost for network hardware (NIC cards and wiring), software and installation at just under $600 per user on a 10-person network. Then add another $2,000 or $3,000, at minimum, for a centralized network server with large data storage capacity, a high quality power protection device and a data backup device. This does not include ongoing service and support or training for employees.
<p>
The costs are even higher if you are starting from scratch. For example, Vetter, who was able to buy some secondhand PCs and peripherals to minimize the cost of Document Services' system, says that the company has about $12,000 to $13,000 tied up in its five-user network.
<p>
Companies with existing hardware and software in place may also run up against additional, unforeseen costs. Among the typical unexpected expenses, according to Fantozzi, are the costs of purchasing new applications software, either to standardize the applications used throughout a company or to upgrade from outdated versions that will not work on the network. But it doesn't end there. Says Fantozzi, "If the new version doesn't do a conversion of data real well, then we may have to convert your data. That is more cost."
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><b>Don't Cut Training</FONT SIZE></b><p>
When decision-makers become fully aware of the costs, says Fantozzi, "They always try to trim back, and the one place where they almost immediately trim back is training." That is nearly always a mistake, experts say. <p>
Bob Ryberg, director of operations at RG Technology, gives a useful analogy. "If Port Authority said, `We are going to hire a lot of new drivers, but we are going to cut back on training on how to drive a bus,' [they] are going to have a lot of accidents. So they say, `When we hire, we train.' " Likewise, he says, companies must emphasize training to overcome employee fear of the unknown technology and to get the most out of the investment in people and machines.
<p>
According to Bisson, training also sets a tone that emphasizes manage-ment's commitment to using the network. "Training employees and getting them involved in the process makes them feel comfortable that management is behind that activity."<p>
Employee involvement, however, should come long before the network is installed, in planning what kind of system to install. In the case of Industrial Scientific, key operational personnel, specifically Pike, were involved in determining what the system would do. But Pike was not initially involved in the purchasing decision. As a result, he says that the company originally purchased a network that "was very complex and very cumbersome" to use with the company's PCs. As a result of the imperfect fit between the network's server and the PC workstations used by employees, Pike later lobbied to replace the network with the PC-based system currently in use. <p>
In Document Services' case, Vetter was the point man in planning and purchasing the system. From this experience, Vetter sees a lesson for other companies: "The one thing that would stick out is that there has to be some ownership of the network at the location. You could have a consultant, and they could come in and ... build a Cadillac when all you need is a Ford. So you have to have some kind of understanding of what your requirements are."
Besides planning the network, Vetter believes this ownership must carry over to network operations, so that the company has a person who understands enough to perform basic backup and troubleshooting, but who also knows when it is time to call out for help. "There has to be a person with the time and initiative to get involved. You can't just turn it on and let it play by itself," he says.
<p>
Bisson strongly recommends using suppliers as on-call network trouble-shooters by purchasing service contracts when you buy equipment. "That is a cost savings, because you don't need a real seasoned MIS staff." Steward likens his company's network service and support contracts to the services he gets from a CPA. Pinnatech employees could do the company's books, but, he says, "We have accountants do our books because they can save us money in the long run."
<p>
Similarly, Steward cautions against do-it-yourself network installation, even in fairly simple cases. "We make a living going out and fixing other people's problems." Even if a company has internal computer know-how to draw on, they may do better turning to a specialist. Says Steward, "If time is money to the company, they are going to want us to do it because they are going to save a lot of time and effort." A typical installation, he says, takes one Saturday afternoon; the customer has no downtime.
<p>
According to Bisson, lower costs make networking a viable option for many smaller businesses. And, as many users will attest, networks open up possibilities for employees and managers to accomplish more in a workday and to change for the better how they get things done. Pike, Schmalz and Vetter are hard-pressed to imagine how a company could not benefit from networking their computers.
<p>
But before companies make a leap for the technology, they must determine what specific problem or process the network is meant to address. If the problem is simply a lack of productivity of computers in one's organization, the immediate solution may not be to throw more technology (i.e., a network) at the user. Rather, the challenge may be to modernize the work force.
<p>
To borrow a maxim from the retail industry, the three most important things in employing computers in the workplace are training, training and training.
<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+1><b>Network Primer</FONT SIZE></b><p>
<DL>
<LI>Network: Network operating system (NOS) software provides the essential file sharing and communications functions between PC workstations and a PC server on a network.<p>
<LI>Client-Server Network: A computer network in which one PC acts as a central storage point (a server) for shared data resources that can be used by other PCs (workstations) on the network.<p>
<LI>Peer-to-Peer Network: A lower-cost alternative to a client-server network in which each workstation contains shared file resources that can be used by others. In a peer-to-peer network, there is no server.<p>
<LI>Network Interface Card (NIC): A small printed circuit board that is inserted in a workstation or server, by which the PC is connected by wire to the network.<p>
</DL>
<hr>
