<B><h2>
Education: Target Marketing </h2></B><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
Colleges and universities are 
becoming increasingly sophisticated 
in targeting their audiences.
</FONT SIZE><br><i>By Lydia Strohl  (8 pages)</i>

<p>
Institutions of higher education used to think that marketing was beneath them. But decreasing numbers of high school graduates, a decline in test scores and a proliferation of higher education options has forced schools to compete for top students.
<p>
"In 1979, the word marketing was an unspoken thing," says Kathy Greuter, vice president of the National Research Center for College and University Admissions. "It was commercial; it had nothing to do with black robes and pillars. Just in the last five to 10 years that word has become very acceptable in college communities --  they had to seek the help of experts."
<p>
That movement led to a plethora of new titles infiltrating college administration, like director of enrollment management and director of enrollment marketing. They talk about target marketing, mission statements and the four Ps: price, product, promotion and placement. But far from evoking winces from the hallowed halls, these new techniques are being embraced.
<p>
"Back in the olden days, in the late '60s and early '70s, we were the gatekeepers," says Kevin Altomari, executive associate director of admissions and financial aid at the University of Pittsburgh. "We collected applications and decided who got in --  there were lots vying for a few spaces. Now it's a buyer's market, and institutions need to find a way to market themselves uniquely among their peers."
<p>
Schools are becoming increasingly sophisticated in targeting their audiences; they buy lists, peruse applications from their own students for commonalities and look at national demographics to see which areas have a dearth of the educational opportunity they are offering. They target these audiences with intense media campaigns, which include television, radio, print and even billboard ads. They undertake mass mailings of slick publications. They visit high schools across the nation, ask alumni to represent them in their home communities and court high school counselors.
<p>
But it is what they're saying that has become the important part. No longer is teaching theory enough. Colleges and universities are finding it necessary to prove that their education is relevant for today's market.
<p>
"The buzz [phrase] is: What will I be prepared to do when I graduate?' " says Jim Emrietti, dean of enrollment at Carlow College. "We are a liberal arts college with a keen eye toward orientation in earning a living. Not many students these days are professing a desire to learn purely for learning's sake."
<p>
Chatham College, which vetoed going co-ed in 1991, has modified its program to better prepare women students for the working world. The administration guarantees opportunities for two internships to each student, and has instituted cooperative programs. Chatham students can take an engineering or teaching degree in conjunction with Carnegie Mellon University. Another program guarantees early admission to medical school. Alums are called on for career and professional advice. And the school has started master's programs in both physical and occupational therapy, in response to growing demand in these professions.
<p>
"We chose to be an Olympic training village rather than a protected cloister," says Dr. Esther Barazzone, president of Chatham College. "We felt we needed to offer broader opportunities if we were truly taking women's aspirations seriously."
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><b>
Following Job Trends </FONT SIZE></B> <p>
It is common for schools to follow employment trends when choosing program direction. Duquesne University's School of Health Sciences, which was developed five years ago, now has 700 students.
"We have added 46 new programs in six years," says Dr. John Murray, president of Duquesne University. "We look at societal needs, and talk to people doing it for a living."
<p>
One example of practical partnering is going on at Point Park College, which has developed an environmental protection science major in conjunction with the Environmental Protection Agency.
"The EPA found they had to retrain college graduates," says Dr. J. Matthew Simon, president of Point Park College. "These students are ready to hit the road running when they graduate."
<p>
Examples of niche filling can be found all over the region. Washington & Jefferson College has an entrepreneurial management program; Point Park offers a degree in mortuary science. Butler County Community College does training in total quality and computer-aided design for local corporations.
<p>
Robert Morris College is responding to feedback from the business world by changing its curriculum across the board to incorporate training in an area executives proclaimed a major gap in student preparation: communication.
<p>
"Students follow jobs--parents do too--and they're savvy consumers. In the past, many of us forgot that," says Dr. Edward Nicholson, president of Robert Morris, where the dominant degrees are in science and business administration. "We asked our advisory board what they would change for graduates, and without hesitation they said, `Why can't students write better? They can't give a good presentation. They aren't articulate in front of a group.' "
<p>
The program change will increase the core communications requirement from two to nine courses, beginning in 1995. Four of these courses must be communication-intensive offerings within the student's major, in which they are graded on knowledge, writing skills and oral presentation.
<p>
These programs are marketed to an increasingly wide geographic range. Many schools in the region that traditionally drew primarily from western Pennsylvania now have national and international representation in their ranks. Of this year's University of Pittsburgh freshman class, 25% are from Allegheny County, down from 50% 10 years ago. Duquesne University's 1994 freshman class represents all 50 states and 82 nations.
<p>
International affiliations have become a mainstay of universities around the region. Washington & Jefferson has relationships with universities in England, and is developing them with colleges in Mexico and perhaps Colombia. Duquesne has affiliations with universities in Pakistan, Spain and some African countries.
"These are not just junior year abroad programs," says Murray. "We have both student and faculty exchanges. They increase diversity and point of view on the campus. It's a new dimension in education."
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
Comes Down to Money</FONT SIZE></B> <p>
Most schools add programs that dovetail with existing offerings, or need few additional resources.
"We look at programming in terms of what we can do with relatively little money," says Nicholson of Robert Morris College. The school added football this year, attracting 150 new students for an investment of $452,000--the cost of a practice field, locker room and equipment--$150,000 of which was a gift. "We're not, for example, going to start a new music school," he says.
<p>
Nonetheless, expanding programs and attracting new students often means investing in new facilities and equipment. Last fall, La Roche College completed a $6 million fitness center, and is planning a new dormitory and an academic building for a total cost of $12 million. These buildings include facilities for not only La Roche itself but also the whole North Hills community, with additions like a gallery and video editing lab.
<p>
"We intend to be a resource for the North Hills," says Sister Carolyn Winschel, vice president at La Roche. "The NAACP, Il Campanoli and the Ebony Women meet here already, and the library is open to all North Hills library cardholders. It's probably not the only reason, but when we opened the gym our freshman class increased from 119 to 160."  
<p>
Rather than build a clinic for their nurse anesthetist program, however, 
La Roche uses five area hospitals for the clinical portion of that degree. Affiliations like this profit the school by requiring little investment and attracting students, and benefit the students by giving them real world experience.
<p>
New dimensions often target specific audiences. A drop in numbers of high school graduates (8.3% nationwide from 1988 to 1993), prodded many colleges and universities to provide offerings to attract nontraditional students.
"Attendance is up at our off-campus learning centers," says Dr. Bill Katip, vice president for enrollment services at Geneva College in Beaver County. "Twenty years ago we didn't recruit at all. But today is a different ball game all together, with the decline in traditional students. Especially in Beaver County, where we have lost half of our high school classes."
Geneva College has extension programs in Moon, Philadelphia, New Castle, Butler, Monroeville and the South Hills. It offers a degree completion program, which has more than 300 enrollees with an average age of 37.5.
<p>
This entree by four-year residential colleges into evening and weekend classes raids the traditional realm of the community college. So, in an effort to keep numbers steady, community colleges have increasingly appealed to the traditional student. This proliferation of higher education options being aggressively marketed to students, believes Don Munce, president of NRCCUA, probably accounts for the increase in percentage of students entering college. In 1984, 44% of Pennsylvania high school seniors went on to some form of higher education; in 1994, that number jumped to 64%.
<p>
"There are less students to go around, but more are going to college," says Munce. "More and more colleges are after students, and that encourages them to go. Plus, they can work and go to school right in their hometown."
<p>
Enrolling in part-time and community college courses also takes the financial sting out of higher education. With tuition rising about 5% a year among local institutions, students are looking for the best buys.
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>
Price Shopping </FONT SIZE></B><p>
"We find a lot of competitive advantage in being the most affordable institution of higher education in Allegheny County," says Dave Egan, director of public relations at the Community College of Allegheny County. According to a study done by Executive Report, tuition at CCAC as of August 1994 was $1,488; community colleges in Butler and Westmoreland counties are comparably low.
<p>
On the high end are Carnegie Mellon University at $16,960 per year and Washington & Jefferson at $15,360 annually. The range is complete in between, from Pitt and Penn State at $4,962 and $3,602 respectively, to Carlow College at $9,826 and Seton Hill at $10,240 annually.
<p>
To help potential students afford education, colleges are offering a variety of programs. In some of their majors, Point Park offers "College-Fast," an accelerated, fixed tuition program.
"Two things work together to yield a 30% savings," says Simon. "No increases are passed along during those years, and you finish the degree in three years, rather than four."
<p>
Schools offer a variety of financial aid incentives: state-affiliated schools give breaks to Pennsylvania residents; others will raise money for scholarships or provide the money themselves. Robert Morris, which offered $200,000 in institutional aid in 1989, awarded more than $1 million in 1994.
<p>
A common practice now is discounting, where the institution lowers its cost to entice a potential student without getting that money from another source, in essence, eating the difference.
"Financial aid is often awarded as colleges are working much harder to recruit students than in the past," says Greuter. "But they can't give away too much or there will be no revenue stream from tuition. Giving more aid means cutbacks, and when those reach recruiting and marketing it means less students and less tuition. It's a self-fulfilling prophecy."
<p>
Schools are spending ever more on recruitment and marketing efforts. Duquesne University now spends $700 to recruit a student. Geneva College's Katip estimates that the college spends an average of $2,000 per student in recruiting and marketing, a figure that's doubled over the past 10 years. Nicholson says that in the last five years, Robert Morris' promotional budget has increased 600%, from $75,000 to $425,000.
<p>
But it seems to be paying off.  The colleges around the region are finding their niches and report that they are pleased with attendance levels. To most this means that the niche fits.
"We are looking for the match. We want to recruit graduates, not just students," says Katip. "Half of the students that come here are first generation college students. We are a blue-collar campus. A lot of our students say it is easier for them to fit in here than it was in high school."
<p>
Top of mind for most college administrators seems to be matching values with those their student desires. But whether a student is looking for a blue-collar, Catholic, community-service, all-women, urban, rural, technical or liberal arts environment, they have a friend in western Pennsylvania.
<p>
<hr>
