<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report December 1994 Issue</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.EN.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/editor.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2>Beam Us Up Scotty </FONT SIZE><i> By Jane A. Black</i><P>
With this issue, our 150th, Executive Report proudly enters the electronic age. We are now on the Internet, a vast confederation of computer databases and users. While Internet is not the much talked about information superhighway, it is a publishing and communications medium to be reckoned with. <p>

Internet is a government spawned network, that, at press time, has 25 million users in over 150 countries. (About 2 million users are signing on every month.) In western Pennsylvania, there are some 100,000 Internet users. <p>

Executive Report, like other magazines and newspapers, really had little choice in whether to get on the Internet, or some other on-line service. Why? Because, as Rosalind Resnick, publisher of the Interactive Publishing Alert, notes, "aspiring publishers with nothing more than a personal computer and a modem will soon be eating [our] lunches" if we don't get in on the act. Consider this: More than 2,700 newspapers are now experimenting with some kind of electronic venture. In 1989, there were just 42 plugging in. <p>

Being on the 'Net certainly has its rewards -- for all the new people we are reaching, we have none of the traditional printing or distribution costs. We haven't had to pay one extra penny for paper, presses or postage. <p>

There are other advantages. We will be able to track how many people have looked at our publication, and solicit reader feedback in a user-friendly way. Armed with such knowledge, we will be able to better address the wants and needs of readers when it comes time to plan the editorial calendar.  <p>

Certainly there are those who think that the new electronic media sounds the knell for more traditional concerns such as newspapers and magazines. But as Donald D. Kummerfeld points out in Folio, radio didn't kill off print, and television did not snuff out radio or print. "What new media do is force each old medium to redefine what it does best," Kummerfeld says. Indeed. And these new media will go far in helping us in that endeavor. <p>

Truly this is an exciting time for publishers and editors. We are in the embryonic stages of a new economy, one that is being propelled by technology and information. This information age will be as different as the industrial revolution was from the agricultural era. <p>
Not long ago, I read that there is more information in one Sunday New York Times than my great-grandparents encountered in a lifetime. If the information explosion continues at its current pace, the world's knowledge base will double every 70 days by 2010. Here's to surviving the information overload. <p>

By the way, if you have any comments about this or any other issue, you can now send us e-mail at er_editor@execreport.com.<p>
Visit our storefront at Url: http://www.execreport.com/er.html provided by Internet Services Corp. of the North Side. We're glad to be aboard, and please bear with us while we're under construction.<p>
