<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report December 1994</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.L.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<font size =+2>Some Taxing Matters</font size><p>
I found "Tax-Deferred Annuities: More Taxing Than Commonly Believed" by Richard D. Rosen in the September 1994 issue to be filled with generalities and misinformation.
There are two points by Mr. Rosen I consider factual: Annuities are not for everybody and tax deferral may not be an advantage. Beyond [this], I find Mr. Rosen's analysis of annuities lacking.
<dl>
He lists six points following the statement "Most annuities also have the following disadvantages." I would like to address each:
<LI> Variable annuities often have high expense charges. However, there are more than a few which don't. Furthermore, an alternative -- a regular mutual fund -- usually either carries a load with an expense fee or no load but the same 2% fee structure or higher! 99.99% of all fixed annuities have no expense charges at all!
<LI> The state premium tax applies only to funds in non-qualified annuities. If you use an annuity to fund your IRA, SEP, or profit-sharing plan, there is no tax. Also, [with] a non-qualified annuity, there are a few companies who [pay the tax for you] or add it to the surrender charge; as the charge disappears, so does the tax. Either way, the tax does not come out of the annuitant's deposit.
<LI> Twenty years ago annuities did charge upfront sales charges. Today, I know of no annuity which carries an upfront load. A seller of an annuity does make a commission, typically 4% to 5% of the amount invested, but it does not come out of the investor's deposit, [it] is paid by the annuity company.
<LI> [The fourth] statement is basically accurate, except for one omission -- most annuities allow the annuitant to have 10% of his funds after the first policy anniversary without any surrender charge. This gives the annuitant access in an emergency, yet protects the company so it can credit a better long-term rate to invested funds. The surrender periods help the company price the product, and pay the selling agent. But again, there is almost never an upfront sales charge.
<LI> [The fifth point is] definitely true, and the prime reason why no one under age 45 should consider buying a non-qualified annuity. However, IRAs, 401(k)s, and other qualified money are subject to the same penalty. Someone looking to piggyback their fully funded retirement plan should consider the annuity part of the plan. Also, if the annuity is to be used inside an IRA, 401(k), etc., the pre-59 1/2 rules already apply.
<LI> The annuities available today have provisions that completely contradict 
Mr. Rosen's statement [on withdrawal limitations]. How about an annuity that will pay out interest monthly, directly to your checking account? How about [one] that allows you access any time without penalty if you have to go into a nursing home? How about an annuity that guarantees to pay out the minimum distribution required by the IRS on IRA accounts for people over age 70 1/2? How about a split-annuity?
</DL>
Mr. Rosen [says] that annuities should be considered only as a replacement for "ordinary income-type investments." Not true! A fixed annuity is ideal for someone wanting to secure their hard earned dollars. People nearing/in retirement should be looking at annuities as an alternative to non-guaranteed accounts such as stocks, bonds and related mutual funds. They should see them as having the advantage over guaranteed CDs because of higher credited interest rates and the tax deferral! <p>
It is interesting that not one word was mentioned about probate. Annuities generally escape probate costs and thus keep settlement costs down. <p>
Mr. Rosen's premise [was] "tax deferral isn't all it's cracked up to be," but I believe the implication is that the only objective advisors are those who don't sell, but consult. <p>
I must be cautious not to get involved in the "unauthorized practice of law" and to be wary of dishing out tax advice. I've never heard of someone telling an attorney or CPA to dispense from the "unauthorized practice of insurance" and to keep from evaluating financial products. <p>
<i>Stephen E. Fuhrer, ChFC, Fuhrer's Inc.</i><p>

<b>Editor's note:</b> <i>Mr. Fuhrer's letter was edited for space. A response from the article's author, also edited for space, follows. </i>
<hr>
[My] thesis ... was that many people purchasing variable annuities focus on tax deferral and are unaware of tax disadvantages, expenses on returns and the inflexibility of these instruments. The tax disadvantages which were the focus of my article were: <p>
Variable annuities convert long-term capital gains into ordinary income.
<DL>
Variable annuities cause certain appre-ciation to be taxed as ordinary income.
<LI> I stated that annual expense charges reduce the rate of return. Mr. Fuhrer admits that "variable annuities often have high expense charges." However, he asserts that mutual funds, including no-loads, purchased outside of an annuity have "the same 2% fee structure or higher!" In actuality, the expense ratios of most no-loads are well below 2%, although some are this high. With respect to my failing to mention that most fixed annuities have no expense charge -- [Mr. Fuhrer] apparently misunderstood. I was cautioning readers to consider the expense charge when projecting returns on variable annuities. There obviously are expense charges even in fixed annuities. They simply are not separately stated.
<LI> I pointed out the 2% Pennsylvania premium tax. Mr. Fuhrer [says] this tax doesn't apply if you buy the annuity inside a qualified retirement plan. I don't know why anyone would buy a variable annuity inside such a plan. The plan itself provides the tax deferral.
<LI> I had no evil purpose in my use of the phrase "sales commission" as opposed to "sales charge."
<LI> Mr. Fuhrer correctly points out that most annuities permit annual withdrawals of up to 10% of the annuitant's funds without any surrender charge. Unfortunately, the IRS in many cases will impose a 10% penalty on such withdrawals.
<LI> Mr. Fuhrer agrees that there is a 10% income tax penalty on any earnings withdrawn from an annuity before the investor reaches 59 1/2. His rebuttal is that the same penalty applies to withdrawals from qualified plans. [That] is irrelevant. My article is comparing mutual funds bought inside annuities to mutual funds bought directly.
<LI> Mr. Fuhrer feels my statement that annuities impose limitations on the timing and manner of withdrawals is out of date. To support his position, he asserts that today's annuities allow you to access your funds at any time without surrender charge "if you have to go into a nursing home" or will "pay out the interest earned monthly directly to your checking account." When compared to the availability of money invested in mutual funds outside of an annuity, I'm not impressed.
</DL>
Mr. Fuhrer takes exception to my statement that annuities should be considered only as a replacement for "ordinary income-type investments." Mr. Fuhrer states that "people nearing/in retirement should be seriously looking at annuities as an alternative to non-guaranteed accounts such as ... mutual funds." Good advice, but irrelevant. My point was that an investor who has determined that he should invest in mutual funds will generally be better off doing so outside a variable annuity. I indicated that when ordinary income-type investments such as CDs are the preferred investment, fixed annuities will sometimes be preferable and listed the criteria to be examined in order to make this determination. <P>
Mr. Fuhrer's final point was that annuities avoid probate. If payable to a beneficiary other than the annuitant's estate, this is correct. My article was not intended to be an encyclopedic treatment of annuities. I was attempting to restore some balance by pointing out matters under-emphasized in sales literature.<P>
<i>Richard D. Rosen, director, Cohen & Grigsby </i>
<hr>
