<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report December 1994</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Opinion.GE.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+3><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="GuestEditor.gif"> </FONT SIZE><FONT SIZE=+2>Why Building Codes and Politics Don't Mix</FONT SIZE><br><i>By Roger L. Kingsland</i><P>
Last spring, I came across a cover story in a local magazine featuring New York City real estate developer Richard Penzer. With great interest, I started to read it but soon became alarmed at Penzer's suggestion that the city relax its building codes in order to make it easier for him to develop projects in Pittsburgh. <p>
Several of my colleagues were also alarmed at this possibly danger-ous mix of politics and public safety. Therefore, on behalf of the American Institute of Architects (AIA), we wrote a letter to the mayor's office warning the dangers of changing a model building code for political reasons. While it's always tempting to attract outside money to invest in Pittsburgh, City Hall should realize that making adaptations to building codes as a result of lobbying efforts can have far-reaching ramifications -- all negative.  <p>
Understanding that there is no shortage of important issues for the mayor and the rest of City Hall to address, we were not surprised when we didn't receive a response. However, it's still an important issue of which the public and local business community should be aware.  <p>
Although it would seem relatively simple to change just a few aspects of the building code, it's important to understand that building codes represent minimum life safety standards. They are established through rigorous research and constant updating by the sponsoring agency (in this case, BOCA, the Building Officials & Code Administrators International Inc.). In combination, all of the aspects of a building code are intended to ensure an adequate, practical level of life safety. Building code decisions should be made by people with technical expertise in life safety issues, not by politicians or real estate developers. <p>
When examined, Penzer's intimation that Pittsburgh's building code is inflexible (and thereby hinders downtown development) is found wanting. BOCA, recognizing the need for code flexibility, adopted Article 32 in 1985, which established a numerical rating for various components of building safety for adaptive reuse of existing structures. As long as architects achieve an overall minimum score, they are free to choose the best combination of building safety components relative to the specific building.  <p>
There is yet further evidence to support our contention that Pittsburgh's building codes should not be relaxed. For example, the BOCA code was adopted locally in 1981 specifically to replace the then antiquated 1947 city of Pittsburgh code with a nationally recognized standard. Second, the BOCA code is one of three model building codes in use in the country. Each of them is constantly being updated by recognized technical experts in building safety. A new edition of the code is issued every three years, and we hope that the city, which is presently using the 1990 edition, adopts the already published 1993 version soon. <p>
The BOCA code is viewed so favorably that Pennsylvania, which has not had a state building code for over 20 years (and is one of the few states in the nation without one), has begun the legislative process to adopt it as the code for the entire commonwealth. <p>
But let's not forget the most important aspect of a good building code that affects everyone: "It helps ensure the health, safety and welfare of the general public." Architects, as licensed design professionals, are morally, ethically and legally bound to protect that health, safety and welfare of the general public. <p>
So let's think twice when someone, no matter how good his or her intentions may be, suggests that a building code be changed to make development more attractive. It may be possible to make codes more adaptable to specific forms of commercial development. However, the decision should be based on hard research and conclusions arrived at by experts in the field of public safety. In the long run, we're all better off keeping political influence out of the realm of public safety, still one of the primary roles of government.  <p>
In the opinion of the Pittsburgh chapter of the American Institute of Architects, Pittsburgh is and will continue to be a viable market for downtown development, as evidenced by the building surge in the 1980s (e.g., One Oxford Centre, One Mellon Center, CNG Tower, Fifth Avenue Place, The Vista Hotel, The Pennsylvanian, et al.). Such investment has carried through to today, typified by the recent redevelopment of the Cultural District and elsewhere. Relaxing our building codes sounds like good sense on the surface, but will only threaten public safety in the end. According to the aforementioned article, New York City may have "looked the other way" regarding its codes when Penzer came calling, but we've proven it's not necessary in order to promote both investment in the city and public safety.  <p>

<i>Roger L. Kingsland, AIA, is managing partner in the North Side architectural firm of Kingsland Scott Bauer Havekotte (KSBH) Architects. The opinions expressed here are the author's own. </i>
