<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report December 1994 Issue</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.ER.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
The month ending Oct. 14 was another good one for western Pennsyl-vania stocks. The ER Index, which is com-prised of 25 area companies, improved 0.25%, while the S&P 500 declined 1.2% for the same period. Since the start of the index on Aug. 15, the ER Index is up nearly 8.9% vs. 1.71% for the S&P 500. <p>
The advance has been led primarily by a resurgence in technology issues, including Fore Systems, Black Box Corp., Legent and Cable Design Technologies, each of which recorded strong gains during the month. Fore Systems, the leader in local area networking products based on the fast growing ATM (asynchronous transfer mode) technology, exploded more than one-third, to 50 1/2 per share from 37 3/4, during the month. The Warrendale-based company announced it would supply Hewlett-Packard with its ATM adapter cards. <p>
Black Box Corp. moved up more than 8.5% for the month, to 12 3/4. The company announced a record quarter ended Sept. 30, with revenues up 15% and earnings up 34%. The company continues to steadily pay down debt, and also announced a new product sourcing program that should cut costs by $6 million over the next three years. Black Box Corp., which is headquartered in Lawrence, is the world's leading direct marketer of networking and connectivity products. <p>
<DL>
<LI>It was not a good month for rail stocks, however. MK Rail and Johnstown America Corp. both plunged. MK Rail, which primarily remanufactures locomotives, announced for the second time in as many quarters that results would be disappointing. The company cited higher than expected costs as the main culprit. The stock sank to its lowest levels since coming public in April, before recovering somewhat. At 10 3/4, MK Rail is selling for about half of its high for the year, 21. 
Johnstown America, which manufactures coal and intermodal cars, dropped 24% for the month, to 20 1/2. Concerns over earnings and ongoing negotiations for a new labor agreement with the steelworkers union in Johnstown, combined with an untimely exit out of the stock by a couple of the company's former venture investors, helped to push it down. Management, by the way, is extremely bullish about the company's prospects.
<LI>Speaking of steelworkers, it seems that the 10-week strike against Allegheny Ludlum earlier this year was so successful that 470 of the company's 2,000 salaried workers now want to join the union.
When was the last time you can recall blue-collar employees complaining about mandatory overtime? It seems just a short time ago workers were shoving each other out of the way to work overtime. Not anymore. At manufacturing plants around the country, and Pittsburgh is no exception, the recent upsurge in factory utilization rates, combined with continuing downsizing, seems to be taking its toll. It is clear that while people may differ about where we stand in the current economic cycle, there is little doubt that the recovery is resulting in some significant fatigue on the plant floor. As one local labor leader said to us the other day, "What ever happened to the 40-hour workweek?"

<LI>Mylan Laboratories continued its impressive rise, tacking on 1 5/8, or 6.3%, for the month, closing at 27 5/8. Mylan announced it would sell a generic version of Eli Lillys antibiotic drug, Ceclor, for Lilly. It is the latest in a string of such announcements. Mylan has recently entered similar arrangements with SmithKline, Upjohn and Pfizer.
<LI>American Eagle Outfitters recorded a 47.9% increase in sales for the five weeks ending Oct. 1. Same store sales rose 4.1%. Sales for the nine weeks ended Oct.1 rose 53.9%, to $48.5 million. American Eagle, which has opened an astounding 21 stores so far this quarter, plans to have an additional 28 ready for the holiday selling season.
<LI>Dravo announced it would sell its construction aggregates business to Martin Marietta Materials for about $130 million. Dravo, which had been seeking a buyer for some time, says it intends to focus on other areas within its lime business.
<LI>Respironics, which voluntarily pulled its popular line of BagEasy disposable manual resuscitators off the market last year after some minor defects were discovered, announced it has received approval from the U.S. Food & Drug Administration to resume selling a new family of resuscitators, which have been "comprehensively redesigned." The new product has two-thirds fewer parts and requires two-thirds fewer operations to manufacture than the former line. At a presentation in New York, the company's chief financial officer, Dennis Meteny, was extremely upbeat about the company's opportunities in the non-invasive respiratory market. Respironics' stock price, which tumbled to 16 last year and has since recovered to about 20, is still selling well below the company's growth rate.
</DL>
<I>ER Index is compiled by Doug Thomas, vice president and director of research at the HomeState Pennsylvania Growth Fund in Lancaster.<I>
