<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report December 1994 Issue</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.C.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Taking a Page from Mellon</FONT SIZE><br>
Mellon Bank has made its way between the covers of a relatively new book on business process reengineering (BPR) as one of 11 case studies. The book, "Beyond the Basics of Reengineering: Survival Tactics for the '90s," takes a holistic look at one of the latest management philosophies sweeping the business world.<P>
BPR has been defined by its creator, Dr. Michael Hammer, as "the fundamental rethinking and radical redesign of business process to achieve dramatic improvements in critical, contemporary measures of performance, such as cost, quality, service and speed." The Kodak Co. is credited with being the first to use formal BPR methodology as introduced by Hammer in 1990.<P>
Fitzwilliam, N.H.-based Consultant News publisher Jim Kennedy says BPR is "no different than dozens of other fads that have preceded it," adding that it is past the wild acceptance and digestion stages and on to the disillusionment stage.<P>

A survey of chief information officers in North America by Deloitte & Touche, however, indicates that two-thirds of the responding CIOs were somewhat satisfied or very satisfied with the results of their companies' business process reengineering efforts.<P>
The coverage of Mellon in "Beyond the Basics of Reengineering" focuses on changes in the company's master trust services area. Mellon, through its business performance improvement department, has designed an ambitious BPR plan for the trust department which uses technology and forward-minded methodologies to satisfy a sophisticated, demanding customer and to gain an edge in a growing, lucrative market.<P>
The goal is to revolutionize the way Mellon processes and services 401(k) accounts. A new workflow management system was to be rolled out over a period of nine months. If successful, other areas in the bank such as private asset management, jumbo mortgages, global securities, global asset management, investment services and investment products may get in on the act.<P>
"Beyond the Basics of Reengineering" was published in May by the Institute of Industrial Engineers in Norcross, Ga. IIE is a nonprofit, international professional association of more than 30,000 members whose principle endeavor is produc-tivity and quality improvement through systems integration. There is a Pittsburgh chapter.<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>Pay Slide</FONT SIZE><br>
According to a survey by Hewitt Associates, Pittsburgh area employees have experienced a decline in salary increases over the past two years.<P>
The survey compared both local and national salary increases in relation to executive groups, unions, non-unions, exempts and non-exempts.<P>

Mike Lee of Hewitt Associates' Pittsburgh office sees two reasons for the decline: national fixed costs and result-based pay. Lee believes there is a trend toward companies' managing costs conservatively.<P>
"Companies do not want higher costs so they are focusing the pay on performance," says Lee. "If results are there, the rewards are there."<P>
Downsizing, on the other hand, is a trend that is not a direct result of salary figures.<P>
"In many cases, companies need to figure that in the long run they will have to pay people more because of additional duties," says Lee. "When they downsize, they put more responsibilities on others."<P>
The market and the cost of living in Pittsburgh are two factors that Lee says are keeping employees here regardless of salary figures.<P>
"Pittsburgh is an attractive place to work and live," says Lee. "People would rather look long and hard for a job than move away. So once you take these factors into consideration, the figures really aren't so surprising."<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>Lawyers' Lawyers</FONT SIZE><br>
Aiken, S.C.-based Woodward/White Inc. has released the results of its biennial survey identifying the "best and brightest" in the legal profession.<P>
Based on a 12-month poll of lawyers across the country, this year's list contains 13,417 lawyers nationwide, slightly more than 1% of the nation's 862,954 lawyers. Four new categories -- banking, franchise, workers' compen-sation and legal malpractice -- have been added, and the number of women lawyers listed has increased by 68%.<P>
This year's effort involved 15,000 letters and 32,000 phone calls. The company routinely couched its inquiries in the following terms: "If you had a close friend or relative who needed [for example] a real estate lawyer, and you couldn't handle the case yourself for reasons of conflict of interests or time, to whom would you refer them?"<P>
The company indicates in the introduction the possible problems with this methodology, but the editors maintain that these lists represent the "most useful guide to the best lawyers in the United States ever compiled."<P>
Published results appear in the "The Best Lawyers in America: 1995-1996," which comes out this month. This sixth edition is priced at $110.<P>
Four hundred and eighty-four of the listed lawyers are from Pennsylvania. The accom-panying list shows the number of lawyers from Executive Report's readership area.<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>Active County</FONT SIZE><br>
The economic surge taking place in Armstrong County in past months is making it "The Best Thing Next To Pittsburgh," like its new slogan states.<P>
Recent marketing strategies and new businesses have left the sixth-class county with a new outlook on the business world.<P>
The county recently kicked off a two-year economic development marketing program. Richard Palilla, executive director of the department of planning and development, says that both the Chamber of Commerce and the board of directors wanted to reintroduce the county to western Pennsylvania businesses, so they developed a plan.<P>
But even before the campaign began, Armstrong County was starting to attract more businesses to the area.<P>
On July 1, the former Moonlight Mushroom farm went back into operation under new management as Creekside Mushrooms Ltd. Creekside has more than 150 employees and hopes to double the figure later this year.<P>
Leading Technologies, a division of Composide Inc. that manufactures semiconductor lead frames and other interconnect products, began operating in a 67,000-square-foot spot in the Parks Bend Farms Industrial Park in September.<P>
The company has 30 employees. That number is expected to grow to 100 over the next three years.<P>
The Speedex Tractor Corp. also became the largest tenant in the Parks Bend Farms New Venture Center in August, leasing 10,000 square feet of manufacturing space. Speedex has contracts to sell tractors in Mexico and is pursuing other international business opportunities throughout Europe.
Word has it that Armstrong County may also be the site of a new federal prison. Palilla says that there are sites in the county that could hold the prison, but no plans have been made.<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>New Business</FONT SIZE><br>
Via Veneto, an Italian retailer of artwork and clothing, has opened its first U.S. store in The Galleria in Mount Lebanon. Praxair Inc., an industrial gas producer, has opened an office in Pittsburgh.

This month's Chronicles was written and compiled by Jane A. Black and Kristin Giron.
