</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Report December 1994 Issue</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="http://www.pittsburgh.net/cgi-bin/imagemap/ERBanner">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../pictures/Departments.MM.gif" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>How to Select an Advisor </FONT SIZE> <i> By David B. Root Jr.</i><p>
Investing is a full-time job. Given the vast amount of information available for review and the complexity of the task, a part-time effort by an individual investor has little chance of achieving long-term success. That is why individuals who cannot devote substantial time to their own investment activities should seek the full-time commitment of a professional advisor.<P>
However, just as not all doctors are skillful surgeons and not all politicians are brilliant orators, not all professional money managers are financial wizards. If you're looking for a good investment advisor, a lot of people will be glad to recommend one. But it may turn out that all they really know about him is that he's a nice guy -- and has a 6 handicap at golf. In the past, investment managers of multi-million dollar pension funds were all too often selected in the same way. Corporations that carefully reviewed the performance of their executives frequently made little effort to review the performance of the people managing their retirement funds.<P>
How does one go about selecting an advisor? The challenge is understanding precisely what they do, evaluating the validity of their approaches (do they make sense?) and assessing their integrity (do they do what they promised, and is it in your best interest?).<P>
There is no better place to begin one's investigation than with personal ethics. Do the advisors eat home cooking? That is, do they manage their own money in parallel with their clients? I can think of no more important test of an advisor's integrity and the likelihood of success than his or her own confidence in the approach pursued on behalf of clients. It is interesting to note that few bond fund managers or brokers invest their own money in derivatives. In other words, they eat out.<P>
The decision to employ an investment professional should be made only after a thorough analysis of the past performance of the individual or organization under consideration. Some questions are obvious: How long a track record is there? Was it achieved over one or more market cycles? Was it achieved by the same person who will manage your money, and does it represent the complete results achieved during some favorable period? Did this manager invest conservatively in down markets, or did clients lose money? Were the results fairly steady over time, or were they volatile? Is this manager still following the same strategy employed to achieve his or her past success?<P>
Once you've satisfied yourself that the track record is above average -- that it has been consistently better than the market indices -- there are two more questions to ask: What were the factors that went into that record? And what is the probability that those same factors will continue to work?<P>
For individuals who cannot devote substantial time to their own investment activities or do not have the minimums necessary to hire their own money managers (keep in mind that many will work with as little as $100,000), mutual funds offer a viable alternative. Mutual funds are, in theory, an attractive alternative combining professional management, low transaction costs, immediate liquidity and reasonable diversification. In practice, however, they mostly do a mediocre job of managing money. According to Lipper Analytical Services, a leading mutual fund rating service, only 17% of the 426 equity mutual funds in existence over the 10 years ending Dec. 31, 1993, were able to outpace the Standard & Poor's 500 Composite Index.<P>
A good mutual fund organization, however, has a built-in advantage: It concentrates its entire effort on a limited number of portfolios which are subject to constant public scrutiny. No mutual fund manager can afford not to devote full attention to them. Portfolios can't get lost in the shuffle or be given simply routine attention. Nor can they be delegated to a trust officer or account executive whose greatest strength is in client relations rather than portfolio management.<P>
Unfortunately, many investors choose their mutual funds the same way they pick horses at the track: They see who has performed well lately and bet on them. It is helpful to recognize that there are cycles of investment fashion; different approaches go into and out of favor, coincident with recent fluctuations in the results obtained by practitioners. If a manager with a good long-term record has a poor recent one, he or she may be specializing in an area that is temporarily out of favor. If so, the returns achieved could regress to their long-term mean as their cycle matures; several poor years could be followed by several strong ones. Obviously, it makes sense to limit your selection of an investment manager to those who are able to demonstrate that they've done consistently better than the averages.<P>
Finally, one of the most important matters for an investor to consider is personal compatibility with an advisor. If rapport is lacking, the relationship will not last. Similarly, if the investor is not comfortable with the investment approach, the choice of managers is a poor one. A conservative investor may not feel comfortable with a professional short-seller, no matter how favorable the results; by contrast, an aggres-sive investor may not be compatible with an advisor who buys securities and holds them.<P>
Once an advisor has been hired, the client must monitor his or her behavior and results on an ongoing basis. Remember, the questions involved in selecting a manager are just as applicable once you've hired one.<P>

<i>David B. Root Jr. is a CFP and president of D.B. Root & Co. Inc. in Pittsburgh. </i>
