"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0796.Feature.2.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0796.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>Managing Managed Care<BR>
</B></FONT SIZE><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I> <BR>
</CENTER>
<P><HR><BR>
Lots of people entering managed care for the first time wonder how their
healthcare will change - but the truth is, if you learn the rules, the quality
of care you get doesn't have to change drastically.<BR>
<BR>
What's most likely to change is the system through which your care is delivered.
Consumers in this new paradigm should take a more active part in managing
their own health - which, truth be told, they should have been doing all
along <BR>
In Part I of Executive Report's series entitled Managing Managed Care, we
examined last month the process of entering a managed care program. In Part
II this month, we look at how consumers can work the system in their own
favor and get the care they need and desire.<BR>
In managed care, the key is to partner with the primary care physician to
manage your healthcare, according to industry insiders. Consumers must learn
how to communicate with the primary care physician<BR>
&quot;Take the initiative to establish a relationship - most plans cover
an initial visit, or require only a small co-pay,&quot; says Tom Chepel
of the state's bureau of healthcare financing. &quot;If you have no contact
with them, then have a problem at 3 a.m. on Sunday and the primary care
physician knows nothing about you, it's very difficult for the  doctor.&quot;<BR>
Experts suggest that consumers chart their own healthcare: 
<UL>
  <LI> 	Keep notes, files and copies of all 	paperwork. 
  <LI>	Before going to the doctor, make a full list of symptoms and any
questions.
  <LI>	Ask for test results and go to other 	sources for information.
  <LI>	If you disagree with the doctor, ask for a second opinion. Or ask
to go 	to a specialist. 
</UL>
<BR>
Be careful, however, to read the fine print in your contract first. If you
get a test or visit a doctor who is not covered, you will probably have
to pay for it yourself. And on this you can't rely on your primary care
physician because every contract is different. Not only is the coverage
each insurer offers different, but they negotiate different benefit packages
for each insured group.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Physicians may not know all the rules either, though they should have
a reasonable knowledge of the plans,&quot; says Marvin Gaynor, a professor
at CMU's Heinz School of Public Policy.  &quot;It's all still pretty new
stuff.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
If you know what the rules are on precertification and authorization for
areas like emergency care and use of a specialist, you're less likely to
have to fight with the HMO for coverage after the fact. <BR>
If you do feel you need a  service that isn't covered, talk with your primary
care physician. Unfortunately, in this new paradigm, doctors spend a lot
of time negotiating with managed care companies for incremental coverage.
<BR>
<BR>
It's also possible for consumers to go to bat for themselves. And there
are ways to win.<BR>
&quot;Few HMOs will refuse to allow patients to seek another option if they
come armed - the bigger problem is that the consumer doesn't get enough
information,&quot; says Sean McLinden, executive director of Duquesne University's
Pittsburgh Health Research Institute. &quot;And they must be persistent.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
When Eric Nickeson left Allegheny General Hospital for Ohio Valley Health
Services and Education two years ago, the family changed managed care plans
- and had to change doctors. That can be hard at the best of times  - but
when there's a kid with a mysterious illness involved (Nickesons' daughter
has an unusual kidney condition), it can border on traumatic. The only pediatric
nephrologists available to monitor his daughter Hannah's illness were at
Children's Hospital, and appointments were a 17-week wait. The Nickesons
weren't satisfied with the wait, or the physicians. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;They were used to seeing very sick kids, and Hannah continued to grow
and develop normally,&quot; says Eric's wife, Ellie Nickeson. &quot;So they
just weren't very interested in her. It seemed to us that there was a power
struggle in the group - every time she went, a different doctor saw her,
and recommended something different.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Nickesons began to look for other specialists and were referred to a
well-respected pediatric nephrologist named Ben Broohard, affiliated with
the Cleveland Clinic. Despite the fact that the Nickesons' new plan advertised
affiliation with the Cleveland Clinic, the Nickesons' discontent with the
practitioners here wasn't enough for the plan to justify coverage. They
 had to get a doctor's letter saying that the care should be changed; even
then, Hannah was allowed just one con-   sultation. <BR>
Compounding the matter, Hannah needed a bone density scan to see if her
condition was affecting her bones; the highly technical test was not included
in their coverage.  One specialized instrument necessary to do the test
existed in Pittsburgh, and it was only licensed for research. But  the Nickesons
worked the system, and Hannah eventually got the scan, which showed no problems.<BR>
The Nickesons - because they are both employed in the healthcare industry
- did have a network of professionals to turn to. But there is more and
more information available to consumers without that inside track. One is
the library or bookstore: A plethora of consumer health magazines have cropped
up, as well as books on individual conditions. Another is the phonebook:
Agencies exist for many diseases, like diabetes, heart disease and cancer,
and these organizations can lead to many resources. Local and state medical
associations can also be sources. <BR>
<BR>
Information is increasingly being made available in new ways, too. Time
Life recently formed Time Life Medical, which puts out a series of videos
on the top 30 conditions afflicting the American public. They are done in
collaboration with such experts as former surgeon general C. Everett Koop,
and the company says they will be continually updated. Booklets in the packet
have other resources for help, too. Available at drugstores, the videos
cost about $20 each.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Managed care has decreased the time physicians spend with patients,&quot;
says Koop, who was in Pittsburgh in May. &quot;But when people are shocked
in the doctor's office by news they didn't expect, it's not the time for
patient education. If you say, 'That lump is cancerous,' they don't hear
much else. We urge patients to be informed about their problems, so they
can take charge of their health, which is taking charge of their life.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Corporate Connection<BR>
</B><BR>
According to a recent study done by benefits consulting firm Hewitt Associates,
88 percent of over 1,000 major U.S. employers surveyed have introduced some
kind of health management program  - to either promote health, prevent unnecessary
risk or intervene in the early stages of disease. The reason? Good health,
though it's not been statistically proven, results in lower healthcare costs
impacting the bottom line.<BR>
<BR>
The programs they implement range from education and training to health
risk assessments to financial incentives or disincentives (like a penalty
for smokers). Some even give physicals and flu shots, or will subsidize
a fitness program. (See this month's Healthbeat, page 62.)<BR>
<BR>
The Internet also has a wealth of healthcare information on-line, if you
can find it. At West Penn Hospital, for instance, Dr. Robert Selker found
he was getting queries from patients who pulled information off the Internet
about his clinical trials for the treatment of brain cancer. One patient
from Cleveland came to Selker because of information she found on-line.<BR>
<BR>
Selker now exchanges electronic mail with other cancer specialists in London
and Washington, D.C., and discusses treatments via e-mail with patients
as far away as Germany.<BR>
&quot;This is a tremendous tool of empowerment to patients,&quot; Selker
says.<BR>
<BR>
The problem is, as with anything on the Internet, that its value is dependent
on the veracity of the source; anyone can set up info on the Internet. However,
federal agencies, research hospitals, universities and nonprofit groups
do provide good information via this channel.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Recourse<BR>
</B><BR>
Even the best educated consumers may at some time get caught in the managed
care system, but fortunately, there are a number of ways to appeal. Pennsylvania
requires that managed care plans have an approved consumer grievance system
and report these grievances once a year to the state.<BR>
At the most basic level, if your grievance is a general complaint about
a process or doctor, you can call the member service hotline, which will
be listed in the member guide. Most plans also conduct periodic member surveys,
which, during this period of percolating competition, they do look at. <BR>
Managed care is a system that benefits from volume, so they're concerned
with member satisfaction and retention rates and the efficiency of their
systems, because they want to keep members in the plan.<BR>
<BR>
If you have a specific grievance, the managed care company is required to
have a two-step internal grievance process which you can appeal to; if you
are still unsatisfied, the state will consider your case. As a first step,
the plan usually will internally review your case, using an administrative
appeals committee. They will inform you of their decision and your right
to further appeal if they do not decide in your favor.<BR>
<BR>
The next step is an appeal before an appeals committee that consists of
not only plan administrators and board members, but plan members, participating
employers and providers. Parties involved in the grievance can be present.
If that appeal, too, is overturned, the member then has the right to appeal
to the state. <BR>
<BR>
In 1994, there were 1,379 first level grievances among members of Pittsburgh
area HMOs. Of those, 296 grievances were heard at the second level by the
HMO; just 29 were appealed to the state. According to the state, consumers
will continue to appeal if they are not satisfied, so the state assumes
that those who did not appeal further got what they wanted or realized their
case was without merit. Figures for 1995 are not yet complete, but the state
heard 49 appeals from this area. Emergency care coverage was the most frequently
grieved issue.<BR>
<BR>
The bureau of healthcare financing also receives complaint calls: It got
700 in 1995 statewide. The bulk of those have to do with decisions to pay
claims, consider courses of treatment that members desire, approval of referrals
to noncontracted providers and expedition of special review cases. Robert
Achenbach, deputy secretary for quality assurance and health planning in
the Pennsylvania department of insurance's bureau of healthcare financing,
contends that the fact that so few of these ever come to the state's attention
formally is a credit to the HMOs.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The HMOs are bending over backwards to satisfy even borderline cases,&quot;
says Achenbach.<BR>
The moral? If you've got a case, make it known. If you don't like the result,
you can always vote with your feet. You have the right to another doctor,
and, when your re-enrollment period comes around, another provider.<BR>
<BR>
Taking these steps does mean more work for the healthcare consumer. But
in the end, it hopefully will mean better healthcare in the aggregate, as
we move from a fragmented system to one that, with our participation, coordinates
care. The processes are not all smooth yet; but most agree that Pittsburgh
has a good provider community, working primarily in the interest of the
healthcare consumer.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's clear that HMOs cannot be characterized as being wracked by fraud
and abuse,&quot; says CMU's Gaynor. &quot;But on the other hand, it's very
competitive, and there is a lot of pressure on the cost side to keep utilization
and cost down. You do hear about cases, like where the man collapsed at
home, and his wife called the HMO about getting an ambulance - by the time
the ambulance got there, he had died. That's a process problem, but it's
obviously not completely separate if the intent is to control utilization.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The bottom line is profit - if the HMOs can't sustain a profit, they
go out of business. But they can't do that if you provide poor quality care.
That's clearly not good for business.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Gaynor and others put the impetus on employers to drive for quality healthcare.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Most of the concern at present is that the buyers of HMO insurance
are employers. They are concerned with the costs, and HMOs are responding.
But that's beginning to change because people are beginning to realize that
sometimes there is too little quality, and maybe, sometimes, you have to
sacrifice for quality.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
