<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0596.Feature.1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><IMG BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"></a><a href="../zine/0596.Supplement1.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
 
</center><p>
<p>
<center><b><FONT SIZE=+2></B>
</FONT><br>
<FONT SIZE=+>What We Needed Was a <br>Little Stability
</FONT SIZE><br>
<i>By Jim Urban</i>
</CENTER>
<hr>


<P>Executive Report: Why buy a financially troubled team in a market that is losing population?<P>Kevin McClatchy: There are a couple things.  I thought there was a very dedicated base of fans.  Having looked at the Oakland A's and very, briefly, the San Francisco Giants, I felt there were better fans out here.  That's important.<P>Also, there was more of an opportunity, eventually, to get a new stadium in Pittsburgh as opposed to other markets.  Given those two factors, I thought it would be a great opportunity for a turnaround situation.  After our first meeting with the mayor and city, wefelt we could negotiate some form of lease concession package to help us bridge that gap.<P>ER: And you bridged that gap soon after taking control of the team. Please explain what you've done with the budget and where you are now.<P>KM: There are some things -- some we've done, some were luck -- that help us financially.  One was negotiating the lease concession package with the city, which will save us -- minimum in hard costs -- $8 million annually.  That number can go up if our attendance increases.
<P>The new Fox/NBC national television contract has brought us close to  $4 million more annually than we projected in our numbers. So before we threw the first pitch, we were $12 million a year better than when we first took this thing over. <P>Also, last year we drew less than      1 million fans; our goal this year is      1.4 million. Some people think that is aggressive. In reality, it's not when you look at the Pirates' historicals. The fans are there. You just have to get them to the park. I think by putting a better team on the field, we will be able to hit our projected attendance figures. That will bridge that gap even more.<P>There's one other thing, revenue sharing, that is very important to what we are doing here in Pittsburgh.With preliminary approval already, there's reason to be optimistic about it.<P>ER: You mentioned fielding a better team. Can the small-market teams - such as the Pirates - do that? <P>KM:  There were a couple problems when we took over: One, that the fans don't know who the players are; and two, the perception that the Pirates don't keep their players. That's not a complaint unique to Pittsburgh. It's a complaint that has been common throughout baseball, and now sports.<P>We have signed some of our better core players to more than just one-year deals. We'd like to create some stability with the fans and the people they are trying to identify with. We've done quite a bit, to be honest, and it has worked out well. Jeff King is in for two years. We have an option on a second year for Charlie Hayes. Jay Bell and Carlos Garcia are both here for the next two years. Al Martin and Orlando Merced are here for the next two years. <P>We've negotiated a lot of contracts - almost every starter is locked up for another two years. I think people can get used to these players because some of them are pretty good. Garcia was in the all-star game in 1994, Bell has been in the all-star game, and I think Merced and King are very good players. Denny Neagle, who was in the all-star game last year, is a pretty good pitcher. What we needed was some stability, which has not been present among the Pirates the last couple years.<P>Our farm system is in good shape. Sporting News ranked it seventh, behind the Dodgers, Cleveland, the Yankees, Mets ... some very good organizations. We are going to be as committed or more committed to our minor league system. When you are a small market team, you have to be. You develop your players. The key is getting your revenues to a point where you can sign some of those players to long-term contracts. We will continue to put more money into the minor leagues and hopefully grow revenue to the point where we can sign some of the better players instead of being a farm system for the rest of the league. That's one of the real challenges.<P>ER: What do you say to those - and there are many - who think Three Rivers Stadium is just fine?<P>KM: There are a lot of different reasons for a new park. One, it's important for the franchise to remain competitive long-term. People are going away from what they call the cookie-cutter stadiums of the '70s. Baseball is obviously a much different sport than football, where you have 10 home dates a year and the fans tailgate. With baseball, you have 81 home dates a year, which is a lot. People would like to be comfortable when they go out to the stadium. If you look at Cleveland or Camden Yards in Baltimore, you are right on top of the action, it's a comfortable place to watch a game. And the stadiums are downtown where there are other things going on. There are restaurants, bars, hotels, or people go straight from their office to the game.<P>Because of the comfort, they tend to draw a lot of people, which gives them the ability to be more competitive financially with other franchises.<P>Three Rivers Stadium, I think, is not the worst place in the world, but it is not a good baseball park. It is a good place to watch football, and there are some good seats for baseball, but only about 20,000. <P>When we went to get the lease concessions, that was because we had the worst lease in all of baseball. We are a small market team and we had the worst lease in baseball, so it was tough to be competitive. At least now, we are toward the middle of the pack in terms of the lease. Three Rivers did not give us the ability via concessions, via parking, via luxury boxes, to get some of the revenues that most clubs get that make them competitive.<P>ER: You favor a location in downtown or very close. Why?<P>KM: That is another aspect to a new baseball stadium. In Colorado [Coors Field], the area where they put that stadium was kind of run down, and it has been a tremendous boost to the merchants downtown. The same at Jacobs Field in Cleveland and Camden Yards in Baltimore. When you are bringing 35,000 or 40,000 people downtown, and they are spending their money downtown, it helps.<P>Having lived in a hotel room in downtown Pittsburgh for five months as we worked on this deal, I can tell you that downtown Pittsburgh could use a shot in the arm. And I don't mean this as a negative comment. When you get a new facility, you all of a sudden see more restaurants, more activity. That's what baseball is at these new facilities. They are not just games, they are events, and they add a lot to the city.<P>One other aspect: I think if you are a mid-level CEO looking to locate your business to another city and you go to a Cleveland or a Baltimore during the summer, maybe go to a game and there are 40,000 people downtown, a lot of restaurants and bars - this is a quality of life issue that someone looking to relocate a business will consider. I don't think when they go to Three Rivers they will experience that.<P>As far as location is concerned, we  as a team have not really looked at all the different components, at parking, accessibility. I think it should be downtown or very close to downtown.<P>People in Cleveland walk a fair amount. Their offices are maybe not right near the park, but walking 10 or 15 minutes is not a bad thing. You have to make it accessible for walking. <P>I am convinced Pittsburgh needs a new facility and I've stated that since I got here. It's not something I came out with after closing the sale.<P>As far as timing, we need to explore sites and pick one within two years. Other cities have picked sites more quickly, but there's nothing wrong here with taking some time and doing it right. After we pick the site, you are looking at two to three years to build it, so we are probably five years out before we have a new stadium.<P>ER: How do you pay for the stadium without passing most of it on to the residents of the region?<P>KM:  We are going to ask the city to play some role in it, to come up with some piece of the financing. There are different avenues, such as a hotel tax or some other things, that don't actually hit the people who live in the city. On the county side, we want all the counties to be players. The Pirates are a regional team and these outlying counties have plenty of Pirates fans in them. <P>The current county commissioners in Allegheny County have their program and want to stick with it. We will sit down with them and show them how this has been done in other markets. For example, in Phoenix, they have an airport tax. Every time you fly into the Phoenix airport, you help pay for their stadium. There is no reason why we can't do something similar in Pittsburgh.<P>The final piece of this is the state, and we've had some good conversations with Gov. Ridge. He understands the importance of a new facility to western Pennsylvania. What we are talking about is a public-private partnership, the city, county, state and us. <P>ER: Once the deal was done, you jumped into a marketing and advertising campaign. What did you learn from looking at the Pirates' recent history and how did that influence what you are doing now?<P>KM: It's tough because the Pirates have gone in waves. They didn't need to market when they had Barry Bonds, Andy Van Slyke, Bob Bonilla and Doug Drabek. They could put the players out there and get away without marketing. I think they could have possibly done a better job marketing some of those players when they were here. Once those players were gone and the team was stripped, then came the strike. I don't know if there was much the team could have done. Spending $2 million advertising probably would not have made a difference.<P>We feel now we have to take a very proactive stance with marketing. We'd like to market our players, let the public know who our players are. With our television campaign, with some of the key players in these commercials, people get to see their personality.<P>Another thing is to get out as much as we can and listen to what the fans are telling us. We recently took an ad out in newspapers that was a fan survey. We got 1,000 responses, which means 1,000 people took time to clip it out, write on it and send it back to us. There were a lot of good ideas, it gave people the chance to tell us their feelings about the Pirates. We are getting out to talk to as many groups as possible. You call it grass roots marketing. <P>One thing that is sometimes missing in sports is a link between the ownership and the fans. If you pull yourself away from all the glamour of sports, it still is a business. And there is nothing wrong with the person who runs a business, whether it be a corner deli or Major League Baseball team, getting out and talking to customers. I've done that, and I think there has been a positive reaction. It's a different type of marketing. It has bridged the gap and created renewed interest in the Pirates.<P>ER: How soon can you expect to turn the team around financially? <P>KM:  As far as ticket sales, [in early March] we were up 80,000 to 100,000 in ticket sales, which was pretty good. We hadn't even started our advertising campaign. We had just taken over the team. This was done without our media program.<P>I think if I do my job  - I'm making a commitment to the fans, and I need them to make a commitment to me, and I think if we both do our jobs, we can make this thing work. <P>This is a team that has been knocked around the last few years. If this franchise received the lease concessions we received six or seven years ago, you would not have the debt you have now. I don't think this franchise has been going in its best direction. What I want to do is give this thing a real shot, and I don't necessarily think that's been done.<P>I think we'll lose money this season, but I think we can turn around and break even in two years.<P>ER: What kind of CEO will you be?<P>KM:  I am going to be very hands-on, probably much more hands-on than people are used to with the Pittsburgh Pirates. The previous ownership did not have an office at the stadium, which I already have. I think it's important. I think the people of Pittsburgh appreciate knowing who the owner is. That's one of the reasons I get out and meet people. It's a lot of work, but a lot of fun.<P>ER: Has your age of 33 years helped or hurt you in this process?<P>KM: When we first got into this, we weren't the only ones. I think some people looked at me and said 'That guy, we don't need to worry about him.' I think some people discounted our ability to do this deal.<P>Overall, the age thing was a plus. It helped slightly in the negotiation process in competing with other people, but I think it was somewhat of a negative in that people would ask for or try to get away with more than they should have.<P>The age thing helps in other ways. I haven't been the CEO of a Fortune 500 company. If I had been, maybe I wouldn't want to go to a mall and be with fans. So it's helped that way. I think it also has helped attract younger fans, generate some excitement. Even people in college think, 'This guy is not much older than me.' The older fans think my age is refreshing. They think I look like their son-in-law. The fans are a key to what we are trying to accomplish.<P>ER: How much of your investment is your own money?<P>KM: All the money that's on my side is my own money. I have one other investor that's a family member, Brown Maloney, a cousin. He came in as a limited partner. But all the money that's in there, none of it's from our company, none of it's from my family, it's all my money. There's no big Fortune 500 company backing me on this one.<P>ER: What do you think you have to learn in this business?<P>KM: My educational curve will probably come with the politics of baseball as far as the workings of the Major League folks. The game itself, I know very well. But I know enough  to let Cam [Bonifay] and Jim [Leyland] make decisions. They'll come to me with recommendations and I'll try and support them most of the time.<P>I think I surprised a lot of people when I talk to them about certain players, because they think, 'Wow this guy really knows his stuff.' But I know if you're close enough to sports you know what you do know and you don't know. I know people's batting averages, how they played and where they've played, but the guys that are really involved in baseball, they really know so much more than sports fans. And you've got to let the baseball people do their thing. <P>What I hope to bring to the  party is marketing, those kinds of things. The combination of the two should make a good team. The Pirates organization has some good people, but they've had their challenges. It's been tough working in this environment where they're constantly taking your budgets down, then the strike. People's hands have been tied, so we're going to have some fun with it, let people run with it.<P>We're going to evaluate everything. We took over with a month to opening day. Now is not a good time to make changes. I don't believe in change just to make change. You make mistakes.<P>ER: When will you be able to go after the better free agents?<P>KM: I think, especially with revenue sharing, we'll be more competitive to bid on some of those folks next year. It's important to understand that spending does not necessarily equate to winning in baseball. The Baltimore Orioles spent close to $50 million last year and had a losing record. The Yankees made the playoffs last year but prior to that it was 1981 since they had made the playoffs, and they outspent a lot of people. I think you can grow your minor league system, and then have enough money to sign some of those players and keep them in your system. A team that I grew up not liking very much but I had to give them hats off, is the Dodgers. They've done a good job growing talent and then keeping it. Cleveland: If you ever want to draw a parallel to what I think Pittsburgh can do, just go two hours down the road. They built a new stadium, and as their revenues grew they signed more players to longer term contracts. It was a relationship that went hand in hand. I think we can do that here. We've already started to sign some of our players to longer contracts. We're going to continue to grow our minor league farm system, and as attendance grows and revenue grows, we're going to be more competitive.<P>The year before any of these teams moved into new ballparks you'd see a million jump in attendance because the fans wanted to get the first right of refusal in the new ballpark. A million jump, that's dramatic to your bottom line and gives you the ability to go out and sign free agents at a pretty decent pace. But we are a small market, and we need to spend wisely.<P>ER: What about personal seat licenses?<P>KM: You could possibly do it on a limited basis here, but not full scale.<P>ER: Do you like Pittsburgh?<P>KM: It's just unbelievable how nice people have been wherever I go. They're genuinely warm people. I think it has some challenges. You need to get some younger folks, mid-level corporations. Right now, I'm trying to stay focused on what's immediately ahead of us, but down the road I will get involved.<P>





