<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<center>

<a href="../HomePage.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"></a><a href="../zine/Archives.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"></a><a href="../search/wais.cgi"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" alt="search"></a><a href="../brochure/Help.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="../zine/0196.Contents.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" alt="Contents"></a>
<BR>
<a href="../zine/0196.Chronicles.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" alt="Previous"></a><img border=0 src="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"><a href="../zine/0196.People.html"><img border=0 src="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" alt="Next"></a>
</center>

<P>

<P align=center><B><font size=+2>The Bigger Picture</b> 
</font><br>
<font size=+1>Pennsylvania is Trying to Be Business Friendly,<br>But Many Businesses Still Say They Would Leave                 

</font><BR>
<i>By Jim Strader
</i>

<HR>
In the rough-and-tumble of Harrisburg politics, you have to know the players to stay in the game. The state's business community has a team on the field in the Pennsylvania Chamber of Business and Industry, but it's a team that's staring at some daunting numbers.<P>The chamber keeps track of the active issues in the statehouse and works to advance the interests of industry. Lobbyists push the business agenda in Capitol corridors, through the mail, with analyses of specific pending legislation and by briefing chamber members to help them make their own case to local lawmakers.<P>The chamber is lauding some of the business friendly measures included in Gov. Ridge's first budget, but sees a bigger problem needing the attention of state government. Fred Sembach, the chamber's top lobbyist, cites a recurring question asked of business in an annual survey: "If you could leave Pennsylvania, would you?"<P>In 1993, the question drew an affirmative answer - companies would leave the state if able - from 58 percent of those who responded. In 1994, the percentage peaked slightly, to 58.7 percent. In the April 1995 survey, taken a couple of months after the Ridge administration began its work, the number of those who said they would leave had dropped to 43 percent.<P>"That's a step in the right direction, but 43 percent is still too high," Sembach says.<P>Reasons companies want to leave center on the business climate -  how they are treated when a problem needs government attention -business taxes, workers' compensation and healthcare matters.<P>The chamber sees the response to this one question as a key indication that the business community continues to have problems in Pennsylvania. Addressing it dominates the work of Sembach and other chamber lobbyists, who represent 4,600 members from across the state - almost half of the private sector work force. Though membership takes in all of the state's Fortune 500 businesses, 80 percent of member companies have fewer than 100 employees.<P>The chamber develops positions through direct contact with companies. The organization also counts on a nonscientific monthly survey to generate feedback, Sembach says. The annual scientific survey that generated the 43 percent figure also goes into the mix.<P>Despite Sembach's concern, he concedes that the chamber's work has seen big change owing to the Republican control of the General Assembly and the governor's office. Despite the good working relationship the chamber has had with the statehouse in the past year, Sembach was reluctant to attribute too much to   partisanship. <P>"We don't look at party. We look at those who are ready, willing and able to work with us," he says. "The key thing in '95 has been a better appreciation and more of an inclination to solve business's problems."<P>In the past eight years, with the Democratic administration of Gov. Robert P. Casey in power, the chamber found itself facing an agenda from state government that was "essentially aimed at making business pick up various costs," Sembach says. "We were finding a lot of mandates, things business would be expected to do. Now we're looking at solving the problems of business, not creating new ones.<P>"We've seen a markedly different attitude," he adds. "Many of the things that have been accomplished in '95 have been done on a bipartisan basis."<P>The chamber and the business community at large are heralding reductions in business taxes of more than $220 million, as well as reform in regulatory and workplace issues. The tax cuts were seen by chamber members as a good opening measure in what they hope will be a continued lowering of business taxes. Regulatory relief centers on the former Department of Environmental Re-sources, which saw its focus narrow to regulatory matters as its parks and forests bureaus were spun off to a new agency. In addition, new laws were passed to provide incentives for the cleanup and reuse of abandoned and polluted industrial sites. <P>In the workplace, Sembach says, a new law defining hearing loss was a step in the right direction toward continued reform of workers' compensation, which is leading the list of chamber priorities in the coming year.<P>If workers' compensation reform goes through without being ravaged by special interests, it's likely that 43 percent disapproval figure will drop some more by next year.<P>
<P>





<hr>

