     <TD><A HREF="239/index.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="239/_cover.jpg" WIDTH=100></TD>
     <TD><A HREF="239/index.htm"><FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><B>Issue 239</B></FONT></A><BR>September 1996</TD></TD>
     <TD><A HREF="240/index.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="240/_cover.jpg" WIDTH=100></TD>
     <TD><A HREF="240/index.htm"><FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><B>Issue 240</B></FONT></A><BR>November 1996</TD></TD>
     <TD><A HREF="241/index.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="241/_cover.jpg" WIDTH=100></TD>
     <TD><A HREF="241/index.htm"><FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica"><B>Issue 241</B></FONT></A><BR>December 1996</TD></TD>
    </TR>
   </TABLE>
  </CENTER>
  <P>As well as the magazine itself, <IMG SRC="name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> produces a song book, full of stirring, humorous and ironic songs that are sung at their regular Glee Clubs. The Glee Club was once described as 'the best political sing-song around', and you can find out why by looking at the songs by clicking below.</P>
  <P><IMG SRC="bullet.gif" HSPACE=5><A HREF="songs/index.htm">Read the Song Book</A></P>
