<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 233 Commentary</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 233 Commentary</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Down In The Gutter</H2>
    </CENTER>
    <P><STRONG>Just when one thought that the Tories could stoop no lower, along comes their assault on refugees, possibly the most defenceless group of people over whom they have control.</STRONG></P>
    <P>At the time of writing, regulations were due in force in early January which will turn up to 10,000 destitute people onto the streets for no reason other to win Peter Lilley a cheap round of applause from the baying racist end of his party's conference. Under his proposals, asylum seekers who have had their applications to remain rejected will have no entitlement to benefits while they pursue their legal right to appeal.</P>
    <P>And those who apply for asylum after arrival in the UK, perhaps students or visitors stranded here after some political upheaval in their own country, will get no benefits at all.</P>
    <P>What this means in human terms is that people facing persecution at home will be left penniless in the UK, dependent on the goodwill and resources of charities which themselves cannot absorb this burden on top of their normal work.</P>
    <P>Though the numbers involved are enough to overwhelm charities, they are tiny as a proportion of the UK population. The money saved by refusing them housing and other benefits is trivial as a proportion of government spending.</P>
    <P>Even with this government the motive for this callousness cannot be wholly financial.</P>
    <P>And sure enough, it is not. The Tories now scarcely bother to hide their belief that being 'tough on blacks' is a vote-winner, and that the spectacle of men, women and children with the wrong colour skins being deported to 'safe' countries like Nigeria will help them win back the allegiance of disillusioned Thatcherites.</P>
    <P>If asylum seekers end up forced to beg and sleep in the streets, Tory campaign strategists will be delighted to play the law and order card in depicting them as a problem to be dealt with by more repression.</P>
    <P>If a few of these unfortunates end up being jailed, tortured or killed as a result of deportation, it will not worry the Tories either, particularly as it is quite likely to emerge that the UK has a thriving arms trade with the regime concerned.</P>
    <P>The proposed requirement to oblige employers to check up on illegal immigrants has succeeded in outraging even the CBI, normally a friend of the government, for imposing on employers an aspect of law enforcement they cannot reasonably take on. It is likely to tip the balance further against ethnic minority job applicants, even those born in the UK.</P>
    <P>But the Tories have a further motive beyond striking postures against ethnic minorities in particular, and foreigners in general, to impress their more neanderthal supporters. They want to force Labour either to annoy many  of its supporters by acquiescing in these measures, or allow itself to be portrayed as 'soft on blacks' by opposing them.</P>
    <P>True to form, the Blairite Labour party has so far squirmed and evaded, no doubt secretly hoping that the Tories do enact these measures, so saving a future Labour government the aggravation of having to do so itself.</P>
    <P>The UK has had a proud record of giving refuge to victims of persecution including, ironically, the parents of the home secretary Michael Howard, whose record on the asylum issue is worse even than Lilley's.</P>
    <P>The only major party now prepared to defend that record is the Liberal Democrats. This follows a tradition which encompasses the old Liberal Party's stand in 1972 as the only major party willing to welcome expelled Ugandan Asians to the UK.</P>
    <P>There will no doubt be some floating voters who desert the Liberal Democrats because of this. But the party's stand, while principled, is not without its positive electoral consequences too.</P>
    <P>The issue of asylum seekers' rights is symptomatic of the way the political scene has changed in the past year. With every attempt to put 'clear blue water' between themselves and Labour on social issues, the Tories simply find Labour moving closer to them.</P>
    <P>It is clear now that Labour's strategy is based on the premise that traditional Labour voters will vote Labour because they have nowhere else to go, and can consequently be taken for granted as the party moves to the right in the fond hope that it will add floating voters to its original base. This in turn forces the Tories to follow the logic of their strategy into yet further right-wing extremism.</P>
    <P>There is no middle ground here that the Liberal Democrats should inhabit even if they could. But there is a chasm opening up in the areas vacated by Labour into which the Liberal Democrats might move, and their willingness to oppose tax cuts is a sign that they have grasped this.</P>
    <P>But what Labour is now abandoning as fast as possible is not 'the left', in the sense of old Labour statism. That is probably dead beyond recall. It is the things which at times gave a tinge of liberal decency to old Labour, whatever its other faults. And the Liberal Democrats can take advantage of this only by being consistent and unafraid about drawing on their Liberal heritage.</P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
