<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 233</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 233</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Food For Thought At Hornbeam</H2>
    </CENTER>
    <P><B><I>One former Young Liberal's attempts to think globally and act locally is attracting a number of awards. Liz Wood tells the story so far.</I></B></P>
    <HR WIDTH=50%>
    <P><B>If you live in the town, where can you go to enjoy a decent meal</B> and find out about environmental issues at the same time? The answer is Gannets, the award winning cafe at Hornbeam Environmental Centre in Hoe Street, Walthamstow. Gannets is a vegetarian and whole food cafe which was the brain child of former Young Liberal, Joanna Lewis and her friend, Diane Sizer. It has been running for just over a year, and during that time has established a reputation for delicious vegetarian food and the centre has won several awards. In October, on the day that the alcohol licence was obtained, Hornbeam won the Big Issue Award for the Environment out of over 4,000 nominations; just before its first anniversary this month, the centre won an award from the BURA Charitable Trust for 'Best Practice in the Community'; and it has been strongly recommended by several newspapers.
    <P>Joanna Lewis was born in the Essex countryside, but when, after graduation she found herself joining the throng of London's jobless, she determined to do something about it. After a number of jobs she found herself in a vegetarian cafe in Walthamstow. This was an ideal meeting ground for many members of the local environmental forum. When the cafe closed Joanna became more determined than ever to do something positive to help the environment rather than simply being a vegetarian and using recycled loo paper. She felt that the people of Waltham Forest needed a centre where they could meet over a cup of tea, receive information and discuss environmental matters; more than that a centre which would become the disseminator of such information and the instigator of action, a place where informed advice could be sought and found. Moreover, it would provide jobs for some of the unemployed. In order to become self financing, the environmental centre would need some means of generating income. Diane, a young chef, also a member of Waltham Forest's Environmental forum and also now jobless, had often dreamed of running her own cafe. They decided to work together to create Hornbeam Environmental Forum and Gannet's Cafe.
    <P>One of the first steps was to approach the local council to see if they would be interested in the project. The present Tory government, in spite of its splutters about pollution, has not been renowned for its support of environmental projects. However, John Major did send representatives to the Rio Earth summit in 1992. Among other things Agenda 21 of the Summit meeting required local authorities to draw up an agenda to develop strategies for local sustainable development, ways in which they would meet people's needs and improve the quality of their lives without damaging the environment. The conference summary stressed the need for everybody in a local community to help determine the sort of environment they should have, and to work together to achieve it. The aim of Hombeam was to provide a focus for exactly this kind of activity, so through supporting projects like Hornbeam, the council could partially fulfil their obligations under Agenda 21.
    <P>Next, having enlisted the interest of Waltham Forest Council they looked for a suitable building. Now one such already existed in Hoe Street near the Baker's Arms, part of it being in use as a community recycling project. The building, which belonged to Waltham Forest Council, was in a very dilapidated state and would need gutting and refurbishing throughout. As neither Joanna nor Diane had any money they drew up a business plan and began trawling various organisations with a view to raising the necessary capital. A committee was set up to manage the centre and, when they were finally ready, local volunteers were recruited, including many jobless. All the building work was done by volunteers, over 100 of them, aged from 4 - 74, able bodied and disabled, skilled and unskilled; only the roof which needed re-slating was left to professionals. On one occasion a painter passed down the street and berated the girl who was painting the front, saying, 'It's people like you who put me out of work.' This was, of course, untrue, for there was no money available to pay the workers.
    <P>The conversion was carried out as far as possible according to green principals: no hardwoods of any kind; Warmcel Insulation, which is made from recycled newspaper and is pleasant to handle, was used in the loft; and Auro, an organic paint was used. Wherever they could, materials were carefully stripped out and used again; they scoured the district searching for second hand and discarded items which could be reclaimed; even the nails were recycled.
    <P>The building thus demonstrates in practical terms the green ethos of its founder members, even though this process was inevitably much slower than starting with new components. Projects in the near future include the installation of a solar panel and a wind generator: these will provide electricity for Hornbeam and enable the public to see them in action at the same time.
    <P>After two years later, the centre was ready for the grand opening: actually the schedule was so tight that the volunteers were still cleaning the paint off their hands, and the china for the cafe was being unpacked and washed as the mayor and local dignitaries gathered on the pavement outside!
    <P>Hornbeam achieved its first birthday on April 23rd. It is a community led project and the success of Ganet's cafe is essential to generate income for its continuation. For this reason, efforts have been concentrated so far on the cafe but much has already been done to achieve its environmental brief. Meeting rooms are available for local pressure groups, pictures by local artists are always on display, information is disseminated through leaflets and posters, there is a small environmental library (currently awaiting awaiting relocation), talks and presentations take place, environmental workshops and play schemes are initiated. Fair trade items, which return the profits largely to the makers, are on sale and items from local crafts people also have a retail centre is still mainly run by unpaid volunteers although it is hoped eventually to employ more paid staff.
    <P>During its first year the cafe has established a reputation for fine food, showing that vegetarianism need not be a form of penitential masochism. Hornbeam has already won high acclaim and is currently one o f ten finalists for this year's BT-WWF award.
    <P>Waltham Forest has been the centre of protest for many years. It contains not only the controversial M11 trunk route, still the focus of impassioned demonstrations by local people frustrated by the government in their attempts to save their homes and trees from the road builder's bulldozers, but also the ancient woodlands of Epping Forest and the William Morris Gallery, home of that great Victorian champion of the environment. Just as William Morris campaigned to save the forest's hornbeams from the developer's axe, so his spiritual descendants at Hornbeam work today to try to restore the last vestiges of the natural environment in the area and ensure that their children's children will still have some fresh air to breath amongst the trees in the forest.
    <P><I>Hornbeam, at 458, Hoe Street Walthamstow, is a non profit making venture and depends largely for its financing on its cafe, Gannets . The cafe is open from 10-4 on Tuesdays and Wednesdays and from 10 - 10 pm on Thursdays, Fridays and Saturdays. Booking is advisable as accommodation is limited. Tel: 0181 558 6880</I></P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Liz Wood</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
      <map name="BUTTONS">
