<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN//2.0">
<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 233</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 233</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Tower Hamlets - Labour's Shame</H2>
    </CENTER>
    <P><B><I>Dan Falchikov, political adviser to the Lib Dem group reports on Labour's shambles as it destroys decentralisation.</I></B></P>
    <HR WIDTH=50%>
    <P><B>May 1994 saw Labour win a landslide in Tower Hamlets</B>, winning 43 of the 50 seats. Labour saw it as a jewel in their crown and a number of leading Liberal Democrats were, frankly, glad to see the back of the only inner-city Borough that the party controlled. Many of those Liberal Democrats continue to think that the party may be better off without Tower Hamlets, but the people of Tower Hamlets certainly aren't better off without the party. This is the story of Labour's first year back in office.</P>
    <P>One of Labour's first acts, after their election, was to give the Mayor a 28,000 a year allowance and award themselves mobile phones and extra allowances. This was obviously the only thing that they could agree on as they immediately split over a far left challenge to the Leadership. The "moderates" holding on by just 3 votes.</P>
    <P>Labour set about destroying every vestige of eight years of Liberal administration, regardless of cost or efficiency. Neighbourhoods were abolished and central directorates were created. This immediately caused a financial crisis as Labour forgot to appoint finance officers to monitor budgets! Labour set about closing anything that was local, estate offices, employment centres and one stop shops were all threatened with closure.</P>
    <P>Labour received rap over the knuckles in November 1994 when the District Auditor found that they had illegally paid special responsibility allowances to 12 Vice-Chairs. Staff morale fell as confusion reigned over restructuring, with over 300 requests for voluntary redundancy since May. Over 700,000 was paid to those taking redundancy or early retirement in the first 6 months of Labour rule. Staff sickness soared, adding 2 million to the wage bill.</P>
    <P>Towards the end of November a damning report went to committee saying that recentralisation could lead to "increased bureaucracy, reduced access a loss of morale and a reduction in front line services." Undaunted Labour pressed on. The cost of Labour's new bureaucracy was now becoming apparent. Demand for photocopying committee agendas soared from 8 million copies a year to 17 million. To cope Labour spent 200,000 on a new photocopier!</P>
    <P>In December Labour announced that they would not consult residents on their budget, unlike the Liberals who had held a referendum in the previous two years. In the new year figures were released showing that the number of empty Council properties rose as managers struggled with recentralisation. The use of bed and breakfast also rose as well as homelessness. The Liberal Democrat administration had reduced homelessness from over 1,600 families to just 600 in two years, under Labour 20 more families per quarter were counted as homeless, despite voids increasing.</P>
    <P>Also in January, Labour announces plans to reduce discretionary awards for students staying on at school. Labour announce that a further 1 million is needed for office accommodation due to restructuring. Labour reduce the number of ethnic minority Councillors on a key Committee. Liberal Democrat Leader, Janet Ludlow, challenges the decision and forces Labour to think again.</P>
    <P>Labour announce as part of the delayed budget process that Council tenants would have to pay a compulsory 10p a week levy to pay for tenants associations. Tenants representatives are up in arms calling it a new poll tax.</P>
    <P>Two major events are announced - Gay Pride will take place in Victoria Park in July and Blur will play in Mile End Park in June. Local people affected by both events were not consulted about the use of these parks. Attempts to query any arrangements by Liberal Democrat Councillors are met with calls of "homophobic".</P>
    <P>February sees the third highest rent rises in London announced. 3 million of tenants money go to purchase new office accommodation for the newly recentralised Housing Department. This works out at an average of 3.30 a week for each of the Borough's 35,000 council tenants. The budget process see Labour target cuts on the elderly, with day centres being axed, cuts to lunch clubs, telephone help service, holiday vouchers, care wardens and a range of charges being increased. Age Concern's funding is halved. On Valentines Day, schools students receive a boost when plans for cutting their grants are declared illegal.</P>
    <P>Labour now turns its fire on housing with a massive closure of local offices and one stop shops. Rent and benefit payments will in future be available at just four offices across the Borough. The amount saved by the closures is exactly the same as the amount set aside by the Housing dept to pay for redundancy as part of the restructuring. March sees budget Council when the full effects of centralisation become apparent.</P>
    <P>The cost of administration has risen by 6.3 million a year. 8.3 million of balances have been blown on restructuring. Combined with an extra 3 million in housing the grand total comes to 17.6 million.</P>
    <P>By cutting bureaucracy to 1994/95 levels Lib Dem budget proposes 2 million extra for education, 1 million extra for social services, 1.4 million to save the one stop shops and estate based offices as well as a 25 a year reduction in Council Tax.</P>
    <P>Also in March Labour decline to back Diana Maddock's all party "warmer homes bill". Tenants face increase repair charges in spite of 18% increase in rents. In April the Council's new found political correctness takes a bizarre twist. Two play groups in Bethnal Green apply for funding. A Bengali, Muslim only, play group receives 14,000, but a Christian one, which is open to all faiths is turned down for a grant of 1,700 on the grounds that it is a "religious based organisation" and it would be anti equal opportunities to fund it.</P>
    <P>Redundancy costs soar. Having all ready put aside 2 million, officers come back with a request for a further 1 million as staff leave the sinking ship that Tower Hamlets has become. Liberal leader Janet Ludlow, comments "Under the Liberal Democrats the Council paid people to deliver services. Under Labour the council pays people to do nothing and then sacks them!".</P>
    <P>Labour's splits become increasingly bizarre with a Councillor suspended for "faking" a fax accusing the leader of racism. May sees new contracts for street cleaning introduced with parts of the Borough seeing the frequency of cleaning halved. Labour's first Mayor in eight years ends his office in ignominy. He covers up his spending, amidst rumours of overspending his not insubstantial 28,000 a year budget and he fails to deliver his promise to lead a campaign against racism. Liberal Democrats call the special Council meeting he failed to do.</P>
    <P>The hard left finally win the internal battle for Labour leadership, with a new leader being elected after a series of Labour Group meetings, one of which ended in the votes being tied. The new leader continues as the old one left off by announcing that the Council is to spend thousands replacing all the street and estate signs with a new green and blue logo, that will have the partially sighted up in arms.</P>
    <P>In the summer of 1995 three separate, but similar, scandals come to light. The former chief executive of Stepney Neighbourhood has been paid to do nothing since the previous May at a cost of 95,000 to local taxpayers. The Director of Social Services is seconded to Birmingham University for two years, taking her conveniently to early retirement - cost 60,000 and a local head teacher will continued to be paid by the council for 18 months for the duration of her NUT presidency - cost 52,000.</P>
    <P>In the Autumn, desperate for more office accommodation, the council plans to spend 0.5 million bringing back into use empty offices, the Liberals had planned to sell off. The Council sets up a Complaints Hotline to deal the ever increasing number of complaints. Unfortunately it is based in Berkshire, much to the delight of the local paper's headline writers! Tower Hamlets hits the national papers when a former Labour Councillor, who happens to be the husband of the Planning Chair, has his rent arrears written off in mysterious circumstances. The officer concerned is disciplined, but the debt remains outstanding.</P>
    <P>In November of this year Labour Councillors and senior officers meet at a 4-star hotel in Essex (at a cost of 7,000) to discuss a paper by the Chief Executive. The paper is damning in its criticism of how the council is now being run. The Chief Exec claims "staff are often demotivated and frightened..     there exists a culture of blame - always blame someone else for failure..... Departmentalism is rife. There is little or no sense of working together as an organisation..       .staff are not encouraged to find solutions that might involve colleagues from other directorates...       Some of the basics of Council workings are not in place - far too much is going on at committee, creating excessive amounts of paper...."</P>
    <P>During this period Tower Hamlets Liberal Democrats have also had to find the resources to fight four by-elections. All have been lost to Labour, despite their record in running the Council. Labour have a formidable by-election machine, pulling in help from across the country and managing to get out to vote all those who supported them in May 1994. Liberal Democrats are left with the same dozen local activists and little or no outside help. The most recent by-election, Limehouse, however showed two signs of hope for the future. Firstly Labour's vote fell by about a hundred from its May 1994 high. Secondly, the BNP, who had been polling 15-20 per cent slumped to just 147, beating the Tories by less than a hundred. Tower Hamlets is clearly once again a two party fight. The Liberal Democrats having had a bad two years are now clearly set to benefit when Labour's slump comes.</P>
    <P>It's been 19 months since Labour had their Tower Hamlets landslide. What I have outlined is just some of the more bizarre/ idiotic/ incompetent/ dogmatic/ loony (delete as appropriate) decisions in those months. I hope that those party members who last year thought we well shot of Tower Hamlets, now realise what Labour rule really means. It provides a salutary lesson for anyone foolish enough to wish for a Labour victory.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Dan Falchikov</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
