<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 234 Commentary</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 234 Commentary</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Bypass Surgery</H2>
    </CENTER>
    <P><STRONG>The Battle of the Newbury Bypass has brought two Liberal principles into head-on collision. For the Liberal Democrats, it is an extreme example of what can happen when local party members who have won control of their council follow a policy which annoys and embarrasses many supporters elsewhere.</STRONG></P>
    <P>This sort of thing is likely to happen with increasing frequency as the number of councils under the party's control rises.</P>
    <P>But both sides at Newbury can cite impeccable justifications in Liberal principles for their stance.</P>
    <P>The council, and Newbury's MP David Rendel, can argue that local public opinion, which they are elected to represent, is substantially in favour of the bypass. Those who believe in devolution of decision making must surely respect this. Who, after all, is better equipped to judge whether Newbury needs a bypass or not than its inhabitants and their elected representatives?</P>
    <P>Those Liberals who treat the devolution of power to 'communities' as the greatest good in politics would have to leave the argument there. The local community, as far as anyone can reasonably tell, wants a bypass. Local opinion somewhere else, for equally valid reasons, might not want a local bypass. There is no conflict between these positions; each can be judged on different local needs. So should a good Liberal respect this and cheer the bulldozers?</P>
    <P>This comes up against the other Liberal principle of sustainability. This is a modern buzzword for an old idea; that the earth's resources should not be heedlessly consumed but reasonably safeguarded for the future.</P>
    <P>Two policies in which this principle finds expression are support for public transport over the private car, and support for increased use of rail rather than increased construction of new roads.</P>
    <P>The idea that improved roads in themselves increase traffic, rather than simply easing the flow of traffic which already exists, was once supported only by an environmentalist green fringe. It is now so mainstream that it half-heartedly informs even the present Government's planning policy.</P>
    <P>Viewed solely from this perspective, the Newbury bypass is an abomination. It destroys protected countryside, and by clearing a bottleneck, makes the A34 corridor more attractive to heavy traffic, ensuring that the problem it seeks to solve will recur at some future time.</P>
    <P>This clash of principles puts Liberals in general, and the Liberal Democrats in particular, in a bind.</P>
    <P>In most of the country, party activists campaign against projects such as this, whether from environmental conviction or nimbyist opportunism.</P>
    <P>Paddy Ashdown's Glasgow conference speech went out of its way to stress adherence to 'green' ideas. And there are plenty of members of his party, and sympathisers beyond, for whom green issues are the most important in politics. The Liberal Democrats, and the Liberals before them, are generally recognised as the 'greenest' mainstream party, particularly after events showed up the Green Party as a frivolous shambles.</P>
    <P>But now Newbury's stance on the most high-profile current environmental issue threatens to put the party on the 'wrong' side of the debate on protecting the environment. Opponents will argue that a party which supports the concreting of part of Berkshire, cannot be trusted to oppose road building anywhere else.</P>
    <P>What will be done? It is a safe bet that with a parliamentary seat at stake, the Newbury local party will not be destroyed from on high, as was Tower Hamlets when the leadership last felt embarrassed by local activity.</P>
    <P>No other part of the Liberal Democrats can compel Newbury to drop its support for the bypass without trampling on local decision-making, one of the party's other key planks.</P>
    <P>In philosophical terms, there is always going to be tension when Liberals devolve power and then feel that those to whom it is devolved are using it for what those above them consider illiberal ends.</P>
    <P>In practical political terms, the best that can be done is to point up the difference between general national policy and particular local cases.</P>
    <P>The party leadership owes it to local members in Newbury not to charge in feet - first to force them to either be quiet or change their minds.</P>
    <P>And Newbury members owe it to their colleagues elsewhere to stress that they support the bypass as a one-off response to an especially acute local pollution problem, and that in general and in other circumstances, they do support sustainability and a commitment to reducing road traffic and road building.</P>
    <P>There is an obvious line of attack on the Government, which has cancelled road building for financial reasons, and far from improving public transport, is simultaneously destroying that for the same motive.</P>
    <P>And the very recognition of local factors opens up an obvious difference between Liberals and the more fundamentalist type of anti-road protester. The latter are creating a climate in which it will become impossible to build any infrastructure, whatever the local circumstances or importance to a national network, without massive protests. It will be interesting to see their response if and when a different future government starts to build new railways across the countryside.</P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
