<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 235 Commentary</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 235 Commentary</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Canary Dwarves</H2>
    </CENTER>
    <P><B>Most readers would agree</B> that John Major can claim little credit for anything. But, on the principle that even a broken clock is right twice a day, there was one thing which most of us might have been thankful for, and that was the Northern Ireland peace agreement. The IRA bomb at Canary Wharf must bring that achievement into question. The immediate blame for this outrage rests firmly with the IRA. The political context is another matter.</P>
    <P>Nothing can justify planting terrorist bombs. But the Canary Wharf bomb would not have occurred had the British Government not been stalling on the peace agreement. The Government's demands for decommissioning of weapons and for elections to all-party talks do not stem from a realistic assessment of what will bring about a lasting peace. They are motivated by the Government's desire to appease the Ulster Unionists.</P>
    <P>The Conservatives' parliamentary majority is being whittled away by death and defection. You do not need to be a qualified actuary to realise that this majority will disappear at some point during 1996. If Canary Wharf teaches us anything, it is that the Tories will stop at nothing to cling on to power until the last possible moment. In this context, the 9 Official Unionist votes in the Commons represent a lifeline to the Tories.</P>
    <P>We must therefore ask the question: why did Tony Blair and Paddy Ashdown not express this blindingly obvious point? In the immediate aftermath of a terrorist bomb, the pressure is on for all spokespeople to condemn the outrage and express sympathy for those killed or injured. But a courageous politician would then go on to draw some fundamental lessons.</P>
    <P>It is not enough for opposition politicians to open up the thesaurus at the word 'condemn' each time a bomb goes off, and offer no analysis or prescription. Now is surely the time for the opposition to abandon formally the all-party consensus and to challenge the Government's true motives. British politicians ought to look at recent peace agreements in the Middle East and South Africa. They would then realise that disarmament is a subject on the agenda of all-party talks, not a precondition for such talks.</P>
    <P>It would be a shame if John Major sacrificed his one real political achievement on the altar of Unionist intransigence. But it would be just as great a shame if opposition politicians accepted this agenda instead of offering bold alternatives.</P>
    <HR>
    <H2>Plus Ca Change...</H2>
    <P><B>If the truth be told,</B> the debate within the Liberal Democrats about Tony Blair's 'New Labour' has been dominated by, not only parochial considerations, but also a fear for the Liberal Democrats' political virginity. The greatest danger of a Labour government tends to be forgotten - that a Labour government will leave the Tories' highly centralised government machine intact, ready for a subsequent Tory administration to inherit at some time in the future.</P>
    <P>The new book by Peter Mandelson and Roger Liddle offers few reassurances on that score, with its talk of 'super ministers', a dictatorial role for the Prime Minister, and an all-powerful overseeing job that looks suspiciously like a job description for one P Mandelson.</P>
    <P>A priority for any incoming non-Tory administration should be to dismantle the apparatus of autocratic government, so that the Tories can never possess absolute power again. That means some form of electoral reform. It means devolution of power to local government and to Scottish and Welsh parliaments. It means a Freedom of Information Act. It means the effective abolition of a corrupt and pernicious MI5. It means the break-up of monopolies of media ownership. Above all, it means a system of checks and balances instead of the exercise by ministers of the absolute powers of the Crown. But the signs are not good. For example, Labour should be committing itself to dismantling the 'quangocracy'. Instead, it is engaged in an internal row between those who want to return powers to elected bodies and those who see quangos as a future means of patronage.</P>
    <P>Liberator readers doubtless have firm views on the subject of deals with Labour. But if Paddy Ashdown finds himself holding the balance of power after the next general election, this is the area where he can and should extract the best deals. His role is to ask Blair: do you want to challenge the Tory machine or merely run it yourself? A Labour government will be concentrating its efforts on the economic front. In this area of policy, the Liberal Democrats will have no clout, either because they agree with Labour, or because they have nothing to say, or because Labour can call their bluff.</P>
    <P>Why not outflank Labour on the left and demand some constitutional changes which are no skin off Labour's nose but would help prevent the recurrent nightmare of Tory rule?</P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
      <map name="BUTTONS">
