<DOCHDR>
http://www.liberator.org.uk:80/235/1.htm 194.207.26.203 19970122140023 text/html 13040
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 22 Jan 1997 13:59:45 GMT
Server: Apache/0.8.10
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 12867
Last-modified: Tue, 21 Jan 1997 13:36:15 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN//2.0">
<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 235</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 235</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>The Back-Door Death Penalty</H2>
    </CENTER>
    <P><B><I>Lord Russell explains that Liberals should cherish the Welfare State, because if the State demands peoples' allegiance, it has a duty to keep them alive.</I></B></P>
    <HR WIDTH=50%>
    <P><B>Liberalism is not, as Margaret Thatcher ignorantly supposes,</B> about minimum government: it is about minimum oppression. Oppression is  not always by government. It may be done by anyone who has power. Who can be more oppressed than a Filipino maid, beaten, starved and locked up by her employer, and unable to escape for fear of being deported as an illegal immigrant? In this sort of situation, the intervention of the state can create liberty, by freeing people from the arbitrary power of private individuals. This is the sort of case which should serve to construct a paradigm of Liberal principles on Social Security.</P>
    <P>If asked 'what is the Social Security system for', the basic answer must be that it ensures that people have enough to eat to stay alive, and a roof over their heads to keep the frost out. I do not advance this as a natural right, though I would often like to: I know that were I the President of Ethiopia, I might have to admit that I was unable to deliver such a right. I see no need to admit this in Britain, which, for all its economic woes, is still securely in the top ten economic powers in the world. We do not have to let our people starve, and the 350 a year who die on the London streets are a mark of political, not of economic failure.</P>
    <P>I would base this on the central bargain which English lawyers have recognised for centuries as giving legitimacy to the state. We owe the state allegiance because the state owes us protection. It has been understood, at least since the Elizabethan Poor Law, that 'protection' does not just mean external defence: it means that the state has an obligation to keep its citizens alive if it can. That includes an obligation, so far as its power extends, to protect them against poverty.</P>
    <P>If we deprive people of that protection, we are doing something very like the medieval process of making them outlaws: we are depriving them of the protection of the state. To what extent that relieves them of the obligation to obey the state is a question I am reluctant to stir too far: I have never been quite sure that I agree with St. Thomas Aquinas that the destitute commit no sin if they steal to support themselves. It is a useful quotation to throw at John Patten or Anne Widdecombe, but it is a slippery slope, and I would rather we kept off it.</P>
    <P>Being destitute also means being subject to the arbitrary power of anyone willing to offer support, however unpleasant. It means people may be compelled by fear of starvation to take up drug pushing or prostitution. This is neither liberal nor good for society: it is another form of being subject to arbitrary power, and one of the purposes of Social security is to save people from it. Some 16 and 17 year olds, with no right of benefit, are being pushed into prostitution against their sexual orientation. Can arbitrary power go much further? We are committed as a party by the LDYS motion at Harrogate in 1992 not to disentitle groups of people as a class to Social Security benefits regardless of what they have done. I would like to go further: I would like a policy that we do not disentitle anyone to benefits. we have abolished the death penalty: we should not use the Social Security system to bring it in by the back door.</P>
    <P>This does not mean that the state has no rights. In return for protection we have a duty to keep the laws. The laws at present require us, if unemployed, to seek work actively. As a party, we see nothing wrong with that: it is a perfectly reasonable bargain. If we do not obey this obligation to seek work, we may legitimately be punished. The difficulty is how to punish people we do not want to imprison, and who have no property. It seems that there has to be a benefit penalty short of disentitlement, but until benefit levels can be higher, the penalty cannot be large one without breaking the state's duty to keep people alive and in sufficient health to resume work when there is a chance.</P>
    <P>The state's financial interest in the benefit system is to ensure that people who lose their jobs remain employable and do not fall ill or disappear into a criminal underclass. If, as we are told, the job for life becomes rarer, this function of the benefit system will become even more essential. this means the system needs a host of detailed alterations to make it easier for people to get off benefit into work. This is now an all-party consensus, and we contributed a great deal to making it so. This principle holds together many of the measures we approved at Brighton in 1994. It is one in which humanity and the state's financial interest coincide.</P>
    <P>The obligation of actively seeking work should be consistent with some dignity and individuality. The disabled woman who was held not to be actively seeking work because she would not work as a nude model is a story we should not have to hear again. Similarly, people who leave jobs because of sexual harassment should not be punished for being voluntarily unemployed. It is not only Cabinet ministers who should be able to say 'I can no longer serve with honour'.</P>
    <P>The whole system should be run in the knowledge that it is being applied to individuals, who cannot be treated exactly alike. All politicians in office are tempted to treat people as if they were plasticine - to mould them into whatever shapes they like the look of. People on benefit, because of their comparative powerlessness, are very vulnerable to this approach. As Nancy Seear has stressed many times, any obligation to undertake training must be suitable training. We do not want cases like the man who wanted to work with animals, and was sent to work in an abattoir, or the asthmatic who was sent to work as a painter. Both were refused benefit for rejecting these opportunities, the asthmatic after making himself ill trying. We do not want illiterates required to produce written records of their job applications, as has happened despite ministerial attempts to prevent it.</P>
    <P>Two conclusions follow from this. One is that we should be very careful in making arbitrary rules which require people to fit into a particular pattern which they may have good reason for objecting to. In particular, we must beware of the formula. Formulas, because they deny individuality, are particularly illiberal things. The formula for the medical test for Incapacity Benefit for unfitness to work and Child Support Formula for the C.S.A. both attempt to treat people alike by leaving out half the relevant evidence. That is treating people as if they were plasticine. For example, to require people to pay a set sum to support their children regardless of the fact that they may be paying thousands to support their parents is neither good humanity nor good budgeting for the state.</P>
    <P>The second is that the whole system needs to be better controlled by law. The sudden arbitrary deprivation of benefit before any appeal is very much like the "civilised" modern version of the midnight knock on the door, and may be just as devastating in its effects. Take, for example, the man in Sussex who needed a car to go to work. He had a car breakdown on the way to work, did not get there, and was dismissed. He then suffered a 40% loss of benefit for 'voluntary unemployment', and presumably had to sell the car without which he could not work, thus becoming unemployable. That is the sort of thing that happens if people can lose benefit before appeal. It gives quite junior functionaries the sort of power no one in a civilised country should be allowed. It is profoundly illiberal - and a reminder that the Social Security system stands to save money by better public transport.</P>
    <P>The system is run by regulations, which are very hard for Parliament to check. This is justified by claims of 'flexibility' very like those made by Geoffrey Howe and William Waldegrave for the guidelines for the export of arms to Iraq. In each case, it means our old friend the Cambises Clause: "The Secretary of State may do what ever he likes". That sort of power isn't any good for anyone. It isn't good for Liberals either. The difference is that we know it isn't good for us. It is a case of the familiar Liberal principle that we need to come into office ready to control our own power.  To that end, European law, with its concentration on general principles, is likely to be our best instrument. It is yet another reason for joining the Social Chapter.</P>
    <P>None of this has said very much about cost. We are quite right to be worried about cost, but we need to identify where the costs are coming from before we can control them. The costs come from two things. One is the increase of people of pensionable age, which has risen from 11% to 16% of the population since 1951. However, it is only projected to rise another 2%, to 18%, before 2021. For the next 25 years our competitors will be experiencing much more rapid rises than us. We might be thinking in terms of a rise in the retirement age after 2021, but it is not an urgent problem.</P>
    <P>The other big problem is the number of people out of work. This is a bigger number than the unemployment figures show. 13.2% of adults depend on Income Support, and this figure, unlike the unemployment figures, is still rising. No less than 25.4% of children are on Income Support. This is not yet all. We must add in the number of people of people over 50 who have not worked for ten years. This number is 2,594,000 people. Some of these will be included in the Income Support figures, but in many cases unemployment is disguised as early retirement, and are increasing the actuarial pressure on pension funds. when we consider how many people it is being asked to support, the Social Security budget is cheap at the price. Anyone who blames the Department of Social Security for the cost of the Social Security budget is shooting the messenger. It is like blaming the inhabitants of Lundy Island because their beaches are covered with oil.</P>
    <P>If we put people under the obligation actively seeking work,  there is a duty on us to make sure there is some work to seek. Social Security can contribute some policies, such as childcare and better tapers, to bring this happy state of affairs about. The main solutions are in the hands of the economic ministries.</P>
    <P>So long as we have something over 20% of the population dependent on means tested benefits of one sort or another, there is no cheaper solution than the one we have at present. The people will not go away if they lose benefit. Some may become homeless, some may fall ill, some may get divorced, some may take to crime, prostitution or drug pushing. Some may do all of these things. None of them are ones the state can legitimately regard as an economy. There is no cheaper solution until these people have work. Anything else is like blaming Lundy Island for the cost of cleaning up its beaches. we have to stop the spill first. Thank God we, unlike Labour, belong to a party whose leaders know these things.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Lord Conrad Russell</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
