<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 236 Commentary</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 236 Commentary</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Standing Up, and Lying Down</H2>
    </CENTER>
    <P><B>The Liberal Democrats can be proud of their opposition to the Government's bulldozing through parliament of stop and search powers.</B> It is considerably more than 'new' Labour.</P>
    <P>The Liberal Democrats smoked out the fiction that these powers were a response to an emergency. The police had sought them for some time, but they were introduced neither before the ceasefire, nor immediately after it ended, nor during the debate soon after on the prevention of terrorism act.</P>
    <P>Why could these powers not have been subject to normal parliamentary scrutiny? As Alan Beith said, that is what parliament is for. If it cannot scrutinise legislation it might as well not exist.</P>
    <P>It is hard to avoid the conclusion that the Government's priority was to embarrass Labour, by forcing it either to alienate its own civil libertarians by supporting the measure, or be painted as 'soft on terrorism' by opposing them.</P>
    <P>Labour duly leapt into the trap. The way 'new' Labour is going, it is hard to avoid the conclusion that, even if the IRA disarmed and disbanded tomorrow, a Labour government would retain these powers the better to harass beggars, 'squeegy merchants' and other of Jack Straw's scapegoats.</P>
    <P>Any free society faced with a terrorist threat has to take special powers to confront it. But the fact that those powers are special requires that they are examined properly before being implemented, and that the limits of their use are clearly defined.</P>
    <P>Hasty legislation is almost by definition bad legislation; ill-thought-out, and unlikely to be effective. This ineffectiveness leads to a ratchet effect of increasingly oppressive legislation. And governments rarely voluntarily surrender authoritarian powers.</P>
    <P>This point may have been at the back of the Liberal Democrats' minds. It was after all a Liberal government which in 1911 forced through the Official Secrets Act in one day, in a similar spate of panic. Not even Michael Howard pretends that the Kaiser's spies still pose a threat. But the powers to deal with them are still there.</P>
    <P>This was not the only recent issue over which Labour lay down to be counted. Its attempt to loosen the Tories' proposals on cross-media ownership suggest that in Government it would be as concerned as the Tories to abuse power to do its friends favours. Its pathetic evasions over the sale of Railtrack symbolise its intention  to merely mind the shop for the Tories.</P>
    <P>Every utterance of Tony Blair's stresses what he will not change, not what he will. With every speech he commits himself to keep his hands off yet another part of Thatcher's Britain.</P>
    <P>Labour is trying to gain power without winning any arguments and without committing itself to any changes. It is relying entirely on public disgust with the Tories incompetence and  sleaze.</P>
    <P>There is a strong and serious arguments that democracy will not long survive uninterrupted one-party government.</P>
    <P>But a Labour government elected on a platform of promising not to do anything will find at the first sign of trouble that its support is built on quicksand.</P>
    <P>Even in their present dire straits, the Tories seem more intellectually confident than 'new' Labour, as well they might be since Blair challenges none of their basic assumptions.</P>
    <P>Far from getting closer to Labour, its current behaviour opens up a huge gap for the Liberal Democrats, or anyone bold enough to fill it.</P>
    <HR>
    <H2>To Them That Have</H2>
    <P><B>Whatever one thinks of the Liberal Democrats' new support for student loans,</B> there is an issue they must sort out quickly if they are not to send canvassers naked onto the doorsteps of student voters (and more to the point, parents of intending students).</P>
    <P>Repayment of loans once one's income rises above a certain level is fine for those whose qualifications are reasonably likely to move them rapidly to a high income. It is also fine in a way for those in vocations who may never hit the threshold.</P>
    <P>It is not fine at all for the vast bulk in the middle, who, because interest will rack up on loan repayments, face eventually paying back far more than will wealthier contemporaries who progress more quickly to higher incomes.</P>
    <P>Even if one accepts the basic argument, this is a gaping flaw. It effectively forces most intending students to gamble thousands of pounds of debt against the likelihood that their future salary increases will outstrip rising interest payments.</P>
    <P>Paddy Ashdown said this debate showed the Liberal Democrats taking 'tough' decisions. 'Tough' need not be a synonym for 'gratuitously courting unpopularity'. It will be if this policy's loose ends are not tied up.</P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
