<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 236 Radical Bulletin</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG WIDTH=100% SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 236</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="../rb.gif">Radical Bulletin</H1>
    </CENTER>
    <H2><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="../rb2.gif">Silent Movies</H2>
    <P>The second of the Liberal Democrat party political broadcasts under the control of its general election team was certainly unusual. Did you know the connection between Paddy Ashdown, the Three Graces, a wealthy retired gardener and the Ribble Valley by-election? No? Evidence suggests few viewers of the broadcast did either.</P>
    <P>The first oddity was that it was silent with captions and music.</P>
    <P>What was more unusual was the content. Each year since the party's formation in 1988 rolled by with notable events linked to Liberal Democrat achievements.</P>
    <P>The selection of the former bordered on the weird. 1988 was marked by Eddie The Eagle. Didn't the party wish to get away from the image of being an heroic failure? It was also the year Elton John auctioned his possessions at Sotheby's, but then of course no-one needed reminding of that.</P>
    <P>Oh, and Paddy Ashdown was elected leader of 'the only British party to have one-member one-vote elections.'</P>
    <P>1989 was marked by that noted tipple 'beer with the alcohol taken out' going on sale in pubs, and of course by the number of Liberal Democrats councillors exceeding 3,000. It wisely refrained from pointing out that this was a decrease.</P>
    <P>In 1990, as everyone remembers, the English National Ballet was saved by the Arts Council and 'an Oxfordshire man refuses to remove a shark from his roof'. Meanwhile 'the Liberal Democrats wrong foot the Conservatives in the Eastbourne by-election'. Why not come out and say that they won it?</P>
    <P>1991 saw Gerald Ratner in trouble for describing his own goods as 'crap' [why put ideas into viewers' heads? - Collective] and the victory in Ribble Valley.</P>
    <P>And what of 1992? 'A retied gardener finds Roman treasure worth 10 million', as if anyone knew or cared now. 'And the Liberal Democrats continue their rise in popularity. 20 MPs are elected'. Pity it was 24 before the election, but there you go.</P>
    <P>And what great issues did that trusty band get stuck into the next year? 1993 was marked by 'England's cricketers [being] told to smarten up', and it was 'goodbye to Sunday lie-ins for shop workers as Parliament passes Sunday trading laws'. An unnecessarily pejorative way of describing an issue on which there was no party line and where reform was supported actively by many Liberal Democrats.</P>
    <P>From here on at least the Liberal Democrat events mentioned were all genuine advances straightforwardly described, though the comparative events, including keeping the Three Graces in Britain and the banging-up of Nick Leeson were consistently peculiar.</P>
    <P>The final caption said 'The news is the Liberal Democrats are growing in strength, winning the trust of those millions of people. Join the people who are making the news'.</P>
    <P>After each such broadcast volunteer teams are drafted into Cowley Street to deal with the rush of phone calls from enthused members of the public.</P>
    <P>For reasons that can best be guessed at, it was deemed unnecessary to call on other party members in building who had been told to hold themselves on standby to assist the volunteers with the expected rush. One estimate was that this generated the lowest response of any Liberal Democrat broadcast.</P>
    <P>But perhaps viewers were simply too busy trying to work out what on earth it had been about to spare time for that vital phone call.</P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
      <map name="BUTTONS">
