<DOCHDR>
http://www.liberator.org.uk:80/236/1.htm 194.207.26.203 19970122141015 text/html 11778
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 22 Jan 1997 14:03:39 GMT
Server: Apache/0.8.10
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 11605
Last-modified: Tue, 21 Jan 1997 13:37:43 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN//2.0">
<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 236</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 236</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Ending Poverty, Increasing Choice</H2>
    </CENTER>
    <P><B><I>Liberal Democrat policy on financing higher education took a lot of stick at and after the Nottingham conference. Policy working party member Michael Woods argues that the proposals are honest, realistic and principled.</I></B></P>
    <HR WIDTH=50%>
    <P><B>They say that timing is everything. One day the government announces an inquiry into higher education, the next the Liberal Democrats launch their new higher education policy. One day a BBC journalist reports that the government will not risk the favoured but politically sensitive option of student loans repaid through National Insurance; the next day the Liberal Democrats introduce a policy based on -loans to students repaid through National Insurance.</B></P>
    <P>Foolish or farsighted? The reaction of many radical Liberal Democrats has been, predictably and understandably, one of horror. Colin Ross in Liberator 235 and columns of speakers at the Nottingham conference have articulated genuine unease about a policy which appears to swap a long-standing and allegedly 'fair' system of student funding for one in which they claim to detect the whiff of Thatcherism. I think both these presumptions are disputable - the old system wasn't fair, and our proposed new system needn't be Thatcherite.</P>
    <P>The present system of student grants is clearly neither fair nor effective. A recent survey has confirmed that the average student debt on graduation varies between 1,500 and 4,000 depending on age and geography; with mature students being most debt-laden. At the same time, means-tested grants discriminate most against those potential students whose parents earn just above the threshold, but whom are unable or unwilling to pay their 'parental contribution'. The new policy paper rightly restates our commitment to abolishing the parental contribution - access to higher education should not be determined by parental generosity - but the implication is that all students should receive full grants. Such a policy was sustainable in the mid 1980s, but not today.</P>
    <P>In 1996, we have a higher education sector that has been rattled to its foundations by nearly two decades of reckless expansion without matching investment, forced upon it with the usual cavalier incompetence by a fly-by-night government aided and abetted by greedy university administrators who scrapped for short-term gain without a thought for what would happen when the wind changed. The number of students in HE is now more than the entire population of Northern Ireland; giving them all a 1979-level grant would cost over 4 billion - as much as the whole Employment Department budget for 1994/5. And that's even before we've considered the over-crowded buildings, under-stocked libraries, out-dated equipment, shelved research and the demoralised, under-paid staff; not to mention all the other non-education but equally deserving demands on a Liberal Democrat government's wallet. Even Colin Ross acknowledges that "our old student funding policies are now untenable."</P>
    <P>The sense of crisis in HE was ever-present throughout the working group's deliberations; ideas proposed at one meeting  would be overtaken by events before the next. But it was the  threat by Vice-Chancellors to impose 'top-up' fees that threw our proposals into sharpest relief. The policy paper unequivocally states that the Liberal Democrats will "ensure that education is made available free at the point of entry." That is worth repeating: a Liberal Democrat government would ensure that students will not have to pay up front to go to university. That is a guarantee that neither Labour nor the Tories can currently give.</P>
    <P>If students are not to pay-as-they-learn, the money has to come from somewhere. And the fairest solution is that those who have benefited most from a university education should contribute something back. This is not a new idea. The students of the last boom in the 60s and 70s went to university expecting that they would repay the cost through paying a higher rate of income tax. The success of Thatcherism in changing the boundaries of political discourse means that simply hiking up income tax for high earners is no longer an option. To implement the same principle we have to specifically target high-earning graduates and tell them what they are paying for - it's being honest about taxation again.</P>
	 <UL>
     <P>The proposals for student funding contained in the new policy paper are therefore based on two very sound, very liberal, principles:</P>
	  <LI>the State has a duty to enable everyone to meet their potential in tertiary education regardless of their financial position; ensuring that there are no financial restrictions to entering higher education and that no student should be compelled to live in poverty.
     <LI>Those who have benefited financially from their higher education should contribute retrospectively towards the cost of their education - as they are able to afford -in order to give others the same opportunity.
	 </UL>
    <P>Whatever its complexity, the 'Individual Learning Account' (ILA) approach is a much fairer and more effective means of enacting these principles than the present grant system, or student loans, or a graduate tax or any other concoction I have seen suggested. It makes money available to students whilst studying, and protects low-earning graduates from demands to pay up.</P>
    <P>If there is a fault in the policy paper, it is in its ambiguity. Like the Scott Report, the paper can be interpreted in a number of ways. Post-Nottingham, the challenge for radical Liberal Democrats is to ensure that the party leadership interpret it in a manner consistent with the principles outlined above.</P>
    <P>Firstly, it is unclear exactly how much of their tuition and maintenance costs graduates would be expected to repay. The tuition element was originally included on the understanding that student maintenance would be supported through the benefits system - but the paragraph pledging this disappeared shortly before publication along with a commitment of government funding for two years of education or training. At present there is nothing to stop our  opponents suggesting that graduates would have to repay 99%  of the cost - if that is to be avoided then the party has to be clear about how much the government's contribution to ILAs will be. (I trust none of the costings being bandied around - least of all those from David Wheeldon - a lobbyist for the NUS and the most right-wing member of the working group - quoted in Liberator 234).</P>
    <P>Secondly, the fairness of these proposals depends on a respectable minimum earnings threshold for repayment being set. A vague reference to "a certain level" is much too Blairite for credibility and needs to given more precision. The party may be reluctant to indulge in numerical figures, but citing a level relative to average earnings would strengthen the argument.</P>
    <P>Thirdly, if graduates cannot be expected to repay until they meet an earnings threshold, why should their debts accrue interest? Indeed, if interest is charged on debts from the point of borrowing the result will be that those who can least afford it will end up paying more - undermining the whole logic of the ILA framework. If we must charge interest on ILA debts - and I am unconvinced - we should state that interest will only be triggered at the same point as repayment, and we have to indicate what the rate of interest might be (Colin Ross is right to say that 1.5% above the mortgage rate is too high).</P>
    <P>Finally, the policy paper was about more than student funding. Much of what it says about increasing access, promoting choice, ensuring quality and investing in research will be welcomed - but not everything. The much-quoted gushing praise of the policy paper from the Association of University Teachers omitted the more lukewarm comment that "the proposal to move research funds from the funding councils to the research councils needed to be treated with caution". The conventional wisdom is that concentrating all research funds with the research councils is incompatible with guaranteeing active research across the university sector - but the policy paper promises both. The present wording may be a convenient compromise, but more thought will be needed to convince the academic community. Similarly, at a time when Nottingham Trent University's proposed honorary degree for Ken Clarke has exposed the undemocratic governance of universities (effectively super-quangos), the policy paper says very little on what might have been expected to be a Liberal speciality (largely due to the disinterest of those drafting the paper). Instead we are left with a less radical policy on university governance than the CVCP!</P>
    <P>'The Key to Lifelong Learning' is not a perfect policy paper, but it is an honest, realistic, principled, fundamentally fair and timely response to a problem created (as ever) by Tory incompetence. Labour and the Tories may choose to hide behind Dearing with their usual cowardice, but they know that the outcome of his inquiry will be some form of student contribution. Even the NUS have abandoned grants for a system remarkably like that we propose. Of  course some of our more scurrilous opponents will make  sniper attacks from the safety of their policy vacuums -but only if we let them. Far from 'new HE policy' and 'vote-loser' being synonyms, I believe that policies such as 'more money for students', 'ending student poverty', 'no entry fees', 'more choice in education', 'increasing access to education', 'ending the part-time/full-time divide', 'ending the vocational/academic divide', 'investing in education', 'investing in research', and 'protecting low earning graduates' can and must be turned into vote winners. The task for radical Liberal Democrats in all sections of the party is now to ensure that the principles and the promise of this policy are honoured by the party leadership.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Michael Woods</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
