<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 237 Commentary</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 237 Commentary</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>The Last Straw</H2>
  </CENTER>
    <P><B>Jack Straw, Labour's Shadow Home Secretary, is pursuing a strategy of out-toughing the Tories on law and order.</B> His latest proposal, to impose a night-time curfew on all children, certainly does that.</P>
    <P>But why stop there? Why not have everyone locked-up permanently? That should work wonders for the crime statistics.</P>
    <P>Law and order has traditionally been seen as Tory territory. But the Tories' record on tackling crime looks decidedly threadbare. For all the Tories' talk (not to mention a massive increase in spending on police and prisons), their 17 years in office have seen crime continue to rise.</P>
    <P>Tory policy has been essentially about playing to the gallery, by making 'tough' gestures without actually achieving anything. This failure presents an opportunity to opposition parties.</P>
    <P>Tony Blair's slogan (developed before he became Labour leader), 'tough on crime, tough on the causes of crime', showed promise. It demonstrated a belated recognition on the left of people's legitimate fears about crime (and, indeed, it is Labour's natural supporters in Britain's poorest communities who suffer from crime more than anyone else).</P>
    <P>But it also demonstrated a recognition that crime has roots in social and economic problems and is not simply a product of 'evil'. This sophisticated response is now being abandoned by Labour. Crime is a difficult issue for any elected politician to tackle intelligently. People's responses tend to be highly emotional, and these emotions are regularly whipped up by the tabloid press. How much easier it is to pander to prejudice, lock up more people and subject some of them to pointless military drill.</P>
    <P>The art of politics is usually about reconciling principles and pragmatism. Labour has to address real issues if it wants to win the next election. But there comes a point at which principles are compromised fatally. Jack Straw has now gone beyond that point.</P>
    <P>On this, as on other issues, Labour has displayed remarkable timidity in confronting Tory values, for fear of a bad press. But if Labour wins, it will be because people want a change, not because they want more of the same.</P>
    <P>What is the point of a change of government if there will be no change in policy?</P>
    <HR>
    <H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Where's The Beef?</H2>
    <P><B>If you want to know why a traditional nickname for the Conservatives is 'The Stupid Party',</B> you need look no further than Britain's 'war' with its partners in the European Union over the beef crisis.</P>
    <P>Here was a crisis of the Tories' own making. By deregulating animal feed, the government allowed manufacturers to include the flesh of diseased sheep in feed destined for herbivorous animals. Warnings at the time were rubbished or ignored.</P>
    <P>Only when a crisis of consumer confidence broke out earlier this year did the government react seriously to the threat of BSE. By this stage, a multi-million pound export industry faced ruin.</P>
    <P>It is hardly surprising that many consumers do not want to take the risk of contracting a fatal brain disease. Large numbers of British consumers abandoned beef overnight (although many have been won back by supermarket price cuts). But they were not subjected to abuse by the British government. The governments of the USA, Canada, Australia and New Zealand all moved quickly to block imports of British beef But they were not subjected to British sanctions.</P>
    <P>Why single out the EU for blame? The answer is simple. Tory strategy has nothing whatever to do with restoring consumer confidence or raising standards in the beef industry. It a shameless publicity stunt.</P>
    <P>This 'war' is simply a vehicle for Tory Euro-sceptics to attack the European Union. As a practical measure, British blocking tactics in the Council of Ministers are counterproductive. 'Non co-operation' makes it less likely that our EU partners will co-operate with us in restoring confidence in British beef. We should not forget that Europe is the largest market for our beef exports; before the BSE crisis, France alone accounted for more than half of all our exports.</P>
    <P>Does anyone seriously imagine that the EU would have been any more sympathetic if Britain were outside the EU? Europe would have simply blocked British beef imports and the British government would have been powerless to do anything about it.</P>
    <P>A sensible political strategy would have enlisted the support of our European partners. Instead, what we are getting from the British government is a crude piece of xenophobia designed to appeal to the worst instincts of the domestic electorate.</P>
    <P>It is the last throw of a government desperate to cling on to power at any price. That price is being paid by British beef farmers.</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
