<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 237 Radical Bulletin</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG WIDTH=100% SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 237</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="../rb.gif">Radical Bulletin</H1>
  </CENTER>
  <H2><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="../rb2.gif">Then There Were Two</H2>
  <P>The Liberal Democrats are always ready to stress their commitment to ethnic minorities, so it remains to be seen how they will cope with the imminent arrival of two organisations, both of which claim to be the legitimate Ethnic Minority Liberal Democrats.</P>
  <P>One is led by Ramesh Dewan (Liberator 236), who succeeded in getting a slate elected to the executive, after rival candidates withdrew claiming irregularities in the election process.</P>
  <P>Nasser Butt, who chairs the party's Multi-Faith Forum, himself withdrew from the elections and encouraged others to do likewise. He is now setting up the other EMLD. In a circular he has sent to party officers and MPs, he names Navnit Dholakia, Zerbanoo Gifford, and Rabi Martins among his supporters.</P>
  <P>The disputed election was overseen by president Robert Maclennan and by David Alworthy, Cowley Street's head of membership. The Butt group's circular makes a number of serious allegations about the election's conduct and related matters, which at the very least should be investigated by some disinterested body. These centre on disputes about the alleged validity of the EMLD membership of many of those who voted. Since the new EMLD is threatening to challenge the Dewan version at every level of the party's processes, this may yet force some fresh intervention by Cowley Street.</P>
  <P>One Dewan supporter is Pash Nandra, who was recently selected as PPC for Harrow West after Cowley Street ordered a re-run of the original election which she lost by three votes to former council leader Chris Noyce. The re-run election was held, on federal party instructions, on a different electoral roll to the original, allowing a large number of people who joined in the intervening period to vote. This continues to be controversial in the constituency.</P>
  <HR>
  <H2><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="../rb2.gif">Hanging In The Privy</H2>
  <P>David Steel's portrait now hangs in the National Liberal Club. Sir David had taken the perhaps unusual decision to wear full Privy Council dress for the sitting, though admitting that the practice had effectively died out with the likes of Ted Heath and Christopher Soames.</P>
  <P>Privy Councillor not withstanding, what was Sir David doing with this piece of schmutter? Lady Read, the wife of Sir Carol, had passed it on, advising him "Wear it whenever the spirit moves you". The portrait, by Anthony Oakshett, has a wry wit about it. The spirit apparently moved Sir David on the basis that he thought the portrait might fit in with several others of previous generations adorning the Club's walls.</P>
  <P>However it does prompt the too obvious RB comment about hanging it in the Privy; sorry David, you knew that one was coming. But then he would be in good company, that of F E Smith, Lord Birkenhead, the Tory Chancellor famed for using those facilities.</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
