<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 237 Reviews</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 237 Reviews</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>The Blair Revolution: Can New Labour Deliver?</H2>
   <H3>by Peter Mandelson and Roger Liddle<BR>Faber, 7.99</H3>
  </CENTER>
  <P>What is the point of the Labour Party?</P>
  <P>For years, we thought we knew. Labour may have embraced a wide spectrum of views from social democracy to near-Leninism, but it remained constitutionally committed to common ownership: it was broadly clear that a Labour government would mean more state ownership, and more state control, of industry and the provision of social services, and less reliance on market forces.</P>
  <P>A decade of victorious Thatcherism and global socialist retreat shattered Labour's self-confidence. Labour rejected its past, abandoned Clause 4, and put in its place - well, what?</P>
  <P>Two of Tony Blair's closest advisers, Peter Mandelson and leading social democrat Roger Liddle, were supposed to provide the answer with this book.</P>
  <P>They fail. Roy Hattersley, one of the few people left in the Labour Party who seems to have any idea what he stands for, described this book as "banal, pretentious, and risibly inadequate". Mr. Hattersley can be criticised only for understatement.</P>
  <P>The message is that things are awful under the Tories. They really are tremendously awful. But look, here is new Labour, which Mandelson and Liddle unveil in the political equivalent of a corporate public relations brochure - long on feelgood phrases and short on content. We have two hundred and sixty pages of "concepts" and "ideas", which are, of course, "meaningful".</P>
  <P>"Times change", we are told "and we must learn from experience and live in the world as it now is". Liddle and Mandelson do not explain how it would be possible to live in the world as it now isn't. "Community is a robust and powerful idea, and it is at the heart of the stakeholder economy New Labour wishes to create. It means teamwork ... It means mutuality ... It means justice...". It is a pity that we are not told exactly what "community" is, or how it will achieve these wonderful things.</P>
  <P>If you are trying to promote a political party which has no idea what it is for, you can always try creating a personality cult around the leader. Liddle and Mandelson devote an embarrassingly sycophantic chapter to Tony Blair himself. Here is a flavour: "Importantly, Blair is not a prude or a prig in his private life. He never tries to push religion on anyone, and most people would never realise he goes to church every Sunday. He does not feel morally superior to those who choose to live their lives differently, and he is not judgmental about those friends who are not in conventional marriages or who are single parents, or who are gay." Well, that's alright then.</P>
  <P>Amid the jumble of vacuous phrases there are two proposals (or rather, "concepts" - nothing is actually presented as a firm proposal) which have received some attention. Neither is workable and both are somewhat authoritarian.</P>
  <P>One is the idea that the government should give soft loans to "young couples" of, say, a few thousand pounds. How exactly is a "couple" to be defined, and what if they are not "young"? Why should people who choose to live their lives alone (an increasing number) be taxed to subsidise those who don't? Why should a couple of modest means who have saved hard before setting up home together be taxed to pay for a couple with the same income who have simply squandered their money? What would Liddle and Mandelson do about "couples" who have become a couple purely in order to get their hands on the loot? Would gay couples be included? The whole idea is a recipe for unfairness leading to resentment and frustration.</P>
  <P>The other concept is "mentoring": young people in trouble at school or with the police would be taken in hand by a slightly older, more successful person, probably from the same community and the same background. It is hard to see why those selected by the state for "mentoring" would not quickly become stigmatised as potential troublemakers, and would not resent the imposition of an implicitly superior mentor. In particular, mentors would probably be hated by the parents of the young person being mentored. The state would be saying that it could do a better job than the parents and everyone concerned would know it.</P>
  <P>Given the authoritarian streak, Jack Straw's latest proposal, to impose a curfew on young people, comes as no surprise. Perhaps mentors would help to enforce the curfew and soft loans would be withheld from those who had broken it.</P>
  <P>Liddle and Mandelson do not tell us what the point of the Labour Party is, and, to the extent that they come up with anything at all apart from catch-phrases, they reveal a nasty inclination to run our lives for us. Those Liberals who seem to be looking forward to a Blair government should get real.</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Andrew Lee</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Home Page" coords="32,2,4,23,1,56,85,56,81,25,56,22,33,2,33,3" href="../index.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="The Collective" coords="88,40,91,59,138,59,144,47,118,1,101,0,96,39,89,39" href="../Collective/Collective.html">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Read Liberator" coords="151,41,148,56,218,55,207,45,214,29,195,22,196,2,165,0,153,40" href="../read.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Write for Liberator" coords="224,56,273,57,273,8,253,0,229,3,219,31,223,49" href="../write.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Subscribe" coords="288,57,360,42,371,26,344,0,305,4,278,38" href="../subs.htm">
