<DOCNO>WT10-B35-152</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA030-000642-B042-120</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.liberator.org.uk:80/237/1.htm 194.207.26.203 19970122141225 text/html 6873
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 22 Jan 1997 14:11:57 GMT
Server: Apache/0.8.10
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6701
Last-modified: Tue, 21 Jan 1997 13:38:45 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 237</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 237</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Standing On The Corner</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P><B><I>There is no point in providing youth clubs when young people really prefer to meet on street corners. Liberal Democrat Oadby and Wigston decided on a liberal approach to youth non-conformity. Councillor Mark Cox explains how.</I></B></P>
  <HR WIDTH=50%>
  <P><B>In the late 1980s I served on Leicestershire County Council's youth and community review. One of the key recommendations was the insistence on more 'face to face' work with young people. Some five years on the county is hardly any further forward towards achieving this aim. However, it is not all doom and gloom. Many individuals and community centres have tried to implement the recommendations within their own resources, with varying success. One such is my borough of Oadby and Wigston.</B></P>
  <P>When the Liberal Democrats took control in 1991 we were determined to do something for young people, even though we were not the statutory authority. Following the setting up of a youth committee, with councillors, young people, youth workers and other members of the community, we commissioned a youth questionnaire. The results confirmed that what young people desired more than anything was face to face contact and information on a range of issues. It was agreed that a detached youth work project should be set up, with the aim of meeting young people where they were - on the streets. The object was to meet and talk with young people about issues of concern to them, to find out more clearly what their real needs were, and to provide information (not advice!) on social issues.</P>
  <P>Since the project started nearly two and a half years ago, we have employed four part-time youth workers, each working five hours a week, to go out on the streets in the evenings to carry out the aims of the project. They have encountered many problems and issues such as drug abuse, homelessness and family break-ups.</P>
  <P>They have passed many young people on to the information and counselling service which is now provided on a Thursday evening. The workers have also instigated two 'drop-in' centres meeting on Mondays and Fridays in different parts of the borough. These are available to any young person in the area and are staffed by two workers. Thy provide somewhere warm and dry for young people to meet and are totally unstructured. The activities that take place are decided by the young people themselves.</P>
  <P>It is important to remember that the remit of the project is not to clear the street corners of young people.</P>
  <P>Many local people, including some councillors and police certainly thought this was the idea. I would argue that nothing could be further from the truth.</P>
  <P>If young people wish to meet in the local park or behind the local shops then we would work with them there, not try to move them on. If a local centre can provide somewhere for them to meet, then that's fine of they wish to go. Some of the best work took place on street corners.</P>
  <P>The second point is that this not an 'outreach' project. The idea is not to make contact and then try to persuade young people to join one of the local clubs. The vast majority of young people know exactly what is on offer in their area, its just that some of them choose not to go.</P>
  <P>The most common statement from adults is that young people 'hang around' on street corners only because there is nothing for them to do. The majority actually enjoy 'hanging around street corners', and would not go to a club even if one were provided. They enjoy talking to their friends; in some cases it is quite a social gathering, and, most importantly, they are not constrained by club type rules.</P>
  <P>I believe this type of work, as well as being successful, is essentially liberal. It places the emphasis on the individual, as opposed to group work, and celebrates young people' non-conformity rather than stifling it. The local Labour Party, for instance, has criticised it for not providing more 'facilities', whatever that means. They fail to appreciate that all young people have different needs and aspirations and simply providing a club does nothing to meet those needs.</P>
  <P>Indeed, some of the youth clubs are struggling to attract young people, yet the drop-in centre has a regular turnover of 60 young people.</P>
  <P>Though it was not the project's original intention to tackle crime directly, it has certainly had an indirect effect. Both the police and neighbourhood watch groups acknowledge that petty crime has reduced since the start of the project, and in particular since the start of the drop-in centres.</P>
  <P>Many other projects have now started around the county. Many youth tutors and local politicians are now realising that it is a relatively cheap and effective way of dealing directly with the concerns of young people.</P>
  <P>One footnote to this is that a few weeks ago the Monday night drop in centre was closed by the local community association because of an alleged theft. Though it was never proved, it was the young people who took the blame. Since then, I've received a petition from local residents complaining about young people 'hanging around' the local park. It seems that we adults never learn, and we should not be surprised if young people hit out when we alienate them from the rest of society. The youth committee is currently searching for an alternative drop in centre venue.</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Mark Cox</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
