<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 237</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 237</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Legal Weapons In Environmental Campaigns</H2>
    </CENTER>
    <P><B><I>Liz Loughran reports on an alternative form of legal practice and explains her environmental law work.</I></B></P>
    <HR WIDTH=50%>
    <P><B>Traditional legal practices seem to be putting an ever increasing distance between the market they serve - the clients - and themselves. Combined with the demise of legal aid, the time has come to rethink the way in which the provision of legal services is delivered, a project undertaken by Lord Justice Woolf's Civil Justice Review. One way is for solicitors to learn good practice from barristers. Solicitors Chambers was founded in 1989 with the intention of making high quality legal services available at an affordable price. By keeping overheads to a minimum, the ten sole practitioners who practice at Chambers keep their costs down and can pass these savings on to the clients. As a result, typical hourly rates can be under 50-60% of what a conventional firm would charge. Organising in a similar way to barristers, each member of chambers is self employed, but the client still has the assurance that the matter is being dealt with by an experienced solicitor in the relevant field of law. I am the first woman solicitor to be admitted into this arrangement.</B></P>
    <P>The solicitors in Chambers range from late thirties to early fifties. Specialist legal advice is available on mental health law from a Mental Health Act Commissioner. Another solicitor has come from a major trade union and gives advice on employment law and industrial accidents. There are no common politics. It's quite an idiosyncratic bunch in some respects - just as you would find in any firm of solicitors. The difference is that we can all be who we want without any restrictions on style and personality. If there is any friction, rife in most firms because lawyers are generally appalling managers, it is moderated because there are no pressures to perform or conform to a corporate style. There is no threat of redundancy or loss of pay review either. You get what you put in.</P>

    <H3>Twyford Down</H3>
    <P>My work specialises in environmental and planning law litigation. Following a successful defence of two protesters against the international paper company, Scott (which produces Andrex). I was instructed to defend the protesters who were injuncted from protesting on and around Twyford Down between 1992 and 1993. I also prepared the defence to a claim for nearly 2 million by the Department of Transport which was aborted by the Department in 1995. The original case started with six defendants and expanded into a case with seventy six defendants. The injunction was fought on every point o domestic and European law. I prepared a case for the Court of Appeal for a member of a large trade union which was successful and important for protecting the right to protest. Two limbs of the injunction were discharged and the Department will shortly be paying costs.</P>
    <P>Throughout the Twyford campaign, the Lib Dems and the Labour party were active in their support for the protesters. Simon Hughes MP organised a successful press conference at the House of Commons, and MPs attended the Down to join the protesters. This high profile public support, including a debate in the House, was important for the campaign.</P>

    <H3>After Twyord - The Newbury Bypass</H3>
    <P>I was instructed to expose possible illegalities regarding the construction of the Newbury Bypass. Many people worked on this campaign. I exchanged correspondence with the European Commission and the government and at the end of 1994 the government was persuaded to conduct a review of the route. Protesters mistakenly thought they had won but that was far from the case. The road was back on the agenda by the end of June 1995 but the government was persuaded that the entire project had to be readvertised throughout Europe to satisfy the EC public procurement regulations. This was conceded and contracts were held up yet again for months.</P>
    <P>In January this year I successfully represented protesters from four camps in possession proceedings. Against counsel for the Department of Transport, I persuaded the junior Judge to adjourn the case to a full High Court Judge, thereby obtaining a significant breathing space for the protesters with their action. Regretfully, the first counsel instructed did not appear for the protesters. The case went ahead and was lost. I strongly advised against an appeal because experience has taught me when to recognise a fruitless effort. However, another team of lawyers went ahead with an appeal and lost. I consider this decision to have damaged the campaign although I can understand why other lawyers felt they wanted to contribute to such an important case.</P>
    <P>Of all the campaigns I have worked on, Newbury was the most fraught, disorganised and difficult I have encountered. The protesters did not pull together as a coherent group; many groups and indeed individuals had their own mini agendas which went in diverse directions and diffused energy in unproductive ways.</P>
    <P>The confusion amongst the Lib Dems was acute, for example. Here is a political party which has done some excellent environmental campaigning work on roads now being seen, in the form of the local MP David Rendell, to support roads policies associated with the Tories. Of course, there were valuable and sincere contributions from thousands of supporters and organisations. Friends of the Earth financed an office which was a vital nerve centre. There was financial support from groups like WWF UK and committed benefactors.</P>
    <P>But the energy came too late. The use of the law as a proactive and empowering tool was marginalised. The strength of the law relies upon well-planned early strategy. Environmental campaigning has to change, along with the courts and the politicians. There is a need for fresh ideas and more cohesive support which accommodates diversity of thought and expression but is firmly focused on the target for success. Early strategy may be seen as dull and lacking in heroic glamour but it has a higher success story. It is essential to respond in the early stages in planning law cases. Campaigns that win in a community have positive knock-on effects for years.</P>

    <H3>Skye Bridge</H3>
    <P>The benefits of a campaign for a community are illustrated in the current no toll Skye Bridge campaign. Clients from a group called Skye and Kyle against Tolls have asked me to advise on technical and European human rights issues. This time the Lib Dem MP, Charles Kennedy, is supporting the campaigners. So is the Highland Council.</P>
    <P>The tolls levied on the bridge, built through a public finance initiative (PFI), are so high that support for the protesters is drawn as far afield as the USA and New Zealand. I have been asked to comment on the case for the Wall Street Journal, amongst other papers. This contrasts with support in England which has thus far been poor. A return fare to cross the 570 metre bridge in the high season is 75.00; for an HGV class 2 vehicle, 50.80; for a car 10.40. This contrasts with other bridges throughout the UK, some of which are longer and far grander and which have been built by finance from the public purse, where there are no tolls, or toll tariffs which average less than 2.00 for a return journey.</P>
    <P>The government has issued summonses against 176 non payers and hundreds more have been charged. This is curious given that the government is prosecuting for a private company in an action which would normally attract a civil remedy for breach of contract. I believe this to be constitutionally unacceptable. On 17 April Sheriff Cameron openly pronounced in court in Inverness that these cases should never come before his court. Various defendants who were unrepresented pleaded guilty for personal reasons, not least the cost of travelling to a court over 130 miles away from Skye. He refused to fine or sentence the offenders although found them technically guilty of a criminal offence.</P>
    <P>This contrasted with a view of Sheriff Fraser at a trial I attended in Dingwall on 11 April. He refused to hear any European law arguments, deeming them irrelevant. He fined a Mr. Anderson a total of 150 for five offences and ordered that the fine be collected by 'civil diligence' - or forcible removal of goods, a practice frowned upon by the High Court in London. He also indicated that all other defendants who came before him would be dealt with on the same basis. He added that he intended to increase the fine if they re-offended after 11 April.</P>
    <P>I have been instructed to advise on the human rights issues regarding the infringement of the right to respect for private and family life and entitlement to a fair and public hearing by an independent and impartial tribunal. The toll affects families who live between the island and the mainland who are unable to see each other regularly because they cannot afford the tariff. The protesters have also been refused legal aid and, as described above, have been dealt with by a biased tribunal on at least one occasion.</P>
    <P>I also believe there has been a breach of the EU Council Directive 93/89 regarding the maximum charges that can be imposed on toll bridges. I am pursuing this with the Commission. These are points that can be run in court via a request that the Scottish court refers the case to the European Court of Justice for an interpretation on the meaning of the Directive on a preliminary point of law.</P>
    <P>PFIs are said to bring fundamental changes to the way in which the public sector procures infrastructure projects. The purpose is to transfer the financial risk to the private sector. Scotland is frequently used as a political and legal laboratory for new government experiments, the Skye Bridge being the first PFI experiment. A remarkably bad choice, since the island of Skye is in one of the most deprived economic areas in Europe. The protest should be alerting the public in England and Wales to future government plans for PFIs this side of the border. Significantly, the government has announced that all English PFI projects will be joint venture projects. Has it anticipated that the Skye scheme, which is a financially free standing project might just be unacceptable to the English?</P>

    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Liz Loughran</B></P>
    <P><I>Liz Loughran can be contacted at Solicitors Chambers, 169 Malden Road, London NW5 4HT; tel 0171 428 9544; fax 0171 916 2553. Initial inquiries on legal issues are free of charge.</I></P>

