<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 238 Commentary</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 238 Commentary</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>What A Waste</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P>It would be rather ironic if the Liberal Democrats having waited nearly 80 years for a share of government, and Labour having waited 18 years to be in government, accomplished nothing in the way of constitutional change.</P>
  <P>But that must be a risk from the increasing obsession of both parties with referenda on reforms.</P>
  <P>Tony Blair last month caved in to entirely predictable Tory pressure and committed himself to referenda in Scotland and Wales before devolution is put to parliament. Paddy Ashdown, unlike most Liberal Democrats, was conspicuous in his refusal to condemn Blair's about-face.</P>
  <P>It now seems that the Liberal Democrats are moving towards supporting a Labour government from outside, retaining an independence which full coalition would destroy. That is good news.</P>
  <P>But the price allegedly being demanded is yet another referendum, on electoral reform. This is worth having only if Labour will commit itself in advance to support and campaign for an acceptable new system.</P>
  <P>Otherwise, a referendum which saw the Liberal Democrats and some minor parties pitted against combined Labour/Tory opposition would be a catastrophe. It would bury the issue for a generation.</P>
  <P>It starts to look as if a Labour government supported by Liberal Democrats would devote its entire five years to organising referenda. Quite apart from the likelihood of one on the European single currency, we already have referenda in sight on Scotland, Wales and electoral reform, possibly on the House of Lords, and maybe the English regions.</P>
  <P>Given each of these issues will take up huge amounts of parliamentary time, and given also the government would have to run the country in its spare moments, there is a depressingly high risk that this approach would ensure that nothing was done. This would be particularly acute if this great wodge of referenda drifted on, becoming giant opinion polls on a Government facing mid-term blues.</P>
  <P>It is argued by some that a 'yes' vote would entrench each reform against future Tory meddling.</P>
  <P>This is rubbish. Were the Tories to win again (something which five years of perpetual voting and lack of concrete results would make more likely) they would be able to claim a general election mandate for whatever they had campaigned to do.</P>
  <P>There is only one way to entrench these reforms, and that brings us back to electoral reform. The fairest systems are those which would ensure there is a never a Tory majority, or any majority government again.</P>
  <P>But can Labour be made to realise that its current popularity is mainly the result of public disgust with Tory incompetence and corruption, and that the experience of the last 18 years suggests that, long-term, the present system is no more in Labour's interest than that of any non-Tory party?</P>
  <HR>
  <H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Tabloids Lose 1-0</H2>
  <P>Are the British, and particularly the English, as xenophobic as the tabloid press and Tory Euro-sceptics hope? This is the first <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> since the end of the Euro 96 football competition, and the first since the Government's climb-down from its ludicrous 'beef war'.</P>
  <P>These disparate events both suggest that the public is a good more sensible about Europe than many politicians are willing to credit. There was some disorder after key football matches, but nothing like the scale of violent nationalism feared beforehand.</P>
  <P>The Daily Mirror's odious 'soccer war' feature, far from appealing to its readers, damaged that paper's already battered reputation and public outrage forced a change of tone.</P>
  <P>Perhaps the far right-dominated Tory Eurosceptics, and SirJames Goldsmith's absurd Referendum Party, will find less fertile ground than they thought for their simplistic foreigner-hating.</P>
  <P>And so with the beef issue. Tory ministers raved about Brussels banning the export of beef products, even while Malcolm Rifkind was memorably unable to name a single country likely to wish to buy the stuff. European policies the Government might otherwise have supported were voted down, in the interests of tallow, gelatine and semen.</P>
  <P>The public, clearly, is less obsessed with semen than are the Tories. Nothing happened. The Tory poll rating remained obstinately where it was. The public knew perfectly well that BSE's cause is nothing to do with Brussels and everything to do with the Tories' dogmatic obsession with deregulation.</P>
  <P>There are dangers lurking in the Maastricht convergence criteria, but pro-European politicians need to take more risks to put their case. The public does not want to see Britain as a sweat-shop of ill-trained cheap labour for the rest of Europe, which is all the Eurosceptics offer.</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
