<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 238 Radical Bulletin</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG WIDTH=100% SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 238</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="../rb.gif">Radical Bulletin</H1>
  </CENTER>
  <H2><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="../rb2.gif">Two-Terms Of Endearment</H2>
  <P>A recent speculative piece in the Independent on Sunday about the likelihood of the Liberal Democrats offering Labour a '10-year partnership' had the fingerprints of Alan Leaman, LibDem strategy director, and leading Ashdown advisor.</P>
  <P>Since these leaks are the only way most ordinary Liberal Democrats get to know if they are being sold to Tony Blair, and for how much, it is worth putting in context.</P>
  <P>For those who missed it, 'a Liberal Democrat source' said the country needed at least 10 years of non-Conservative government, and that the Liberal Democrats would not bring down a Blair government, though they might vote against individual policies. The country does indeed need at least 10 years of non-Conservative government, though this rather invites the question of how the Liberal Democrats would set about fighting the mid-point general election - as Labour's formal partner or not? The piece even stated that Paddy Ashdown favoured a semi-formal partnership, rather than a 'full-bloodied coalition'.</P>
  <P>If so, this is a considerable advance. Full coalition would destroy the Liberal Democrats as an independent party, neuter their influence in a hung parliament once the coalition was signed, and give them mere trappings and baubles in return (which would, however, undoubtedly be enough for some people).</P>
  <P>But what would the Liberal Democrats want in return for a 'semi-formal partnership'?</P>
  <P>The answer given was a referendum on electoral reform (see <A HREF="comment.htm">Commentary</A>).</P>
  <P>Ashdown has become so enamoured with referenda that it is hard to see how he could back down from holding one, even though, by the mid-term of the next parliament, it might become a referendum on the government's popularity rather than on the issue itself.</P>
  <P>The IoS story also attributed to the 'Liberal Democrat source' the view that Blair would need 10 years 'to transform the country'.</P>
  <P>But can a leader who fudges and evades all questions about what he would do, and who forever takes refuge in motherhood and apple pie generalities, seriously be considered to be in the business of 'transformation'?</P>
  <P>If Labour is to be pushed into even the most modest reforms, the Liberal Democrats will have to be regularly prodding Blair with sharpened sticks, not with warm words.</P>
  <P>And there is little sign of that. It is an open secret that many very senior figures are worried that negotiations may be taking place about a post-election relationship with Labour, and that they, let alone the rest of the party, are being given only scant information on this.</P>
  <P>Some activists fear that a deal with Labour might presented to the party on a 'take it or leave it' basis straight after the election, with minimal time for consultation and precious little room for post-election negotiation.</P>
  <P>But could a deal be sold to the country which could not be sold to the party at large, or even to a changed post-election parliamentary party?</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Home Page" coords="32,2,4,23,1,56,85,56,81,25,56,22,33,2,33,3" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/index.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="The Collective" coords="88,40,91,59,138,59,144,47,118,1,101,0,96,39,89,39" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/Collective/Collective.html">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Read Liberator" coords="151,41,148,56,218,55,207,45,214,29,195,22,196,2,165,0,153,40" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/read.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Write for Liberator" coords="224,56,273,57,273,8,253,0,229,3,219,31,223,49" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/write.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Subscribe" coords="288,57,360,42,371,26,344,0,305,4,278,38" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/subs.htm">
