<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 238 Reviews</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 238 Reviews</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Fit to Govern?</H2>
   <H3>by Leo McKinstry<BR>Bantam Press, 12.99.</H3>
  </CENTER>
  <P>Former Islington Labour councillor McKinstry, having belatedly recognised the true nature of the Labour party, reviews its personalities, organisation, policies and record when in power, and concludes that Labour is not, in the words of the title, fit to govern this country.</P>
  <P>This is a critique from a particular perspective, namely that the 'new Labour/Blairite' line is basically sound, but that behind it, fatally, there lurks the loony left and the p.c. Thought Police. Reflecting McKinstry's own sudden conversion from convinced Socialist to conviction Conservative, there is an underlying assumption that market forces must reign supreme and any form of public spending or social regulation is a Bad Thing, of course, the dichotomy between the right wing policy and left wing ideology of Labour <I>is</I> a fatal flaw; but any Liberal must find the Daily Mail - style pronouncements of Blair, Straw et al, abhorrent in principle; and one almost finds oneself in sympathy with Labour left-wingers quoted here who disagree with them.</P>
  <P>But the book provides ample evidence to support its central theme - the awesome chasm between the words of the Blairistas and the words and actions of the rest of the Labour party. Few of the examples of hypocrisy, obfuscation double-dealing and veniality quoted in this book are new, but seldom can so many have been gathered together to such devastating effect. Scarcely any aspect of Labour's Programme for government is free from contradiction - spending pledges are unrelated to revenue-raising commitments, and the entire ethos of the party - as evidenced by its performance in local government - runs counter to every plank of the Blairite platform.</P>
  <P>Although clearly written and produced at some speed (and why the hell isn't there an index?) it is highly readable, topical and illuminated with some entertaining anecdotes. The sections on internal party groups and Labour party phraseology are especially recommended.</P>
  <P>The depressing thing about this book, however, is the thought that the moral putrefaction and monumental incompetence of the present Government are such that a majority of voters are likely to conclude that they are even less fit to govern than the subjects of this book. McKinstry's satisfaction will be to have been proved right; there won't be much comfort for the rest of us.</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Harry Lewis</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
