<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 238</TITLE>
  <META NAME="description" CONTENT="Liberator Article: Goya Covered - Revolutionary Liberalism fights its way back onto Liberator's cover. Stewart Rayment explains why">
  <META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="Liberator Liberal Democrats Radical Democracy Politics Political Magazine Green Liberty Equality Community Francisco Goya Art">
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 238</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Goya Covered</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P><B><I>Revolutionary Liberalism fights its way back onto Liberator's cover. Stewart Rayment explains why.</I></B></P>
  <HR WIDTH=50%>
  <P><B>Early in July the inquest on Srebrenica brought a flood of images back to our newspapers</B>, with tales of French/UN betrayal adding poignancy to the atrocities. The woman who hanged herself on hearing the news of the fall is particularly memorable.</P>
  <P>Why do these images keep coming before us? Will humanity never learn? Are not the memories of miseries enough? Are there not sufficient teachers to keep them to mind and hold our hands from such folly?.</P>
  <P>There are, too many even; but humanity never learns. Perhaps some of the finest and strongest examples are in the work of Francisco de Goya, born in Fuendetodos, Aragon in 1746, 250 years ago. He died in exile amongst fellow Liberales in Bordeaux in 1828.</P>
  <P>Apocryphally we are told that Goya began his drawings of the Peninsular War (1808-1814) the day after Napoleon's General Murat ordered shootings of civilians in reprisal for the rising of May 2nd in Madrid. A servant asked the artist, long established as the leading court painter of his day, 'Why do you paint these barbarities that men commit?". "To tell men that they should not be barbarians", Goya replied.</P>
  <P>The French revolutionary wars awakened Liberalism in much of Europe. Spain was no exception, but Napoleonic games meant something else, not least double dealing with the monarchy. Spanish Liberales, many of whom would have looked positively towards France, found themselves caught between an all too clear imperialism on the one side and their own ultra-conservatives, Holy Inquisition and all, on the other. Whilst putting themselves at the front of resistance to the French (with whom they might at first have worked) they could never been sure of when the priests might launch the rabble upon them. This ambivalence is captured in the Disasters.</P>
  <P>The war went backwards and forwards, neither side able to consolidate itself it seems; as civil war and guerrilla war as well as the conventional this is hardly surprising. Spain's erstwhile ally, Great Britain could prove as rapacious as the French, and the Duke of Wellington was predictably no friend of the Liberales. However the Constitution of 19th March 1812 is a bench mark in Liberalism and remained an inspiration into the revolutions of 1820 and 1836. This Constitution proclaimed the sovereignty of the nation and said that the people alone were entitled to enact the fundamental laws of the country. Its representative organ the Cortes, was to be elected every two years under universal manhood suffrage, without any property qualification. Rather ahead of its time in the European context. Circumstances favoured the return of progressives to the first Cortes and these grouped together as Liberales, the first such party to assume that name. Although not in the majority, with the aid of representatives from the Americas the Liberales were able to carry many constitutional measures, but lost on the economic front where the Americans tend to vote with the Serviles. At the end of the day it was the bayonet beside the monarchy which determined the issue.</P>
  <P>Aldous Huxley commenting during the Second World</P>
  <P>War wrote of the Disasters:</P>
  <BLOCKQUOTE>"War always weakens and often completely shatters the crust of customary decency which constitutes a civilisation. It is a thin crust at the best of times and beneath it lies - what? Look through Goya's Desastres to find out. The abyss of bestiality and diabolism and suffering seems almost bottomless. There is practically nothing of which human beings are not capable when war or revolution or anarchy gives them the necessary opportunity and excuse; and to their pain death alone imposes a limit... His concern is exclusively with war as it affects the civilian population, with armies disintegrated into individual thieves and ravishers, tormentors and executioners - and occasionally, when the guerilleros have won a skirmish, into individual victims tortured in their turn and savagely done to death by avengers of their own earlier atrocities".</BLOCKQUOTE></P>
  <P>Huxley is generally correct; maybe Agustina of Aragon, a solitary women firing a cannon at the siege of Saragossa speaks of glories, though its starkness decries them, even capturing the pathos of such heroism. A man of few words, Goya captions this 'What Courage'. Short pithy captions are the mark of the Disasters. 'Why', 'One can't look', 'Charity' - a mass grave, and so on. Such economy heightens the terror of the images. I have a feeling that Goya's black images are not the product of a deranged mind, especially the later Disasters and Capricios, but as deliberate and rational as any other of his works.</P>
  <P>Goya did not dare publish the Disasters in his lifetime. After the 1820 revolution he fled to France, an old man, deaf and losing his sight. The plates were entrusted to his friend, the Liberal publisher Bermudez and finally appeared in the 1860s. In the Nineteenth century the Romantic mind paled in terror before these images. Baudelaire and Huysmans were amongst there champions. They are one of the most potent icons of the inhumanity of humanity and an essential ingredient of everyone's education.</P>
  <P><I>Dover publishes Goya's engravings including Disasters of War, Disparates, La Tauromaquia and Goya Drawings</I></P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Stewart Rayment</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Home Page" coords="32,2,4,23,1,56,85,56,81,25,56,22,33,2,33,3" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/index.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="The Collective" coords="88,40,91,59,138,59,144,47,118,1,101,0,96,39,89,39" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/Collective/Collective.html">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Read Liberator" coords="151,41,148,56,218,55,207,45,214,29,195,22,196,2,165,0,153,40" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/read.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Write for Liberator" coords="224,56,273,57,273,8,253,0,229,3,219,31,223,49" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/write.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Subscribe" coords="288,57,360,42,371,26,344,0,305,4,278,38" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/subs.htm">
