<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 238</TITLE>
  <META NAME="description" CONTENT="Liberator Article: The Road to Peace - Kiron Reid looks at recent events in Northern Ireland">
  <META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="Liberator Liberal Democrats Radical Democracy Politics Political Magazine Green Liberty Equality Community Northern Ireland Sinn Fein Orangemen Terrorism">
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 238</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>The Road To Peace</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P><B><I>Kiron Reid looks at recent events in Northern Ireland.</I></B></P>
  <HR WIDTH=50%>
  <H3>Additional Powers</H3>
  <P>The Prevention of Terrorism (Additional Powers) Act was rushed through Parliament in one day, on Tuesday 2 April (or 24 hours and 47 minutes to be precise). In the House of Commons the allocation of time for the Bill was debated at 3.43 p.m., the Second Reading took place at 10.10 p.m., the Third Reading at 1.21 a.m. on Wednesday morning, and the Bill completed its passage through the House of Lords at 4.30 p.m. the same day. The Opposition acquiesced in the Bill being rushed through Parliament by the Government. The legislation allows the police to search clothing following the exercise of random stop and search powers, for which no reasonable grounds are required, and provides for searches of non-residential premises (such as a series of lock-up garages, or a lorry park) on a warrant issued by a justice of the peace. It also permits searches of any goods on accompanied or unaccompanied vehicles entering or leaving Great Britain or Northern Ireland, and provides a power to impose a police cordon and for the application of parking prohibitions and restrictions. The stop and search powers were the most controversial feature of the legislature, as potentially involving the greatest interference with individual liberty. But, due to the guillotine only Clause 1 of the Bill, on the stop and search powers, was actually considered by the House of Commons in Committee. One instance example of the problems of emergency legislation passed in haste.</P>
  <P>The 1996 Act was rushed through Parliament just two weeks after the renewal of the PTA itself. The political reasons for so doing have been a matter of fierce contention. One reason put forward was the approach of the 80th anniversary of the republican Easter Rising in Dublin in 1916. This led Earl Russell to comment "We are told that it is the 80th Anniversary of the Easter rising. I should exaggerate if I said that we have had 80 years' notice of that, but I should not exaggerate very much." (Lord Russell was described as 'infantile' by a not amused Earl Ferrers). It appears that the only reason the Bill can have been rushed through when it was, was to embarrass the Labour Party twice within two weeks, a trap which Jack Straw gleefully led the Labour Party into. It was noticeable that the most intelligent and comprehensive analysis of the legislation came from the Labour left, most notably former Northern Ireland spokesperson, Kevin McNamara. Both MPs and peers (including very effective contributions by Lord Rodgers) called for the legislation to be given full parliamentary scrutiny as soon as possible. The Liberal Democrats, to their credit, opposed the bill being rushed through Parliament, with Alan Beith and others strongly opposing the abuse of the Parliamentary process. However, as reported by Nick Brown in Liberator 237, the Liberal Democrats got their priorities entirely wrong - opposing the procedure, but not opposing the attacks on civil liberties. There may be very good reasons for some of the legislation, (such as the power to impose police cordons - so vital in saving lives in Manchester), there are equally certainly flaws in the legislation as well.</P>
  <H3><IMG SRC="ireland.jpg" ALIGN=RIGHT>Major Flop</H3>
  <P>The rushing through of the emergency legislation does more than embarrass Her Majesty's Opposition, or show up logical inconsistency in the Lib Dem approach to Liberty. It shows up far more fundamentally the washed up policy of the Government that must take a large part of the responsibility, in reality, for the end of the ceasefire. Nothing can justify the end of the ceasefire. Nothing can justify atrocities like the bombs in Manchester and at Canary Wharf. Most of all nothing can excuse a small band of terrorists shattering the hopes of millions of people in the north-eastern counties of Ireland. But the Government must take the political blame. The Government did nothing to dismantle emergency legislation throughout the months of ceasefire, but instead used the end of the ceasefire as an excuse to rush through even more draconian measures (that hadn't been required in the previous twenty years). The Government did nothing to show the terrorists that they were achieving anything through peace - no end to exclusion orders, painfully slow movement on the release of prisoners. Yes, many troops were removed and patrolling ended, a returning to normality for the people of the area, but more needed to be done. Whether this criminal idleness was due to some secret deal with the Ulster Unionists to shore up John Major's ailing majority, or whether it was just down to crass stupidity, we will never know. One thing, though, is certain. John Major's place in the history books was secure. Apart from a footnote for replacing Margaret Thatcher, John Major was assured an historic role in possibly bringing peace. Now he has thrown that away - the one really worthwhile thing he might have done - for being too cautious to take chances for the risk of peace. Even talks without preconditions should have been tried - for the sake of peace.</P>
  <P>Recent events in Portadown remind one of the astonishing and bigoted attitude of Unionist politicians. A year previously at Portadown - what was 'the Reverend' Ian Paisley's response to the ceasefire: to incite Orangemen to march and riot. Astounding. It is understandable that unionists felt threatened. The withdrawal of troops, while the Provisional IRA retained all its weapons, and the horrific terrorist 'punishment' attacks continued daily, must understandably have left many anxious. Unionist politicians, though, should have behaved responsibly.</P>
  <H3>Orangemen</H3>
  <P>Events at Portadown may appear bemusing to many outside people. Why the Orangemen want to march may appear something of a mystery. They may even appear somewhat harmless - like Morris men. After all, wanting to process down the street doesn't seem like much to ask. Many of their supporters made eloquent and reasonable sounding speeches about exercising their right to walk down the Queen's Highway. This might appear to be a demand to exercise a very basic civil liberty. But that is not the case when that 'right' has been used for well over a century - and throughout the years of the se8an Stormont Parliament -to demonstrate that Unionists were in control, and to show to Catholics that they were second class citizens in their own country. The marches have been used throughout this century to demonstrate Unionist domination, and to intimidate Catholic populations. This was affirmed by the decision of the Chief Constable of the RUC to hand over to the Orangemen at Drumcree. In stopping the march initially, and calling in the troops for backup, the Chief Constable must greatly have increased his force's credibility with nationalists. to then capitulate in response to Loyalist roadblocks and disorder, (and unknown possible political pressure) was a disaster. I am a fervent supporter of non-violent direct action - but what we saw in the 6 counties was the sinister underlying threat of violence and intimidation.</P>
  <P>It has been suggested that Catholics should in this day simply ignore the marches, and turn their backs (as indeed was done in one instance in Derry last year - orchestrated possibly by Sinn Fein). This would undoubtedly be a mature approach - to let the Orangemen march, surrounded by their history, and simply ignore them. (And leave the world asking why the men in bowler hats march - whether it be in Liverpool or Belfast). But it is very hard to ask people to do this when that history has been founded, in the not too distant past, on Protestant domination of Catholics. Once again Ireland seems bedeviled by its adherence to history. So what solution is there to the problem of the marches? Certainly not a policing one given the behaviour of the RUC. The only solution can be a community-based one - and that has to involve dialogue and compromise between both communities.</P>
  <H3>The Peace Process</H3>
  <P>So, what of the peace process? The Government has been dragging all along. The precondition on talks was a disgrace - they had a duty to talk if it might have stopped any violence. The rejection of the Mitchell report - a major propaganda boost for Provisional Sinn Fein (when Sinn Fein would have found it very difficult to accept the report anyway), forcing elections, which tells us no more than we knew anyway, and then barring one of the democratically elected parties. The 'peace process' may now be irretrievably broken down. Loyalist terrorists may or may not have been responsible (perhaps unofficially) for the murder of a Catholic taxi driver. A republican faction may or may not have been responsible for the bombing of a hotel in Enniskillen. If the Loyalist ceasefire is allowed to come to an end, that will be the greatest crime of the Prime Minister. The loyalists have held their ceasefire for 6 months after the PIRA resumed their murderous campaign (albeit not foolish enough to renew it in northern Ireland itseL9. I would never have a good word for Loyalist 'paramilitaries' with their indiscriminate and deadly incompetent trail of murder and killing, but the spokespeople of the loyalist fringe parties, Gary McMichael of the Ulster Democratic Party (linked to the UDA), and David Ervine of the Progressive Unionist Party (linked to the UVE3 and the real stars of the ceasefire. Both men have made a great impact with their reasoned speeches and constructive contributions to the process. Once the PIRA was ended, John Major should have made sure to hold the Loyalist ceasefire - by releasing loyalist prisoners. Prisoners are influential in the terrorist movements. Releases could have been made conditional, and always been revoked in the violence had been resumed. But loyalist prisoners should have been released. The Government can still do this. It can still also play the prisoner card to show willingness to Sinn Fein.</P>
  <H3>Sinn Fein</H3>
  <P>The Govemment's inactivity has been unforgivable, but they can still try and rectify their mistakes. It is in this spirit that the Government was right to meet the loyalist delegations at 10 Downing Street. Even, John Major was right to shake hands with the convicted murderer. There may be questions about why he has ever been released at all (likewise it is debatable whether terrorist murderers should be part of any 'political' releases), but given that he had, the Prime Minister was right to meet him. Reconciliation is needed all round. Else, in the words of David Ervine, Northern Ireland may be on the road 'to hell and back.'</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Kiron Reid</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Home Page" coords="32,2,4,23,1,56,85,56,81,25,56,22,33,2,33,3" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/index.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="The Collective" coords="88,40,91,59,138,59,144,47,118,1,101,0,96,39,89,39" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/Collective/Collective.html">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Read Liberator" coords="151,41,148,56,218,55,207,45,214,29,195,22,196,2,165,0,153,40" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/read.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Write for Liberator" coords="224,56,273,57,273,8,253,0,229,3,219,31,223,49" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/write.htm">
