<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 239 Commentary</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 239 Commentary</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Clear On Coalition</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P>Is there any less honest political project under way in Britain today than 'new' Labour?</P>
  <P>There are political projects which are more evil or misguided, but there is a peculiar brazenness about Labour's willingness to see what the opinion polls and tabloids are saying, and then meekly follow it.</P>
  <P>Liberal Democrat relations with Labour matter because key figures in the party have said and done enough to make the issue a live one for the media, but not enough to resolve it either for voters or their own somewhat bemused members.</P>
  <P>Sooner or later Tony Blair's attempt to fool all of the people all of the time will come unstuck. When it does, those identified with it will suffer at the public's hands.</P>
  <P>Trying to pin down what a 'new' Labour Britain would be like, is akin to wrestling with a jellyfish. Each time there appears to be something firm to hold onto, it slips away.</P>
  <P>Labour's commitments on social security benefits, pensions, rights at work, the future of the railways, and devolution have all been fudged out of meaningful existence.</P>
  <P>Labour refuses to say whether public spending will rise, while giving the vague impression that it will, but magically without any tax increases, (a subject on which the Liberal Democrats have been admirably honest). Its environmental policies are vague and of low priority.</P>
  <P>On civil liberties, Jack Straw's every utterance shows he would be as big a menace as is Michael Howard, arguable more so since defenders of civil liberties are at least on their guard when the Tories are in office.</P>
  <P>But hardly a week goes by without some hint about Liberal Democrats working with Labour in future, if not from Paddy Ashdown himself, then from 'senior sources. Most guilty of all are the old Jenkinsites whose continual praise of Labour goes without reprimand.</P>
  <P>It is an open secret that there is nervousness in parliament and among national officers that the Liberal Democrats will have a post-election deal with Labour sprung on them to take or leave. One problem is a generalised suspicion that something is going on, which has not been either answered or denied.</P>
  <P>The perception, true or otherwise, of the Liberal Democrats' stance towards Labour, will turn more votes, divert more campaigners' time and fill more of the airwaves than any issue of Liberal Democrat policy.</P>
  <P>Those  in authority who have kept raising this issue without resolving it can hardly now claim that it is all an invention by the media.</P>
  <P>At conference time last year, Liberator argued that the Liberal Democrats could sustain a Labour government in office, but only on issue-by-issue support, in return for clear concessions, and by retaining their own status outside government as an independent party.</P>
  <P>We argued that a formal coalition menaces the Liberal Democrats' ability to survive as a separate party because they would be linked inextricably with Labour. They would have  responsibility without power, forever having to threaten to destroy the coalition to exert any weight. Sadly, nothing has moved on, and this point must be made again.</P>
  <HR>
  <H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Postmen's Knockers</H2>
  <P>The world appeared to have turned upside down when the Liberal Democrats backed the postal workers' grievances in the summer, while Labour muttered and evaded when asked about its stance.</P>
  <P>But things have only reverted to a past in which Liberals were by no means as lukewarm towards trade unions as the Liberal Democrats have been, and Labour tried to stamp on any strike which might embarrass it electorally.</P>
  <P>The Liberal Democrats demand for the postal workers to share in their employers' profits was a welcome return of the Liberal principle of employees sharing in the fruits of their productivity. At this rate, the Liberal Democrats will start reviving the abandoned Liberal agenda of employee participation in management, and co-ownership, both ditched through a combination of fear, ignorance and hostility sometime in the Alliance era.</P>
  <P>The Post Office was a particularly good example to choose. Until the latest bout of strikes, which have anyway been managed from behind by the Government, it has been a standing reproach to those who insist that the private sector is always superior to the public sector.</P>
  <P>It has also been a reproach to those who use as their excuse for inaction on the continuing scandal of the utilities, the claim that "ownership does not matter". Which would most people say has been better run, the Post Office or British Gas? Which has served its customers better, the Post Office or the water companies?</P>
  <P>It was also cheering to see that one of the postal workers' objections was to trendy management fads, in this case under the name 'team working'. The 1990s employee knows that the slogans spouted by employers and politicians about 'empowerment', 'flatter structures', and 'business re-engineering' all mean job losses and harder work for the survivors, when translated into English. It is good to see one group of workers rebelling against this trend.</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
