<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 239 Radical Bulletin</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG WIDTH=100% SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 239</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="../rb.gif">Radical Bulletin</H1>
  </CENTER>
  <H2><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="../rb2.gif">Take Outrage</H2>
  <P>If the Liberal Democrats have any judgement they will find who dreamt up the Take Courage slogan, bind and gag them, and confine them to a dungeon until the general election is over.</P>
  <P>The slogan adorns conference agendas and supporting documents and, worst of all, is to form the backdrop for the conference podium. Its subtext 'for the future' is merely political clich.</P>
  <P>'Take Courage' is an even worse slogan than the infamous 'One More Heave' used in October 1974. That at least required a mildly warped turn of mind to extract the double meaning.</P>
  <P>As anyone old enough to have read or heard an advertisement during the last 30 years or so will know, 'Take Courage' was the slogan of Courage beers. As such, it became one of the best-known advertising slogans ever.</P>
  <P>Everyone we tried out the new LibDem slogan on, LibDem member or not, reacted with horrified disbelief, usually adding a remark to the effect of "you're joking" or "they must be mad", or even "they must have been drunk".</P>
  <P>But even if Take Courage were not a famous beer advertisement, it would still be a dire political slogan.</P>
  <P>The words Take Courage are ordinarily used as encouragement to someone about to undergo an ordeal, a risky medical operation, or a difficult examination, for example.</P>
  <P>The whole underlying message is, "a vote for the Liberal Democrats is a vote for policies which will be unpleasant and possibly dangerous, but for your own good if they succeed, so hold your nerve and vote for some necessary but nasty medicine."</P>
  <P>In how many key seats has the party's private polling identified statistically significant numbers of masochists among the electorate?</P>
  <P>Even more worrying for Liberal Democrat members should be the process by which this slogan was chosen.</P>
  <P>Members of the conference committee were not told about Take Courage until it was fixed in late July. Nor did the campaign committee know, nor more than a handful, it would appear, of the MPs.</P>
  <P>The conference communications committee, which brings together conference organisers, campaign organisers and the party's media specialists, first heard of it at its July meeting. It was received with general horror, but members were told they could not even discuss the matter.</P>
  <P>There followed a series of trenchant messages to Paddy Ashdown warning that adorning the conference with an old beer slogan would make his party look ridiculous and overshadow other conference business.</P>
  <P>By mid-August, ALDC members had started to attack the slogan on Cix, the LibDems electronic mail system. In less than a week, more than 100 derogatory messages were recorded.</P>
  <P>At this point, Paddy Ashdown felt obliged to reply. He admitted: "It could be made fun of because of connections with Courage Beer, though this is pretty old now and will be remembered best by, chiefly, men of a 'certain age'. This will no doubt amuse the sketch writers. But we are not speaking to the jaded press corps and political cognoscenti. We are speaking to the British people...the chief concern at the moment is to ensure that the public know what we stand for (not just policies but what kind of party we are and what role we can play. Distinctiveness is vital if we are to continue to resist the squeeze)."</P>
  <P>He went on to note concerns, "that we are saying subliminally that you must have courage to vote LibDem. Frankly, this risk was more of a worry. But we believe we can put it across in ways which don't indicate that".</P>
  <P>Ashdown then explained his thinking about the slogan's meaning, which we reproduce here in full. Further comment is unnecessary.</P>
  <P>"What is Take Courage For The Future: a reaffirmation of our commitment to a better Britain, and to the basic values of the British people; a statement of Liberal Democrat support for the instincts and patriotism of the British people; an expression of Liberal    Democrat self-confidence; a declaration of optimism for Britain and for the role of the Liberal Democrats; an encouragement to millions of people to take heart and to have the courage of their convictions with a vote for the Liberal Democrats; confirmation that Liberals Democrats are prepared to be open and clear about where they stand on key issues, that Liberal Democrats will be honest about the challenges that need to be dealt with.</P>
  <P>"What take Courage For The Future is not: not a challenge to the electorate to be either brave or foolhardy; not an incitement to Liberal Democrats to be left-wing; not a signal that Liberal Democrat policies are risky or frightening; not an endorsement of Courage bitter".</P>
  <P>Strange to relate, several months ago Lord Holme picked 'Take Courage' as his horse in LDYS' Night at the Races conference fund-raiser.</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
