<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 239</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 239</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Part Of The Unions?</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P><B><I>Liberal Democrats have been wrongly suspicious of trade unions. But if they looked, they would find union members are much like them, and that the Liberal Democrat Trade Unionists are preparing workplace campaigns, says ALDTU secretary Andrew Hudson.</I></B></P>
  <HR WIDTH=50%>
  <P>From the merger until the 1992 election, campaigning within the Liberal Democrats for a better understanding of trade unions was ALDTU's priority. While the party cannot be regarded as hostile towards trade unions, it could certainly have been accused of being agnostic towards them. The experience of ALDTU members on policy working parties was that many party members were unconvinced of the benefits of trade union membership. This may be due to the party hierarchy containing a large number of middle-class professionals who do not appreciate that, for many people, advancement comes largely through collective action. There are also some doubts about the compatibility of collective rights and individual rights.</P>
  <P>The first employment policy paper Citizens At Work demonstrated why ALDTU faced an uphill struggle. Worker participation schemes were regarded as a panacea which would make trade unions obsolete. This was followed by a Youth and Student Charter which contained quite a bit about animal rights but nothing about employment rights, and supported free market economics.</P>
  <P>These papers' errors of omission were followed by the notorious economics paper Economics For The Future, which committed the party to support decentralised pay bargaining and opposed minimum wage legislation.</P>
  <P>At Harrogate in 1992, ALDTU proposed a motion calling for a rethink of the party's approach to trade unions, and for a policy paper which looked again at decentralised bargaining and minimum wage legislation. It was passed overwhelmingly, despite some opposition from the federal policy committee.</P>
  <P>ALDTU was given representation on the resulting working group. It was able to play a key role in ensuring that the final draft was largely welcomed by the TUC. ALDTU had helped change the party's attitude to unions into a positive one.</P>
  <P>At the same time, a dtente was initiated between the party and the TUC, largely by the then employment spokesman Alex Carlile.</P>
  <P>In September 1994, the federal conference adopted the employment working group's paper Working For Change, which treated national wage bargaining with an open mind, as it did public sector pay. Conference also accepted minimum wage legislation through a minimum hourly rate determined by a Low Pay Commission.</P>
  <P>Tony Blair is one of our best allies with his hands-off approach to trade unions. Although we would not seek to replace Labour's union links with an equally incestuous alternative arrangement, we are now in a position where the TUC general secretary John Monks can admit that the Liberal Democrats have signed up to as much of the TUC's agenda as Labour has. Only the more blockheaded Labour supporters can really believe they are going to get any special favours for trade unions from a Blair-led Labour Party, whose leader appears not only to want to distance himself from the unions, but who seems to have no appreciation of the historical reasons which resulted in those links in the first place.</P>
  <P>There are, regrettably, still people in our party who see trade unions as alien entities best abandoned to Labour. Policy working groups still produce reports displaying an ignorance of trade unions.</P>
  <P>For example, the party's recent part-time workers' guarantee suggested that employers could implement the policy without waiting for legislation. A party that believes in empowering people should not seek to rely on the generosity of employers who have so far shown little sign of it on other issues.</P>
  <P>There is no conflict between trade union membership and individual rights. With the abolition of the closed shop, trade unions are voluntary organisations which can and do support individual rights.</P>
  <P>Working For Change correctly calls for a framework of employment rights; but there is a   vast difference between having rights enshrined in law and exercising those rights. Access to the law can be expensive.</P>
  <P>One of the great trade union success stories of the 1990s has been increasing amount of compensation won at tribunals for those injured at work.</P>
  <P>ALDTU's next tasks will be widening support for the Liberal Democrats within trade unions. To do this effectively it needs to reach a critical mass of members.</P>
  <P>Ironically, the average Liberal Democrat member is not all that different to the average trade unionist. Labour force surveys show that trade union membership is now strongest among professional and managerial workers. There are more trade unions affiliated to the TUC which are not also affiliated to Labour than are.</P>
  <P>The workplace is an area where liberals can participate in community politics through trade union activities. The shop steward is the local community activist campaigning, lobbying, representing their community in negotiations with the employer, and representing individuals by taking up casework.</P>
  <P>Union activity might particularly appeal to those in the public sector who suffer restrictions on their party political activity. Perhaps not surprisingly, the largest concentration of ALDTU members is in the public sector union Unison.</P>
  <P>With the increasing growth of the global economy, the trade union movement offers one of the few channels by which ordinary people can organise to counteract the multi-nationals. ALDTU will strive to raise within the party the plight of trade unionists in other parts of the world who are deprived of their basic rights. Judging by the debate on world trade in the party, this will not be a pushover.</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Andrew Hudson</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Home Page" coords="32,2,4,23,1,56,85,56,81,25,56,22,33,2,33,3" href="../index.htm">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="The Collective" coords="88,40,91,59,138,59,144,47,118,1,101,0,96,39,89,39" href="../Collective/Collective.html">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Read Liberator" coords="151,41,148,56,218,55,207,45,214,29,195,22,196,2,165,0,153,40" href="../read.htm">
