</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 239</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 239</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Greenery Or Community</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P><B><I>Tim Beaumont argues that Green Liberal Democrats need to determine whether they are environmentalists or ecologists</I></B></P>
  <HR WIDTH=50%>
  <P>It is common ground, I take it, among all Greens of whatever shade that we are embarked on a paradigm shift, in that the world has reached "The Limits of Growth" and must in future live sustainably or not live at all. And it is so much accepted that the Governments of the world have gone on record as accepting this, whether they really understood what they were saying or not.</P>
  <P>And it therefore is not surprising, given that we are in a paradigm shift, that all British political parties are in a turmoil even if the symptoms of some of their present schizophrenias do not appear to have an overtly green tinge.</P>
  <P>For instance, the present surface schizophrenia of the so-called Conservative party is about Europe, but the undergoing malaise goes back to the moment when Baldwin looked at the Backbenchers in the twenties and saw the rows of "hard-faced men who had done well out of the war". Those men (few women) provided the seedbed for the neo-Liberalism of Margaret Thatcher and Sir Keith Joseph and for the gradual but wholesale ousting of the squirearchy, the Gilmours, the Whitelaws and the Priors, to the House of Lords.</P>
  <P>That squirearchy, of whom my father was one, would have been able to adapt to "the sustainable revolution" particularly if they were, as they could have been, the ones who were sustained. The present party can probably not so adapt and its future is beyond the scope of this address and possibly of coherent prediction.</P>
  <P>The Labour party also suffers from schizophrenia. It was from the beginning rooted in an alliance between Trade Unionists who had not much time for ideology and ideologists who despised Trades Unionists, for much the same mix of social and ideological reasons that the Social Democrats despise the Liberals. Once again the present schizophrenia has not much to do with Greenery, being between pragmatists on the one hand and an unholy alliance of differing nostalgias on the other. Once again the old set up could have produced a viable Green movement, based on the dreams of William Morris and the practicality of Jesse Collings. Once again the wrong side lost, or to put it in suitably dialectical terms, both thesis and antithesis vanished and the synthesis has turned out to be incompatible with the realities of today.</P>
  <P>Confronted with a situation like this, the student of politics obviously looks for a similar schizophrenia in the Liberal Democrat Party. We can, I think, shrug off the most obvious recent place of fissure, the Liberal/Social Democrat alliance, where David Owen has expelled himself and the rest of the Social Democrats have, in my judgement, been slowly  ingested by the Liberals, like a boa-constrictor's lunch. No, once again we have to go back to an earlier situation to see the fault lines, back, even before Asquith/Lloyd George to a basic split between Whigs and Radicals where Whigs firmly represented the new manufacturing interests and Free Trade, which meant cheap food for the urban voter. And Radicals did not represent any distinct ideology but were, to their credit, seriously interested in democracy, which Whigs, when they thought of it at all, were against (which was why Disraeli was able to dish them).</P>
  <P>But the rebirth of the Liberal Party under Jo Grimond gave birth to a new eclectic Party which was ripe for Greenery. There were plenty, of whom I was not one, who saw that there was danger in this and who, like Michael Meadowcroft and Gordon Lishman, pleaded for a basic "Liberal Philosophy", but they, for reasons which I will not go into now, lost out and so the party has come happily blundering along into the situation which exists today where it really does not understand the seriousness of some of the problems which confront it.</P>
  <P>"What is the problem?", we ask. "We are all in favour of the countryside, and animals; The Green Pressure Groups give us good marks (with only slight reservations) and Sutton & Richmond and "that authority in the South-East with a new rather green name" win all  the awards for Green administration. Is not everything in the garden (which we will quickly create in some urban setting and win a commendation for) lovely?"</P>
  <P>And my answer to you is sadly: "No". And it will not be lovely until we have faced up to at least three important questions. The first is: "Are we Environmentalists or Ecologists?". The second follows directly on and involves facing up to the fact, so unpalatable to Liberals, that if we are ecologists, we have to be much more Protectionists than we are Free Traders, and the third means a lot of hard graft in working out a philosophy as to what power should reside at what level. The last will become very important in thinking at the international level but also rears its ugly head in matters like the Newbury and Salisbury bypasses.</P>
  <P>How does it happen that a group of Liberal Democrat councillors and a Liberal Democrat MP can end up being reviled by all the Greens with whom we are allied? Matthew Taylor, I think put his finger on how it happened. A group of people who know all about NIMBY, did not recognise the related disease OIMBY (Only In My Back Yard: i.e. we are against building roads and will oppose other peoples bypasses to the death if they are environmentally damaging, but this is a special case and it is a special case because the people concerned say that it is a special case.) In other words Greenery meets Community Politics: which is the most important? At what level do we seek to give power in what kind of cases. And that is one area which we in GLD should explore.</P>
  <P>And it is an example which impinges on the first question which I posed. Are we Ecological or Environmental? Have we  faced up to the fact that if we are to produce sustainable energy, we may have to have windfarms on the skyline of the Chilterns? Have we faced up to the fact that if we are to create an ecologically sustainable life for our overpopulated country  we will probably have to repopulate the countryside and in the process destroy most of what the Council for the Preservation of Rural England stands for. As far as the CPRE are concerned the Enclosures and the Clearings were doubtless regrettable, but they feel that we must start from where we are, must we not? After all, no one is trying to repopulate Germany with Jews!</P>
  <P>Have we faced up to the fact that our ecological footprint (the area of land which is needed to support us in the style to which we are accustomed) is much larger than the British Isles and that therefore we are, in the words R H Tawney applied to the rich, "a small class which wears several men's clothes, eats several men's dinners, occupies several families' houses and lives several men's lives"? Have we faced up to the fact that not only is Free Trade probably disastrous for the poorer classes in all except the richest countries, as Herman Daly, Oxfam, Christian Aid and probably all ecologists except Duncan Brack will agree, but also that any Trade at all is probably not a very good thing. "It is not true" as Chesterton pointed out, "that the most obvious thing for a man who has plucked an apple from an apple tree is to put it on a train and send it to the opposite side of England. The most obvious thing is to put it in his mouth." The most obvious place for supermarkets in the Vale of Evesham to get asparagus is from the Vale of Evesham but classical economics ensures that they only stock asparagus from Spain, with all the traffic and pollution that that involves.</P>
  <P>Above all have we faced up to the fact that the practical implications of ecological facts are that we have to become a party which will tell people not only that they are going to get poorer but that also that it is right that they should and morally wrong to do anything else (although we may correctly but confusingly add that everyone must become wealthy).</P>
  <P>To say that this is impossible for a party is not just to give up any hope of achieving a world which will be anything but a monstrous slum by the time our grandchildren are grown up, it is also to tell a lie because those of us who are old enough have lived through a time when those who governed us told us just that and were applauded for it. The causes of the defeat of the Tory party in 1945 were not to be found in wartime austerity, they were to be found in the classical economics of the thirties.</P>
  <P>But if we are to learn anything from that immensely important precedent, we must look at some of the things which made it work.</P>
  <P>Firstly, it could not have worked if the gap between rich and poor had not diminished and that means cropping the riches of the rich and diminishing the poorness of the poor in  order to achieve wealth for all.</P>
  <P>Secondly it could not have worked without a serious restriction of civil liberties. This does not mean that we have all got to become eco-fascists, appoint Jimmy Goldsmith as Dictator and bring in mass abortions like the Chinese. (We should note that the Socialist state of Kerala in India reduced its birthrate from a figure higher than China's to a figure lower than China's over the same period of time by purely democratic means.) But it will involve a move away from Libertarian Liberalism towards Community Liberalism, another subject which I commend to Liberal intellectuals for study. In rural terms for instance it means that we can campaign hard for granting access while rejecting "right to roam". The second will become more and more unthinkable as we use more and more of the countryside for intensive small scale farming as the demand for food increases (reference Worldwatch document Who will feed China? or even the "Foreign Affairs" reply, "Who will feed Africa?).</P>
  <P>Thirdly it involved people realising that the alternative to taking these steps was unacceptable and therefore making sure that all political parties co-operated in the task.</P>
  <P>And fourthly it involved people thinking that there was light at the end of the tunnel. But this time we are not going to offer a return to "normality"; we are going to have to offer a complete paradigm change from the quantitative heaven of the capitalist system to the qualitatively pleasurable human life offered by all the great religions and philosophers.</P>
  <P>It will not be easy; nothing is more daunting than a paradigm change seen in advance; but I suspect that it is not desperately painful in the process because if it is a true paradigm change, it is inevitable and therefore self-reinforcing. It is also a matter not so much of organisation and Shuttleworth, though I would be the last to pan that approach as of education and evangelism. and that surely is the game that the Liberal Democrat Greens are involved in.</P>
  <P>In any case I do not regard the prospect as any worse than I faced as a young Liberal on the morning after the 1950 election. "Who'll come a losing deposits with me?"  And, look we have come through!</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Tim Beaumont</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
