<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 240 Commentary</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 240 Commentary</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Sleazy Does It</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P>The eruptions of Tory sleaze during October provide not only copious reasons for a change of government, but for a change to the system of government.</P>
  <P>Supporters of constitutional reform have always been thwarted by public indifference. The public disgust with the revelations of the Hamilton/ Greer affair offers about the best climate possible to raise these issues, because the allegations go right to the heart of what is wrong the UK's governance.</P>
  <P>As Lord Russell set out in <A HREF="../239/index.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> 239</A>, the UK's government is now more centralised, and the theoretical separation of powers less effective, even than in the eighteenth century.</P>
  <P>Long-term one-party government, and a lack of effective checks on the limits of Cabinet power, create a climate in which corruption not only can flourish, but is almost certain to.</P>
  <P>One feature of British smugness has been the fond belief that the British system of government is the best yet devised, and that only benighted continentals suffer from legislators taking brown envelopes stuffed with banknotes, businesses buying favours and government obstruction of investigations in allegations of wrongdoing.</P>
  <P>Britain, it would appear, now has the lot. And the Tories, far from being shamed, are engaged in a damage limitation exercise.</P>
  <P>It is worth noting that sleaze allegations have come to light not because of parliamentary activity or any mechanism within the system, but through journalistic investigation. This ought to give pause to those who want to restrict the media in the name of privacy.</P>
  <P>John Major aspires to an image as an honest man of the people. Personally honest he no doubt is, but he leads the most corrupt government since the 1832 Reform Act.</P>
  <P>While it is still true that very few British civil servants or local government officials can be directly bribed, the corruption of the Major years takes a more insidious form.</P>
  <P>Powers have been removed from democratically-elected bodies and transferred to quangos stuffed with Tory supporters. The claim that secret donations to Tory funds are merely coincidental to this is now believed by no-one. Similarly disbelieved are Tory claims that Government favour, and the use or not of regulatory powers, is unrelated to party patronage.</P>
  <P>There have been perfectly respectable arguments advanced in the past against a Bill of Rights and a written constitution, based on the contention that these allow people to do only what is permitted, rather than forbidding them to do only what is prohibited. But the unwritten constitution also allows a Government with a majority to do anything it pleases; reverses in the courts are overturned, censure in investigations ignored.</P>
  <P>The unwritten constitution worked only as long as all political parties, the executive and the judiciary accepted their place within the system and played by its rules. It proved a broken reed as soon as a governing party was prepared to centralise powers for itself, put its supporters in charge of most public institutions and sell the remainder to fat cats, and put the favours and privileges flowing from those powers up for sale.</P>
  <P>Similarly long-term unchallenged rule by any  party would probably come to the same thing. The voting system, non-existent constitutional restraints and non-functioning checks and balances that made the current scandals possible all need fundamental change.</P>
  <P>The Tories' response will be to try to tar all politicians with the brush of corruption. The only way to avoid public disgust with the Tories from engulfing every serious party is for other parties to make it clear that they will tackle the problem at its root.</P>
  <P>One side effect of the affair has been to make the Tory Euro-sceptics look ridiculous.</P>
  <P>Unlike Liberal Democrat or Liberal critics of the Maastricht process, the Tory argument has been that the British parliament is perfect, and must be defended from foreigners. How many people are likely to be moved to defend a system and institutions so obviously decayed and inadequate?</P>
  <P>Some government supporters appear as willing to be bought as their Italian counterparts, and the Tories' stubborn attachment to the fiction of self-regulation makes the  investigatory processes here actually less effective than are Italy's magistrates.</P>
  <P>The whole affair poses grave risks for the democratic process, because public revulsion is liable to spread from those deserving of it to the whole of politics. But it does offer an   unusual chance to find an audience for constitutional reform.</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
