<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 240 Radical Bulletin</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG WIDTH=100% SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 240</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="../rb.gif">Radical Bulletin</H1>
  </CENTER>
  <H2><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="../rb2.gif">The Shape Of Things To Come?</H2>
  <P>Once again Lib-Labbery was the issue which dared not speak its name at the Liberal Democrat conference. The formal agenda was devoted to many doubtless important matters, but not the question of whether the party ends up making a deal with Labour.</P>
  <P>Not that it was ignored. The issue was discussed at fringe meetings, in bars and on the seafront. Everywhere, in fact, where ordinary party members' views would attract little attention.</P>
  <P>The party leadership has at least dropped the fiction that speculation about these links is a perfidious invention of the media to distract attention from party policy.</P>
  <P>That stance became untenable because the issue is well-known to be causing ill-feeling in the parliamentary party, rows in federal committees, and a general atmosphere of mistrust.</P>
  <P>The issues in dispute over post-election deals with Labour are well-known and have been well-aired.</P>
  <P>What is causing problems now is the deepening suspicion that this deal already exists in outline and that, if the parliamentary arithmetic works, it will be sprung on the party immediately after the next election.</P>
  <P>Those privy to LibDem/Lab discussions are thought to amount only to Paddy Ashdown himself (and therefore also almost certainly his ever-present aide Alan Leaman), Lord Holme, and, maybe, Menzies Campbell, the latter one of very few MPs to view taking posts in a Labour-led government with enthusiasm.</P>
  <P>With no clear statement from Ashdown himself on what is going on, suspicion has grown. There is discreet head-counting in progress on both sides among the MPs likely to be returned and PPCs most likely to join them. That head counting will probably turn to arm-twisting and carrot-dangling.</P>
  <P>One leading party officer said that Ashdown's attitude was one of: "I am engaged in sensitive and delicate high politics, stop interfering and it will all turn out alright."</P>
  <P>There have been few denials of media speculation about the increasing closeness between the parties. And Lord Jenkins has been remained as leader in the Lords, despite allowing himself to be repeatedly described in public as one of Tony Blair's advisers.</P>
  <P>But what of Alex Carlile and his curious musings about a long-term merger of the LibDems and Labour into one anti-Tory party?</P>
  <P>These were aired on television just as the conference began, and a few days after Carlile had written a highly sceptical article about 'new' Labour in the Guardian. Whichever way round his recording of the interview and writing of the article happened, Carlile must have thought that they would be widely seen as contradictory.</P>
  <P>He must also have known that his musings about Labour links in general and merger in particular would make him highly unpopular with a large part of the conference, while handing the media on a plate a story about internal controversy.</P>
  <P>Was he just thinking out loud rather unwisely? It is possible, but unlikely given that Carlile is an experienced politician not given to hasty statements. There was speculation at conference that Ashdown encouraged him to air these views to test reaction. This can never be proved. But if Ashdown wanted to fly such a kite, he could hardly do so himself.</P>
  <P>Carlile's remarks annoyed a number of activists who have seats to fight where being seen as close to Labour is a serious vote-loser.</P>
  <P>This latter factor has thrown up some surprising Labour-sceptics.</P>
  <P>One might expect ex-SDP members to be enthusiasts for links with Labour. But Robert Maclennan is well-known not to be. And Charles Kennedy's new line 'the allies of change, not the allies of Labour' went down well at Brighton.</P>
  <P>The case of Shirley Williams was more startling. Her end-of-conference speech was overall pro-Labour, stressing that that party was vital to any future anti-Tory government.</P>
  <P>But when she got to the bit about not sacrificing LibDem ideals for a few ministerial posts, she was suddenly cheered long and loud.</P>
  <P>Williams looked astonished. Ashdown looked horrified at the conference's clear expression of hostility to Labour. If not allowed a debate, they would, it seemed, vote  with their applause. But members of the Ashdown circle were suddenly not applauding and looked glum. If this was kite flying too, the response was clear.</P>
  <P>The atmosphere of the conference had been made yet more febrile by Ashdown's New Statesman interview in the preceding week. In this he appeared to imply that PR was no longer a precondition for working with other parties, and that he wished to work with Labour even if it has an outright majority.</P>
  <P>So what would happen if an attempt is made to hussle the LibDems into bed with Labour a few days after the next election?</P>
  <P>Blair could not delay announcing his cabinet more than three days or so. Thus an immediate decision would be needed on any LibDem membership of it. The 'Fred' (fast response, early decision) party consultation mechanism should be in place.</P>
  <P>But the only body which will really count will be the new parliamentary party.</P>
  <P>This is where the head-counting, arm-twisting and carrot-dangling will get serious.  Will new MPs who have just fought against Labour be willing to support them, let alone coalesce? Will the returned MPs be in any mood to do likewise? Will those likely to prove awkward be brought off with junior ministerial posts?</P>
  <P>Only the MPs can stop any deal which appears inadequate, inequitable, and/or liable to jeopardise the Liberal Democrats' ability to function as a successful independent party.</P>
  <P>That raises another intriguing scenario. If the MPs, presented with a deal, said "no", could Ashdown remain as leader?</P>
  <P>The party conference will count for nothing. There is bound to be a special conference because it would not be difficult to get the signatures to call it, though Ashdown would probably call it himself to control the agenda and gain an endorsement.</P>
  <P>But it could not in practice meet for some weeks, and could it vote down any deal? Just imagine the speech that, purely by way of example, Campbell might make:</P>
  <P>"I am the first Liberal minister since Lloyd George's time. Through me, you, conference, are wielding real power. I am implementing vital parts of the manifesto we have all just fought on. Are you really telling me that I and my colleagues must return to the impotence of the opposition benches from which we have only just escaped?"</P>
  <P>The leadership line would probably carry by a huge margin. It is likely to encounter less difficulty, either immediately post-election or later, if Labour lacks an overall majority. It is working with a majority Labour government which would sooner or later threaten the LibDems' cohesion.</P>
  <P>The root of the problem is that enough has been said about LibDem/Lab links for everyone to suspect they are happening, but not enough to explain the reasoning, win hearts and minds, or allay fears.</P>
  <P>This mirrors of what has happened to Labour.</P>
  <P>The old Labour Party has been bullied into Blairism because of its desperation to win. But Blairism is indisputably a top-down project in the Labour Party. Working with Labour in government is similarly a top-down project in the LibDems.</P>
  <P>The whole thing driven by elites talking to each other, confident that dislike of the Tories will be enough to allow them their way.</P>
  <P>This approach is dangerous if a deal is done and the resulting government hits trouble.</P>
  <P>Guardian writer Martin Kettle, an open Blair supporter, said in his column it was: "worrying from a Blairite point of view that he [Blair] is so disdained in LibDem circles." He had earlier noted that it had proved almost impossible to find anyone at Brighton with a good word for the Labour leader, even among those favorably disposed to Labour generally. Blair was seen, "as an unacceptably rightwing trimmer." Well, quite.</P>
  <P>And it seems things are no better in Labour. Kettle said he "very rarely" meets people who are inspired by Blairism, and noted that the spontaneous reaction to mention of Blair's name was more often disappointment than enthusiasm.</P>
  <P>Blair may be popular now, but then anyone prepared to push the populist buttons while avoiding specific commitments could hardly fail to be popular against a corrupt and crumbling Tory government.</P>
  <P>When even a commentator as sympathetic as Kettle can note: "Blairism appears like an  army with plenty of officers and rather few soldiers", it is time for the Liberal Democrats   to think hard about how close they want their officers to drag them to this phantom army.</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
