<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 240 Reviews</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 240 Reviews</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Kemp: The Road To Crecy</H2>
   <H3>by Daniel Hall<BR>Orion 1996.</H3>
  </CENTER>
  <P>No, not the adventures of Richard Kemp, Liberal Democrat standard bearer in the key target seat of Liverpool Wavertree (although we are told that 'Kemp' is from a Middle English word meaning champion, which must bode well for Richard): this is the story of Martin Kemp, our hero the creation of bright young author Daniel Hall.</P>
  <P>Historical fiction with the swashbuckling style of Ivanhoe<D> or Lorna Dorne<D>, or Kidnapped<D>, The Road to Crecy<D> combines the violently realistic battle scenes of Braveheart, with strict historical accuracy that movies have glaringly lacked. Kemp is a novel of the Hundred Years' War, and tells the story of Edward III's march across northern France, with brutal relish. From the dramatic stag hunt of the opening scene, this novel grabs one's attention and holds it throughout. The hero Martin Kemp, a cocky and fairly unsympathetic villien in a village near Leicester, is developed swiftly into more heroic (if initially naive) mould, following tales of King Arthur in his bid to be recognised as equal to any man, and to win the hand of beautiful daughter, Beatrice, of nasty knight Sir John Beaumont. Framed by Beaumont for rape and murder, abandoned in an antiquated and unfair legal system, Kemp is reprieved to join the campaign in France against Philip of Valois. With his longbow our hero departs for his shock awakening that war is far from the childhood tales of chivalry.</P>
  <P>"I wanted to explode the myths of medieval romance and chivalry" Hall has explained. "This is the Hundred Years' War as it really was - dirty, brutal and savage - seen through the eyes of a common archer." A key to the success of this book is its historical accuracy,  Hall putting his background as a history graduate to good use, and even taking archery lessons to get his detail right. We will all recognise influences, borrowed scenes, and stereotypes: the band of companions that Kemp joins become firm friends; the cheery prisoner joking with Martin on their way to the gallows and the unexpected reprieve; the affable Welsh archers who save Martin's life; and firm but fair Sir Thomas Holland and his Sergeant, Preston. And at times Kemp - refreshingly - verges on being the anti-hero that we all love - even burning enemies alive, and wielding a dagger to excess. At 16.99 this is excellent value for a well produced hardback novel, and a must for the Autumn.</P>
  <P>This is an excellent first book for author Daniel Hall, and I look forward to the next in the series. (I am sure we will hear more of Martin Kemp). Hall is well known politically (oft spotted in the bar at Brighton), having been Deputy President of Leicester University Students' Union (with fellow sabbatical one top Lib Dem campaigner Neil Fawcett), and is now political assistant to the Liberal Democrats running new authority South Gloucestershire, under former ALC Secretary, Chris Willmore. Candidates' Mailings suggest that candidates should find time to relax during the campaign. That is good advice for any activist - this is the book to buy to do it.</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Kiron Reid</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
