<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 240</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 240</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Anti-Gun Campaign Holds Mps At Gunpoint</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P><B><I>Public demand for a ban on hand guns has been headline news since the appalling events in Dunblane last March. Gina Buckley welcomes the prospect of a total ban, but wonders whether this is really the way to  change the law?</I></B></P>
  <HR WIDTH=50%>
  <P>Speaking in 'On the Record' on October 20th  Paddy Ashdown made the point that our parliamentarians needed to avoid being bounced into a decision on the handgun ban for the wrong reasons. He and other MPs have been criticised over the summer for declaring their intention to keep an open mind about the ban until Lord Cullen's report was published.</P>
  <P>But, is a ban, introduced under these circumstances demonstrating representative government at work?  The point that seems largely to have been lost in all the media coverage of this issue is that our MPs are elected to make decisions which they believe are in the best interests of their constituents and the country, not merely to reflect public opinion on contentious issues. Although personally anti-gun, it is my view that any decision for an outright ban, would be better if  taken for the right reasons, and not just seem to be an attempt to maintain our share of  the popular vote/curry favour with the tabloids.</P>
  <P>Liberalism recognises that an individual's liberty may have to be curtailed for the benefit of society in general. But I admit to having difficulty reconciling my wish to see handguns banned with the rights of gun club members to pursue what has until now been a legitimate sporting interest, especially when the legislation to bring this about is rushed through.</P>
  <P>Having said that, there seems to be no way that it makes sense for the LibDems to prop up the Tories on this issue - in fact given the overwhelming expression of public opinion over the last few months, and that the Government have already moved beyond Lord Cullen's recommendations - it's hard to see how it could be anything other than a disaster for our Parliamentary Party to back the Tories' position and hold out against the total ban demanded by Labour.</P>
  <P>Bizarre as it feels to find oneself agreeing with David Mellor, I believe he was right to say that the tragedy in Dunblane was a 'defining moment' for the citizens of Britain. 'Ordinary' people have not had a tradition of carrying guns and we have been justifiably proud that our Police Force do not all carry handguns as a matter of course. A total ban is, therefore, a logical step on from this position.</P>
  <P>But, assuming that the vote goes in favour of a total ban, it raises the disturbing point about whether Parliament acceding to this kind of public reaction is akin to giving in to the bring back hanging lobby. What next? Will the tabloids whip up a mass campaign for the castration of sex offenders or chopping off the hands of thieves?</P>
  <P>The Snowdrop campaign showed how effective the mass of public opinion can be in bringing about radical change. So should we be using this as a springboard to demand sweeping changes in other areas that affect our lives?  Our use of motor vehicles perhaps? After all, although they are not purpose built instruments of destruction, speeding vehicles and their exhaust gases harm far more children each day than were murdered in Dunblane?</P>
  <P>Don't get me wrong. I have no wish to be cynical or callous about the loss felt by the bereaved parents and the whole community of Dunblane. Rather I am asking, is this a sign that the public at large are prepared to declare, on a number of issues, that 'enough is enough' and that the benefit to the many is worth the sacrifice of the few? Is this the strongest indication yet that the way forward is to be determined outside the old party political structures and by 'single issue' campaigners?</P>
  <P>If that is the case then we must ensure that liberal principles are at the root of such campaigns. We should also make sure that our elected representatives are allowed to  legislate on our behalf and not be pushed into a haphazard new system of 'government by public opinion, as interpreted by the mass media'.</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Gina Buckley</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
    <area shape="polygon" alt="Home Page" coords="32,2,4,23,1,56,85,56,81,25,56,22,33,2,33,3" href="../index.htm">
