<DOCNO>WT10-B35-168</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA030-000642-B046-29</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.liberator.org.uk:80/240/2.htm 194.207.26.203 19970122142412 text/html 10729
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 22 Jan 1997 14:23:45 GMT
Server: Apache/0.8.10
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 10556
Last-modified: Mon, 20 Jan 1997 20:21:33 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 240</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 240</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>A Dog's Tale</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P><B><I>Bill Le Breton is seeking Liberal Democrats who share his concern about deals with Labour to sign a declaration of the party's independence. He was looking for the right words, when a dog came to the rescue.</I></B></P>
  <HR WIDTH=50%>
  <I>
   <P>I left Brighton feeling that representatives had been disenfranchised.</P>
   <P>For some time now I have considered that we as a Party needed to sign up to a declaration. The form here is but perhaps a hesitant start in what should be a debate amongst the assembled Party.</P>
   <P>I want also to thrust a lightning pole into the ground which might attract and maximise the energy that exists; to rally a faction into action - a large faction. I do worry that three or four late middle aged male suits are looking to the Party at the next election, to propel them into office. I believe that this is anathema to the rest of us, totally the wrong tactic for the Party and an elitist rather than a democratic goal.</P>
   <P>A show of the utmost strength is required to prevent them getting their way.</P>
   <P>My mind was, however, finally made up when, on returning from Brighton I found my ancient and beloved terrier missing. In his old basket, under the piles of blankets and old FOCUS leaflets that once kept him warm, I found the attached much stained manuscript:</P>
  </I>
  <P>He woke to the sound of the alarm, opened an eye and, glimpsing over the top of his basket, saw his master hit the switch on the radio/teasmade/personal computer/alarm clock. He cocked a single canine ear.</P>
  <P>"The Liberal Democrats have today backed a Labour campaign to ban electric tooth brushes," intoned the announcer. "A spokesperson for the Party said that this did not necessarily mean that it was doing so for the same reasons as Labour."</P>
  <P>A thin voice from 'down the line' patched in, "The Party takes a strong moral stance on this issue. It's all about helping individuals to help themselves. Electric tooth brushes, even with a circular action, can be a danger to the public good."</P>
  <P>Struth, he badly needed a drink. So, stretching a long stretch he stepped out of his basket. With a flick of his nose he pushed wide the bedroom door and padded down the stairs, a large tumour dangling uncomfortably between his elderly hind legs.</P>
  <P>When this abomination had been just a tiny lump his master had meant to take him to the vet. But a by-election to win or a Focus to deliver or an ALC conference to attend had one after the other delayed and delayed the visit. The tumour had continued to grow beneath his skin.</P>
  <P>In the kitchen his claws skated over the tiled floor to a water bowl marked "SALLY". As a white haired Welsh Terrier puppy, his owner, George Oliver Forth, had humorously dubbed him Algy. "Because of his likeness to a certain Liberal Prime Minister," George would guffaw to those gathered in his front room for branch meetings.</P>
  <P>When George married seven years ago, his wife insisted Algy's name be changed to Sally. It was very nearly a lot worse.</P>
  <P>Still uneasy about the change he dipped his nose distastefully into the vile bowl and slurped loudly.</P>
  <P>Time to check the Pee-mail he concluded and looked into the hall where a bundle of newspapers were piled beneath a table. "Liberal Democrats GO Forth," the banner headline yelled. "Local candidate chosen AGAIN." In outrageous mustard ink the strap line read, "Liberal Democrats for Safe and Sound Government in a Changing Global Village Makes Common Sense FIRST."</P>
  <P>"Safe and Sound" - that was the Party's new 'fits anything' slogan.</P>
  <P>He could hear his master at the top of the stairs explaining on the telephone the latest development to an editor. "No, this doesn't mean we're in coalition with Labour. We're fundamentally different. We're tougher on Tax for one thing and we want to reduce welfare spending."</P>
  <P>"Not knowingly left of Labour" - that was the Party's new 'safeguards everything' strategy.</P>
  <P>Groaning, he slid through a large hole in the rotting paint-peeled front door and sniffed the morning air. The garden was a disaster since 'she' had arrived. A lifetime's collection of printers, plate makers and folding machines had been thrown out of the house to rust in the borders. "We don't need these," she had declared after the honeymoon. "We can use the media to talk directly at the people. That's the modern way."</P>
  <P>He leapt the garden wall clipping his tumour painfully as he did so. When eventually George had taken him to the vet, they had been told that it was now too late, there was nothing that could be done. He was a victim of George's continual mindless activism, of George's readiness to compromise for short term benefit, of George's trust that it would all work out for the best.</P>
  <P>Across the pavement was his tree. He sniffed the Pee-mail. His tumour, still vibrating from the impact, made him blink. Cocking his leg he greeted his world. "Yo! It is a dog's life!"</P>
  <P>There had been a long gossipy message from the dark curly haired Scottie, the remnants of something wise from the red setter who lived across the valley, Dick from the city centre had left his fleeting mark and Cheggers had obviously slashed by - he was seldom seen these days since the operation had left him a consultant.</P>
  <P>And there was something decidedly strong and long from the Irish setter with the impeccable street fighting pedigree. His had drenched most of the other messages off the bark. "You lot always need someone to blame. You didn't like 'When you need courage drink a pint of Liberal Democracy' now the lot of you are grumbling about the Safe and Sound theme. I'll have you know that polling of lampposts and railings in Islington shows it's going down rather well."</P>
  <P>Back in the house George was still on the dog and bone. "Off the record," he went on, "We've painted ourselves into a bit of a corner. There's only a Labour spending list between us. 99% of the policy is identical. How could we vote against their Queen's Speech?"</P>
  <P>"Well, who walked into the corner in the first place?" Sally wondered as he slipped into the front room where all was as usual. The curtains were drawn, the computer purred like a happy cat and the light from the VDU coloured everything a drab blue. He walked between stacks of old Guardians, piles of Radical Bulletins and tottering mounds of Servile State pamphlets.</P>
  <P>He mounted a chair and viewed the screen. A Liberal Theory of Relativity by G.O. Forth. "I believe ..." So it began and faltered in a single unfinished line, the cursor pulsing. No progress, Sally noted, in the master work.</P>
  <P>Forth now joined him, the fine old FOCUS delivering team together again. His master switched on the T.V. The lunchtime news carried a joint press conference announcing a major agreement between Labour and Liberal Democrats on the justice system. The fax whined into action with details of the agreement, direct from Cowley Street, entitled Crime and Punishment - Safe and Sound Behind Bars.</P>
  <P>"Sally," said George in a great sigh, "We are being destroyed by absorption. And there seems nothing we can do about it."</P>
  <P>At this, the great ancestral Welsh Terrier inside him barked and howled and howled and barked.</P>
  <P>Dashing into the kitchen he drank the bowl dry. He spun it across the slippery floor to rest in front of the fridge and himself jumped on the draining board to drink from the washing up basin. To do what he had made up his mind to do he would need every drop of fluid he could find.</P>
  <P>Leaping back onto the floor by the fridge he bent his head beneath him, took the tumour of caution and weakness between his serrated teeth and, closing his eyes, bit it off.</P>
  <P>In agony he dropped the rotten tissue into that bowl marked SALLY and rushed through the house to the door, to the garden, to the street, leaving a trail of blood and gore in his wake.</P>
  <P>At his tree he sprayed with all his being, "I Sally Forth declare for Liberalism not Contrivance" and ran on to the next. Again he pissed, "I Sally Forth declare for  Principles not Expediency." And down the tree lined avenue he went blasting out his message onto the world wide web with his fierce cocktail of urine, puce and blood, "I Sally Forth declare for Independence not Coalition, for Liberty not Authority, for Co-operation not Surrender."</P>
  <P>Against lampposts and fences, parking meters and telephone boxes, traffic lights and litter bins: "I Sally Forth declare for Conviction not Connivance." Against out of town supermarket doors, school gates, post offices, bookmakers, amusement arcades, charity shops, and government offices he slashed out against conformity, ignorance and dependency, against poverty, bureaucracy and authority.</P>
  <P>Against a statue of Churchill and one of Cromwell, against the wall in College Green and finally, exhausted, anaemic and dehydrated, and, in growing darkness, Sally summoned her final dribbled urination against the small black boot scraper outside No 4 Cowley Street. And there on the doorstep in a pool of his own rhetoric this frail weakened white wire haired terrier keeled over and died.</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Bill Le Breton</B></P>
  <CENTER>
