<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 240 Letters</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 240 Letters</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Straining The Greens</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P>Dear <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator">,</P>
  <P>I feel I must respond to the ecological doom-mongering being peddled by Tim Beaumont (<A HREF="../239/index.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> 239</A>).</P>
  <P>To begin with, the "Limits to Growth" to which he refers were discussed by John Stuart Mill, so they are hardly a new idea. They are also wrong. Mill was correct in his day, but our world is nothing like that understood by the classical economists. We are fast approaching a world where the most important commodity is know-how. And who would put limits on the growth of our knowledge?</P>
  <P>I make my living designing and writing computer programs. Once I have made a suite of programs, I can reproduce them at almost no cost - they can be reduced to nothing more than a tiny set of magnetised particles.</P>
  <P>Our knowledge is advancing at a tremendous rate. For example, we currently make "silicon chips" by etching with acid. This is akin to building the Forth Bridge out of a single carved lump of metal. And so scientists are now investigating building devices from the ground up. Out of individual atoms. This is a field known as "nano-technology" which holds enormous potential.</P>
  <P>In fact, if you plot the trends of our increase in knowledge on a graph, the figures start to go infinite within the next 50 years. We are about to fall into a "technological black hole", where in theory, anything is possible. Providing of course, that eco-fascists are not allowed to stifle human development.</P>
  <P>And here we come to the talk of restriction of civil liberties. I am a Libertarian Liberal. I didn't realise there was any other kind. Liberty, Libertarian and Liberal all come from the same root. All the great advances in human knowledge were instigated by great individuals building on the successes of other great individuals, often at the expense of persecution by their "community". Remember Galileo, put on trial for heresy at a time when heretics were burnt at the stake. His crime? Saying that the Earth was not the centre of the Universe, but rather revolved around the Sun.</P>
  <P>In short, Tim Beaumont's rant against capitalism, free trade (any trade in fact), and calls for restrictions on civil liberties would not have looked amiss in Pol Pot's Cambodia with its "Year Zero Agrarian Peasant's Utopia". I don't know which party Tim Beaumont thinks he is in, but it doesn't bear any resemblance to the party which I thought I had joined all those years ago.</P>
  <P><I>David Wildgoose, Rotherham</I></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
