<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 241 Commentary</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 241 Commentary</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Some Warnings Sound</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P>Liz Lynne and Bill Rogers normally have nothing in common; the one the MP most publicly opposed to working with Labour, the other the most uncritical supporter of Labour links. But in different ways and for different reasons, they both fanned doubts about Labour during the dramas of late November, which saw the latent resentment and mistrust in the Lib Dems about dealings with Labour finally boil over.</P>
  <P>Ashdown was provoked by Lynne's anti-Labour letter, and some more restrained comments by Chris Davies, into an explanation of his stance in Liberal Democrat News. He would have saved himself a lot of trouble had he deigned to publish this months ago.</P>
  <P>The letter from Lynne and her supporters, as quoted in the press, stated: "We are totally opposed to any pact or coalition with Labour before of after the next general election and feel this is in actual fact what you are working towards. We don't believe that you will be able to carry the party with you."</P>
  <P>Perhaps not. If those who want to work with Labour had the sense to stop mouthing off in public about how wonderful they think Tony Blair is, and stopped the stream of joint initiatives (which apart from the constitutional talks are mostly fatuous), they would probably get most of what they want anyway.</P>
  <P>A loose arrangement with a minority Labour government is almost certainly saleable to Lib Dems accustomed to these deals in local government. What is causing the trouble is the wide suspicion that talks between the two parties have already gone further than has been admitted, and that an inadequate 'take or leave' deal will be sprung on the Lib Dems.</P>
  <P>And what of Lord Rogers? Jack Straw's populism has finally sickened even him. The Police Bill gives the police powers to enter and bug private homes more or less at will, but Straw, whose politics seem to be guided by nothing but Sun editorials, has supported this. Even Rogers was moved to condemn him in The Observer.</P>
  <P>Until now the whole issue of working with Labour has been stuck in the thinking of the Alliance years; that the Lib Dems would help Blair neutralise his left wing. It becomes steadily clearer that a Blair government would not be a 'great reforming administration' as a few deluded Lib Dems have claimed.</P>
  <P>It would be a mirror image of the Tory governments of 1951 to 1974. They took Attlee's mixed economy welfare state as they found it, and did little to change anything important. They managed the system slightly differently. That is all Blair aspires to do to the Thatcherism he may inherit.</P>
  <P>The Lib Dems would do better to combine with the Labour left against 'new' Labour's enemies of liberty.</P>
  <P>For Straw's authoritarian populism is only partly a personal abberation. It is also part of what 'new' Labour is all about: a belief in coercive solutions to any behaviour of  which it disapproves, whether criminal (toughness on young offenders) or not (refusal by the young unemployed to follow the future Labour has chosen for them).</P>
  <P>Ashdown wrote in Liberal Democrat News that his party had voted at Glasgow to "work with others on our priorities and policies if they agree with us and if it is in the interests of those we represent".</P>
  <P>Lib Dem members should consider whether a Labour Party content with a home affairs spokesman who even Bill Rogers thinks is illiberal, counts as "others" who "agree with us".</P>
  <P>They should also ponder whether a Labour Party which reneged on the Scottish devolution deal is likely to do the same over constitutional reform.</P>
  <HR>
  <H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Who Chooses?</H2>
  <P><IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator">'s recent articles and letters about Liberal Democrat candidate approval (see page 18 onwards for more), suggest some exceedingly raw nerves have been touched among both interviewers and applicants.</P>
  <P>Any candidate approval system will throw up real or imagined grievances. And no-one wants to revert to the days when unwary drinkers in the National Liberal Club were liable to be hastily empanelled as interviewers.</P>
  <P>The Lib Dems clearly must have some process to filter out the inevitable applicants who are raving mad, have embarrassing criminal convictions, hold plainly illiberal views, or who are simply not up to the task whatever their other merits. Those who dislike the existing set-up must explain what they want instead.</P>
  <P>But there are three genuine concerns being voiced. First, does the current system test political skills and experience, or does it rely on the application by well-meaning amateurs of half-baked psychology, tests of body language and artificial situations.</P>
  <P>Second, does it favour those who often deal with formal interviews and role-play in their professional lives, and so know what is expected of them?</P>
  <P>Third, approval is supposed to be indefinite. What happens if a candidate is a complete disaster in real life?</P>
  <P>Perhaps some of this will be taken on board after the election.</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
   <map name="BUTTONS">
