<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 241 Radical Bulletin</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG WIDTH=100% SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 241</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H1><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="../rb.gif">Radical Bulletin</H1>
  </CENTER>
  <H2><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="../rb2.gif">Stirring In The Ranks</H2>
  <P>As <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> went to press an intriguing behind-closed-doors meeting was in prospect for Liberal Democrat MPs, at which they would be given polling information from the party's most important target seats.</P>
  <P>The object of this presentation, held despite the misgivings of leader Paddy Ashdown, was to provide some factual basis for the argument about what effect the Lib Dems' public closeness to Labour is having on the campaign in target seats.</P>
  <P>Since both Lord Holme and Chris Rennard were to be involved, the MPs could at least expect to hear both sides of the argument about interpretation.</P>
  <P>For it is this factor which is giving many MPs and party officers the vapours about the cosying-up to Labour.</P>
  <P>Few object to any and every sort of post-election deal with Labour. But quite a lot believe that the more the Lib Dems talk about links with Labour now, the fewer seats they will win, and the less likely they will thus be to find themselves in any position to treat with Labour, let alone deliver a full constitutional reform package.</P>
  <P>They cite the Lib Dems' recent appalling run of local by-election results as evidence of the party being punished for being seen as too close to Labour.</P>
  <P>In this context, Liz Lynne stands at one extreme, being opposed to dealing with Labour at all. Her letter to Ashdown, which touched off November's furore, is understood not to have support from other MPs, though it attracted support from prominent party members in the north, which Ashdown would be foolish indeed to dismiss.</P>
  <P>Chris Davies' warning about 'Lib Dem bums in Labour Daimlers' gave voice to concerns that some Lib Dems are worrying more about the trappings of power than about how to get it or what to do with it.</P>
  <P>Meanwhile, an indeterminate number of petitions are circulating demanding special conferences with the object of forbidding further negotiations or joint working with Labour, or of voting down any post-election deal.</P>
  <P>A special conference before the election would be an act of suicidal madness on the part of those opposed to links with Labour. That close to an election, the party leadership would trounce them (complete with the sort of orchestrated vilification which was directed at anti-merger campaigners nine years ago) leaving their cause in a worse position than it is now.</P>
  <P>A post-election conference would be voting on something which had already happened, since it would hardly be physically possible to hold one before a new Government was announced, or before the two parties had announced the shape of their cooperation. Again, the leadership would deploy the argument that they would look ridiculous were they to leave something they had just joined.</P>
  <P>Whatever should happen, in practice it is likely to be the parliamentary party which decides, possibly legitimised  after the event. Calling the meeting on target seat data is a welcome sign that many of the MPs realise this keenly.</P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
