 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 241 Reviews</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 241 Reviews</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>New Britain: My Vision of a Young Country</H2>
   <H3>by Tony Blair<BR>Fourth Estate, 8.99.</H3>
  </CENTER>
  <P>At the beginning of the 1990s it was fashionable for media pundits to say that in the new decade the British were becoming more compassionate and caring than  in the avaricious '80s. No more was heard of such comments after the Tory win in the 1992 general election. But perhaps the lesson of the 1992 election which at the time most people seemed to think Labour would win, was that people want to be more compassionate so long as it costs them nothing in time or money.</P>
  <P>If so then Tony Blair's new Labour is the perfect answer. Now you can look after number one, make millions, hate the poor and still avoid the taint of being an evil capitalist bastard by voting Labour once every five years. It costs nothing in higher taxes and yet shows concern and compassion for others.</P>
  <P>That is certainly the impression this reviewer is left with after reading New Britain, a collection of speeches by Tony Blair. It is full of woolly, generalised statements of concern for the poor, of support for social justice and of desire to help the underprivileged. What it lacks is any clear indication of what new Labour would actually do in government. The emphasis varies from social concern to economic hard-headedness depending on whether Mr. Blair is addressing the Labour Party conference or the Singapore Business Community, but the latter is always expressed in clearer, more specific terms than the former.</P>
  <P>Many Liberator readers will no doubt regret the lack of clear reforming policies from the leader of the Labour Party. I would advise them instead to be grateful. For the one original and clear idea expressed in this book is the "vision of a young country". By this Blair appears to mean not that Britain should be run by seven year olds but that it should be a country whose citizens believe that it will  be great again. Or as Blair puts it: "I want us to be a young country again. With a common purpose. With ideals we cherish and live up to...Ambitious. Idealistic. United." It sounds very similar to imperial rhetoric of a century ago.</P>
  <P>People who have such grand ideas about national destiny and who want to lead the nation toward that destiny are usually highly dangerous and should not be left in charge of anything larger than a corner shop. If there is a Labour government perhaps it will be for the best if it does as little as possible and if the need for fiscal rectitude prevents Tony Blair from implementing his vision of a young country.</P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Iain Sharpe</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
