<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 241</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 241</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>The Crime Bill</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P><B><I>The Tories' bill will waste money and cause more crime as Michael Howard plays to the 'get tough' lobby. Liberal Democrat peer Conrad Russell argues that a bill which is too savage and reactionary for traditional Tories (but not for Jack Straw) will worsen every aspect of crime and justice.</I></B></P>
  <HR WIDTH=50%>
  <P><B>There is only one person in the country I am not certain I would prefer to Michael Howard as Home Secretary, and that person is Jack Straw.</B></P>
  <P>When the Crime (Sentences) Bill had it second reading in the Commons, Jack Straw refused to vote against it. Alex Carlile was left to call a division on his own. It is one of the occasions when Liberal Democrats have had the courage to stand up against both the big parties together, and were praised for doing it in the Commons debate by so improbable a duet as Douglas Hurd and Kenneth Baker.
  <P>The bill is too savage and reactionary for them, but not for Jack Straw.
  <P>This is one of the occasions on which New Labour have cast grave doubt on whether they are an alternative to Toryism. Michael Howard's numerous Conservative critics must rely on us to start any genuine debate on this bill.
  <P>Michael Howard's bill is in essence about longer prison sentences. Anyone who wishes to oppose this should begin by showing what they will do instead.
  <P>There is nothing in Liberalism which suggests that we should not do everything we can to reduce crime.
  <P>Crime, if it deserves the name, infringes Mill's principle that we should allow those things which do no harm to others. Mugging in the street, breaking and entering, assault, vandalism and even leaving litter all do harm to others (as a former pupil who did a vacation job as a street sweeper told me very firmly). We should not be ashamed of trying to stop such things.
  <P>Measures to control crime must pass three tests. First, they must have a reasonable chance of catching the guilty and not the innocent. Second, they must be compatible with common humanity, which must include a chance of rehabilitation of the offender. Third, and perhaps most important, there must be a reasonable chance that they will be effective.
  <P>During an election we need two policies on crime, one to reduce crime, and another to satisfy the voters. The Tories, for 17 years, have been doing the second at the expense of the first, with the result that attempts to satisfy the voters are still ratcheting up the spiral of severity. We must now think of actually reducing crime.
  <P>We cannot do that by increasing sentences, for the simple reason that criminals are not deterred by sentences unless they expect to have to serve them. At present, according to Lord Chief Justice Taylor, a professional burglar has at most three chances in 20 of being caught. As gambling odds, those knock the National Lottery into a cocked hat. Most professional criminals are by temperament gamblers, and so long as their chances of winning are so much better than   they can ever be on the horses, the dogs or the pools, they will not be deterred by what happens to the odd incompetent who gets caught.
  <P>Thanks to the 'efficiency' of the Crown Prosecution Services (efficiency in the Treasury's sense, not mine) their chances of being convicted are far less than their chances of being caught. The chance of being convicted if you commit a crime tomorrow is in the region of three per cent.
  <P>Incredibly, the Government is proposing to cut the funding of the CPS, and Labour's rebuttal unit boasts that it has no plans to reverse that cut. The total cost of the CPS is 300,000. Michael Howard would do more to reduce crime by spending another 100,000 on the CPS, than by the several billions he intends to spend on prisons.
  <P>To deter crime, we should improve prevention, by locking and lighting and anti-theft devices in cars, by having men on station platforms and public transport to keep the innocent on the streets at night. We should then improve detection. This is not only a matter of more bobbies on the beat. We must reverse the run-down of police forensic science laboratories, and allow the police to afford to service their cars. We need to raise the number of women and ethnic minorities in the police to the critical mass which would protect them from harassment. There is no point in raising sentences until we can convince people that they are likely to serve them if they offend.
  <P>All of this is much too rational to interest Michael Howard. He prefers his proposals for what he calls 'honesty in sentencing', which means that people should serve all, or almost all, the sentence imposed on them by the court.
  <P>One can see the attraction of such a proposal to John Major, who intends that we should serve every last day of the five-year sentence we imposed on ourselves in 1992. Michael Howard still intends to allow a small reduction for good behaviour in prison, though whether enough to allow governors to retain control of their gaols we will have to wait to discover. What will not survive is the individual risk assessment involved in the present system of parole.
  <P>Good behaviour in prison is not necessarily an indicator of good behaviour on release. Paedophiles, for example, are almost free from temptation to offend in prison, and under the new scheme many of them will be released earlier than they are now.
  <P>More generally, if people are to serve almost all of their sentences, either there must be clear statutory direction that sentences pronounced by the courts must become shorter, or there will be a massive increase in the prison population. If we have the first, it will be the occasion for new anti-judge propaganda. If we have the second, the Penal Affairs Commission has estimated that it could increase the prison population by between 18,000 and 20,000. The cost of that remains to be counted.
  <P>In legal terms, the most objectionable of Michael Howard's proposals is the proposal for mandatory minimum sentences. It is the same system we now have in the mandatory life   sentence for murder. This is wrong because it abandons the fundamental principle that the punishment should fit the crime. As Lord Hailsham explained last time the House of Lords debated the mandatory life sentence for murder, one murder is not like another.
  <P>Some deserve the Government's description of 'literally the most heinous crime', but Lord Hailsham asked the House to compare the mercy killing of a terminal cancer patient with arson in a crowded tenement in which, by the grace of God, no-one was killed, and decide which was the more heinous crime. When he finally had to give way to the Commons, Lord Hailsham advised us to accept defeat with the memorable words, "let them have their silly way".
  <P>What is true of murder is even more true of rape. One rape is not like another. Some rapes, inflicted at knife point in the street and accompanied by unimaginable cruelties, are justly punished with a life sentence for the first offence. Yet it is equally rape if a woman embraces a man, murmurs endearments to him, takes off her clothes, entices him into bed, and at the very last moment changes her mind. The man who denies it to her commits a crime and should be punished. But does anyone think his crime is of the same severity as that committed by the sadist with the knife? Do they really deserve the same sentence? And if they are not to serve the same sentence, should not that decision by taken by the judge who has heard the evidence and seen the witnesses? Justice is individual: it cannot be done by formula.
  <P>Equally, one burglary is not like another. This route leads to the absurdity of the man in California who stole a pizza and was given a life sentence under the 'three strikes and you're out' rule. No-one should have to commit crime in order to eat, and we would do much more to reduce crime by ensuring that everyone has enough to eat than we will ever do by imposing such injustices in the name of justice.
  <P>It has been suggested that if there are many such injustices, juries will be less ready to convict, and witnesses less ready to come forward. This has happened before. We have had mandatory minimum sentences before. Until the penal reforms of the 1820s, which are part of the prehistory of the Liberal Party, there was a mandatory minimum sentence of death for theft of goods worth more than a shilling. However, the valuation of stolen goods, being a matter of fact, was a matter for the jury. Over and over again, people were accused of stealing goods worth 5 or 10, but convicted of stealing goods worth 11 1/2d, and therefore spared a hanging. Juries might lose patience with recidivists, and the finding that goods were worth 11 3/4d constituted a sort of 'last warning'.
  <P>Professional criminals or strangers to the county tended not to get the sort of mercy locals could usually count on for a first, and often second or third, offence. Severity in legislation was tempered by a populist sense of what was fair. If Michael Howard gets his way, he will find the Sun newspaper, as fickle as its heavenly namesake, crusading against his stupid inhumanity. Poetic justice takes odd   forms.
  <P>All this will not reduce crime. It is not even true that people do not commit crimes inside prison. Prison overcrowding, by reducing supervision, is increasing prison crime to a terrifying level. Crime is the only thing prisoners have in common. They tend to talk about it, and come out knowing far more of how to commit it than they did when they went in. Since cuts in housing benefit, among other things, are making it harder to rehabilitate ex-offenders, ex-prisoners will remain criminals.
  <P>What will all this cost? The White Paper, with blind optimism, estimates an additional 375 million to 435 million for the recurrent costs of extra prisoners. This is wrong, for a start, because it assumes a deterrent drop in the prison population of 20 per cent because of severer sentences. Until the chances of detection and conviction are larger, the true figure will almost certainly be nil. It might be optimistic to double the cost to correct for this. In addition, the figure leaves out the capital cost of building 12 new prisons (which might again have to be doubled if the 20 per cent deterrent effect is a mirage).
  <P>We are given no figure for the cost of this, since it will be done under the private finance initiative, and will be subject to commercial confidentiality. This does not mean there will be no cost.
  <P>If we allow for the effect of the probable massive breakdown in prison security because of understaffing and overcrowding, we could be looking at as much as 3p on the Income Tax. All this, for no reduction in crime, is a waste of public money of Poll Tax proportions.
  <P>We should campaign against it under the slogan 'Tory Tax Bombshell'. I don't see why the devil should have all the best tunes.
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Conrad Russel</B></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
