<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 241</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 241</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Bosnia Ballots On The Brink</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P><B><I>Michael Meadowcroft, co-ordinator of the International Observer mission for out-of-country refugee votes, reports on how war-torn Bosnia grappled with running its first election.</I></B></P>
  <HR WIDTH=50%>
  <P>Waiting in the makeshift military air terminal at Zagreb alongside soldiers of many hues for the IFOR flight to Sarajevo, I watched the giant Hercules army transport 'plane flop down on to the airstrip. As it taxied to a halt its provenance became clear from its markings:</P>
  <P>"Royal Norwegian Air Force". "Great," I overheard an American soldier remark, "the Norwegian flight attendants are much more attractive". There are, of course, no flight attendants as such at all on any flight in or out of Sarajevo but the system of bookings and scheduled flights works reasonably well, administered by the Americans in Zagreb and the French in Sarajevo. From the 'plane one can clearly see the rows of burnt out houses and, on landing, the pitiful state of the Sarajevo airport. The camaraderie of war zones is also warmly apparent. My transport hadn't appeared and a 4x4 stopped at the checkpoint. The Bosnian driver leaned out and smiled, "Your driver hasn't arrived and my passenger wasn't on the 'plane. So, why don't I give you a lift into town?" With hotels still not back in operation the OSCE has a number of "transit houses" in Sarajevo prepared for visiting staff. These are local people's residences in which they enthusiastically let off rooms. Some are notorious! I ask my colleague, "Where am I staying tonight?" "The Dog!" he replies. I immediately know the house, high up on a hill on the east of the city, overlooking the river, where the warm and welcoming couple have a huge hound. Fortunately for once it bears out that well known adage that the bigger the dog the softer it is!</P>
  <P>Later, relaxing with colleagues over a beer in the early evening sunshine on the terrace of a cafe in the old town quarter of Sarajevo, one could be forgiven for imagining that one was in northern France or even - almost - Covent Garden. That is, until one glances across the river to the cemetery on the hill beyond where the hordes of fresh graves are marked with what to western eyes are curiously shaped headstones or simple boards. To a Liberal the reopening of Sarajevo's old town, where perhaps three-quarters of the shops and restaurants are now back in business, is testimony to the remarkable resilience of the human spirit. Owners are daily driving trucks across delicate borders to bring back supplies, and the determination to demonstrate that the horrors of the past will not be allowed to destroy the future is palpable.</P>
  <P>Of course, based in Sarajevo one is partially cocooned from the grim realities of the postwar situation which exists in most Bosnian towns. The stark electoral registration figures give you the picture. 40% of the Bosnian electorate are refugees, half of them outside the country. In other words, only 60% of Bosnians reckoned that they would be able to vote at the place where their names were recorded on the  1991 Census - the qualifying date for taking part in the elections. The logistics of the electoral process were overwhelming and they survived only because those involved  on the spot improvised brilliantly and because the results gave the main parties the seats they anticipated so that they were all prepared to turn a blind eye to the technical infringements of the electoral law. They would, in any case, have been largely self-cancelling, all three sides having indulged in manipulation to a greater or lesser extent. It was inevitable that the nationalists would dominate these first post-war elections but there were liberals who bravely put their heads over the parapets and who made the difficult and unrewarded case against ethnicity and separation. These colleagues deserve our support.</P>
  <P>The Bosnia and Herzegovina elections were miles from being "free and fair" - the lack of freedom of movement and of free media were, for instance, vividly obvious - but they were the best that were possible in the circumstances. At best they have got the nationalistic leaders of the three entities meeting and talking, and at worst they stopped the war and bought a little time. The whole electoral process was in the hands of the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe. The OSCE is the most tangible outcome of the Helsinki talks of the 1970s and is one of the very few bodies that includes Western, Central and Eastern Europe on an equal basis. As such it was generally acceptable to all sides as the executive organisation for the elections agreed under the Dayton Agreements. However, this acceptability should not mask the risks to the future of the OSCE that was inherent in taking on the responsibility.</P>
  <P>Certainly it was a brave act, helped by human rights organisations, such as the Helsinki Committees who, although they believed that enough safeguards were not yet in place to hold reasonable elections, nevertheless gave practical assistance with observing once the decision to go ahead was taken.</P>
  <P>OSCE largely formed the Provisional Election Commission and its Appeals Committee, managed the actual electoral administration, approved the "Supervisors", who formed a unique tier of personnel from outside Bosnia, authorised to intervene if they believed the process was been carried out illegitimately, and co-ordinated the International Observer Mission which monitored the whole process! The main OSCE office is based in Vienna and its Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights (ODIHR) is in Warsaw and it was important for the independence of the Observer Mission that the offices were separate, geographically as well as organisationally.</P>
  <P>The out-of-country refugee registration and voting was organised by an ad hoc Refugee Election Steering Group based in Vienna, largely staffed by personnel from the splendid International Organisation for Migration. This involved the  logistical nightmare of organising the process separately in twenty-four countries. Three-quarters of the 640,000 voters thus registered were in Croatia, Germany and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (ie Serbia and Montenegro) and only Croatia and FRY had in-person voting - all the others voted by post. Given that all the votes had to be counted within  Bosnia, essentially in Sarajevo, the problems of transportation and security were immense.</P>
  <P>Those who are still sceptical about the value of international election observation should realise that the postponement of the Bosnian municipal elections came about through the thoroughness and professionalism of those observing the registration process in Serbia. Unusually, because of the sharp focus on ethnicity in key towns and cities, the local elections are by and large seen by voters in the three entities as being more important than the national and provincial elections. Given this, it would have been disastrous to have gone ahead in the light of the manipulation spotted by the international observers.</P>
  <P>The problem was very simple: under the Dayton Agreements eligible voters could register to vote in any of three places - where they now lived, where they were living at the time of the 1991 Census, and where they intended to live. It was this third provision, inserted for quite proper reasons in order to encourage Bosnian refugees to return and to establish a new home as soon as possible, which caused the problem. The Serbian authorities realised that this provision could be used to entrench a Serb ethnic majority in key towns such as Srebrenica and Brcko and they set about putting illegitimate pressure on refugees in Serbia to register in these two or similar towns. Observers realised what was happening, reported it promptly and their evidence was tested further and then used as the basis for postponement of the municipal elections to next Spring, by which time new rules for registration can be formulated.</P>
  <P>The Bosnian situation is still delicate and the country will need immense political, financial and personnel assistance if it is to retain sufficient stability and security to avoid its atomisation into still smaller micro states. Inevitably, perhaps, it has already slipped out of the headlines. If this is a sign that quiet progress is being made then it may be a good thing, but if it betokens a world weariness with the problems of the Balkans then it could be a sad sign that once more the selfish West wants to wash its hands of its responsibility for the fate of its fellow human beings. Liberals need to keep up the pressure to maintain international involvement until the democratic process is sufficiently entrenched and accepted for the people of Bosnia to be able to look to a peaceful future.</P>
  <P><B>Note: Michael Meadowcroft's views expressed here do not necessarily reflect the opinions of the OSCF.</B></P>
  <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Michael Meadowcroft</B></P>
  <CENTER>
