<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 241 Letters</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 241 Letters</H1>
   <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
   <H2>Strained Green 1</H2>
  </CENTER>
  <P>Dear <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator">,</P>
  <P>Rarely have I read such a depressing letter as that contributed by David Wildgoose in response to Tim Beaumont. His use of the label eco-fascist, and his comparison of Tim Beaumont with Pol Pot, is deeply offensive and unneccessary. To throw these labels around against people who simply take a different view to yourself is to demean the suffering inflicted upon millions of people who experienced at first hand what fascism was really about. I expect that degree of insensitivity from Theresa Gorman (who talks of eco-terrorists). From a Liberal Democrat, the use of the term in this context is nothing short of disgusting.</P>
  <P>Name-calling aside, the core of Wildgoose's argument seems to be that there is no ecological crisis, and no need for gloom, because the advance of information technology will solve all of our problems. This is fatuous. There are few within the Party that will match the Green Lib Dems (and the Green Lib Dems' journal Challenge) for enthusiasm for the new technology, but however good Wildgoose gets at his programming career, his computer software will never feed anybody, nor replace the countless other aspects of the traditional economy which are currently leading to ever greater consumption of energy and raw materials and the production of wastes. Although IT has potential to remove some unneccessary car journeys, there is no expectation it will halt the relentless increase in vehicle ownership and use. The increase in greenhouse gas emissions will continue apace without political action to curb them. And so on.</P>
  <P>It is certainly true that technological advances will have some effect of mitigating environmental impact. Nobody however seriously expects them to remove the fundamental nature of the challenge ahead of us. If Wildgoose wishes to maintain otherwise, evidence rather than insults would be useful. His statements as they stand are merely complacent and fly in the face of current scientific opinion.</P>
  <P>I remember that, some years ago, Cyril Smith made the comment that he had the liberty to damn well drive his car where he wanted, when he wanted, and however much he wanted. As indeed, does David Wildgoose. But if this is to become the definition of liberty in this debate it is a strange throwback to a less sophisticated past, and it is a definition that excludes the freedom to breathe clean air, to live in streets that are safe for children and that have any vestige of community, and that also excludes the right of access for the majority of citizens who do not own their own car. Similar arguments can be applied to the way so-called "free" trade currently works to the disadvantage of a significant proportion of the world's citizens. Liberty in my world is not worth the name if it doesn't apply to everyone.</P>
  <P>So does that justify action to severely curtail individual human rights? I doubt it - and since  neither Tim Beaumont nor the Green Liberal Democrats advocate this I'm not sure why we should waste time debating it. I suppose one might   describe such an exercise as a Wildgoose chase (I bet that's the first time anyone's ever made that joke ...)</P>
  <P><I>Mallen Baker Vice Chair Green Liberal Democrats</I></P>
  <HR>
  <H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Strained Green 2</H2>
  <P>Dear <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator">,</P>
  <P>David Wildgoose's logic, and his understanding of the Green position, are at fault (letters, <A HREF="../239/index.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> 240</A>). The Green case against growth is not against any or all growth, nor is it doom-mongering. Greens certainly have no objection in principle to the growth of knowledge, we would however very much like to see a concomitant increase in wisdom.</P>
  <P>The Green case against growth is quite specifically a warning of what will happen, indeed what is already happening, if policies directed towards undifferentiated 'economic growth' are not seriously and quickly reappraised.</P>
  <P>JS Mill was not the first to accept the notion of 'limits to growth'; the basic principle is as much an ethical as a practical one, and all the great religions incorporate the idea that we should live within our means. The Green movement is following them; in some ways it can be likened to a religion itself.</P>
  <P>Far from being 'wrong', as Mr Wildgoose claims, the limits to growth are very real and present facts of life. They loom much more immediately than in JS Mill's day. Some 150 years ago there was still room in the world for population and industrial activity to expand; Mill recognised the threat posed by unthinking acceptance of the industrial imperative, a threat more apparent then on the ethical front than on the ecological.</P>
  <P>Mr Wildgoose may not know that the explosion in human numbers and the continued expansion of economic activity since then have now brought us to the point where no less than 40 per cent of the world's net primary production (which is, more or less, the total net conversion of solar energy) is now appropriated by our own species, and that proportion is still rising. If it were to go on increasing (as continued economic growth implies) we would be using over 100 per cent of NPP within a few decades, which is of course impossible.</P>
  <P>It is not the Greens who are doom-mongering, it is those who do not see any cause for concern in this headlong rush to disaster. Does Mr Wildgoose seriously believe that our species can go on increasing our share of NPP for ever? If not, when does he suggest we should stop? Are there any lengths to which he would not go? He is assuming (possibly without realising it) an infinite world.</P>
  <P>Mr Wildgoose is quite right to suggest that the economic activities of the future will change and  develop. This is because the natural framework within which all our  activities take place, the biosphere, is finite, and is already showing signs of stress under the pressure of economic growth. Thoughtful people know the limits to growth are very close indeed, in many respects we have already exceeded them.</P>
  <P>There are many people like Mr Wildgoose who find it hard to change their ideas. I suggested above that the Green movement has much in common with a religious movement. I was 'converted' in the early 1970s after reading Schumacher's Small is Beautiful and the Blueprint For Survival, which appeared in The Ecologist.</P>
  <P>I suddenly realised that many of the political and economic objectives of modern society, uninterrupted economic growth being the core belief, were impossible of achievement, dangerous, immoral and unnecessary. So I joined the Liberal Party, thinking I would find like-mined people in it. There were, but not as many as I expected, so I founded the Liberal Ecology Group (now the Green Lib Dems).</P>
  <P>It is sad that Mr Wildgoose regards those who warn against the dangers of our present-day Gadarene rush as 'eco-fascists'. He can rest assured that the last thing Greens wish to do is stifle human development. We are desperately anxious that mankind should mature enough to reject the current obsession with economic growth, and learn to live in peace with each other and the rest of natural creation.</P>
  <P><I>Tony Beamish Littlehampton</I></P>
  <CENTER>
   <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
