<HTML>
  <!--Written by Rob Herbert-->
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 233 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 233 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>The Ultimate Avengers</H2>
      <H3>by Dave Rogers<BR>Boxtree / Lumiere / Channel 4 Books 1995 16.99</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P><I>Steed gives a reference<BR>Emma gets booked</I></P>
    <P>There are a huge number of telefantasy books available these days, of variable quality - ranging from the cheap and superbly researched Virgin Doctor Who and others range, to the dreadful (and less cheap) Pioneer Star Trek  collection.  Boxtree tend to be somewhere in between; their Blake's 7  book is hideous, Doctor Who only slightly better, but The Ultimate Avengers looks, and is, excellent.</P>
    <P>This is a good job, as it is the only Avengers reference book in print.  And the couple of out-of-print ones are by . . . Dave Rogers.  Funnily enough, he's reported to threaten competition into never getting off the ground, but there we go.  This is a thicker but smaller format (and more expensive) version of his previous main work, and is a complete guide from the junked first series onwards to what became the epitome of British high camp and style, and introduced the notion of heroines using their brains - and judo - instead of simpering.</P>
    <P>His summaries of each story are short and stylish, with only occasional mistakes (a figure of 480,000, rather than 180,000, appears in his account of Death of a Batman, while the synopsis for the Cathy Gale story Esprit de Corps, for example, is hopelessly confused and inaccurate -all the more peculiar, as his longer piece in The Complete Avengers had no difficulty). Irritatingly, he puts all the episodes in the order in which they were filmed, rather than actually broadcast - then giving broadcast dates after   each episode, but often getting them wrong!  The swish layout is also rather spoilt by an enormous number of typos, which surely any proof-reading should have spotted. Even a computer's spell-checker could manage some of them!</P>
    <P>The real worth of the book is the huge amount of background  information he's uncovered, both from documentation and exhaustive (and contradictory!) interviews with many  concerned.  The 'behind the scenes' sections are greatly expanded, with additional 'notes in the margin' appearing next to many stories.  Former scriptwriter, story editor, producer and general godfather Brian Clemens provides the greatest volume, although costume designers waspishly revealing who really  did the clothes, after all this time, are worth a read.</P>
    <P>Some of the anecdotes are rather good - I particularly liked the time Steed's clothes were stolen from a car and the stuntmen's dodgy underworld contacts had them returned.  This happened again, but: "Sorry, guys.  It must have been an amateur."</P>
    <P>Both Honor Blackman and Diana Rigg were the second  choices for their roles. There's even a picture of the first  Emma Peel, sacked for having no sense of humour!  For the Diana Rigg episodes to be shot in colour, they needed American money - and so had the most bizarre American restrictions  (guns must not be pointed at people's heads, cigarettes must not be ground under foot, the word 'idiot' may not be used . . . !).</P>
    <P>Poor Linda Thorson, in an attempt to make Tara King unlike Mrs. Peel, was made to have her hair hideously peroxided -and so made her first ten stories with a wig to simulate her natural colour while it grew back.</P>
    <P>Several pictures appear of pretty horrid 'looks' tried out on Joanna Lumley before Purdey was established properly to shoot her to stardom.  Steed and all his main Avengers sidekicks from Ian Hendry's Dr. Keel on had ranged from stunning to very good - until they finally hit one who was just average.  So, what was Mike Gambit for?  And what is Gareth Hunt doing these days, exactly?  Oh, yes. Three kinds of beans.</P>
    <P>Avengers spin-offs you might not have heard of - but Mr. Rogers has - include the stage play, the South African radio series and script extracts for two films that never got off the ground from about 1980 (and what purports to be a story outline for, but is actually just the opening scenes to, a 60s Steed / Mrs. Gale movie called off when Honor Blackman left to do Goldfinger). A brief guide to locations and cars used, as well as merchandising from singles to board games are covered to close, along with an advert for the videos - though, irritatingly, not informing us which ones are available, or on which tapes.</P>
    <P>All in all, it is fortunate that the only book on the market is good enough to highly recommend, but with two strong caveats: the number of silly mistakes makes it hard to escape the conclusion that it was rush-released to tie in with Channel 4's current rescreening of the Fourth Season   (distinguished by special cards at each ad break, which, oddly, aren't mentioned here . . . possibly because his publishers, Channel 4, aren't bothering to use them!); and when (please!), some day, this is not  the only book on the market, the price should be driven down about a tenner.</P>
    <P>Do you think Honor could be persuaded to start doing PPBs for us again? I only ask.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Alex Wilcock</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
