<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN//2.0">
<HTML>
 <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 234 Radical Bulletin</TITLE>
 </HEAD>
 <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
  <CENTER>
   <IMG WIDTH=100% SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
   <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
   <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 234</H1>
  </CENTER>
  <BR CLEAR=ALL>

  <A NAME="01"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Dead Parrot Shot on Launchpad</H2>
  <P>Combining Paddy Ashdown with a word processor and some books and the result is usually trouble.</P>
  <P>His grandly-titled 'Liberal Democrat News Lecture' in January featured a lot of speculation about Lib-Labbery and, only in rather toned-down form, Ashdown's views on the lack of future of the welfare state.</P>
  <P>The section on Lib-Labbery was the most widely reported, but it would not have been had an earlier draft of the speech survived.</P>
  <P>This is understood to have called for an eventual 85 billion cut in public spending by effectively forcing everyone to take out private insurance for those services now provided through the welfare state.</P>
  <P>This was shown to the mild-mannered chief whip Archie Kirkwood, who reportedly hit the roof, and then to the less mild-mannered Liz Lynne, who hit it a good deal more loudly. Lynne, who is not the most influential MP with Ashdown because of differences over the issue of deals with Labour, then enlisted formidable reinforcement in the shape of Earl Russell. This trio managed to convince Ashdown that his original musings were suicidal. A certain amount of backtracking then followed.</P>
  <P>Disaffection with the Tories has at least proved the public's continuing attachment to both the National Health Service and state pensions.</P>
  <P>Russell is fast emerging as the only person of any consequence in the upper reaches of the Liberal Democrats able to relate day-to-day politics to Liberal first principles.</P>
  <P>Ashdown has done this before with a document circulated after the 1992 general election, whose adherence to laissez-faire economics was so over the top that it was not allowed to appear in its original form (<IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> 207). This eventually limped through the Harrogate conference that year, badly mauled in a vote, to become the New Agenda paper and be promptly forgotten with all the other tonnage of policy documents.</P>
  <P>The Lib-Labbery part of his speech gave a welcome refutation of the idea that anyone might engage in a pre-election pact. But the crucial post-election difference, as we have argued before, lies in whether to support a Labour government issue-by-issue, to maximise Liberal Democrat influence. The alternative involves writing Labour an effective blank cheque to support it for five years (let alone 10) in return for a few dubious privileges, effectively signing away that influence. That would be responsibility without power. And if power without responsibility if the prerogative of the harlot, the reverse is the prerogative of the failure.</P>

  <A NAME="02"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Briefs in a Twist</H2>
  <P>Some pretty odd party documents have come <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator">'s way over the years. In this grand tradition, we have the creative brief distributed by the Liberal Democrat general election campaign team to, presumably, advertising agencies.</P>
  <P>We showed this only to Liberal Democrat members with professional expertise in the field. Their opinion could be summed up in the phrase 'round objects'. Their general view was that it was asking agencies to come up with a strategy, rather than asking them to apply their skills to implementing one set by the party.</P>
  <P>The document's origin and precise status are unclear, but it appears authentic. So in the interests of openness, here is a selection of what the activist in the street might be able to look forward to by way of national support in the next campaign.</P>
  <P>It starts from the premise that the 'Liberal Democrat Guarantee' will be a foundation for the campaign. Apparently this is because, "the purpose of the guarantee is to demonstrate the unique "added value" offered by a vote for the Liberal Democrats."</P>
  <P>Well, that is one way of putting it.</P>
  <P>The three well-known themes are investing in people, cleaning up the mess in politics and building for the long term. Snappy slogans? Oh dear no, these soundbites must be "put into layman's terms".</P>
  <P>It continues by stating that voter should see the Liberal Democrats as, "specific, clear, honest, far-sighted, fresh, mature, not insiders". Kind to orphans and fond of furry animals too, perhaps.</P>
  <P>We made up the last two, but you get the drift. And just in case that isn't clear, people must see the Liberal Democrats as "people orientated and real". Phew!</P>
  <P>It seems that Paddy Ashdown's programme for the coming year will afford the chance to "test various options on the road". We wonder if anyone has warned him.</P>
  <P>A variety of stage sets will be built, including something called a "speak to the people set-ette", which may be marketing speak for a soapbox.</P>
  <P>There will be no campaign song, but there has been an offer from the former Animal Alan Price to write the music required. This should be a considerable improvement on the music commissioned by party apparatchik Alan Watson, which unmemorably graced the Liberal Democrats' first conference. What about Price's film score hit 'O Lucky Man'? Or a version of the Animals' hit titled "We've Gotta Get Out of Third Place"?</P>

  <A NAME="03"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Leaks R Us</H2>
  <P>A profusion of leaks seems to have struck the Liberal Democrats of late in publications with an even higher circulation than that of <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator">. First Tom McNally gained press coverage for an article he had written which heavily trailed Ashdown's speech. This signalled most of what would be said about working with Labour and urged support for it. This appeared initially to be an 'official leak', but McNally is reported to have looked sheepish at the federal executive, where displeasure was expressed about this.</P>
  <P>The next day came the leak of a party researcher's scenarios for countering attacks from other parties during a general elelction. This was later said to be an attempt to play devil's advocate, and indeed it is hard to see why such a thing should have been produiced unless this is true.</P>
  <P>But such a document would presumably only have been circulated to senior Liberal Democrat MPs and strategists, a category not previously thought to include the editor of the Daily Telegraph. Since that paper is where the document ended up, the original circulation list would doubtless make fascinating reading.</P>
  <P>Next came an item in Private Eye which claimed that Lord Holme and Menzies Campbell were engaged in secret plots to make the latter party leader. There was a 'draft Campbell' whispering campaign last year, and it may have restarted. Those who know Lord Holme's record will of course find it unbelievable that he would be engaged in any such plot, if indeed it is taking place.</P>
  <P>Anyway, Holme is being kept slightly more busy because he has now agreed to make regular reports to the federal executive on the general election campaign, following the row over this in December.</P>

  <A NAME="04"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Educating Donnie</H2>
  <P>The Liberal Democrats' obsession with tackling tough decisions which they do not need to tackle has found its latest expression in proposals for student support. These would allow for individual learning accounts, of which students would then have to repay part.</P>
  <P>The federal policy committee desired to know from spokesman Don Foster what the grant element in this would be. Would this cover tuition costs? Would students still have some grant for maintennace? Foster was unable to answer, and eventually called in David Laws, who had done the costings, on the grounds that Laws understood these while no-one else did. The current proposals would effectively require students to borrow some 2,500 compared with the 1,000-odd under the Government's current system. What is more, repayment would be at a higher rate than at present. This sounds a real vote winner among students and their parents, especially as any canvasser called upon to defend it can always come up with the convincing response that it must be right because the person who wrote it understands it. As Paddy Ashdown ruefully admitted, "I don't think we will get this through conference."</P>

  <A NAME="05"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Knowing Something We Don't</H2>
  <P>Welcome Emma Nicholson, particularly as the rather limited history of Tory defectors, compared to the rather more extensive one of Labour defectors, suggests that those leaving the Tories are moving to the left, while those from Labour are on an ever-rightward trajectory.</P>
  <P>At least David Steel has not this time told the would-be recruit to go away and form her own party, as happened when Roy Jenkins applied to the Liberals in 1980, precipitating the wasted decade of the Alliance.</P>
  <P>As one reader of <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> wrote on his subscription renewal, "this must be the first example of Lord Holme persuading someone to join the party rather than leave it".</P>
  <P>The strangest part of the saga is that the Liberal Democrats were among the last to know what was afoot. For weeks prior to Christmas, Westminster had been alive with speculation that one or more west country Tories were poised to defect.</P>
  <P>So intense was this that national newspapers were making daily check calls, and the Labour Party was discreetly trying to find out when the Liberal Democrats would unveil their catch, so as not to plan any activity of their own which might be overshadowed by this coup.</P>
  <P>But the Liberal Democrats knew nothing until Nick Harvey jokingly asked Nicholson what the rumours were about, and she gave her now well-known positive response.</P>
  <P>Holme was enlisted to open delicate negotiations with Nicholson via mutual friends of her husband in the book industry.</P>
  <P>The flurry of rumours in December suggests there may be a real possibility of further defections. Nicholson is reliably reported to have happily accepted Liberal Democrat policies without any significant reservation. She was anyway respected for her independent views as a Tory, in particular for her campaigns in favour of the marsh arabs of Iraq. People like her are welcome.</P>
  <P>But the last thing the Liberal Democrats need is a defection of lots of Tories who want a small beach on which they can be large pebbles until their mates succeed in retaking control of their old party, when they can defect back.</P>
  <P>The recent antics of those social democrats who have redefected to Labour shows the danger of throwing open the doors to all and sundry just because they are famous.</P>
  <P>The only dissent over Nicholson comes from Liberal Democrat gay activists. She was the Tory signatory to the declaration of the UN Year of Tolerance. This included equality of sexual orientation, to which she felt, at least then, unable to put her name.</P>

  <A NAME="06"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Foul!</H2>
  <P>Twickenham is one of the Liberal Democrats' main target seats. Matters cannot surely have been helped by the abrupt resignation of its agent Mark Jeffries, after a very brief spell in office. This has now been followed by persistent reports of an assault in a local party meeting. Surely this cannot have been what all the general election talk about 'gearing up for battle' was really about.</P>

  <A NAME="07"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Lost Orders Please</H2>
  <P>We hear that Liberal Democrat members of the Association of District Councils were rather taken aback at a recent meeting to be told by their deputy leader, Congleton's Linda Short, that they could not inspect their group's draft standing orders. The astounded councillors were told that this was because this prize artefact was in the possession of the Cheshire rozzers. They are apparently investigating allegations concerning Congleton, and had swept up this innocent document with others.</P>

  <A NAME="08"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> English Translation</H2>
  <P>In days gone by, western observers would try to deduce what was really going in the Soviet Union from a study of the nuances of Pravda reports of official events. Work is available for unemployed Sovietologists in the decoding of Liberal Democrat News reports of the federal executive.</P>
  <P>Readers of <A HREF="../233/index.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> 233</A> will be well aware that there was a substantial row in December between most federal executive members and Lord Holme over the accountability of the general election campaign team. Neither this nor the substance of it was secret, since leading party figures could speak of little else in the following weeks.</P>
  <P>Yet LDN described this as "the need for effective cooperation between the election team and the federal executive was emphasised". What was more, "a number of matters were discussed". Thus in LibDemspeak, 'emphasising effective cooperation' seems to bear the same meaning as "frank and comradely discussions" did in the Soviet bloc, a phrase used usually prior to someone falling from favour and being shot. Discussing 'a number of matters' means 'enormous row', when translated into English.</P>
  <P>But even <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator">'s finest linguistic scholars have to admit defeat in trying to discover from LDN the exact status of the newly-ennobled Dick Taverne.</P>
  <P>It described as 'heading the list' of gongs, the OBE award for Mike German. This was followed by MBEs. Only then did we come to the life peerage, which would normally be regarded as more 'head of the list' than an OBE.</P>
  <P>One went to Dick Taverne, the premature social democrat of the 1970s, who was nominated by prime minister John Major, but is expected to join the Liberal Democrat bench in the Lords, a status which still does not put him head of the list, so is he or not? At least Paddy Ashdown did not waste a Liberal Democrat nomination on him, which would have fuelled the quite justified discontent over the number of peerages for those who spent the 1970s campaigning for Labour, compared to those for longstanding Liberals.</P>

  <A NAME="09"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Off The Air</H2>
  <P>The Government's broadcasting bill, now before parliament, has afforded the Liberal Democrat policy committee a convenient excuse to jettison the embarrassing media policy proposals which were being promoted by Robert Maclennan, Chris Huhne, and er, that's about it.</P>
  <P>These (<IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> 226 and 230) were worse than the Government's plans, where control of diversity of ownership was concerned, and wanted one regulator to supervise the entire print and broadcast media, an act of centralisation of power which would have made Kim-Il Sung blush.</P>
  <P>The policy committee, despite a body of evidence to the contrary, knows a dodo when it sees it. It seized upon the new bill, arguing that the Liberal Democrats could hardly develop a media policy when the legal position was in a state of flux.</P>
  <P>Huhne, though, has for no very obvious reason been awarded a seat on the committee charged with drafting the general election manifesto.</P>
  <P>It is of course quite unthinkable that anything in a policy paper which never got put to conference should surface in the manifesto, isn't it?</P>

  <A NAME="10"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Seats On Top</H2>
  <P>There were red faces in the London Liberal Democrats when an internal newsletter was leaked to the Independent, which stated quite truthfully that the party was short of candidates in London, and appealed for anyone "remotely interested" to apply. Simon Hughes was obliged to issue a reply, which stressed that there would be a Liberal Democrat candidate in every seat in the capital, and spoke of 'healthy competition' for approvals.</P>
  <P>There are some seats of course in every region where it does not much matter whether a candidate is in place four years or four hours before the deadline.</P>
  <P>Something has to be done about the well-intentioned but slow candidate approval system. It is surely time for some sort of fast track approval process entitling those who pass to fight only a specific seat, or a category of less promising ones, rather than indefinite approval everywhere.</P>

  <A NAME="11"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Fashion Plate</H2>
  <P>Every man has his price, so what is Sir David Steel's? For years Steel was well-known for always wearing a striped shirt with a white collar (not the same one all the time of course). Yet in semi-retirement he has taken up modelling something without a white collar called a 'pinpoint stripe'. This is made by Charles Tyrwhitt, purveyor of gents shirting. What can have caused this change of long-standing loyalties? Is in anything to do with image consultant Mary Spillane (<IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> 232) who has been telling credulous Liberal Democrats how to dress. The next page of Mr Tyrwhitt's catalogue carries an advertisement for 'Presenting Yourself, a personal image guide for men', by Ms Spillane.</P>

  <A NAME="12"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Stoned</H2>
  <P>Poor Bob Maclennan. It cannot be everyday that the Liberal Democrats' president is found in the street throwing stones at a window. But that is what happened when he arrived for the November conference committee meeting late and could not get in. Members eventually heard him and took pity. But at least he was there, which is more than can be said for Charles Anglin. It did not escape members attention that it is now two years since both federal policy committee representatives attended the conference committee at the same time.</P>

  <A NAME="13"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Simon Says, and says, and says</H2>
  <P>Move are afoot to draft Diana Maddock as Liberal Democrat Youth and Students president after a successful speech at their London conference. Simon Hughes damaged his chances of re-election in two ways. He did little to dispel the impression that he was aligned to the defeated Philip Jones/ Charles Anglin slate, and made an unscheduled closing speech which went on for an hour and crowded out debates. Hughes is usually reliable for a rousing call to arms, but on this occasion one delegate was seen sound asleep.</P>

  <A NAME="14"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Liberal Assembly Derailed</H2>
  <P>The Tories have frustrated the Liberal Party in the attempt to carry their Assembly to their Cornish heartland. The problem is one of getting a train out of Cornwall on a Sunday. Even trains from Plymouth don't easily tie in with getting delegates back to the far flung corners of the kingdom. As a compromise, the Assembly, which takes place between 27th and 29th September, will be back at Weston-Super-Mare. Dave Profitt, of the Party's national office in Southport,said it had brought home the full extent of what the government has done to the railways and their general neglect of the South West in a wholly unpredicted way. Would the Assembly be frustrated further by a general election? The Liberal Party says its manifesto is ready to run, but candidates have only been selected in two seats so far.</P>

  <A NAME="15"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Monstrous Erection</H2>
  <P>The desperate attempts of New Labour to appear almost normal could have suffered yet another set back... and its got nothing to do with where toffs send their kids to school. The following letter recently appeared in the East London Advertiser...</P>
  <BLOCKQUOTE>
   <P>"Pick your new priestess right now</P>
   <P>For many years the Temple of Isis has been fighting against the psycho-geographical male-female imbalance caused by the erection of the monstrous phallic obelisk of Canary Wharf on the ley line linking the evil obelisks of Pharaoh Tethmosis III (ie Cleopatra's Needle) and St Stephen's Tower (ie Big Ben).</P>
   <P>This was designed by arch occultists Pugin and Barry as a symbol of the patriarchal; power of Parliament (it is no coincidence that suffragette Emmeline Pankhurst was imprisoned in St Stephen's Tower in 1902).</P>
   <P>But thanks to invocations and psychic manipulation by the Temple of Isis and our trained, psychically gifted agents operating deep within the Labour Party the malign throb of patriarchy is ceasing to beat so strongly.</P>
   <P>A fruit of our spiritual labour has been the decision for an all-women shortlist for MP for Tower Hamlets.</P>
   <P>All contenders have been elevated as honorary Hand-maidens of the Temple of Isis and should be addressed as such. The chosen candidate will become an Archpriestess.</P>
   <P>Unfortunately we will have to ask those not selected to willingly offer themselves up for sacrifice, but that's politics for you.</P>
   <P>Karen Elliot, Total Maximum High Priestess."</P>
  </BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>There are seven such contenders, however the Old Patriarchy of the Labour Party stirs itself. Smart money is on Kumar Murshid for the Bethnal Green & Bow division, unless Councillor Assad, chairman of education, splits the vote.</P>

  <A NAME="16"></A><HR><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=TEXTTOP SRC="../rb2.gif"> Nothing Like a Dame</H2>
  <P>Ronnie Fearn is not treading the boards as the dame in the All Souls' Dramatic Society Panto in Southport this year. Instead he plays the Huntsman in Snow White. No doubt his previous experience as health spokesperson came in useful for cutting the heart out.</P>

  <P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=100% SRC="../border2.gif"></P>
 </BODY>
