<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 234 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 234 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>British Elections & Parties Yearbook 1994</H2>
      <H3>edited by David Broughton & others.<BR>Frank Cass 1995</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P>Here's one for you train-spotters. An academic view of events in the body politic over the period 1992-93 in the main, but going beyond the scope of previous editions in that papers are not purely those presented at the conference of the Elections, Public Opinion & Parties group of the Political Studies Association.</P>
    <P>Now read on.</P>
    <P>So what can you remember from those dark days? Labour was seeking to divest itself of Trades Union influence and tentatively mooted the prospect of all women selection in a rather limited number of Parliamentary seats.</P>
    <P>The 1992 General Election was still in recent memory and analysis was pouring out. Patrick Syed and Paul Whiteley tell us that local campaigning had a considerable impact on the Tory vote in 1992- some lessons there.</P>
    <P>Iain McLain and Jeremy Smith found that the impact of the Poll Tax on electoral registration made grim reading. They reckon that the Tories would have won ten fewer seats had 40% of those not registering voted Labour or Lib Dem (Brecon, Edinburgh West, Portsmouth South) in those divisions. Given Labour's active encouragement of the Poll Tax refuseniks this is especially depressing reading now. Amusing on the Peasant's Revolt, but skip the mathematics.</P>
    <P>The real meat for most <IMG SRC="../name.gif" ALT="Liberator"> readers however will be Lynne Bennie, John Curtice and Wolfgang Rudig on the political identity of Liberals, Social Democrats and Liberal Democrats. Some of you will remember the survey that arrived around the time of the Torquay conference- well these are the results.</P>
    <P>The survey found that as far as most Lib Dems are concerned "the fault lines of the old Alliance have been removed" and it the merger has by and large been successful. Ideological differences between former members of the Liberal Party and the SDP prove something of a paradox. The former Social Democrats are found to be more conventionally liberal on moral issues than former members of the Liberal Party. Is this a case of local power corrupts? On economic issues Social Democrats are found more to the right, completing a trend which began under Owen and which has disturbing repercussions in the Liberal Democrats, in the recent work of the Media Panel for example. Thank goodness Conrad Russell is there to fight the corner.</P>
    <P>Ultimately, the authors conclude, the impact of the SDP was slight. This may seem perfectly obvious now, so was it worth all the pain? There are no short cuts in politics.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>S G Rayment</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
