<HTML>
  <!--Written by Rob Herbert-->
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 234 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 234 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>The Avengers: Cathy Gale volume 2</H2>
      <H3>Lumiere Pictures Ltd, 1995, 10.99</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P><CITE>"You have a surprising faith in gentlemen's agreements, Mr. Teddy Bear - but perhaps you have noticed, I'm not a gentleman."</CITE></P>
    <P>'Mr. Teddy Bear' was the first episode broadcast (although they're being released in production, not transmission order) featuring Honor Blackman as Mrs. Gale. Even today, she's an unusually strong woman character, so the impact she had 10 years before I was born was huge. An anthropologist with a flat designed in the style of her old home in Africa, she's resourceful, handy with a gun or a motorbike, but with a hard moral edge. This brings her into conflict with Patrick Macnee's Steed, at that time a shady ruthless character under the mannered veneer of brolly and bowler: coldly threatening a petty crook; laced with black humour; suggesting a kneecapping; and professionally appreciative of the assassin Mr. Teddy Bear (much to Cathy's disapproval).</P>
    <P>Mr. Teddy Bear is expensive, but effective - whether you  want a macabre practical joke or a public execution, his speciality is death by gadget. The opening killing is particularly ingenious, as is the moving teddy bear through which the killer communicates (in many way a template for later larger-than-life Avengers masterminds). He even has a believable background, though he's a little disappointing in the flesh. Clearly not as stylised as the programme later became, with ordinary sets and primitive cameras, the story is at times slow-paced, but overall it's an effective thriller with a twist. Both Steed and Cathy stand out as superb.</P>
    <P><CITE>"All right. Forty - five shillings a share."<BR>"The brigadier offered me forty-five and six. And a much better seduction too."</CITE></P>
    <P>'Bullseye', the second episode on this tape, is a tale of Stock Exchange skullduggery and gun-running to tribal wars.  It showcases Mrs. Gale (who gets an unarmed combat scene here) at her best, taking the controlling shares in an armaments firm under threat of take-over by business tycoon with a nasty reputation, where the other major shareholders are dying mysterious deaths...</P>
    <P> Steed is kept to a minimal role, supplying Cathy with money, information and innuendo-laden banter with bounces off her iron rectitude. The director keeps a tight script taut with suspense, with scenes such as that where Cathy is framed for murder particularly effective. It lacks the occasional flamboyance of the earlier story, but is sinister enough to make a more satisfying whole. In all, the tape is a fascinating flashback to the thriller style that launched The Avengers, with plotting and performances which more than make up for some creakiness.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Alex Wilcock</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
      <map name="BUTTONS">
        <area shape="polygon" alt="Home Page" coords="32,2,4,23,1,56,85,56,81,25,56,22,33,2,33,3" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/index.htm">
