<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN//2.0">
<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 235 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 235 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Winston Churchill as I knew Him</H2>
      <H3>by Violet Bonham Carter<BR>Wiedenfeld & Nicholson 1995 14.99</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P>Lady Violet's recollections cover the period from 1906 to 1916, when Churchill stepped down as First Lord of the Admiralty following the disastrous Gallipoli campaign. The book deals mostly with events that are commonly recorded elsewhere, but with the insight of Lady Violet's personal and family (she was the daughter of Herbert Asquith) experiences. Churchill at the time of their first meeting was 32 and she 19. Shortly before he had joined the Liberal government, having been increasingly uncertain about the Conservative Party since early 1904, principally because of Joseph Chamberlain's protectionism. This issue was quite clearly splitting the Conservatives but, rather like his successor John Major, Balfour refused to go. Churchill was first adopted by the Liberals in North West Manchester as a Free Trade candidate, wherefore he increasingly drifted towards the Liberal ranks. By-elections reduced the Tory majority from 134 to 68.</P>
    <P>The 1906 general election which followed saw the demonstrations of the suffragettes. Although Churchill supported women's suffrage, he riposted in the face of a demonstration at one of his campaign meetings that he was not going to be hen-pecked over the issue, becoming something of a byword in the election. Defending one of the neighbouring constituencies to that which Churchill fought, Arthur Balfour was himself defeated. As we know, 377 Liberals were elected, whilst their supporters numbered 513 within the House of Commons to only 157 Tories. Can we look forward to something of a repeat over the next 18 months? Not Liberals alas.</P>
    <P>With a view to the next general election, it is interesting that in those days a by-election was fought when a Member of Parliament was elevated to the Cabinet. Defending as he was a traditional Tory seat, Churchill perhaps not surprisingly lost the ensuing by-election in 1907, being duly elected for a safe seat in Dundee shortly afterwards. However it also demonstrates a party's ability to recover from a seemingly disastrous electoral setback, and is a matter which might guide Liberal Democrat strategy during the next parliament.</P>
    <P>It was at Dundee that Churchill gave the classic definition of the difference between Liberalism and Socialism.</P>
    <BLOCKQUOTE>Socialism seeks to pull down wealth: Liberalism seeks to raise up poverty. Socialism would destroy private interests; Liberalism would preserve private interest in the only way which they can be safely and justly preserved namely, by reconciling them with public right. Socialism will kill enterprise; Liberalism would rescue enterprise from trammels of privilege and preference. Socialism assails the pre- eminence of the individual; Liberalism seeks, and shall seek more in the future, to build up a minimum standard for the mass. Socialism exalts the rule; Liberalism exalts the man...</BLOCKQUOTE>
    <P>Of her father's first Cabinet, Lady Violet points out that it was quite an achievement to hold together such men as Lloyd George, Edward Grey, Churchill, Haldane, Morley, Samuel, and John Burns together, without a single resignation until the First World War; the more so when one considers the agenda of that government. Churchill and Lloyd George rapidly formed a partnership. She says of them</P>
    <BLOCKQUOTE>Winston was an intellectual who arrived at his conclusions through his mind though his heart often reinforced it; intellectually Lloyd George had few convictions; his thought was not rooted in any consistent or abiding principals, his mind had no anchor. He lived by instinct and it served him well; he was an improviser of genius and an emotional opportunist.</BLOCKQUOTE>
    <P>Much of the book is anecdotal around events of Parliament, particularly the problems with the House of Lords veto which are gone into in some detail. Vitriol from the Tory benches was particularly directed at Churchill as a turncoat. However, perhaps because we are dealing with one ruling class in both the main parties it is perhaps the case that consensus was more easily achieved than in today's politics. The role of the dinner party or country weekend when politicians of all sides might meet socially shines through clearly in Lady Violet's account and is one of the obvious areas where she adds depth to the more general history.</P>
    <P>The causes of Churchill's departure to the trenches in 1916 are well known and sad to relate again. Herein lies the demise of Liberalism in British politics amongst other matters. Churchill was certainly headstrong; Cable Street demonstrated that much earlier. Politicians were more honourable persons in those days than would appear to be the case today.</P>
    <P>Lady Violet's book came out shortly after Sir Winston Churchill's death. It is not the definitive document on the man or the period, but adds insight and depth to our knowledge of both, making it a must for any Liberal interested in those times.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>S G Rayment</B></P>
    <CENTER>
