  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 235 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 235 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>The Wrong Men</H2>
      <H3>by Jill Morrell<BR>Obtainable from Bridgewater Four Support Group, 723 Pershore Road, Selly Park, Birmingham 29. 2.95 + 1 p&p</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P>This booklet will be particularly useful to those unfamiliar with the facts surrounding the murder of paper boy Carl Bridgewater at Yew Tree Farm, Staffs., in 1978; those who haven't read Paul Foot's Murder at the Farm (Penguin 1993) or missed the three television documentaries between 1978 and 1993.</P>
    <P>There is a brief history of the case, the narrative of the campaign from conviction in 1979 to 1995 and an appendix refuting the prosecution case. Space denies the author the chance to effectively rubbish the logistics of the prosecution case. It was impossible for the defendants to have reached the scene of the crime before 3.30 pm, whereas witnesses state that vehicles were seen at the farm from 12.25 pm until 4.55 pm.</P>
    <P>Apart from the logistics, the case has striking similarities to other major miscarriages of justice in the last twenty-five years. Two of the defendants who subsequently changed their stories implicated the other two. One died in custody. The involvement of our friends the West Midlands Police. The acceptance by the court of hearsay evidence of conversations in prison between the defendants and a prison officer and other prisoners. The presence of another suspect near the scene at the time of the murder, and the very great pressure upon the police to make an arrest, particularly as Devon & Cornwall Police had failed to find the body of paper girl Genette Tate who had been abducted a month prior to Carl's murder.</P>
    <P>Liberals of all persuasions should galvanise their local party; so far Labour has made all the running. After brooding for two and a half years Michael Howard says he is "not minded" to refer the case back to the Court of Appeal, despite a wealth of new evidence.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>John Gover</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
