<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 235 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 235 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>The New Arden Shakespeare</H2>
      <H3>King Henry V Editor TW Craik:  Titus Andronicus  Editor Jonathan Bate: Antony and Cleopatra. Editor John Wilders<BR>Routledge, hardback and paperback.</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P>Arden 2 once seemed the definitive word on Shakespeare, but in recent years new critical movements have made it seem out of date. Increasingly, the demand has been for a text that puts Shakespeare back in the theatre and Arden 3 attempts to do that, with emphasis firmly on the play in production and reference not only to the play's original staging but also to recent productions on stage and film. The volumes retain the clarity of the earlier Arden editions but with many new features, notably illustrations, maps, genealogical tables, suggestions for doubling and an extremely useful index. With the modern return to the bare stage used by the Elizabethans, the act and scene divisions which have no authorial justification have been printed very unobtrusively. This is obviously preferable as an acting version, but can make it less convenient as a study text.</P>
    <P>During the twentieth century, Henry V has often been dismissed merely as an imperialist celebration of national glory in which Shakespeare wisely showed his support for the Tudors. Lawrence Olivier's film version, whilst being an unforgettable film, was used for wartime propaganda in a this way. In his very readable introduction, Craik outlines the various perspectives which critics old and new have attempted to put on the play and brings it up to date with reference both to new historicism and cultural materialism.</P>
    <P>Craik does not attempt to join the debate, leaving it to the student to assess the play for him or herself. There is a full discussion of the early printing history and a particularly fascinating appendix gives a facsimile of the complete First Quarto of 1600, a version of the play which interestingly did not contain either the choruses or the Harfleur speech, Once more unto the breach,' probably the best known parts of the play for a modern audience. Could it be that this nationalistic play was originally staged without these most telling elements? The inclusion of maps of Henry's campaign and his family tree are particularly helpful today when the historical background may not be as familiar as it was to earlier generations.</P>
    <P>If Henry V merits new appraisal, does Titus Andronicus have anything to offer a twentieth century audience? Roman politics and the niceties of revenge tragedy seem far removed from the concerns of our society. Yet Titus Andronicus was not only extremely successful in Elizabethan times but also in modern productions, most notably that of Deborah Warner with Sonia Ritter as the rape victim, Lavinia. Of the three plays represented here, Titus Andronicus would seem to be the most inaccessible, but Jonathan Bate is an ardent and able champion of the play. Whereas earlier editors seemed almost apologetic, often unwilling to attribute the work to Shakespeare or detecting Strong indications of another hand,' Jonathan Bate, whilst acknowledging some problems, is a powerful advocate and his enthusiasm is infectious. He argues that its aesthetics and politics are sophisticated and complicated, deserving a wider audience, moreover that in its willingness to confront violence our culture has affinities with the sixteenth century.</P>
    <P>Titus Andronicus tells the story of a victorious Roman General who loses 21 of his 25 sons in the wars, kills his youngest in an unjust quarrel and then discovers his daughter shockingly raped and mutilated - all a trifle careless as Lady Bracknell might have said. The framework of the play is the revenge which Tamora seeks for the loss of her son sacrificed by Titus and the counter revenge which Titus pursues after the rape of his daughter by Tamora's other sons. Finally, Titus kills his daughter and cooks and serves up her rapists in a pie at a dinner to which he invites their mother, Tamora. Hardly, one might suppose, the ingredients of a successful drama, but Shakespeare was writing in a genre that was highly popular at the time, that of the revenge tragedy, which often contained elements of black humour and in which the obligations of personal versus public revenge could legitimately be explored. Public executions and bloody sports were then a popular form of entertainment. Today, we claim to be more civilised than the Elizabethans, but civil wars not only in the third world but also in Europe bear witness to the same barbarism, cruelty, and desire for revenge; meanwhile films with themes of torture, rape and cannibalism are box office sell-outs.</P>
    <P>If we still feel that rape and mutilation are not appropriate subjects for a play, Bate suggests that one reason why Warner's version was successful was because, as a twentieth century woman director, rape mattered more to her than it could ever have done to Shakespeare and this enabled her to show Lavinia as a real suffering person. This may be so, but the world of Titus Andronicus is wholly male orientated. Though Deborah Warner moved towards a realistic representation of Lavinia's feelings, Lavinia can only be shown from the outside, from the masculine viewpoint. After the savage attack, tongueless and with no hands, she has no way either of communicating her feelings or of identifying her attackers; though an educated woman, she does not even think of scratching words on the ground - that has to be suggested to her by a man. She is predominantly an object of pity, a visual symbol of her violation, but hardly a full human being. As for Titus, it is difficult to be fully sympathetic to a man who has taken his sons to the war and lost twenty-one of them, killed another in an unjust quarrel and then murdered his daughter because he is too sensitive to stand the sight of her.</P>
    <P>Antony and Cleopatra has seldom been out of favour and therefore needs no apologist: perhaps for that reason it seems more predictable than the other two volumes. The introduction is just as readable and takes modern criticism into account, but perhaps the approach has been made more with the new reader or good A-level student in mind rather than the advanced student. Little has changed in attitudes towards Cleopatra. If she is not condemned for ensnaring Antony, she is still condemned because she equivocates after his death. Wilders allows that Antony commits suicide in the knowledge that he has lost both the empire and Cleopatra. She, however, is condemned for pausing to wonder whether she has any future under Caesar and for opting for an easy way to die. Since she has just seen the consequences of Antony's bodged attempt it would seem sensible rather than cowardly to do so.</P>
    <P>As with the other volumes, the emphasis is on living theatre and contains an outline of its acting history. Antony and Cleopatra was subject to some of the most extreme experiments in opulent spectacle so beloved of the Victorians; one performance in 1890 lasted over four hours! Wilders shows how the play gains in clarity from simplicity of scenery and rapidity of performance. The muted act and scene divisions mentioned earlier allow the many changes of scene to flow much more smoothly even in the study, showing how the play works successfully without distractions of frequent scene changes. However for ease of reference it might be helpful if the scene numbers could be indicated a little more clearly. The notes are always full and there is some extremely helpful background information with reference to the historical sources. Wilders also discusses some of the omissions made by Shakespeare for dramatic impact. The map of the Roman empire is particularly useful. In order to make room for these, the full extracts from Plutarch which were given in Arden 2 have been replaced with shorter quotations in the footnotes.</P>
    <P>These new Ardens are attractively produced to the same high standards as previous editions. Whilst the introductions of earlier editions were probably often ignored, these make fascinating reading. The inclusion of so much new material and up to date criticism means that they are considerably longer than their forerunners. They will continue to form part of every student's library. Their size makes it unlikely to be generally used in rehearsal but they should be an indispensable part of every informed actor's bookshelf.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Liz Lewis</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
