      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>A selection of poems from Terrifying Ordeal</H2>
      <H3>by Paul Birtill<BR>Hearing Eye, Box 1, 99 Torriano Avenue, London NW5 2RX, 1996 3.50</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P>Paul Birtill is well known for his poems published in the Guardian and New Statesman, as well as on the London buses, and his plays being read at the Kings Head pub theatre, Islington, and the Southwark Playhouse (whose Patrons include Simon Hughes). Liberator readers will appreciate poems which take the piss out of Guardian and New Statesman readers</P>
    <P><B>Feminist</B></P>
    <BLOCKQUOTE>If I were a feminist I should prefer a bible-thumping misogynist to a liberated male who changes one in ten nappies and lets me go to my night-class on Thursdays....</BLOCKQUOTE>
    <P>but will perhaps not sympathise with Birtill's socialist antics including flying the red flag from his Hampstead council flat in sympathy with the coup against Gorbachov! This collection, published by Torriano Poets, includes a cross-section of Paul's bitingly black humour (he once had a screenplay rejected by the BBC on the grounds that it needed to contain at least some redemption) and his angst-ridden Liverpool Catholic work.</P>
    <P>As the volume concludes:</P>
    <BLOCKQUOTE>Poetry doesn't normally sell, but mine might because I intend to embark on a series of bizarre motiveless murders on and around Hampstead Heath. Poetry doesn't normally sell, but mine might....</BLOCKQUOTE>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Kiron Reid</B></P>
