<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 235 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 235 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Doctor Who - The Evil of the Daleks</H2>
      <H3>BBC Audio Collection, 7.99</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <BLOCKQUOTE>"Somewhere in the Dalek race, there are three Daleks with the Human Factor. Gradually they will come to question. They will persuade other Daleks to question. You will have a rebellion on your planet!"</BLOCKQUOTE>
    <P>My political views came from some odd directions. While Weekending first got me interested in party politics, Doctor Who  was instrumental in converting me to liberalism. I read and re-read the novelisations of stories like Doctor Who and the Silurians  and The Green Death  (which even has Jeremy Thorpe as Prime Minister), with messages about tolerance, equality and ecology, and if the Doctor isn't the epitome of a do-your-own-thing, anarchic liberal, I don't know who is (if you'll excuse the pun).</P>
    <P>The Evil of the Daleks  was a seven-episode story. Thanks to BBC short-termism, only one episode remains on video, and this slightly fuzzy audio version only survives thanks to a fan's tape recorder (with typical grace, the BBC refused to credit him, claiming he shouldn't have taped them in the first place). This is a great shame, as only one video- released story beats it: The Deadly Assassin , which starred Tom Baker, whose moody tones narrate this feast for fans of the late, great Patrick Troughton. Script, performances, period detail and the Daleks for once being sinister, evil manipulators rather than seeming just stupid robots' all mark this out as something very special indeed. The plot revolves around the Doctor being lured to Victorian times by the Daleks to discover for them what makes humans so successful. While the Doctor manages to infect three Daleks with the Human Factor' to provoke a civil war, the Daleks' plan is also not what it seems. Patrick Troughton is utterly compelling as the Doctor, and the central message that questioning, self-reliant individuals must be championed over rigid authority makes this perhaps the most powerfully liberal Doctor Who  story ever made. Even stripped down to sound alone, it's also one of the two best.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Alex Wilcock</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
