<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 235 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 235 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Richard III</H2>
      <H3>(Director Richard Loncraine)</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <BLOCKQUOTE>"I, that am curtail'd of this fair proportion,<BR>Cheated of feature by dissembling nature ...<BR>Why, I, in this weak piping time of peace,<BR>Have no delight to pass away the time."</BLOCKQUOTE>
    <P>Watching Ian McKellan's incredible performance as the twisted Richard III, spinning from power, to charm, to a single moment of naked savagery, I remembered how this quotation introduced the Daleks' creator, Davros, in the best Doctor Who  novelisation. Perhaps the American resurrectors of the good Doctor could use some of their vast budget to hire McKellan, as Richard has never been more clearly Davros's glorious ancestor (even to the point of both being swathed in Nazi imagery).</P>
    <P>McKellan's Richard is one of the screen's finest villains, in one of the screen's finest adaptations of Shakespeare. I'm usually wary of modernised' Shakespeare, but this study in political evil could almost have been written for the 1930s. While the Queen being smeared with witchcraft jars in this context, it is noticeable because everything else fits. Turning the soliloquy I quote to a triumphant public speech that segues into a poisonous afterthought over the urinals, for example, uses the potential of a film in a way that too few interpreters have the imagination for.</P>
    <P>McKellan clearly enjoys himself tremendously, using unmistakable symbols of his wickedness while never lurching into pantomime villainy. The scene where he helps feed' a boar is cruelly funny, just as you know that Richard is the most despicable villain because no-one else could send the nationally beloved Nigel Hawthorne to an ignominious end.</P>
    <P>The fun is increased by McKellan's nods to other films - surely no other Shakespeare adaptation can have modelled its opening scene on Star Wars , or fashioned an ending of gloriously bad taste from White Heat  and An American Werewolf in London .</P>
    <P>The film paints a frighteningly compelling vision of an alternative 1930s, where it is Britain that insidiously slides from decadence to fascism, until suddenly you know that Nuremberg is just around the corner. Startling use is made of buildings that are hardly transformed - most notably Battersea Power Station as the Tower. The abdicated King Edward is clearly retained here with sly twists around his American wife and his infamous wimpy fascism swiftly replaced by Richard's real thing'. Edward Hardwicke's Stanley starts off militaristic and right-wing, in blue RAF uniform; one of the most chilling aspects of the film is the way the militarism gradually increases, until suddenly the civilians don black and Stanley is left looking like an old- fashioned pinko simply by standing still, rather like Roy Hattersley in today's Labour Party.</P>
    <P>Oddly, the flavour it leaves reminds me most not of films or of Shakespeare at all, but of the superb 1987 ITV series Knights of God, which only I and about three other people seem to have watched. That also had Britain ruled by fascists and a modern civil war, with the armoured vehicles driving in at the close to restore the real' monarchy . . . which just goes to show that I always love a good story, whatever its ideology. Mind you, the best character in that was the villain, just as in McKellan's film I was rooting for Richard all the way - it's criminal that the film has only garnered two minor OSCAR nominations. Go and see it. And boo the hero.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Alex Wilcock</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
