<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 236 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 236 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>The Almanac of British Politics</H2>
      <H3>by Robert Waller and Byron Criddle<BR>Routledge 1996 25</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P>As Simon Titley described the Elections Yearbook as "one for the trainspotters" <A HREF="../234/index.htm">(Liberator 234)</A>, then this must be an political anorak's dream. Every constituency laid out in glorious detail: demography, geography, history, previous members and candidates, boundary changes, party local election strongholds, quirks of constituency character and the odd prediction or two. Those with a professional interest in these things - like myself - will devour every paragraph. Casual activists will turn first to their own constituency, and then work through Lib Dem seats and targets. They are likely to be disappointed. Waller is Conservative with a big and a small 'c'. I have often rubbished the comments of previous editions, only to find them entirely justified on election night. If recent history has taught us anything, it is that caution is all in psephology.</P>
    <P>Nonetheless, the picture may be better than Waller suggests. He forecasts the Lib Dems holding all present seats, save for question marks over Gordon, Inverness, and, curiously, Tweeddale, Ettrick and Lauderdale. He is optimistic about David Rendel's chances in Newbury, and Chris Davies's in Oldham East and Saddleworth, and looks to interesting battles in Christchurch and Eastleigh. There are predictions too of gains in St Ives, West Devon, Torbay, Somerton and Frome, Isle of Wight, Portsmouth South, Oxford West, Colchester, Hazel Grove and Southport, with discreet winks towards surprises in Salisbury and Mid Dorset. But elsewhere Waller is pretty scathing of Lib Dem chances.</P>
    <P>The problem is that publication of this book was delayed by legal fine-combing of the MPs' biographies (more anon), and it shows. Emma Nicholson is still "a moderate One Nation Tory aristocrat in a Lib Dem-threatened seat", whilst Alan Howarth is "assured of a life tenure of one of England's safest Tory seats" in the first paragraph, but has "dramatically joined Labour" in the second. More seriously, no account is taken of the May 1995 local elections, smearing egg-on-face over comments like "the Liberal Democrats have never achieved  dominance in local government" in Weston-super-Mare. Waller's predictions look less secure given this demonstration of the radically shifting political environment.</P>
    <P>By far the most entertaining part of the book is the thumb-nail sketches of MPs and leading challengers (Criddle's contribution). Reverence and deference do not get a look in. Anyone involved in higher education will surely allow a smirk at John Patten being remembered "for converting the polytechnics into universities, and vice-versa".</P>
    <P>On the whole, Lib Dems emerge relatively unscathed, apart from (or because of) a liberal scattering of words like "dull" and "uncharismatic". Bob Maclennan, we are reminded, is "the only contemporary MP to have been elected for three different parties in the same constituency....achieved       without igniting the heather or offering a single soundbite"; whilst if an exception must prove the rule, how about Liz Lynne, "an eye-catching figure in primary colours". Hours of fun.</P>
    <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Michael Woods</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
      <map name="BUTTONS">
        <area shape="polygon" alt="Home Page" coords="32,2,4,23,1,56,85,56,81,25,56,22,33,2,33,3" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/index.htm">
        <area shape="polygon" alt="The Collective" coords="88,40,91,59,138,59,144,47,118,1,101,0,96,39,89,39" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/Collective/Collective.html">
        <area shape="polygon" alt="Read Liberator" coords="151,41,148,56,218,55,207,45,214,29,195,22,196,2,165,0,153,40" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/read.htm">
        <area shape="polygon" alt="Write for Liberator" coords="224,56,273,57,273,8,253,0,229,3,219,31,223,49" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/write.htm">
