<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 236 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 236 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Why I Am A Liberal Democrat</H2>
      <H3>edited by Duncan Brack<BR>Liberal Democrat Publications 1996 6.95</H3>
    </CENTER>
	 <P>Inspired by a similar volume 'Why I Am A Liberal' published in 1885, Duncan Brack wrote to a large number of leading Liberal Democrats and party sympathisers, asking them to write a few paragraphs explaining why they are Liberal Democrats. The result is over 100 short essays, and almost every one is a 'measure of the man' (or woman).</P>
	 <P>The best are those which combine the personal and the political, the emotional and the rational. I would include Earl Russell and Bernard Greaves, who both write with passion.</P>
	 <P>Some are ideologically spot-on but emotionally detached and reveal little of the author's personal motivation (Gordon Lishman, Alan Sherwell). Some are surprisingly good (Richard   Holme, Philip Goldenberg). Some  are long-winded manifestos (David Howarth), sometimes arranged in bullet-point form (Mike Bell), or as a numbered list with no shape or priorities (Paddy Ashdown). Some are shallow celebrity endorsements of the party which fail to go much beyond proportional representation and generally being nice (Barry Norman, Nicholas Parsons).</P>
	 <P>A certain generation regularly cites the Suez crisis and Jo Grimond as its formative influences (Michael Steed, Geoff Tordoff, Paul Tyler). One person (Tony Greaves) manages to combine the long-term vision with the short-term frustrations most of us experience. In doing so, Tony probably speaks best for most Liberator readers.</P>
	 <P>Above all, it's good to see Liberal Democrat Publications producing an ideological book instead of another cuddly toy or baseball cap. Does this signify a turning point in the party's attitude towards its own fundamental values? Is ideology finally coming out of the closet? Let's hope so.</P>
	 <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Simon Titley</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
      <map name="BUTTONS">
        <area shape="polygon" alt="Home Page" coords="32,2,4,23,1,56,85,56,81,25,56,22,33,2,33,3" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/index.htm">
        <area shape="polygon" alt="The Collective" coords="88,40,91,59,138,59,144,47,118,1,101,0,96,39,89,39" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/Collective/Collective.html">
        <area shape="polygon" alt="Read Liberator" coords="151,41,148,56,218,55,207,45,214,29,195,22,196,2,165,0,153,40" href="http://www.liberator.org.uk/read.htm">
