<DOCHDR>
http://www.liberator.org.uk:80/236/r3.htm 194.207.26.203 19970122145736 text/html 5360
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 22 Jan 1997 14:57:23 GMT
Server: Apache/0.8.10
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5188
Last-modified: Tue, 21 Jan 1997 13:37:54 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN//2.0">
<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 236 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 236 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Nixon</H2>
      <H3>(Dir Olive Stone, Cert 15)</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P>Richard Nixon's dramatic downfall is just far enough away to be treated as history rather than as polemic on contemporary events.</P>
    <P>Even at the time, it was recognised that, while disgraced by Watergate and by campaign practices dubious even by American standards, Nixon had his achievement in the rapprochement with China.</P>
    <P>That shows the contradiction in Nixon. He might have been a crook at the head of a democracy. But unlike, say, the former leaders of Italy, he does not seem to have greatly enriched himself. Stone suggests that Nixon trusted no-one, not even Kissinger, but saw the ends he was striving for as great deeds. Thus he was not very particular about the means he used to win and keep the presidency.</P>
    <P>Clearly, the political life and formative years of such a  figure must be turned over thoroughly in a biographical film.</P>
    <P>But its single outstanding characteristic is its length, at 192 minutes. Quite honestly, it does not justify this. If Nixon lost 30 minutes or so it would rank as a remarkable achievement, because for most of the time it does hold attention. Crucial to this is Anthony Hopkins's impressive performance as Nixon, on screen almost the entire time.</P>
    <P>Towards the end, with Watergate bringing his world crashing down, I started wishing that Nixon would sign his resignation letter and clear off without yet another self-justificatory soliloquy.</P>
    <P>What Stone does do well is relate Nixon's early life to what he became. His father was a struggling lemon farmer, his mother a religious maniac who in the 1920s addressed her family in the language of the King James Bible, and instilled the fear of God. Nixon saw two brothers die young and clearly felt the weight of his mother's expectations for the family fall on him. Though the use of flashback becomes tiresome, and of sledgehammer-like subtlety, after a while,  we get the point that Nixon's upbringing left him with fatal flaws.</P>
    <P>Nixon's role as Senator McCarthy's hatchetman during the anti-Communist witch hunts of the post-war years, and as Eisenhower's vice-president, are only sketched in before we get to the crucial event which paved the way for Nixon's come-back in the 1960s: the Kennedy assassination.</P>
    <P>Having advanced one conspiracy theory in JFK, Stone cannot resist another. This one is that vice-president Nixon was involved in covert action against Cuba without Eisenhower's knowledge. After Kennedy became president, these continued with a momentum of their own, and a Cuban exile plot to shoot Castro turned into a plot to shoot Kennedy.</P>
    <P>How is never made clear, because the implication is that  Nixon knows this happened, but not exactly how. Even at the start of Watergate, he is uneasily sure that if investigators dig deep enough they will find something to link him to Lee Harvey Oswald.</P>
    <P>Nixon's animosity towards the Kennedys is not just that towards opponents. They represent the wealthy, liberal east coast elite whom Nixon despises. Nixon was the first Republican of modern times to detach a large chunk of the white working class from the Democrats, and the latter have not yet managed to undo this. There are limited parallels with Thatcherism.</P>
    <P>It would be easy to create a victim by depicting Nixon as either a monster or a great man traduced. Stone's film succeeds by showing both sides, and it holds more dramatic tension than one might expect for its first two hours. But by the time of Watergate, its length and repetitiousness cries out for the editing it so clearly lacks.</P>
	 <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Mark Smulian</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
      <map name="BUTTONS">
