<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 236 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 236 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Underground</H2>
      <H3>(Subtitled, Dir Emir Kusturica Cert 15)</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P>To put this into any particular genre would be  difficult -black comedy, political history even buddy movie would all be reasonable epithets. It is a story in three parts which revolves around two friends and black marketeers, Marko and Blacky . They appear at the outset as two swashbuckling Serbian heroes set against the invading Hitler regime. More than once the image of a remake of the Three Musketeers crossed my mind as the contrived set piece fights were played out.</P>
    <P>As Hitler's forces make their progress Blacky literally goes underground with friends and family into the cellars of one of Marko's relatives. There they remain for twenty years manufacturing weapons for the eventual overthrow of Hitler's army, while Marko above ground makes progress in Tito's Government and get's the girl that earlier both had craved. Blacky's eventual break out is a farcical tragicomedy as he comes across a film crew making a film of his own revolutionary past.</P>
    <P>The third section is set in modern times with Blacky leading a Serbian army troupe in war torn Yugoslavia, while Marko is an aging wheelchair bound arms dealer. The ever present theme of betrayal in a corrupt, value-free world is often lost as the comedy is played out. The twin heroes manage to survive bombings with the resilience normally only associated with cartoon characters and this makes them somewhat less sympathetic when the tragedy finally unfolds. </P>
    <P>The fantastical portrayal of the action is embellished throughout by the recurring image of a marching band bellowing out its repetitive refrains in a style best described as Balkan folk music meets Dixieland jazz. The sharp photography and the rich sounds become almost overwhelming for the viewer at times, especially as this film runs for nearly three hours. The final frames are well played however and I suspect that if one had the stamina for a repeat viewing much of the animal imagery would build in significance.</P>
    <P>This is the sort of film that just misses out on potential cult status but is worthy alternative viewing to the current Hollywood output. It gained a prize at Cannes, of course, but you cannot always rely on such awards to establish a film's worth. See it for yourself.</P>
	 <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>William Tranby</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
