<HTML>
  <HEAD>
    <TITLE>Liberator: Issue 236 Reviews</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
  <BODY BACKGROUND="../backgrnd.jpg">
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="../read.gif">
      <H1><IMG SRC="../lib_on.gif"><BR>Issue 236 Reviews</H1>
      <BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>
      <H2>Mighty Aphrodite</H2>
      <H3>(Dir Woody Allen, Cert 15)</H3>
    </CENTER>
    <P>This was the Allen film that was well panned by the London critics largely because, they said, at 60 Woody Allen cannot get away with playing the romantic hero who gets the girl. Especially as the girl in this piece is in her early twenties and about six inches taller than him. Well stranger things than this happen in real life and especially to Woody himself since his affair with Mia Farrow's adopted daughter became headline news a couple of years back.</P>
    <P>It has long been the case, although not accepted by the director himself, that Woody uses the medium of film as a kind cinematic therapy to work through his own neuroses. It  was certainly the case for example with Husbands and Wives, as the Farrow break up emerged, but if there is anything here of Woody's own life it is either a confession that at his age he enjoys the fantasy of having an affair with a six foot tall blonde, or that the quest to find the real parents of adopted children may lead to some interesting surprises.</P>
    <P>Whatever the theories for his motivation for the film, Woody has certainly not excelled himself here. The story revolves around Allen's character Lenny's search for the real mother of his adopted son who seems to be unbelievably bright. It turns out that the mother is the prostitute and porn star Judy Cum.</P>
    <P>There are some lovely one liners, but perhaps not enough of them. There is a lovely cameo role from Michael Rappaport as a truly dumb boxer. And Mira Sorvino's portrayal of the happy hooker is certainly the highlight, although I question whether her performance is really worthy of the Oscar she won for best supporting actress. The Greek chorus idea is a well constructed comic distraction which completes the film with a Broadway style rendition of the Morecambe & Wise song "Give me Sunshine".</P>
    <P>But the real weakness of the film is the poor casting of Helena Bonham Carter as Woody's wife. There is simply no explanation or character building to convince the audience why these two are married. And it is this weak base from the outset which makes the contrast with the developing relationship between Allen and Sorvino even more unbelievable.</P>
    <P>So this is not Allen at his best. But it is suitable for a pleasant afternoon where all one wants is a slightly silly feel-good movie. And real fans of Woody Allen will forgive him his bizarre fantasies for portraying a middle aged sports writer who makes it with a woman at least thirty years his younger. After all this is film as therapy...isn't it?</P>
	 <P ALIGN=RIGHT><B>William Tranby</B></P>
    <CENTER>
      <IMG SRC="../border2.gif"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
      <A HREF="http://www.liberator.org.uk/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/buttons.map"><IMG SRC="../buttons.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#BUTTONS" ISMAP></A>
