<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>The Freedom Server - Book Store</TITLE>        <META Name="Author" CONTENT="William W. Morgan">        <META NAME="Keywords"		CONTENT="Galambos,government,coercion,capitalism,			economics,Bedeman,politics,books. liberty,freedom,			justice,history">			<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">    </HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><HR noshade><CENTER><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><hr noshade><p>This page has been visited </p><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Books.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <p>since 1996, March 16th, although The Freedom Server was created on1995, August 1. <BR></p><A NAME="Books"></A><hr noshade><H2>Bibliography and BookStore</H2></CENTER><HR>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, June 27<br>Version: 002k<HR><CENTER><H4>| <A HREF="Index.html">Home</A> | <A HREF="Contents.html">Table of Contents</A> |</H4><hr noshade></CENTER><p>Most of my teachers, and thus my best friends, are people from the pastwho--because of primitive biological technology--are now physiologicallydead. I emphasize the fact that it is their bodies--and unfortunately theirbrains--which are dead, but not their ideas.</p><p>To illustrate a very important point, I would like to repeat here two ofthe quotations from those that appear elsewhere in these pages: </p><UL>  <LI>Horatius (Quintus Horatius Flaccus) {65 BC - 8 BC}    	&quot;<B>Exegi monumentum aere perennius.</B>&quot;  	  <LI>[<B>I have executed a memorial longer lasting than bronze.</B>     	<p>  	{The significance, endurance and power of <I>right</I> ideas, as opposed  	to the short-term influence of actions}]	</p></UL><p>In the film <I>The Land of the Pharaohs,</I> Pharaoh spent his life buildinga great pyramid to house his mortal remains and to preserve his life andits accomplishments in history. The pyramids are truly impressive, but wetend to think of them as an object, more than the person who created them.And they are slowly--and sadly--crumbling to dust.</p><p>About two thousand years ago, around 250 BC, one of the most&quot;important&quot; and well-known people in the world was the Romangeneral Marcellus. A contemporary of his, Archimedes, was virtuallyunknown. Tragically, and in defiance of the orders of Marcellus, one ofhis soldiers murdered Archimedes. </p><p>Now, more than two thousands years later, their roles--in the sense oftheir prominence in history--are reversed. The reputation of Archimedesand the recognition of his importance continue to grow, while that ofMarcellus goes down in history. The correct direction for all those whodestroy property and lessen the quality of life. In contrast to thosewho create property--especially in the sense of rational and moralknowledge that is useful in the creation of additional such knowledge.Knowledge that increases man's understanding of his world and has the<I>potential</I> to add to the quality of life. A potential greatlyattenuated by a social structure based on coercion that does notunderstand the difference between right and not-right.  The reputationof such people go <B>up</B> in history, not down. </p><p>The main goal of <I>The Freedom Server&copy;</I> is the correction of thisproblem. The knowledge and information presented here, and in the bookslisted herein, take a step in that direction. In connection with the abovethought on immortality and importance in history, and the knowledge to beobtained from the books listed here, it is worth considering the followingquotation:</p><UL>    	<p>  	<LI>Wren, Christopher {1632 - 1723} &quot;<B>...Lector, Si		monumentum requiris, circumspice...</B>&quot;	</p>		<p>	<LI>[<B>...Reader, if you seek his monument, look around...</B>].	</p>		<p>	<LI>Dictionary of Quotations, J.J. & M.J. Cohen, Penguin Books,		1985 Edition, p. 427	</p>		<p>	<LI>Inscription in St. Paul's Cathedral, London (Written by	Wren's son. It should therefore be properly ascribed to his son, but	I do not know the son's name at the moment, however the gratitude for	this beautiful and elegant tribute goes to the son of Christoper	Wren. He understood importance in history more than most people. It	was not the buildings themselves, but the knowledge of how to	design and build them.)	</p></UL><p>The books listed here, and many others not yet listed, have greatly influencedmy thinking, and it is with pleasure and gratitude to the authors, publishers,and booksellers that I list these books here.</p><HR>	<p>	<LI><B>Caveat Lector!</B>	</p>	<p>	As I may have said elsewhere, not everything in every book is	right, however almost any book has something of value in it.	Even something which is wrong may be an aid to learning <I>what</I>	is wrong, illustrating the problem, and providing clues to solution	of the problem. In reading any book a person should remember	what Leonard Reed said:	</p>	<UL>  	<LI>Reed, Leonard [suspected source - 1898 - 1983]  	</p>	<p>	<LI>&quot;Indeed, any serious student will want to read any book	with care and discrimination, gleaning from it such truth as he	can find, and rejecting that which to him seems false or	misleading.&quot;	</p></UL><HR><p>As I mentioned, this is not a book store in the sense of being able to orderthe books, although this could be true in the future. However, since I wantpeople to know where they may find the books, where known I have listedthe ISBN, the last known price, and at least one source for the book. Thekey to the source may be found by clicking on the abbreviation, which willtake you to the source code listing at the end of this document.</p><p>Lastly, it must be remembered that <B>all knowledge is related</B>, andthat no one book or essay will provide complete answers to a problem. Itis therefore necessary to read many things and, as Leonard Reed said, &quot;extractfrom them what truth you find&quot; add it to others, think and create hypotheses,and look for corroboration in the world around you. Only then can you createwhat is called a <I>theory.</I> </p><p>Books are listed alphabetically <B>by author</B>.</p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER><H4>| <A HREF="#A">A</A>| <A HREF="#B">B</A>| <A HREF="#C">C</A>| <A HREF="#D">D</A>| <A HREF="#E">E</A>| <A HREF="#F">F</A>| <A HREF="#G">G</A>| <A HREF="#H">H</A>| <A HREF="#I">I</A>| <A HREF="#J">J</A>|   <A HREF="#K">K</A>|<A HREF="#L">L</A> |</h4><h4>| <A HREF="#M">M</A>| <A HREF="#N">N</A>| <A HREF="#O">O</A>| <A HREF="#P">P</A>|<A HREF="#Q">Q</A>|<A HREF="#R">R</A>|<A HREF="#S">S</A>|<A HREF="#T">T</A>|<A HREF="#U">U</A>|<A HREF="#V">V</A>|<A HREF="#W">W</A>|<A HREF="#X">X</A>|<A HREF="#Y">Y</A>|<A HREF="#Z">Z</A> |</H4></CENTER><HR NOSHADE><CENTER><A NAME="A"></A><h2>A</h2><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE><A NAME="B"></A><H2>B</H2></CENTER><HR NOSHADE><DL>	<DT><B>The Law</B> 	<DT>by Bastiat, Frederic 	<DT>ISBN 	<DT>Price - $2.95 (P) - 76 pages 	<DT><A HREF="#F">Foundation for Economic Education</A> 	<DT>Order Code: 21F </dl>    <dl>	<DT><B>Value & Price</B> 	<DT>by B&ouml;hm-Bawerk, Eugen von 	<DT>ISBN 0-910884-01-3 	<DT>Price - US$9.95 	<DT><A HREF="#L">Libertarian Press</A> </dl>	<dl>	<DT><B>The Discoverers</B> 	<DT>by Boorstin, Daniel J. 	<DT>ISBN 0-394-72625-1 	<DT>Price - $16.00 - 1985 - pb 	<DT><A HREF="#V">Vintage Books</A> </DL><p>One of the best history books ever written, it identifies many of thosein history who created property rather than destroyed it. It includes fewif any politicians, whether civil, military, or religious since--as anyserious student of history knows--they are insignificant in long-termhistory.</p><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="C"></A>C</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><B>A Pillar of Iron</B>   <DT>by Caldwell, Taylor   <DT>ISBN 0-449-20428-6   <DT>Price US$5.95 - 1983   <DT><A HREF="#FAW">Fawcett Books</A> </DL>Reading this very readable historical novel of the life of Marcus TulliusCicero, if you did not know better, from the rendition of the problems ofsociety you would think it was any current major city of the world. Thisconfirms that in one area of knowlege--that of man's social structures--wedo not learn from history. <BR><BR>If this inability to learn from history were true in the so-called &quot;naturalsciences&quot; (more accurately termed the non-volitional sciences), wewould most likely still not have the wheel. And certainly not computers,television, and jet aircraft. Yet the same epistemological tools which permittedthis to occur in the non-volitional sciences can also be used to createknowledge in the volitional sciences (incorrectly called the &quot;socialsciences,&quot; which are neither social nor science, representing a contradictionin terms). <BR><DL>  <DT><B>Writings of Thomas Paine</B>   <DT>by Conway, Moncure D.   <DT>ISBN - not applicable   <DT>Price - unknown - 1894-1896 </DL>Generally thought to be the best biography of Thomas Paine, the intellectual&quot;father&quot; of the United States. And the man who educated the worldto the fact that they did not need kings. Sadly, he did not--and probablycould not have realized--that changing the ruler's name to &quot;president&quot;would not change the basic problem of a societal structure based on coercion.<BR><BR>My personal feeling is that <A HREF="#KEANE">Tom Paine,</A> by John Keanewill become the new standard on the life of Thomas Paine. <BR><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="D"></A>D</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="E"></A>E</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="F"></A>F</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="G"></A>G</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="H"></A>H</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><B>The Conquest of Poverty</B>   <DT>by Hazlitt, Henry   <DT>ISBN   <DT>Price - US$19.95 (P) - $24.95 (H) - 290 pages   <DT><A HREF="#F">Foundation for Economic Education</A>   <DT>Order No: 147F   <DT><BR>  <DT>Business production, not political-state programs, has made all theprogress toward the conquest of poverty.   <DT><BR>  <DT><B>Economics in One Lesson</B>   <DT>by Hazlitt, Henry   <DT>ISBN 0-87000-427-1   <DT>Price - US$10.95 (P) - 76 pages   <DT><A HREF="#F">Foundation for Economic Education</A>   <DT>Order No: 143   <DT><BR>  <DT>This book on economic principles brilliantly illustrates the seenand unseen consequences of economic and political actions.   <DT></DL><HR NOSHADE><H2><CENTER><A NAME="I"></A>I</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="J"></A>J</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="K"></A>K</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><A NAME="KEANE"></A><B>Tom Paine</B>   <DT>by Keane, John   <DT>ISBN 0-7475-20070   <DT>Price - &#163;25.00 - hc - 1995   <DT><A HREF="#B">Bloomsbury Publishing plc</A> </DL>&quot;More than any other figure of the 18th century, Tom Paine (1787-1809)strikes our times like a trumpet blast from a distant world.&quot; So beginsJohn Keane's magnificent biography of one of freedom's greatest champions,a man whose uncanny familiarity to us is partly traceable to his own stupendousachievements. <BR><BR>Setting his compeling narrative in a vivid social backdrop, John Keane meldstogether the public and private sides of Paine's life in a remarkable pieceof scholarship which is also thrilling to read. Meticulously researchedand drawing on newly available material from the United States, Britain,France, Poland, Hungary, Germany, and Belgium, this is the definitive biographyof a man whose life and work are very important to the construction of arational and durable society whose time-scale of existence will be concomitantwith that of our local universe. <BR><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="L"></A>L</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><B>A Greater Than Napoleon</B>   <DT>by Liddell Hart, Basil Henry   <DT>ISBN 0-8196-0269-8   <DT>281 p. - 1927 - US$24.00   <DT>Biblo & Tannen Booksellers &amp; Publishers, Inc.   <DT>P. O. Box 302   <DT>Cheshire, CT 06410   <DT>Tel: (1-800) 272-8778 </DL>This book, a biography of Publius Cornelius Scipio--<CITE>Scipio Africanus</CITE>--wasoriginally published in the UK in about 1930 and went out of print shortlythereafter. It was not printed again until 1971, by Biblo & Tannen in NewYork. I think it is again out of print. <BR><BR>Publius Cornelius Scipio was a man far beyond his time. In an age of relativelygreater barbarism he was a decent man of great foresight, intellect, andhigh character. The major proof of this--although there are many others--ishis statement when offered the rulership of the Roman Empire, saying that&quot;no man should rule other men, and certainly not for a life time.&quot;Eventually he did accept the consulship for one year, but only as a tokenof his gratitude to the those who supported him in defense of his country--againstthe aggressor Hannibal--in the Second Punic War. <BR><BR>His relatively less significant achievement is that of being the greatestgeneral of all time, by his defeat of the man most people incorrectly believeto be the greatest general, Hannibal Barca. Scipio, in defense of his homeland,defeated Hannibal's forces in every battle they fought, although almostalways outnumbered by at least two to one, and up to five to one. And, intheir only personal encounter, he defeated Hannibal at the Battle of Zamaon 202 BC, August 19th, while outnumbered three to one, ending the war.Hannibal lost most of his army of 65,000 men, while Scipio lost a fractionof his 20,000 mean. <BR><BR>Conventional historians should at least recognize him as the founder and&quot;father&quot; of the Roman Empire for, after the defeat of Hannibal,Rome was the unchallenged master of the &quot;Occidental&quot; world. And,in fact, it can be said that Scipio, by his defeat of Hannibal, ensuredthat Europeans would have an Occidental heritage rather than the Orientalone they would have had had Hannibal won the Second Punic War. <BR><BR>It is almost certain that Gen. Douglas MacArthur had studied Scipio, bothin his display of military strategy and tactics, and in MacArthur's treatmentof Japan. Scipio appointed his defeated enemy, Hannibal, as Military Governorof Carthage, with the result that within a few years Carthage was more prosperousthan it had ever been. <BR><BR>Scipio's life offers many clues to those who wish to understand the problemsof the current society of man, and to the solution to these problems. <BR><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="M"></A>M</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><B>The Anti-Capitalist Mentality</B>   <DT>by Mises, Ludwig von   <DT>ISBN   <DT>Price - US$8.95 - Paper   <DT><A HREF="#F">Foundation for Economic Education</A>   <DT>Order No. 215 </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="N"></A>N</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="O"></A>O</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="P"></A>P</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><B>The Age of Reason</B>   <DT>by Paine, Thomas   <DT>ISBN 0-806505-4   <DT>Price US$8.95 - Paper - 192 p.   <DT><A HREF="#CIT">Citadel</A> </DL>Certainly the best book ever published on the subject of religion. Becauseof this book Paine is often accused of being an atheist, yet on the veryfirst page Paine clearly states that he believes in God. <BR><BR>For anyone who thinks religion is a bit confusing and doesn't make muchsense, this book will clear things up for them. If it doesn't, then thereader has serious problems. <BR><DL>  <DT><B>Common Sense</B>   <DT>by Paine, Thomas   <DT>ISBN 0-14-039016-2   <DT>Price - US$3.95   <DT><A HREF="#P">Penguin Books</A> </DL>Paine wrote three of the best selling books of the 18th century. <CITE>CommonSense</CITE> was published on 1776, January 10th, and by July had sold 500,000copies. This in a population of three million people. Of which approximately500,000 were slaves. That would be equivalent to selling more than 38 millioncopies with today's US population. <BR><BR>With Common Sense, Paine became the intellectual father of the AmericanRevolution, the only true social revolution in man's history. All the resthave been merely rebellions against established authority, with nothingresembling a solution for man's societal problems. <BR><DL>  <DT><B>The Rights of Man</B>   <DT>by Paine, Thomas   <DT>ISBN   <DT>Price </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="Q"></A>Q</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="R"></A>R</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><B>Alas Shrugged</B>   <DT>by Rand, Ayn   <DT>ISBN 0-451-17192-6   <DT>Price   <DT><A HREF="#SIG">Signet, NAL-Dutton</A>   <DT><B>The Fountainhead</B>   <DT>by Rand, Ayn   <DT>ISBN 0-452-27333-1   <DT>Price US$14.95 - 1994 - Paper   <DT><A HREF="#PLU">Plume - NAL - Dutton</A> </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="S"></A>S</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="T"></A>T</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><B>Philipp Reis: Inventor of the Telephone</B>   <DT>by Thompson, Sylvanus P.   <DT>ISBN 0-405-06060-0   <DT>Price - $14.95   <DT><A HREF="#A">Arno Press</A> </DL>After reading this and other books on Philipp Reis, there can be littledoubt that he is more surely the inventor of the telephone than Bell, whostole the idea from Reis as he attempted to steal the airplane from Wilburand Orville Wright. <BR><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="U"></A>U</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="V"></A>V</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="W"></A>W</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><B>Mainspring of Human Progress</B>   <DT>by Weaver, Henry Grady   <DT>ISBN   <DT>Price - $5.95 (P) - 270 pages   <DT><A HREF="#F">Foundation for Economic Education</A>   <DT>Order No: 400F </DL>Perhaps the best available introduction to the concept and history of freedom.<BR><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="X"></A>X</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="Y"></A>Y</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H2><CENTER><A NAME="Z"></A>Z</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><H3><CENTER>Bookseller &amp; Publisher Connections</CENTER></H3><hr><A NAME="A"></A><DL>  <DT>Arno Press   <DT>Not Listed in Books in Print   <DT>May be out of business   <DT>U.S.A. </DL><hr>