<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>The Freedom Server - Book Reviews</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"></HEAD><BODY><HR NOSHADE><H1><CENTER>The Freedom Server&copy;</CENTER></H1><H3><CENTER>Second Edition</CENTER></H3><P><CENTER><HR><BR><BR>This page has been visited <BR><BR><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Book-Reviews.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <BR><BR>since 1996, March 16th, although it was created on 1995, August 1. <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><A NAME="Contents"></A></CENTER><H2><CENTER>Book Reviews</CENTER></H2><HR><TT>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, June 1<BR>Version: 002i<BR></TT><HR><H4><CENTER>| <A HREF="index.html">Home</A> | <A HREF="Contents.html">Tableof Contents</A> |</CENTER></H4><HR NOSHADE><H3><CENTER>Reviews by The Universal Salvage Corporation</CENTER></H3><LI><A HREF="#FREE">The Freedom Revolution</A> <BR><BR><LI><A HREF="#PAINE">Thomas Paine: A Political Life</A> <BR><BR><HR><H3><CENTER>Reviews of <A HREF="#MCGE">Prof. Robert W. McGee</A></CENTER></H3><LI><A HREF="#SHAP">The Shaping of Environmentalism</A> <BR><BR><LI><A HREF="#MIRA">The Mirage of Oil Protection</A> <BR><BR><LI><A HREF="#MKT">Free Market Environmentalism</A> <BR><BR><HR><BR><H3><CENTER>Reviews of <A HREF="#RME">Prof. Richard M. Ebeling</A></CENTER></H3><LI><A HREF="#SD">Shakedown: How the Government Screws You from A to Z</A><BR><BR>See a related essay from the Foundation for Economic Education publicationThe Freeman, written by James Bovard, the author of this book. <BR><BR><A HREF="../FEE/Economic-Education.html#SF">Seizure Fever: The War on PropertyRights</A> <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><H3><A NAME="FREE"></A>The Freedom Revolution</H3><DL>  <DD>by Dick Armey   <DD>Regnery - 318 pp - US$24.95 </DL><UL>The cover of the book says that the new &quot;House Majority Leader&quot;tells why big government failed, why freedom works, and how we will rebuildAmerica. <BR><BR>A person who understand history and semantic precision need read no moreto know that the author understand neither of these concepts. Since thebook proposes a &quot;solution&quot; to the problems of society within thepolitical mechanism, the title represents are contradiction in terms. Freedomcan not exist in a politically-based society, and such a system is certainlynot &quot;revolutionary.&quot; There is nothing knew about the failed conceptof societal structures based on coercion. <BR><BR>The author suggests using unfettered capitalism as the solution to poverty,education, the health-care crisis and assorted other problems. That wouldbe a good idea, but when he suggests a &quot;flat&quot; income he is notsuggested true capitalism, showing that he does not understand what capitalismis--and isn't. There is nothing capitalist about a system that proposesto confiscate 17% of the income of its victims. Anything more than 0% isnot capitalism, but warmed-over socialism, communism, democracy, republicanismetc., as they all mean the same thing in principle: A society based on coercion,with the only thing left to decide being the style and extent of coercion.<BR><BR>A 17% tax means that people are &quot;only&quot; 17% slaves. But, does anyonebelieve that the politicians could give up local state and city taxes? Soit would be more. Perhaps 25% slavery. And then there is the problem oftaxes on alcohol and cigarettes. Besides raising revenue, they are alsoto control the usage of these items in order to &quot;protect&quot; thepeople from themselves. How would they do that without taxes? Well, of coursethey could require the usage of ration coupons for them... <BR><BR>At the same time the author and his subject are proposing a &quot;capitalist&quot;solution, the &quot;House Majority Leader&quot; is apparently proposingto usher in the true &quot;Big Brother&quot; system, with the American politicalmechanism trying yet again to introduce a national identity card so theycan have ever increasing control over their hapless victims. Why not justtatoo the SS number (a very appropriate designation) of each individualonto their arm, as the SS and GESTAPO (Geheim Staats Polizei) did underHitler? Apparently the author and subject feel that such a system had meritafter all. <BR></UL><H3><A NAME="PAINE"></A>Tom Paine: A Political Life</H3><DL>  <DD>by John Keane   <DD>Bloomsbury - 644 pp - &#163;25.00   <DD>ISBN 0-7475-2007-0 </DL><UL>There have been many books written about the Life of Thomas Paine, butvery few good books. Many books have been scurilous, outright attacks onPaine, often sanctioned and paid for by people who resented his attemptsto create better societal structures with freedom for the individual. Peoplesuch as King George III, who rightly feared Paine's concepts. <BR><BR>Until Keane's book, the only good and reliable book available was <I>TheLife of Thomas Paine</I>, by Moncure D. Conway. Keane's meticulous and scholarlyresearch has uncovered much information not available to Conway or, indeed,to any earlier biographers. <BR><BR>Keane, while I think he tries to be impartial, clearly recognizes the importanceof Paine and his relevance to the societal problems of our time. He is friendlytoward Paine, yet his work is clearly scholarly, presenting facts as theyare. He has uncovered and catalogued much new material related to Paine'slife. <BR><BR>Although I can't find a reference to it at the moment, I believe I readthat he is working on a Paine bibliography which, if so, is good news forthose respecting and having gratitude for the work of Paine. <BR><BR>I am grateful to Keane for his excellent biography, which I think will bethe new standard for a Paine biography. I recommend it highly. <BR><BR></UL><HR NOSHADE><H3><CENTER><A NAME="MCGE"></A>Reviews by Prof. Robert W. McGee</CENTER></H3><HR><H3><A NAME="SHAP"></A>The Shaping of Environmentalism in America</H3><DL>  <DD>by Victor B. Scheffer   <DD>University of Washington Press - 249 pp - US$19.95 </DL><B>The Shaping of Environmentalism in America</B> in <A HREF="Shaping-Environmentalism.txt">Text</A>Format, 11 Kb file. <BR><BR><B>The Shaping of Environmentalism in America</B> in <A HREF="Shaping-Environmentalism.pdf">AdobeAcrobat</A> Format, 14 Kb file. <BR><BR><HR><H3><A NAME="MIRA"></A>The Mirage of Oil Protection</H3><DL>  <DD>by Robert L. Bradley, Jr.   <DD>University Press of America - 266 pp </DL><B>The Mirage of Oil Protection</B> in <A HREF="Mirage-of-Oil-Protection.txt">Text</A>Format, 11 Kb file. <BR><BR><B>The Mirage of Oil Protection</B> in <A HREF="Mirage-of-Oil-Protection.pdf">AdobeAcrobat</A> Format, 11 Kb file. <BR><BR><HR><H3><A NAME="MKT"></A>Free Market Environmentalism</H3><DL>  <DD>by Terry L. Anderson and Donald R. Leal   <DD>Westview Press - 1991 - 192 pp - US$14.95 </DL><B>Free Market Environmentalism</B> in <A HREF="Market-Environmentalism.txt">Text</A>Format, 11 Kb file. <BR><BR><B>Free Market Environmentalism</B> in <A HREF="Market-Environmentalism.pdf">AdobeAcrobat</A> Format, 14 Kb file. <BR><BR><HR noshade><H3><CENTER><A NAME="RME"></A>Reviews by Prof. Richard M. Ebeling</CENTER></H3>Professor Ebeling is the Ludwig von Mises Professor of Economics at HillsdaleCollege in Hillsdale, Michigan, and serves as vice president of academicaffairs for the Future of Freedom Foundation. <BR><H4><A NAME="SD"></A>Shakedown: How the Government Screws You from A toZ</H4><DL>  <DD>by James Bovard   <DD>(New York: Viking, 1995)   <DD>132 pp - US$14.95 </DL><B>Shakedown: How the Government Screws You from A to Z</B> in <A HREF="Government-Screws-You.txt">Text</A>Format, 11 Kb file. <BR><BR><B>Shakedown: How the Government Screws You from A to Z</B> in <A HREF="Government-Screws-You.pdf">AdobeAcrobat</A> Format, 14 Kb file. <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><P><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE>&copy; 1995 - TheUniversal Salvage Corporation <BR><I><BR>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I> <HR NOSHADE><B>Contact Information:<BR></B><TT>E-Mail: administrator@Freedom-Server.co.uk<BR></TT><HR>The URL of this page is: </CENTER><P><P><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Book-Reviews.html&gt; <HR NOSHADE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
