a of its content.</P><P>I do not intend at this time to comment on any author by name in thissection of<CITE> The Freedom Server&copy;</CITE>, although I may ofcourse comment on an author and things they have said when Iincorporate their thinking in one of my own essays.  I preferto comment on concepts, irregardless of the author, unless of course itis something for which they should receive credit.  Either positive ornegative.  In this forum, I think it should be up to each individualreader to evaluate any article for correctness, and to assign a"credit rating" to the author based on the amount of "rightness" in thethinking and writings of the author.</P><P>I think that the articles are all superior to that which is normallywritten on the subject, although failure to include an article does notmean that I think it is inferior.  Mostly it means I have not had timeto read an article.</P><P>As a general statement, I think the articles tend more toward fixingwhat is an unfixable concept, and that they are only offering a"non-solution" within the current concept of operating a socialstructure based on coercion.  Just making it "nicer" and more "equitable"coercion.  With no solution that creates a rational and durable societalstructure.</P><P>That is my opionion.  But you, the reader, must make your own decision.</P><HR><p>I am beginning to supply documents in HTML format in addition tothe text and Adobe <b>Acrobat</b> formats.  These documents haveHyperText linked footnotes and links to related documents whereappropriate.</p><p>Not only will clicking on the footnote number in the document take youto that footnote, but there is a <b>Return</b> in the footnote, so thatclocking on <b>Return</b> will take you back to the paragraph fromwhich you started.</p><hr noshade><CENTER><H4>The Foundation for Economic Education.</H4></CENTER><P>	"Ever since 1946, the Foundation for Economic Education (FEE)	has been promoting an understanding and acceptance of the free	market, private property, limited government way of life and the	moral and intellectual principles which form the basis of the free	society. FEE's spirit is uplifting, reassuring, and contagious: it has	inspired the creation of numerous similar organizations at home	and abroad."</P><P>	FEE publishes a monthly publication entitled <I>The Freeman </I>	 containing articles embodying their principles.  Please consult them	for further details.</P><P><DL>	<DD> The Foundation for Economic Education	<DD> 30 South Broadway	<DD> Irvington-on-Hudson, NY 10533	<DD>U. S. A.	<DD>Tel: (1-914) 591-7230	<DD>Fax: (1-914) 591-8910</DL><p>You may contact FEE directly from this page via E-mail <a href="mailto:freeman@westnet.com">The Foundation for Economic Education</a></p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><CENTER><H3><I>The Freeman</I> magazine</H3><IMG SRC="Freeman.gif"></CENTER><P>The following articles are from the publication <I>The Freeman</I>,published monthly by the Foundation for Economic Education.</P><hr><P><LI><B>Peace, Political Science, and Pedagogy</B></P><UL>	<p>	One of the latest fads in schools is a so-called "peace curriculum."	It is wrought of the notion that peace is engendered by a certain	kind of attitude: that if we teach teenagers and young adults	to think and talk more about peace, or if we condition them to	have a sort of knee-jerk aversion towards anything military, then the	world will consequently be a more irenic place.	</p>			<P>	by Stephan G. Barone	</P>		<p>	Stephen G. Barone is a practicing psychologist and writer	who teaches at the University of Wisconsin, Platteville	</p>				<P>	<B>Peace, Political Science, and Pedagogy</B>	</p>		<p>	<A HREF="Teaching-Peace.html">HTML</A> Format	</P>	</UL><HR><P><LI><B>Sorry, Charley, But That's Not Capitalism!</B></P><UL>	<P>	by Mark Skousen	</