 Ebeling (Hillsdale, Michigan),vice president of academic affairs. There are nine members on theFoundation's board of trustees.</p><P><I>FreedomDaily</A></I> is published monthly by The Foundation. It consists ofessays, book reviews, and quotes by freedom's greatest champions.Subscribers come from thirty-five countries. The price for a one-yearsubscription to our monthly print publication is $18 ($20 foreign).  Ane-mail subscription is available for $12.</p><P>The Foundation also shares its ideas on liberty with others throughlectures, speeches, seminars, and radio appearances, primarily with Mr.Hornberger and Professor Ebeling.</p><P>The Foundation neither solicits nor accepts governmental funds.Operations of The Foundation are financed through subscription revenuesas well as donations, which are invited in any amount.</p><P>Please contact The Future of Freedom Foundation for additionalinformation. We hope you might choose to join them in their important work.</p><P><DL>	<DD>The Future of Freedom Foundation	<DD>11350 Random Hills Road, Suite 800	<DD>Fairfax, VA 22030	<DD>U. S. A.	<DD>Tel: (1-703) 934-6101	<DD>Fax: (1-703) 352-8678	<dd><a href="mailto:info@fff.org">The Future of Freedom Foundation</a>	<dd><a href="mailto:freedom@fff.org">Freedom Daily</a></DL><hr><p>You may also visit the <a href="www.fff.org/freedom/fff/fff.htm">Home Page</a> of the Futureof Freedom Foundation from this location.</p><p>Please mention that you were referred to them by <b>The FreedomServer</b><sup>&copy;</sup>.</p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER><H3>New Additions</H3></CENTER></CENTER>	<P>	The following three articles are considered to be extremely	important for two reasons:		<UL>		<P>		<LI>They point out a little-known but very important fact which			forms a very basic part of the dwindling freedom which			individuals have to protect themselves and their			property from the onslaught of the American political			state.		</P>					<P>		<LI>They illustrate the way in which individuals can take			control of their destiny in a basically coercive society by			altering and even eliminating increasingly repressive			political laws.		</P>	</UL><hr><p><LI><A HREF="#TBJ">Trial by Jury</A></p><P>by Jacob G. Hornberger</P><LI><A HREF="#ETBJ">An Essay on the Trial by Jury.</A><P>by Lysander Spooner</P><LI><A HREF="#TMBT">The Magic Bullet That Stops Tyranny in	Its Tracks.</A><P>by Don Doig</P><HR NOSHADE><CENTER><H3>Foreword</H3></CENTER><P>The essays in this section are published through the courtesy of <CITE>The Future of Freedom Foundation </CITE>and the individual authors.Their appearance here is at the pleasure of the Foundation, the essayauthor, and the Universal Salvage Corportation.  Any article willremoved at the request of the author or the Foundation.</P><P>The Foundation indicates the articles may be reprinted withoutpermission providing that appropriate credit is given, and that twocopies of such reprinted article(s) be provided to the Foundation.</P><P>I read all articles before deciding to publish them here, but I donot necessarily agree with everything in an article.  It is my policyto not criticize or say anything negative about any articles.  I may makea positive comment about something, or merely describe an article sothat a prospective reader will have some idea of its content.</P><P>I do not intend at this time to comment on any author by name in thissection of<CITE>The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup></CITE>, although Imay of course comment on an author and things they have said when Iincorporate their thinking in one of my own essays.  I preferto comment on concepts, irregardless of the author, unless of course itis something for which they should receive credit.  Either positive ornegative.  In this forum, I think it should be up to each individualreader to evaluate any article for correctness, and to assign a"credit rating" to the author based on the amount of "rightness" in thethinking and writings of the author.</P><P>I think that the articles are all superior to that which is normallywritten on the subject, although failure to include an article does notmean that I think it is inferior.  Mostly it means I have not had timeto read an article.</P><P>As a general statement, I think the articles tend more toward fixingwhat is an unfixable concept, and that they are only offering a"non-solution" within the current concept of operating a socialstructure based on coercion.  Just making it "nicer" and more "equitable"coercion.  With no solution that creates a rational and durable societalstructure.</P><P>That is my opionion.  But you, the reader, must make your own decision.</P><HR NOSHADE><CENTER><H3>Essays</H3></CENTER><HR NOSHADE><p><LI><B>Takings: The Evils of Eminent Domain.</B></p><UL>	<P>	by Sheldon Richman.	</P>		<P>	Mr. Richman is senior editor at the Cato Institute in Washington,	D.C., and the author of <CITE>Separating School &amp; State: How	to Liberate America's Families,</CITE> published by the Future	of Freedom Foundation.	</P>		<P>	<B>Takings: The Evils of Eminent Domain</B>	</p>		<p>	<A HREF="Eminent-Domain.pdf">Adobe Acrobat</A> Format, 14 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Eminent-Domain.html">HTML</A> Format	</P></UL><HR NOSHADE><p><LI><A NAME="TBJ"><B>Trial by Jury.</B></p><UL>	<P>	by Jacob G. Hornberger	</P>		<P>	This essay points out the fact that trial by jury is the ultimate	bulwark against tyranny by the political state, including the	fact that individuals can be acquited of "crimes" based on the fact	that the law they are accused of violating is a bad law.	</P>		<P>	Further, it points out that instructions by judges are often lie	to all participants, saying that they must accept laws as written.	And that juries do not have the power to challenge the laws as in	fact they do have.  In fact, juries have the ultimate power in the	American political state.		<P>	<B>Trial by Jury</B>	</p>		<p>	<A HREF="Trial-by-Jury.pdf">Adobe Acrobat</A> Format, 18 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Trial-by-Jury.html">HTML</A> Format	</P></UL><HR NOSHADE><p><LI><A NAME="ETBJ"><B>An Essay on the Trial by Jury.</B></p><UL>	<P>	by Lysander Spooner	</P>		<P>	As this essay points out, trial by jury is presents us with the	difference between despotism and some modicum of liberty.	</P>		<P>	<B>An Essay on the Trial by Jury</B>	</p>	<P>	<A HREF="Jury-Trial.pdf">Adobe Acrobat</A> Format, 7 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Jury-Trial.html">HTML</A> Format	</P></UL><HR NOSHADE><p><LI><A NAME="TMBT"><LI><A NAME="ETBJ"><B>The Magic Bullet That	Stops Tyanny In Its Tracks.</B></p><UL>	<P>	by Don Doig	</P>		<P>	As this essay points out, trial by jury presents us with the	difference between despotism and some modicum of liberty.	</P>		<P>	<B>The Magic Bullet That Stops Tyanny In Its Tracks.</B>	</p>	<P>	<A HREF="Tyranny-Jury.pdf">Adobe Acrobat</A> Format, 14 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Tyranny-Jury.html">HTML</A> Format	</P></UL><HR><p><LI><A NAME="STAT"><LI><A NAME="ETBJ"><B>Demystifying the State</B></p><UL>	<P>	by Wendy McElroy	</P>		<P>	Ms. McElroy resides in Hamilton, Ontario, Canada. This is an edited	version of an essay that originally appeared in "The Voluntaryist,"	Box 1275, Gramling, South Carolina (USA).  A sample newsletter is	available upon request to "The Voluntaryist."	</P>		<P>	The minions of the political state mystify their victims, and perhaps	and perhaps even themselves through semantic obfuscation regarding	their real objectives.	</P>		<P>	<B>Demystifying the State</B>	</p>	<P>	<A HREF="State-Mysticism.pdf">Adobe Acrobat</A> Format, 14 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="State-Mysticism.html">HTML</A> Format	</P></UL><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top 