ng down the wage payer;	<dd>you cannot keep out of trouble by spending more than your income; 	<dd>you cannot further the brotherhood of man by inciting class hatreds; 	<dd>you cannot establish security on borrowed money; 	<dd>you cannot build character and courage by taking away an individual's 	  initiative and independence;	<dd>you cannot help men permanently by doing for them what they could	  and should do for themselves."		<p>	This is often--and incorrectly--ascribed to Abraham Lincoln,	although I suspect that he would agree with it.	</p></dl><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Butler, Samuel</b> {1835 - 1902}	</p><ul>	<p>	<li>"The reasonable man adapts himself to the world, but the		unreasonable man tries to adapt the world to himtherefore,		all  progress depends on the unreasonable man."	</p>	<p>	<li>"The man who lets himself be bored is even more contemptible		than the bore."	</p></ul><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="C">C</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Carlyle, Thomas</b> {1795 - 1881}	</p><blockquote>"Respectable Professors of the Dismal Science" [Political Economy].<p>The origin of calling Economics "the Dismal Science."</p><p>Latter Day Pamphlets, No. 1 - Present Time</p></blockquote><hr><p><li><b>Cicero, Marcus Tullius</b> {106 BC - 32 BC}</p><blockquote><p>"True law is right reason in accord with nature;  it is of universalapplication, unchanging and everlasting..."</p><p>Marcus Tullius Cicero, <i>Commonwealth</i>, 51 BC</p><p>Cicero is referring to "Natural Law," the laws of nature, with which--bydefinition--all volitional beings and anything they create must conform.Which includes their societal structures, or they will fail.  Asevidenced by all of the societal structures created to date on this planet.</p><p>Cicero's reference to "right" reason refers to an absolute concept ofrightness, with which any man-made laws must conform to be called"true" law.  History and science tell us that any laws, whether politicalor otherwise, do not work and will not survive unless they are "right" inan absolute sense, conforming to nature.</p></blockquote><hr><p>	<li><b>Crockett, Davy</b>  {1786 - 1836}	</p>	<blockquote>	"We have the right, as individuals, to give away as much of our own	money as we please in charity; but as members of Congress we have	no right to appropriate a dollar of public money."		<p>	Crockett, the famous frontiersman, was a member of Congress from	1827-1831 and 1833-1835. He lost his fourth bid for election	 because of his oppostion to Jackson's Indian-removal policies, and	 then died at the Alamo on 1836, March 6.	 </p>	 	 <p>	 America grew to be the most powerful political entity on the	 planet during the 19th century.  But, by the latter-half of the	 century it was already in decay, living off of the growth engendered	 by relatively much-less interference in individual life and property	 which existed in the 18th and 19th centuries in America.	 </p>	</blockquote><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="D">D</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Descartes, Ren&eacute;</b>    {1596 - 1650}	</p><blockquote>"Cogito, ergo sum."<p>[I think, therefore I exist]</p><p>People who wonder whether or not they exist should contemplatethis.</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Disraeli, Benjamin</b> {1804 - 1881}	</p><blockquote>"To be conscious that you are ignorant is a great step to knowledge."</blockquote></ul><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Drake, Edwin L.</b> {19th century)}	</p><blockquote>	"Drill for oil?  You mean drill into the ground to try and find oil? 	You're crazy."		<p>	Said to Drake by drillers he tried to enlist for his project to drill	for oil in 1859.	</p></blockquote></ul><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Duell, Charles H.</b> {unknown}	</p><blockquote>	"Everything that can be invented has been invented."	<p>	Said by Duell in 1899 in his proposal to shut down the U. S. Patent	Office.	</p></blockquote></ul><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="E">E</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Ericksen, John Eric</b> {unknown}	</p><blockquote>	"The abdomen, the chest, and the brain will forever be shut from the	intrusion of the wise and humane surgeon."	<p>	Ericksen had been appointed Surgeon-Extraordinary to Queen	Victoria in 1873.	</p></blockquote></ul><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="F">F</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Fielding, Henry</b>   {1707 - 1754}	</p><blockquote>	"He in a few minutes ravished this fair creature,<br>	 or at least would have ravished her,<br>	 if she had not, by a timely compliance,<br>	prevented him."		<p>	[Reminds one of the poor taxpayer and "voluntary" compliance.	Except with taxes you are presented with a false alternative.	You are ravished in both cases, even if you do "voluntarily" comply.]	</p><p> Jonathon Wild, bk iii, ch. 5</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Fitzgerald, F. Scott</b>  {1801 - 1940}	</p><blockquote>	"Once a change in direction has begun, even though it's the wrong one,	it still tends to clothe itself as thoroughly in the appurtenances of	rightness as if it had been natural all along."<p>The Gay Science, 1882-1887</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Flynn, John T.</b> {unknown}	</p><blockquote>	"Private industry must produce the income out of which the losses	of these Government industries are paid, and the attendant costs	of Government as well."		<p>	<i>Forgotten Lessons: Selected Essays of John T. Flynn</i>, edited	by Gregory P. Pavlik. Foundation for Economic Education (1995)	</p>	<p>	People who think they are getting something for nothing through	political state subsidy programs and other such nonsense should	remember this	</p></blockquote></ul><p><li><b>France, Anatole</b> [Jacques Anatole	Francois Thibault]  {1844 - 1924}</p><blockquote>	"Ignorance is the necessary condition of life itself.  If we knew	everything, we could not endure existence for a single hour."<p>The Garden of Epicurus - 1894</p></blockquote><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="G">G</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Galilei, Galileo</b>  {1564 - 1642}	</p><blockquote><p><i>"...Eppur si muove"  </i>[...yet it does move]</p><p>[The possibly apocryphal response of Galileo to the Pope's dictum thatthe earth stood still while the sun moved around it.  Though beautifullyin character for Galileo!]</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Gibran, Kahlil</b>  {1883 - 1931}	</p><blockquote>"That which is never seen until someone expresses it [clearly]."<p>Dictionary of Quotable Definitions, Eugene Brussell</p><p>[Most probably originated with Christian Morgenstern the Younger] qv</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Greenspan, Richard</b> - Head of Radiology, Yale Medical School	</p><blockquote>	"People who have learned something as the truth don't particularly	like to hear that they've based their careers on things that were	either incomplete, or not completely correct."	<p>	Gary Taubes, "An Electrifying Possibility," <i>Discover,</i> April	1986, p. 37</p></blockquote><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="H">H</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Harmon, Kenneth O. J.</b>  {contemporary}	</p><blockquote>	"Peace follows justice as surely as night follows day."<p>Stated personally to the editor.</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Helmholtz, Hermann von</b>  {1821 - 1894}	</p><blockquote>	"The originator of a new concept...finds, as a rule, that it is much	more  difficult to find out  why other people do not understand him,	than it was to discover the new truth."	</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Heraclitus</b>  {6th Century BC - 5th Century BC}	</p><blockquote>	"A hidden connection is stronger than an obvious one."	<p>	[We much prefer a complicated non-solution to a simple, true	{right} solution].	</p>	<p>	Fragments, 54, c. 500 BC	</p></blockquote><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Herodotus</b>  (c. 480 - c. 425 b.c.)	</p><blockquote>	"Custom is King."	</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><a name="HORATIUS"><b>Horatius</b>  (Quintus Horatius		Flaccus)  {65 BC - 8 BC}</A>	</p><blockquote>	"Exegi monumentum aere perennius."	<p>[I have executed a memorial longer lasting than bronze.<br>{The significance, endurance and power of <i>right</i> ideas, as opposed tothe short-term influence of actions}]</p></blockquote><hr><p><li><a name="HITLER"><b>Hitler. Adolf</b>  {1889 - 1945}</A></p><blockquote>	"1935 will go down in history! For the first time a civilized 	nation has full gun registration! Our streets will be safer, 	our police more efficient, and the world will follow our 	lead in the future!"	<p>And so they have followed Hitler's lead.  A person must wonder if the Jewswould have gone so docilely to the gas chambers if they had had a means ofdefending themselves.  They seem quite capable of defending themselves inIsrael...</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Hugo, Victor</b>  {1802 - 1885}	</p><blockquote>	"There is nothing so powerful as an idea whose time has come."	</blockquote><hr>		<p>	<li><b>Huxley, T. H.</b>    {1825 - 1895}	</p><blockquote>	"It is the customary fate of new truths to begin as heresies and to	end as superstitions."	</blockquote><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="I">I</h2></center><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="J">J</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Jefferson, Thomas </b> {1743 - 1826}	</p><blockquote>	<li>"Mr. Paine is...too well entitled to the hospitality of every American,	not to cheerfully receive mine."	<p>	Randall, <i>The Life of Thomas Paine</i>, vol, 2, p. 644.	</p>	<p>	Said by Jefferson when he was president of the United States,	reprimanding those who were deriding <a href="#PAI">Paine</a>	and his achievements.	</p>		<li>"[The] sum of good government is to restrain men from injuring		one another," to "leave them ... free to regulate their own		pursuits of industry and improvement," and to "not take from		the mouth of labor the bread it has earned."			<p>This Jerrersonian philosophy of good government was widely		shared in nineteenth-century America, but has been increasingly		and grossly perverted by the succeeding vacuum-heads who		have occupied the presidency, seeking only to accumulate		ever-increasing powers for the political state.	</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Jung, Carl</b>  {1875 - 1961}	</p><blockquote>	"The individual is increasingly deprived [by the political state] of	the moral decision as to how he should live his life, and instead	is ruled, fed, clothed and educated as a social unit..."	<p>	[The cause of many of the ills of any political society.  The	individual is told to stop thinking for himself, and eventually	does, abrogating responsibility for the rational and moral	conduct of his life to his "masters."]</p><p>The Undiscovered Self, 1958</p></blockquote><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="K">K</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Keane, John</b> {dates unknown}	</p>	<blockquote>	"Supporters of referenda are never more trusting of "the people"	than when the latter agree with their views."	<p><i>Tom Paine: A Political Live</i>, by John Keane. BloomsburyPublishing plc - 1995  p.363</p></blockquote><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="L">L</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Lewis, C. S.</b> {1898 - 1963}	</p>	<blockquote>	"Of all tyrannies a tyranny sincerely exercised for the good of its	victims may be the most oppressive.  It may be better to live under	robber barons than under omnipotent moral busybodies. The robber	baron's cruelty may sometimes sleep, his cupidity may at some	point be satiated; but those who torment us for our own good	will torment us without end, for they do so with the approval of	their own conscience."		<p>	This is not a problem in a free society.  It is a problem only when	the "do-gooders" can invoke the coercive power of the political	state to achieve their ends.	</p>	<p><i>The Freeman</i>, 1994, January. p. 3</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Locke, John</b>  {1632 - 1704}	</p><blockquote>  	   	 <li>"New opinions are always suspected, and usually opposed,  	 without any other reason but because they are not already  	 common."  		<p>	An Essay Concerning Human Understanding (1690, dedicatory epistle)	</p> 	  <li>"Government has no other end but the preservation of property." 	 	<p> 	2nd Treatise on Civil Gov't, 1681 	<p> 	</blockquote> <hr>	<p>	<li><b>Lowell, James Russell</b>  {1819 - 1891}	</p><p><dl>	<dd>"New Occasions teach new duties: 	<dd>Time makes ancient good uncouth;	<dd>They must upward still, and onward, 	<dd>who would keep abreast of Truth."</dl></p><hr noshade><center><h2><a name="M">M</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>McKensie, Richard B.</b> {unknown}	</p>	<blockquote>		"Centralized direction of the economy invariable means reliance on	the limited knowledge of those who give direction."		<p>	"The Foundations of Political Disarray: Lessons frm Professor	Hayek," <i>The Freeman</i>, October, 1995, p. 618	</p></blockquote><hr><p><li><b>Mill, John Stuart</b>  {1806 - 1873}</p><blockquote>  		<p>	A general state education is a mere contrivance for moulding	people to be eactly like one another  in proportion as it is	sufficient and successful, is estalblished a despotism over the	mind, leading by natural tendency to one over the body.	</p>		<p>	<i>On Liberty</i>, (1962), Fontana edition, p. 239	</p></blockquote>  	<hr><p><li><b>Morgan, William</b>  {c. 500 b.c. - c. 2000 a.d.}</p><ol>  	<p>  	<li>"The limits of growth are found in the minds of small men."  	</p>  		</p>		<p>	<li>"A prayer a day keeps rationality away."	</p>		<p>	<li>"In true capitalism there are no guarantees of successthere	is only the guarantee of  the full, unhindered right to try for it,	and be compensated according to the results."	</p>	 	 <li>"What a tangled web we devise,<br> 		 when first we subsidize." 	 	<p> 	<li>"Freedom and democracy are mutually exclusive concepts. 	In a political society based on the concept of democracy, true 	individual freedom can not exist.  In a free society, the concepts 	of a political society based on democracy would be unthinkable. 	There would be no market demand for the concept."	</p>		<p>	<li>"The Grail for which the Knights of the Roundtable	searched--and for which all volitional beings search--is not just	truth as they thought, but truth combined with validity and	morality, which then become rightness."	</p>  		<p>	For it is <b>rightness</b> in ideas and actions that produces useful	knowledge, enhances the quality of life, and leads to long-term	survival for all volitional beings. It provides the mechanism for	creating societal structures whose time scale of existence is	concomitant with that of their local universe.	</p>	<p>	This thought occurred to me while watching "Excalibur," John	Boorman's interpretation of Malory's <i>Arthurian legend.</i>	</p>	<p>	<li>"Science is organized, <i><b>right</b></i> knowledge."	</p>	<p>	With credit to Herbert Spencer, whose only error was in leaving out	the word "right."  And to A. J. Galambos, my teacher, without whose	guidance I would never have been able to think rationally and on a	grand scale.	</p>	<p>	<li>"Generally speaking, the importance of a public speaker bears	an inverse relationship to the number of microphones into which	he or she speaks."	</p>		<p>	<li>"Politics presents the only contractual relationship wherein a		person contracts with a representative or agent and pays for		certain services, then loses complete control of what services		are provided or not provided, and the price and quality of the		services."	</p>		<p>	The fact that "things have always been done this way" is no more a	valid reason than was the fact that until the 1850s medical doctors	had never washed their hands nor practiced any other from of	antisepsis.	</p>		<p>	<li>"The longer and more extensive is the interference in the free	market process, the more difficult and traumatic is the return to	freedom, sanity, and morality."	</p>		<p>	In fact, it can reach the point where there is no return, and the	associated coercive society self-destructs.  With inceased	cooperation between the rulers and ruling bodies of such societies	comes the increased probability of the destruction of the specie	itself.	</p>		<p>	<li>There is a direct connection between morality in a volitional		society and individual physiological immortality. [96/09/18]	</p>	<p>	This explains the short life span of volitional beings living in	primitive societies based on coercion.	</p>		<p>	<li>"There is an inverse relationship between the importance of a new		idea, and the ease and time in which it is understood, accepted,		and implemented."	</p>		<p>	<li>"The disarray in politics itself--the mechanism which tries to	impose "equality" and uniformity on its victims--confirms the	natural law of the diversity and uniqueness of individual human	aspiration and the absurdity of a mechanism which hopes to destroy	it."	</p>		<p>	The fact that individual politicians can not even agree on the method	for imposing uniformity and equality on their victims--and the extent	of the "equality"--corroborates the existence, strength and resilience	of that which they hope to eliminate.	</p>		<p>	It is a bit like the American politician who proposed a decree to	change the value of the mathematical concept known is "pi" to 3.0	to make it easier for people to work with it.  Or to repeal the law of	gravity to prevent their constituents from falling down and hurting	themselves.  They may play around and try to change the laws of	nature, but repealing the law of gravity and then stepping off of a	building will be about as successful as trying to impose equality on	the victims of any particular political group.	</p>		<p>	<li>"The supreme act of fraud and witchcraft for politicians and the	political mechansim--and especially for proponents and apologists	for the concept of democracy--is in controlling the lives and	property of their victims while at the same time having them believe	they have freedom and are free."	</p></ol><hr><p><li><b>Morgenstern, Christian</b> [The Younger, Lyric Poet]</p>	<blockquote>		"Das Offensichtliche ist das, was man nicht sieht, bis jeman es	erkl&auml;rt."		<p>	[The obvious is that which is not seen until someone first explains	it clearly].	</p></blockquote><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade><center><h2><a name="N">N</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Newton, Isaac </b>     {1642 - 1726}	</p><ul>	<p>	<li>"If I have seen further than others, it is because I have stood	on the shoulders of giants."	</p>	<p>	Letter to Robert Hooke - 1676/02/05	</p>	<p>	This is a proper--and very elegant--expression of the gratitude which	person of great achievement invariably have for ideological	antecedents."	</p>	<p>	<li>"I do not know what I may appear to the world,<br>	but to myself I seem to have been only like a boy<br>	playing on the sea-shore<br> 	and diverting myself in now and then finding a smoother pebble  	or a prettier shell than ordinary,<br> 	whilst the great ocean of truth 	lay all undiscovered before me." 	</p>	<p>	from Brewster, Memoirs of Newton, [1885] vol II, ch. 27	</p></blockquote><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="O">O</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Occam, William of</b>  {c. 1300 - c. 1349}	</p>	<blockquote>		"Entia non sunt multiplicanda prter necessitatem."	<p>	[No more things should be presumed to exist than are absolutely	necessary, or,  Entities should not be multiplied unnecessarily].	</p>	<p>	Quodlibeta Septem, [c. 1320]	</p></blockquote><hr><p><li><b>Orwell, George</b>  {1903 - 1940}</p><blockquote>	<p>	<li>"Who controls the past controls the future.  Who controls the		present controls the past."	</p>	<p>	<li>"Doublethink means the power of holding two contradictory		beliefs in one's mind  simultaneously, and accepting both of		them."	</p>	<p>	<li>"In our time, political speech and writing are largely the		defence of the indefensible."	</p></blockquote>	<hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="P">P</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Paine, Thomas </b>   {1737 - 1809}	</p><ol>	<p>	<li>"A long habit of not thinking a thing wrong, gives it a superficial		appearance of being right, and raises at first a formidable outcry		in defense of custom.  But the tumult soon  subsides.  Time makes		more converts than reason."	</p>		<p>	Thomas Paine, Introduction to Common Sense, Penguin	Books, 1983, p. 63	</p>	<li>"Man has no property in man (neither has any generation a		property in generations  which are to follow)."		<p>		Rights of Man, pp. 63-64	</p>	<li>"O ye that love mankind!  Ye that dare oppose, not only the		tyranny but the tyrant, stand  forth!  Every spot of the old world		is over-run with oppression.  Freedom hath been  hunted round		the globe.  Asia, and Africa, have long expelled her.  Europe		regards her like a stranger, and England hath given her		warning to depart.  O!  receive the fugitive, and prepare in		time an asylum for mankind."	<p>		Common Sense [1776]	</p>	<li>"In England a king hath little more to do than to make war		and give away places; which  in plain terms, is to impoverish		the nation and set it together by the ears.  A pretty business		indeed for a man to be allowed eight hundred thousand sterling		for, and worshipped into the bargain!  Of more worth is one		honest man to society and in the sight of God, than all the		crowned ruffians that ever lived."		<p>		ib.		</p>	<li>"...that what each man has is his own, that no despotic		government can take from him."			<p>		Dissertations on Government, the Affairs of the Bank and		Paper Money		</p>	<li>"The heathens paid divine honours to their deceased kings,		and the Christian world hath improved on the plan by doing		the same to their living ones.  How impious is the title of		Sacred Majesty applied to a worm, who in the midst of his		splendour is crumbling into dust."			<p>		Common Sense [1776]		</p>	<li>"...what at first was submitted as a convenience, was		afterwards claimed as a right."		<p>		ib.		</p>	<li>"Men who look upon themselves born to reign, and others to 		obey, soon grow insolent; selected from the rest of mankind		their minds are early poisoned by importance; and the world		they act in differs so materially from the world at large,		that they have but little opportunity of knowing its true		interests, and when they succeed to the government are		frequently the most ignorant and unfit of any throughout		the dominions."				<p>		ib.		</p>				<p>		This accurately describes the majority of all politicians, whether		of the civil, military, or religious branch.		</p>		<li>"Government, even in its best state, is but a necessary evil;		in its worst state, an intolerable one."				<p>		ib.		</p>				<p>		"Necessary" evils are still <b>evil</b>.  Yet it happens in this		case there is available a societal system which does not		involve evil. It is available through greater knowledge.		</p>	<li>"It is an affront to truth to treat falsehood with complacency."		<p>	<li>"The mind once enlightened can never become dark."		</p>	<p>	[Corollary: "The mind once dark, can barely stand the light of 	knowledge."  Morgan]	</p>	<li>"Taxes are not raised to carry on wars, but wars are raised		to carry on taxes."		<p>	<li>"These are the times that try men's souls.  The summer soldier		and the sunshine  patriot will, in this crisis, shrink from the		service of his country; but he that stands it␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀ld they obtain it."	</p>		<p>	ib.	</p>	</ol><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Palmer, Elihu</b> {unk - unk}	</p>	<blockquote>	"Kings could not exist without priests.  Their trades exactly fit	each other. First enslave the mind, and the slavery of the body	follows as natural as the shadow its object."		<p>	Read in <i>Tom Paine: A Political Life</i>, by John Keane, quoted	in John Fellows, "Memoir," in <i>Posthumous Pieces by Elihu	Palmer</i>, (London, 1824).	</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Pascal, Blaise</b>   {1623 - 1662}	</p>	<blockquote>	"I have made this letter longer than usual, only because I have not	had the time to make it shorter."	</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Poincair&eacute;, Jules Henri</b> {1854 - 1912}	</p>	<blockquote>	"Science is built up with facts, as a house is with stones.<br>	But a collection of facts is no more a science<br>	than a heap of stones is a house."	<p>	Quoted from Bertrand Russell in preface to Science and Method {1913}	</p>	</blockquote><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="Q">Q</h2></center><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="R">R</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Reed, Leonard</b> {1898 - 1983}	</p>	<blockquote>	<li>"Indeed, any serious student will want to read any book with care		and discrimination, gleaning  from it such truth as he can find,		and rejecting that which to him seems false or misleading."		<p>	Suspected source.	</p></blockquote><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="S">S</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Santayana, George</b>   {1863 - 1952}	</p><blockquote>	"Those who do not remember the past are condemned to repeat it."</blockquote><hr><p>	<li><b>Scipio, Publius Cornelius</b>   {236 BC - 183 BC}	</p><blockquote>	<p>	"No man should rule other men, and certainly not for a lifetime."	</p>		<p>	Said when, as a result of his victory over Hannibal at Zama in 202	BC during the Second Punic War, he was offered the rulership for	life of the Roman Empire.  The empire he had created.	</p>		<p>	The victor in every battle fought against Hannibal's troops, he is	the most competent general in history.  The fact that he only became	a soldier when Rome's situation in the Second Punic war was desparate	makes this decision  moral and rational.  His statement concerning	societies based on coercion reinforces his position as one of the most	significant half-dozen examples of </i>homo sapien</i> of all time.	I am really at a loss for words in being able to express my admiration	for Scipio.	</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Shakespeare, William</b>  {1564 - 1616}	</p><blockquote>		"O! this learning, what a thing it is."</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Silver, Spencer</b>  {unknown}	</p><blockquote>		"If I had thought about it, I wouldn't have done the experiment.  The	literature was full of examples that said you can't do this."		<p>	Silver's comment on the work which led to the discovery of the	unique adhesive for 3M's <i>PostIt Notepads</i>.	</p>	</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Solon</b>  {630 - 555 BD}	</p><blockquote>		"I grow old ever learning many things."</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Sparks, John C.</b>  {unk - unk}	</p><blockquote>		"How could roads be built and operated privately?  I do not know.	This is a subject to which none of us directs his creative attention.	We never do think creatively on any activity preempted by	government.  It is only until an activity has been freed from	monopoly that creative thought comes into play..."[1954]		<p>	Quoted from <i>The Freeman</i>,vol. 44, no. 2, 1994, February,	p. 79	</p>	</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Spencer, Herbert</b>  {1820 - 1903}	</p><blockquote>		"Science is organized Knowledge."</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Stevenson, Robert Louis</b> {1850 - 1894}	</p>	<blockquote>		"To know what you prefer, instead of humbly saying Amen to what	the world tells you you ought to prefer, is to have kept your soul	alive."	</blockquote><hr>	<p><b>Spencer, Herbert</b>  {1820 - 1903}	</p><blockquote>		"Science is organized Knowledge."</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Storr, Anthony</b> {contemporary, unknown}	</p>	<blockquote>		"Most people in the world subscribe to belief systems for which there	is no evidence and which do not stand up to critical evaluation."		<p>	Quoted from <i>The Sunday Times</i> books section of 96/06/09,	reviewing Storr's book "Feet of Clay: A Study of Gurus,"	<i>HarperCollins</i>, pp253.	</p>	</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Swift, Jonathan</b>   {1667 - 1745}	</p><blockquote>		"When a true genius appears in the world, you may know him by this	sign, that the dunces are all in a confederacy against him."		<p>	Thoughts on Various Subjects, Moral and Diverting	</p>	</blockquote><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Szent-Gy&uuml;rgyi von Nagryapult, Albert</b>  {1893 - 1986}	</p><blockquote>				"Discovery consists in seeing what everyone else has seen,<br> 	  	and thinking what no one else has thought." 	  </blockquote><hr noshade><center><h2><a name="T">T</h2></center><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="U">U</h2></center><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="V">V</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Virgil</b>  {70 BC - 9 BC}	</p><blockquote>		"Macte nova virtute, puer, sic itur ad astra."		<p>	[Blessing on your young courage, boy; that's the way to the stars].	</p>	</blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Voltaire</b>  [Francois Marie Arouet]  {1694 - 1778}	</p><blockquote>		<li>"It is forbidden to kill...unless to trumpets."				<p>		It is "ok" for the political state to kill, especially by		creating wars, but it is "not ok" for anyone else to kill.		</p>		<li>"If God did not exist, it would be necessary to invent him."		<p>		[Si Dieu n'esistait pas, il faudrait l'inventer].		</p>				<p>		This explains the origin of all concepts of religion.  Individual		volitional beings require some understanding of the world		around them before they can venture forth into it to acquire		knowledge about it.  When they know almost nothing, they accept		fabulous concepts proposed by those who see this as a way of		controlling others.		</p></blockquote><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="W">W</h2></center><hr noshade>	<p>	<li><b>Wren, Christopher</b>  {1632 - 1723}	</p>	<blockquote>		"...Lector, Si monumentum requiris, circumspice..."		 <p>	 [...Reader, if you seek his monument, look around...].	 </p>	<p>	Dictionary of Quotations, J.J. & M.J. Cohen,  Penguin Books,	1985 Edition, p. 427	</p>	<p>	Inscription in St. Paul's Cathedral, London (Written by his son.	It should therefore be properly ascribed to his son, but I do not	know the son's name at the moment, however the gratitude for	this beautiful and elegant tribute goes to him.)	</p></blockquote><hr>	<p>	<li><b>Wright, Wilbur</b>   {1867 - 1912}	</p><blockquote>		"If you are looking for perfect safety you will do well to sit on a	fence and watch the birds, but if you really wish to learn, you	must mount a machine and become acquainted with its tricks by	actual trial."	</blockquote><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="X">X</h2></center><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="Y">Y</h2></center><hr noshade><center> <h2><a name="Z">Z</h2></center><hr noshade><h4>Version History</h4><hr><p>Version 01: 1983, July<br>Version 02-15: various dates<br>Version 16: 1996, August<br>Version 17: 1996, September 18<br>Version 18: 1996, September 22</p><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade><p>If you have any comments on these quotations or wish to suggestquotations to add to this list, please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">administrator</a> at The Freedom Server.</p><hr noshade><center>&copy: 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation<p><i>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</i></p></center><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><center>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Quotations.html&gt;</center><hr noshade></BODY></HTML>
