<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>The Freedom Server - Preface</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"></HEAD><BODY><HR><H1><CENTER>The Freedom Server&copy;</CENTER></H1><P><CENTER><HR><A NAME="Preface"></A></CENTER><H2><CENTER>Preface</CENTER></H2><HR>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, June 1<BR>Version: 002i<BR><HR><H4><CENTER>| <A HREF="index.html">Home</A> | <A HREF="Contents.html">Tableof Contents</A> |</CENTER></H4><HR><BR><BR>As you read the essays issued under the copyright of the Universal SalvageCorporation, you will notice that many times things are repeated. Perhapssometimes verbatim and in the same context and other times stated differently--butusing the same principles--in a different context. <BR><BR>There are very simple reasons for this, and it is something you should beaware of and think of, else you may think I am unintentionally repeatingmyself, and/or there is no sense to the repetition. <BR><BR>Also, I would like that state the basis on which the essays are based. <BR><OL>  <LI>Nature is comprehensible, and all knowledge is related;   <LI><BR>  <LI>Since all knowledge is related, I must leave many things &quot;hangingin the air&quot; and incomplete, else I need to repeat all useful knowledgecurrently existing, in addition to my additions to that.   <LI><BR>  <LI>Further, leaving something &quot;dangling&quot; from time to timeis a part of the teaching and learning process, requiring or giving peoplethe chance to think on their own about how the thought or discussion mightcontinue.   <LI><BR>  <LI>The discussion is about moral solutions only;   <LI><BR>  <LI>The political state is a mechanism based on property interference,or coercion;   <LI><BR>  <LI>Semantic precision is necessary for the creation of useful, moralknowledge   <LI><BR>  <LI>Our universe is a closed, thermodynamic model;   <LI><BR>  <LI>There is a difference between the unknown, the knowable, and the unknowable;  <LI><BR>  <LI>Actions which violate the laws of nature are intrinsically and, bydefinition, impossible.   <LI><BR>  <LI>Things which do not violate that laws of nature are possible, butmay be improbable, or can not be done at this time because of lack of knowledge;  <LI><BR>  <LI>Individuals whose occupation involves property interference or thedestruction of property are insignificant in long-term history;   <LI><BR>  <LI>There are epistemological tools which can be used to determine whetherany idea, proposed action, or action is right on an absolute basis, whetherit involves volitional or non-volitional concepts;   <LI><BR>  <LI>The <CITE>miasma</CITE> of false information under which we all live--ofthings we believe to be true merely because it has never been shown theyare false--so clouds our thinking that it is highly improbable most peopleeven realize there is a catastrophic, near-terminal problem with our societalstructures, and therefore that a solution is needed;   <LI><BR>  <UL>    <LI>And, if the solution is presented, lack of ability to comprehendit;     <LI><BR>  </UL>  <LI>Finally, because man--for the first time in history--has the technologicalability to destroy his own specie, time for implementing a solution is nowcritical and urgent.   <LI><BR>  <LI>While you may take exception to some or all of the above, these conceptswill be used and discussed in the essays of <CITE>The Freedom Server</CITE>which are written under copyright of the Universal Salvage Corporation.  <LI><BR>  <LI>If I were to discuss all of the above fully, such a discussion wouldthen consist of all of the existing essays, plus others yet to be written.I will however discuss some or all of them briefly here. Both as a foundationfor the essays, and as an &quot;appetizer&quot; for the essays. To giveyou something on which to base the discussions, plus something to thinkabout before, during, and after reading the essays.   <LI></OL>Before we start discussing things in some detail, two more thoughts: <BR><OL>  <LI>Always my intention is to discuss principles, and therefore quibblingover insignificant things is not in order and will hinder learning.   <LI><BR>  <LI>For example, in a following paragraph I talk about the time frameof man's existence as a specie, tossing out two million years as a figure.Whether it is one million or five million is not germane to the discussionof the principles involved.   <LI><BR>  <LI>The other is that it is much easier to refer to the specie as &quot;man,&quot;a term which was useful for many years until it fell into disrepute as abeing &quot;sexist.&quot;   <LI><BR>  <LI>Rather than spend time trying to work around it with cute phrases,I will continue to use the word <CITE>man</CITE> to indicate the dominantvolitional specie on this planet, which includes all ages and sexes of thespecie.   <LI></OL>Now, let us begin. <BR><BR><LI><B>Nature is comprehensible, and all knowledge is related.</B> <UL>When you think about it, that is the way it <CITE>must</CITE> be inany one universe. And, I believe that for an observer who could observetwo or more different universes, they would see that all knowledge is alsorelated between the observable universes. Why must this be true? <BR><BR>If not, we would have the ultimate chaos. A universe that did not work,was incomprehensible, and could not be &quot;made&quot; workable. Therewould be no life. A volitional creature faced with such a situation wouldself-destruct. <BR><BR>With all knowledge being related, it only remains for the volitional specieto begin the process of understanding how nature works-- defining the &quot;lawsof nature.&quot; A process which took the volitional specie on this planetabout two million years before they had discovered the first few basic laws.<BR><BR>For two million years there was no significant increase in our understandingof the laws of nature. Think of the hundreds of thousands of years it tookto domesticate animals and crops, and to acquire the beginnings of a technologyin metals. And then the hundreds of years to go from one metal to another.Think of the fact that as recent as several hundred years ago, there willstill major areas of the world where the wheel had not been discovered.<BR><BR>The names of most, if not all, of the individuals who created these innovationsmore than 3,000 years ago are probably lost forever. Yet without their achievementthere would have been no succeeding innovations. They are truly the &quot;unsungheroes&quot; of civilization. <BR><BR>Current political rulers and associated bureaucrats are parasites with nocreative ability or even interest in it, living off of and plundering thismagnificent legacy of civilization. <BR><BR>Then, in less than five hundred years, the increase in our articulationof the laws of nature was dramatic. Also interesting--and significant--was the delay of several hundred years in creating technological applicationsfrom these laws. In 1666 the basic concepts necessary to create the moderntechnological world were elucidated, yet it was another 200 years beforethe technological applications really began to appear. <BR><BR>Thus, it was only the past 150 years or so that there was any <CITE>significant</CITE>change in the way the specie lived. <BR><BR>For the first few million years: <BR><BR>  <LI>Effective social and creative life ended between sunset and sunrise;  <LI>The &quot;town crier&quot; was high technology in news distribution;  <LI>About seven miles (12 kms) was the maximum distance a very adventurousperson (and rich, since it would require a horse) would travel in a dayfrom their own village.   <LI>Most natural calamities were ascribed to angry gods;   <LI>Diseases were the work of witches and devils, and innocent adultsand children were murdered to end these episodes. <BR><BR>  <LI>Then, &quot;suddenly,&quot; the specie began to understand natureand some of its very basic laws--the only laws of any value. Then, <BR><BR>  <LI>No longer did social and creative life end at sunset;   <LI>Communication extended beyond the horizon, and was virtually instantaneous;  <LI>There was understanding of the true cause of why rivers rose and fell,crops grew and did not grow, there were electrical storms, etc. <BR><BR>  <LI>Man began to understand that nature was in fact comprehensible. And,the technology--in the form of moveable-type printing and books-- becameavailable for the recording, storing, and dissemination of what was learned.No many people could work on the same problems, and it was also seen thatknowledge created in one area could lead to the solution of problems inother areas. <BR><BR>  <LI>To realize the beauty and grandeur of this, and to appreciate ourunique position in time in the history of this planet and its volitionallife, you need only do and think of one thing.   <LI><BR>  <LI>Think of a graph, where the &quot;x&quot; axis is time, with a scalefrom zero to, say, two million years. The &quot;y&quot; axis is the numberof laws of nature understood at any one time. <BR><BR>  <LI>The curve is essentially flat for all but about 150-200 years of thattime. Then, suddenly, there is a &quot;knee&quot; in the curve, and it beginsan exponential rise. Occasioned by an event 330 years ago, which will bediscussed in another essay or essays. </UL><LI><B>The discussion is about moral solutions only.</B> <BR><UL>There can never be an excuse for the interference in the property ofanother. Property destruction and creation are mutually exclusive concepts.That should be obvious. It should also be obvious that you an not destroywhat has not been created. <BR><BR>It took man millions of years to build the beautiful cities with their artand books which existed in 1935. It took Hitler ten years to cause the destructionof much of that which it took the millions of years to create, along withthe lives of fifty million people. A &quot;few seconds ago&quot; on theevolutionary clock, those fifty million exceeded the population of the entireplanet. A few more second before that and it exceeded all those volitionalbeings who had ever lived on this planet. <BR><BR>Does it seem like a suitable destiny for the specie to be continually buildingand destroying? Is it something you want as the legacy of your life, andworld into which you want your biological successors to be born and be requiredto endure? <BR><BR>Surely that must be true, else why would we not only continue that pathin our current lives, but we fantasize it as the way of life for the future.We create a vision of a future world through what we euphemistically call&quot;science fiction&quot; in which we propagate the worst features ofour civilization into the future. <BR><BR>A world and universe in which there are &quot;galactic federations,&quot;something like a super &quot;united nations.&quot; Wherein there are roving&quot;battlestars&quot; taking on &quot;alien&quot; invaders. This is aprojection of wars with the neighboring tribe, a concept that has gone onfor millennia. And &quot;super crime syndicates&quot; which then of courserequire a &quot;super lawman&quot; to battle. This subject of &quot;falseheroes&quot; in history will be discussed in other essays. <BR><BR>If this is to be the destiny of man, what is the purpose of living? Withone group of people destined to create property, and the other to destroyit? Why bother? Why not just destroy everything now? Why bother creatingchildren if this is to be their destiny? Do we need both creators and destroyers?Is that is what is called &quot;the balance of nature&quot;? <BR><BR>The other animals of the planet only kill for food to survive, and onlyvery rarely is that their own specie. And those are generally only the predatorclass of animals. If they had the intellect to preserve food and distributeit through supermarkets, they might find that easier and less stressful.And then they would have more time to contemplate and enjoy nature. Takevacations, and things like that. <BR><BR>And yes, they do fight among themselves to see who will be the dominantanimal in their group, just as man does. But they are significantly lessintelligent, so we can &quot;forgive&quot; them. Or, more correctly, understandand empathize with their situation. <BR></UL><LI><B>Semantic precision is necessary to the creation of useful knowledge.</B><BR><UL>Unless people have mutually agreed and understood definitions therecan be no effective communication, with the attendant possibility of creatingnew and useful knowledge. <BR><BR>Think of four people, one each from the USA, Hong Kong, Singapore, and Australia.They wish to buy and sell property among themselves. The currency of eachtribal area is what is called a &quot;dollar.&quot; Yet the value on anabsolute basis is different for each. If they do not specify which typeof dollar they are talking about, they will not be able to conduct businesseffectively. <BR><BR>If some people interpreted horsepower to mean torque, or octane rating tomean tire pressure, you could not build a workable car. If people thoughtthat wave length was the same as impedance, there would be no television,computers, or anything involving what we call &quot;electronic&quot; or&quot;electrical&quot; equipment. <BR><BR>Why then can we expect things to work in the social sphere when there area myriad of ideas of what constitutes property, justice, crime, legality,inflation, price increase, liberal, freedom, democrat, democracy, socialist,conservative, human rights, and all the other operative concepts associatedwith social structures? <BR><BR>By definition, man--the animal who is the dominant volitional specie onthis planet--is a part of nature. Resident in the same universe as automobiles,penicillin, oxygen, cosmic rays, x-rays, water, etc. The laws of natureapply to man and his social structures as they do to all other parts ofour universe. If not, we are living a purposeless illusion. If that is true,I really do want to get off the celestial bus before it self-destructs.If that is not true, then I want to stop the bus and fix it before thereis a major accident. <BR></UL><LI><B>Our universe is a closed, thermodynamic model.</B> <BR><UL>Acceptance of this reality will allow us to solve the problem of thermodynamicpollution and determine the purpose of life. <BR><BR>Too much to discuss further here. <BR><BR></UL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>|[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]|<HR NOSHADE> </CENTER><P><LI><B>Individuals whose occupation involves property interference orthe destruction of property are insignificant in long-term history.</B><BR><UL>Why do we have twenty or thirty pages in an encyclopedia extolling thelife and +virtues&quot; of Napoleon, and less than a page for Newton? <BR><BR>We revel in the &quot;glory&quot; of the man who destroyed vast amountsof property and impoverished France for a century. Yet there is--what isin essence--only a passing mention for the man who created the IndustrialRevolution, and thus our modern technological world. Think of the amountof property that was destroyed, vs. the amount created. Which person isthe better role model in history? <BR><BR>Suppose you had spent a lifetime building up a successful business, hada wonderful marriage, and several very fine children. Now someone comesalong and destroys your business, your home, and all your property. <BR><BR>I am sure you would grab pencil and paper (your computers were no doubtlost) and write a flowing tribute to the person who did this. Dwell on thewonder, grandeur, and glory of this person's life. And tell your children,&quot;This is the person I wish you to emulate in life.&quot; This is whatyou would do, yes? So that your children would seek to accomplish what this&quot;wonderful&quot; person has accomplished. And, with luck, one of themcould be as &quot;successful&quot; as this person, perhaps even be a Hitler.<BR><BR>This in preference to something like solving the problem of cancer, Alzheimer'sdisease, being able to reconnect severed nerves, design a &quot;pollution-free&quot;automobile, find the solution to the problem of crime. <BR><BR>After all, what is the value of such mundane things compared to the abilityof being able to watch the wars of the future from your living room as ifyou were there on the battlefield, and to be able to send and receive faxesto your son or daughter on that battlefield, giving them hints on how tobetter annihilate the &quot;enemy.&quot; While at the same time perhapsbeing able to help by disrupting the faxes from an &quot;enemy&quot; fatherto his son on the battlefield. <BR><BR>That is the future we wish to create, yes? That is the true destiny forour specie, yes? I have seen something similar to that--being able to communicatewith your children on the battlefield--proposed as a model for the futureby a prominent North American politician. One who is in an ideal positionto assist in creating that future. <BR></UL><LI><B>There are epistemological tools which can be used to determine whetherany idea, proposed action, or action is right on an absolute basis, whetherit involves volitional or non-volitional concepts.</B> <BR><UL>There would be no point in discussing the problems of society if therewere no tools for repairing the problem. <BR><BR>It is knowledge--useful knowledge--which fixes problems. Even when the problemis a leaky faucet. Without the knowledge of how a faucet works, it wouldtake a very long time to fix it. If you have a new battery, a spare tire,a can of petrol, an air pump, a washer, an extra postal envelope, a hammer,a pipe wrench, an adjustable wrench, a pair of pliers, a screwdriver, anda drill, if you don't know which one to use, how to use it and when, youwon't fix the problem. Each item is the solution or part of the solutionfor a problem, but not knowing how to use the tools makes problem solutiona haphazard event. <BR><BR>The tools mentioned above were tangible tools. The tools for repairing aknowledge problem are intangible tools, those evolving from epistemology,or the study of the nature of knowledge. <BR><BR>For this we can examine what tools have been used successfully for the creationof useful knowledge in other subjects. We might ask ourselves if there areareas in which there has been relatively large and successful increasesin useful knowledge, and how this was done. And whether or not the lessonslearned there would be useful to us in creating a rational and durable civilization.<BR></UL>The answer to this is the purpose and function of <CITE>The Freedom Server.</CITE><BR><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE><BR>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation <BR><BR><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I> </CENTER><P><HR><BR><B>Contact Information:<BR></B>E-Mail: administrator@Freedom-Server.co.uk<BR><HR>The URL of this page is: <BR><P><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Preface.html&gt; <HR NOSHADE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
