<H3>This Day in History &amp; Value in Society</H3><H4>| <A HREF="Day-in-History-Apr.html">This Day in History--April '96</A> |  <A HREF="Day-in-History-May.html">This Day in History--May '96</A> |<BR>| <A HREF="Current-Values-Mar.html">Values in Society--March '96</A> |</H4><HR NOSHADE><H3>Background</H3></CENTER><p>The various societies on this planet of the volitional specie known as <I>man</I>are in a state of accelerating decline. This can confirmed and measuredby:</p><UL>  <LI>crime   <LI>social disorder   <LI>wars   <LI>unemployment   <LI>state deficits   <LI>inflation, recessions, depressions   <LI>decline in the quality of medical care while the cost increases </UL><p>Most of what we believe to be correct and right about our social structure,and all knowledge except that related to what is normally called <I>science,</I>is wrong. Something which can be corroborated by history, and whichwill be demonstrated in <I>The Freedom Server</I></p><p>The reason behind this was eloquently and succinctly illustrated by thegreat Thomas Paine, when he said: </p><center><b>"A long habit of not thinking a thing wrong,<br>	gives it a superficial appearance of being right..."</b></center><p>It is precisely because we have <I>not</I> accepted that political societiesare wrong (that is, societies based on coercion), that we believe they areright and will eventually work. Yet millennia of history shows this to notbe true, yet something our minds do not accept. We believe that tinkeringwith the mechanism will eventually fix it, and that enforcing the will ofone group of people on another produces a viable societal mechanism.</p><p>Our social structure is like a giant Rube Goldberg machine that continuesto fall apart and be patched. One for which the drawings were long ago lost,along with the configuration history. Yet the problem is that the basicpremises upon which the machine was designed are faulty (although in realityit just happened, and was not consciously designed), and it can <B>never</B>work using these basic premises.</p><p>Further, it is very important to understand that it is <B>only</B> increasedknowledge--new and useful kowledge--that truly solves problems. The problemsof society can <B>NOT </B>be fixed through violent means. Besides beingimmoral, violence and property destruction is irrational and only bringsincreased state repression and less chance that the problems can be fixed.The problems can not be fixed by marching and protesting for or againstthings. They can not be solved by inteference in the property of others.They can only be fixed by providing an alternative that is personally profitableto each individual.</p><p>What is necessary is to create a mechanism that works? One which is &quot;profitable&quot;for each individual, bringing an increased quality of life and continuouslyincreasing opportunity for each individual. The summation of individualsbeing a society. When this happens, and such a mechanism competes with thepolitical state in the marketplace, individuals will freely select the mechanismwhich is best for them. This allows a transition without disorder and propertydestruction.</p><p><I>The Freedom Server</I> will illustrate what is wrong and how to fix it,although the emphasis will be on fixing the problems. With a little bitof knowledge about what is wrong you will eventually learn to recognizethe examples yourself, which are myriad. It is more important to know <I>why</I>it is wrong, and how to fix it than to have endless renditions of the problems.You can read those everyday in what is euphemistically called "news."</p><p>Occasionally there will be intentional humor, yet this is not a subjectto be taken lightly. The evolution of man has been very long and very painful,more like a tragic comedy in many ways. And, when we could and should beon the verge of making the transition to a rational and durable society,we are faltering with quite probably disastrous, terminal results. We aresliding almost inexorably into an abyss filled with failed civilizations.And, as an astute observor will note, thare are no miraculous resurrectionsfor failed civilizations. And this time it is the sum-total of mankind thatwill disappear, and not one civilization out of many.</p><p>Our clue for this should be that history is mostly a rendition of &quot;TheRise and Fall of -----,&quot; and fill in the blank with the name of a failedcivilization. Together with the fact that the life span of each such failedcivilization has become shorter than the last. And, lastly, as we have seenin recent years, civilizations and societies around the world are inter-lockedin this dance of death. An economic problem in one country, even small ones,reverberates around the world. A war or other terrorist act sucks in a multitudeof nations. And the victims are almost never the perpetrators, who sit inguarded palaces and travel in bullet-proof limousines.</p><p>It is pathetic and tragic seeing ignorant people in a position of powerover the lives and destiny of all others. We have not learned who our trueleaders are: <I>individuals who create new and useful knowledge with thepotential of increasing the quality of life for all mankind.</I> Yet wevenerate and actually seem to respect not these people, but those whoselives have been devoted to the destruction of property-both tangible andintangible. Examples of this will appear in other sections of <I>The FreedomServer.</I></p><p>As one example to consider now before you go on, you might consider thatof Napoleon and Amp&egrave;re, who were contemporaries. Napoleon, besidesthe vast property destruction which occurred during his short reign, impoverishedEurope and France for a century. He rates about thirty pages in encyclopedias.Amp&egrave;re, the father of electromagnetism, the foundation of our modernworld, rates less than a page. Which is the truly important figure in history?And why? Which figure <I>should</I> children wish to emulate? Which figure<I>do</I> children wish to emulate? Why? What lessons can we learn fromthis?</p><HR><center><p><LI><B>Notice:</B></p></center><p>I did not intend to start this publishing venture until more material anda secure server were available, but certain personal events have made medecide to do it now, even though additional essays and other items willnot be added for a few weeks.</p><p>Where it indicates in the Table of Comments that certain things are notyet available, most of them have been written, but I am not yet sure howI wish to distribute them and on what basis. They should appear in the not-too-distantfuture.</p><HR><p>For an introduction to the essays that will appear in the future, and foran idea of what is to come on <I>The Freedom Server</I> please read the<A HREF="Preface.html">Preface.</A></p><p>The preface can also be viewed in HTML format from the Table of Contentssection, and also downloaded in Adobe <I>Acrobat</I> format from there.</p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]<HR NOSHADE><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></p><HR NOSHADE></center><p>Contact Information:</p><a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">administrator@freedom-server.co.uk</a><HR><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER><P>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/index.html&gt;</p></center><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
