ofhistory and current events.  Except where I <b>do</b> provideexplicit credit, the ideas are essentially original or independentwith me based on my observations and thought concerning what I reador observe in the world around me. </p><p>At the same time, as indicated in the "Credits" section of theserver, I must give credit to my intellectual antecedents.  Those who havecreated intellectual or intangible property--the ideologicalflowstream of our specie--and thus constitute the mainstream ofhistory. And, for that term and concept I must give explicit credit to mygreat and wonderful Teacher.</p><p> With gratitude to my Teacher, and an obligation to him andmyself, one very major, on-going project is the creation of adatabase of those I suspect of having influenced my thinking, and tocreate and implement a system of credits and royalty accrual forthem. </p><p> By the very way in which knowledge is created, each individual isindebted to their intellectual antecedents.  Even if the personcreating new knowledge lives in a virtual vacuum and has only thework of two or three people on which to draw ideas from our specie'swarehouse of knowledge, those two or three people almost certainlyhad access to the entire warehouse. </p><p> Thus, we all owe gratitude to the entire intellectual mainstreamof history.  However, with the caveat that--by definition--this onlyincludes the creators of property, and not those who interfere in ordestroy property. </p><hr><p>If you would to comment on any existing or proposed articles pleasecontact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">administrator</a> at The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup>.</p><hr noshade><center><h3>Essays Available for Purchase</h3></center><p>Individual essays may be purchased, although it will becost-effective and convenient to have a subscription when available.</p><p>Those essays written and available for purchase have two differentprice ranges:</p><ol>	<p>	<li><a href="#ZPE">Zero Price Essays</a>	</p>	<p>	These are essays for which the price is zero, as opposed to	being "free."  This is an important distinction in a world in	which many things are advertised as being "free."  There are actually	very few things that are truly free--things for which there can	be or is no price.  In fact, the only one I know of is "access	to nature."  That must be free, although political states even	try--and sometimes do--control that also.	</p>	<p>	Actually, while access to nature (what this means will be explained	in an essay--it doesn't mean what most people assume it to	mean) should be free, any volitional specie has a very basic	price they must pay if they wish to survive in the long term. 	Meaning, a time scale concomitant with that of the existence of	their local universe. That price is that they must strive to explore	and understand their universe on a moral basis, and with a	rationality consistent with their understanding of their universe at	any one time.	</p>	<p>	This is a concept I have redefined  as the "Holy Grail" for any	volitional specie, resurrecting that term from the mystics and	restoring it to place of honor and significance.	</p>	<p>	<li><a href="#NZPE">Non-Zero Price Essays</a>	</p>	<p>	As this implies, there will be a price greater than zero.	</p></ol><hr>	<p>	<li><a href="#FCE">Forthcoming Essays</a>	</p>	<ul>	<p>	In addition to essays already written, I have a large backlog of	subjects on which I will write essays.  Time permitting.  I currently	have a backlog of work requiring something on the order of 800	years to complete and, unless someone understands what I have	written and does some work in biology, I am unlikely to complete	the tasks in the queue.	</p></ul><hr noshade><center><a name="ZPE"><h3>Zero Price Essays</h3></a></center><hr><p><li><a name="PHAR"><b>The Land of the Pharaohs</p>	<ul>	<p>	The Concept of Importance and Fraud in History,	</p>		<p>	and the Survival of Man</b>.	</p>	</ul><ul>	<p>	Who is important in history and will be remembered, and why?	Can an individual ensure they will be remembered?  Those for	whom stone and bronze monuments are erected are the least	important in history, and those who are truly important need	erect no monuments. The failure to understand who and what is	important in history has a direct bearing on the quality of	individual life, and even on the survival of the specie itself.	</p><p>	<a href="Land-of-Pharaohs.html">HTML</a> Format, 	24 Kb file size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Land-of-Pharaohs.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	24 Kb file.	</p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="OPR"><b>The Origin, Purpose and Use of Religions<br>	<ul>	<ul>	and<br>	</ul>	</ul>	The Decline of Civilization</b></a></p><ul>	<p>	Revsied 1996, October 2	</p>		<p>	All volitional species will develope the concept of a god	during their primitive stage of development.  However, the concept	presents an opportunity for mischief and must be quickly discarded	else the specie will not make the transition to a rational and	durable societal structure.  Using the universal  laws of volitional	behavior it is possible to prove that god is not volitional and, in	fact, that god can exist only as a figment of human	imagination.	</p>		<p>	The essay also illustrates how belief in religion will prevent the	transition of a volitional civilization from that of a primitive one	dooming the specie to extincition within a relatively short time	to that of rational and durable civilization and specie whose	time-scale of existence will be concomitant with that of its own	universe.	</p>		<p>	<a href="Origin-Purpose-Religions.html">HTML</a> Format, 	45 Kb file size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Origin-Purpose-Religion.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	48 Kb file.	</p></ul>	<hr><p><li><a name="HBF"><b>The Hilary Factor: Why All Political Societies				Fail</b></a></p><ul>	<p>	Many people see there are problems with our society. Some know	these have persisted throughout history.  Few have even an inkling of	the cause. And, while there is a solution, people are either	not interested or do not have the epistemological tools available to	analyze the solution, and the willingness to apply it.	</p>		<p>	<b>The Hilary Factor: Why All Political Societies Fail</b>	</p>		<p>	<a href="Hilary-Bedeman-Factor.html">HTML</a> Format, 	30 Kb file size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Hilary-Bedeman-Factor.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	30 Kb file.	</p></ul>	<hr><p><li><a name="CR"><b>How Do You Know You Are Right?</b></a></p><ul>	<p>	This is a very profound question for any volitional specie.  Perhaps	<i>the</i> most profound question of all those facing mankind	today. The ability to determine right from not right has been	the basis for our modern technological world.  The failure to use the	same intellectual tool in the social sphere is the cause of <b>all</b>	our societal problems. The solution to all of these problems is	simple if we but clear away the pollution in our minds. To be able	to judge what is right and not right in the social sphere.  What has	worked and will work, what has not worked and will not work.	</p>		<p>	<b>How Do You Know You Are Right?</b>	</p>		<p>	<a href="Concept-of-Rightness.html">HTML</a> Format, 	24 Kb file size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Concept-of-Rightness.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	21 Kb file.	</p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="LTP"><b>Long-Term Profitability</b></a></p><ul>	<p>	Our current understanding of how to create and maximize profits	is not correct.  This essay discusses the historic concept of	the "job," and the solution to our current problems of innovation,	productivity, and quality.	</p>		<p>	<b>Long-Term Profitability</b>	</p>		<p>	<a href="Long-Term-Profitability.html">HTML</a> Format, 	21 Kb file size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Long-Term-Profitability.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	21 Kb file.	</p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="LPS"><b>Loopholes and Political Societies</b></p><ul>	<p>	This essay will explain and discuss one of the two basic, motivational	and behavioral characteristics of volitional beings: The desire	to create, accumulate, and use property.  And, how this is contrary	to the wishes of the politicians, who want to control and limit	the accumulation and use of individual property.  How this creates	the search for "loopholes" in the system, with the politicians	also looking for them, but to close them.  How this creates	increasing stresses in the associated society, leading to increasing	violence and the eventual destruction of the society.	</p>		<p>	<b>Loopholes and Political Societies</b>	</p>	<p>	<a href="Loophole-Political-State.html">HTML</a> Format, 	21 Kb file size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Loophole-Political-State.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	18 Kb file.	</p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="PHS"><b>Protest &amp; Human Survival</b></p><ul>	<p>	In political societies, in which the rulers and their minions	try to create "equality," protesting is the attempt by individuals to	maintain their own identity and pursue their individual aspirations	in a sea of sameness.  This leads to increasing disorder in which the	societal structure either self-destructs or is taken over by another	political entity.  The only solution to this basic dilemma is	the creation of a rational and social structure based on the	nature of man (the specie).	</p>	<p>	<b>Protest &amp; Human Survival</b>	</p>		<p>	<a href="Protest-Human-Survival.html">HTML</a> Format, 	18 Kb file size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Protest-Human-Survival.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	15 Kb file.	</p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="HN"><b>Need and Morality in Society</b></p><ul>	<p>	In the discussion of need and morality this essay also promulgates the	two principle upon which all human behavior is based and can be	analyzed.  In the process of which it provides basic information	required for the creation of a rational and durable societal	mechanism to replace our present defective and unworkable systems	based on coercion.	</p>		<p>	<b>Need and Morality in Society</b>	</p>		<p>	<a href="Human-Need.html">HTML</a> Format, 21 Kb file size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Human-Need.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	18 Kb file.	</p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="HN"><b>In Certain Cases Terrorism Is Okay</b></p><ul>	<p>	I do not agree with that statement--I am merely stating a fact	on something that is accepted by everyone.  Not the image, that	is not acceptable to most rational and moral people.  However,	the principle of what I have said is accepted by everyone. Why	do I say this? Because no one uses a proper definition of terrorism,	and because people do not think in terms of principles, but rather of	appearances or images.	</p>		<p>	<b>In Certain Cases Terrorism Is Okay</b>	</p>		<p>	<a href="Terrorism-is-Okay.html">HTML</a> Format, 21 Kb file size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Terrorism-is-Okay.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	18 Kb file.	</p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="PROP"><b>The Concept of Property and the Political 	State</b></p><ul>	<p>	A proper understanding of the concept of property is essential to	understanding the cause of the problems associated with coercive	political societies and how to build a rational and durable social	structure.	<p>		<p>	This essays is not meant to be totally definitive and all inclusive,	having been written as a precursor to the subject of <b>ethics</b>,	which follows.	</p>		<p>	<b>The Concept of Property and the Political State</b>	</p>		<p>	<a href="Property-and-Politics.html">HTML</a> Format, 18 Kb file	size.	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Property-and-Politics.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	12 Kb file.	</p>	</ul><hr><p><li><a name="ETH"><b>Ethics</b></p><ul>	<p>	A very short, but definitive and important essay on the subject of	ethics.  You should have read the essay on "The Concept of Property	and the Political State" before reading this essay.	</p>		<p>	<b>Ethics</b>	</p>		<p>	<a href="Ethics.html">HTML</a> Format	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Ethics.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format	</p>	</ul><hr><p><li><a name="PORT"><b>Importance in History</b></p><ul>	<p>	This essay, which is a "preface" to the Database of	Important People in History discusses the concept of importance and	demonstrates what and who is important and not important in history,	and why. This is a short discussion of the subject, with a longer,	more detailed essay to follow.	</p>	<p>	In this and the following essay, you will learn why politicians	are not important in history--why they achieve insignificance in	history as soon as they descend to political office.  The higher they	go up in the political hierarchy the more insignificant they become	in long term history.  Thus, there is an indirect relationship between	political significance and importance in history.	</p>	<p>	<a href="Importance-in-History.html">HTML</a> Format	</p>	<p>	Adobe <a href="Importance-in-History.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format, 21 Kb file size. 	</p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="CAT"><b>Cat License or Death</b></a></p><ul>	<p>	This essay illustrates why all political states must, in the	final analysis, insist that <b>all</b> political laws must have death	as the ultimate penalty for disobedience.  It also explains	<b>why</b> this is "something not seen."	</p>	<p>	<a href="Cat-License-or-Death.html">HTML</a> Format	</p>	<p>	Adobe <a href="Cat-License-or-Death.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format, 	14 Kb file size.	</p></ul><hr><p><li><b>On...Government of the People, Against the People</b></p><ul>	<p>	This essays discusses how the concept and intentions of the	"Framers and Founders" of the United States have been	perverted by their lower class successors.	</p>		<p>	Government of the people, by the people, and for the people is now	no different than what the "Framers and Founders" hoped to	eliminate.  Their hope to sanctify and protect individual property	has turned into a contest to see which politician can plunder the	most.  And the concept of "one girl, millions of votes" prevails.	</p>		<p>	<a href="Govt-Against-People.html">HTML</a> Format	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="Govt-Against-People.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	14 Kb. file size.	</p></ul><hr><li><b><a name="CORR">The Correct Question</a></b><ul>	<p>	Generally speaking, in conversations or articles related to the	subject of the "social sciences" and/or politics, people always ask	the wrong question.	</p>		<p>	They ask whether we need this or that law, whether people should be	forced to do one thing instead of another.  If the Republicans or the	Democrats are right on a particular issue.  Whether a person should	vote for this or that person or in favor of or against a particular	referendum.  But these are not the correct questions.	</p>		<p>	For some enlightenment on this subject, please read the following	essay on <b>The Correct Question</b>:	<p>		<p>	<a href="The-Correct-Question.html">HTML</a> Format	</p>		<p>	Adobe <a href="The-Correct.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	18 Kb. file size.	</p></ul><hr noshade><center><a name="NZPE"><h3>Non-Zero Price Essays</h3></a></center><p><li><b>Electronic Democracy</b></p><ul>	<p>	Some people predict a societal or "political" trend in	which--through electronic means--the world will evolve toward a	concept of "electronic democracy."  With all citizens "wired," and a	constant plebiscite in which people express their wishes on what	should be done in society.	</p>	<p>	This essay explains why democracy has not worked and can not	work, why this non-solution will be an even greater disaster, and the	solution to the problem.  Which is <b>not</b> within the political	mechanism.	</p>	<p>	File Size: approx. 14 Kb.<br> No. of Words: 2,150 (approx.)<br>	No. of Pages: 3 (approx.)	</p>	<p>	Price: to be determined	</p></ul><hr><p><li><b>False Alternatives and Human Destiny</b></p><ul>	<p>	This essay describes the problems of societal structures	based on coercion--such as all of the societies on this planet--and	provides the concepts and principles for building a rational and	durable social structure.  Such a social structure will provide for	an increasingly high quality of life for all volitional beings on	this planet.	</p>	<p>	File Size: approx. 42 Kb.<br> No. of Words: 6,200 (approx.)<br>	No. of Pages: 13 (approx.)	</p>	<p>	Price: US$1,000.	</p>	<p>	<b>Restricted distribution</b>.  This essay is available only at the	discretion of the Universal Salvage Corporation after purchase of	certain other essays, and submission and review of a commentary on	those essays by the prospective purchaser.	</p></ul><hr><p>For more information on the above essays please contact the<a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">administrator</a>.</p><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade><center><a name="FCE"><h3>Forthcoming Essays</h3></a></center><hr><h4>On... the Redefinition of Hell</h4>	<ul>		<p>		This subject was inspired by an article in <i>The Times</i> of		London, on 1996, July 15, entitled "Synod backs rethink on		traditional view of Hell."		</p>				<p>		Man's need to invent the concepts of "heaven" and "hell" originate		from his original lack of knowledge of his "natural" world.  Why		there was lightning &amp; thunder, why there were seasons and		they changed, why there was food and then no food, etc.  And		the associated fact that life was extraordinarily difficult, and		the wish that it were better and "easier," and the creation of		an imaginary world in which this would be so.		</p>				<p>		Life on earth was truly "hell" in a relative sense for millions		of years, and only became partially better--and certainly more		bearable for many--through the discovery and understanding of		basic concepts of nature which lead to the introduction of what		is commonly called "technology."		</p>				<p>		However, life continues to be "hell" in a relative sense since		man still lives under the primitive tribal and societal concept		known as "politics."		</p>	</ul><hr>		<h4>On...Pollution</h4><ul> <p> When the subject of pollution is discussed, the firstthought is usually of smokestacks and automobiles belching smoke,polluted rivers and other graphic and obvious evidences of pollution.</p><p> The solution to the problems of traditional pollution is actuallyquite simple. The problem is that it releases so much energy--makingthe H-bomb seem like a firecracker in comparison--that the knowledgeof its implementation is much too dangerous in the hands of primitivesocieties based on coercion.  There are already enough ways for thevarious political r&eacute;gimes to kill their own subjects and thoseof other, competing r&eacute;gimes.</p><p> Yet there is another type of pollution that is <b>much</b> moredangerous, and which is preventing us from effectively solving themore graphic and obvious types of pollution mentioned above.  And ofcreating a rational and durable social structure.</p></ul><hr><h4>On...Societal Empowerment</h4><ul> <p> One of the hottest topics in the business world is that of"empowerment," and there are trends toward trying to implement anequivalent thing in society. </p><p> This essay will discuss this non-solution.</p></ul><hr><h4>On...A Rational System of Education</h4><ul> <p> Schools are a disaster almost everywhere, and the systemitself is a total disaster, based on improper concepts of education.Even the best schools use improper concepts. </p><p> This essay outlines the very simple principles of an educationalsystem which is also very simple to implement.  In principle, thebest teachers should have incomes that exceed the highest incomesexisting in the current business world.  Morally and rationally,every student--or parents of students--must pay for the educationtheir children receive, and for their education only.  The essaydescribes a system in which it is possible for any child to availthemselves of the best and highest paid teachers, and the mostexpensive education.</p></ul><hr><h4>On...There Must Be Rules</h4><ul> <p> When a solution to societal problems that does not involvepolitical laws is discussed, the first response is "...but there<b>must</b> be rules." </p><p> This is very true, but only one, very simple "law" or rule isrequired. This then brings up two more complaints.  One is that "Itis a good idea, but it won't work."  The second is "Yes, but how doyou 'enforce' the rule in such a system?" </p><p> The first follow-on subject is covered in a separate essay asindicated below.  The latter subject is covered in <cite>FalseAlternatives and Human Destiny.</cite> </p> </ul><hr><h4>On...That's a Good Idea, but It Won't Work.</h4><ul> <p> This statement is very common, but represents an internalcontradiction.  If something is a good idea, it <b>will</b> work,else it is not a good idea. </p><p> This subject dwells on the science of epistemology, the natureof knowledge.  Included is a brief discussion of the differencebetween hypotheses and theories, and how knowledge is created. </p></ul><hr><h4>On...Political vs. Moral Solutions to Problems</h4><ul> <p> Politics and morality--and rationality--are mutuallyexclusive concepts, which is why there has never been a politicalsolution to any problem, in the sense of a moral and rationalsolution. </p><p> When there is a "disturbance" with the threat of war or militaryaction, a common statement is "...we need to find a 'political'solution to this."  The implication is that this will be a "peaceful"solution.  Yet this is not possible under the non-principles on whichpolitics is based.  A "political solution" to a problem would be tobomb the "offending" people into oblivion, since the military ismerely a branch of politics and thus a part--a very essentialpart--of the political system. A military solution <b>is</b> a"political solution" to the problem. </p><p> This essay discusses the true nature of politics, and theinternal logic contradictions within it as intimated by the title.</p></ul><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade><h4>On...Inflation is Not a Price Increase, and<br> A Price Increaseis Not Inflation.</h4><ul> <p> I know of only a few people on this planet who couldcorrectly be termed "economists," and those have been virtuallytotally ignored. Some of them have sold millions of copies of theirbooks, but it is obvious that--assuming they have been read--eitherno one understood what they read or, worse, that they did not believevolitional life was worth trying to save on this planet.  There seemsto be no other excuse for the nonsense that passes for what happensin the financial world. </p> </ul><hr><h4>On...The Problems of Societal Transition.</h4><ul> <p> A major problem in illustrating an advanced, rational, anddurable society as a substitute for the failed concept in use today,is "Yes, it might work, but how do we get there?" </p><p> This is a major, very real problem, as the distortions caused bymillennia of coercion-based societies makes it difficult to breachthe gap, and make the transition to a durable societal structure.  Adifficulty that is now increasing almost exponentially. </p><p> This essay discusses the problem and how to handle it in arational and <b>moral</b> manner that will increase the quality oflife, not only for those who participate in the solution, but for allbeings. </p> </ul><hr><h4>On...Marriage and Other Political Licenses.</h4><ul> <p> What makes the political state such an expert on marriagethat it should issue marriage licenses?  Why should <b>anyone</b>believe that they need a political license to be married?  Is it alicense that makes a marriage? </p><p> A political state requires and issues marriage licenses tofurther their control over their subjects and to provide anadditional revenue source.  Other license requirements, such as formedical doctors, lawyers, and a myriad of other functions arerequired for the same purposes, plus the ostensible "benefit" that--by requiring a license--the state will therefore guarantee thequality of services provided.  I am sure everyone agrees this hasbeen the result, and that there are no medical or legal quacks. </p><p> This essay discusses this situation and the rational and<b>moral</b> solution to the problem of guaranteeing the quality ofservices. </p></ul><hr><h4>On...Death and Taxes.</h4><ul><p> It is often said that the only things certain in life are "deathand taxes."  The only thing certain within that concept is that ifsocietal systems in which the mechanism of taxation is a dominantfeature continues, that death of the associated volitional specie is acertainty. </p> </ul><hr><h4>On...Why "Think Tanks" Have Never Solved Any SocietalProblems.</h4><ul> <p> The so-called "Think Tanks," and especially those related tothe solving of man's societal problems, are really just havens forfuzzy-logic thought processes, based in false premises. </p><p> A seemingly endless stream of papers on societal ills such asinflation, unemployment, war, deficits, terrorism and assorted otherthings have been spewing forth from the "Think Tanks." Meanwhile, theproblems of society get worse, not better. </p><p>There is a basic reason for this, the recognition of which willdrastically alter the institution.</p></ul><hr><h4>On...Hereditary Rule.</h4><ul> <p> "The King is Dead--Long Live the King."  This is the imageof hereditary rule.  Something the so-called "democratic societies"have long since dispensed with, yes?  The image is different than thereality. </p> </ul><hr><h4>On...Fighting for Causes.</h4><ul> <p> "Fighting for (a cause)" has the image of a noble, solitaryindividual struggling to "right a wrong."  Yet "fighting" is anartifact of war, and the techniques of war are often used, includingthe murder of those who do not agree with the "fighter."  Is this theway to solve the problems of society? </p> </ul><hr><h4>On...the Stoplight Mentality</h4><ul> <p> Increasingly in political states, that which is notexpressly permitted is assumed--and may actually be--prohibited. Thiscreates an increasingly timid and therefore incompetent group ofpeople with decreasing self-esteem.  This in turn increases theclamor for "more and better laws" to "protect the people." This leadsto a general decline of the quality life and the eventual death ofpolitical structures. </p> </ul><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade><h4>On...Minority vs. Majority Rule</h4><ul><p>The typical image of minority rule is that of a small"elite" or perhaps "aristocratic" group of people ruling all others.Majority rule is thought of as, well, "the majority" of allpeople deciding what they want for themselves.  The most common formbeing that of "representative" government in the form of a republic.The truth of what happens in such a society is much different thanthe image.</p><p>So-called "self-governing" through a representative or republicform of political state presents an internal contradiction in termsand has a hidden trap.  It creates a "representative body" or a"middle-man" group.  These middle-men represent an organization thatacquires a life of its own, becoming a self-perpetuating group thatin fact acts as a ruling minority that is no different than traditionalminority rule by an elite or aristocratic group such as a hereditarymonarchy.</p><p> In fact, such a group is much more dangerous than that of atraditional hereditary monarchy for reasons explained in the essay.</p></ul><hr><h4>On...The Rights of Man</h4><ul> <p> As pointed out by Keane in his recent biography of Paine."Tom Paine: A Political Life" (Bloomsbury Publishing plc - 1995),"The Rights of Man" by Thomas Paine was--relatively speaking-- themost widely read book of all time, in any language. </p><p> It was almost "heretical" in nature, calling for a totally newand different societal structure based on representative"government," in which the people would determine how they would beruled.  It represented such a huge intellectual leap that neither Paine--norothers--could foresee that this was only an interim solution tosocietal problems, which would create its own problems. Paine shouldnot be faulted nor criticized for this. </p><p> This essay will discuss the reason the problem could not beforeseen, and provide pointers to the next and last step necessaryin the creation of a rational and durable societal structure. </p></ul><hr><h4>On...Definitions</h4><ul> <p> This essay discusses the epistemological basis for worddefinitions and the need for semantic precision as the basis foreffective communication and the development of new and usefulknowledge. </p><p> This essay will also explain why I try to avoid the use ofcertain words, emphasize others, and the attempt--not alwayssuccessful-- at semantic precision.</p></ul><hr><h4>On...Financing Medical Research</h4><ul> <p> Innovation in general is not financed properly, but medicalinnovation is a special victim of a primitive concept of innovationcompensation.  The medical field is also a victim of the concept thatthere should be zero or a very small profit from medical advances.</p><p> This essay will describe a medical innovation compensation systemthat has the potential for creating startling improvements in medicalcare.  The reason I had to use the word "potential" is that thepolitical state acts as a tremendous hindrance to medical advances.There is also a simple, moral solution to this problem. </p> </ul><hr><h4><a name="LAND">On...the Land of the Pharaohs</h4><ul> <p> Volitional beings with a very short life span, such as iscurrent on this planet, continuously strive for ways to mark theirexistence and the validity and significance of their life.  Thosewith no valid understanding of the concept of property and ofimportance attempt to validate and signify their life through theerection of stone or metal monuments.  There is an indirectrelationship between this and the durability of the associatedsocietal structures and civilization in general. </p><p> The reader can gain an insight into this concept by some thinkingon the statements of Horatius and Wren in the list of <ahref="Quotations.html#HORATIUS">Quotations.</a> </p><p> See also <a href="#POP">On...Popularity and Importance.</a></p></ul><hr><h4>On...Satisfaction of Individual Need in a Rational Society</h4><ul> <p> The wishes and desires of individual volitional beings are,for all practical purposes, unbounded and very great.  For a societyto be durable, these wishes and desires must be balanced against thetrue <b>need</b> for physiological survival to arrive at a clearunderstanding of the concept of "need." </p><p> Based on the carbon-oxygen life cycle on this planet, the individualvolitional being requires water and food for physiological survival.And, except in temperate and/or warm climates, shelter from theelements of weather.  Other life forms in other parts of theuniverse--and the associated volitional beings--could derive theirenergy from a chlorine cycle, radiant energy, or some other means andthus have different physiological needs. </p><p> Beyond that, the satisfaction of wishes and desires can only beachieved and restrained in a rational and moral manner based on theability of each individual to satisfy these wishes and desires<b>without interfering in the property of another</b>.  Failure toobserve this concept results in a societal structure with a built-inself-destruct mechanism.  A society that will pass through increasingchaos until its ultimate and inexorable demise.  On this planet thedust-bin of history is rapidly filling with such failed societies.</p><p>In the past this could be viewed as not being critical since--althoughrepresenting the ultimate personal tragedy for each effectindividual--the volitional specie on this planet did not yetpossess the technological ability to destroy its own specie.  Thisis no longer true.</p><p>At the risk of sounding repetitious, the purpose of these essaysis the creation of a rational, moral, and durable mechanism thatprevents this disaster.</p></ul><hr><h4>On...Judges, Flower-Show and Political</h4><ul> <p> There are rational and moral concepts of "judging," and thenthere are political concepts of the subject. </p><p> This essay will discuss the societal implications of the subject.</p></ul><hr><h4>On...Free Trade</h4><ul> <p> As a concept, free trade has almost universal appeal andacceptance. Yet when there are attempts to implement truly freetrade, almost everyone wants to protect some product or service. </p><p> As is always the case in politics, false advertising is rampant.A case in point is the so-called North American Free Trade Agreement,or NAFTA.  In reality, it should be called the North American<b>Restrictive</b> Trade Agreement (NA<b>R</b>TA), because trade isnot free, and is certainly restricted. </p><p> The natural interest and condition of volitional beings is tofreely exchange goods and services.  It is only politicalstates, for their own nefarious reasons--including the ability to"justify" their continued need and existence--which wish to regulatetrade.  If restricted trade is a good idea, why not protect the"interests" of Los Angeles against those of San Francisco? Or twoneighbors across the street?  It is only primitive concepts of life,property, prosperity, money, and other things which prevent freetrade.</p></ul><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade><h4><a name="POP">On...Popularity and Importance<a/></h4><ul><p>We have an increasingly distorted view of importance on thisplanet, equating it with popularity.  With a correct understanding ofthe two concepts, people such as Tesla and Maxwell should be amongthe most popular people today.  The reason being is that it is Teslawhose ideas power and light the modern world.  And Maxwell whoseideas give us virtually instant, world-wide communications and thetechnological devices which bring us television and radio.</p><p>Conceptually, there is also nothing wrong with the popularity ofanyone who brings happiness to people and increases the quality oflife.  Thus, "entertainers" are also important in the properdefinition of the word.  The problem at the moment is the failure toassign an "importance quotient" to achievement and to understand andappreciate the value of those such as Tesla and Maxwell.  And, tothen provide continuing gratitude for the achievement of suchindividuals.</p><p>This essay will discuss these concepts and their significance forthe survival of our specie.</p><p>See also <a href="#LAND">On...the Land of the Pharaohs.</a></p></ul><hr><h4>On...A Moral "Regulatory" System</h4><ul>	<p>	Attempts to regulate various activities in a society through the	use of the coercive powers of a political state are clearly immoral	in any time frame, and certainly irrational in the long term if not the	short term.  They are also in fact irrational in the short term, but	this is more difficult to realize, as it conflicts with the image	and intent of regulation	</p>		<p>	There is a very simple way of "regulating" things in a society using	several currently-existing mechanisms.  This essay will explain	the principle of these mechanisms, and how they work in practice.	</p></ul><hr><h4>On...Advertising, Editorials and "News."</h4><ul>	<p>	Most people believe that advertising and editorials, and what is	commonly called "news," are three completely different things.	A close examination will reveal they are not.	</p></ul<hr><hr><h4>On...Laissez-Faire City &amp; Concepts of Utopia</h4><ul>	<p>	In primitive societies based on coercion, wherein the quality of	life on an absolute basis continues its inexorable decline until	the problems are recognized and fixed, or the societies and the	volitional specie creating it are destroyed, people yearn for a	solution to their problems in the form of a "utopia."	</p>		<p>	The concept always exists in such primitive societies, but was	given special voice by Thomas More [1478-1535] in 1516 in his	book of the same name.  All known concepts of Utopia would fail,	and for the same reason as all societies based on coercion--that	they fail to take into account the nature of volitional beings.	</p>		<p>	The "Laissez-Faire City" concept recently advertised is as bad or	worse than other previous non-solutions to the problems of primitive,	coercive societies.  The intentions may be good, but we all know	what the road to the place no one wants to go to is paved with.	</p>		<p>	The historical concept of Utopia will be discussed as related to	primitive political societies, and why they did not and cannot work.	A rational concept of "Utopia" will then be discussed.	</p></ul><hr><h4>On...CNN News &amp; the Future of Man</h4><ul>	<p>	Does what we see on CNN News represent the future of the	volitional special on this planet?  What if CNN had existed	several thousand years ago?  Wouldn't we be seeing essentially	the same things we are seeing now?  The Legions of Rome would	be fighting somewhere, either an offensive war in far-off places,	or--as in the case with the Second Punic War--a battle for survival	against attack upon Rome itself.	</p>		<p>	Today we see famines, wars, inflation, depressions.  It is safe to	say, had CNN existed 2,000 years ago, people then would have been	seeing the same thing.  It was going on then, as now, the only	difference being the immediacy of the news.	</p>		<p>	This offers us powerful lessons for our time.  Lessons that have	been available for thousands of year, but no one his understood	the lesson.  We therefore find ourselves reliving history.  Is there	a solution for this problem?</ul><hr><h4>On...Intellectual Baggage and Problem Solution.</h4>	<ul>	<p>	The reason that--after millennia of trying--we have not been	able to solve our societal problems is that we carry too	many misconceptions about history and what it tells us.  We	make great advances in the non-volitional sciences because	we do not accept the status quo and are willing to break out	of the bounds of accepted thinking and "conventional wisdom."	We are willing to review existing theories, make extrapolations	based on this, formulate hypotheses of "what might or could	be,"  And to then test them for correctness or "rightness"	against historical and current events.	</p>		<p>	We then create new and arbitrary definitions, based on the best	available knowledge, for the purpose of explaining our hypothesis and	communicating it to others.   And, if we are creating a new branch	of knowledge, we propose two or more postulates upon which to	base it.	</p>		<p>	The reason we have never made any progress in solving our societal	problems is that this was never done for what is commonly called	the "social sciences."  It "just happened," with the result that we have	a system based on false premises and increasing chaos and	misunderstandings caused by millennia of attempts to repair a	basically unworkable system.	</p></ul><hr noshade><p><b>Note:</b></p><p>Some of these essays have already been written, some of them manyyears ago, with others nearly finished.  They are not being releasedyet as there is the problem of how to protect the property from beingviolated.  An unfortunate but very real artifact of our currentsocietal mechanisms.</p><p>I have released--and will occasionally release others--withoutany protection so that readers have something on which to judgewhether or not to purchase additional essays.</p><p>Part of the reason for the concern is the <b>guarantee</b> I wishto provide. This is that the purchase price of any essay would bereturned upon request, with no reason necessary.  For this, I wouldlike to ensure that such a purchaser would not retain a copy of theessay.  This would be immoral, but certainly not easily preventedwith current technology. In a rational and durable society--thecreation of which is the purpose of <i>The FreedomServer</i><sup>&copy;</sup>--this thought would not even occur.</p><p>Since all knowledge is related, it may happen that one or moretitles and concepts of intended essays will be merged into one title.The explanation of many things is so simple that in principle it maytake few words to explain the problem and the solution, and theresulting essay would <b>appear</b> to be too short to provide valuecommensurate with the cost.  If the value is there, the cost isjustifiable, yet many people may not realize the value they arereceiving.</p><hr noshade><center>[<a href="#TOP">Top of Page</a>]</center><hr noshade><center>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation<p><i>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</i></p></center><hr noshade><p><b>Contact Information:</b></p><p><a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co">administrator</a></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Essays.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY>